<HEADLINE>
TIME'S SPEEDED-UP ISSUE MISSED SOME OF THE NEWS  
 IN LOS ANGELES, IT'S PAPER VS. PAPER  
 FATE OF JOURNAL REPORTER ADDS TO SOUL-SEARCHING  
 CRITIC SAYS TWO COLUMNISTS SHOULD `COME CLEAN' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN:Calif., Mass., N.Y.)  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The calls went out to magazine printing presses
around the country last Monday morning. Time magazine's editors
wanted to print their Aug. 31 issue several days early. Otherwise,
the magazine's coverage of President Clinton's grand jury testimony
would not appear until Aug. 24, well after even the most devoted
scandal aficionados would have had more news than they could take.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Marsel, the manager of the Quad Graphics Inc. plant in
Saratoga Springs, N.Y., said that his shop was one of seven plants
_ owned by Quad Graphics, World Color Press, Quebecor Printing and
R.R. Donnelley &AMP; Sons _ that rejiggered their schedules after
Time's representatives asked to move the work ahead from the usual
weekend time slots. On Wednesday night, the plants began printing
more than 4 million copies of Time. Andrew Blau, Time's director of
operations, confirmed Marsel's account.
</P>
<P>
   A coup? Time's managing editor, Walter Isaacson, thought so. For
Time, changing the scheduled press run is a rare event, usually
pegged to national elections or superpower summit meetings. The
furor over Clinton's admissions met the test because, Isaacson
said, it ``is one of those stories where you want to give it to
people this week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be chewed over by Sunday newspapers and Sunday
talk shows,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday afternoon, however, Blau was checking to see whether
there was any weekend press capacity left anywhere. U.S. cruise
missiles had struck targets in Sudan and Afghanistan. The next
scheduled issue for Time, which is owned by Time Warner Inc., was
11 days away.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Brunett, a spokesman for Newsweek, which is owned by
Washington Post Co., clearly relished the idea that Newsweek would
have this week to itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the bombing story,'' he said. ``You have U.S. air
strikes. You have Monica's testimony. There's news developing.
Cooler heads prevailed here to maintain our regular press
schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Newsweek thought about printing early? Marsel of Quad
Graphics said the magazine's representatives called 24 hours after
Time did but found that in Saratoga Springs, at least, there was no
midweek press time left. But Brunett said, ``We could have come up
with the press time.''
</P>
<P>
   What about Time? If Time had wanted to come back with another
edition Monday, it had ``various contingency options,'' Isaacson
said on Thursday. ``The weekend capacity is there,'' he added. A
day later, he said that the bombing story was ``receding,'' adding,
``We're absolutely happy with where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   _ FELICITY BARRINGER
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, It's Paper vs. Paper
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a battle of words reminiscent of a classic
newspaper war, The Los Angeles Daily News reported last Monday that
the publisher of the rival Los Angeles Times was a member of a
powerful business group, one which not only required a $40,000
contribution to join, but had recently taken a stance on a
much-disputed political issue.
</P>
<P>
   The report was published about a week after The Daily News
disclosed, after inquiries by The Los Angeles Times, that it had
contributed $60,000 to a group called Valley Voters Organized
Toward Empowerment. The group is circulating petitions for a first
step toward secession of the San Fernando Valley from the City of
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Headlined ``L.A.'s Power Elite,'' the Daily News article said
Mark Willes, publisher of The Los Angeles Times and chief executive
of its parent company, Times Mirror Corp., was part of the
26-member Los Angeles Business Advisers. The group has said it
opposes efforts to win more power for newly created ``neighborhood
councils.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times first reported Willes' membership in the
group on May 31, though a company spokesman, Mike Lange,
acknowledged it did not report the Times Mirror payment of the
$40,000 membership fee until its Aug. 20 paper, in a response to
criticism from Valley VOTE.
</P>
<P>
   Willes said he did not think his membership in the group and
Times Mirror's $40,000 payment was fundamentally different from The
Daily News' contribution to Valley VOTE, though he said the
contribution was comparatively smaller than The Daily News'
donation, which made up a significant proportion of the money
raised by the Valley group.
</P>
<P>
   He said his participation in the business group fit with a
tradition of media chief executives and publishers being active in
their communities and was not in conflict with a company policy
barring donations to political campaigns or groups that advocate
ballot initiatives. As long as the corporate activities remain
separate from the newsroom, he said, there will not be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``In institutions like ours,'' Willes said, ``as we work very
hard to do, reporters and editors are very clear about their
journalistic responsibility and keep that very separate from the
corporate activities.''
</P>
<P>
   _ CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN
</P>
<P>
   Fate of Journal Reporter Adds to Soul-Searching
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Has journalistic rigor gone too far? Are news
executives going overboard? Those questions, first asked when The
Boston Globe cracked down on its columnist Mike Barnicle for
borrowing jokes without attribution, returned with renewed force
last week after James Hirsch lost his job as a Boston correspondent
for The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch and The Journal parted company Tuesday after he reported
erroneously that The New York Times Co. had ``declined to comment''
on The Globe's Aug. 11 decision to rescind its demand for
Barnicle's resignation. The Times Co. owns The Globe.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch, who said in an interview that in nine years The Journal
``has sent me all over the world and let me cover some of the most
important beats,'' acknowledged last week that he had not called
The Times that day. He said he had been on a tight deadline and had
believed, based on earlier interviews with The Times' spokeswoman
on issues related to The Globe, that her response would be, in
effect, a ``no comment.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day of Barnicle's reprieve, Nancy Nielsen, the
spokeswoman, gave reporters who inquired this prepared statement:
``The New York Times Co. has a policy that all of its media
properties have editorial independence and autonomy. In keeping
with our policy, we support The Globe's right to make its own
decisions, just as we would with any of our other media
properties.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nielsen confirmed last week that after she saw Hirsch's
article, she wrote to The Journal's managing editor, Paul Steiger.
On Tuesday, Steiger's deputy informed Hirsch that he had committed
``a fireable offense,'' Hirsch recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is proportionality: Is it fair or not fair?''
Hirsch asked. He continued: ``It was an error, and it shouldn't
have happened. But it had no bearing on the story. And it certainly
wasn't journalistic malice or deception.'' Asked if other issues
were involved, Hirsch said, ``This offense was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Miller Pensiero, a spokeswoman for Dow Jones &AMP; Co., The
Journal's parent, responded ``it is simply not true'' that no other
issues were involved. She did not elaborate on that point but did
add that the Globe incident alone would justify termination.
``There are few, if any, more serious violations of journalistic
norms than knowingly printing a falsehood,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Martin, the grievance chairman of the union that represents
Journal reporters, the Independent Association of Publishers'
Employees, said last week that a grievance filed Tuesday contended
that Hirsch was ``terminated without just and sufficient cause.''
</P>
<P>
   _ FELICITY BARRINGER
</P>
<P>
   Critic Says Two Columnists Should `Come Clean'
</P>
<P>
   One footnote to the resignation last week of the columnist Mike
Barnicle from The Boston Globe:
</P>
<P>
   The media critic for the online magazine Slate issued what he
called a ``challenge to America's press: come clean about the Mike
Barnicles in your midst before you have to.''
</P>
<P>
   The critic, Scott Shugar, who writes Today's Papers, the daily
assessment of the front pages of several national newspapers, said
that he had ``the goods on'' two columnists whose editors were
aware that they were ``fiction artists and plagiarists.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid of exposing them,'' he said, adding that he had
issued his challenge ``to see what shakes out.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA NAPOLI
</P>
<P>
   &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
