<HEADLINE>
RANGERS HOLD ON TO BEAT YANKEES, 12-10
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ They're gone.
</P>
<P>
   Now another manager can compare them to the Big Red Machine and
other great teams of the past, and another city of baseball experts
can wax eloquent about their many virtues.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees are through in Texas, and the Rangers
watched them go with a glimmer of hope that the best team in the
American League is not totally invincible.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers haven't been able to out-pitch or out-field the
Yankees at all this year, but a 12-10 victory at The Ballpark in
Arlington last night reinforced the notion that on occasion they
can out-hit them.
</P>
<P>
   Barely.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers twice enjoyed six-run leads, and ended up needing
every run they could squeeze out of Yankees starter Orlando
Hernandez and four relievers to salvage one victory in five tries
against New York at home this year. The Yankees hit five home runs,
including two by catcher Jorge Posada, but the Rangers survived
because all five were hit with nobody on base.
</P>
<P>
   ``After last night (a 12-9 loss), it was very important we got a
win,'' first baseman Will Clark said. ``The reason being, it could
have been very easy for the team to say we've run into some tough
luck. Instead, we got six in the first and continued to put the
pressure on them the entire game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers hammered Hernandez for six runs in the first inning
and added five more against relievers Mike Stanton and Ryan Bradley
in the sixth. The big blow was a three-run homer by Rusty Greer off
Bradley right when the Yankees appeared ready to finish off another
morale-crushing comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not invincible, but they are a very good team,''
second baseman Luis Alicea said. ``To beat them, you can't make
mistakes and you have to score a lot of runs because they keep
coming at you. They've got a lot of good hitters and if it's not
one guy, it's another. But tonight, it was a team effort for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Barely.
</P>
<P>
   The victory allowed the Rangers to remain within 21/2 games of
the Anaheim Angels in the American League West and they finished
7-10 in a 17-game stretch against the Yankees, Red Sox and Indians,
the top three teams in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   They also have hope things could change quickly because now it's
the Angels who must deal with the Yankees in a five-game series
that starts tonight in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're in for a very tough drive, but it's still going to be
tough for us because we're a couple of games back,'' shortstop
Royce Clayton said. ``You prefer to be in front, but we've played
some tough teams lately and finished on a high note. We won a very
tough ballgame tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers starter Rick Helling got the victory, his 16th of the
season. But it was never secure until John Wetteland took over in
the ninth and got Bernie Williams, representing the tying run, to
hit into a game-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we're supposed to do,'' Rangers manager Johnny
Oates said. ``We've had a lot of nip-and-tuck games with these guys
lately. Scoring six runs in the first inning made us feel better,
but you see they don't give up. In the end, they had the tying run
at the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez held the Rangers scoreless on two hits through 81/3
innings on Aug. 13 in New York. The difference last night, Oates
said, was ``I thought his command wasn't as sharp as it was in
Yankee Stadium. It seems like in Yankee Stadium, he could throw
that big slow curveball over the plate any time he wanted. And
tonight, our right-handers didn't chase that sidearm slider off the
plate. That was the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Barely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
