<HEADLINE>
MILE WINNER, WILD WONDER, MAKES DOUGH FOR OWNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, Wash. _ I'd like to think I had a hand in the outcome of
Sunday's Longacres Mile.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't a hand so much as two chubby cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   A horse belonging to the guy who invented the Winchell's Donuts
chain of cholesterol factories won the big race at Emerald Downs.
Given my decades-long investment in his business, the least Verne
Winchell could have done was offer me a small cut of his $110,000
in winnings.
</P>
<P>
   But no. Nothing. Not even a glazed chocolate with sprinkles.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was good news Sunday, even if the local pony yard's
own hero and defending Mile champ, Kid Katabatic, looked as if he
loaded up a donut shop on his back in the stretch and faded out of
the money.
</P>
<P>
   The good news was Verne Winchell is a vigorous 87 years old. A
near-lifetime of eating his own product hasn't harmed him a bit. On
top of that, he merged Winchell's with the Denny's restaurant chain
in 1967 and ran the company until he retired in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that nutritional neutron bomb, despite all those years
of looking at orange vinyl, he was around to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   The irony was the guy who actually did have a little more
influence in the outcome probably has seen the inside of a
Winchell's only in the pages of a National Geographic (Attack upon
American Arteries, July, 1989).
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Delahoussaye hardly weighs more than a tray of custard
creams, but the weight of his history and experience was too much
for the field to bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming in, we didn't know if we had the best horse in the
race,'' said trainer Greg Gilchrist of his steed, Wild Wonder.
``But I knew we had the best rider.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the longest and best known names in racing, Delahoussaye
is a little past his splendid prime, but the Hall of Fame jockey
can still spot a mark when he sees one. The Mile may be the
Northwest's most prestigious race, but it usually has been an easy
plum for California horses. The big studs ship up for the weekend
for a simple little Grade III action, clobber the locals and are
back home with the whiskey, women and loot before anyone here has
the wits to call for the sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   Spotting a light weekend in his duties at San Diego's Del Mar,
and getting a wink and nudge from Gilchrist and Winchell,
Delahoussaye broke away for what turned out to be a remarkably
simple heist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a perfect trip,'' he said. ``It was fantastic. I don't
have too many more years of riding. I'm glad I have it under my
belt.''
</P>
<P>
   As the jock who won the Kentucky Derby in 1982 (Gato del Sol)
and 1983 (Sunny's Halo), plus two Belmont Stakes, five Breeders'
Cup races and more than $100 million in purses over 5,000 career
victories, the 46-year-old Cajun craftsman was being a bit generous
in glorifying the Mile. The race is not found on the big-time
national radar screen, and even its local luster has diminished in
the Emerald Downs digs, as attested by Sunday's crowd estimate of
11,500 _ almost 10,000 below the race's heyday at the defunct
Longacres.
</P>
<P>
   But that is the way of thoroughbred life almost everywhere. In
fact, the modest improvements this year in Emerald Downs' purses
and fields contrast with many downward arrows nationally. Before
the race, Delahoussaye lamented about his industry's decade-long
turn for the worse.
</P>
<P>
   Citing federal tax law changes that discouraged small-time horse
owners as well as the competition with other forms of gambling, he
aired a litany familiar to any veteran of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't like the direction it's going,'' he said. ``A lot
of the younger trainers are not really horsemen. They're learning
the business and are more like promoters. They might be car
salesmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put slot machines at a track and a large percentage (of
patrons) will just sit right there at the slots. What gets them
involved with horses? The slots help the purses but they don't help
fans and create new owners.''
</P>
<P>
   As a man from racing's prime time, Delahoussaye, who has never
broken a bone in racing and had only one injury, in 1982, that
required much recuperation, is discovering more dangerous times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've ridden horses I'd never thought I'd ride again,'' he
said. ``At my stage, I really don't need to take chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was not a day of risk. There was too much quality between
his knees.
</P>
<P>
   Wild Wonder, who in his last start finished second to the highly
regarded Free House in the Bel Air Handicap at Hollywood Park, was
the betting favorite. Delahoussaye kept him within a length of the
speed horse, Kid Katabatic, through all the turns before blasting
past in a pure flash of genetic superiority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew if we could catch that speed horse, nobody else (in
the field) would go up there,'' said Winchell. ``We felt all along
we had an edge in class.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost always in racing, class tells. Even when it's from a
donut peddler.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
