<HEADLINE>
LATE RALLY NOT ENOUGH AS THE BULLPEN FALTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Having suffered through the New York Yankees'
game against Texas Sunday night, Manager Joe Torre might choose a
more stable profession. A Wall Street broker, perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees plummeted and soared for nine innings until they
finally crashed, 12-10, despite hitting four home runs, including
two by Jorge Posada. The Yankees were unable to overcome the
deficit posted early by Orlando Hernandez (8-4).
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees took two of three games in this series, and their
overall record is 94-33. They Yankees remain on a pace to win 120
games as they return home to play Anaheim in a five-game series,
including two make-up games from April.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, the Yankees fell behind by 6-0, got as close as
6-5, fell behind again by 12-6, and then made another late push.
Derek Jeter, who had 26 hits and 19 runs batted in in 11 games
against the Rangers this season, had a run-scoring double in the
seventh, and Paul O'Neill hit a two-run single, cutting the lead to
12-9.
</P>
<P>
   Posada mashed his second home run in the eighth, cutting the
Rangers lead to 12-10. After a pitching change, Chad Curtis came
within a foot or so of hitting a home run, settling for a double.
But the surge stopped there, and Hernandez was the losing pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deficiency on the mound was one thing, but the way we kept
battling back made the whole experience worthwhile,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez left Cuba on a makeshift, 17-foot leaking craft, and
he has come a long way since then. Killing time before his start
Sunday night, he flipped through the pages of a yacht catalog.
</P>
<P>
   He had been the Yankees' best pitcher this month, allowing just
14 hits and three runs in 33 innings coming into Sunday night's
game.
</P>
<P>
   His aggressiveness and command have been exceptional. Hernandez
struck out 13 batters and gave up two hits against the Rangers Aug.
13. This time around, he pitched to the other extreme.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez seemed to have no idea where he was throwing his
sidearm slider, a pitch that devastated the Rangers 10 days ago.
His fastball repeatedly drifted over the plate, into the hitters'
range. The Rangers' first five hitters to face Hernandez reached
base, only one fewer base runner than Hernandez allowed the Rangers
in his entire eight-and-one-third-inning gem on Aug. 13. He needed
41 pitches to get through the first inning Sunday night, and it was
not until his 35th pitch that a Ranger batter missed at one of his
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have good control of my pitches,'' Hernandez said.
``I believe that's what cost us the game, the first inning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers piled up a 6-0 lead, and it goes without saying that
they were still in jeopardy, facing the majors' highest-scoring
team. Posada hit a home run in the second inning, O'Neill drove in
a couple of runs in the third, and Scott Brosius hit his 16th home
run in the fifth. Suddenly, and without any surprise whatsoever,
the Yankees trailed by a single run.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Hernandez stabilized somewhat. Between innings,
he and Posada, his catcher, consulted in the dugout. They managed
to shut out the Rangers through the second, third and fourth
innings. But the toll of the first inning, exacerbated by the
91-degree heat, finished off Hernandez in the fifth inning, when
the Rangers plated their seventh run.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tino Martinez smashed the Yankees' third home run of the night
and his 22nd of the season in the top of the sixth. Torre
demonstrated his resolute belief that his team was going to win
this game by inserting Mike Stanton, his left-handed set-up man, to
relieve in the bottom of the sixth. Hold the Rangers another inning
or two, and the Yankees would be on their way.
</P>
<P>
   But Stanton, who blew a save chance Saturday, walked the leadoff
batter on four pitches and then gave up a single; for the second
consecutive game, Stanton, a veteran of nine seasons, was relieved
by Ryan Bradley, a big-leaguer for three days.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton returned to the bench to watch the Rangers jump on
Bradley for four more hits, including Rusty Greer's three-run
homer. The Rangers' lead soared to six runs.
</P>
<P>
   John Wetteland, who blew a lead on Saturday, pitched the ninth
inning for Texas and ended the game by getting Bernie Williams to
hit into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   In five games between the Yankees and Rangers in Texas this
season, the teams combined for 83 runs.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees bolstered their stock of right-handed relievers,
swapping the disappointing former No. 1 draft pick Shea Morenz and
minor-league pitcher Ray Ricken to San Diego for minor-league
pitchers Jim Bruske and Brad Kaufman. Bruske, 33, was General
Manager Brian Cashman's primary objective in the deal. He spent
most of this season in the majors with the Los Angeles Dodgers,
before San Diego traded for him July 23 and optioned him to Class
AAA Las Vegas shortly thereafter. Bruske was 3-0 with a 3.48 earned
run average with the Dodgers and allowed three runs in seven
innings for the Padres. Because of injuries to Jeff Nelson and
Darren Holmes, and because right-handers Marty Janzen and Scott
Brow have pitched poorly for Class AAA Columbus, the Yankees are
somewhat short-handed in right-handed relief. Bruske probably won't
be part of the Yankees' post-season roster, but he'll likely be
recalled for the month of September and used in middle relief.
Others likely to be promoted from Columbus, along with Bruske,
after the rosters expand in September: Catcher Mike Figga,
infielder Mike Lowell, outfielders Shane Spencer and Ricky Ledee,
and pitchers Mike Jerzembeck and Mike Buddie.
</P>
</TEXT>
