<HEADLINE>
BETTER PLAY A MUST, EVEN VS. WEAK FOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ It had been a 17-game stretch against the
Godzillas, and when it was over last night, the survivors could be
remembered more by words than deeds.
</P>
<P>
   Like Rusty Greer, who became an advocate for mental health. ``If
we dwell on it,'' he advised, ``we all go crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates sounded like an Alka-Seltzer salesman before the
series and regular-season wrapup against the Yankees. ``I left the
park with heartburn (Saturday night), but I woke up feeling fine,''
noted the manager. This, of course, was before last night's acid
cocktail, which at times almost became impossible to stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Infielder Luis Alicea, meanwhile, juggled mathematical formulas
until he found sunshine among the numbers. ``Considering
everything, the Angels should have been built a bigger (divisional)
lead on us, don't you think?'' wondered Alicea.
</P>
<P>
   Tell you what, Louie, those 2 1/2 games still look rather
sizable.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the Rangers out-slugging New York, 12-10, to end the
17-game stretch, some damage control was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees won five of seven, the Red Sox four of six and thank
goodness for the Indians, who lost three of four. This was three
weeks that were supposed to define the season for the Rangers. To
do so, however, first you'd have to define the Yankees, who have
played beyond description for an entire season. And certainly
continued to do so against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A media guy comes up to me the other day and wanted to know
how we compare against the 1906 Cubs,'' Don Zimmer, the Yankees'
bench coach, said last night. ``Hell, do I look that old?''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer has spent 50 season in professional baseball, including
39 as a major-league player, manager and coach. He was a rookie on
one of the best teams of all time, the 1955 Brooklyn Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm asked repeatedly about that comparison,'' said Zimmer,
``but the '55 Dodgers had five Hall of Famers. What's there to
compare? I don't know anything about comparisons. I just know this
has been, to date, one heckuva magical season.''
</P>
<P>
   If someone wants to say these Yankees have five future Hall of
Famers, or 25 for that matter, the Rangers won't disagree.
</P>
<P>
   And just because the Yankees left town last night, that doesn't
mean the Rangers are done with baseball's merchants of mass
destruction. Call it the best news of all.
</P>
<P>
   As of this morning, an Arlington chapter of the Bronx Fan Club
will convene at The Ballpark in Arlington. Now it's the Angels'
turn to test the Yankees, and beginning tonight Anaheim will have
to do so under some extreme conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the falling beams that shut down Yankee Stadium in
April? The makeup dates for the Angels start with a doubleheader to
kick off a five-game series in the Bronx. Then it's on to Boston
for three and Cleveland for two. Can Anaheim handle that heat any
better, or worse, than the Rangers?
</P>
<P>
   This is a case of sudden schedule switching _ the Rangers' next
19 games are against sub-.500 teams, starting tonight against
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was so much emphasis from the fans and the media on the
past 17 games,'' said Greer, whose nuclear home-run blast of 423
feet in the sixth inning last night plated three runs to eventually
break the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know everyone, including the team, came away with
disappointment,'' continued Greer. ``What has to be realized,
however, is there's now another game, another series and another
stretch coming up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get down to it, this next stretch is much more
important to us than the last stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit, the White Sox, the Twins, Kansas City, Tampa Bay _ it's
hardly the glamour of the Yankees, but the pressure is no
different. These are inferior teams, based on records, but it's
like Oates says, ``if you aren't playing well, you don't
consistently beat anyone you're playing.''
</P>
<P>
   And above all else, at least be scoring runs. Which,
interestingly enough, the Rangers did well in the seven games
against the Yankees. The one huge advantage for New York is
pitching, but despite being shutout twice, the Rangers scored a
staggering 46 runs in the other five games.
</P>
<P>
   What the Rangers couldn't outscore was pitching and defensive
misery. If that continues, the next stretch of schedule won't be
any more successful than the last.
</P>
</TEXT>
