<HEADLINE>
BACK-TO-SCHOOL PLANNING JUST GOT EASIER 
</HEADLINE>
   By AMY DOAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
With September looming, there are plenty of school-related
financial resources available. Consumer Reports online has a free
back-to-school buying guide at
www.consumerreports.org/news/backtoschool/. It has detailed
information on desktop computers, backpacks, phone cards and even
bed sheets for college dorm rooms.
<TEXT>
<P>
   One section shows how misleading marketing for student-targeted
credit cards can be. Students should avoid cards that encourage
them to maintain a balance in order to earn rebates on future
purchases, the guide says. &UR;  &LR; That's because the value of these
so-called rebates is far less than the finance charges connected
with maintaining an account.
</P>
<P>
   The California Department of Consumer Affairs has prepared some
tips for college students in a free fact sheet called Successful
Credit Management Takes Planning. The department also has
information on how to select a school, rent an apartment, and
protect your credit identity. All of this information is available
on its Web site at www.dca.ca.gov, or by calling (800) 952-5210 or
(916) 323-7239. The rental guide, called California Tenants, costs
$2.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN &AMP; INVESTING: The average salary of all female workers in
the &UR;  &LR; United States is about 20 percent less than that of men, and
75 percent of women have no idea how much money they'll need for
retirement, according to American Express. AmEx has launched a
program called ``Smart Choices'' that is designed to attract women
investors to its funds. Participation in the wide-ranging program,
which includes financial planning newsletters and a free investing
book, requires a $2,000 investment in one of the company's mutual
funds. But you can get one brochure _ 10 Questions Women Ask About
Investing _ for free by calling (888) 811-2558. You don't have to
be female to get the pamphlet.
</P>
<P>
   HEAVIER DEBT LOAD: On average, Americans have 2 percent less in
liquid assets than they would need to pay off all their debts,
according to the Federal Reserve Board. By comparison, the average
household in 1985 had 52 percent more than it needed to pay off
creditors. The Fed believes that's because the prolonged bull
market has made investing seem more attractive than paying off
credit cards, mortgages and other debts.
</P>
<P>
   WEB QUOTE SERVICE: IQC Corp. has upgraded its free online stock
quote service at www.iqc.com. The site now has technical analysis
and historical information on securities. Investors can get basic
quotes for tracking stocks, as well as more detailed quotes with
technical, fundamental, price and volume information in chart
format.
</P>
</TEXT>
