<HEADLINE>
FOR BROADCAST.COM, IT'S TIME TO DELIVER TO SHAREHOLDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK VEVERKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Now comes the hard part for Broadcast.com chief executive Todd
Wagner.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not that launching a successful Internet venture from his
business partner's home was a piece of cake, but it is time to
deliver on the lofty expectations of shareholders.  &LR;   &LR; 
Broadcast.com was one of the most successful initial offerings of
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which broadcasts live audio and video over the
Internet, went public at $18 on July 17 and traded as high as $74
on its opening day. Friday's close was $55.50.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he thought the IPO was underpriced, Wagner was
predictably diplomatic. ``We knew there would be strong demand, but
we're happy that the institutions were able to make some money,''
says Wagner, who is a securities lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, did they ever. But Wagner isn't exactly flipping burgers
either. The 38-year-old executive's stock holdings, without
options, are worth more than $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Internet darlings, investors have rewarded
Dallas-based Broadcast.com for being a ``first-mover'' or category
leader in a particular Internet segment.
</P>
<P>
   The niche in this case was broadcasting live sporting events _
such as Super Bowls and college basketball's NCAA Final Four &UR;  &LR; _
over the Net.
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration for Wagner and his partner, President Mark
Cuban, was Hoosier basketball. The Indiana University graduates are
rabid hoops fans, and they turned to the Internet for play-by-play
radio accounts of Bobby Knight's squad.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Wagner is now trying to expand the company's reputation
beyond sports. He wants it to be known as the principal Webcaster
of all types of audio and video programming.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Wagner fancies Broadcast.com a ``next-wave
portal,'' making it different from Yahoo or America Online.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just a passing-though point (of entry), but a place
where people will stay for a while,'' Wagner explains.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Wagner thinks that Broadcast.com will become most
useful in the corporate world. Already, it's broadcasting speeches,
teleconferences and internal meetings over the Internet and company
intranets.
</P>
<P>
   His company is aggressively going after business-to-business
accounts because corporations are the ones with the hardware right
now that can best download video and audio over the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the real meat and potatoes of this is,'' Wagner
says.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter's Mary Meeker, the doyenne of
Internet stock analysts, pointed out recently in a research note
that corporate-service events broadcast by Broadcast.com have risen
162 percent over the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Meeker states that she ``likes this company a lot'' and thinks
that the ``fundamental business outlook is great.'' But she
initiated coverage last week with a ``neutral'' rating based on the
stock's inflated market value of nearly $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Naturally, Broadcast.com doesn't make any money. In its first
financial report since going public, the company posted a net loss
for its second quarter of $3.9 million, which was more than double
the red ink for the year-ago quarter.
</P>
<P>
   NAME-BRAND PARTNER
</P>
<P>
   You've got to hand it to Venture Strategy Partners, a fledgling
venture capital firm in San Francisco that specializes in building
brands. One of its partners founded the Republic of Tea and another
worked with Dannon yogurt for years.
</P>
<P>
   What's impressive is that they've brought in a name-brand
partner, Bill Hambrecht, and access to capital.
</P>
<P>
   How did they swing that?
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Hambrecht's winery was a client of the firm's
consulting business, and they ``started to collaborate,'' says
Joanna Gallanter, founder and general partner of Venture Strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht, who retired from the investment banking firm that
bears his name earlier this year, helped pioneer the Bay Area's
worldwide reputation as a wellspring of VC dough. He has launched
his own boutique investment firm, W.R. Hambrecht + Co., which could
possibly underwrite and advise Venture Strategy's clients down the
line.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
