<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FOR A JOB CAN BE A LONG, PAINFUL PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ILANA DEBARE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 Q:   I recently applied for a civil service position and was
invited back for a fourth and final interview. The interview
occurred in the morning. The afternoon mail included a letter from
the agency's personnel department telling me that I finished second
in the selection process. This suggests two things to me. One,
there was a lack of communication within the agency. Two, the final
interview was a sham and the decision was made before I even got in
the door. Do I have any recourse?
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  We all know how traumatic it can be to lose a longtime job.
But _ as this letter to Workways and the next one show _ sometimes
applying for a job can be as confusing or painful as losing one.
</P>
<P>
   You're probably right in blaming this particular mess-up on a
lack of communication. The right hand that was interviewing you
didn't know about the doings of the left hand, which had already
rejected you.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have any grounds for a lawsuit, however.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that you haven't suffered any financial damage.
Another is that the agency never actually made you a job offer _ so
you can't try to claim that it breached a contract.
</P>
<P>
   You're certainly free to write a polite complaint letter to the
head of this agency. That might prod the agency into straightening
out its hiring process in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, maybe you should count your blessings that you didn't
end up working for such a disorganized organization. And keep in
mind that someday you'll find this whole episode funny when you're
safely and happily settled in a job somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;   &LR; I applied for work with a company and went through five
separate interviews, including two with vice presidents. I then
received a verbal job offer from the company, with the
understanding that an official written offer would follow. But
several days later, I got a call from my contact at the firm saying
the offer was rescinded. When I asked why, all I was told was ``an
upper-level manager didn't think your qualifications matched the
job.'' Don't they owe me more of an explanation? I find this
unprofessional and confusing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  This company did treat you rudely and unprofessionally. In
the long run, that will hurt the firm more than it hurts you:
Employers can't afford to alienate good applicants in today's tight
job market.
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, you're lucky that you didn't quit your current
job when you got that verbal offer. I've gotten letters from other
folks who received a job offer, quit their current job and then
found themselves without employment or income when the offer was
unexpectedly withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Stansbury, owner of Stansbury Staffing Consultants in
San Francisco, advises applicants never to quit their current job
until they have a written offer firmly in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with saying yes to a verbal offer, but
absolutely don't give notice until you receive that formal offer
letter,'' said Stansbury, president-elect of the Northern
California Human Resources Association.
</P>
<P>
   So how should a well-managed company notify applicants that
they've been accepted or rejected?
</P>
<P>
   Stansbury says that managers should avoid making job offers on
impulse during interviews. ``Go back, discuss it with all the
decisionmakers so you get buy-in, and then make an offer,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Verbal offers are fine, but they should be followed up promptly
by written letters that include the new employee's starting date
and monthly salary.
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes to rejecting candidates, companies need to be
equally forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people who went through six or seven interviews, and
then found the company simply stopped returning their calls,''
Stansbury said. ``That's not right.''
</P>
<P>
   The best way to reject a candidate who's been through the
interview process is with a personal phone call, Stansbury said. If
company officials are too busy to phone, they should send a
personal letter that includes the reason for their choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should give some reason, such as `The candidate we've
chosen had more qualifications in our industry,' '' she said.
``Candidates in today's market are very, very valuable, and should
be treated graciously and politely.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;   &LR; I have two teenage nephews in Ireland who are interested
in coming to America. Is there any good book I can recommend to
them about jobs and careers in this country?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  There's a book called the ``Young Person's Occupational
Outlook Handbook,'' which gives brief descriptions of the 250 most
common jobs in America as well as their educational requirements.
It's based on the Occupational Outlook Handbook compiled every two
years by the U.S. Department of Labor, and is published by JIST
Works. Call (800) 648-5478 to order it, or visit JIST's web site at
www.jist.com.
</P>
<P>
   Another potentially helpful book is ``Finding a Job in the
U.S.,'' by Joan Friedenberg and Curtis Bradley (NTC Publishing
Group).
</P>
<P>
   You might also send your nephews a good general book on choosing
a career. One new one that's lively enough to interest teens as
well as adults is ``Cool Careers for Dummies,'' written by Bay Area
career counselor Marty Nemko and Paul and Sarah Edwards. That's
available from IDG Books Worldwide, at (800) 762-2974 or
www.dummies.com.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, your nephews should use the Internet to find out more
about any career ideas that grab their interest. There are plenty
of Web sites with information about particular jobs or professions
_ and they can be reached just as easily from Ireland as from the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   _ MORE ON FIRING: Last week, I listed several guidebooks for
employers who need to terminate somebody. Here's another good one
that arrived too late for last week's deadline: ``Rightful
Termination: Defensive Strategies for Hiring and Firing in the
Lawsuit-Happy 90's'' by James Walsh. Long and thorough, this book
is available from Merritt Publishing at (800) 638-7597.
</P>
<P>
   Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways,
San Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or
send e-mail to workways &LR; sfgate.com. Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query in person, but we will answer as many
in print as we can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
