u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-24 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Padres, home field Astros' next targets
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ First, there was a rumble.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there was a boom.
</P>
<P>
   A loud boom.
</P>
<P>
   A very loud boom.
</P>
<P>
   It rattled the rivets and shook the rafters. It was a Blue Angel
F-15, buzzing so low overhead at Wrigley Field that the afterburn
could have roasted peanuts. It was so low, you could see the
pilot's rank _ Captain, I think. Blond dude. Looked like Ice Man
from Top Gun.
</P>
<P>
   It was so low, well, we'll let catcher Brad Ausmus take over
from here, because Ausmus did a lot of taking over Sunday anyway:
``A good popup would have knocked that thing down.''
</P>
<P>
   Bogeys at Clark and Addison.
</P>
<P>
   The sonic boom made the hair on the back of 38,714 necks stand
on end. The same would have happened to Ausmus, who was standing in
the crosshairs at home plate, had he not been drenched in sweat
from playing one whale of a game (4-for-4, five RBIs and a
perfectly called contest against anyone not named Sammy).
</P>
<P>
   ``It scared the hell out of me,'' said Ausmus, who ducked out of
the box when the plane screamed by. ``It came out of nowhere.
Luckily, the umpire jumped back, too, because the pitch was right
down the middle. It was loud.''
</P>
<P>
   And on this day, when another Cubs-Astros battle was supposed to
happen but instead the Gulf War broke out, it was so symbolic.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom of order top-notch
</P>
<P>
   Choose your favorite metaphor: Turning on the jets. Dropping a
bomb. Blue Chicago. Speeding to victory. F-15 vs. Piper Cubs. Angel
of Mercy.
</P>
<P>
   Any way you say it, it was Astros 13, the Republican Guard 3.
</P>
<P>
   Death to the tyrants from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   This National League Central war the Astros have been fighting
is over. Switch back to regular programming. The Astros have a
9{-game lead on the Cubs with 31 games remaining. France has
surrendered its flag on less.
</P>
<P>
   If there is one thing you should count on between now and late
September, it's the Astros not surrendering their division flag for
another year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel comfortable, but I don't feel overconfident,'' Astros
manager Larry Dierker said about the division race.
</P>
<P>
   He should feel gallant, maybe even noble.
</P>
<P>
   This was a three-game set the Cubs had hoped to use as a
springboard to get back into the division race. The Cubs were
hoping to somehow survive a thin pitching staff, a constant strong
wind blowing toward left field, and an Astros team that does
nothing if not cover its flanks.
</P>
<P>
   Take Sunday. The meat of the Astros lineup again only nibbled at
the scorecard, Derek Bell finishing 0-for-4 and Jeff Bagwell merely
tapping an infield hit on the way to a 1-for-5 day.
</P>
<P>
   But on the flanks _ Craig Biggio at the top of the card and the
six-through-nine guys at the bottom _ the Astros swarmed Chicago
into submission.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio hit a pair of three-run homers, a feat that certainly
deserves more than one sentence. But today it's just not possible,
because look here:
</P>
<P>
   With Ausmus also hitting a three-run homer, the Nos. 6-9 guys
grunted their way to a marvelous day that included reaching base 12
times in 15 official at-bats, with nine runs, seven RBIs and
general havoc wreaked on every hurler the Cubs tried.
</P>
<P>
   Lima brave, victorious
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Astros pitcher Jose Lima, who in stifling heat
tossed a lot of great pitches over eight innings and, ever the
crowd-pleaser, managed two fat ones to Cubs slugger Sammy Sosa, who
stayed in the race to catch Roger Maris with his 50th and 51st
homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a chicken. I'm going to pitch to Sammy Sosa,'' Lima
said. ``If he hits a home run, so what? Big deal. We are here to
get the `W,' and we got it. I heard the Cubs couldn't wait for us
to come in here. But we are here, and now we've got two big wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the NL Central battle is over. It's time for the Astros to
shift their focus to the Western Front, specifically San Diego,
where the Padres suddenly are looking catchable in the race to a
home-field edge in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have earned the head-to-head tie-breaking edge on the
Padres this season. And when Dierker looked at the standings after
Sunday's effort, that was not a misprint he saw. The Astros are but
two games behind San Diego in the win column.
</P>
<P>
   There's one more game in this Chicago series today, but the
reason the Astros want to win it has changed. The next rumble you
hear could be the Padres going boom, much like the Cubs have.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we have to do to get where we want to go
this year is beat good teams on the road,'' Dierker said. ``This
will be a good series for us. We can begin to focus a little more
on (the Padres).''
</P>
<P>
   Cover your flanks, San Diego.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
