<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8326 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC--DREXLER-HNS &LR;      08-24 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC--DREXLER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Drexler quickly puts stamp on program
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Wave of interest engulfs UH basketball
</P>
<P>
   By JERRY WIZIG &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   The answer to the question _ Can Clyde Drexler coach basketball?
_ must wait for at least several more months. But some things have
become obvious before Drexler assumes his new seat on the
University of Houston bench for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The man can sell tickets, spark enthusiasm for a program and
attract the interest of talented prospective recruits, all within
the space of about four months.
</P>
<P>
   Drexler will take his time filling the wall space in his new
office at UH's Athletics/Alumni Center. He also will fend off
remarks like the one voiced recently by one of his fellow UH
coaches in another sport, ``At least I'm not the best player on my
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Drexler's response: ``That is not an option. I'm not putting on
a uniform again. My playing days are over.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that there was any doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far in this blissful honeymoon, UH athletic director Chet
Gladchuk places Drexler's economic impact at nearly $1.5 million at
the ticket window, based on the sale of nearly 5,000 season tickets
(at $150 each), more than 250 VIP floor seats ($1,000 a pop), and
20 luxury boxes ($15,000 per season for a three-year lease) being
built on the concourse level.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that,'' Gladchuk said smiling, ``is before Clyde has even
coached a game.''
</P>
<P>
   That will occur the night of Nov. 17, when the Cougars host
Texas and its new coach, Rick Barnes, in an opener to be televised
by ESPN2. Later, there are non-conference dates at Rice (Nov. 21)
and North Carolina State (Dec. 12), the team that stunned Drexler
and his Phi Slama Jama teammates at UH in the 1983 NCAA final. The
Cougars also return to the site of that disappointment, playing in
The Pit for the University of New Mexico's tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Ten scholarship players return from last season's UH team, which
was the first in school history to lose 20 games and averaged about
2,800 in home attendance. The two incoming recruits are 6-5
freshman Moses Malone Jr., signed by previous coach Alvin Brooks,
and 6-2 George Gervin Jr. from San Jacinto College. A third
recruit, 6-7 Cedric Taylor of Waltrip, may qualify to enter school
in the spring semester of his sophomore year after playing at a
junior college.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to play up-tempo and trapping, pressing
basketball,'' Drexler said.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is this team can only do that if a short lineup is
able to rebound. The tallest returnees are 6-9 Kenny Younger, 6-8
Early Smith and 6-8 William Stringfellow.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Drexler says there is more to his early days in office
than basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between evaluating prospects (during the July recruiting
process) and putting in a game plan for the program, those are just
part of the job of coaching a Division I program and running a
staff,'' he said. ``There's the media, alumni and school functions;
the list goes on. But it's been fun.''
</P>
<P>
   On a shelf behind Drexler's desk is a thick NCAA manual of rules
and regulations. Next to that is a biography of Abraham Lincoln.
There also is a team picture of the Rockets, a framed photo of
Drexler and Guy V. Lewis, his coach at UH, and another of former
teammate Hakeem Olajuwon. On a table is a crystal plaque
commemorating Drexler's becoming the third player in NBA history
(with Oscar Robertson and John Havlicek) to compile 20,000 points,
6,000 rebounds and 6,000 assists. On his desk is a picture of his
wife, Gaynell, with their children, Erika, Austin, Adam and Elise.
</P>
<P>
   During the transition between Drexler's 15th and final NBA
season and his full-time arrival on campus, assistants Reid Gettys
and George Walker fielded the brunt of the phone calls and
paperwork. Later, Reid Martinka (from Vanderbilt) was hired as the
third assistant coach, and Byron Smith, a former Cougar player and
UH graduate, was named coordinator of basketball operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was incredible,'' Gettys said of those weeks, which
included a large number of blinking lights from callers on hold,
office visitors and guests just wanting a word with the new coach.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those calls were inquiries from at least 10 players
interested in transferring from other Division I schools to play
for Drexler and UH. Four were from players (or their families) at
one Big 12 school.
</P>
<P>
   Gettys, who gave up his career as an attorney, and Walker, the
head coach and assistant athletic director at South Florida
Community College when hired by Drexler, also spent a lot of time
dealing with calls and visits from prospective walk-ons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hundreds. Zillions,'' Gettys said.
</P>
<P>
   Drexler's name recognition, what Gettys calls ``the C.D.
factor,'' afforded Drexler, and UH, easy access to prospects,
within NCAA guidelines, at summer camps and leagues. The most
notable result thus far is a verbal commitment from 6-5 point guard
Antonio Falu of Waltrip, a senior considered one of the nation's
best.
</P>
<P>
   Verbal commitments are non-binding until the NCAA's November
signing period. Meanwhile, Falu, who spent part of the summer
playing against former Rocket Sam Cassell and Denver's Anthony
Goldwire, will receive several hand-written letters a week from the
Cougars _ and probably dozens of other schools.
</P>
<P>
   Another early positive is the addition of guard Bernard Smith of
Conroe, a sophomore transfer from Texas who must sit out this year
and then retains three seasons of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Talents such as Malone, Gervin, Smith, Taylor and Falu, combined
with returnees Chad Hendrick, Trey Austin and Charles Fordjour,
figure to provide a solid foundation on which to rebuild a program
that reached lofty heights in Drexler's playing days.
</P>
<P>
   In his UH career, Drexler played on the first two of the
Cougars' three consecutive Final Four teams (1982-83-84), passing
up his senior season to start his NBA career. Near its end he was
selected as one of the top 50 players in NBA history. Now, he has a
five-year contract with an annual base salary of $150,000, with
incentives and outside income sources that could bring the amount
to $300,000 per year. He also has endorsement and
personal-appearance agreements with Denny's, Sprite, Enron and a
local car dealer.
</P>
<P>
   With all that to Drexler's credit, it might be well for
collegians or high school seniors to heed his advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would advise every high school senior to spend at least two
years in college,'' Drexler said. ``In high school, every hour of
your time is planned out for you. When you get to college, you have
to learn how to use your time between academics, basketball and
your social life, and that takes a lot of maturity.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Drexler's first decisions as UH coach was to ask Lewis to
return on a volunteer basis. One day last week, Lewis, 76, was back
on the Hofheinz Pavilion floor with Drexler and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enthusiasm and good feeling that Clyde has brought back to
the program is unbelievable,'' Lewis said. ``His personal
popularity says a lot about how people feel about him. I've been to
functions with him where they have stood in line for hours to get
his autograph. I tell Clyde that I'm for him 100 percent. Just
don't expect me to sit on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   As a volunteer, Lewis can't get on the floor at practice. But he
can watch and make suggestions to the staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be sitting right where I have since I retired _ on the
front row in the stands,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Drexler's coaching ability, Lewis has no doubt it will
surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clyde knows about running the floor, passing and rebounding,''
Lewis said. ``He's going to be a great communicator with his
players because they all will know the kind of player he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have players; we all know that. I have no
hesitation in saying that Clyde is going to make a great coach,
because he is going to recruit great players. I tell everybody that
is going to take time, but that doesn't mean this is going to be
just a throw-away year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
