<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARKANSAS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
A N UTT F OR T HE RAZORBACKS
<TEXT>
<P>
   With contagious enthusiasm, new coach looks to get Arkansas on
winning track
</P>
<P>
   By BILL SULLIVAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   They suggested he go directly to the fans to try to drum up
support for the next day's game, which generally wasn't the talk of
the campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked them when to come,'' Houston Nutt said. ``Say, seven
o'clock?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, no, midnight actually would be more like it, he was told.
The crowd would be its largest by then, and if you were going for
numbers
</P>
<P>
   This explains why a young head coach found himself on the roof
of a fraternity house, touting Murray State football.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one big party, and I had to make sure they were all
there,'' Nutt said with a smile. ``I didn't realize I'd have to
crawl out on the roof with a bullhorn, but it was the greatest
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next day, we had a record number students.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Nutt finds himself in a different sort of sales job.
Returning to his home state, where he remains one of the most
celebrated high school players in history, the 40-year-old Little
Rock native tries to breathe life into an Arkansas football program
reeling from consecutive 4-7 seasons under the gone-and-unlamented
Danny Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to win everywhere you go,'' said Nutt, who spent five
years at Murray State and Boise State before getting the call from
Arkansas athletic director Frank Broyles last December. ``But this
is a little more special because it's home.''
</P>
<P>
   And because it's home, Houston Nutt needs no introduction.
</P>
<P>
   Out of high school, he was one of the last players recruited by
Broyles before the coach resigned at the end of the 1976 season.
Nutt played two years in Fayetteville, but his skill as a drop-back
passer didn't fit with new coach Lou Holtz's preference for the
option and a mobile quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Nutt was part of the Orange Bowl team that shocked heavily
favored Oklahoma. He also played on the Razorbacks basketball team
with the fabled ``Triplets,'' Sidney Moncrief, Ron Brewer and
Marvin Delph.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't enough. Nutt wanted to play football and soon realized
he wouldn't be doing much of it for Holtz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough,'' he said. ``(Holtz) would get off the bus in
Little Rock, and the first thing he'd hear was, `Are you gonna play
Nutt today?'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's hard all around. We were running the veer that year,
and I was one of the slowest quarterbacks in America.''
</P>
<P>
   So Nutt left for Oklahoma State, where he played two years,
again doubling in basketball. After spending two more seasons as a
graduate assistant in Stillwater, he was invited to come back as a
graduate assistant under Holtz at Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always appreciated him doing that for me,'' Nutt said.
``When a guy leaves, sometimes there are hard feelings, and you
can't come back. Coach Holtz was great about all that.''
</P>
<P>
   After working assistant jobs at Arkansas State and Oklahoma
State, Nutt returned again to be part of Arkansas staffs from
1990-92. By then, at a career crossroads, he approached Broyles for
advice.
</P>
<P>
   Broyles told him to get a job.
</P>
<P>
   Any job.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to either be a coordinator or a head coach,'' Nutt
said. ``One of the best decisions I made was to take the Murray
State job.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk about night and day. All those years being with Barry
Sanders and Thurman Thomas and all those good players couldn't add
up to one week where you're in charge of the budget, the coaches,
the family and their lives. Every single decision comes across your
desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank those two little bitty schools for giving a little
bitty assistant a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Nutt gets the chance he really wanted at a school where the
only thing itty bitty lately has been the number under the ``W''
each fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The '90s have been tough,'' he said. ``It hasn't been much
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   To help create interest, Nutt crisscrossed the state, doing as
many speaking engagements as possible. By late July, the number of
dates had approached 80.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew there were Razorback Clubs all over the state,'' he
said. ``But it seems like there's always one more.''
</P>
<P>
   The name _ and Nutt's enthusiasm _ struck a nerve. In July,
season-ticket sales had exceeded last year's total by more than
6,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's basically stolen the hearts of everyone in Arkansas,''
senior defensive tackle Ryan Hall said. ``I'm running into people
who are saying, `We've got our season tickets. We're ready to
go.'''
</P>
<P>
   Players seem to have responded to the call, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to expect,'' Nutt said. ``Every program I'd
taken over, it seemed like there were 14 or 15 guys who didn't want
to accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nutt set the tone early, holding ``Dirty Dozen'' workouts in
January, putting his team through 12 demanding conditioning
sessions that began at 6 a.m. This summer, 73 players stayed around
to get ready for the season, as opposed to 22 the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, everyone's excited about going to practice,'' flanker
Anthony Lucas said. ``It seemed like the love for the game had
dropped for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   If the love affair continues, it might be something of a happy
accident. Mississippi coach Tommy Tuberville was the early
front-runner for the job, but Tuberville eventually pulled out of
the running.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being from Arkansas, I figured I'd be a fool if I didn't
listen,'' Tuberville said. ``But they hired an excellent guy in
Houston Nutt. It was fun talking to them, but we both ended up
where we needed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   If Nutt felt snubbed by the perception that he was a second
choice, he keeps it to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that I'm here today to represent the
University of Arkansas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nutt realizes he'll need results to keep the good vibes going.
Turnovers (32) were a problem in 1997, and the Razorbacks, who lost
six of their last seven games, averaged a dismal 56.5 yards per
game rushing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he says, the fires are still smoldering in the Ozarks,
even if they haven't been stoked for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a little boy growing up, you know the fans are special,''
Nutt said. ``But I never dreamed they'd be this special, where
they'd buy 6,000 more season tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call it a honeymoon, whatever. I feel an awesome
responsibility to the fans who are going out on a limb, not waiting
to see what this guy can do.''
</P>
<P>
   At home, you might be on a different sort of limb, but at least
you don't have to crawl out on any rooftops to get attention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
