<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADDUX ON ROPES, BUT BRAVES SURVIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For Greg Maddux, it was the worst game of his career.
For Carlos Perez, it was business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   But Maddux was the winning pitcher Sunday in the Atlanta Braves'
12-7 victory over the Dodgers despite getting shelled for
back-to-back homers and three overall. He had never done that
before.
</P>
<P>
   Perez's fifth start since joining the Dodgers after a July 31
trade from Montreal was another beating that is starting to worry
the club. He was brought in to stabilize a starting rotation that
has been rocked by injury and ineffectiveness but has been more of
a problem than the solution.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did he allow nine hits and eight earned runs in less
than four innings, he seemed bent on throwing fastballs to fastball
hitters instead of the well-placed changeups that made him so
attractive less than a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about the control,'' manager Glenn Hoffman said
after Perez (7-13) walked four. ``And it's not just the walks, it's
the location of the pitches. They just haven't been there.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Dodger he has 16 walks in 281/3 innings pitched with a 6.35
ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman wouldn't speculate on what will happen when Ismael
Valdes returns to the starting rotation in a week or so. Valdes
injured his right index finger Saturday and during a rehab start in
Florida and won't be back Thursday as the club had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got time to think about that,'' Hoffman said. ``I still
have to think about this game. Once I get back to the hotel, I'll
think about tomorrow's game.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot to consider. On a night they could have picked up
a game in their fading wild-card hopes, the Dodgers hit three
homers and lost. Two were hit by Eric Karros, who also had a double
off Maddux. The 10 total bases by Karros is believed to be the most
by one player off Maddux in the career of the four-time Cy Young
Award winner.
</P>
<P>
   It also was just the second time Maddux had allowed seven earned
runs in a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I would rather have gone 0 for 4 and won,'' said Karros,
who entered the game 2 for 27 lifetime against Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers trail the Mets with just 32 games left and face
16-game winner Tom Glavine today in the season finale with the
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are still having this conversation in a week,'' everyone
will know our situation,'' Karros said. ``Every game makes it
tougher. It will be more improbable, but still not impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux, who pitched seven scoreless innings against the Dodgers
in a May 6 victory here, clearly was the not the same pitcher who
has dominated the National League the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   He was spotted a 4-0 lead after one inning on a pair of two-run
homers by Andres Galarragea and Eddie Perez off Perez (7-13).
</P>
<P>
   But the first batter Maddux faced in the second inning, Gary
Sheffield, hit the first pitch into the left-field stands for his a
21st homer.
</P>
<P>
   Karros was next and hit a rare drive to right that landed
several rows back in the bleachers. It cut Maddux's lead to 4-3,
and though the Braves added a run in the second, it hardly was the
end of his trouble with Karros.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi opened the third with a single to left and
Sheffield walked. It was Maddux's second of the game, which was a
tip things weren't right. He entered the game with 29 walks in 27
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Then Karros hit his 17th homer. His five RBI give him 71 for the
season and an outside chance to reach 100 for the fourth
consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   But by that time, the Braves had routed Perez, who was gone
after allowing three more runs in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that Perez walked Maddux to open the inning. Or
that he was hurt when Mark Grudzielanek bobbled Gerald Williams
grounder for hit and Bobby Bonilla misplayed Chipper Jones grounder
for an error.
</P>
<P>
   But Galarraga did the real damage with RBI single that chased
Perez. His replacement rookie right-hander Sean Maloney immediately
gave up an RBI single to right, but struck out Perez and retired
Danny Bautista to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Bautista got back at the Dodgers in the sixth when he doubled
home Chipper Jones against Antonio Osuna to give the Braves their
11th run. Jones singled home Williams, who opened the inning with a
triple to the gap in right-center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
