<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S WIN AGAIN; ONE-RUN SPREE AT THREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Every time Paul Spoljaric makes another start, he
makes it look like he belongs in the Mariners' rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has found his niche,'' Mariner pitching coach Stan Williams
said.
</P>
<P>
   On a day Ken Griffey Jr. rediscovered his home run trot and
Shane Monahan homered for the second time this season, the Mariners
hopped aboard the pitching of Spoljaric and relievers Bobby Ayala
and Jose Paniagua to defeat the Chicago White Sox 3-2 Sunday before
35,159 fans at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   The M's have won three straight, all by one run after starting
the series 4-20 in one-run games.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's 43rd homer of the season _ his second in August _ was
a two-run bullet into the second deck in right field that pulled
Seattle into a 2-2 standoff in the fourth inning. Monahan's blast
to right-center, also off losing pitcher John Snyder, came in the
fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Both of Monahan's homers have won games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking `three' (triple) when I hit it,'' the left
fielder said. ``I don't have the kind of power to know when a ball
is going out. I thought it would hit the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoljaric said he ``hit the wall'' in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   A reliever most of his professional career, the left-hander
moved into the starting rotation on Aug. 2, three days after the
M's traded Randy Johnson to the Houston Astros. Spoljaric has been
building confidence and stamina ever since. The seven innings he
pitched Sunday in his fourth start represent a personal
long-distance record. He hadn't gone more than five innings in his
previous starts.
</P>
<P>
   Spoljaric said he was ``pretty much done'' after seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   When Williams went the mound to check on his pitcher, the fans
noticed Ayala warming up in the bullpen. They wanted Spoljaric to
stay in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to give him a little break and ask how he
felt,'' Williams said. ``I could tell he was getting tired. His
breaking ball was rolling and there wasn't as much zip on his
fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   But with two outs and two on, Spoljaric stayed in the game. He
fell behind in the count 2-and-0 to Chad Kreuter before retiring
the Sox catcher and ex-Mariner on a shallow fly ball to Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala pitched a spotless eighth inning, and Paniagua finished up
for his first career save, dodging a two-out walk and wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Timlin, the usual closer, wasn't available because he had
pitched in three straight games, including a two-inning outing
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua's save secured Spoljaric's fourth win, his first as a
starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is really settling down as a starter and throwing the ball
well,'' manager Lou Piniella said. ``When we got him (from Toronto
last season), we thought he could be productive as a starter, but
we signed Bill Swift during spring training and we already had
three lefties in the rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's trade created an opening and Spoljaric moved right in.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just seems more relaxed and has better tempo as a starter
and has been a blessing in disguise,'' Piniella said of Spoljaric.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the plan is to keep Spoljaric in the rotation,
even when Freddy Garcia and Brett Hinchliffe are promoted from
Class AAA Tacoma early next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of our five (starters),'' Williams said of Spoljaric,
who says he prefers starting over relieving. ``Even after we make
the (roster additions), we'll basically stay with our regular
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The third game in the four-game series took only 2 hours and 3
minutes to play, the Mariners' fastest game of the season. Each
starter allowed only three hits.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the six were home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Wil Cordero cracked a leadoff homer in the third inning as the
Sox took a 1-0 lead. Chicago then made it 2-0 on the first of two
errors by Mariner third baseman Russ Davis (extending his
club-record to 33), a stolen base, catcher Joe Oliver's throwing
error and a single by Mike Caruso that nearly beaned Spoljaric.
</P>
<P>
   It stayed that way until the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Cora, extending his hitting streak to nine games, became
the Mariners' first baserunner with a single to right. One out
later, Griffey ended a streak of 32 homerless at-bats with a
no-doubt-about-it blast to right.
</P>
<P>
   Although Griffey has been in a power drought, he still has more
home runs after 128 games this season than he did last season, when
he had 40 on this date en route to a career-high 56.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to see him hit one out, and we need for him to get
hot _ and I don't mean hitting home runs,'' Piniella said. ``We
also need to get David (Segui) going again.''
</P>
<P>
   Segui, the Mariner first baseman, went 0-for-3 and is 8-for-50
since missing four games with an injured right knee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 0142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
