<DOCNO> NYT19980824.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8336 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI &LR;      08-24 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOON IMPRESSIVE AFTER PRESEASON WAKEUP CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ He had called the plays, taken the snaps, made
the handoffs and thrown those laser-beam passes it seems only he
can throw.
</P>
<P>
   But there was one thing Warren Moon had not experienced since
ending his 25-day holdout and resuming control of the Seahawks'
offense: Contact.
</P>
<P>
   Until, that is, the second play of Saturday night's preseason
game against the Arizona Cardinals at Sun Devil Stadium. After
dumping a pass to running back Ricky Watters, Moon was leveled by
the Cardinals' Simeon Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Rice was penalized 15 yards for roughing the passer, but Moon
felt like thanking the 260-pound defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got introduced to the preseason right away,'' Moon said.
``That's what you need to let you know the season is here. I got
knocked on the ground and that kind of wakes you up and says,
`Let's get going.'''
</P>
<P>
   Moon got off his rear and pushed the offense into high gear.
Before calling it a night, he completed 8 of 15 passes for 202
yards, including touchdown passes of 69 yards to Joey Galloway and
55 yards to James McKnight. All in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   It was his first game action since the team's season finale
against the San Francisco 49ers last Dec. 21. He made it look easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's easy, but it's natural for me,'' Moon
said. ``I just look at it as being natural. Those practices this
week really helped me as far as getting my sharpness back and
seeing things that you need to see. When you recognize the things
you need to see, then your natural ability is going to take over.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon was a few phases shy of perfect and was the first to admit
it. He had two passes go off the hands of Cardinals defenders and
another go off the chest of McKnight that was intercepted, and he
could have had two more TD passes by making the proper reads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't make those and that means there's some room for
improvement,'' Moon said. ``Overall, I thought my performance was
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   But considering that he was playing after practicing just six
times last week, the effort against the Cardinals was a giant step
in the right direction for Moon and the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warren executed extremely well,'' coach Dennis Erickson said
Sunday after reviewing video of the 31-24 victory. ``He made a
couple of mistakes. ... Other than that, he played pretty
flawlessly, really.''
</P>
<P>
   The longest completion to a wide receiver in the first three
games was a 25-yarder to Mike Pritchard, and the longest pass play
was a 30-yarder to Watters that was more run-after-the-catch than
pass. Saturday night, Moon went to Pritchard for 26 yards on his
first completion and then had the bombs to McKnight and Galloway.
</P>
<P>
   Moon passed for 202 yards on just eight completions against a
Cardinals defense that, while not exactly the 49ers, had held its
first two opponents to an average of 163.5 yards passing for the
entire game while allowing only one TD pass. Moon completed five of
his first eight passes for 104 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't sure what was going to happen,'' offensive
coordinator Bob Bratkowski said. ``To step right in and play after
a week of practice is not easy. There were some plays we ran that
Warren hadn't even practiced this week. To his credit, he just let
it rip.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon's final tuneup for the Sept. 6 regular-season opener in
Philadelphia will come Friday night against the 49ers at the
Kingdome. How much Moon and the No. 1 offense will play has yet to
be determined, but it probably won't be more than three or four
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warren and I will talk (today). We just need to get a feel for
what he thinks he needs,'' Erickson said. ``Obviously I wouldn't
play him unless the whole first unit was in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon got plenty of help from his friends against the Cardinals.
The offensive linemen not only protected him well _ especially
tackles Walter Jones and Howard Ballard against the Cardinals' Rice
and Eric Swann _ they also got Watters untracked early to help set
up the deep throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last touchdown was a play-action pass, and the way we were
running the ball they had to respect the run,'' guard Pete Kendall
said. ``Those long touchdowns are nice. They count for seven on the
scoreboard, but it doesn't take as much out of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon's best throw was one even his teammates didn't think he
could make _ the 69-yard post pattern to Galloway, who beat
cornerback J.J. McCleskey and then used an explosive burst to blow
past free safety Kwamie Lassiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Joey take off and I thought, `Oh, man. Joey's just
outrun another quarterback,''' Kendall said. ``There aren't many in
the league who can get him that ball, but Warren did. He hit Joey
in stride.''
</P>
<P>
   It just goes to show that Moon _ even at 41, especially at 41 _
is not just another quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``That pass was Exhibit 9,000, right there,'' Kendall said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
