   FILM-PRODUCER-MEDIA (New York) _ Tracey Trench has followed the
unlikeliest of career paths to emerge as the kind of person who can
be trusted to get a picture made on a tight budget. By Linda Lee.
(With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   TECH-BANKING (Philadelphia) _ Earlier this decade, bankers and
software developers looked ahead eagerly to 1998 and 1999 as the
period when electronic banking would evolve from a niche business
to a ubiquitous service, saving financial institutions millions of
dollars in transaction costs. Instead, it is proving to be the era
of megamergers and millennium preparation, two issues that have
distracted software and system developers and have, for the time
being anyway, delayed consumer banking via personal computers. By
David J. Wallace. (With graphic and photo.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ In a volatile economy, analysts
say, newspaper industry stocks tend to be like the canary in the
mine, singing their hearts out while the air smells sweet, and
keeling over at the first couple of sniffs of toxic economic fumes.
This spring and summer have tended to bolster that notion. By
Felicity Barringer. (With graphic.)
