<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8349 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOICE-VARIETY-875&AMP;ADD     08-24 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOICE-VARIETY-875&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANESTHETIZED BY THE STEADY, THE SUAVE AND THE PERKY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MARGO JEFFERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I firmly believe that the Internet expands our curiosities and
capacities for written language. That's the fun of it all: the
linguistic roles and disguises to be taken on, the words to be
coined, the strategies to be used according to site and
circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   But pity the human voice, for its range diminishes every day.
And don't blame computers; this has been going on for decades. So
much of our media define authority as vocal conformity and ignore
shifts in the culture's needs; much of the media industry still
depends on vocal styles that have been stripped of emotional
content, and much of it presumes that the only way to reach the
widest audience is to give us vocal stereotypes that hit our brains
and feelings like stun guns.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to television broadcasters as they apply a
half-century-old bag of vocal tricks to international bombings,
sexual trysts and human interest stories. The men must have voices
that are stern and deep; no tenors here, everyone is or pretends to
be a take-it-on-the-chin baritone. And those voices must issue
forth from mouths that barely move: a firm jaw means a firm hold on
the facts, even when those facts are actually opinions or leading
questions. Sam Donaldson bites off his words to convey scrappy
tenacity. Dan Rather spaces his firmly and evenly: there is steel
beneath that steadiness. And Ted Koppel uses the most vibrato and
the most stately pacing of the three, a style meant to suggest that
he is the most statesmanlike of journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Women tend to follow the same guidelines if they are local
reporters or national correspondents. But if they are stars like
Barbara Walters, Diane Sawyer or Katie Couric, they occupy a
feminized space where the interviewer-commentator is also a
hostess, a gracious facilitator determined to make us comfortable
with everything from hard news to celebrity musings.
</P>
<P>
   Let's square our shoulders and toughen up, the male voices
signal, however minor the story. I know it's upsetting, but we'll
be all right, the women's voices signal, however major the story.
Ms. Walters pioneered this style with her suave, solicitous tones
and ``womanly'' vibrato (replaced by girlish hesitancy when she
asks an intimate or trivial question). Ms. Sawyer has perfected a
crafty mass-market version of that ancient court ideal, the voice
that is ``ever soft,/Gentle and low, an excellent thing in woman.''
And Ms. Couric is the perky cheerleader and Pep Club president who
many parents must still want their daughters to be.
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream television entertainment rarely goes after dramatic,
comedic or vocal richness. Shows give us fixed settings, situations
and characters who are supposed to become as familiar to us as our
friends and families. Good television actors have (or use) just
enough range to produce a highly artificial version of naturalistic
speech. We grow attached to their unchanging conversational tics
and timbres. But what's most naturalistic is that they use more
craft to show no more range or depth than most of us have.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the best television dramas give actors more emotional
and vocal chances than they used to. Compare monotoned Ben Casey
and mellifluous Dr. Kildare with the doctors on ``ER.'' And the
best actors play much more interestingly. Listen to Andre Braugher
on reruns of ``Homicide,'' the texture of his voice and the diction
shifts. Listen to the cast of ``The Practice,'' with their clash of
pitches, accents and pacing. (Camryn Manheim, Steve Harris and
Dylan McDermott give me particular pleasure.)
</P>
<P>
   Television comedies just keep deteriorating. Except for
dizzyingly uneven late-night variety shows like ``Saturday Night
Live,'' most are vocally and to my mind comically stupefying. Tim
Allen and Kirstie Alley versus Drew Carey and Fran Drescher? What
are we talking about _ gamuts of A to B versus A to C?
</P>
<P>
   There has been a lot of justified talk about the cynically bad
level of black sitcoms. But compare them with the average white
ones, and the difference comes down to one of careless rather than
careful cynicism. The first kind is based on contempt; the second
on knowing smugness. Speechwise, it is the difference between
ebonic trash and standardized tripe.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment that was never intended to be good is infuriating.
But entertainment that once was and is no more is unspeakably
depressing, too. When I turn on the radio and listen to what passes
for soul music now, I'm astonished. Compared with its predecessors,
your average hit today sounds about as soulful as Pat Boone or Gogi
Grant sounded compared with Little Richard and LaVern Baker. Listen
to Sam Cooke or Marvin Gaye, then to Luther Vandross or Babyface.
Listen to the young Aretha Franklin versus Whitney Houston or
Mariah Carey.
</P>
<P>
   Where did this glut of melisma come from _ sometimes murky and
dank, sometimes high-pitched and preening? What do these bogus
little moans and cries signify in terms of feeling? Diana Ross had
a limited voice, but it had its own sassy little sound, and she
could phrase with charm. Janet Jackson's voice is a tiny cipher
that could be filled with Monica's voice or Brandy's voice, or that
of many other one-name, one-note singers. (The note? High, breathy
and coy.)
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   They say people get the rulers they deserve, and we could say
the same for journalists and entertainers. But how dreary to have
our sense of reality and possibility, not to mention pleasure, so
censored and constricted. I have been reading a wonderful book
called ``Freeing Shakespeare's Voice,'' by the voice teacher, actor
and director Kristin Linklater. It is meant to help guide actors
through the linguistic and emotional extremities of Shakespeare,
but it can be read by anyone who loves and therefore admits no
impediment to the marriage of voice, speech and song.
</P>
<P>
   How did speech begin, Ms. Linklater asks? Might it have been as
open-throated grunts and groans that dealt with life and death? She
writes: ``The quantum leap (or crawl) in the evolution of speech,
if speech began thus, was articulation, and the agents that
articulated, interrupted and shaped the flow of roaring sound were
parts of the mouth which had hitherto been used for
appetite-related functions: chewing, biting, licking, sucking.
Appetite and communication presumably occupied the same brain cells
until the tongue, the teeth and the lips were fully adapted to new
demands. Taste, smell and texture _ pleasure, desire and
satisfaction _ must have permeated the process of speech for
thousands of years. Speaking would have been on a par with sex and
eating _ an extreme experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, we're not likely to get these extremes every day, even
in private, nor do we need them. But we need so much more than
we're being given. We have never had more access to cultural
information and material of every kind. And our speech connects
less and less to it. Vocal malnourishment hurts body, brain and
soul. We are starving in the midst of plenty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
