<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8375 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-COMPTON-NYT &LR;      08-24 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COMPTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSPLANT RECIPIENT TEES IT UP IN AMATEUR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. _ Erik Compton, the nation's top-ranked junior
golfer, may never know the identity of the person whose heart beats
in his body. ``Whoever is with me, I'm taking them for a ride,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Compton, an 18-year-old from Miami, is the sentimental favorite
at the U.S. Amateur Championship, which begins Monday here at Oak
Hill Country Club. He is the first heart transplant recipient to
qualify for the event, amateur golf's most prestigious tournament,
but he has already earned distinction far beyond his medical
chart. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He has captured two of junior golf's majors _ the Rolex Junior
Championship in 1997 and the Pine Isle Championship earlier this
year _ and he has finished in the top three in the last nine
national junior tournaments. Compton hopes to play professionally,
but first he will attend the University of Georgia on a
scholarship, beginning next month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Compton sat in the deserted Oak Hill bowling alley Saturday
morning, reflecting on his fortune. He spent the critical years
after his transplant at age 12 trying to hide his history. Now he
is at peace with being known as the golfer with the heart
transplant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I'm going to have to deal with for the rest of
my life,'' he said. ``If I play golf and I play well, it makes a
better story.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Compton's mother, Eli, said later, ``Once he got to be No. 1,
then it was OK, because he made it without the transplant being
mentioned.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Compton was a sports-obsessed 9-year-old when he went for a
routine examination. The doctor listened to Compton's heart and
called in two more doctors to listen. Then two more doctors showed
up. They excused Compton and called in his mother. ``I knew
something was wrong,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next day came the diagnosis: He had dilated congestive
cardiomyopathy, an enlarging of the heart that hinders its ability
to pump blood. Compton needed a transplant, and he would have to
cease all athletic activity while he waited. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the worst thing you could say to me because all I did
was play sports,'' he said. ``I didn't believe it. I pretended it
wasn't happening, and I would run around and play and get myself
sick and exert myself to the point I was throwing up and seeing
white spots.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pierine, a Miami suburb, launched several fund-raisers, but
Compton's heart was functioning at 65 percent capacity, relegating
him to low priority on the transplant list. Three years later, his
heart had dipped below 30 percent function and time was running
out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Compton's legs fidgeted and his blue eyes looked far away as he
recalled Feb. 26, 1992. ``It's my new birthday,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A phone ringing woke him around midnight. Compton said he knew
right away and walked into the kitchen to face his father, Peter.
``It's time, right?'' the boy asked. The father nodded. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As he was being wheeled into surgery, Compton could hear the
helicopter carrying the car-crash victim's heart landing on the
hospital roof. His chances of surviving the surgery ranged between
50 and 60 percent, according to his mother, now the head of an
organ-donor agency. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're 12, you don't realize the consequences,'' Compton
said. ``That's why it was a gift from God that I had the transplant
early on in life, because at this age I don't know if I could
handle it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Compton said one of his first post-surgical memories was of
watching a golf tournament on television and becoming frustrated by
a golfer's inability to hit straight. Six months later, Compton,
pumped by anti-rejection drugs that made him ``look like an egg
with pencil sticks for legs and a big head,'' walked on to a golf
course to see if he could do better.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How he got there is another story. The Comptons' house was blown
away by Hurricane Andrew in 1992, and the family relocated to an
apartment in a country club. There he took lessons, grew stronger
and began to pursue golf seriously. At 15, he shot a 7-under-par
65. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 5-foot-8-inches and 135 pounds, Compton relies on steadiness.
``The way Erik plays is not where he's going to make 80-foot
putts,'' said Hank Amundson, Compton's caddy and a childhood
friend. ``He's not extremely weak or strong in anything. It's more
of a complete, consistent game.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And Compton is rarely rattled. ``Going through all that he has,
has created a pretty solid base to handle certain situations,''
Amundson said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Compton's physical resilience continues to improve. He still
takes medication to safeguard against his body rejecting the heart,
but his chances for long-term survival improve with each day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Compton exchanged letters with the donor's family for a while
without knowing the family's name because of confidentiality
considerations. But lately the correspondence has ceased. Their
last letter, Compton recalled, his voice cracking, said, ``Have a
good life.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Compton took a moment to collect himself. ``I try not to focus
too much on it,'' he said. ``I have to live my life and go on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
