<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-HUSKEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKEY SUFFERS A SETBACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Butch Huskey returned to New York Sunday, but it was
a setback rather than a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Huskey's rehabilitation from the strained left hamstring that
has sidelined him since Aug. 3 was placed on hold Sunday. After
playing two games with the Class AAA Norfolk Tides on Friday and
Saturday, he was feeling too much pain to continue, and the Mets
decided that he should return to New York and work on strengthening
the muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a major setback,'' Mets General Manager Steve
Phillips said. ``We're setting off his rehab right now. I talked to
him and he said he had pain coming out of the batter's box. He's
swinging the bat fine. It doesn't hurt him to swing. But getting
out the batter's box, he cannot go 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Huskey was successful swinging the bat with the Tides, rapping
three hits and driving in three runs in his two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought rather than risk doing something where there is
pain, we'd back him off until he's pain-free,'' Phillips said. ``We
knew when he initially injured it that it was a different injury
than the normal hamstring, because it was at the muscle-tendon
junction and there's less blood flow there, so it takes a longer
time to heal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
