<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILD-ABUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN ARRESTED AFTER GIRL, 5, IS FOUND SCALDED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police arrested a 35-year-old man Monday morning
after a 5-year-old Brooklyn girl in his care was found severely
scalded, unconscious and suffering from brain injuries Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   As of early Monday morning, no specific charges had been filed
against the man, Terrence Finney, 35, of 68 Fountain Avenue in the
East New York section.
</P>
<P>
   But Officer George Jensen, a spokesman for the Police
Department, said the charges would likely include assault and
endangering the welfare of a child.
</P>
<P>
   The mother, whose name was not released, was not charged.
</P>
<P>
   The child was in extremely critical condition Monday morning at
Brookdale Hospital Medical Center with brain injuries and severe
burns.
</P>
<P>
   There were also indications that the girl may have been the
victim of sexual abuse, said Detective Robert Samuel, a Police
Department spokesman, but specific details were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-year-old, together with her four siblings, was supposed to
have been in Finney's care Sunday afternoon while the mother went
to church.
</P>
<P>
   But when the mother returned to the apartment about 2 p.m., she
found the girl, her body scalded by hot water, and called 911, said
Samuel.
</P>
<P>
   The police later found the boyfriend and the other four children
at an unspecified location away from the apartment in a two-story,
two-family home, Samuel said. The four children, ages 5 to 11, did
not appear to be harmed.
</P>
<P>
   The four siblings, meanwhile, have been transferred to the
custody of the city's Administration for Children's Services,
Jensen said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors performed brain surgery on the 5-year-old to relieve
pressure caused by bleeding in the brain, said a hospital official
who spoke on condition of anonymity. The girl also had severe burns
on her face and torso, but no determination had been made on
whether skin grafts would be necessary, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately known what caused the hemorrhage, but it
was possible that the injuries were caused by a blow to the head,
extreme scalding or a combination of both, the hospital official
said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no preliminary word on whether the mother or her
boyfriend have a criminal record or a record with the
Administration for Children's Services.
</P>
<P>
   But, as is standard procedure in cases of suspected child abuse,
the Children's Services agency was also investigating the case
Sunday night, said Leonora Weiner, a spokeswoman for the agency.
</P>
<P>
   She said the agency was trying to determine who would take over
care of the four children .
</P>
</TEXT>
