<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8402 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-STANTON-NYT     08-24 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-STANTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITTING CAN'T MASK PITCHING INCONSISTENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Mike Stanton, a former football player from
West Texas, was in a destructive mood when he returned to the
clubhouse Saturday night after giving up back-to-back home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Even in his fury, however, Stanton managed to joke a bit with
David Cone, who had also pitched poorly. They won in spite of us,
Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius hit a three-run homer in the eighth inning off
John Wetteland, the Texas closer, to drive the Yankees to a crazy
12-9 victory Saturday night. Ryan Bradley, whom the Yankees drafted
in 1997 with a compensation selection they received because
Wetteland signed with the Rangers, pitched one and two-thirds
innings to get his first major-league victory in his first
major-league appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees moved closer to 100 victories, to clinching a
playoff spot before the end of August; their magic number for
qualifying for the postseason stood at eight, going into Sunday
night's game.
</P>
<P>
   But Yankees Manager Joe Torre would probably trade that victory
for some assurance that Stanton can resolve his inconsistency
before the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   He did not get it Sunday night. Stanton entered in the sixth
inning, with the Yankees trailing 7-6, and proceeded to give up a
four-pitch walk and a single before being removed. Bradley then
came in and gave up four more hits and a walk, as the Rangers
increased their lead to 12-6 in a game they eventually won, 12-10.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Torre met with Stanton. ``We're going to get it
straightened out,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Stanton: ``The way I feel right now, this is my loss. We
lost by two runs, I gave up two runs. I don't have any
explanations. I don't have any excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   With a month to go before the playoffs, the Yankees' middle
relief is something of a mess.
</P>
<P>
   The odds of the right-hander Jeff Nelson recovering from back
trouble are about 50-50, and there's no telling how effective he
might be after missing more than two months.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton has an 8.19 earned run average over his last 24
appearances. And he isn't quite sure why. His velocity is good;
it's not as though the quality of his stuff is in question.
</P>
<P>
   But his results over the last four months, Stanton said before
Sunday night's game, are unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, lately this team has won more despite
me than because of me,'' Stanton said. ``There's no reason I should
be getting hit like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre theorized that Stanton might simply be losing the movement
on his fastball by trying too hard and by overthrowing.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton can be dominant for a month or two and then ineffective
for a time. ``I've had stretches before in my career,'' he said.
``But not this prolonged, and I would say not this frustrating. I
feel like I was throwing pretty well, but when I give someone a
pitch to hit, they hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, Stanton pitched in relief of Cone, whose control
failed him; he allowed six runs over his five and two-thirds
innings, but nonetheless left the game with a 7-6 lead and a chance
for his 19th victory.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton pulled the Yankees through the sixth and they scored
another run in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   But Rusty Greer singled to lead off the seventh and Juan
Gonzalez hit a low forkball for a two-run homer to tie the score
before Will Clark homered on Stanton's next pitch to give Texas a
9-8 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton was finished for the night, and according to others, he
was apoplectic.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius saved him from a measure of angst, however. Tino
Martinez and Chad Curtis hit singles in the eighth inning, and
Johnny Oates, the Texas manager, called for Wetteland to face
Brosius with two outs. Brosius couldn't remember facing Wetteland
before; maybe in Class AAA, he thought.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland threw a fastball and Brosius reached out and drove the
ball to right, where it cleared the wall by a foot or so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
