<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRONX-FIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRES ARE BLOW TO THE BRONX AS IT TRIES TO LURE BUSINESSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jose Lozano spent Sunday with his son, Tomas Diaz,
and 4-year-old grandson, Frayme, picking through the charred
remains of his auto body shop on Webster Avenue in the Bronx. Not
far from there, on East 170th Street, shoppers expecting to find
discounts on back-to-school outfits at Kids Town or Jimmy Jazz
instead encountered the wreckage of another devastating fire.
</P>
<P>
   And over at Southern Boulevard and Boston Road, Sunday services
took place as usual at the Mision de Dios Pentecostal Church, which
was rebuilt after a fire in May. But rubble was all that remained
of the five other businesses that had burned.
</P>
<P>
   For a few years, politicians and Bronx boosters have been
boasting about the rebuilding of the borough, which has seen more
than 30,000 homes and $2.5 billion in new construction in the last
decade. That, they said, finally repaired the damage done in the
1970s and early 1980s, when arson obliterated whole neighborhoods
and made the South Bronx infamous around the world as a symbol for
urban decay.
</P>
<P>
   But now, at a time when officials are trying to lure businesses
back to the borough, eight major fires in the last six months have
destroyed more than two dozen small businesses and indirectly hurt
many others, mostly in the South Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   No one has died in the eight unrelated fires, save the puppies,
parakeets and other animals killed when a pet shop was leveled in
the Throgs Neck section on Feb. 8. And all but two fires that are
still under investigation have been ruled accidental.
</P>
<P>
   But the fires have rekindled memories of an era when the skyline
was ablaze day and night, and when investors, like residents, were
in full flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in those days, there were fires everywhere in the
Bronx,'' recalled Gustavo Guerra, 40, a mechanic at Lozano's shop,
El Che's Body Repair, on Webster Avenue near 166th Street in the
Morrisania section. ``Now, it seems like there's a fire here almost
every day,'' he went on, pointing every which way: ``Here, there,
there-there-there.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, while they had no statistics available Sunday, Fire
Department officials said that the seeming outbreak of burning
businesses did not begin to approach the activity seen in the
1970s, when a city policy that provided housing for residents
displaced by fire prompted many to burn themselves out of their own
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember when I was a captain in a battalion then,
standing on a rooftop and seeing two or three multiple-alarm fires
going at the same time within a mile from me,'' said First Deputy
Fire Commissioner William Feehan.
</P>
<P>
   As for fires at businesses, he said, ``We probably had eight
taxpayer fires a week back then.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York City parlance, ``taxpayers'' are one-story
commercial buildings, usually constructed on the cheap by property
owners hoping to recover just enough in rent to pay their real
estate taxes. And the Bronx seems to have more of them than any
other borough, Feehan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taxpayer fires in the Bronx have been the bane of this
department's existence for decades,'' he said. ``Most of them are
quite old, and there'll be a cockloft between the ceiling and the
roof board that extends over several shops. Often the partition
walls extend only up to the ceiling, so the fire'll spread through
the cockloft, right down the block.''
</P>
<P>
   Worse, many of the businesses that go up in flames are filled
with combustible material like oil, gas or propane tanks, he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The four-alarm fire Friday morning at East 170th Street and
Walton Avenue, for example, began when workers who were building a
second floor atop the Jimmy Jazz and Kids Town stores accidentally
set off an explosion with a welder's torch, said Hermes Caraballa,
an official in the Bronx borough president's office. More than 50
people were evacuated from an adjacent apartment building as the
fire burned for more than four hours, and eight firefighters were
treated for minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Gas and telephone service still had not been restored Sunday to
several neighboring buildings.
</P>
<P>
   On Webster Avenue Sunday, Lozano was busy trying to salvage a
compressor or two from among the oily black ash and the briar patch
of jagged metal where his 12-year-old body shop had stood.
</P>
<P>
   The fire there, which also consumed a travel agency and a
transmission shop, began Aug. 16, when a can of gasoline spilled at
a 24-hour garage a few doors down, Lozano said. Rather than throw
sand on the gasoline, someone hosed it down with water, he said _ a
dangerous mistake. The water and gasoline spread underneath a hot
water tank, where it was ignited by a pilot light.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never even got a chance to use their fire
extinguishers,'' Lozano said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
