<HEADER>
A8447 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEOWN-KEOWN-SFCHRON-4     08-24 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEOWN-KEOWN-SFCHRON-49ERS </SLUG>
  
 3 RECEIVERS ARE HUNGRY FOR WORK  &HT;     By TIM KEOWN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; The 49ers say there will be plenty of receptions to go around
this year, which means enough for the statistics to accumulate fast
enough for three egos to remain soothed. And without drawing too
fine a point on anything that happens before school starts, the
49ers might want to hope they're right.
</P>
<P>
   To look at it another way, they probably don't want to see what
happens if they're wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was raised Sunday after Terrell Owens went through the
Miami Dolphins' defense as if it wasn't there, and most of the
afternoon it wasn't. He came out of the game with seven receptions,
142 yards, three touchdowns and an odd end-zone dance. The dance
included a hand-waving gesture indicating something down there
stunk; it might have been the Dolphins' secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Owens has spent the first four games of the virtual season
working on his telepathy skills with Steve Young. It worked Sunday,
especially on a 72-yard touchdown that must have been harder than
it looked. In fact, Owens might have exerted more energy dancing in
the end zone than he did getting there in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people look at me to be like Jerry Rice, to get in
the end zone and act like I've been there before,'' Owens said.
``At some point in my career I'll incorporate that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice is watching this from the sideline, reluctantly and against
his wishes. In two weeks, he'll be off restriction and on the
field, along with Owens and J.J. Stokes. Owens doesn't consider
himself a second option, Stokes isn't interested in being a decoy
and everyone knows what Rice will expect when he returns.
</P>
<P>
   This, however, the 49ers see as a good thing. One look at the
excruciating performance of the team's second- and third-teamers is
enough to make them be thankful for depth, wherever it might be.
</P>
<P>
   Young says Rice ``is sulking because he's not on the field. J.J.
is sulking because he's not making big plays. I love that. We're
going to be explosive.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of equal distribution is gaining support across party
lines, and while it sounds good and teamlike and all that, it also
includes an element of necessity. By the early looks we've had of
the running game, the passing game is going to be carrying all the
dressers and sectionals.
</P>
<P>
   Last season Young became discouraged with Steve Mariucci's
insistence on the running game. This season Mariucci promised Young
an offense that would rip at the seams, with runs and passes
merging in seamless gulps of yardage.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday's 21-20 loss to the Dolphins included 276 yards
passing and 50 rushing. The yards-per-carry average of 2.1 was
bloated; Young ran three times for 17 yards to pad the running
stats. It was shades of the good old days, when Young running for
his life was the 49ers' idea of a diverse offense.
</P>
<P>
   But before we get too far down this road, a word from Young:
``Don't fret over the preseason too much. It's never as bad as it
looks or as good as it looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Young's final pass was a touchdown over the middle to Owens, who
covered 26 yards compared to zero for the Dolphins' secondary. At
the end of the play, Young banged his throwing hand on a defensive
player's helmet and stood on the sideline with it wrapped in ice
for the rest of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The game plan during the exhibition season is to get some work
in and get out _ as soon as possible, in both cases. Get your
starters into halftime with all the proper cords attached and
genuflect at your good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   The speed and passion with which the training staff descended on
Young as he left the field reinforces the contention that this is a
team being held together by slim threads.
</P>
<P>
   The one place they have depth, to return to the original
premise, is wide receiver. They don't have it on the defensive or
offensive lines, and they don't have it behind Garrison Hearst at
running back. And as for quarterback _ put it this way: Ty Detmer
and Jim Druckenmiller combined to complete 7 of 19 for 44 yards,
and the statistics look much better on paper than they did while
they were being compiled.
</P>
<P>
   (Because Druckenmiller has become the designated frog on the
dissection table during the exhibition season, he's worth further
mention. For one, he threw Sunday like an outfielder missing a
cutoff man. For another, when Mariucci was asked what it would take
for Druckenmiller to be a good NFL quarterback, he said, ``Time,
coaching, preparation, practice time, repetition ...'' In other
words, everything but taking the snap.)
</P>
<P>
   With those factors safely digested, and the memory of Sunday's
game safely tucked away in his head, Mariucci said he won't give
his starters more than a few fleeting seconds of action Friday
night in the second installment of the heated and storied Seahawks
rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   No one had to ask him why.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
