<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 03:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8448 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FBN-49ERS-SFCHRON     08-24 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FBN-49ERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 49ERS' PASSING ONLY PLUS IN LOSS  &HT;     By IRA MILLER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; The 49ers' passing game _ at least with the starters on the
field _ is ready for the regular season to begin, which should
hardly come as a surprise. When has it not been ready?
<P>
   But, aside from Steve Young's three touchdown passes to Terrell
Owens and another stout performance from new left tackle Dave
Fiore, the news from their penultimate exhibition exercise Sunday
was hardly encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   As it has been all summer, the running game, which was so good
last year, was awful. Once more, the backups looked dreadful,
blowing a 13-point second-half lead and allowing the Miami Dolphins
to escape with a 21-20 victory. Second-year quarterback Jim
Druckenmiller threw poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Also, coach Steve Mariucci passed up an opportunity to at least
get a line on what the only placekicker on the roster, John
Becksvoort, could do with a tough field-goal chance in the home
stadium _ which could mean Mariucci has decided to look elsewhere
for a kicker.
</P>
<P>
   And veteran offensive lineman Harris Barton, who has made a
marvelous comeback from four knee surgeries, suffered a sprained
ankle late in the game, complicating planning for tomorrow's first
mandatory NFL roster cutdown because Barton is the primary backup
at center. His injury, however, is not believed serious.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci took encouragement from the 20-7 lead built by the
49ers while starters from both teams were in the game. He was
pleased with the way his front-line defense held up against the
combination of Dan Marino and Miami's running game behind an
improved offensive line. But he minced no words about the 49ers'
lack of depth, which has been apparent all summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we take out our starters ... we really drop off,'' he
said. ``We've got to find some people who can help us win in those
backup spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Those starters were fine, even though &LR; ju  &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; c,12p2  &LR; Young was not at mid-season sharpness. He missed several
throws but still completed 13 of 21 for 232 yards while playing one
series into the second half. He scrambled well, directed receivers
down the field to turn at least one busted play into a 40-yard
completion to Mark Harris, and threw a TD pass on an audible.
</P>
<P>
   Young was due to go out after his one series in the third
quarter, anyway. But on his last play, a 26-yard touchdown pass to
Owens on a play Young changed at the line when he saw a blitz
coming, Young hit his passing hand on a Dolphins' helmet, bruising
it ever so slightly. He came off the field shaking the hand in the
air, and an ice pack was applied on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of 49ERS (100127 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``I'm fine,'' Young said after the game. ``It just stung. It's
absolutely not a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens, who could be ready for a breakout year, caught seven
passes for 142 yards and was Young's primary target most of the
game as J.J. Stokes drew extra coverage on the other side. Stokes
caught just four passes for 33 yards but nonetheless showed some
significant progress. For example: fighting for extra yardage and
requiring the Dolphins to gang-tackle him.
</P>
<P>
   Now, about some of those other areas:
</P>
<P>
   _The backups. The 49ers gained 255 yards on 36 offensive plays
with the starters in the game and 66 yards on 28 plays with backups
in the game. Backups on both sides were on the field, with the
49ers' defenders unable to get away from blocks, when rookie John
Avery ran 71 yards for the winning touchdown early in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   _The running game. Not counting scrambles by Young, the 49ers
rushed for 33 yards on 21 carries, an average of barely a yard and
a half. The four-game rushing average is a dismal 2.3 yards a
carry. Coaches admit they are starting to get concerned; Mariucci,
who has been trying to open up the offense this summer, said he
might need to put more emphasis on the running game again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not run the ball like we intended to last year or
hoped to this year,'' Mariucci said. ``We need to be better in our
running game. That's an absolute must.''
</P>
<P>
   _The kicking. Last week, Mariucci said he would look for chances
to try a field goal more than he might during the season. But when
the 49ers had an opportunity, on 4th-and-2 at the Miami 32-yard
line in the third quarter, he called instead for a pass.
Druckenmiller, who completed just 5 of 12 for 34 yards with an
interception, threw incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci said he didn't want Becksvoort to attempt a 50-yarder
into the wind. But for the second week in a row, he also was
critical of Becksvoort's kickoffs, principally the first of the
game when the kicker slipped and the ball traveled only to the
28-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be better in that area,'' Mariucci said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of 49ERS (100127 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Becksvoort, who said he made a 58-yarder in the same direction in
warmups (the wind changed during the game), has tried, and made,
only one field goal in four exhibition games, and that was a
31-yarder in a dome. It is known to get windy at Candlestick Point
in the fall, too, but Mariucci chose not to see what Becksvoort
could do on a field-goal attempt in those circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ready to hit that field goal if he wanted me to,''
Becksvoort said.
</P>
<P>
   From Mariucci's comments, it appears the 49ers will plan to take
a look at some other kickers who will become available this week.
All NFL teams must trim their roster to 60 players by tomorrow; for
the 49ers, that means a reduction of 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
