   NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2475 --
August 24, 1998 We are offering the following articles for sale.
Please contact us for availability your country. Best regards, Karl
Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. PRINCESS DIANA : A LOOK BACK Who could forget her? The
``people's princess,'' was a devoted mother and determined
humanitarian who died one year ago at the height of her popularity.
This cover story from Biography magazine takes a look back at the
life of Princess Diana, who felt she was just beginning to fulfill
her personal destiny. By Dorothy Rompalske. 4,000 words. 2. DUMB
DOLPHINS? SCIENTISTS NOW SAY EVEN RATS ARE SMARTER Dolphins, with
their streamlined bodies and permanent smiles, have long been
thought to be among the smartest creatures in the ocean. Stories of
drowning sailors being helped to safety by the sleek mammals are as
old as the sea. No one who has seen them perform stunts can fail to
be impressed. But scientists have now gone to the core of the
dolphin mind, minutely studying inner brain structures. The
dolphin, they conclude, is in most ways quite low in intelligence -
below even pigeons, and rats. From Der Spiegel. 800 words. (English
translation available.)
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
IRELAND'S UNCERTAIN PEACE At best, Northern Ireland was stuttering
and grumbling its way toward a highly uncertain peace. Although it
withstood one severe challenge this summer, the Omagh bombing is a
threat even more tragic and perilous. By John Lloyd. From Foreign
Affairs magazine. 1,800 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
VIAGRA AND THE WEALTH OF NATIONS Reading the headlines about
Viagra, what popped into the head of this typical, fun-loving
economist? After a series of calculations estimating the gross
domestic product and so forth, he came to realize that Viagra
signifies how economics is not about wealth - it's about the
pursuit of happiness. By Paul Krugman. From The New York Times
Magazine. 800 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
ONTOGENY RECAPITULATED Biologists are learning to turn on the genes
that make our cells young. With them, we might repair our bones,
replenish our blood, replace our limbs - and, maybe, some brain
cells too. By Gary Taubes. From Discover magazine. 1,500 words +
photos.
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   6. WHAT'S DOING IN BERLIN Berlin's physical past is being
confronted, restored, reshaped or at times obliterated to make way
for the 21st-century capital. Eve Schaenen gives tips on events,
sightseeing, hotels and restaurants in this German city. From New
York Times Way To Go! 1,500 words + photos + map. 7. TODAY'S
BLOCKBUSTER HOLLYWOOD SCRIPT FACTORY One writer adds a few jokes,
another beefs up romance, still another polishes dialogue - these
days, a big budget movie travels an ever-growing conveyor belt of
specialists to production. By Jaime Wolf. From The New York Times
Magazine. 2,000 words. 8. From NATURE NEWS SERVICE (Embargo : 18h00
GMT Wednesday August 26. N/A France and Spain.)
</P>
<P>
   A. Feminine Attractions : What is it about a face that makes it
attractive? Attraction seems to lie in features perceived as more
feminine - in males as well as females, - according to a new
report. B. Starving The Immune System : Malnutrition can kill, but
often the cause of death is an infectious disease rather than a
direct lack of nutrients. The susceptibility to infection in people
with low body weight is linked to a suppressed immune system, but
it was never clear how. A new report describes why starvation diets
have such a detrimental effect on the immune system. C. To
Canterbury, By Computer : The Canterbury Tales is a classic of
early modern English literature. Written by Geoffrey Chaucer in the
14th century, one would have thought that the text of such a
prominent work would have been settled centuries ago - but far from
it. Six hundred years later, 20th-century computing is pointing the
way towards a radical reassessment of Chaucer's work.
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
ATTACKING HIV An infectious-disease specialist at the Dana-Farber
Center Institute in Boston has created an antibody that attacks HIV
inside T cells. If the trials are successful, doctors may have a
new weapon against AIDS. By Josie Glausiusz. From Discover
magazine. 700 words + photo.
</P>
</TEXT>
