<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-SEVEN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S LIST OF CHALLENGES NEEDS SERIOUS WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My disappointment in Bill Clinton is deep and broad. How could
he? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'll tell you how: He didn't ask me. I'd have told him what the
``seven big long-term challenges'' facing the country are. Instead,
in a recent but widely ignored political speech in California, he
listed his own magnificent seven. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What a joke. Not that his list doesn't contain legitimate stuff
about which someone should worry. But his list proves he's lost
touch with the average American, who is, as you know, the American
who thinks he's above average. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is Clinton's list and my helpful thoughts about why they're
so dumb. (No need to thank me. It's my job.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``We have got to stop playing with whether we're an
isolationist power or whether we're going to lead the world for
peace and freedom and prosperity.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No nation led by a man whose list of girlfriends is longer than
the list of names in the Hope, Ark., phone book is an isolationist
anything. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``We have got to build one America across the lines the divide
us.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No, no. The lines that divide us are called borders. Borders are
good. They keep Iowa from leaking into Missouri. They keep New
Hampshire from claiming to be Vermont. They keep cartographers
employed. These lines are not a problem. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``We have got to look out for the next generation and the
implications of the retirement of the Baby Boomers.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why should we worry about people who insist they are smarter
than we are? The next generation hasn't listened to us for years.
What makes Clinton think they're about to start now? And if the
Baby Boomers want to retire, let 'em. It'll mean fewer of them on
the highways at rush hour. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``No serious person believes we have the best system of
elementary and secondary education in the world. . . Until we can
say we do, we will never be what we ought to be.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quality is fine, but if you get to be the best in the world at
something, people resent you. Why else do you think you see so many
``Yankees go home'' signs all over the world? It's because the
Yankees are, at the moment, the best in the world _ about 60 games
over .500. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``We've got to prove that we can grow the economy and improve
the environment.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No, first we've got to prove we can get back to using the word
grow correctly. But that's probably a lost cause. Bill Clinton has
been talking about how to ``grow the economy'' for so long that it
almost sounds right. Can we outgrow it? Probably not, but let's
try. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``We've got a great economic recovery, but there are places _
cities, rural areas, Indian reservations _ where there is no free
enterprise economic recovery.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cities, rural areas and reservations? That's about the whole
country. Well, wait. Maybe he means this been a recovery only for
suburban malls and small towns. And that's unfair. So let's tear
down all those dispiriting shopping centers and, instead, plant law
schools. So many lawyers are tied up working the Clinton scandals
that now there aren't enough to let Americans file all the
frivolous suits they love and that keep the economy humming along. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Finally, health care.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Health care, shmealth care. If we keep improving health care,
some day everyone will live to 110 (except Clinton, whom Hillary
may kill Jan. 21, 2001). Then we'll have to listen to a lot of
110-year-olds talk about the good old days. You know, back when
there were only seven big long-term challenges. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
