<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 09:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     08-24 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, Aug. 30.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE NAPOLEON OF CRIME: THE LIFE AND TIMES OF ADAM WORTH, MASTER
THIEF &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Ben Macintyre. Delta, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   The Victorian era's most famous crook was an ingenious
quick-change artist whose career culminated in the heist of
Gainsborough's celebrated portrait of the Duchess of Devonshire;
after his death, he was mourned by his nemesis, William Pinkerton,
as one of the ``great gentlemen thieves.'' Last year, John Mortimer
called this ``a hilarious and highly readable account.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HOTEL EDEN: STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Ron Carlson. Penguin, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   With their self-deprecating narrators and confiding tone, these
12 tales invite the reader's participation, making the frequently
farfetched scenarios _ a baseball player becomes famous by
accidentally killing 11 spectators with his hitting, for example _
believable. Even the most realistic stories, about a rafting trip
on the Green River or the sexual awakening of a college student on
summer vacation, have weird, surprising moments. Last year,
reviewer Margot Livesey admired the ``lavish imagination'' of the
author, calling him ``a master of that rarity in contemporary
fiction, the happy ending.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GLASS, PAPER, BEANS: REVELATIONS ON THE NATURE AND VALUE OF
ORDINARY THINGS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Leah Hager Cohen. Doubleday, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   Fixing her attention on her morning newspaper, her coffee and a
glass tumbler, the author explores in meticulous detail the
history, politics and economics behind these common objects, and
their hidden connections. ``After you read it, nothing ... will
seem ordinary again,'' Jeanne Schinto wrote last year. A more
cosmic look at how things tick,  &UR; THE FABRIC OF REALITY: THE SCIENCE
OF PARALLEL UNIVERSES _ AND ITS IMPLICATIONS &LR; , by David Deutsch
(Penguin, $14.95), maintains that quantum theory _ which allows for
a multitude of other universes _ is not just a measuring tool but a
serious explanation for how the world really works. The book ``is
full of refreshingly oblique, provocative insights,'' George
Johnson wrote in in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOCTOR DOGBODY'S LEG &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By James Norman Hall. Owl/Holt, $13.
</P>
<P>
   In an 18th-century British pub called the Cheerful Tortoise, a
Royal Navy surgeon spins a series of increasingly outlandish yarns,
each capped by a different version of how he lost his ``larboard''
leg. This seafaring adventure, reissued as part of the publisher's
Heart of Oak Sea Classics series, is ``about the jolliest bit of
chaff one is likely to come across in a long month of Sundays,''
Percy Hutchison wrote in 1940. Another title in the series,  &UR; THE
BLACK SHIP &LR; , by Dudley Pope ($15), is a nonfiction account of the
bloody mutiny aboard the British frigate H.M.S. Hermione in the
Caribbean in 1797, and the ship's subsequent recapture. In 1964 one
critic called this ``an exciting story'' and ``a thoughtful study
of those inexhaustible subjects, discipline and leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEXICO: BIOGRAPHY OF POWER. A HISTORY OF MODERN MEXICO,
1810-1996 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Enrique Krauze. Translated by Hank Heifetz. Harper Perennial,
$18.
</P>
<P>
   This ambitious study takes a volcanic view of Mexico's history
as a series of eruptions of its Aztec-Spanish colonial past in the
present, a connection that explains the nation's semisacred
attitudes toward authority. ``This shrewd and in many ways brave
book is necessary reading,'' Sarah Kerr wrote in 1997. Jeffery M.
Paige, the author of  &UR; COFFEE AND POWER: REVOLUTION AND THE RISE OF
DEMOCRACY IN CENTRAL AMERICA &LR;  (Harvard University, $18.95), argues
that the only way to understand Central American politics is by
focusing on the coffee-growing elites that have long dominated the
region. Last year, reviewer Thomas Carothers found the approach
limited, but said ``Paige has illuminated a path for comprehending
countries'' that are often poorly understood.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE OF THE HAPPY SHADES: AND OTHER STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Alice Munro. Vintage Contemporaries, $12.
</P>
<P>
   In this early collection of short fiction, the author focuses on
the revelatory moments that bubble up in the lives of farmers and
townspeople in southwestern Ontario. ``Munro poses more questions
than answers _ a refreshing strategy,'' Martin Levin wrote here in
1973.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TIMEQUAKE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Kurt Vonnegut. Berkley, $13.
</P>
<P>
   The author mixes the best bits from an unworkable novel set deep
in Vonnegut country with a running commentary on his own life and
its relationship with his imagination. It's a strange but ``highly
entertaining'' brew, Valerie Sayers wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFTER THE DEATH OF A CHILD: LIVING WITH LOSS THROUGH THE YEARS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Ann K. Finkbeiner. Johns Hopkins University, $15.95.
</P>
<P>
   The author, whose 18-year-old son died in a train accident,
interviews others who have lost children and finds that although
acute grief usually eases in a few years, the bereaved never
entirely ``let go.'' In 1996, Winifred Gallagher called this a
``powerful book.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BLU'S HANGING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Lois-Ann Yamanaka. Bard/Avon, $12.
</P>
<P>
   Three precocious children in a Hawaiian village are beset by
misfortunes and humiliations after the death of their mother and
the descent of their father into poverty. The novel ``fluidly
explores the brutal divide between family duty and
self-preservation,'' Megan Harlan wrote last year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
