<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 09:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8691 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN26-CO     08-24 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The savings that may not be
 &HT;    (For release, Aug. 26, 1998)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Florida, chock-full of ex-New Yorkers, this year stole a
page from New York City's political gambitry. State legislators,
flushed with a sales tax surplus, decided to curtail collections a
trifle with a one-week abatement of its 6 percent sales tax, but
only on certain items of clothing costing $50 or less.
</P>
<P>
   New York City, on the other hand, is waiving its 8 1/4 percent
sales tax on most clothing and shoes for items costing $500 or
less. Both were timed for the week that back-to-school clothing
sales would be at their peak.
</P>
<P>
   A comparison of the two examples is best focused in a New York
Times illustration of savings on a pair of running shoes. The sales
tax waiver ``will mean a savings of $7.42 on a $90 pair of Nike Air
Max running shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, however, with its $50 cap, there would be no savings
on the shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Likely, others soon will begin following the disparate examples
of New York City and Florida. Legislators will commence issuing
their own version of sales tax savings because, come election time,
politicians love to point out that they voted for a tax respite.
</P>
<P>
   All this tells us that the states, or in the case of New York
City, the cities, are floating in surplus funds while habitually
telling the public there is not enough money to go around for
schools, roads, etc. (During Florida's sales tax relaxation last
week, I got my new property tax notice; it's going up.)
</P>
<P>
   Canceling the sales tax on clothing items for one week amounts
to a tax break of $19.2 million in Florida, or enough to build some
schools, or hire a bunch of teachers, or more police, or to fix up
the jails where we don't have to release convicted murderers
because the prisons are too crowded.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, $19 million won't come close to answering our funding
problems, but it can make some dents in some badly needed public
services.
</P>
<P>
   I would not be carping about this were it not for a suspicion
that the sales tax abatement has more to do with helping out
retailers than it does families buying back-to-school clothing.
</P>
<P>
   That's a pretty nasty generality, but let me cite an example.
</P>
<P>
   A mother of three, a conservative shopper, had been scouting
clothing sales for several weeks prior to Florida's tax-free week.
She carefully noticed the continuing sales prices, their relation
to the $50 week cap, and what would or would not be considered
eligible for the tax break. (No ties, Monica, but suspenders are
OK.)
</P>
<P>
   In particular, at this one store, she zeroed in on an article of
clothing that was marked at two for $13. When she went into the
store last week, during the tax break, that clothing was now marked
at $10 apiece, thus more than negating the tax savings and putting
a bigger profit into the store's cash register.
</P>
<P>
   Behind this is the naivete of many shoppers who come to accept a
routine 10 percent off sale as day-to-day stuff, but who smash down
the doors to get into a store when the 6 percent sales tax is
waived _ even though the 10 percent savings has been eliminated by
shrewd retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, I do not accuse all retailers of taking advantage of
the politically motived savings being passed out but there are
those out there who do _ and, in at least this one cited case, did.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with retailers doing better business, but
let us be clear about what is transpiring.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the politicians are gathering good-guy points for
their efforts. The New York State Legislature, feeling the heat
generated by New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's example,
already has voted to eliminate, beginning Dec. 1, 1999, the state
sales tax on clothing and shoes costing less than $110.
</P>
<P>
   It's a trend with a future, but before you begin getting excited
about it, wonder if the total savings will be there, or if
retailers are the eventual beneficiaries of the savings.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
