u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-NIGERIA-RELIGION-RE     08-24 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NIGERIA-RELIGION-REVIEW-875&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
22.) 
 A LAND WHERE GOD IS WORKING OVERTIME 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, August(The Week in Review) 
(lb) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria _ In southern Nigeria, which is mainly Christian,
religious bumper stickers abound. ``Be a sweatless winner,'' says
one. ``Work with us at the Living Faith Church.'' Another advises
that ``Jesus Christ gives, heals and delivers.'' Or there is this
simple admonition: ``Be careful, God is watching.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhortations can be hard to read through the black exhaust
fumes that belch from Nigeria's crumbling fleet of vehicles, but
there is no mistaking the religious fervor that has gripped the
southern half of Africa's giant as misery has grown. In Lagos,
billboards advertising cut-rate Bibles hover over streets seething
with people fighting to survive.
</P>
<P>
   In the north, where Islam is dominant, religious belief is no
less fervent, but it takes another form. Ordered, hierarchical,
rigorous, fatalistic, the faith of the dominant Hausa and Fulani
ethnic groups provides the bedrock of a society still structured
around the authority of traditional Muslim rulers.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria's motto is simple: ``Unity and Faith.'' But there is so
little of the former and so much of the latter that the survival of
Africa's giant is no simple affair. As Nigeria moves toward a
treacherous democratic transition next year, after decades of
military rule, unity is as fragile as the religious faith is
diverse.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is faith, in the end, that may offer the nation its best
hope for unity. The simple habit _ and its extraordinary intensity
_ is something that almost every Nigerian believer seems to share.
</P>
<P>
   God, constantly invoked, works overtime in Nigeria. He alone,
for many people, can explain how an oil-rich country came to find
itself without gasoline; how more than $10 billion a year in oil
revenue can be stolen or squandered; how a longed-for democracy has
taken the form of a repetitive mirage. If there is a single refrain
from the suffering, it is ``What this country needs is a
God-fearing ruler.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if Nigeria finds one _ and Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar,
who took office in June, shows signs of more probity than his
predecessors _ the wounds are deep. Old fault lines _ ethnic,
cultural and social _ have been worsened by a spreading poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Having fallen apart once _ in 1967, when the southeastern Ibo
declared the state of Biafra _ Nigeria is haunted by fears of going
down Rwanda's path. Because of its weight in Africa _ in
population, resources, universities, military power or its vibrant
press _ such a road would be a cataclysm.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the fissures in this country, which was thrown together
on the whim of a British colonial governor in 1914, those based on
religion may be the most treacherous. But it is still not clear
whether religion will ultimately push Nigerians toward fracture or
reconcile them.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three main ethnic groups, the northern Hausas are Muslim,
the southeastern Ibos are overwhelmingly Christian and the
southwestern Yorubas mixed.
</P>
<P>
   But that is only part of the picture: There are more than 200
other groups of various religions; the relaxed, fluid Islam of many
Yorubas has nothing to do with that of the Hausas; paganism is
strong in some areas; thriving Baptist, Pentecostal, Catholic,
Seventh-Day Adventist and other churches compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Religion _ whether Christian, Muslim or pagan _ is a booming
business throughout Nigeria,'' said Onaolapo Soleye, a former
finance minister from the southwest. ``But in the north, religion
is different: more fatalistic and more all-encompassing. Everything
there is Allah's work. Well, we do not think it's Allah's work that
more and more people are poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Such sentiments reflect a thinly veiled resentment in the south
over what is seen as the long domination by northern, devoutly
Muslim generals. The most reviled was Gen. Sani Abacha, the
dictator who died suddenly in June. There is a widespread
conviction in Lagos and other southern towns that a northern Islam
has held sway too long.
</P>
<P>
   Abacha's predecessor, Gen. Ibrahim Babangida, enraged many
Christians with actions that included steering Nigeria into the
Organization of the Islamic Conference in 1986. In the early 1990s,
riots between Muslims and minority Christians in two northern towns
left more than 1,000 people dead. The army clamped down, but the
danger still lurks.
</P>
<P>
   Babangida, now in retirement, has abruptly become vociferous
about the need for compromise in the interests of Nigerian unity.
``When I decreed a two-party system for the 1993 election, everyone
said there would be a Muslim-Christian split,'' he said. ``Well,
they were wrong. There were Muslims and Christians in both parties.
Nobody wants to break this country into pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   The apparent winner of that election was Moshood K.O. Abiola, a
Muslim and a Yoruba from the south who attended a Baptist school
and won huge support in the Islamic north. His following did
suggest that the religious divisions could be overcome, but then
the army annulled the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Abiola was jailed, and was still in detention when he died last
month. Now, with resentment about his loss running high, it will be
more difficult, perhaps impossible, to find a leader who can reach
across Nigeria's religious and regional divides.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But there are voices of reason, including the emir of Kano and
other prominent northerners who suggest it is time that a
southerner rule.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt in any part of the country that it was God's
intervention that saved Nigeria from Abacha. On that point, unity
is absolute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nigerians really do pray,'' said Bashir Ikara, a university
professor in the northern town of Kaduna. ``There may be a tug or
war between us, but we are united in our prayers. And tell me, what
does the average northern Nigerian really have to show for the long
domination of a small northern caste?''
</P>
<P>
   In a Lagos slum, Stephen Aiyeyimi, an unemployed university
graduate and an ardent Christian, expressed similar sentiments.
``Everyone in Nigeria is very close to God,'' he said. ``That is
because we have all been pushed to the wall, northerners and
southerners. We have been made poor, we have little money to meet
our needs, and so there is a tendency to want to depend on a
strange, unknowable force.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
