u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLS-APOLOGY-REVIEW-4     08-24 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLS-APOLOGY-REVIEW-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
22.) 
 POLITICIANS: PEOPLE WHO NEVER SAY THEY'RE SORRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, August(The Week in Review) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never admit fault or apologize after a car accident, especially
if you caused it. That's the standard warning of a personal-injury
lawyer, but unnecessary advice for politicians. Most would rather
be flayed than express actual contrition for a mistake, especially
if they have to use those two unthinkable words, ``I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that a simple, direct apology is often the one thing
voters most want to hear, as polls showed many Americans were
telling President Clinton last week. Such words are simply
unutterable for most public figures, whose fear of weakness is
hard-wired into their souls.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's inability to use any form of the the word
``apologize'' last week in his speech to the United States about
his affair with Monica Lewinsky was the aspect of his remarks that
was most criticized the next day and placed him in the pantheon of
elected officials who couldn't quite say they were sorry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mistakes were made'' is the famous circumlocution, and a
marvel of compact indirection, used by President Reagan to explain
the arms-for-hostages deal.
</P>
<P>
   More common is the phrase ``If I've offended anyone, I'm
sorry,'' used by Sen. Alfonse D'Amato after he mocked Lance Ito,
the Japanese-American judge who presided in the O.J. Simpson case;
it was a conditional construction that conceded no real ground to
his accusers.
</P>
<P>
   A more elaborate variation came from Sen. Bob Packwood in his
reference to women who accused him of physical trespass: ``Am I
sorry? Of course _ if I did the things that they said I did.''
</P>
<P>
   If an apology is absolutely required, its power can be reduced
with explanations, excuses and the half-hearted stiffness of a
schoolboy summoned to the front of the room.
</P>
<P>
   When Kurt Waldheim, the president of Austria and a Nazi
intelligence officer during World War II, had to apologize on
behalf of his country for Nazi war crimes, he did it this way:
``Obviously there is no collective guilt. Nevertheless, as head of
state of the Republic of Austria, I wish to apologize for Nazi
crimes committed by Austrians.''
</P>
<P>
   Asian politicians appear to have a better understanding of the
cathartic value of complete repentance, although Japan has long
refused to apologize for its wartime atrocities in Korea and China.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is more than unbearable for me to face you and make this
confession of my shameful deeds, and I deeply apologize,'' said
former South Korean President Chun Doo-hwan in a 1988 admission of
abuse of power. ``The scar will be forever with me in my heart for
the people who have suffered, and for this I feel more regret than
I can express.'' Now that's remorse.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the United States, though, the most effusive apologies are
often those made by politicians for someone else's mistakes. ``I
apologize to the citizens of Crown Heights, to the Rosenbaum family
and to all of the people that were affected by this,'' New York
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said recently, referring to the way his
predecessor, David Dinkins, conducted himself during the 1991
disturbances in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   But after he criticized his electoral opponent, Ruth Messinger,
last year for failing to attend a Catholic Mass, he issued an
apology ``to anybody who feels they need an apology.''
</P>
<P>
   President George Bush was full-throated when righting a
historical wrong. ``The internment of Americans of Japanese
ancestry was a great injustice,'' he said, ``and it will never be
repeated.'' But he was a bit more pragmatic in wishing he had never
raised taxes: ``I did it and I regret it and I regret it. Any time
you get hammered on something, I guess you want to redo it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did express regret in his remarks last week, and said
his actions were wrong. In the taxonomy of political penitence,
that at least is a few degrees above the norm, as captured in this
classic 1987 statement from former New York Mayor Edward Koch,
referring to the president of one of the city's boroughs: ``If I've
insulted him in the past, then I'm sorry and I withdraw my remarks.
But I can't think of any.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 0956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
