<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8783 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT     08-24 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
22.) 
 HIGHLIGHTS OF THE PAST WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, August(The Week in Review) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Underground Site May Hide North Korean Nuclear Reactor
</P>
<P>
   When North Korea signed an agreement in 1994 to ``freeze'' its
huge nuclear weapons development program at Yongbyon, north of the
capital of Pyongyang, U.S. officials knew it was not an ideal
accord. The North, they thought, might still be hiding enough
material to make two bombs. And building tunnels is almost a
national sport, which means other nuclear plants may be hidden away
where inspectors cannot roam.
</P>
<P>
   Now U.S. spy satellites have found one: a huge cavern being dug
out under a mountain 25 miles from Yongbyon, with 10,000 to 15,000
workers at the site.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. intelligence agencies are fairly certain that it is being
prepared for an underground reactor and reprocessing center, where
nuclear waste is turned to bomb-grade plutonium. But they expect
the North Koreans to claim that it is innocuous _ perhaps a giant
underground parking garage. There's only one problem with that
explanation: The country is so poor it has almost no cars.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID E. SANGER
</P>
<P>
   Public Housing May No Longer Be Mostly for the Poor
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans and the Clinton administration are on
the verge of agreeing to legislation that would allow public
housing authorities to give more vacant apartments to working
families.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, federal rules have required that almost
all open public housing units go to the very poor, which has hurt
inner-city neighborhoods, Republicans and many housing experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise bill would not bring about swift change because
waiting lists at most housing authorities are already long. But
housing officials around the country say it will help them begin
marketing campaigns to entice low-income working families.
</P>
<P>
   _ JAMES DAO
</P>
<P>
   Protests in China
</P>
<P>
   Defying a ban, students and women's groups held emotional
protests over the looting, killing and rape directed against ethnic
Chinese during the riots in Indonesia in May.
</P>
<P>
   The rioting initially received scant coverage in China. But
photo essays in two newspapers this month caused an outpouring of
public anger primarily aimed at Indonesian leaders and criticism of
Beijing's response. Moreover, the protests showed a greater
willingness to speak out and the government's slightly greater
tolerance of it.
</P>
<P>
   A Revived Policy
</P>
<P>
   The largest insurance company in Italy, Generali, agreed in
federal court in New York to pay $100 million to Holocaust
survivors and their heirs who were denied payment on life and
annuity policies after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Generali also said it would give lawyers suing other European
insurers confidential documents detailing how competing companies
cooperated with the Nazis to loot policies owned by Jews, putting
pressure on the insurers to settle.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID CAY JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   Inching Up
</P>
<P>
   As a group, young single black mothers have been firmly stuck on
the bottom rungs of the economic ladder. But new data indicated
that from 1993 to 1996 _ the last years for which complete data are
available _ their incomes have risen by more than 20 percent, the
first significant increase in more than 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Experts cite a booming economy, hikes in the minimum wage and a
revamped welfare system as the major reasons for the improved lot
of this group.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVEN A. HOLMES
</P>
<P>
   Balloonist Fails, Again
</P>
<P>
   Steve Fossett found himself just short of becoming chum when his
balloon plummeted into the shark-infested waters of the South
Pacific. He was two-thirds of the way toward completing an
around-the-world voyage that, if successful, would have made him
the first balloonist to circle the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Fossett, 54, was found off eastern Australia after traveling
15,200 miles since lifting off from Argentina on Aug. 7, breaking
his own distance mark of 10,360 miles set in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Vive the Rule of Law
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't necessarily be a Velvet Revolution. Canada's Supreme
Court said Quebec could legally separate if it did so in accord
with the constitution and with the consent of the rest of Canada.
French-speaking separatists dismissed the court's advisory and
vowed to proceed with plans for provincial elections and another
referendum on independence.
</P>
<P>
   _ ANTHONY DePALMA
</P>
<P>
   Justice, 32 Years Later
</P>
<P>
   After four trials ended in deadlock in the 1960s, a former
klansman was found guilty of ordering the firebombing death of a
black civil rights activist in his home in Hattiesburg, Miss.
Samuel Bowers, 73, was convicted of arson and murder in the death
of Vernon Dahmer. Prosecutors said Dahmer was killed for helping
blacks register to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Several ex-Klansmen testified that Bowers, as imperial wizard of
the Ku Klux Klan, had ordered the killing. The verdict carries a
life term.
</P>
<P>
   Assisted Suicide Tally
</P>
<P>
   After Oregon's voters reaffirmed by a solid majority last year
an earlier and much-challenged vote to make theirs the first state
in the union to allow physician-assisted suicide for the terminally
ill, horrified opponents predicted abuse and suicides by the dozens
or hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   So far, according to state figures released last week, only 10
people have been given authorization to take lethal medication
after filling out a one-page form, titled ``Request for medication
to end my life in a humane and dignified manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Of those, the state said, eight had taken the drugs and died,
while the two others died before actually taking the drugs. The
average age at death was 71. Under the law, the drugs can be
prescribed to an adult of sound mind with, in the opinion of two
doctors, less than six months to live. The state's Catholic
Conference, calling the news a ``tragic development,'' said it was
eight deaths too many.
</P>
<P>
   _ SAM HOWE VERHOVEK
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
