<SLUG> BC-KELSEY-GRAMMER-IN-FRAISER-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KELSEY GRAMMER GETS HIS DREAM: THE 9 P.M. THURSDAY TIME SLOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Kelsey Grammer (with hands together) and
David Hyde Pierce in a scene from `Frasier.' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Kelsey Grammer dreamed of the day that ``Frasier'' would assume
the nine o'clock slot on NBC's blockbuster Thursday night schedule.
 &HT;    Now that ``Seinfeld'' has gone the way of pterodactyls,
Grammer's fantasy becomes a reality on Sept. 24, when his acclaimed
comedy series switches from Tuesdays to Thursdays for its sixth
season.
 &HT;    The scenario conjures up that old devil's advocate chestnut: Be
careful what you wish for. You just might get it.
 &HT;    ``I suppose it might seem like a pressure situation, but I've
got enough self-inflected pressure to deal with,'' the affable
Grammer says by phone from his ``Frasier'' dressing room after a
rehearsal. ``Nobody's a harsher critic of me than I am. Nobody
drives me harder than I drive myself, and nobody expects more of
`Frasier' than I do.
 &HT;    ``I've already got that mixed blessing of being an
obsessive-compulsive personality. So I don't feel any additional
pressure.''
 &HT;    And, this from a character who plays a shrink!
 &HT;    Perhaps he shouldn't feel the pressure, for precious few shows
so consistently achieve ``Frasier's'' level of quality and
sophisticated humor. For those not in the know, ``Frasier'' casts
three-time Emmy Award winner Grammer as Dr. Frasier Crane, a
well-meaning if pompous bundle of neuroses who earns his living _
or did until last year's season finale _ as an on-air psychiatrist
for a Seattle radio station.
 &HT;    Alternately aiding and abetting or driving Crane to distraction
are his competitive brother, Niles (David Hyde Pierce); gruff
father, Martin (John Mahoney); outspoken producer, Roz (Peri
Gilpin); Martin's daffy live-in nurse, Daphne (Jane Leeves); the
radio station's repugnant sportscaster, Bulldog (Dan Butler); and
Martin's feisty pooch, Eddie (Moose).
 &HT;    ``It's an incredibly well-oiled machine,'' Grammer says. ``We've
acquired what I call requisite disrespect, meaning we don't spend
that much time on things.
 &HT;    ``We trust that if we don't get something right in rehearsal
we'll get it right the next day. We know where scripts will work
and where they won't work
 &HT;    ``Nobody beats their brains out. If we run into a brick wall
once in a while, yeah, we all sit for an hour or two and kick it
around.''
 &HT;    Grammer laughs a bemused laugh.
 &HT;    ``But those sessions are rare these days,'' he continues. ``We
have a great machine, well-built, that always fires on every
cylinder.''
 &HT;    The trick to keeping it fresh, Grammer notes, is to always push
the envelope and travel new terrain, but not to do so arbitrarily.
Thus, audiences tuning into the show this season will witness,
among other developments, Frasier dealing with unexpected
unemployment and Niles struggling with his divorce.
 &HT;    ``Basically, we'll be exploring the next logical steps in all of
these characters' lives,'' Grammer says. ``It just makes sense.''
 &HT;    Amazing as it may seem, Grammer first portrayed Crane 15 years
ago, when he joined the cast of NBC's ``Cheers'' as a love interest
for Diane Chambers (Shelly Long). So associated with Crane is
Grammer that a fair number of people think of him as the character
and not a theater-trained actor portraying a character.
 &HT;    ``I certainly understand the tendency to do that, but I think
it's a shame,'' Grammer says somberly. ``I think it's really a
shame when the creative minds of my own industry have done it.
 &HT;    ``It happens and sometimes you've got to face the music and
realize that, yes, it's hard for people to imagine you in another
situation,'' he says. ``I'm doing my best, believe me, to make sure
that's not always the case.''
 &HT;    Grammer's also toiling hard, day in and day out, to stay sober.
His battles with the bottle, of course, spilled into public view a
couple of years ago, after an inebriated Grammer totaled his brand
new car, a gift from NBC.
 &HT;    The glare of the limelight shines bright enough during the good
times, but as Grammer learned the hard way, it's downright blinding
during the bad times.
 &HT;    ``It's shaming to realize that your privacy is completely done
away with as a result of celebrity,'' Grammer says. ``But it's also
kind of freeing to overcome your failures.
 &HT;    ``That I'm still around is a testament to the fact that I have a
great deal of tenacity and maybe even courage,'' he says. ``I hate
to even pander to the word `demons,' because if a person doesn't
have any demons they wouldn't be interesting.
 &HT;    ``I wouldn't be a good actor without them. Demons are my best
friends.''
 &HT;    He pauses again, just for a split second, as he searches for the
right words to convey his feelings.
 &HT;    ``When you have a disease, you have a disease,'' he says. ``You
either treat it or you don't treat it.
 &HT;    ``Finally getting the treatment I needed was the best thing that
ever happened to me. All the old insecurities remain,'' Grammer
notes. ``I'm just better now at dealing with them.''
 &HT;    Helping Grammer deal with his insecurities and demons is his
wife, Camille, whom he married on Aug. 2, 1997.
 &HT;    ``I'm still wildly in love with Camille,'' he says warmly.
``It's new to me, and it's certainly new to me to be in a
relationship with somebody who really cares about me.
 &HT;    ``That has made quite a bit of difference in my life.''
 &HT;    Grammer spent the better part of ``Frasier's'' summer hiatus
relaxing with Camille and his daughter from a previous
relationship. But he also found time to co-star in an upcoming
feature film, ``New Jersey Turnpike,'' his first since the
waterlogged Naval comedy ``Down Periscope'' (1997) was torpedoed by
critics and audiences alike.
 &HT;    ```New Jersey Turnpike' is an affectionate look back at a
charming time in our recent history, the 1970s, when we had the
American Basketball Association (ABA),'' he says. ``It's a fun
movie and, hopefully, it captures the music and clothes of that
period, and the period itself.
 &HT;    ``I play the general manager of a fictional basketball team that
almost made it into the NBA but didn't because of one horrible,
tragic evening.''
 &HT;    And now it's back to ``Frasier,'' which suits Grammer just fine.
 &HT;    ``We've been on for six years, and we're just getting started,''
an enthusiastic Grammer says. He may join co-stars Mahoney and
Pierce for a limited run in the Broadway show ``Art'' during the
next ``Frasier'' hiatus. ``Frasier is this incredible mouthpiece
for all of creation for me.
 &HT;    ``You can do a Shakespearean role for a couple of years and
think, `OK, I've done it.' But `Fraiser' is an everyman in a weird
kind of way.
 &HT;    ``He can absorb all of what's going on in a contemporary society
but still hang onto his tenuous principles, his assumptions about
the world and life,'' Grammer says. ``He's willing to change his
mind about life and people as he gets older.
 &HT;    ``So I don't see even another three or four years of `Frasier'
being a problem.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
