<HEADER>
A8793 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LARENZ-TATE-IN-WHY-DO     08-24 1435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LARENZ-TATE-IN-WHY-DO-FOOLS-FALL-IN-LOVE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARENZ TATE HAS THREE WIVES AT THE SAME TIME _ ON FILM, OF COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 &HT;     Includes a color slide of Larenz Tate (center) with Vivica Fox,
Halle Berry and Lela Rochon, stars of ``Why Do Fools Fall in
Love?'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    And you thought Bill Clinton had problems. Larenz Tate has three
wives _ all at the same time.
 &HT;    Only in the movies, of course. For Tate, getting married might
be normal for a single character. But on a sound stage, he's
already promised to marry Vivica Fox, playing a petty thief, and
Lela Rochan, playing a teacher.
 &HT;    That was the previous week. Today it's Halle Berry's turn to be
the bride. Her character is a singer.
 &HT;    Tate knows the drill by heart. ``The first move when you're
getting married multiple times in a movie is to buy a giant sized
bottle of Listerine,'' the star of ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love''
advises. The movie opens Aug. 28.
 &HT;    In Hollywood, they are already dubbing the film ``First Widows
Club,'' after the ``First Wives Club''(1996).
 &HT;    Tate plays singer Frankie Lymon, a black teen idol, who died in
1953 at age 26 of a heroin overdose, leaving three wives. No big
deal these days except he never got divorced. He was married to all
three at the same time _ much to their shock when it comes to
splitting up the estate. (It wasn't hashed out until a 1988 trial.)
 &HT;    Then again, all this love directed at one handsome young man
doesn't sound that outlandish.
 &HT;    Fox calls Tate a fantastic screen lover. ``He was so limber at
one point I thought he was gonna do the splits,'' she says. Berry
told Jane magazine, ``Tate has the fattest, widest, juiciest,
thickest tongue I've ever seen. On that alone, I would have to give
the kissing a 10.''
 &HT;    ``He is a beautiful young man,'' Rochan says.
 &HT;    Tate readily admits his shortcomings. He didn't think he would
get the role, because it's hard to play a singer when you don't
sing. ``I don't have a good voice,'' he admits. ``I did do a lot of
lip synching.''
 &HT;    His character is seen in flashbacks when the widows go to court
over his fortune. ``It's a powerful story about a young man people
might not remember, but was important in black history because he
was one of the first young black singers who crossed over,'' Tate
says.
 &HT;    ``The movie is framed by the women telling their story about
Frankie and who he was to them,'' Tate reveals. ``Each claims that
she was his true love.''
 &HT;    One problem he faced was too much kissing. ``I would get up in
the morning and think, `Oh gosh, another day and I've got to do
kissy face scenes.''' Again, the girls took it the worst. ``Halle
would come in and say to me, `Did you kiss her today?' I wasn't
even sure which `her' she was talking about, but I would bow my
head and nod.''
 &HT;    Tate would use a defense unavailable to most married men. ``I
would yell, `Come on! It's in the script.' Give me a break.''' Of
course, he didn't hope for other breaks. Fox is engaged to R&AMP;B star
Christopher Harvest, who goes by the name Sixx-Nine.
 &HT;    That refers to his height. ``I'd check with Vivica now and then,
and she would say, `Sixx-Nine understands it's just acting although
he might come to the set to make sure everything is cool.'''
 &HT;    Then again, Tate could rely on his street smarts. He's from
Chicago's west side. ``I'm from the `hood, but to me I didn't grow
up in a rough neighborhood,'' Tate says.
 &HT;    As a child, he always knew city limits wouldn't contain him. ``I
was so extremely smart that they couldn't sit me in a classroom,''
Tate says. ``I was just smarter than the other kids (so) that they
had to put me one-on-one with a tutor.''
 &HT;    The little genius never wanted to be an actor. But at age 8, his
father moved to Los Angeles to finish college. The family missed
him so they moved there for the school year and returned to Chicago
for summers.
 &HT;    In Los Angeles with his parents and two brothers, Tate grew
restless. His mother thought a perfect way to ``burn off my extra
energy'' was to perform.
 &HT;    Originally, Tate wanted his brothers and himself to form a
mini-Jackson Five. When that didn't work, he returned to the couch.
``My brothers remind me to this day that I was the one who said, `I
don't want to act. I just want to sit on the couch and watch
cartoons.'''
 &HT;    His mother enrolled him in dance class.
 &HT;    ``I was like, `Come on, man. This dance class is not me.' I
wanted to hang out with the guys and play basketball,'' Tate
recalls. He changed his mind when he nabbed his first role on
televisions's new version of ``The Twilight Zone'' (1987).
 &HT;    ``I was Kid No. 1 on the Christmas show,'' he says. ``I was told
to sit on Santa's lap, but the deal was Santa was supposed to be
drunk, so I fall off his lap.''
 &HT;    Commercials followed, including one for Matchbox cars. The real
money and exposure happened when he got cast on sitcoms. He did a
stint on ``The Fresh Prince of Bel- Air,'' where Tate romanced Will
Smith's cousin.
 &HT;    Tate moved to larger roles in ``Menace II Society'' (1993),
``Dead Presidents'' (1995) and ``Love Jones'' (1997).
 &HT;    ``For me acting was a way out,'' he says. ``As a teen-ager in
both LA and Chicago, I watched some of my buddies making the wrong
choices in life. They just wanted to hang out on the corner and get
in trouble. They didn't want to focus on the bigger picture,'' Tate
says.
 &HT;    Now, Tate lives in Hollywood where he's auditioning for upcoming
roles. With his first starring movie, you might think the ego would
kick in, but he remains good natured. Tate even has a sense of
humor about his megaflop last Christmas, ``The Postman.'' In case
you didn't see it, he played Ford Lincoln Mercury, Kevin Costner's
right hand man.
 &HT;    ``I still think it's a cool movie. Maybe later people will find
it on home video,'' Tate says, adding, it was a chance to work in
the big leagues.
 &HT;    Are the bigs ready for him? Tate has already proven himself as a
dangerous actor. He recalls his first meeting with Costner in
``Postman.'' ``I tackled him.
 &HT;    ``We did a scene where I don't want the Postman to go after the
bad guys,'' Tate laughs. ``I have to scream, 'No! No! Stop Postman!
They're going to kill you!' Kevin didn't know I would follow this
line up by giving him a football tackle hug.''
 &HT;    By all accounts, Costner was ``stunned.'' Tate recalls, ``Kevin
was like, `Wait a minute, man. Get off me.' It was our first
bonding moment. Then Kevin said to me, `Easy, easy, easy, kid.' I
looked him in the eyes and said, `Kevin, this is not the love
scene. Just in case you're wondering.'''
 &HT;    Costner burst out laughing.
 &HT;    Now Tate shakes his head. ``All my female friends are still
going, `What was it like to embrace Kevin Costner?' I say, 'I don't
think I got the same feeling you did.''
 &HT;    The perks included filming in a small town in Washington State.
``I'm a downtown city guy,'' Tate says. ``I don't like Mayberry.
The minute we were done with that movie I couldn't wait to get back
to the big city and just go to a supermarket.''
 &HT;    Almost 30 and still single, the on-screen ladies man is mum on
life partners. ``I think of myself as a down to earth guy who will
put his family first,'' Tate says. First, he is planning on
retiring his mother.
 &HT;    ``She's a sweet lady, and I want to give her the best in life,''
he says.
 &HT;    No wonder ladies love him. Rochon says his only fault is too
much lip smacking during kissing. ``I mean it,'' she says.
 &HT;    ``Boy, do I have these women fooled,'' Tate says.
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
