<HEADLINE>
FRENCH STEWART GOES WEIRDLY WHERE NO ONE HAS GONE BEFORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of French Stewart (standing in colored
shirt) pictured with cast of ``3rd Rock From the Sun.'' 
 By DAVID KRONKE  
 c.1998 TV Guide (Canada)  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The most impressive thing about French Stewart is not that he's
willing to wear a peach plaid leisure suit and royal-blue loafers,
it's the way he wears them.
 &HT;    As he sits off to the side of the ``3rd Rock From the Sun'' set,
Stewart, 34, carries himself seriously and with something actually
approaching dignity. As Harry, the alien emissary to Earth who
makes tapioca seem to belong in the same intellectual league as
Immanuel Kant, Stewart has transformed the doofus into a lovable
lug of a guy.
 &HT;    And he's proud of it. ``I like the fact that he's an epic
idiot,'' Stewart says, ``an idiot the likes of which have not been
seen _ an idiot on any planet, a universal idiot.''
 &HT;    It's difficult to imagine anyone else playing Harry, though
executive producers Bonnie and Terry Turner originally had someone
quite different in mind. ``At first, we had the idea that Harry
would be a big guy,'' Terry Turner says, ``but French came in and
sat down and read, and I immediately locked on to him.''
 &HT;    Stewart won over the Turners after auditioning a scene in which
Harry fawns over the aliens' landlady's Angora sweater.
 &HT;    ``She said, `I like the color,' and he said, `Well, it's
wunn-derr-fulll.' He read the line as if feeling and sniffing the
sweater was the way you experience color,'' Terry recalls. ``He was
so completely different and on-target.''
 &HT;    As Stewart remembers it, his audition came just after he had
been dropped from another pilot. ``I felt like I was getting a
little tired and thought that maybe things weren't gonna pan out
for me as an actor,'' he says.
 &HT;    ``So I walked in and just did whatever I wanted to do, and they
seemed to enjoy it. I've had that before, but getting past networks
has always been a treacherous business for me,'' he says. ``I'm
just plain weird, let's face it.''
 &HT;    Terry Turner would be hard pressed to disagree. ``French has
this Buster Keaton thing going. He's one of the few comedians in
television that works in a full-body shot,'' he says. ``His feet
are as important as his face.''
 &HT;    Stewart's career began its ascent in 1989, when he joined Los
Angeles' Cast Theater, a funky enclave whose productions win rave
reviews and cult audiences.
 &HT;    ``Zombie Attack! is the longest running show in Los Angeles,''
he reports. ``I must've been in that show for four years, just
hundreds and hundreds of performances. A lot of people would come
to see shows, and I would get work from it.''
 &HT;    He met his manager at the Cast, and eventually won a recurring
role as the zany disc jockey in ``The New WKRP in Cincinnati''
(1991), though today he admits, ``I'm grateful for that time in my
life, but I felt like it wasn't my strength. It just wasn't what I
do.''
 &HT;    Stewart has also landed a few small parts in movies, including
``Leaving Las Vegas,'' (1995) where he played ``a pervert, you
could say,'' and the recent cinematic incarnation of ``McHale's
Navy'' (1997). But his first love remains ``3rd Rock.''
 &HT;    ``I would love to ride it till it drops, because I've done
enough television to be able to recognize when something's
special,'' he says. ``And we've found our crowd. I feel like the
people who really appreciate us are with us. We enjoy each other.''
 &HT;    He's enjoyed the ride on the show so much he professes not to be
too troubled by the fact that he's been typecast as a dimwit. ``I
used to be able to play a large variety of parts but this has been
so specialized,'' Stewart says.
 &HT;    ``When people call me, they want me to trip over stuff, or some
facsimile of that, which is OK with me. I would love to think that
at some point I could do different things, but I don't know if it's
gonna happen,'' he adds.
 &HT;    ``But I have no complaints, because I've had my shot. This is
more than I expected _ my career has been a wonderful surprise.''
 c.1998 TV Guide (Canada)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (David Kronke is a staff writer for TV Guide Canada.)
