<SLUG> BC-CELEBRITY-DEATHMATCH-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CELEBRITY DEATHMATCH' CATCHES ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of `combatants' Elvis (left) vs. Jerry
Garcia (right) in a scene from ``Celebrity Deathmatch.'' 
 By MATTHEW PHENIX  
 c.1998 The New York Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Could that be the movie reviewer Gene Siskel swinging around his
longtime pal Roger Ebert, helicopter style, by his stock-and-trade
thumb? It could indeed.
 &HT;    Well, almost. Clay renderings of the hotshot critics recently
appeared on ``Celebrity Deathmatch,'' the animated MTV series that
drops news makers into a wrestling ring where they can pulverize
each other.
 &HT;    This half-hour show, shown since mid-May on Thursday evenings at
10, takes celebrities' adversarial relationships, real and
imagined, and pumps them to gleeful, steroidal extremes. Hillary
Rodham Clinton hammering away on a certain ex-White House intern,
for instance, is a scene unlikely to be realized anywhere else but
here.
 &HT;    ``Celebrity Deathmatch'' is the brainchild of the 29-year-old
animator Eric Fogel, whose cartoon series ``The Head,'' about an
average guy who awakens to find an alien named Roy living in his
head, ran for two seasons on MTV in 1994.
 &HT;    The first ``Deathmatch,'' just a brief bout, appeared on MTV in
1997, as part of the network's animated variety series, ``Cartoon
Sushi.'' Clay versions of Marilyn Manson, the singer, and infamous
murderer Charles Manson entered the squared circle to prove once
and for all who was the ``Most Evil Man in America.'' (Charles
Manson won.)
 &HT;    In January, fight fans were treated to MTV's Super Bowl halftime
special ``Celebrity Deathmatch Deathbowl '98,'' featuring Pamela
Anderson and RuPaul fighting each other tooth and nail, and the
Hanson boys slugging it out with the Spice Girls. That broadcast,
with more than 3 million viewers, was the clincher for MTV:
``Celebrity Deathmatch'' is in the middle of a 13-episode run.
 &HT;    Stop-motion animation, whether with clay figures like those used
by the animator Art Clokey in the 1950s for ``The Gumby Show'' or
the articulated dolls he used in his 1962 children's series ``Davey
and Goliath,'' has been a persistent if sporadic presence on
television.
 &HT;    The term ``Claymation,'' often generically applied to clay
animation, is in fact a registered trademark of Will Vinton
Studios, the animation company responsible for the ``Califoria
Raisins'' advertising campaign and the spectacular stone-faced Nome
King in the 1985 film ``Return to Oz.''
 &HT;    Because oil-based clay melts under studio lights and becomes
grimy when handled repeatedly, working with it takes as much
patience as skill. A 30-minute ``Gumby'' episode, for instance,
required the figures to be moved more than 43,000 times _
one-eighth of an inch at a time _ and photographed individually.
 &HT;    From 20 to 30 duplicates of the characters were needed as
backups during the weeklong process of creating an episode. The
process hasn't changed much since Gumby and his horse, Pokey, came
on the scene.
 &HT;    Fogel says he decided on clay animation for ``Celebrity
Deathmatch'' because he enjoys its immediacy. Two episodes of the
show, each with three celebrity bouts, are photographed
simultaneously in a suite of eight rooms at MTV. The network has
set up an ``audition line,'' Fogel said, to find and record the
best celebrity imitations, regardless of location.
 &HT;    If a great Newt Gingrich imitator is found in Los Angeles, the
actor will simply record his part on the West Coast, with Fogel and
company monitoring the session from New York. Because of the show's
topical nature, it is not unheard of, Fogel says, for an episode to
be completed just a day before it is broadcast.
 &HT;    The clay image and real voice of the boxing referee Mills Lane,
who officiated at the notorious 1997 fight that ended with Mike
Tyson's biting Evander Holyfield's ear, presides over most of the
``Celebrity Deathmatch'' bouts.
 &HT;    The brawlers are chosen by Fogel and his team of writers, who
meet three times a week to pore over magazines, searching for
unwitting personalities to sic on each other: Oprah Winfrey and
Rosie O'Donnell, for example.
 &HT;    On its Web site (www.mtv.com), MTV offered fans the chance
recently to vote for the celebrity combatants in a future ``Viewers
Choice'' match. Among the 30 MTV suggestions were Richard Simmons
and Courtney Love.
 &HT;    MTV included a write-in box, should a fan of the show be struck
with the irresistible urge to see, say, a leotard-clad Martha
Stewart puree Bob Vila. Fogel says there were ``thousands upon
thousands of suggestions.''
 &HT;    The most popular requests will be aired this weekend, Aug. 29
and 30.
 c.1998 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Matthew Phenix is a news assistant with the Arts and Leisure
Section of The New York Times.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
