<HEADER>
A8804 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-SHORTS22-COX     08-24 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SHORTS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brief book reviews
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1988 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Into That Good Night. By Ron Rozelle. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux.
$22. 182 pages.
</P>
<P>
   This memoir about memory _ or rather the loss of it _ at first
seems as plain as its East Texas landscape. Ron Rozelle's father,
an educator who ushered integration into the Oakwood schools in the
1960s, develops Alzheimer's disease in his 80s. The book is slow to
get off the ground. Then, lying in bed, little Ron hears a truck
come through Oakwood in the middle of the night. He muses that the
driver ``will know nothing of the lives that are played out daily''
in the town, and ``there seems something not right about his
piercing through, in a matter of seconds, my entire world.'' Those
shocks of fine perception are the batteries that keep this memoir
humming. One poignant chapter describes the effects of Alzheimer's:
His father asks the grown-up Ron: ``Who are you?'' Though Rozelle
places his dad _ who was his home _ front and center, the reader
may wish to know more about his far more intriguing mother, whose
mental illness and shocking death are glossed over. There are
snakes living under the rocks in East Texas, and one wishes Rozelle
had looked under a few more of them.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Zone. By Tim Green. Warner. $24. 325 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his pro football success, Luther Zorn, NFL linebacker
for the Florida Marauders, still struggles with the psychological
effects of having an abusive father. On the field, he's meaner than
Joe Green. Off the gridiron, he's nice enough, helping out an
abused woman (who becomes his lover) and her son. He's also having
an affair with the wife of the team's owner, and when the owner
turns up murdered, Zorn is the prime suspect. Unfortunately, the
revelation of the real murderer is the only surprise in this
formulaic mystery in which all the characters are cardboard
cutouts. Green, a former Atlanta Falcon, writes clean prose about
dirty doings and is not afraid of examining racial issues in
sports. But the plot is about as engaging as a Falcons game when
the team is down 49-0 in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Last Manly Man. By Sparkle Hayter. Morrow. $22. 260 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Sparkle Hayter draws on her experience as a news writer at
Atlanta's CNN and as a comedy writer in this comic mystery
featuring Robin Hudson, a reporter at All News Network in
Manhattan. Her TV project about men who plan the future is
interrupted by an incoherent stranger who gives her a hat before he
is hustled away in a limo. Next thing you know, her already
too-full life is overtaken with a mystery that includes her double,
an unidentified body, animal rights activists, mobile drug dealers,
nutsy neighbors and needy boyfriends. It all comes down to some
abducted chimps and a ``Stepford Wives''-like plot to subjugate
women. Little of that matters; Hayter's one-liners and comic scenes
(particularly when she is injected with sodium pentathol) will have
you guffawing. Hudson seems gutsy, but a nightmare reveals her
vulnerability: She has ``one of those Jesus dreams like I used to
have as a kid, after my dad died,'' when Christ swoops down out of
the sky to the rescue. Ultimately, this is a finer portrait of a
single woman than ``Bridget Jones's Diary.''
</P>
<P>
   Spin. By Tom Lowe. Pocket Books. $23. 287 pages.
</P>
<P>
   When political spinmeister Jim Asher meets the son of the
California Republican candidate for whom he works, he is pleased
because ``the little rascal ... looked like a great decoration for
family-values speeches.'' Asher loves spinning facts and images on
behalf of his party. He loves his huge salary, his Armani suits,
the leggy models at his sexual beck and call, the limousine life.
But the line between image and criminal activity blur, and Asher is
caught up in a scandal not entirely of his own making. Spin, he
discovers, controls him more than he controls it. Lowe's prose is a
far cry from F. Scott Fitzgerald's, but Jim Asher is a postmodern
Great Gatsby, naive at heart, wending his way toward political
status in California politics. And the book asks a serious
question: Can one play the political game and remain honest?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980824.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8805 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS25-COX     08-24 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Nosferatu'' adds little to lore of silent films
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Shepard's novel ``Nosferatu'' (Knopf, $22) studiously keeps
you at arm's length throughout, but it belongs on that short but
select shelf reserved for fictional treatments of the silent film
era: Howard Rodman's ``Destiny Express'' (about Fritz Lang), John
Baxter's ``The Kid'' (about Charlie Chaplin) and Garson Kanin's
``Moviola,'' among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nosferatu'' concerns itself with F.W. Murnau, the great German
director of ``The Last Laugh,'' ``Sunrise'' and ``Tabu,'' and it
ricochets for no good reason between third-person objective and
first-person diary entries.
</P>
<P>
   Murnau is an especially rich subject because of his enormous
talent, his early death in a car accident in 1931 and his oblique
personality. Shep-hard's take is that Murnau was haunted by the
death of a lover in World War I and was able to climb out of
himself only through his work:
</P>
<P>
   ``Filmmaking offers shelter for a failure to live. The essence
it transfers to the medium is stolen from life.'' This is
undoubtedly true, but the same thing can be said of artists in any
field.
</P>
<P>
   Shephard's book has to be considered a disappointment in that it
conveys little more than a short story about Murnau that Shephard
published two years ago in a collection titled ``Batting Against
Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case at least, less was more.
</P>
<P>
   INSECT LIFE . . . Chronicle Books has published, with an
admirably straight face, ``Bugs in 3-D'' ($18.95), some very nice
photos of all manner of insects, complete with a built-in 3-D
viewer.
</P>
<P>
   The illusion of depth is excellent, and if you have any kids
interested in entomology, or you're just pining for another viewing
of ``The Hellstrom Chronicle,'' this is definitely the book for
you.
</P>
<P>
   The photos of butterflies are particularly beautiful, and you'll
never get a better view of a pair of toad bugs mating than you will
here.
</P>
<P>
   Also new, and worthy of your attention, is ``Art of the Gold
Rush,'' just out from University of California Press ($24.95), the
catalog of an exhibition at the Crocker and Oakland Museums.
</P>
<P>
   There is not a profusion of famous artists, which actually works
to the advantage of the paintings _ you can see through to the
compositions, faces and artifacts without having to get past a
style. These paintings then, are Canaletto, not Titian, but
cumulatively they give you an admirably comprehensive sense of a
period I always associate with Bret Harte.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE . . . ``Does modern society need serious books? Is
the financial trouble we all find ourselves in a reflection of a
cultural change?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Naumann, chief executive officer of Henry Holt &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
