<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For ex-smoker, it's thin line between craving, caving
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm not sure what's holding me together right now. A promise to
my kid. A little guilt. A report from the surgeon general. Who
knows? Maybe it's nothing more than just a thread.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe it's much simpler than any of that. I mean, maybe the
one and only reason I haven't smoked tonight is because I can't
find one. I've already checked. Dirty ashtrays. The pocket of my
husband's jean jacket. An old purse of mine. Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   This is crazy, I know. It's been more than four months since I
smoked my last cigarette. Four months. Most days are easy, most
days just whiz by. But sometimes, out of nowhere, comes an urge so
powerful, so compelling, so mind-controlling, that I am frozen
right then and there. Sometimes I stand, stuck in this crazy,
obsessed, I-want-to-smoke limbo, unable to move back, unable to
move forward, unable to move.
</P>
<P>
   And that's where I am tonight, feeling as though the one thing
in this world that would make me happy is a cigarette. It would
balance my checkbook, and my hormones. It would calm the deadline
nerves, teach the 7-year-old how to handle conflict. It would
ensure that my dad gets home from the hospital. It would make me
appreciate my husband.
</P>
<P>
   It would make me happy, wouldn't it?
</P>
<P>
   That's the thing about smoking, it becomes part of our lives.
We're excited, we smoke. We're unhappy, we smoke. We're mad, we
smoke. Indeed, in the weeks and months and years after we quit,
it's difficult to laugh or cry without wanting to share it with a
cigarette. It's a sick, symbiotic addiction.
</P>
<P>
   But once we decide, for whatever reasons, to quit, researchers
say it doesn't take long for our bodies to heal. According to them,
within two weeks of the last one, my blood pressure and pulse were
back to normal. My circulation was improved and my nerve endings
started to regrow.
</P>
<P>
   By now, say the researchers, I should have more energy, cough
less and walk easier.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is true.
</P>
<P>
   All of which means nothing when you want a cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   I know exactly when and where this latest I-want-to-smoke seed
was planted. It was a comment by an old friend. We'd run into each
other when I was on vacation and he said he'd quit seven years ago.
But just recently, he'd started to have one, occasionally, at a
party, at a ballgame. It was going well, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is any ex-smoker's dream, to have one once in a
while.
</P>
<P>
   And, so, the thought of that one cigarette has haunted me since.
I want to take it from the pack, smell it, feel the nicotine burn
my lips. I want to strike the match, smell the sulphur, feel that
glorious buzz.
</P>
<P>
   I want to forget about it, but I can't.
</P>
<P>
   This no-smoking business is as serious as it is hard. The last
time I wrote about quitting, I got a boatful of mail from other
people who had quit. I know it can be done. I know I'm going to do
it.
</P>
<P>
   But then, along comes a day like today when I'm ready to chuck
it all, the promise, the good health, the sense of accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Along comes a night like tonight, when all I want is one, sick,
narcissistic rendezvous with a Winston Light. What a crazy way to
live. But I guess it's better than dying.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
