<DOCNO> NYT19980824.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8808 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORCHID-LOVE22-COX     08-24 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORCHID-LOVE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Orchids: A perennial love
 &HT;    By Caroline Kalfas
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Call him Mr. Green Thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Francis Belcik cares for a budding collection of more than 800
orchids.
</P>
<P>
   No, make that 919.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to a meeting, and I bought a few more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The former assistant professor of biology, who retired from East
Carolina University in June after 33 years, collects the flowering
plants, which he says are a part of heaven.
</P>
<P>
   His passion for the exotic flowers extends to orchid memorabilia
including plates, stamps, cups, tins, crystal bowls and silk
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes like an obsession over time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Belcik is not alone.
</P>
<P>
   John Myhre of Garner has collected more than 400 orchids. He and
his wife are expanding their 14- by 14-foot greenhouse another 18
feet to give the plants more room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we'll have more orchids than we did before,'' Myhre
said.
</P>
<P>
   Myhre, past president of the Triangle Orchid Society in Raleigh,
knows people with much larger collections than his. Many are fellow
society members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The group includes people with one or two orchids up to people
who have many thousands,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ned Nash, director of education and conservation for the
American Orchid Society in West Palm Beach, Fla., said many orchid
growers amass a large selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orchid people are collectors and accumulators,'' he said.
``And orchids are like `National Geographic.' Nobody ever throws
them away _ even if they should.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of orchids stems from their vast diversity and
beautiful flowers, which bloom in all seasons in an assortment of
fragrances, sizes, colors and shapes.
</P>
<P>
   The average orchid costs between $15 and $20. But the plants
range in price from $3.50 to $25,000, Nash said. They also vary in
size. The plants can be as small as a person's smallest fingernail
or as large as vanilla, an orchid with vines that grow to be
hundreds of feet long.
</P>
<P>
   Orchids grow worldwide with more than 30,000 species in almost
every color. The perennials are known for their vivid, long-lasting
blooms and can be cultivated or found growing in the wild. North
Carolina boasts 56 native species, Belcik said.
</P>
<P>
   Growing orchids is difficult enough to be a challenge, but not
so tough that the job's impossible, Nash said.
</P>
<P>
   Belcik keeps most of his plants in his shady back yard. A
crowded greenhouse protects many of the orchids. Others are hanging
in teakwood baskets on the branches of a cherry tree or placed in
various plastic and clay pots on the grass near a cement statue of
St. Francis of Assisi, the patron saint of animals.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of his orchids are in bloom in July. They show
their best colors in winter-spring, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kind of like being under the trees in the summertime,''
Belcik said. ``If they're sick, they go inside.''
</P>
<P>
   In July, when daytime temperatures hover around 90 degrees or
above, Belcik waters the plants three days a week, usually early in
the morning between his two cups of coffee. The task takes about
one hour, and watering the plants early gives the roots of the
plants plenty of time to dry during the day, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When the temperatures begin to drop, Belcik decreases his
watering schedule to Wednesday and Saturday in 80-degree weather
and Saturday only when temperatures reach 70 degrees or below.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't give each plant individually what it needs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And not all of them survive.
</P>
<P>
   Since Belcik began collecting orchids in 1991, he said he has
accidentally killed more than 300.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing orchids is a little more difficult than growing
geraniums or African violets,'' he said. ``You have to know the
plant.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcik learned his lesson with the first orchid he bought. The
white moth orchid captured his attention right away because of its
vibrant red stripes and spots. His intentions were good, but the
plant died under his care.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I think I watered it eight times,'' he said. ``That's
not what it needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcik has since learned how to better care for the plants with
much success. One of his moth orchids has been in bloom since
April.
</P>
<P>
   He recently produced a bloom from an orchid hybrid bred from
parent plants of two different species and genera. He named the
orchid Centrum Prism Irish Starr and is having it registered with
the Royal Horticultural Society in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The organization, which was founded in 1804, is part of a
network of International Registration Authorities that promote
uniformity, accuracy and stability in the naming of cultivated
plants.
</P>
<P>
   Many collectors depend on orchid societies to provide up-to-date
information about their hobby and a chance to network with other
growers.
</P>
<P>
   Belcik is a member of the American and Triangle orchid societies
and recently was elected president of the Neuse River Orchid
Society in Kinston.
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR:
</P>
<P>
   For more information about orchids, contact the following
societies:
</P>
<P>
   -- NEUSE RIVER ORCHID SOCIETY: The organization of about 30
members meets at 2 p.m. on the second Sunday of each month at the
Lenoir County Cooperative Extension Complex on N.C. Highway 11
South in Kinston. Newcomers are welcome. A picnic is planned for
the August meeting at Fairfield Park in Kinston. For more details
about the picnic or the organization, contact Francis Belcik,
president, at 756-9855.
</P>
<P>
   -- TRIANGLE ORCHID SOCIETY: The organization of about 200
members is based in Raleigh, but draws regional members from Chapel
Hill, Southern Pines, Greenville, Wilson and Durham. They meet at
7:30 p.m. on the second Tuesday of each month at Brooks Avenue
Church of Christ in Raleigh. Meetings often include national and
international speakers. In addition, a show table is provided for
members who wish to bring their orchids for discussion. For a
brochure or more information, contact John Myhre, 1005 Park Ave.,
Garner, N.C. 27529-4163, (919) 772-5514.
</P>
<P>
   -- AMERICAN ORCHID SOCIETY: The organization of about 30,000
members is based in West Palm Beach, Fla. Membership includes a
subscription to the society's full-color monthly magazine
``Orchids.'' For information, write to American Orchid Society, New
Membership/Orchid Web, 6000 S. Olive Ave., West Palm Beach, Fla.
33405, or call (561) 585-8666. Check out the society's Web site at
orchidweb.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
