<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8811 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPLIT-SHIFTS22-COX     08-24 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPLIT-SHIFTS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Split Shifts
 &HT;    By Kim Grizzard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ The arrangement works this way: Betsy
Barnacascel has her two boys Monday through Friday. Their father,
Reggie, gets them on the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But this is no custody agreement. The Barnacascels are a happily
married couple. They've simply divorced themselves from day care.
</P>
<P>
   And they didn't have to quit their jobs to do it. On weekdays,
Reggie heads off to his job as a project manager at WIMCO Corp.
General Contractors in Washington, N.C. Three weekends a month,
Betsy works as a home health nurse for Beverly Health Care.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like there's a lot of family splitting, and there
is,'' Betsy said, ``but we're happy when we're together. I feel
like I've got the best of both worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent study shows many two-income families are dividing the
child care responsibilities two ways instead of three, eliminating
day care from the equation. A third of the two-income families
surveyed by the Families and Work Institute report that they rely
on each other _ not day care centers or baby sitters _ to raise
their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the biggest thing is you've got to make up your mind
if you want to let somebody else raise the kids every day,'' Reggie
said. ``It (the arrangement has) allowed the children to be home
with a parent at all times, and it has helped financially as far as
the cost of day care.''
</P>
<P>
   Betsy returned to her job after she had her firstborn, Heath,
now 4. But when Coleman, now 9 months, came along, the Barnacascels
had to consider whether they'd still come out ahead after doubling
the costs of day care.
</P>
<P>
   James and Molly Tripp faced that same decision after their
daughter, Brylie, now 14 months old, was born. Financially, it was
hard to see how Molly could justify keeping her schedule as a nurse
practitioner while the family spent $800 a month on child care for
Brylie and 3-year-old Jamie.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Molly took a nursing job at Pitt County Memorial
Hospital that allows her to work a weekend schedule. She works
12-hour shifts Friday through Sunday. James adjusted his schedule
as a sales manager and installer for Thulman Eastern fireplace
company so he could be home when Molly is working.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to school four years,'' Molly said. ``I always wanted
to be a nurse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really have to give up. I'm still able to have a
full-time job and have adult interaction, but yet I have four days
a week that are 'Mommy days.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm able to take my little girl to dance, to swimming lessons
_ even little side trips during the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``(James) enjoys the special time that he has with them to do
things. They go out to breakfast. When I go out to work, it's their
special time.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol-Ann Tucker, director of the East Carolina University
Regional Training Center, said the split-shift arrangement can be
beneficial to parents and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the good things about it is they get to spend a good
amount of quality time with each parent,'' she said. ``Lots of
times, I don't think children get an opportunity to spend time with
Daddy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also gives each parent an opportunity to see what it's like
to be a child rearer,'' she said. ``(Many times) the mother is
given the responsibility to raise a child, whether she's working or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   When James and Molly decided to eliminate day care, James
already knew what it was like to get up in the middle of the night
to change and feed the baby. What took some getting used to was
doing that on Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever my buddies have got a big golf match going on, I just
drool at the mouth,'' James said, ``but you just gotta do what you
gotta do.''
</P>
<P>
   Reggie has also had to get used to the idea that his golfing
days are over. Since Betsy is off one weekend a month and the
couple have family nearby, he still gets in a game now and then.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is harder,'' Reggie said of juggling the kids and their
schedules. ``The inconvenience is more, but I think the outcome in
the end will be worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Barnacascels are already seeing some of the benefits. Heath
seems happy and secure knowing Mom or Dad is always around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's a lot happier this way,'' Betsy said. ``I think my
favorite thing is not being rushed in the mornings. You're not
rushed to eat, rushed to dress, rushed to do this. We're not so
rushed and so stressed out.''
</P>
<P>
   James said the arrangement has meant his wife doesn't have to
feel torn between work and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of mothers feel guilty having to work,'' he said. ``The
single best part of it is she doesn't have to feel guilty by doing
that. She still feels secure and confident with who's watching the
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Molly also finds satisfaction in knowing that she isn't missing
the best years of her children's lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with day care,'' she said. ``It's a
viable option for a lot of people. I just felt they were seeing a
lot of things that I wanted to be there to see. I wanted her to be
doing those things with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we drive past her old day care, she never says anything
about going back.''
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR:
</P>
<P>
   If you're considering the split-shift child care option, there
are a number of factors you should consider:
</P>
<P>
   -- Are your work schedules flexible?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people have jobs where employers will allow them to
work at home,'' said Carol-Ann Tucker, director of the East
Carolina University Regional Training Center.
</P>
<P>
   -- Are both of you in favor of making the change?
</P>
<P>
   ``It really has to take an understanding spouse,'' Ms. Tucker
said. ``(Both spouses) have to buy into it.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Do you have the support of extended family members?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't have extended family,'' Ms. Tucker said.
``(Involving extended family in the care of a child) is a wonderful
way for a child to get to know a grandparent or an aunt. It's also
a way for them to get to know older people.''
</P>
<P>
   If you decide to try this:
</P>
<P>
   -- Don't forget to figure in some time for you and your spouse
as a couple as well as time for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to schedule that (couple times) just like you
schedule other activities in your life,'' Ms. Tucker said.
``Couples still need to be a couple and then a parent, even though
that child is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Communicate frequently about discipline. Children need to
know that rules are consistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If parents don't communicate well, there can be some real
problems,'' Ms. Tucker said. ``It can actually get into a little
manipulation _ just like when they get to go to Grandma's they get
to eat all they want and stay up late.''
</P>
<P>
   -- This arrangement is not for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are people who would not be comfortable every
day taking care of a child,'' Ms. Tucker said. ``Some people can
balance it. I think it takes special people to balance it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
