<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWINS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Double take: twins talk about remake of ``Parent Trap''
 &HT;    By Jennifer White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ When Hannah and Caitie Forde-Smith decided to
trick their teachers by switching places, they figured no one would
be the wiser.
</P>
<P>
   True, the rising third-graders at Elmhurst Elementary are
genetically the same, but their personalities couldn't be more
different.
</P>
<P>
   The twins' switch went unnoticed until lunch, when Caitie's
teacher noticed she (really Hannah) was eating the ``wrong'' chips.
Caitie normally ate barbecue chips, but on this day, she was eating
Cheetos, Hannah's favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's the little details that reveal the big
differences between identical twins.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the case in the Disney remake of the movie ``The Parent
Trap,'' which opens Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The original movie featured Hayley Mills playing each of two
14-year-old twins who were separated when their parents divorced.
The remake stars Dennis Quaid, Natasha Richardson and 11-year-old
Lindsay Lohan. Lohan plays identical twins Hallie and Annie, twins
unaware of one another and living a continent apart until they meet
at a summer camp, then conspire to get their parents back together.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve-year-old twins Jill and Janet Hudson thought it strange
that one actress would play both roles instead of casting twins for
the parts. But the plot of the movie, twins switching places, is an
idea that's all too familiar to Janet and Jill, rising
eighth-graders at Chicod Elementary.
</P>
<P>
   When they were in the sixth grade, Janet was manager of the
softball team. When she didn't feel like going to practice one day,
she sent Jill instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coach doesn't know to this day,'' said Donna Hudson, the
twins' mother.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers and coaches aren't the only adults easy to fool.
Sometimes even parents have a hard time telling their own twins
apart.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Smith and Lindsay Forde-Smith, parents of Hannah and
Caitie, admit that they don't always know which twin is which.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always says, 'Hi Caitie,''' Hannah said about her dad. ``I
say, 'I'm Hannah.'''
</P>
<P>
   Donna and Robin Hudson sometimes get their twins confused, but
the girls usually let the mistake go unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I call Jill and I've got the wrong one, they don't pay me
any mind,'' Donna said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the trouble that adults have telling the twins apart,
Lindsay said their friends always know the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids always know who they are,'' she said, adding the
Forde-Smith twins are best friends with three other sets of twins.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are easily distinguishable now _ Caitie has
pierced ears and longer hair _ the girls wore hospital bracelets
for the first year so their parents could tell them apart.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, the Forde-Smith twins say that people often treat them
as one person instead of two individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say, 'Hi twins,''' Hannah said. ``I want to be called by
my own name.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that they look alike shouldn't fool anyone; ``there are
millions'' of differences between the two, Caitie said.
</P>
<P>
   The girls have never dressed alike _ Hannah likes purple and
Caitie prefers blue _ and have been in different classes at school
since first grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I kept them in kindergarten together for me, and I've
requested that they not be together since then,'' Lindsay said. ``I
think every child ought to leave school every day thinking they're
the teacher's favorite, the best and brightest and most popular.
That's hard to do when your twin sister is sitting in the desk
right beside you.''
</P>
<P>
   They twins also have different hobbies. Caitie enjoys horseback
riding and basketball, while Hannah likes hockey, skating and
soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They perceive themselves to be just Caitie and just Hannah,''
Lindsay said. ``I have always worked incredibly hard at creating
their uniqueness.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the twins do share some similarities besides their
genetic likeness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the Spice Girls the same, especially Geri,'' Hannah
said. ``(When I'm older) I'm going to either be a model or a Spice
Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   They also benefit from each other's company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always have somebody to play with,'' Caitie said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Hannah and Caitie, the Hudson twins consider themselves
more alike. The girls have asked to be in the same class at school
since kindergarten, and even at 12, they still occasionally dress
alike.
</P>
<P>
   Both are also members of an All Star softball team where Janet
is pitcher and Jill is catcher.
</P>
<P>
   Although Janet plays in the school band and Jill is the more
artistic of the two, the girls have many of the same friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a freckle on her nose,'' said Jill, about the
difference between herself and Janet.
</P>
<P>
   The only time Janet and Jill don't like being twins is when they
get in trouble for each other's mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you don't do something right, they think it's you, but
it's the other one,'' Jill said.
</P>
<P>
   For their parents, sibling rivalry takes on a whole new meaning
when the kids are the same age.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very competitive,'' Lindsay said. ``I have encouraged
them to be cheerleaders for the other one.''
</P>
<P>
   Donna said that, although her twins are two different children,
they both have agreeable personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody pretty much gets along around here,'' she said.
``When they play ball, they try to compliment each other. I don't
see the rivalry between the two girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
