<SLUG> BC-IMAGE-MAIN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``We don't do trendy''
 &HT;    Has two sidebars: IMAGE-CUTS, IMAGE-MYTHS
 &HT;    PHOTOS AVAILABLE
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ They know about skirts cut like carwash
flaps and platform sneakers and nail polish in blue. But they also
know to avoid all this.
</P>
<P>
   Although image consultants are fashion experts, they're hardly
fashion sheep. You won't, as a rule, find them lumbering off a
cliff into fad land, teeny backpacks a-bouncing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do trendy,'' says Irene Nathan of London, in Miami
last month for the Association of Image Consultants International
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to teach people about investment dressing, you
want them to know that classic styles are the best buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a double-breasted suit in wool crepe. Or a neutral silk
blouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on what function you're attending, but for the most
part, we live in a conservative world,'' says Susan Bigsby, a
consultant in Delray Beach. ``Look at the most cutting edge fashion
statement for fall _ longer length skirts.''
</P>
<P>
   At the AICI opening session, most skirts were neither long nor
short but right around the knee. Most shoes were neither stilettos
nor flats, but somewhere in between. And the clear-cut No. 1 outfit
choice? A suit. Timeless, tailored, safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to look like you know what you're doing,'' says
Elaine Stoltz of Fort Worth, Texas. ``But you don't want to look
like you struggled.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1036EDT &QL; 
