<DOCNO> NYT19980824.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8816 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMAGE-MYTHS25-COX     08-24 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMAGE-MYTHS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Top tasks: Teaching poise, self-esteem
 &HT;    Sidebar to IMAGE-INTRO
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's more to being image savvy than what frock you wear or
whether your tie's long enough.
</P>
<P>
   And consultants will tell you that whipping someone's wardrobe
into shape is just part of what they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Image is an umbrella term that includes communication as well
as appearance,'' says Mari Lyn Henry, who lives in New York. ``It
includes how people present themselves through their voice. Plus,
there's the nonverbal, like body language and posture.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Tel Aviv-based Tami Lancut Leibovitz says, ``If you teach
someone to dress well, but they don't sit up straight, you haven't
done your job.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a worldwide economy, a growing part of image
development is global etiquette, consultants say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give someone a gift in Japan, for example, you can't
expect that person to open it right away,'' Henry says. ``They
don't tear the paper off and throw the ribbon on the floor like
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're thankful for the act of giving but prefer to open the
gift in private. If you're an American businessperson and don't
know this, you might be taken aback.''
</P>
<P>
   Clare Speigel of Coral Springs teaches not just how to organize
your closet but also how to organize your life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Creating personal style involves more than building a
long-term wardrobe,'' she says. ``It's building self-esteem, which
includes being in control of your time.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney World image specialist Melissa Valiquette, meanwhile,
instructs employees on handshakes, what fork to use, even how to
act at an after-hours party.
</P>
<P>
   And Lauren Castle, publisher of The Image Networker _ an
industry newspaper _ polishes resumes as well as appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to handle all areas of marketing a person when you're
an image consultant,'' she says. ``I can help someone create a
drop-dead resume, then they wear sweats to the interview. So you
can't focus on one area more than another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work to make the entire package appropriate for that person
_ not make that person fit into a mold.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology also has broadened the scope of an image consultant's
duties.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, a client may have sought advice about what to
wear to a board meeting. Nowadays, that same client will want to
know what colors show up best on TV because the meeting will be
video-conferenced.
</P>
<P>
   ``How people look on camera is more important than it's ever
been,'' Henry says. ``That and making an entrance. All stars know
how to do it, but most non-celebs in the business world need
guidance.''
</P>
<P>
   The image profession, however, isn't always about business.
Sometimes, it can be about pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've helped people pick the cologne they're going to wear on
their honeymoon night _ both brides and grooms,'' says Brenda
Kinsel of Fairfax, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I even help people learn how to get dates. That's when my
job is the most fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
