r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RED-ECHO25-COX     08-24 0289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RED-ECHO25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spinoff to develop cartoon series, related software
 &HT;    By Lori Hawkins
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Human Code co-founder Chipp Walters is starting a new
Austin company to develop animated features for television and the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The company, called Red Echo, is working on a Saturday morning
cartoon series called ``Mission to Avalon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan is to produce the Avalon TV series first and build
the brand, and then publish Avalon software,'' said Walters, who
left Human Code earlier this month. ``We think it has a lot of
potential, and we're excited about getting it out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The show tracks the adventures of the Earth's best and brightest
kids on a journey through the galaxy in the 22nd century.
</P>
<P>
   Walters, Liz Walker and Gary Gattis founded Human Code in 1993.
Human Code develops multimedia products for the entertainment,
business and education industries. Walker is Human Code's chief
operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Walters said Red Echo has signed a letter of intent with a
funding group that plans to distribute the show.
</P>
<P>
   As it develops the Avalon product, Red Echo is getting revenue
from multimedia work for corporate clients. Walters also is
providing seed money to get the company off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The company has seven employees, most of whom were formerly at
Human Code.
</P>
<P>
   Walters developed the Avalon concept at Human Code, which has
granted property rights to him. Human Code will receive partial
royalties on sales related to Avalon.
</P>
<P>
   Human Code also will have the option to develop any interactive
Avalon work, such as creating an on-line community.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
