<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Presidential peccadillos highlighted on the Web
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the media frenzy surrounding the current presidential
scandal, it's important to remember that President Clinton isn't
the first president to run afoul of special prosecutors,
bloodthirsty media or a pretty girl.
</P>
<P>
   A quick and witty presidential history lesson from the San Jose
Mercury News traces presidential infidelities all the way back to
Thomas Jefferson, the nation's third president and author of the
Declaration of Independence. The site at
http://www.mercurycenter.com/nation/media/krt/president takes a
lighthearted but comprehensive look at nearly 200 years of scandal
with the cheeky title ``Presidential Peccadillos? Shocked? Don't
Be.'' The site has brief but illuminating looks at presidential
infidelities throughout history with nifty caricatures accompanying
each thumbnail history.
</P>
<P>
   The venerable Washington Post also offers a similar history of
presidential scandals (http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv
</P>
<P>
   /politics/special/clinton/stories/scandalhistory.htm), but it's
bundled with the newspaper's coverage of the Clinton scandal and
lacks the visual punch and breezy style of the Mercury News' site.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the media circus surrounding the Clinton scandal, TV
and cable networks have been turning to former Washington Post
reporters Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein, who more than 25 years
ago broke the story of the break-in at the Watergate Hotel in
Washington and the subsequent trail of cover-ups culminating in
President Nixon's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward and Bernstein have been busy reminding news anchors, TV
pundits and anyone who asks that the Watergate scandal, unlike the
current Clinton debacle, involved crimes and misdemeanors far more
serious than a dangerous liaison in the Oval Office. There was
embezzlement, stealing, burglary, lying and corruption in nearly
every nook and cranny of the executive branch of government.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief Watergate history lesson, start with the Washington
Post article that triggered the newspaper's investigation: http://
</P>
<P>
   washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/tours/scandal
</P>
<P>
   /watergat.htm. The article from June 19, 1972, is simply titled
``GOP Security Aide Among 5 Arrested in Bugging Affair,'' and only
begins to hint at the revelations to come. It's also important to
note that the article also acknowledges the help of six other Post
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   To commemorate the 25th anniversary of Watergate, The Washington
Post has also assembled a sharply designed and informative site to
document Watergate. The Post site offers a cast of characters, a
search engine to locate particular players or events and a
description of what the fuss was all about. There's also a Q&AMP;A with
Woodward and Bernstein, who talk about the mechanics of reporting
potentially disastrous news about the president of the United
States without having to worry about Matt Drudge, Salon or even The
Associated Press beating you to the story.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, digging up dirt on a U.S. president was not something
one did as a matter of course. The site can be a little busy and
hard to read at times, but remember this is the primary source for
information about one of the most significant events in American
history. However, if the graphics and the sheer volume of each
information-packed Web page are too much for you, try
http://vcepolitics.com
</P>
<P>
   /wgate.htm. This site looks like a textbook, but the same
information is there and has a more academic feel than the Post's
``you are there'' aura.
</P>
<P>
   What's new:
</P>
<P>
   Budget Travel: Think you can't afford Hawaii? Well, how does
$189 round trip from San Francisco strike you? Budget Travel
provides tons of information about low fares to destinations around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.budgettravel.com/
</P>
<P>
   Relocation Mall: Like the idea of a human agent managing your
move? Go to the Relocation Mall and fill out a form offering
details like the time frame of your move and how to get in touch
with you. Before you know it, an expert will assist you in finding
that perfect new apartment, mover, roommate or renter's insurance
policy.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.relomall.com/
</P>
<P>
   WWW.Woofs: A ``nonprofit newspaper dedicated to the benefit of
our best buddies,'' WWW.Woofs covers every aspect of a dog's life.
Dog lovers and prospective owners can find information on canine
health care, training tips and techniques, and the when, where and
how of dog adoption.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.woofs.org/
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
