<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marilyn Geewax's Business Commentary: Clinton's pain might
 &HT;    be felt on Main Street
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When he spoke on the Monica Lewinsky matter last week,
President Clinton insisted that his private life should remain
private. Unfortunately, what the president did behind closed doors
with a former White House intern does directly involve all of us
and our wallets.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewinsky scandal may yet lead to Clinton's impeachment. Even
if it does not, his lies have left him politically damaged and far
less able to shape economic policy. When you are the president,
your private problems quickly become our pain.
</P>
<P>
   Already we can see examples of that in Atlanta. Local
entrepreneurs who wanted to begin offering stock to the public this
summer have had to delay or kill their plans because the stock
market has turned so choppy. The volatility is being caused, in
part, by fears about political instability.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout from Clinton's confession could get much worse. For
example, the president may now be too politically weak to assemble
the coalition he needs to win ``fast-track'' authority to negotiate
trade agreements. Without such authority, U.S. exports _ and jobs _
will suffer.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, exports already are slowing because of problems in
Asia. Georgia-Pacific Corp. has had to cut 25 percent of its
pulp-making production because of the drop in orders from Asia.
Georgia companies that produce paper, chemicals, textiles and other
exports must quickly find new markets through ``fast-track'' deals.
</P>
<P>
   Every president since Gerald Ford has had the power to open
markets by negotiating trade agreements and then putting them on a
speedy track through Congress for an up-or-down vote with no
amendments. No country would waste time reaching a trade deal only
to have it rewritten at the last minute by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The House plans to consider fast-track legislation next month.
But does Clinton still have the clout to expand trade the way he
did when he secured the North American Free Trade Agreement?
</P>
<P>
   Congress also needs to approve a $17.9 billion appropriation to
shore up the International Monetary Fund. If Clinton cannot muster
the votes for IMF funding, the Asian and Russian economic crises
could worsen and further hurt our exports.
</P>
<P>
   Global trade isn't the only concern. The president also must
block irresponsible tax cuts that could send the budget deficit
soaring again. He has to put Social Security reform on track, and
make sure both government and industry are fixing the Year 2000
computer bug.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, the president must maintain his image as a strong
leader who can preserve world order. When Clinton approved surprise
missile attacks on terrorist facilities in Sudan and Afghanistan
Thursday, he underscored the United States' vital role as global
cop. A powerful president discourages terrorists who want to
disrupt order and commerce around the world.
</P>
<P>
   If impeachment hearings begin this fall, Congress may have
little energy for other issues. The stock market could become even
more volatile, consumer confidence might wane and terrorists might
become emboldened.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's sensible, centrist policies have
been good for the country. On his watch, trade has expanded amid
relative peace in the world, budget deficits have disappeared,
welfare rolls have shriveled, and the unemployment rate has
tumbled.
</P>
<P>
   This golden era may well end now that Clinton's immoral behavior
has damaged his presidency beyond repair. It's a shame that we will
all have to lie in the bed the president has made.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
