<SLUG> BC-HOMEOWNER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IDA program helps pave way to homeownership
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Homeownership may soon be more than just a dream to
some Georgia residents.
</P>
<P>
   More than two dozen people are participating in an innovative
program designed to open the door to homeownership.
</P>
<P>
   The IDA (the individual development account) Home Ownership
Program is similar to incentive-based savings programs across the
country and is at work in three metro Atlanta neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   In Norcross, a person's savings account is matched 4-to-1 by the
United Way of Metro Atlanta, which has lined up contributions from
corporations. Participants agree to deposit $50 a month into a
special account, said Nancy Macleod, a housing counselor for the
Gwinnett Housing Resource Partnership in Norcross. If someone puts
$150 in the account, the United Way would contribute another $600.
</P>
<P>
   The matched funds are not available until the person is ready to
buy a home. The program's first new homeowner was scheduled to
close a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
   The program is also under way in two central city areas,
Reynoldstown and the Old Fourth Ward. Plans call for the expansion
of the program into two additional communities, said Eric Muschler,
United Way director of community and economic development.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals and communities benefit. ``It's going to revitalize
and reinvigorate the neighborhood,'' Macleod said. At the same
time, participants can clean up bad credit and develop sound money
management skills.
</P>
<P>
   Participants include hairstylists, secretaries, sales
representatives and schoolteachers. The minimum income ranges from
$19,150 for a single person to $57,750 for a family of eight.
</P>
<P>
   The program also helps participants learn more about managing
money and credit, the home-buying process and maintenance of a
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the program is economic literacy training, which
really talks about how families develop wealth, and buying a home
is the most significant aspect of wealth creation,'' said United
Way's Muschler. ``We're creating good neighbors as well as
opportunities for individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
