<SLUG> BC-BANKER-DEAD25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bankers association chief dies
 &HT;    By Earl Golz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Robert E. Harris, president and chief executive
of the Texas Bankers Association, the largest and oldest state
banking organization in the nation, was found dead of a heart
attack Friday, August 21, in Madison, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, 54, led the association, a trade group for 700 banks,
through the bank failures of the 1980s and into the banking
industry's recovery and record profits in the early 1990s. His
death came as the group was discussing a possible merger with the
smaller Independent Bankers Association of Texas, which represents
community banks.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Banking Commissioner Catherine Ghiglieri said Harris'
passing represents a ``great loss to the banking industry. He was a
very strong advocate for the Texas Bankers Association and their
issues. He is going to be missed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a terrible tragedy and a shock to all of us,'' said
Steve Scurlock, senior vice president of the Independent Bankers
Association of Texas. Scurlock worked for Harris at the Texas
Bankers Association from 1991 to 1995. ``Bob had done a good job
leading the Texas Bankers Association into prosperous times from
what was basically a de facto depression in the banking industry
and the Texas economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris became president of the group in 1988. During his tenure,
the bankers association expanded to represent other financial
institutions, including savings and loan associations, trust
companies and savings banks.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to joining the Texas association, Harris served as chief
executive of the Oklahoma Bankers Association for eight years,
preceded by five years as chief executive of the Nebraska Bankers
Association. He also was senior executive vice president of the
First National Bank of Lincoln, Neb.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the board of directors of the Graduate School of
Banking at the University of Wisconsin, he was in Madison to attend
a board meeting when he died.
</P>
<P>
   He is a past chairman of the State Association Division of the
American Bankers Association and of the Central States Conference
of Bankers Associations and has served as a member of ABA's
Government Relations Council.
</P>
<P>
   He also was a member of the boards of directors of the Graduate
School of Banking at Louisiana State University, the Southwestern
Graduate School of Banking at Southern Methodist University, of
PULSE EFT and the executive committee of BancInsure, an insurance
company for banks owned by banking associations. He also was a
founding director of the Institute for Certified Bankers, a
nationwide banker certification program.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, Betty Jo, three sons, one daughter,
three grandchildren and his parents.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
