<HEADER>
A8833 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMER-WATCH25-COX     08-24 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-WATCH25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Buyer beware when using prepaid phone cards
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a big time of year for college students and prepaid
phone cards. Tens of thousands of students are returning to class,
and many are carrying prepaid cards with them.
</P>
<P>
   The prepaid cards are very convenient but, for some of the
students, they may also serve as their No. 1 consumer lesson:
caveat emptor, let the buyer beware.
</P>
<P>
   Prepaid cards are marketed by about 500 firms, and about 300
million cards are sold annually, according to the International
Telecard Association. Students _ or their parents _ are major
purchasers because of the convenience the cards offer for calling
home.
</P>
<P>
   The cards are also sold in large numbers to travelers; to
immigrants who often call overseas; and to people, such as
prisoners, who don't have normal access to phone service. Others
buy the cards for ``emergency use,'' perhaps when their car breaks
down and they have no change for a pay phone.
</P>
<P>
   Prepaid cards typically range in price from $5 to $25, and they
are sold at various retail outlets, including convenience stores,
newsstands, drugstores and groceries.
</P>
<P>
   The cards are marketed by firms that buy time from lotance
carriers at wholesale rates, mark up the price and sell it to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   To use a prepaid card, you dial an 800 access number, punch in
your card number, then dial the number you are calling. This is
very convenient, but with the convenience comes a need to shop
carefully. Keep these things in mind:
</P>
<P>
   -- Most prepaid cards are marketed by legitimate firms, but some
are bad deals, even frauds. The card doesn't work, or the service
is very poor, or you are hit with undisclosed surcharges when you
make calls. To check the card's quality, buy a small-denomination
one first, say $5, to test the service.
</P>
<P>
   -- Per-minute charges vary tremendously from card to card. They
normally are higher than regular phone charges, but not always.
Most honest cards disclose their U.S. rates on the package or
vending machine. Some cards charge a minimum amount, regardless of
the length of the call. This should be disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   -- Before buying a card, look for a toll-free customer
assistance number on the card or vending machine and call it. If
the number is constantly busy or not answered, or if there is no
customer service number, that's a red flag.
</P>
<P>
   -- Perhaps the best way to find a good prepaid phone card is to
do as you might with other services or products: Ask for
recommendations from friends or relatives who have used prepaid
cards.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
