<HEADER>
A8836 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEART-SELTZER25-COX     08-24 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-SELTZER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    West Palm Beach man's heart 'beautiful' after 50 years of study
 &HT;    By Ron Hayes
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ On Sept. 27, the city of Framingham, Mass.,
will honor the 10,000-plus men and women who have taken part in the
largest, longest and most productive study of heart disease in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   After careful consideration, Samuel Seltzer has decided not to
make the trip from his Century Village apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' he says, waving the very idea out the window. ``What do
I wanna do that for?''
</P>
<P>
   The famous Framingham Heart Study turned 50 this year, and
Seltzer turned 103.
</P>
<P>
   Both are still going strong.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, when the U.S. Public Health Service decided to study
heart disease, Framingham was chosen because it offered a stable
population with low unemployment, an ethnic mix and proximity to
Boston's teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Seltzer was 53 at the time, a native of Russia who came to the
United States in 1919. _ ``It cost me $52.'' He'd started out with
a horse and cart, peddling clothes around Framingham, and worked
hard until he owned a store.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't ask me much,'' he remembers. ``They wouldn't take
my wife, but they liked me. They checked me a lot of times.''
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the study agreed to be examined every two years.
After his wife's death in 1969, Seltzer moved to Long Island, then
to Century Village in 1977. His examinations became infrequent, but
the study sent a nurse to examine him four years ago, while he was
visiting his children on Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart, they told me it's beautiful,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But not the oldest heart they've ever seen. Esta Shindler, a
study spokeswoman, says that honor goes to a woman three months
older than Seltzer, who's confined to a Canadian nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   But people listen when a 103-year-old man who still lives alone
offers health tips:
</P>
<P>
   ``Every night, I go to bed at 7 p.m., and I'm up at 5 a.m.,'' he
explains. ``When it's clear, I walk a quarter-mile to services
every morning. Then I come back and have breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast is All-Bran, Raisin Bran or Cheerios, a slice of
pumpernickel bread and _ this is important _ juice diluted with a
little water.
</P>
<P>
   Lunch is fruit cocktail or cottage cheese, with a slice of
pumpernickel and a glass of milk _ diluted with a little water.
</P>
<P>
   For dinner, boiled eggs and tuna fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't take much ice cream,'' Seltzer says with a shrug. ``A
little vanilla.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than a sip or two of wine at Passover, he has not drunk
alcohol, and he never smoked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is,'' he says, holding up a finger for attention,
``I didn't eat what I don't like.''
</P>
<P>
   During Seltzer's 103 years, he has seen America change from a
place where horse carts were common to a place men leave to walk on
the moon.
</P>
<P>
   What's the most impressive change he's seen?
</P>
<P>
   Seltzer thinks a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to buy a suit of clothes for $30,'' he says. ``Now
you'd pay $90.''
</P>
<P>
   He shakes his head in amazement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, listen,'' he says, ``I'm doing the best I can, and
whenever it comes, I'm ready. I live from day to day. I don't
expect miracles.''
</P>
<P>
   The clock says 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should be in bed by now,'' Seltzer says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
