<DOCNO> NYT19980824.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8839 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BONNIE25-COX     08-24 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bonnie gives Florida a near miss
 &HT;    By Joel Engelhardt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hurricane Bonnie, its winds churning at 115 mph, followed a
track to keep it far out to sea when it passes Palm Beach County
tonight, according to forecasts from the National Hurricane Center
in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters don't expect the 300-mile-wide storm to hit land,
saying it should be 250 miles out to sea and as far north as South
Carolina by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   They put the chance of Bonnie hitting Palm Beach County at 5
percent and the Treasure Coast at 7 percent. They expect the
Category 3 storm to be more than 400 hundred miles out to sea when
it passes South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   As a Category 3 hurricane, Bonnie is considered capable of
causing severe coastal flooding and serious damage to buildings and
homes if it nears land.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Andrew, which hit south of Miami six years ago today,
carried recorded winds of 145 mph, making it a Category 4 storm.
Forecasters, whose instruments failed them, believed Andrew's winds
were much stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie slowed to about 5 mph Saturday night after initially
racing across the ocean at speeds of close to 20 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters cautioned _ as spooked residents already knew _ that
it was too early to say exactly what Hurricane Bonnie would do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're keeping the (possible landfall) area pretty broad
because it isn't moving, it's just meandering a little bit,'' said
center meteorologist Michelle Huber. ``We're not letting anybody
off the hook.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales of hurricane supplies such as plywood and water slowed
Sunday in Palm Beach County and the Treasure Coast as residents
took note of the hurricane's path.
</P>
<P>
   Mead, Eastpak and Bic took the place of Duracell, Evian and
Energizer as the hot products at a Target store in Delray Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have many more people interested in back-to-school
supplies. . .today,'' manager Gary Black said.
</P>
<P>
   The Home Depot near Royal Palm Beach brought in extra cashiers
but sent them home early when business didn't pick up where it left
off Saturday, assistant store manager Kevin Wagaman said.
</P>
<P>
   The storm moving slightly northward was 180 miles east-northeast
of San Salvador in the Bahamas at 8 p.m., centered near latitude
24.8 north, longitude 71.8 west. But the hurricane center said it
was expected to turn to the northwest later Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The computer models remain consistent with the slow turn to
the northwest,'' said Daniel Brown, another meterologist with the
hurricane center. ``They feel pretty confident that it will happen.
It's still worth watching. The official forecast has it going 250
miles east of the Carolinas.''
</P>
<P>
   The coastline, Brown noted, was within the 300-mile margin of
error of the three-day forecast. Any possible landfall would be
late Tuesday, but already a heavy surf advisory was posted from
Jupiter Inlet to Brunswick, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane dwarfed the sparsely populated Bahamian islands,
drenching them with some rain and gusty winds. Its worst
thunderstorms battered the open seas to its north, said National
Hurricane Center forecaster John Guiney.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lucky thing is ... the Bahamas will not be feeling the
full brunt of the storm,'' he said. But he noted that Bonnie has
been ``very erratic ... meandering around,'' making forecasts less
reliable.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew blasted its way ashore around 4 a.m. Aug. 24, 1992,
pummeling south Dade County for five hours until 100,000 homes and
80,000 businesses had been damaged or destroyed. Parts of
Homestead, just south of Miami, were practically leveled. Chaos
reigned as residents faced a wasteland without electricity or food;
animals, even escaped monkeys, roamed; and swindlers moved in to
take advantage of the confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Tad DeMilly, who was mayor of Homestead then, said the town of
24,000 still has not recovered economically. Fully 90 percent of it
was affected, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want it to turn to the north soon, then immediately to the
east, and get rid of it,'' he said. ``We don't want anybody else to
go through what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post reporters Rachel Masory, Seth Mnookin and Joe
Viduiera contributed to this story, which was supplemented with
information from wire stories.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
