<HEADER>
A8843 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN25-COX     08-24 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: I had eveything to do with my son's success
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio. _ My son Kristofor was an early talker - just
about 11months that sultry July afternoon he stuck his first words
together.
</P>
<P>
   I was putting him down for a nap when he declared: ``Mmm wants
Pwacky.'' Translation: ``Bring me Pyewacket (the cat).'' He wasn't
about to close an eye without his best Siamese buddy by his side. I
was thrilled. ``It was an entire sentence!''
</P>
<P>
   I proudly babbled to anyone who would listen.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week later, he hotfooted it into the kitchen
(another surprise since he hadn't bothered to let me know he was
walking), grabbed a handful of my leg, and demanded: ``Drammich,
Momma!''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``I'm hungry woman; how about a sandwich?''
</P>
<P>
   Unprepared as I was for the finer points of motherhood, my
budding orator caught me with my signs down, an oversight I quickly
remedied.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, everything in the house had a label stuck to it...except,
of course, Pyewacket, whose dignity would have been offended at
being labeled a C-A-T.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spell it, Momma,'' young son would command and point.
``P-I-A-N-O'' I'd carefully sound out and then pronounce:
``Piano.''
</P>
<P>
   ``P-I-A-N-O'' he'd copycat. ``Paano.'' Close enough. Soon it was
routine.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever I said to him, he'd insist I spell it first. And when I
reminded him, ``It's time for B-E-D,'' he would answer in kind:
``N-O,'' which of course called for bribery. ``How about an
S-T-O-R-Y?'' I'd ask. He'd grin, grab Pooh bear by his remaining
ear, and spell, ``O-K.''
</P>
<P>
   And so my son's fascination with words and their meanings had
begun.
</P>
<P>
   He was reading before he started kindergarten. No Plato or James
Joyce, but he could rip his way through Sendak and Scarry like a
pro. ``Storytime!'' he'd announce as he grabbed his book of the
moment and headed for his room. That meant the cats and I were to
follow him down the hall and join him in his bottom bunk. After a
brief, extemporaneous introduction, he'd read us all to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Kristofor was 14 when he joined the high school debate team. It
was no surprise that he began bringing home trophies he'd earned
with his silver-tongued shmooz. I already knew this kid could argue
the horns off a Billy goat and it didn't make a bit of difference
whether or not he knew anything about the topic under discussion.
He could invent believable facts faster than a politician on a
platform, which came in
</P>
<P>
   real handy once he started driving.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, as the years passed and the boy eased into manhood, I
found myself basking in the spillover of his various
accomplishments. When he graduated from high school with that gold
cord around his neck attesting to his honor student status, I
secretly congratulated myself for having done all of the right
stuff when he was just a sprout. Later, when he was accepted into a
particularly selective grad school program, I was convinced it was
my love, affection, and dedication that had brought him this far.
</P>
<P>
   But that was last week. This week all the talk is about a book
written by a New Jersey grandmother who claims parents have little
or nothing to do with their children's successes or failures.
</P>
<P>
   According to ``The Nurture Assumption'' by Judith Rich Harris, a
writer of psychology textbooks, the only thing a parent contributes
to a kid is genes (not limited to the designer kind), which leaves
me out in limbo land if my adopted heir-apparent buys into the
book. Ms. Harris allows that environment counts, but not the home
kind _ more the peer group and schoolhouse kind. She insists that
the person a child becomes has little or nothing to do with how his
parents brought him up, hence the statement: Sometimes good parents
just have bad children.
</P>
<P>
   Okay, that comes under the heading: ``Stuff happens.''
Meanwhile, how am to explain to my 31-year-old son that all of his
accomplishments do NOT stem from my devoted parenting? That his
successes are in no way related to my chocolate chip cookies and
erudite chat? Or even worse _ that my nagging was in vain?
</P>
<P>
   Time to come clean. I call my son and confess. You know what he
says?
</P>
<P>
   ``Bull!''
</P>
<P>
   That's what he says.
</P>
<P>
   So there, Ms. Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett is a writer and teacher in Gibsonburg, Ohio.
She may be e-mailed at: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
