r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEATURES-BJT25-COX     08-24 1410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURES-BJT25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE TUESDAY FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These stories for release Tuesday, August 25, 1998, are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   NEWSMAG-GLUT _ If there's one thing you've probably already
noticed on TV and will notice even more this fall, it's
newsmagazine shows. There are so many, and they are so cheap to
produce, that they are taking over the spots traditionally held by
one-hour dramas. And this is not pleasing TV people like Law &AMP;
Order's Dick Wolf and others, who see this as a bad trend for TV
viewers. (Thompson, Palm Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TV-CHARMED _ They're back! Shannen Dougherty stars in WB's
``Charmed.'' 10. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURFER-COLUMN _ PBS airs ``Mind Traveller,'' an interesting
series involving health issues. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA
8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   STATION _ CD reviews: Emmylou Harris' ``Spyboy'' (John T), Bob
Mould's ``The Last Dog and Pony Show'' (Chris R), Korn's ``Follow
the Leader'' (Chris R), James Brown's ``Say It Live and Loud''
(McLeese), Tripping Daisy's ``Jesus Hits Like the Atom Bomb''
(Kberg). (Austin American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSTAND _ Newsstand column. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   RED-ECHO _ AUSTIN _ Human Code co-founder Chipp Walters is
starting a new Austin company to develop animated features for
television and the Internet. The company, called Red Echo, is
working on a Saturday morning cartoon series called ``Mission to
Avalon.'' The show tracks the adventures of the Earth's best and
brightest kids on a journey through the galaxy in the 22nd century.
(Hawkins, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN-WARNER _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Time Warner Cable will launch a
local all-news, 24-hour television channel next spring _ a
CNN-style station for Austin. It will report on local news, sports,
weather and special features from Austin and Central Texas,
operating from a 20,000-square-foot studio that will be built at
16th and Colorado streets. Time Warner will most likely change the
format of an existing television channel for the news channel,
officials said. (Breyer, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ON-BOOKS _ Jim Shepard's novel ``Nosferatu'' (Knopf, $22)
studiously keeps you at arm's length throughout, but it belongs on
that short but select shelf reserved for fictional treatments of
the silent film era: Howard Rodman's ``Destiny Express'' (about
Fritz Lang), John Baxter's ``The Kid'' (about Charlie Chaplin) and
Garson Kanin's ``Moviola,'' among others. And other news on books.
(Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   MARRIAGE _ Talking to couples who have lived in the public eye
for some time and who have managed to stay faithful to one another.
In the wake of the continuing Clinton scandal, they talk about
fidelity, publicity, love and committment . (Austin
American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   IMAGE-MAIN _ They know about skirts cut like carwash flaps and
platform sneakers and nail polish in blue. But they also know to
avoid all this. Although image consultants are fashion experts,
they're hardly fashion sheep. You won't, as a rule, find them
lumbering off a cliff into fad land, teeny backpacks a-bouncing.
``We don't do trendy,'' says Irene Nathan of London, in Miami last
month for the Association of Image Consultants International
convention. (Grantham, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IMAGE-CUTS _ Quotes on fashion. (Grantham, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IMAGE-MYTHS _ There's more to being image savvy than what frock
you wear or whether your tie's long enough. Or as Tel Aviv-based
Tami Lancut Leibovitz says, ``If you teach someone to dress well,
but they don't sit up straight, you haven't done your job.'' Thanks
to a worldwide economy, a growing part of image development is
global etiquette, consultants say. (Grantham, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE (a and/or l category)
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-TEST _ Dr. Douglas Smith, an emergency-room doctor at Good
Samaritan Medical Center, is developing an at-home kit that tests
for marijuana, cocaine, amphetamines, opium and heroin. He plans to
hand out kits free to parents. (Warejcka, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HEART-SELTZER _ WEST PALM BEACH _ On Sept. 27, the city of
Framingham, Mass., will honor the 10,000-plus men and women who
have taken part in the largest, longest and most productive study
of heart disease in the world. The famous Framingham Heart Study
turned 50 this year, and Samuel Seltzer turned 103. Both are still
going strong. (Hayes, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ ATLANTA _ The Encyclopaedia Britannica has been
published since 1768, and in the 230 years since its founding in
Edinburgh, Scotland, the venerable reference work has saved
countless numbers of students who waited until the night before an
essay was due to start writing. In July the company opened another
chapter in its long history by launching eBLAST. (Ghirardini,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ ATLANTA _ This week was one of the most important
in Apple Computer's recent history. It marked the company's
re-entry into the consumer market. And it was quite a debut. Star
of the ball was its iMac computer, a model that includes a built-in
screen and retails for $1,299. It's the best deal Apple Computer
has ever offered on a new computer. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ A quick and witty presidential history lesson from
the San Jose Mercury News traces presidential infidelities all the
way back to Thomas Jefferson, the nation's third president and
author of the Declaration of Independence. The site at
http://www.mercurycenter.com/nation/media/krt/president takes a
lighthearted but comprehensive look at nearly 200 years of scandal
with the cheeky title ``Presidential Peccadillos? Shocked? Don't
Be.'' (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DIGICAM _ Perfect for the impatient, the computer geek or anyone
who wants to see photos in seconds, these hand-held and sometimes
pocket-sized cameras allow you to snap pictures, and see the images
on a computer screen or on paper within minutes. And you can use
your computer to edit the photographs _ no darkroom required.
(Swartz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DIGICAM-SIDE _ List of information on digital cameras. (Swartz,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ For those who are middle-aged or older, the Year
2000 had a magical sort of feeling. Back in the '60s and '70s, the
new millennium was seen as almost impossibly far away. And, if
folks thought about a Year 2000 problem at all back then, the
problem was in living that long. The Year 2000 is almost here now.
It's no longer magical. And, for the governments and businesses of
the world, it is a multi-billion dollar problem. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ Most folks strain and fret too much when getting
ready to buy a new PC. They study magazines, ask friends, consult
psychics and hang out in computer stores. Truth is _ until recently
_ you could do pretty well by simply setting a budget for how much
you can afford to spend on a PC, then shopping for the most
powerful machine you can find in that price range. Well, if you are
one of those fretters I was talking about, do I have good news for
you. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-TOOLS _ ATLANTA _ My (relatively) new computer is equipped
with a DVD-ROM drive, a technology for which little appears to be
available presently, so I had to go afield for something with which
I could make valid comparisons. For the purpose, Microsoft sent me
the DVD, or digital video disc, version of its popular Encarta
Deluxe encyclopedia. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
