<P>
   These stories for release Tuesday, August 25, 1998, are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   NEWSMAG-GLUT _ If there's one thing you've probably already
noticed on TV and will notice even more this fall, it's
newsmagazine shows. There are so many, and they are so cheap to
produce, that they are taking over the spots traditionally held by
one-hour dramas. And this is not pleasing TV people like Law &AMP;
Order's Dick Wolf and others, who see this as a bad trend for TV
viewers. (Thompson, Palm Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TV-CHARMED _ They're back! Shannen Dougherty stars in WB's
``Charmed.'' 10. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURFER-COLUMN _ PBS airs ``Mind Traveller,'' an interesting
series involving health issues. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA
8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   STATION _ CD reviews: Emmylou Harris' ``Spyboy'' (John T), Bob
Mould's ``The Last Dog and Pony Show'' (Chris R), Korn's ``Follow
the Leader'' (Chris R), James Brown's ``Say It Live and Loud''
(McLeese), Tripping Daisy's ``Jesus Hits Like the Atom Bomb''
(Kberg). (Austin American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSTAND _ Newsstand column. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   RED-ECHO _ AUSTIN _ Human Code co-founder Chipp Walters is
starting a new Austin company to develop animated features for
television and the Internet. The company, called Red Echo, is
working on a Saturday morning cartoon series called ``Mission to
Avalon.'' The show tracks the adventures of the Earth's best and
brightest kids on a journey through the galaxy in the 22nd century.
(Hawkins, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN-WARNER _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Time Warner Cable will launch a
local all-news, 24-hour television channel next spring _ a
CNN-style station for Austin. It will report on local news, sports,
weather and special features from Austin and Central Texas,
operating from a 20,000-square-foot studio that will be built at
16th and Colorado streets. Time Warner will most likely change the
format of an existing television channel for the news channel,
officials said. (Breyer, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ON-BOOKS _ Jim Shepard's novel ``Nosferatu'' (Knopf, $22)
studiously keeps you at arm's length throughout, but it belongs on
that short but select shelf reserved for fictional treatments of
the silent film era: Howard Rodman's ``Destiny Express'' (about
Fritz Lang), John Baxter's ``The Kid'' (about Charlie Chaplin) and
Garson Kanin's ``Moviola,'' among others. And other news on books.
(Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
