<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8859 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN25-COX     08-24 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Joke lifting a common failure among reporters, including
me
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Barnicle, who wrote a fine column for the Boston Globe for
25 years,
</P>
<P>
   resigned recently after a weeks-long furor over stolen jokes and
fabricated
</P>
<P>
   stories.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Barnicle was suspended without pay after lifting some
jokes from
</P>
<P>
   comedian George Carlin's book without properly attributing them.
The paper
</P>
<P>
   asked him to resign but then backed down when he refused and
hundreds of
</P>
<P>
   readers raised Cain about his imminent departure.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle says he used jokes friends told him or he found on the
Internet,
</P>
<P>
   and he had never read Carlin's book. Trouble is, Barnicle, who
appears
</P>
<P>
   regularly on a Boston TV station, had plugged the book a month
or so before.
</P>
<P>
   He still says he never actually read the book, and that's his
story and he's
</P>
<P>
   sticking to it.
</P>
<P>
   Then he resigned after it became obvious he had made up entire
parts of a
</P>
<P>
   column several years ago. He should have quit. Stealing jokes is
one thing.
</P>
<P>
   Making up stories and pretending they're true ought to get any
journalist
</P>
<P>
   canned.
</P>
<P>
   I found this story fascinating and sad, for two reasons. The
Boston Globe
</P>
<P>
   is one of the newspapers I grew up reading, so it's always held
a warm place
</P>
<P>
   in my heart. I got my addiction to ink on paper reading the
Globe, its
</P>
<P>
   blue-collar competitor the Boston Record-American, and then the
New
</P>
<P>
   Hampshire papers, the staid, classy Concord Monitor, and the
right-wing
</P>
<P>
   foaming-at-the-mouth Manchester Union-Leader. The latter's
publisher then
</P>
<P>
   was William Loeb, who made Ed Muskie cry in 1968 while running
for
</P>
<P>
   president, effectively ending his campaign. My dad, a commercial
artist, did
</P>
<P>
   occasional free-lance editorial cartoons for the Union-Leader in
the late
</P>
<P>
   1950s. I remember one cartoon he drew showing Russia's Kruschev
wearing
</P>
<P>
   devil horns just before the famed Kitchen Debate with Nixon.
Subtlety was
</P>
<P>
   not a virtue at the Union-Leader, and my dad understood that.
</P>
<P>
   The Union-Leader is still right-wing but considerably better
</P>
<P>
   journalistically under Loeb's widow. The Concord Monitor, to
which my mother
</P>
<P>
   still subscribes, is one of the finest small dailies in the
country. The
</P>
<P>
   Boston Globe is owned now by The New York Times, while the
Record-American is still a delightfully trashy tabloid.
</P>
<P>
   The second reason I avidly read every word I could about the
Barnicle saga
</P>
<P>
   is that I constantly steal jokes, puns and one-liners for
columns. If you
</P>
<P>
   read a joke or pun in my column, the odds are overwhelming that
I stole it.
</P>
<P>
   There, I said it.
</P>
<P>
   There is a difference, however. I have always freely admitted
that I stole
</P>
<P>
   the material, whether I got it over the Internet - the world's
best resource
</P>
<P>
   for jokes and puns - or a friend told it to me. And I tell where
I stole it
</P>
<P>
   from.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is wonderful because:
</P>
<P>
   There are millions of jokes floating around in cyberspace, no
doubt
</P>
<P>
   contributing to a decrease in productivity among white-collar
workers.
</P>
<P>
   The jokes are written down.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, I can just cut and paste them into my column. This is a
good thing,
</P>
<P>
   because my ability to remember jokes ranks right up there with
my ability to
</P>
<P>
   dunk a basketball into a regulation goal. Zip. Zilch. I am
</P>
<P>
   punchline-challenged. I have mangled jokes so badly that
listeners thought I
</P>
<P>
   had lapsed into tongues. But I can cut and paste them with the
best.
</P>
<P>
   Since I recently wrote a column with a few stolen jokes and
one-liners in
</P>
<P>
   it, I have been happily deluged with one-liners and such from
readers across
</P>
<P>
   the country. One reader, in Moline, Illinois, wants to know what
the heck
</P>
<P>
   ``Nacogdoches'' means. ``Sounds like a Mexican greeting,'' he
wrote. I set him
</P>
<P>
   straight in a hurry. Another reader, in Lima, Ohio, sent a
rather ribald
</P>
<P>
   joke that can't be printed in a family newspaper. And yet
another, writing
</P>
<P>
   from the anonymity of cyberspace, sent:
</P>
<P>
   10 Words That Don't Exist, But Should
</P>
<P>
   Hope you enjoy. Remember, I stole these. I'm admitting it.
</P>
<P>
   1. AQUADEXTROUS (ak wa deks' trus) adj. Possessing the ability
to turn the
</P>
<P>
   bathroom faucet on and off with your toes.
</P>
<P>
   2. CARPERPETUATION (kar' pur pet u a shun) n. The act, when
vacuuming, of
</P>
<P>
   running over a string or a piece of lint at least a dozen times,
reaching
</P>
<P>
   over and picking it up, examining it, then putting it back down
to give the
</P>
<P>
   vacuum one more chance.
</P>
<P>
   3. DISCONFECT (dis kon fekt') v. To sterilize the piece of candy
you
</P>
<P>
   dropped on the floor by blowing on it, assuming this will
somehow ``remove''
</P>
<P>
   all the germs.
</P>
<P>
   4. ELBONICS (el bon' iks) n. The actions of two people
maneuvering for one
</P>
<P>
   armrest in a movie theater or airplane.
</P>
<P>
   5. FRUST (frust) n. The small line of debris that refuses to be
swept onto
</P>
<P>
   the dust pan and keeps backing a person across the room until he
finally
</P>
<P>
   decides to give up and sweep it under the rug.
</P>
<P>
   6. LACTOMANGULATION (lak' to man guy lay' shun) n. Manhandling
the ``open here'' spout on a milk container so badly that one has
to resort to the
</P>
<P>
   ``illegal'' side.
</P>
<P>
   7. PEPPIER (pehp ee ay') n. The waiter at a fancy restaurant
whose sole
</P>
<P>
   purpose seems to be walking around asking diners if they want
ground pepper.
</P>
<P>
   8 PHONESIA (fo nee' zhuh) n. The affliction of dialing a phone
number and
</P>
<P>
   forgetting whom you were calling just as they answer.
</P>
<P>
   9. PUPKUS (pup'kus) n. The moist residue left on a window after
a dog
</P>
<P>
   presses its nose to it.
</P>
<P>
   10.TELECRASTINATION (tel e kras tin ay' shun) n. The act of
always letting
</P>
<P>
   the phone ring at least twice before you pick it up, even when
you're only
</P>
<P>
   six inches away.
</P>
<P>
   Hang in there, Mike. Maybe the Record-American needs a good
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His
</P>
<P>
   e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
