<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8873 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YELTSIN-SHOULD-RESIGN     08-24 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YELTSIN-SHOULD-RESIGN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 YELTSIN SHOULD CALL FOR NEW PRESIDENTIAL and PARLIAMENTARY
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Just weeks ago, after many rounds of hard bargaining, the IMF
finally authorized a $22.6 billion loan package for Russia.
Meanwhile, the Russian markets have continued to plunge and fears
of a total inflationary collapse persist. Despite initial optimism
from the IMF, investors are asking hard questions about progress,
before putting money into Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all this, the ordinary men and women on the street are
