<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
  
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, Aug. 24, 1998
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TERRORIST-KIN (San Antonio) _ Terror suspect Osama bin Laden had
an older half-brother who lived and worked in Central Texas until
his death in a 1988 ultralight aircraft crash. Friends of Salem bin
Laden say his family disowned Osama bin Laden as the younger man's
politics and world view turned militantly anti-American in the
1980s. By SUZANNE HOHOLIK and TRAVIS E. POLING.
</P>
<P>
   ACUPUNCTURE (Undated) _ Acupuncture, especially for pain
management, is becoming increasingly common. HMOs are starting to
pay for the ancient Chinese therapy, and last week the California
Legislature sent the governor a bill requiring workers'
compensation policies to cover it. Many already do. By ULYSSES
TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YIP-COLUMN (Undated) _ When picking stocks it is easy to get the
numbers on the company's revenues and profits. What is hard is
evaluating whether the executives running the company are any good.
By PAMELA YIP.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FREETHINKERS (Boerne, Texas) _ Latin is no longer their language
of choice, but freethinkers still are debating the great issues of
the day _ just as their forefathers did 150 years ago. ``We talk
politics. We talk religion. We talk about whatever's on our
minds,'' says Julie Fisher of Texas Hill Country Freethinkers. By
ZEKE MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-UNIFORMS (Albany, N.Y.) _ As more schools adopt uniform
policies to lessen peer pressure about fashion and to instill a
serious, disciplined atmosphere, a whole new market is opening up
for designers and retailers. By MICHAEL LOPEZ.
</P>
<P>
   CARRIAGE-LANTERNS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Carriage lamps or lanterns
add the feeling of an earlier time to a home. These sturdy lanterns
were originally used on road coaches and carriages of the 18th and
19th centuries to provide safety and illumination, just as car
headlights do today. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   URBAN-CREEP (Bandera, Texas) _ Pushed by San Antonio residents
buying into the rural lifestyle, property in nearby Bandera County
has surpassed $1 billion in market value for the first time.
Despite the sprawl, much of this 797-square-mile county remains
undeveloped and is farm or ranchland. By ZEKE MacCORMAK.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A reader wants to know about compost.
How is it beneficial, and how can we make this special material in
our home gardens? By KATHY HUBER
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-DIANA-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Day Diana Died,'' by
Christopher Anderson, is a meticulous account of the final days of
Diana's life, which ended in a car accident on Aug. 31, 1997. By
CLIFFORD PUGH.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-CHILDREN-REVIEW (Undated) _ Jon Scieszka and Lane Smith,
the dynamic duo that produced ``Math Curse'' and ``The Stinky
Cheese Man and Other Fairly Stupid Tales,'' have moved on to fables
with ``Squids Will Be Squids, Fresh Morals, Beastly Fables''
(Viking, $17.99). These are read-aloud stories, mostly because they
are so funny you can't keep them to yourself. By JANE P. MARSHALL.
</P>
<P>
   TV-NEWS-JOBS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Television news directors at
stations across the nation are growing increasingly concerned that
males, particularly qualified and experienced male anchors, are not
just hard to find, but simply don't exist. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (``i'')
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-MALARIA (Mexico City) _ With more than 10,000 known cases
so far this year, the southeastern Mexican state of Oaxaca is
fighting an epidemic of malaria, a Pan American World Health
Organization official says. By PHILIP TRUE.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-McGWIRE (New York) _ Flashbulbs blink at every pitch now,
shining thousands of points of light on Mark McGwire. People know
they are witnessing something special, something they'd like to see
and feel and touch and taste as long as they live. McGwire gets
standing ovations when he lumbers to the plate for batting
practice. By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Houston) _ In baseball, August is referred to as
the ``dog days'' of a long, arduous season. Seems baseball and
travel have much in common _ except, in this instance, several
readers urge this columnist's banishment to the doghouse for
suggesting that first-rate B&AMP;Bs owe guests a hot, freshly prepared
breakfast in a formal setting. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   ARDUOUS-VACATIONS (Undated) _ The majority of Americans opt for
vacations at the beach, Disneyland or a Carnival Cruise. But if you
feel an inexplicable attraction to the adventurous, you're a
candidate to join the tens of thousands of Americans annually who
volunteer their vacation time for what they believe to be a
righteous cause. By VICKI HADDOCK.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Polls show Americans are happy
about last week, because two days after Bill Clinton admitted being
a liar, he shot $100 million worth of fireworks at bad guys holed
up in two beggar nations. He was ``sending a message,'' the form of
warfare used by a president more concerned with symbolism than
substance, and more concerned with not taking losses than winning.
By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The disappointment among
President Clinton's usual supporters and friends with his
restrained confession to the nation early last week is a tell tale
sign that this country is in for a rough two years no matter how
this deplorable affair eventually concludes. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ When it comes to mid-life
hanky-panky, Gov. George W. Bush is no President Clinton, and
Texans of all political persuasions can be thankful for that.
Although public officials are entitled to some privacy, their
constituents also are entitled to expect those lives to be guided
by a moral compass that doesn't seem to be in need of constant
repair. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   CLACK-COLUMN (San Antonio) _ Bill Clinton is a good president
who could have been a great president. None of the other men who
has occupied the Oval Office in this century was as intellectually
and politically gifted as he. But he has allowed his Achilles' heel
of deceit to slay his legacy. By CARY CLACK.
</P>
<P>
   RICHTER-COLUMN (San Antonio) _ Out of all the millions of good
men and women in this country, how did we get Bill Clinton? He
burst in like a young missionary full of ideas, but now he's the
house guest who stayed too long _ who's freeloading, lounging in
his underwear and eying our wives and daughters. By BOB RICHTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
