<HEADER>
A8893 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUTURE-OF-HEALTH-LIFE     08-24 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUTURE-OF-HEALTH-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL BREAKTHROUGHS YOU CAN TOUCH
</HEADLINE>
  Color slides of Innoventions hall and robotic mascot Tom Morrow are
available. 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By KATHY SENA 
 c.1998 California Health magazine 
 (Eds.: Innovention is cq.)
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ahh, Disneyland. Mickey Mouse, Space Mountain, the very latest
in ultrasound equipment...
</P>
<P>
   Huh? Ultrasound equipment?
</P>
<P>
   That's right. The health-and-fitness world of the future (along
with the worlds of the home, the workplace, transportation and
entertainment), is now on display in Tomorrowland's new
``Innoventions'' exhibit. The exhibit combines Disney's
storytelling abilities with the expertise of companies like Kaiser
Permanente to demonstrate the hottest developments in technology.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking hands-on fun here, for grownups and kids. Kids
ages five and up will get the most out of the ``Focus on Health''
exhibit, says Disneyland spokesperson John McClintock. But even
younger kids will enjoy the lights, sounds, and action o and will
love running through the interactive heart and hearing the steady
``thump, thump, thump'' sound. (And after viewing the Kaiser
exhibit, parents of preschoolers and busy toddlers will want to
stop by Honeywell's ``Home'' exhibit, where young children can
crawl through a designed-for-kids heating system that includes a
maze of ductwork.)
</P>
<P>
   In the ``Focus on Health'' exhibit, you'll learn, at interactive
kiosks, about medical advances such as artificial skin, minimally
invasive surgery, ultrasound, and how plants such as bananas can be
used to deliver the immunizations of the future. (Now why didn't
they have that when my son needed his baby shots?)
</P>
<P>
   ``'Innoventions' breaks new ground on many levels,'' says Terry
Dobson, Walt Disney Imagineering senior concept designer for the
exhibits. ``Guests have traditionally visited Disneyland to ride
the rides and see the shows. Now they'll be able to play
interactive games together as well.''
</P>
<P>
   When you enter ``Innoventions,'' you'll board a ``loading pod''
on the slowly rotating lower level. You'll be greeted by your
enthusiastic audio-animatronic host, ``Tom Morrow'' (with actor
Nathan Lane o a perfect choice o providing the voice). You'll then
step through a portal to enter the turning building, where more
than 120 interactive games, displays and activities await.
</P>
<P>
   At the ``Focus on Health'' exhibit, you'll visit hands-on
ultrasound and MRI (magnetic resonance imaging) kiosks, see the
latest devices for laparoscopic surgery, and compare the workings
of the heart and lungs as they are influenced by both healthy and
unhealthy lifestyles. And be sure to check out the ``Dr. Elixer''
live show, which involves guests in a high-energy, truly funny show
about health.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exhibits are very theatrical,'' says Richard Hutton,
senior vice president, creative development, for Walt Disney
Imagineering. And (yippee!) you won't have to tell the kids ``don't
touch,'' he adds. ``Today, people learn best in an interactive
environment. You remember something if you can touch it, feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Hutton says, ``You can play with an MRI machine
that scans the human body, slice by slice.'' Another highlight is
the 10-foot-high interactive human heart, he adds, noting that when
you put your hand on the heart, you can hear your own heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Advances in healthcare and wellness aren't strictly limited to
the ``Focus on Health'' exhibit. If you have allergies or asthma,
for example, be sure to check out Honeywell's ``Home'' exhibit,
which showcases an innovative indoor-air-quality system.
</P>
<P>
   As time and medical technology march on, won't ``Innoventions''
look a little, ah, dated? Not to worry, says Hutton. ``Innoventions
will be refurbished every year, and totally redone every three
years. It will be very dynamic.''
</P>
<P>
   What's my favorite part of ``Innoventions''? You can stay as
long as you like, playing games and interacting with some truly
cool exhibits. Unlike many Disneyland attractions, which feature
lines followed by a two-minute ride (Don't get me wrong o I love
Space Mountain), ``Innoventions'' lasts as long as you want it to.
</P>
<P>
   When you leave ``Innoventions,'' you'll probably come away with
some great ideas for improving your family's health and fitness.
For tips on staying healthy while you're at Disneyland, check out
the sidebar.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, a little cotton candy o followed by a ride on
Space Mountain, of course o can't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Kathy Sena is a Los Angeles-based health-and-fitness writer
and the mother of a 2-year-old son.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
