<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8895 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOPPING-SOFTWARE-LIF     08-24 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-SOFTWARE-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKE YOUR SHOPPPING 'ROBOT' SEARCH THE NET
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By BRUNO GIUSSANI 
 c.1998 CyberTimes 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As commercial venues on the Internet continue to multiply, it
has become increasingly difficult to find the best bargains.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for a book, for example, chances are that
you'll search for it at one of the big American online bookstores,
like Amazon.com, Barnes &AMP; Noble or Borders and end up buying it
from one of these stores.
</P>
<P>
   But is the price they charge really the lowest possible? What
about delivery deadlines? How do you know there isn't another
lesser-known store somewhere on the Web that can ship it cheaper
and faster?
</P>
<P>
   Enter the shopbots, or shopping robots, software agents that
automate traditional Web surfing and search the Internet for the
best prices or shortest delivery times. Shopbots have long been
regarded as a technology with the potential to revolutionize
consumer retailing on the Internet by making comparative shopping
easy and fast.
</P>
<P>
   They may ``help to overcome the barriers that keep consumers
from using the Web,'' said Heather Stark, a principal with Ovum, a
British consulting company. ``They can make the Web faster and more
reliable, and make online shopping a convenient experience,'' she
added in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Stark and her team estimated in a study that total revenue
earned from agent-related sales on the Web will hit $1.6 billion by
2001, up from $19 million in 1996 and $159 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet so far shopping robots have been fairly primitive. The
category's ancestor, Andersen Consulting's Bargain Finder, searches
10 online stores for the price of a compact disk and displays the
results on a single page. Since its launch two years ago, however,
Bargain Finder has not been developed any further.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, other services like Yahoo's Shopguide, Snap's
Deal Finder or Viaweb's Shopfind have hit the Web. They cover a
broad spectrum of products, from sporting goods and flowers to
computers and peripherals, but they work much like a standard
search engine and don't provide the buyer with a good comparison of
the retailers' offerings beyond prices.
</P>
<P>
   Two young Germans have now gone a step further toward a
``smarter'' shopping agent.
</P>
<P>
   While studying economics at the University of Heidelberg, over
the last year Christopher Muenchoff, 22, and Christoph Janz, 21,
have been developing Acses, the most interesting example to date of
the way shopbots may evolve.
</P>
<P>
   Users of Acses can search for a book by title, author, keywords
or an International Standard Book Number (ISBN).
</P>
<P>
   Unlike all the other systems, Acses does not submit queries
directly to the bookseller's Web sites. It digs first into
Muenchoff and Janz's own database, and comes up with all the
matches.
</P>
<P>
   A search for ``Into Thin Air,'' for example, would bring up
references to books from seven different authors with the same
title. Users can then select Jon Krakauer's best-selling account of
the tragedy that occurred on Mount Everest two years ago, in the
format they prefer (hardcover, paperback, audio).
</P>
<P>
   This allows the system to identify the unique ISBN number
attached to the exact book the user is looking for.
</P>
<P>
   The query is then sent to the online bookstores based on this
number, but not before an additional layer of information is added:
users are asked about their geographic location and how they would
like the prices displayed (half a dozen currencies are available at
the moment).
</P>
<P>
   Then the Acses robot checks 25 American, German, British and
Australian online bookstores -- new ones are constantly added --
and returns the matches ranked by price. Prices include shipping
and handling charges calculated according to the location of the
customer, and delivery time is displayed as well.
</P>
<P>
   Clicking on a link takes the customer directly to the store,
where she can actually buy the book.
</P>
<P>
   Handling and delivery information are unavailable from Acses's
competitors, yet both are essential to allow the comparative
shopper to weigh shipping time against price and thus find the
buying scheme that best suits her needs.
</P>
<P>
   To take another example, Arie De Geus's management book ``The
Living Company'' was available from over a dozen different
bookstores. At $22.83 Books.com clearly had the best price, but
shipping would take 6 to 12 weeks, while Barnes &AMP; Noble, when using
a parcel service, would guarantee delivery in 3 to 5 days --
charging $53.41.
</P>
<P>
   Studying the list, however, I found two other stores that best
matched my preference for both a reasonable all-inclusive price and
a quick delivery. Kingbooks of the United States promises shipping
in 3 to 7 days and would charge $29.95, while for an extra dollar
Bookpages of Britain (recently acquired by Amazon) would have the
package delivered at my door in 4 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often, lesser-known stores are cheaper,'' Janz said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   To make the service even more effective, Muenchoff and Janz have
introduced a couple of enhancements.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid wasting time waiting for one slow Web site to answer
the queries, users can define a maximum access time, say 18
seconds, after which the search is timed out and the slow store is
excluded from the displayed list -- which, in return, may encourage
online booksellers to install powerful servers and high-speed
connections.
</P>
<P>
   If somebody wants to buy 10 books, it is possible to launch an
parallel Acses search for the entire package.
</P>
<P>
   Janz concedes that his and Muenchoff's system is far from
perfect, and that shopbots in general still suffer from a high
level of customer wariness, especially when it comes to reliability
and privacy protection.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, exporting the model to goods other than books may be
difficult. ``Technically, books are easy targets for our software
robot because of the standardized ISBN number,'' he explained.
``Since the same product is available from all retailers, price and
shipping time are the only variables on which a customer makes a
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The system may be used for other commodity items like CDs or
diskettes -- and indeed, as more online buyers start to use
shopbots, retailers in these markets may soon feel downward price
pressure. But in other sectors, consumers may still want to see and
touch the products they want to buy, and take into consideration
other factors like service after the sale.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, even Acses is still a pale imitation of true
personal agent technology in development in labs around the world,
which, Stark said, could even take into consideration ``situations
where your software agent meets my agent and they negotiate for
prices and conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES:
</P>
<P>
   _ Bargain Finder: http://bf.cstar.ac.com/bf/
</P>
<P>
   _ Acses: http://www.acses.com/
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Bruno Giussani is a free-lance writer based in Switzerland. He
writes the Eurobytes column for CyberTimes.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
