<HEADER>
A8899 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAY-GOODBYE-LIFEBEAT-     08-24 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAY-GOODBYE-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS WHO CAN'T SAY GOODBYE
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's LifeBeat
lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By MARGERY D. ROSEN 
 c.1998 Child magazine 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The negotiations rivaled those between President Clinton and
Saddam Hussein. Trying to cajole my daughter into leaving a
friend's house was excruciatingly delicate, requiring all the
fortitude of diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah hated goodbyes, and from around age 2 until 6,
leave-takings were difficult. Despite my telling her when I planned
to pick her up and promises of fun stuff for her at home, she'd
either hide or announce that she ``needed'' to do 103 things first.
</P>
<P>
   As a last resort, she'd fling herself onto some furniture and
lose all movement in her arms and legs.
</P>
<P>
   I'd apologize and try to cover my embarrassment with a few bon
mots. Still, after a day of work, I'd inevitably lose my temper,
and threaten punishments that I rarely enforced. After what seemed
like an eternity, Sarah would surrender.
</P>
<P>
   My second child, Michael had difficult moments, but I was
delighted that leave-taking wasn't one of them. Experts agree that
children vary widely in ability to cope with transitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What seems like an inconsequential step for an adult can loom
quite large in the eyes and mind of a child,'' notes Allan Gonsher,
president of Kids Inc., a counseling center in Omaha, Neb.
``Interestingly, parents often prepare for the major changes in a
child's life - a switch in schools, a move to a new town, the birth
of a sibling, the day Mom goes back to work - but overlook the
hundreds of small moments in the day that can be just as tough for
a child to negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
   Change is easier for some children than for others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although almost all kids have trouble with transitions from
time to time, temperament plays a major role,'' says Harold S.
Koplewicz, M.D., director of New York University's Child Study
Center in New York. ``Youngsters are born with either an ability or
an inability to adjust to change in their external as well as
internal environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some possess a basically sunny disposition, which allows them
to shift gears and go with the flow,'' he says. ``Others are by
nature more sensitive, cautious, and rigid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Change is stressful for youngsters because they thrive on
predictability,'' adds Debbie Webb Blackburn, Ph.D., director of
clinical training at the Virginia Treament Center for Children in
Richmond, Va. Even positive change, like leaving home for a party
or the beach, can trigger anxiety in kids.
</P>
<P>
   Although young children have short attention spans, they often
focus on an activity singlemindedly. It's not easy to break that
concentration. To be told by a parent or teacher that they must is
even more stressful.
</P>
<P>
   ``A child wants to feel that she has some control over her
life,'' notes Harry Z. Coren, M.D., a San Francisco-based child and
adolescent psychiatrist. ``Consider how much less burdened you feel
when you make your own decision to do something, as opposed to when
your boss or your spouse says that you have to.''
</P>
<P>
   While my daughter was temperamentally change-challenged, there
was much I could have done to help her. Kids need parents to guide
them through changes of emotion and environment.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to get a child to move faster can backfire and trigger a
struggle because dawdling is a child's way of saying she's in
charge. As I learned late, there are effective ways to encourage
kids to handle transitions.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a change-resistant youngster, many assume our child
is dragging his heels to get back at us, and we expect an F in
Parenting 101.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Claire Lerner, the mother of 7-year-old Sam and
2-year-old Jessica, assumed. Though now a child development
specialist with Zero to Three, the National Center for Infants,
Toddlers and their Families in Washington, D.C., Lerner was stumped
when she noticed Sam fussed at even minor transitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``While his pre-school classmates seemed to glide with relative
ease from activity to leave-taking, Sam became gridlocked when it
was time to say goodbye,'' Lerner recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Experts advise stepping back and asking, ``What is my child
struggling with here? Is he scared? Tired? Worried?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to understand what led up to the behavior before you
can figure out how to handle it,'' explains Blackburn. If you don't
give yourself distance, you may do things that are ineffective in
getting what you want - and what your child needs. Yelling and
ultimatums don't work.
</P>
<P>
   Tell your child that you know change is hard, and that her
feelings are legitimate. ``The emotions welling up inside a child
can be confusing and overwhelming,'' says Koplewicz. ``Parents have
to interpret what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   When Sam Lerner had a tough time leaving school or a friend's
house, his mother found it helped to put her arms around him and
say softly, ``I know that it's very hard to put all the toys away
and say goodbye, so why don't we do it together?'' His teachers
started to handle things the same way; things improved.
</P>
<P>
   Until age of 6 or 7, kids have little concept of time. ``Telling
a child of 3 or 4 that you're leaving in five minutes means nothing
to her,'' notes Coren. Although you should still give these
messages, add visual cues or link times to an event in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Ginny Anzelmo Glasner, a mother of three in Potomac, Md., sets a
kitchen timer so her kids can see the arrow moving. ``I think it
gives them a sense of time passing,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Some children have difficulty with transitions because they
think that all their fun is being removed - and that they'll never
have a good time again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have enough life experience to know that though one
good thing is ending, something else will take its place,'' notes
Coren. So use a positive spin: ``I'm sad, too, that we have to
leave the museum, but when we get home we can read the book we
bought that tells all about what we saw.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider how flexible you can be and what choices might be
appropriate. You might say, ``It's time to get ready to go, but we
can still read one more story or draw one more picture. Which would
you like to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Still struggling? Try behavior modification, suggests Koplewicz.
You can say, ``This seems to be hard for you. Here's the deal: Each
time you leave a play date without a fuss, you'll get a star. If
you earn three stars, you can pick a small prize.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, sometimes, the best-laid plans don't work. If your
child loses control, says Coren, you might say, ``We can do this
the easy way or the hard way, but we must go.''
</P>
<P>
   When you help children build skills to deal with change, you are
teaching them how to handle whatever curveballs life brings.
</P>
<P>
   I confess my daughter rarely left anyplace without at least a
small struggle until, well, maybe fourth grade. Still, I can say
that my husband and I found that understanding why she was behaving
this way helped us cope better and apologize less.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Margery D. Rosen is a contributing editor to Child magazine.
She lives in New York City. &LR; ) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
