A8961 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NEWS-JOBS-HNS &LR;      08-24 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWS-JOBS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WANTED: TV NEWS GUYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Rob Puglisi, the news director of Albany-area
station WTEN-TV, picked out a pile of applicant tapes at random
from his office and started ticking off the names.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth. Jennifer. Karen. Allison. Doug. Erica. Cathy.
Roselle. Mary Ann. Kelly. Gail. Kristen. Glenn. Holly. Robert.
Melanie. Luke. Barry. Tim.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen names, six men. And you want to know the unusual thing
about that list?
</P>
<P>
   That there were that many men.
</P>
<P>
   Where are the guys? News directors at television stations here
and across the country are growing increasingly concerned that
males, particularly qualified and experienced male anchors, are not
just hard to find, but simply don't exist.
</P>
<P>
   WNYT News Director Paul Conti said out of the 200-plus tapes he
received for an open anchor spot, women applicants outdistanced men
20 to 1. WRGB reported the same breakdown. None of the Albany-area
stations seeking candidates stated any gender preference in hiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of all the tapes which I received, say 80 tapes, I'd say
at most 15 were from men,'' Puglisi said. ``I don't know why more
men aren't attracted to the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Fitzpatrick does. The San Francisco-based headhunter is
possibly the foremost expert on television news talent. Need a
certain anchor, a certain age, heck, a certain hair color? He'll
find one for you.
</P>
<P>
   But guys? Well, that is a hard one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys have not gotten into the business for the last 10 to
12 years,'' Fitzpatrick said. ``What is happening in Albany is
happening in every television market in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick offers some historical perspective: Television news,
like so many bastions, was an all-white, all-male industry at its
inception, drawing on-air people from radio and newspapers. With
social changes exploding in the 1960s and 1970s, the Federal
Communications Commission came out with guidelines (which are now
being challenged) mandating the hiring of more women and
minorities, Fitzpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   In the game of catch-up, men, particularly white men, were
frozen out. A generation or two was lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the sudden it was a total dead end for men,''
Fitzpatrick said. ``Men were finding it very difficult to be hired
by stations.''
</P>
<P>
   So men turned away from the business in the 1980s. This means
graduates from that era would today be 34 to 38 years old, the
ideal range for an anchor to be brought into a market and developed
over time. But instead they are computer programmers or accountants
or lawyers or whatever, leaving local television stations
scrambling.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Papper, a professor of telecommunications at Ball State
University in Munice, Ind., said women are still a minority in
television but make up the majority of reporters, producers and
students. Papper said the shortage of males is made more critical
by the proliferation of news outlets like Fox affiliates and cable
shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have is an enormous strain on the system,'' Papper
said. ``We have stations scrambling over kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick lectures at colleges across the country, and said he
knows of only one broadcast journalism program where males
outnumber females in pursuing on-air jobs: Syracuse University in
New York. But Syracuse has more males only because there are still
guys out there who want the success of alumni Bob Costas, Marv
Albert and others in sportscasting.
</P>
<P>
   Take away those who want to go into sports and the student ranks
there are also predominantly female.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Smith, a former WTEN general manager, teaches at Syracuse.
He said low starting wages and a lack of opportunity caused men to
turn away from television news, a situation that will continue to
get worse as established newsmen step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is going to happen is the male anchors are getting older
and starting to retire,'' Smith said. ``It is very difficult to get
a male anchor. The men have been discouraged because there haven't
been that many jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said something interesting: he has a theory that women may
be ``better communicators.'' But if this trend continues, they may
be the only ones talking.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
