<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLACK-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITHER THE YOUNG BILL CLINTON? 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARY CLACK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ On May 28, 1964, Bill Clinton gave the benediction
at his graduation from Hot Springs High School in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   In what his biographer, David Maraniss, calls his first
political speech to a sizable audience, the young Clinton said,
``Now we must prepare to live only by the guide of our own faith
and character. We pray to keep a high sense of values while
wandering through the complex maze which is our society. Direct us
to know and care what is right and wrong, so that we will be
victorious in this life and rewarded in the next.''
</P>
<P>
   Today those words are far removed in time and practice from the
17-year-old who became president of the United States. The complex
maze that is Clinton's character has guided him to disgrace. There
on national television was the most powerful man in the world
confessing that he'd had a sexual liaison with a White House intern
and lied about it.
</P>
<P>
   If the essence of Kenneth Starr's case against Clinton is
consensual, albeit ``inappropriate'' sex, between two adults, we
didn't need to know this. No more than we need to know the details
of anyone else's sexual life that doesn't affect us.
</P>
<P>
   But for all of Starr's creepy obsession with the president's
hyperactive libido, it is Clinton's recklessness that has relegated
him to a national embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, as Hillary Rodham Clinton stated, there has been a
right-wing conspiracy to get Clinton. How else do you explain Jerry
Falwell and Larry Nichols peddling videos that all but link the
president with every murder in Arkansas throughout the past decade?
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't the right-wingers who made the president drop his
pants for Monica.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the president's daughter, Chelsea Clinton, there are
no innocents in this tiresome and nauseating peep show. But no one
is more to blame than Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It was his choice to engage in behavior he now concedes as
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   It was Clinton who looked the nation in the eye and lied.
</P>
<P>
   It was Clinton who lied to close friends and advisers and sent
them out like lemmings to foolishly declare his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Clinton who is responsible for those same friends and
advisers accruing tens of thousands of dollars worth of legal
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it was Clinton who, if he'd had the courage, could have
made his confession in January, won the nation's forgiveness
without dragging it through seven months of sordid nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton is a good president who could have been a great
president. None of the other men who has occupied the Oval Office
in this century was as intellectually and politically gifted as he.
But he has allowed his Achilles' heel of deceit to slay his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1964 benediction, the young Clinton asked the Lord to
``leave within us the youthful idealism and moralism which have
made our people strong. Sicken us at the sight of apathy, ignorance
and rejection so that our generation will remove complacency,
poverty and prejudice from the hearts of free men.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, the 17-year-old Bill Clinton sounds much better than
the 52-year-old president.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cary Clack is a columnist for the San Antonio Express-News,
P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
