</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICHTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAREWELL, MR. PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOB RICHTER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Out of all the millions of good men and women in
this country, how did we get Bill Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   He burst in like a young missionary full of ideas, but now he's
the house guest who stayed too long _ who's freeloading, lounging
in his underwear and eying our wives and daughters.
</P>
<P>
   He's been reduced to a bull's eye for abuse here an abroad.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been better. Clinton is an appealing genius. He
has the aw-shucks goodness of a Sheriff Andy Taylor, not the
pedantic, wise meanness of, say, Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   He is comfortable in jeans or a tux. He has a savvy that appeals
to Wall Street, to old and new money, as well as to Elvis fans and
jocks and people of arts and letters.
</P>
<P>
   He can talk to people of all ages and backgrounds, and this
nation has more rings of life than a redwood tree.
</P>
<P>
   He can be anyman, anywhere, anytime. While some call that
disingenuous, those are qualities that made many of us feel
comfortable with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, he has demonstrated that he is genuinely interested
in lifting all the boats in this nation's sea. And he's made good
on his promise to have an administration that mirrors the makeup of
the American people.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, Clinton was lucky. Just think of those who
helped him get where he got:
</P>
<P>
   _ Saddam Hussein, the Iraqi leader who continued to belch
brimstone after George Bush thought he'd put him away.
</P>
<P>
   _ Former Sen. Bob Dole, whose presidential campaign style was
that of an angry neighbor swearing at the kids who punted their
football into his yard.
</P>
<P>
   _ Voters who stayed home in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   _ And, lately, the Republican leadership in Congress who make
the aforementioned Saddam look like a brilliant tactician.
</P>
<P>
   But after special prosecutor Kenneth Starr sends Congress his
report, it will be up to those clueless Republicans to decide what
to do with the adulterous, dissembling president.
</P>
<P>
   It will be tempting to dawdle, to let Clinton and every Democrat
running for office this fall twist in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   But, to cut to the chase, here are the options: (1) Congress
will either impeach him, (2) not impeach or (3) Clinton will
resign. Nos. 1 and 3 are bad; No. 2 may be worse.
</P>
<P>
   If Starr's report contains nothing more damning that the tawdry
coupling between the president and a young intern, we don't see
Clinton being impeached.
</P>
<P>
   But he'll be ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, the Republicans can have some fun with this. But
they run the risk of putting politics over the national good.
</P>
<P>
   I expect that as the process most certainly drags on, Democratic
Party leaders will grow restless and pressure Clinton to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Clinton is no different than other talented
individuals who are told every day how wonderful they are until
they think they're bulletproof.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Clinton isn't. He looked quite mortal in his pathetic
mea culpa.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will do the American people a favor and prove that he
cares more about us than himself if he resigns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Richter is a columnist for the San Antonio Express-News,
P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
