 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY
TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR
PAGES! SEE ABOVE FOR A SALESPERSON IN YOUR TERRITORY.)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Shirley Fong-Torres, founder and owner of Wok Wiz Walking Tours
in San Francisco's Chinatown, guides a group of mature travelers
across narrow, bustling Grant Avenue and past Pagoda Gate with its
two stone lions.
 &HT;    ``Notice the curved roof line on many of the buildings,'' she
points out. ``The Chinese are very superstitious. They believe that
evil spirits travel in a straight line. By curving the roofs, evil
spirits stay away.''
 &HT;    Accompanying Fong-Torres' group is our friend, Millie Alexander,
who tells us about the continuing growth of ethnic communities in
the San Francisco area.
 &HT;    Chinatown is a favorite attraction for many first-time visitors
to San Francisco. While they expect to see cable cars, the Golden
Gate Bridge and many different types of boats on the water, ``what
comes as a surprise are the large number of newly arrived
immigrants now living in the City by the Bay,'' Alexander says.
 &HT;    The picturesque 24-block community of Chinatown continues to
provide housing and social interaction for thousands of new Chinese
and Asian immigrants, she says. They love it because it reminds
them so much of home. They love the sound of mah jong tiles
clicking against one another in boisterous games. They love the
pungent smell of healing herbs prescribed by white-coated herb
doctors. And they love the sight of roasted ducks hanging in
restaurant windows, inviting them inside for a delicious meal.
 &HT;    The entire city is a kaleidoscope of ethnic diversity.
 &HT;    The Hispanic culture marks the Mission District, with salsa
music blaring from inside dance clubs. Taquerias serve handmade
tortillas, and colorful murals adorn walls, fences and garages.
 &HT;    On the other side of the hills not far from the ocean is Geary
Street, where the golden onion domes of the Holy Trinity Russian
Orthodox Cathedral bring a touch of home to Russian emigres.
 &HT;    Although they're eager to begin a new life in America, they
still long for familiar foods such as piroshkis and pelmeni. Many
bakeries, delicatessens and restaurants specialize in Russian food
and advertise with signs printed in both English and Cyrillic
letters.
 &HT;    ``We shouldn't be a melting pot in America but a salad bowl,''
says Dorothy Quock, a guide with Wok Wiz Walking Tours. ``Each
culture should keep its ethnic identity, yet still be part of the
mix.''
 &HT;    ``San Francisco has had a long history of accepting (sometimes
reluctantly) different nationalities into its salad bowl,'' says
Alexander, who has lived in the Bay Area for many years. She
explains that since the days of the 1849 Gold Rush, the city has
had mass migrations of Italian fishermen, Chinese railroad workers,
Mexican laborers and, most recently, Vietnamese boat people, all
seeking happiness in the Golden State.
 TOURING THE CITY  
 &HT;    For the visitor, this multi-ethnic flavor presents an
extraordinary sensory experience in sights, sounds and tastes. And
Alexander adds that it's all reachable by buses, streetcars and
cable cars at discounted prices for mature travelers.
 &HT;    Personal guides go to famous neighborhoods such as Pacific
Heights and Telegraph Hill, Castro Street and the Haight Ashbury.
 &HT;    ``Because of its cultural diversity, San Francisco has a flavor
that does not exist in other cities,'' says Thomas Weed, who runs
Tours for One, a personalized guide service, (415) 387-3448. ``I
learn what interests the visitors, and then we go exploring in
those neighborhoods.''
 &HT;    To fully enjoy San Francisco, however, the mature traveler
should bear in mind several facts, says Alexander:
 &HT;    The city is located on the tip of a peninsula with the Pacific
Ocean on one side and San Francisco Bay on the other side. This
means that micro-climates abound, especially during the summer
months. While the sky can be sunny and blue at Pier 39, it may be
gray and foggy at the Cliff House. Consequently, sweaters and
jackets _ even lightweight coats _ are appropriate for the city's
mercurial weather.
 &HT;    San Francisco is also located on 43 hills with Lombard Street
being the steepest and most famous for its eight curves. Cars full
of uneasy passengers carefully navigate these S-turns while more
ambitious pedestrians climb up and down Lombard Street on the
sidewalk stairs.
 &HT;    Not all the city's famous attractions are on hills. Fisherman's
Wharf, Golden Gate Park, Union Square and Ocean Beach are on level
ground that requires comfortable walking shoes. Attractions located
on hilltops are accessible via cable cars, taxi cabs and tour
buses.
 &HT;    For touring other city sights, Muni, the public transit system,
charges visitors ages 65 and older a 35-cent fare instead of $1 to
travel around the city all day.
 SAN FRANCISCO RESOURCES  
 &HT;    Because San Francisco is so popular with visitors, advance hotel
reservations are a must, Alexander warns, adding that in the first
three quarters of 1997, San Francisco hosted 11.4 million visitors.
 &HT;    To help with accommodations, the San Francisco Convention and
Visitors Bureau has a city-wide hotel-reservations service. By
calling toll-free (888) 782-9673, mature travelers can make
reservations at more than 70 hotels. Be sure to inquire about their
senior discounts.
 &HT;    In addition, the visitors bureau has a new Web site,
www.sfvisitor.org, to help visitors plan their trips. The
Information available includes travel tips, frequently asked
questions (FAQs), maps and links to other San Francisco resources
on the Web.
 &HT;    One useful guidebook published by Good Life Publications is
``Good Life San Francisco,'' and purchasers ages 50 and older get
30 percent off.
 &HT;    Book tours like Wok Wiz Walking Tours through your hotel.
 ----- 
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Gene and
Adele Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St.,
14th Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send the Malotts a postcard from
your trip with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you
find for seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to the Malotts by electronic mail.
The address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on
your keyboard.)
 &HT;    _______ 
