<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S DOING IN BERLIN 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
</P>
<P>
   (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
</P>
<P>
   TWO COLOR SLIDES are available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   (HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY
TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR
PAGES! SEE ABOVE FOR A SALESPERSON IN YOUR TERRITORY.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By EVE SCHAENEN &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   These days, when the sun is shining and daylight lingers into
late evening, Berliners are outside talking about their city. The
question is always the same, accompanied by a sweeping gesture
toward the crane or bulldozer inevitably positioned nearby: ``You
think it will work?''
</P>
<P>
   For the visitor interested in urban development, contemporary
architecture or, indeed, world history, Berlin is a veritable candy
store for the mind. All over town the city's physical past is being
confronted, restored, reshaped or at times obliterated to make way
for the 21st-century capital.
</P>
<P>
   There is the newly transplanted heart at Potsdamer Platz, where
the steel-and-glass towers of Sony and Daimler Benz near
completion. The area was the commercial center of prewar Berlin _
but it was also the site of Hitler's bunker, of the wall and the
mined no man's land behind it.
</P>
<P>
   There is the Reichstag, birthplace of the Weimar democracy in
1918, but also the setting for the infamous fire used by the Nazis
to seize power in 1933. Refashioned by Sir Norman Foster, the
British architect, the building will once again house the German
Parliament in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   On a less monumental scale, there is the old Jewish quarter in
the Mitte district. Due to conflicting claims, much of the area was
off limits to investors after the wall fell, resulting in a
squatters' paradise and a flourishing subculture that left its mark
in the neighborhood's trendy galleries, clubs and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Yet all this is just the sideshow. For in reclaiming its status
as government capital, Berlin is determined to reclaim its 1920s
role as cultural capital of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The city boasts three state-subsidized opera houses, five
symphony orchestras and three ballet companies. Some 15,000 seats
are available nightly for concerts and musical theater. And a
dizzying array of privately sponsored alternative performances and
exhibitions recall Berlin's history as home to the avant-garde.
 &UR; EVENTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Sept. 2 through Oct. 5 the 48th annual Berlin Festival
Weeks will focus on Vienna from 1750 to 1950. Claudio Abbado will
conduct the Berlin Philharmonic Orchestra in the opening concert,
an evening of Wolfgang Rihm and Beethoven's Ninth Symphony. The
festival box office is at 48 Budapesterstrasse; information and
tickets: (49-30) 254 89254, fax (49-30) 254 89111.
</P>
<P>
   For those who enjoy their Viennese music in a somewhat less
conventional setting, the director Georg Tabori and the Circus
Roncalli are staging ``The Magic Flute: Mozart's Opera in the
Circus With Elephants, Goats, Apes and other Collaborators.''
Performances are Tuesday, Wednesday, Friday and Saturday at 7 p.m.,
Sunday at 6 p.m. through Sept. 23. Tickets are available at
Fullhouse Service, 48 Budapesterstrasse, or at the circus box
office, 111 Friedrichstrasse. Tickets from $9.80 to $59, calculated
at 1.73 marks to the dollar: (49-30) 254 89254.
</P>
<P>
   Opening Sept. 30, the National Gallery in the Hamburger Bahnhof,
50-51 Invalidenstrasse, (49-30) 397 8340, presents ``Sensation,''
works by young British artists from the Charles Saatchi Collection.
The show made waves at the Royal Academy of Arts in London. Hours:
Tuesday through Friday, 10 a.m. to 6 p.m.; Saturday and Sunday, 11
a.m. to 6 p.m. Admission: $4.60. Tickets for ``Sensation'' are
$6.95.
</P>
<P>
   The first Berlin Biennale opens Sept. 29 with ``Berlin/Berlin.''
Over 70 artists, architects, filmmakers, musicians and designers
who have worked in Berlin will participate in the interdisciplinary
event.
</P>
<P>
   Installations, videos, photographs and paintings will be shown
in three historic buildings in Mitte: the Academy of Arts at
Pariser Platz (next to the Brandenburg Gate); the former
Postfuhramt, 17-19 Tucholsky Strasse; and the Kunst-Werke art
center, 69 Auguststrasse. Hours: Tuesday through Thursday, and
Sunday, 10 a.m. to 8 p.m.; Friday and Saturday, 10 a.m. to
midnight. Telephone: (49-30) 285 99148. The Biennale closes Jan. 3.
 &UR; SIGHTSEEING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The best way to immerse oneself in the rhythm of Berlin is to
step into its noisy unfinished center. Emerge from the Potsdamer
Platz S-Bahn station to a sky filled with 30 cranes, lifting,
swiveling, loads dangling.
</P>
<P>
   Two-and-a-half-hour tours through the construction sites at
Potsdamer and Leipziger Platz are given as part of the ``Showcase
Berlin'' summer program. The English-language tour (No. 9) begins
Thursday at 10:30 a.m. through Sept. 3. Tickets ($9.85) can be
bought beneath the Info Box building by the S-Bahn station.
</P>
<P>
   If Potsdamer Platz offers a glimpse at Berlin's self-styled
future, Tacheles, 54-56 Oranienburger Strasse, bears witness to the
city's disappearing past.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1909 as part of a noble shopping passage connecting the
Friedrichstrasse to the Oranienburger Strasse, the building was
scheduled for demolition in 1990 when an idealistic group of East
and West German artists occupied the space.
</P>
<P>
   This autumn may be the last chance to visit the ruin in its
dilapidated glory. The artists expect to be evicted before the end
of the year by the new investors, who have presented plans to
integrate the space into a larger commercial complex.
</P>
<P>
   A short walk into the heart of the old Jewish quarter leads to
the Hackeschen Hofe, 40-41 Rosenthaler Strasse, eight connecting
Jugendstil buildings and courtyards that successfully combine the
public life of cafes, galleries, clubs and fashion boutiques with
private housing.
</P>
<P>
   Two museums opened this June. The Picture Gallery at the
Kulturforum, Kemperplatz, (49-30) 2090 55 55, unites some 1,000
masterworks of European painting, an encyclopedic collection
divided in two for the past half-century by the exigencies of war
and the wall. The understated building relies almost exclusively on
natural overhead light. Open Tuesday through Friday 10 a.m. to 6
p.m. Thursday until 8 p.m., weekends from 11 a.m. to 6 p.m.
Admission: $4.60.
</P>
<P>
   The Allied Museum, in the former American military movie theater
at 135 Clayallee, offers a multimedia depiction of the history of
Berlin and the Allies from 1945 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Among the items on display are an original raisin bomber from
the Berlin airlift, the Checkpoint Charlie house and a piece of the
wall. Open daily except Wednesday, 10 a.m. to 6 p.m.; (49-30) 818
1990. Admission free.
 &UR; WHERE TO STAY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bleibtreu Hotel, 31 Bleibtreu strasse, (49-30) 884 740, fax
884 74444, is hidden in an artfully designed courtyard just off
western Berlin's toniest shopping street, the Kurfurstendamm.
</P>
<P>
   The 60 quiet rooms feature Italian designer furniture in natural
materials. Doubles, including breakfast, from $164 on weekends,
$197 weekdays.
</P>
<P>
   The ultramodern 100-room Art'otel Ermeler Haus, 70-73
Wallstrasse, (49-30) 240 620, fax 240 62222, serves as a gallery
devoted to one of Germany's most prominent contemporary artists,
Georg Baselitz, featuring 300 signed works. Original rococo dining
and breakfast rooms are in the incorporated Ermeler Haus, one of
the city's few remaining patrician mansions. Doubles, $136 to $182.
</P>
<P>
   Budget: Situated in trendy Kreuzberg directly over the
Marheineke market hall, the 16-room Gasthaus Dietrich Herz, 15
Marheineke Platz, (49-30) 693 1173, offers clean, no-frills
accommodations with front-row seats for one of Berlin's liveliest
street scenes. Rooms have private bath and shower; some have
balconies overlooking the Platz. Doubles from $69 to $81, including
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Specializing in the accommodation of families with small
children, the 31-room Hotel-Pension Wittelsbach, 22
Wittelsbacherstrasse, 10707,(49-30) 862 1345, fax (49-30) 862 1532,
devotes a floor to fairytale inspired doubles and suites, complete
with castle- or fort-shaped bunkbeds and a gingerbread house in the
corridor. There is a small playground in back. Doubles from $104
including breakfast; $145 for a four-person family room.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury: The 204-room Four Seasons, 49 Charlottenstrasse, (49-30)
20338, fax 2033 6166, opens onto one of the city's most impressive
imperial squares, the Gendarmenmarkt, with its twin cathedrals and
concert hall.
</P>
<P>
   The oak paneling and marble fireplace in the corner dining room
suggest traditional opulence, while the fitness room and
technologically equipped business centers comply with more modern
needs. Doubles from $228 to $315.
</P>
<P>
   The Kempinski Hotel Bristol Berlin, 27 Kurfurstendamm, (49-30)
884 340, fax 883 6075, remains a grande dame among Berlin hotels,
with 301 traditionally luxurious rooms on the Kurfurstendamm. The
breakfast buffet, served in a sunny winter garden, is one of the
finest in town. Doubles with breakfast from $231.
 &UR; WHERE TO EAT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Situated in the house where Rahel Varnhagen conducted her famous
literary salon in the 1790s, Vau, at 54-55 Jugerstrasse, attracts
an elegant business crowd with its contemporary classic interior,
exceptional service and haute cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   The four- and six-course menus (at $51 and $109) feature
seasonal specialties, such as sauteed langoustines on white beans
and summer truffles. A three-course dinner for two with wine starts
at $116. Vau's special lunch offer, any dish on the menu for
$11.60, has become an insider institution. Reservations, at (49-30)
202 9730, are necessary. Both lunch and dinner are served.
</P>
<P>
   With its blood-red velvet settees and live piano music, Die
Mowe, 1 Palais am Festungsgruben, (49-30) 201 2029, recalls the
sophisticated salon ambiance of prewar Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   A generous seasonal salad can be followed by roast duck with
kohlrabi puree. Dinner for two with wine is roughly $80. Monday
night is ``Art Enjoyment'' _ a changing program of musical
entertainment with a thematic three-course meal for $35. Reserve
ahead. Dinner only.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarzenraben, across from the Hackeschen Hofe, 13 Neue
Schonhauser Strasse, (49-30) 2839 1698, serves Italian fare in a
cool beige setting with a heaping side order of attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Assorted cold grilled vegetables or pheasant pate (each $10.40)
make good starters. The piatti di mezzo _ such as baby lamb chops
in red wine sauce with summer vegetables ($13.85) _ are large
enough for a main course. Dinner for two with wine starts at about
$80. Lunch and dinner are both served.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin is renowned for its breakfast culture; indeed, many cafes
serve breakfast to late risers well into the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Situated in an 1885 villa with idyllic garden seating,
Cafe-Wintergarten im Literaturhaus, 23 Fasanenstrasse, (49-30) 882
5414, offers six breakfast specials ranging from basic Milchkaffee
and croissants ($4.90) to house-smoked salmon and champagne
($15.60), plus many a la carte selections. Open daily 9:30 a.m. to
1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Kamala, 69 Oranienburger Strasse in Mitte, (49-30) 283 2797,
serves inexpensive and delicious Thai food. The $8.40 lunch
includes soup and a main dish. The underground restaurant is small
and fills fast; you may have to share a table. Open daily from
11:30 a.m. to 11:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   There is a German saying: Everything has an end _ only the wurst
has two. The standing tables at the Currywurstbude, 195
Kurfurstendamm, are crowded with business people and shoppers
sampling Berlin's preferred fast food. The classic Currywurst is
$1.80.
</P>
<P>
   (Eve Schaenen is a journalist who lives in Berlin.)
