<HEADER>
A8995 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ANALYSIS-HNS &LR;      08-24 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTHS AFTER OUSTER, RUSSIAN PREMIER LIKELY TO HAVE BROADER
AUTHORITY 
</HEADLINE>
   News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Victor Chernomyrdin.MDBR/.MDNM/ returns as Russia's
prime minister in a more powerful personal position than he was
before President Boris Yeltsin fired him five months.MDBR/.MDNM/
ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of a financial crisis, Yeltsin has ``humiliated
himself by recalling the man he abruptly dismissed along with the
whole Cabinet,'' said Nicholas Chomsky, who runs a Paris-based
management consulting agency for foreign investors in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it was Chernomyrdin's successor, the young and
politically inexperienced Sergei .MDBR/.MDNM/Kiriyenko, who
unceremoniously got the ax. ~``Yeltsin has effectively admitted
Kiriyenko, his personal choice, was a complete error,''
Chomsky.MDBR/.MDNM/ said. ``At the same time, he has acknowledged
Chernomyrdin was the only viable option and that he was wrong to
fire him in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Vishnogradov, a specialist in Russian politics at the
respected French National Research Council, added that it is
``virtually inconceivable Yeltsin would remove Chernomyrdin a
second time, so he looks safe for the last two years of Yeltsin's
presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   This makes him a leading contender to succeed Yeltsin,
Vishnogradov said. Not a popular figure, Chernomyrdin.MDBR/.MDNM/
is nonetheless widely respected for being hard-working and
moderate.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Russian president is notoriously unpredictable and
could change his mind again, he appears to have turned full control
of government actions over to Chernomyrdin. This is the sort of
power no previous prime minister has possessed, Vishnogradov said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experiment in naming the untried Kiriyenko was supposed to
demonstrate Yeltsin's political flair,'' he said. ``But, instead,
it was such a flop that Yeltsin had little recourse but to summon
Chernomyrdin whose price for returning was greater power and much
less presidential interference.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, 60, came back only days after the government was
compelled to devalue the ruble by more than 30 percent. Kiriyenko,
36, lacked personal prestige in financial markets and his
tough-seeming steps to sustain the ruble had been contemptuously
dismissed by financial experts.
</P>
<P>
   While Chernomyrdin had plenty of ups and downs during his first
stint as prime minister, his reputation among Russian bankers and
businessmen stands high. As a former head of Russia's gas industry,
he is considered by them to be one of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Vishnogradov described Chernomyrdin as ``an insider who knows
which strings to pull. He may lack charisma, but he has savvy which
may be more important these days in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Relations between Chernomyrdin and Yeltsin, never really close,
have been strained since the Cabinet shuffle in March, Vishnogradov
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could hardly be more contrasting,'' he noted. ``Yeltsin
is typically Russian: impulsive and tending to rely on his
intuition. Chernomyrdin also is a typical Russian, but of a
different type. He is serious, methodical and not inclined to place
his trust in others.''
</P>
<P>
   He reportedly regards Yeltsin as having grown dangerously
erratic, Vishnogradov said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the two men who are now fated to stand together in
order to rescue the country from economic shambles,'' Vishnogradov
concluded. ``They are an unlikely couple.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
