<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL CLINTON NEEDS TO SPEAK AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The disappointment among President Clinton's
usual supporters and friends with his restrained confession to the
nation early last week is a telltale sign that this country is in
for a rough two years no matter how this deplorable affair
eventually concludes.
</P>
<P>
   If it turns out that the president's credibility in his office
has been undermined by what appears to be regarded by some of the
public as an inadequate expiation of his sins, there is no recourse
apparent to extract this nation from the political purgatory in
which it would find itself.
</P>
<P>
   This would be a triumph for obsession and recklessness: the
personal behavior of Bill Clinton and the professional behavior of
Ken Starr and his years' long investigation that in its denouement
has come down to exposing sex between two consenting adults. On
such underpinnings is our crisis of national confidence erected.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton's Republican critics argue that the crux of the
Starr investigation is not about sex (about which the American
people have said they really don't care and don't want to hear any
more), but about weightier matters of perjury and the subornation
of perjury.
</P>
<P>
   But that is merely camouflaging what is happening. In fact, the
perjury and obstruction of justice allegations now on the table
emanate not from the probe of Whitewater, or Filegate or
Travelgate, but only from what Bill Clinton and Monica Lewinsky did
in private, by mutual consent. As contemptible as his behavior was,
as much as her role was deplorable, what they did violated no
statute. Therefore, any obstruction of justice so far alleged is
based on sex, and nothing but sex.
</P>
<P>
   What next? The odds against impeachment are very long, because
perjury and obstruction of justice hinge on intent and are
considered by legal authorities to be difficult to prove.
</P>
<P>
   If the president were to lose the effective backing of the
public in his official role, which he has so far retained, would
resignation emerge as a possibility because he would no longer
possess the requisite stature needed to govern? In that event,
would the country find relief and renewal knowing that the crisis
ws founded not on grave constitutional issues, but on sexual
truancy?
</P>
<P>
   Upon taking office, would the new president, Al Gore, be able to
accomplish what his damaged and dented predecessor could not: Unite
the people and Congress behind bold policies at home and abroad?
</P>
<P>
   Or is it more likely that a President Gore would himself become
beleaguered by political opponents within his own party and without
because of his announced ambitions to run for president two years
from now?
</P>
<P>
   The future is not promising. Thursday's anti-terrorist strikes
against the United States underline one aspect.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's motives were immediately questioned. More
impacting than the handful of Republican partisans, were the doubts
expressed by the general public. It is useful for the citizenry to
retain a certain reserve about the acts of government. That is
built not only into the Constitution but hopefully also into the
American political character.
</P>
<P>
   But the instantaneousness and the depth of the skepticism, in
the face of fairly clear evidence that the cruise missiles were not
launched to bury the Lewinsky scandal (and in fact would not do
so), revealed the unusually wide gulf between the people and their
president right now.
</P>
<P>
   That rift exists partly because President Clinton likely made a
political miscalculation in his speech Monday night. His
acknowledgment of an inappropriate relationship with Monica
Lewinsky, his taking responsibility and voicing regret left too
many people feeling short-changed.
</P>
<P>
   It was said he should have apologized explicitly for having lied
to the people, that he was too artful in characterizing the
Lewinsky relationship, that he should have shown more remorse.
Republicans, not surprisingly, tended to add that he should not
have tried to shift responsibility onto Starr's investigation.
Nevertheless, so far the pattern of his support holds: His
job-performance approval remains very high, while he gets much
lower marks on his personal behavior. Earlier suggestions by some
politicos that forgiveness and understanding would follow honest
confession appear to have given way as opponents now assail him as
a self-convicted liar.
</P>
<P>
   The actual loss in public esteem he will suffer has to be gauged
over a longer time. But Bill Clinton would be well served if he
again spoke to the American people, not to address the shortcomings
voiced by political opponents, but rather to speak to the general
disquiet and dissatisfaction with his person. He should do so as
soon as the terrorism crisis permits.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
