<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-BLOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BLOOD OF BOTH SIDES FLOWED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAGH, Northern Ireland _ Geraldine Breslin and Ann McCombe were
the best of friends.
</P>
<P>
   And so last weekend, when a policeman burst into the clothing
shop here where the two women worked, saying there was a bomb
scare, Breslin and McCombe left the store together. They linked
arms, as women here do, and walked down High Street to a security
cordon the police had put up.
</P>
<P>
   But either because of the sheer incompetence or the breathtaking
calculation of the bombers, the two women unwittingly walked
directly toward the maroon sedan that contained the 500-pound bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Geraldine Breslin and Ann McCombe were standing together,
probably still arm in arm, when the bomb exploded, killing them
instantly. They lived as soulmates, mothers who chatted endlessly
about their kids, and they died together.
</P>
<P>
   Geraldine Breslin, 43, was a Catholic. Ann McCombe, 48, was
Protestant. They were just two of the 28 people who died when a
dissident Irish republican group's bomb exploded in this market
town on Aug. 15, in what has been described as the worst atrocity
in Northern Ireland this century.
</P>
<P>
   But their deaths reflect a bigger story than the tragic events
of last week.
</P>
<P>
   There have been many acts of violence because of the ancient
squabble over national identity that the Irish, in their inimitable
penchant for understatement, call ``The Troubles.'' But in nearly
all of these acts, one or the other of Northern Ireland's two
communities _ Catholic nationalists who consider themselves Irish,
or Protestant unionists who see themselves as British _ was the
intended target, while the other side was the perpetrator.
</P>
<P>
   The violence here in Omagh changed that, and in a perverse way
demonstrated in the most compelling way ever that the blood of
people on this island is not orange or green, but red.
</P>
<P>
   As the rubble in Omagh is carted away for forensic examination,
and the terrible litany of disfiguring injuries is added to the
horrific catalog of death, the dignity of most people on this
island, but especially those in County Tryone who have borne the
brunt of the suffering, has shown through. They have eulogized and
buried their dead with awe-inspiring grace.
</P>
<P>
   And by and large, they have resisted the urge to call for
anything but a redoubling of efforts to make sure the peace process
that the overwhelming majority of people on this island have
endorsed by referendum continues. This is a starkly different
reaction from those that greeted most of the other atrocities over
the last three decades.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, Protestant extremists bombed McGurk's Bar in Belfast,
killing 15 Catholics. The bombers said it was retaliation for IRA
bombs that had killed Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, British paratroopers shot dead 14 Catholic civil rights
marchers in what became known as Bloody Sunday. Most Protestants
were ready to accept the British Army's initial claim _ later shown
to be a lie _ that the victims had been armed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the IRA bombed a British Army war veterans'
commemoration in Enniskillen, a quiet town just 20 miles from
Omagh, killing 11 Protestant civilians. The IRA claimed it wanted
to kill soldiers, but the deaths of civilians gathered in the
square for a ceremony was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the IRA put a bomb in a fish shop on the Shankill Road
in West Belfast, saying it wanted to kill loyalist extremists who
were meeting upstairs. There was no meeting. Nine Protestant
civilians, some of them children, and the IRA man who carried the
bomb, were killed. In retaliation, loyalist gunmen sprayed a
Catholic bar in Greysteel with gunfire, killing six Catholics and a
Protestant. The killers said it served the Protestant right for
drinking in a Catholic bar.
</P>
<P>
   The segregation of suffering has prevented many people here from
finding the common ground of victims. It helped create an
ambivalence about violence when it was directed at ``them.'' Over
the last decade, whenever people were asked how they felt about
violence being carried out in their name, very often the response
was a defensive, ``What about what they did to us?''
</P>
<P>
   That was not the case in Omagh last week, where neither side had
a monopoly on suffering.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb in Omagh killed Catholics and Protestants, nationalists
and unionists, men and women, boys and girls. It killed twin girls
in their mother's womb, less than a month from birth. It killed
three little boys from the Irish Republic. It killed two Spanish
visitors, incredibly, the first tourists ever killed by an act of
terrorism in Northern Ireland. It killed Brenda Logue, 17, whose
family supports Sinn Fein, the political allies of the IRA. It
killed Esther Gibson, 36, a Sunday school teacher in the church of
the hardline unionist Rev. Ian Paisley.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the 1974 bombings in Dublin, when 27 people were
killed on the same day six were killed by a bomb in Monaghan, the
Irish Republic has been largely insulated from the violence that
has been so common in Northern Ireland. But three of the victims
were boys from Buncrana, in County Donegal, shopping in Omagh with
their Spanish friends who every summer for the last 10 years had
come to Ireland to learn English.
</P>
<P>
   David Trimble, the newly elected leader of the Northern Ireland
Assembly, crossed the border to attend the funeral of the three
Donegal boys _ as much a crossing of the Rubicon for the leader of
mainstream unionism as was the Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams's
unequivocal condemnation of the bombing last weekend. It was the
first time Adams condemned an act by armed republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Adams and Trimble were in St. Mary's Church as the bishop of
Derry, the Rev. Seamus Hegarty, eulogized the three boys. Looking
at Trimble, Bishop Hegarty said, ``You, Mr. Trimble, are
particularly welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic congregation burst into applause.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble _ who refuses to speak to Adams because of Sinn Fein's
links to an IRA that, despite a cease-fire, will not give up its
weapons _ did not shake hands with Adams. But there was a handshake
that did suggest what happened in Omagh has had a humanizing
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble and Mary McAleese, the first president of Ireland to
hail from Northern Ireland, were bitter rivals at Queens
University, where they both worked as law professors. The rivalry
turned to open hostility when McAleese got a promotion that Trimble
thought should have gone to him. But in St. Mary's Church, they
shook hands and greeted each other warmly.
</P>
<P>
   There is a tendency to overestimate the impact the sudden,
violent death of innocents can have here. Last month, the loyalist
firebombing of a Catholic home in Ballymoney killed three little
boys and shocked the world. Some people said that would be the end
of it. Of course, sectarian hatred will survive the peace process.
But there is considerable evidence that the peace process will
survive even the horrors of Omagh.
</P>
<P>
   It may be what happened in Omagh is a turning point in this
island's tortured history. Because maybe the people here have
finally found common ground. How sad, how terribly sad, that it had
to be a burial ground.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Kevin Cullen is chief of the Globe's London bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
