<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9050 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-RISKS-BOS &LR;      08-24 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RISKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR POWERFUL LEADERS, A THRILL IN DANGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There must be some reason why a politician who is
riding high risks it all on an illicit romance. Otherwise, it would
not happen again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Even close friends of President Clinton say they are baffled by
his behavior. Why, they ask, would a man stalked by the reputation
of a womanizer and truth shader be tempted to have a White House
affair with Monica S. Lewinsky, a 21-year-old intern, and then
emphatically deny it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confused and disappointed,'' said Robert Reich, a
classmate of Clinton's at Yale Law School and the labor secretary
in his first term. ``I said in January he couldn't have had this
relationship ... because he wouldn't have been so stupid. I was
wrong on both counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so sad to see him throw away such a huge opportunity,''
said Reich, now a professor at Brandeis.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton biographer David Maraniss calls such risk-taking both
the central feature and the ``riddle of Clinton's life.'' The
recurring themes of his career have been exhilarating win,
humiliating loss, and remarkable recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``One has followed the other with unerring regularity since the
beginning of'' Clinton's political career, Maraniss, a Washington
Post reporter, wrote in a recent essay. ``When the public perceives
him as being down, he is already plotting his comeback. When he
thinks he is on top, the seeds of disaster have been planted.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Comeback Kid showed up once again last week. On
Thursday the president's commanding authority over US military
strikes on terrorist targets overseas erased, at least for the
moment, the image of an angry and embarrassed president confessing
to a relationship that was ``not appropriate'' on national
television Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who voted for Clinton in 1992 knew they weren't voting
for a saint or the pope, but they were voting for someone who would
turn the country around,'' said Skip Rutherford, an old friend of
Clinton's and coordinator of his planned presidential library in
Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   ``They also knew he was human _ a young president who wasn't
content just to sit on the front porch,'' Rutherford said. ``I
think a lot of people can relate to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Former secretary of state Henry Kissinger once called power
``the ultimate aphrodisiac,'' which could help explain why
politicians, including a long list of presidents, have expended
considerable energy and taken unusual risks in the pursuit of women
and sex. There is no way of knowing whether Washington's
extramarital affairs have become more common in recent years, but
they have become riskier because the media show less restraint in
exposing them.
</P>
<P>
   There does seem to be a pattern that the higher the stakes, the
greater the risk-taking. In 1992, candidate Clinton gambled that he
could explain away an alleged affair with Gennifer Flowers and
still win the Democratic nomination and the presidency, which he
did. The gamble in his second term is that he can explain away a
relationship with Lewinsky and save his presidency and legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Former Colorado senator Gary Hart, the leading Democratic
presidential hopeful in 1987, set a milestone in risk-taking when
he dared the press to find him unfaithful. Reporters did; Hart got
caught in a Washington townhouse and on a yacht called Monkey
Business with Donna Rice, a young woman who was not his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Another high-stakes risk-taker was former senator Robert
Packwood, Republican of Oregon. He was chairman of the Finance
Committee when he was forced to resign over allegations from dozens
of women of sexual misconduct. Two decades before, Wilbur Mills, an
Arkansas Democrat, was one of the House's most powerful lawmakers
when a stripper known as Fanne Fox, the Argentine Firecracker,
jumped from his car and into Washington's Tidal Basin.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Berglas, a clinical psychologist at Harvard Medical
School, said these men are representative of those who suffer from
a psychiatric disorder, which he loosely calls a success syndrome.
Highly successful men, at the top of their game, get bored and seek
new challenges and conquests that frequently drive them to extremes
and to savor the thrill and risk of going beyond what is legal,
moral, or appropriate, Berglas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexual gratification is never what the power-crazed,
philandering executive is after,'' said Berglas, who treats many
white-collar criminals in his practice. ``It's about daring the
devil, ducking under the radar, and seeing what, clandestinely,
they can get away with. It's truly an abuse of power, not a sexual
addiction.''
</P>
<P>
   While a subject of controversy itself, ``sexual addiction''
could explain the president's irrational behavior, said Jerome
Levin, a psychotherapist who treats addictions at the New School
for Social Research in New York. In his book, ``The Clinton
Syndrome,'' Levin suggests the president's traumatic childhood and
dysfunctional family _ his stepfather was an alcoholic and abusive,
his mother was a gambler, his brother was hooked on cocaine _ set
the biological and environmental stage for Clinton's own addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton does have a problem with sex, and'' it ``has led him
to do impulsive, dangerous things that make little sense,'' said
Levin, who acknowledges he has never met the president. ``His
actions suggest a drivenness and compulsiveness that certainly have
the overtones of addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing the president could do is admit he has a
problem with sex and compulsion and get some professional help,''
Levin said.
</P>
<P>
   It does not take a psychiatrist, of course, to know that
politicians tend to have oversized egos, appetites for adulation,
and serious needs to be wanted and loved. The risks inherent in
those needs turning sexual are often overlooked and occasionally
even encouraged by political groupies and aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unspoken, but staffers do facilitate and find ways for
their bosses to, well, relax,'' said a former aide to several
senators and who asked not to be identified. ``It's in the staff's
interest to know their horse and know what keeps him ready to run
and win the race.''
</P>
<P>
   To Patricia Ireland, president of the National Organization for
Women, that is sexual exploitation at the highest levels. ``No CEO
and no elected official, including the president, should take
advantage of the aphrodisiac of power to have sex with interns or
staff,'' Ireland said. The president, according to Ireland, seems
to divide women into two categories: ``Women he must treat with
respect ... and those he can use and toss aside like tissue
paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Massachusetts governor Michael S. Dukakis said the
president's behavior makes ``absolutely no sense,'' but he has
studied the presidency long enough to know that throughout history,
the smartest leaders have taken unnecessary risks and made colossal
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Presidents, like all of us, are fallible, they make
mistakes,'' Dukakis said. ``Only theirs are magnified because the
spotlight is so intense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
