<DOCNO> NYT19980824.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9055 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKMAN-COLUMN26-COX     08-24 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKMAN-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's not too late to spare us the gory details
 &HT;    By Jay Bookman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of the several roads still open to President Clinton, one seems
almost certain to lead to his further humiliation and a forced
exodus from office.
</P>
<P>
   That's the road Clinton seems stubbornly determined to travel.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech last week, Clinton claimed he had been ``legally
accurate'' in the Paula Jones case when he denied a sexual
relationship with Monica Lewinsky. By sticking to that claim, the
president still hopes to avoid perjury charges.
</P>
<P>
   There are two dangers in that lawyerly approach. First, it
insults the intelligence of the American public to claim that what
went on between the president and Lewinsky did not constitute a
sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The second danger is more subtle and more threatening.
</P>
<P>
   By quibbling over the definition of a sexual relationship,
Clinton makes the details of who did what to whom relevant. In
essence, it extends an invitation to independent counsel Kenneth
Starr to explore the physical details of the Clinton-Lewinsky
relationship in excruciating detail.
</P>
<P>
   And Starr is apparently making the most of that invitation.
White House spokesmen say that in his grand-jury testimony, Clinton
refused to answer several questions from Starr because he
considered them too intimate. Ordinarily, such a stand might win
Clinton a lot of sympathy. But in this case, the president cannot
logically base his defense on quibbles about details and then
refuse to discuss those details.
</P>
<P>
   And it's the details that will ruin him.
</P>
<P>
   The American people have run out of patience with both Clinton
and Starr. They have had their noses rubbed in someone else's dirty
laundry for months now, and they don't much like the experience.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, few Americans are demanding that Clinton leave
office. However, release of graphic details about the president's
sexual behavior _ which seems inevitable _ would move his
relationship with Lewinsky from something almost hypothetical to
something that is all too real.
</P>
<P>
   It would make the whole thing much harder to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton had chosen instead to admit his perjury, the probable
consequences would have been relatively minor. Some Republicans
would no doubt have seized upon the admission as grounds for
impeachment, but the American people would not have supported such
a move.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the perjury occurred as Clinton gave immaterial
testimony about his private sex life in a politically motivated
case that was thrown out of court as groundless. Americans would
not accept that as reason to abandon a successful president. The
punishment would seem out of line with the crime. The fact that
Clinton was manipulated into the perjury by a conspiracy among
Jones' attorneys and Starr's office would also have counted in his
favor.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton has already traveled so far down this road to
ruin that turning back is impossible. His grand jury testimony and
that of Lewinsky may be more or less secret for the moment, but it
is bound to emerge eventually.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's legalistic defense has doomed the American people to
learn exactly what Bill did to Monica and what Monica did to Bill.
That sordid knowledge and the revulsion it inspires will erode
public support for Clinton just as surely as the Colorado River
carved the Grand Canyon, and far more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jbookman(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
