<SLUG> BC-SCI-SMALLPOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALLPOX STOCKS VULNERABLE, SCIENTISTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The modern-day terrorist's arsenal typically is stocked with the
highest of high-tech weapons, from nerve gas to night goggles,
remote detonators to heat-seeking missiles.
</P>
<P>
   But what has some scientists more worried than any of those
new-age armaments is a potential tool of destruction that dates
back at least 3,000 years: the virus that causes smallpox, the
deadliest disease ever.
</P>
<P>
   Although the virus was eradicated in the wild 22 years ago,
small stocks of it are still kept in research laboratories. If they
get into the wrong hands, they could be turned into a biological
weapon that virologists say would be impossible to contain or
counteract.
</P>
<P>
   Those fears were spelled out last week by two of America's most
eminent authorities on smallpox, who insisted the world must
destroy its remaining stocks of the virus and restart large-scale
manufacture of smallpox vaccine. Their call, published in the New
England Journal of Medicine, seemed to take on new urgency
following American cruise missile strikes that same day against
terrorist targets in Afghanistan and Sudan in retaliation for the
recent US embassy bombings in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've asked the questions, `Why would we keep our smallpox
virus? To zap them if they zapped us?' Everyone agrees that is
morally not right,'' said one of the journal authors, Dr. Donald A.
Henderson, in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our destroying all of our smallpox doesn't guarantee everyone
will destroy all of theirs...but it would put a lot of pressure on
Russia and other countries to conform,'' added Henderson, who runs
the Center for Civilian Biodefense Studies at Johns Hopkins
University. He coauthored the journal article with Dr. Joel G.
Breman of the National Institutes of Health.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over the fate of the world's remaining stocks of
smallpox virus has been raging for years within the scientific
community, and last week's events showed nothing is settled.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joshua Lederberg, a Nobel laureate and professor emeritus at
Rockefeller University in New York, had a decidedly different
outlook: ``If there was a way you could wave your magic wand and
destroy all the smallpox in the world, I would be very much for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But that simply isn't going to happen, Lederberg said. Although
there is no immediate need to the further research with the virus,
he said, ``I don't want to destroy that opportunity irrevocably.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides in the debate are gearing up in anticipation of a
decision early next year by the World Health Organization on
whether to proceed with plans to eliminate all stocks of the
smallpox virus. It is an intense controversy, stoked by all the
memories that smallpox stirs.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just that smallpox has exacted a larger death toll than
any disease in human history, dating back at least to ancient
Egypt. It's also the way it has touched nearly every part of the
planet, killing up to 30 percent of those infected.
</P>
<P>
   The illness typically shows itself within 12 days of infection,
beginning with a high fever and aches and pains that mimic the flu,
then quickly progresses to form small pimples, which grow into
pustules that blend into one another as they spread across the
body. Among survivors, the pustules turn to scabs and leave pitted
scars that serve as lifelong reminders of the disease. For the less
fortunate, death generally comes within a couple weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A universal vaccination program had eliminated smallpox in
America by 1949. A worldwide eradication campaign began in 1966,
when smallpox still was killing 2 million people a year, and within
a decade the disease was wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   But while the illness is gone, the virus that caused it remains.
Officially, there are only two labs in the world that have it _ one
at the US Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta and the other at a
government facility in Russia _ both of which maintain the
highest-level security. Unofficially, however, ``there is a lot of
discussion currently about the possibility that smallpox may have
ended up somewhere other than these two centers,'' says Brian Mahy,
who as director of CDC's Division of Viral Diseases oversees that
agency's stock of the virus. There is special concern that it may
have been stockpiled at at least three unauthorized labs in Russia,
along with labs in Iran and Iraq, where there was an outbreak of
the disease in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming terrorists have the smallpox virus, or could buy or
steal it, could it pose a threat?
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't be difficult to administer,'' said Henderson, who
led the WHO eradication campaign. ``It certainly is possible to put
up an aerosal of smallpox, have it drift a long way ... and have it
infect people with very few particles. It would not become apparent
like a bang... There'd be a delay in recognition, and the disease
would begin to spread by the time the diagnosis was made.''
</P>
<P>
   The speed and efficiency with which smallpox can spread was
underscored in 1970 in Germany when a young electrician developed
the disease. He was taken to a specially-equipped hospital where
everyone was vaccinated, but the disease still infected more than a
dozen others, including an unlucky visitor who, Henderson says,
``came to a corridor door a long way from where the patient's room
was, opened the door, asked for directions, then left. That visitor
came down with smallpox.''
</P>
<P>
   To make things more perilous, there is no known treatment for
smallpox. There is a vaccine, but Americans haven't been getting it
since 1972. Researchers say most vaccines administered before then
probably aren't effective any more, and US stocks of vaccine are so
low that they could only protect about 10 million people.
</P>
<P>
   All that means a biological weapon armed with smallpox could
pose an even greater public health threat than the oft-raised
specter of a weapon bearing anthrax, said Dr. Alfred DeMaria,
director of communicable disease control at the Massachusetts
Department of Public Health. ``We've talked about it considerably,
we've done tabletop simulations,'' he added. ``The problem is,
there's no resources to stockpile (smallpox) vaccine.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution, say Henderson and his coauthor in the New England
Journal, is a four-pronged approach: The WHO should call on all
countries to immediately destroy their stocks of the virus.
International agreements should be signed to ensure more rigorous
inspection of suspect facilities worldwide. Production of vaccines
should be ratcheted up. And plans like one proposed recently by
President Clinton should be developed to cope with attacks by
smallpox-fueled biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The WHO already has approved such a program, but it is due to be
considered again by its executive board and full assembly.
Opponents argue that countries we most fear aren't likely to abide
by any call to destroy the virus, and that further research on it
could yield clues to how human disease-fighting mechanisms work and
help society cope with related viruses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The net effect of proceeding with destruction would be that
the US would destroy its stock and be very poorly positioned to do
research for therapeutic measures if smallpox should come back,''
said Lederberg.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of eradicating remaining virus stocks, however, say
noninfectious DNA strands still would be available for research,
along with safer samples of the related monkeypox virus. And they
say they have learned all they can from available supplies of the
virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no use from a public health sense of these two stocks
of virus, and they are a public health threat,'' concluded Mahy,
who has responsibility for the freezer at the CDC that contains its
stock. After a centuries-long battle to rid the planet of smallpox
virus, he said, ``It would be an entirely logical ending to the
campaign to get rid of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
