<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS TO MARS: WE NEED TO TALK
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   You live with a man, share every intimacy, until one day, sooner
or later, he says or does something and you find yourself thinking:
Who is this person?
</P>
<P>
   These Mars Moments are among the reasons John Gray's 1992
self-help book ``Men Are From Mars, Women Are From Venus'' has sold
more than 6 million copies, spawned spinoff books, seminars,
workshops, a magazine, and, most recently, a board game. Gray's
basic premise, that men and women are so different that they might
as well live on separate planets, is attractive not only because
there's a lot of truth in it, but because it's so simple.
Bewildered by the man in your life? He's from Mars. That explains
it.
</P>
<P>
   At the opposite end of the self-help spectrum is the newly
published ``We Have to Talk,'' subtitled ``Healing Dialogues
Between Men and Women.'' The authors, Janet Surrey and Samuel Shem,
the pen name of novelist/psychiatrist Dr. Stephen J. Bergman, are
married and on the faculty of Wellesley College's Stone Center.
They see Gray's Mars/Venus model as ``a masked return to the
stereotypic 1950s couple.'' Shem and Surrey emphasize the
similarities, not the differences, between men and women.
Biological differences are important, they write, but social
conditioning is what leads to those Mars Moments.
</P>
<P>
   In the separate worlds of Mars and Venus, men retreat into their
emotional caves while women talk. Gray doesn't advocate wholesale
behavioral changes but suggests little ways to bridge the
communication gender gap. The authors of ``We Have to Talk'' think
that if men and women are going to learn to connect, big behavioral
changes are in order, changes that may be especially threatening to
men. They suggest that men and women stop thinking of relationships
as sexually polarizing power struggles and instead think in terms
of mutuality, not just of ``I'' and ``you,'' but ``we.''
</P>
<P>
   In their work at the Stone Center, Shem and Surrey found that
some men hesitate to improve their ability to communicate within a
relationship for fear they will become ``more like women.'' ``The
book's title, then, is an interesting choice, since, as the authors
note, ``To men, these may be among the most feared words in the
language.'' Uttered by a woman, the phrase ``We have to talk,''
often results in what the authors call ``male relational dread,''
characterized by responses like, ``Let me out of here!'' and ``Next
stop, divorce.''
</P>
<P>
   The title won't scare women, the chief buyers of relationship
self-help books. With so many books of this genre in print you
might think relations between the sexes would have improved to the
point where no new titles would be necessary. But they keep coming.
A little while ago a book landed on my desk, ``All Men Are Jerks: A
Woman's Guide to Understanding Men,'' a title that doesn't seem
likely to promote rational discourse between the sexes. But
rational discourse isn't always the point. Consider ``The Rules,''
Ellen Fein and Sherrie Schneider's much-publicized guide to
manipulating men by playing hard to get. It's stupid and
superficial, but it's a bestseller.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with ``We Have to Talk'' is that it's not simple
enough (or simple-minded enough). It's not gimmicky. It doesn't
hold out the possibility of a quick fix. Serious changes in
attitude and behavior take a lot of hard work. Surrey and Shem
write that gender dialogues, as they call them, should start young,
in grade school. Boys and girls should be encouraged to talk,
together, about their differences and their similarities, and to
make friends across gender lines. The result, they believe, will be
adults who won't find themsleves trapped on Mars or Venus.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
