<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-McGWIRE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 WITH EYE ON THE PRIZE, McGWIRE REMAINS A HUMBLE DIPLOMAT  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Flashbulbs blink at every pitch now, shining
thousands of points of light on Mark McGwire. People know they are
witnessing something special, something they'd like to see and feel
and touch and taste as long as they live.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire gets standing ovations when he lumbers to the plate for
batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the St. Louis Cardinals are at home or on the road,
thousands of fans show up hours before game time to marvel at
McGwire's matter-of-fact shows of force. Fans good-naturedly boo
when McGwire performs the obligatory bunt attempt at the first
batting-practice offering. The boos give way to oohs and awe, to
slack jaws and bulging eyes, as soon as McGwire begins swinging in
earnest.
</P>
<P>
   Before Friday's doubleheader against the New York Mets, McGwire
took six swings during his first round of batting practice and
deposited six baseballs over the outfield wall. McGwire took four
swings in the second round and hit four more home runs. He homered
again with his next swing before settling for a line drive that
would have decapitated anybody in its path.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven swings. Eleven home runs. Not once did McGwire change
expression. McGwire has too much respect for what he does, for
everybody and everything that has preceded him, to allow the daily
carnival surroundings to turn him into the jester. His word for the
public's fascination with every step he takes toward the season
home run record is ``overwhelming,'' but he has come to peace with
it rather than declare war.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a kid and playing the game, who keeps track of
hitting home runs?'' McGwire wondered aloud the other day. ``You
play the game because you enjoy it, kids in school play it, you
want to do what everybody in school is doing. I never dreamed of
being in this position. I dreamed about trying to be a big
leaguer.''
</P>
<P>
   They say that God watches over fools and small children.
Somebody up there must have a soft spot for baseball, too, because
there is no logical explanation for the forces that serendipitously
intervene on behalf of the grand old game.
</P>
<P>
   When the Black Sox scandal undermined the very fabric of the
game, baseball got Babe Ruth swinging from the heels and making his
way around the bases with little pitty-pat steps. When a strike
robbed fans of a World Series, Cal Ripken Jr. reminded a country
that some players want to give an honest day's work for a day's
pay. When the time came for Roger Maris' season record of 61 home
runs to come under assault, baseball got McGwire to lead the
charge. McGwire has a chance to elevate the nation's interest in
and esteem for the game, and he takes the responsibility seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's America's pastime,'' McGwire said. ``Every child, boy or
girl, has picked up a bat, ball, glove and played the game in some
form. Softball. Whiffle ball. Little League. I think that's why
people are drawn to baseball more than other sports. Not everybody
has picked up a basketball and shot it. Not everybody has picked up
a golf club and swung a golf club or played football, bowling,
hockey. That's why I think this is the best sport in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine if a self-centered, obnoxious creep like Albert
Belle had been put in this position of public trust? Fans would
come to the ballpark to boo and heckle Belle, hoping and praying
that their ill will would sidetrack his efforts. Each time the word
of another home run by Belle would come, fans would fling their
newspapers and remote controls in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, baseball gets a thoughtful, appreciative 34-year-old
hulk of a man who is holding on to his sense of proportion as
forcefully as he grips his bat. McGwire could have sold his
services to the highest bidder last year, but he made a
quality-of-life choice to stay with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   People took him in as one of their own after a mid-season trade,
and that meant more to him than money. Upon announcing that he
would donate $1 million a year to a charity for battered children,
McGwire broke down in tears.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was genuinely moved Thursday night when he became the
first player in history to reach 50 homers in three consecutive
seasons. After all the questions had been asked and answered,
McGwire grabbed a couple of boxes of baseballs. He took them to his
hotel room, and he began writing. Into the wee hours, McGwire wrote
personal notes on the balls to his teammates, his coaches, his
manager, the equipment men, the public-relations staff. He wrote
the date on each ball, putting the numbers 50-50-50 after each
signature.
</P>
<P>
   If what goes around comes around as often as it should, any
balls of historical or sentimental significance that McGwire hits
will come into his possession. The ball that McGwire hit for No. 50
landed in the hands _ sigh _ of a Yonkers lawyer who is _ groan _
weighing his options.
</P>
<P>
   A Long Island man showed up to Shea Stadium that night waving a
fistful of $100 bills and offering $10,000 for the ball. The
possible asking price for the ball for the record-breaking 62nd
homer is too sickening to contemplate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad thing is, all these balls are going to be held up for
ransom,'' McGwire said. ``I don't know if I'll get (the No. 50
ball) back, or if somebody will buy it _ some collector. I would
like to have it back, and I sure would like to give it to the Hall
of Fame. It's history, and that's where the history of the game is
_ in Cooperstown.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A part of McGwire wishes he were better-versed in the history of
the game, that he had taken an interest when he was younger. A
bigger part of him understands that it is better this way, because
too much analysis could cause just enough paralysis to undermine
his efforts. As a rookie in 1987, McGwire's uncluttered mind
triumphed to hit 49 homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great low-ball hitters of our time,'' Mets manager
Bobby Valentine, then with the Texas Rangers, called McGwire in
those days.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers adjusted, learned that they could tie up McGwire with
high fastballs. McGwire hit .201 and bashed only 22 homers in '91.
His career and confidence were in shambles when a new batting coach
arrived the next year. Doug Rader convinced McGwire that every out
was not a failure, that pitchers occasionally deserve credit for
doing their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had the mental aspect that I use now back when I was
24,'' McGwire said. ``I really don't know how I did it. All I know
is this game is 99 percent mental. I've worked on it very, very
hard. This game is about failure. It can really beat you up. Your
mind is the strongest thing on your body. If you're going to allow
your mind to put yourself down or think about failure or not being
successful, then you're not going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   An onslaught of foot injuries had McGwire seriously considering
retirement just four years ago. McGwire thought of how his father
had polio and couldn't play sports. He decided he was fortunate
just to have the chance to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've climbed a wall, or busted through the wall, quite a few
times,'' McGwire said. ``It has made me a better person, a better
player, because of it. There's a lot of players who never climb
that wall or never bust through it, and you never hear from them
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody is listening to this or somebody is going to read
it _ if it's a ballplayer in college or a minor-leaguer who is
going through a rough time _ I'm a perfect example that you can
turn things around.''
</P>
<P>
   Flashbulbs blink, shining thousands of points of light on Mark
McGwire. People are watching something special and magical,
something they want to capture and never let go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
