<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9069 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-MUSEUMS-CHANGE-BO     08-24 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-MUSEUMS-CHANGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUMS' PERMANENT COLLECTIONS DO CHANGE, AS CAN PAINTINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``Where Do We Come From? What Are We? Where Are We
Going?'' It was the third question in the title of the great
Gauguin painting in the Museum of Fine Arts that sprang to mind as
I wandered through the museum the other day, wondering where some
of my favorite paintings had gone.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that Monet Mania _ preparations for the ``Monet in the
20th Century'' exhibition opening on Sept. 20 _ has caused a
massive domino effect in the galleries, with star attractions
including the fabulous little Rembrandt ``Artist in His Studio''
relocated and three big permanent collection galleries closed.
``Monet,'' in sheer acreage the biggest show the museum has ever
mounted, will spill over from the temporary exhibition space into
permanent collection galleries _ where the installation isn't
permanent at all.
</P>
<P>
   Few things in museums are. That goes for the MFA's neighbor,
too, the Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum, still ruled by that pesky
will that says everything will stay just as Mrs. Gardner left it,
forever. It can't, of course. Paintings have lives. They get dirty
and have to be whisked away for cleaning. They get loaned to shows
at other museums. They get downgraded, upgraded, and reattributed:
Thursday's Rembrandt is today's ``school of.'' They get stolen, as
in the horrifying 1990 heist that left the Gardner without its
prized Vermeer.
</P>
<P>
   The painting that's undergone the biggest recent change at the
Gardner is ``Juana of Austria and a Young Girl,'' a 16th-century
work that, in curatorspeak, used to be ``given to'' Alonso Sanchez
Coello and, before that, to Titian. The great art historian Bernard
Berenson, acting as Gardner's agent, procured it for her ``at a
Titian price,'' says Gardner Museum chief curator Hilliard
Goldfarb. Gardner paid between 15,000 and 20,000 pounds for the
painting; scholars don't yet know if Berenson got a cut from the
seller, as he probably did in certain other instances, which would
have made it worth his while to see Gardner pay a hefty price.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, ``Juana'' has been misidentified, misattributed,
and misdated. Now, research by Portuguese historian Maria Kusche
indicates that the painting was the work of the first major woman
artist of the Renaissance, Sofonisba Anguissola. An Italian
noblewoman who studied painting in her native country and then went
to Spain in 1559, Sofonisba became a royal portraitist of such
stature that, after she retired to Italy, Van Dyck made a
pilgrimage to her home to pay his respects. Kusche's efforts on
behalf of Sofonisba are part of the burgeoning research on women
artists of centuries past, which promises to turn female painters
including Sofonisba, Judith Leyster, and Artemisia Gentileschi into
the Frida Kahlos or Georgia O'Keeffes of their eras.
</P>
<P>
   What makes art historians take a painting away from one artist
and ``give it'' to another? In this case, there was evidence both
stylistic and substantive. Kusche found a letter Sofonisba wrote,
describing how she was working on a portrait of Juana for the pope.
At the time she wrote the letter, in 1561, her style of painting
was the same as in the Gardner ``Juana.'' While Sanchez Coello's
works were hard and enamel-like, ``Sofonisba's of this period show
an Italianate interest in more softly modulated lighting and
looser, more atmospheric brushstrokes,'' says Goldfarb.
</P>
<P>
   About three dozen paintings are now given to Sofonisba, who is
one of only a handful of female painters of note in the
Renaissance. As part of her rediscovery, Sofonisba was the subject
of a 1995 exhibition at the National Museum of Women in the Arts,
in Washington, D.C., but although a color reproduction of ``Juana''
was the catalog's frontispiece, the painting itself was too fragile
for the Gardner to send to the show. It's since been bolstered up
in the conservation labs at Harvard, though, and this fall it goes
to the Prado, in Madrid, for a show about Philip II, the king of
Spain who was Juana's brother _ and who liked Sofonisba so much
that he personally paid her dowry.
</P>
<P>
   While there's a lingering public impression that the Gardner
will doesn't allow loans, Goldfarb says there's no specific
prohibition on them, and that Gardner herself loaned works during
her lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   That lifetime was almost at its end when Gardner's friend John
Singer Sargent painted his last portrait of her, ``Mrs. Gardner in
White,'' in 1922, just two years before her death. He showed her
wrapped head to toe in a pale shroud, her face receding under a
gauzy hood, as if she were already retreating from the here and
now. The portrait, inaccessible to the public for several years,
can now be seen again, thanks to the museum's recent reopening of
the gallery where it lives, the ground-floor Macknight Room. Named
for another of Gardner's artist pals, Dodge Macknight, it is filled
with small works by Degas, Paul Manship, and lesser lights
including Macknight himself, who comes under the category of
``skillful.'' One of the charms of the Gardner Museum as monument
to the chatelaine's taste is that sometimes her taste was for the
tepid. It's fun to see the dramatic fluctuations in quality in her
museum, and to know that the will prevents curators with hindsight
from ``fixing'' her goofs.
</P>
<P>
   Meandering through the paintings galleries in the MFA, unable to
find the little Rembrandt, I did an about-face and headed to the
West Wing Information Desk to ask its whereabouts. The info desk
was gone. There is nothing at all in the room where it used to be:
It's all being done over for ``Monet.'' Meanwhile, there's a tiny
ground-floor information outpost opposite the West Wing escalator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
