<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
! 1/2 ``The Avengers''  Ralph Fiennes and Uma Thurman look cool as
John Steed and Emma Peel, those unflappable defenders of the
British Empire on '60s TV. But the film is clueless when it comes
to capturing the twinkling subterranean interplay between them as
they save the world and pretend not to notice. And Sean Connery
seems surprisingly uneasy as the heavy, a Scottish meteorologist
whose ranting contributes to the dead space. (PG)
<TEXT>
<P>
   (FR)!! &UR; 1/2 ``Blade''  &LR; This film of a gothic comic begins
interestingly as Wesley Snipes's fearless vampire hunter comes
closer than any previous American action star has to Hong Kong's
acrobatic supermen. But the film degenerates into empty special
effects that relegate it to big-screen video game status. (R)
</P>
<P>
   !! &UR; 1/2 ``Dance with Me''  &LR; A clunky soap opera plot is carried by
sizzling dance moves, smartly photographed by Randa Haines. Imagine
``Flashdance'' and ``Strictly Ballroom'' with lots of salsa added
and you'll get the idea. Vanessa Williams projects intensity,
Puerto Rican pop star Chayanne steals the movie with his sunny,
boyish, sexy charm. (PG)
</P>
<P>
   !!! &UR; ``Gadjo Dilo''  &LR; A French musicologist searching for a
legendary gypsy singer is won over to the gypsy way of life,
although filmmaker Tony Gatlif never minimizes its harshness. The
cast of mostly real Romanian gypsies all but explodes from the
screen as they act out their apparent belief that infusing their
second-class citizen status with lusty vigor is the best revenge.
(Unrated) (Romany, Romanian, and French with subtitles)
</P>
<P>
   !!! &UR; ``Next Stop Wonderland''  &LR; A refreshing against-the-grain
quality subverts Hollywood romantic comedy formula as Hope Davis's
melancholy, sharp-tongued nurse and Alan Gelfant's plumber dreaming
of being a marine biologist edge closer together, unbeknownst to
each other, fatefully linked by the fact that each has a stubborn
integrity beneath an unruly surface. (R)
</P>
<P>
   !! &UR; 1/2 ``Regeneration''  &LR; High-minded, brooding but dramaticlaly
inert study of the clash between idealism and expediency in an
upper-class WWI rehab facility, a converted castle in Scotland,
where James Wilby's poet, Siegfried Sassoon, has been stashed as a
shellshock victim to discredit his antiwar writings. Jonathan
Pryce's compassionate doctor and Stuart Bunce as Sassoon's protege,
poet Wilfred Owen, add to the film's sense of committed
craftsmanship. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   ! &UR; ``Dead Man on Campus''  &LR; Dumb and sluggish college comedy with
Tom Everett Scott and Mark-Paul Gosselaar as two flunking friends
who hope to drive their roommate to suicide so they can get
automatic straight As. There are freshman biology lectures with
more laughs than this one. (R) (Renee Graham)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe movie critic Jay Carr's entire archive of reviews may be
retrieved from Boston.com, the Globe's on-line service on the
Internet's World Wide Web; key words ``movie reviews.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
