<HEADLINE>
RECASTING HOLLYWOOD AND LITERARY LISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last June, the American Film Institute released an extremely
silly list that purported to rank the 100 greatest American movies.
A month later, the Modern Library released a list very nearly as
silly, ostensibly ranking this century's 100 greatest novels
written in English. Both proved so controversial they're still
making news.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, AFI took its latest drubbing when TV Guide ranked
the 50 best films on video (the magazine's No.1 title, ``The
Godfather Part II,'' limped in at a risible No.32 on the AFI list).
As for the Modern Library, two members of its selection panel,
Arthur Schlesinger Jr. and William Styron, recently made acts of
literary contrition in, respectively, The Wall Street Journal and
The New Yorker. And The New York Times reports that the Modern
Library, knowing a publicity gold mine when it stumbles into one,
is gearing up a nonfiction list.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with cultural list making is its inherent
misguidedness (isn't a work of art's uniqueness one of the things
that make it a work of art?) but that fact makes lists no less
diverting to argue over or, when they're done better than the AFI
and Modern Library's were, even get some artistic bearings from. In
fact, what's most intriguing about the two lists in question is
that with less they could have been a great deal more: If only it
had occurred to someone to combine them! This idea isn't as crazy
as it might sound. Even the AFI couldn't keep Orson Welles's
``Citizen Kane'' from taking first place on its list, but it did
manage to overlook Welles's next film, ``The Magnificent
Ambersons,'' a work that in its depth of humanity and emotion is
``Kane'''s superior. The omission of ``Ambersons'' may well be the
AFI list's single most glaring sin (well, that or leaving out
Howard Hawks's ``Red River''). Yet the single oddest selection by
the Modern Library is _ what else? _ ``The Magnificent Ambersons,''
just making the cut at No.100, the otherwise-forgotten Booth
Tarkington novel on which Welles based his film. The right title
was on the wrong list.
</P>
<P>
   More generally, the two lists could have come to each other's
rescue through complementing each other. The leading complaint
about the AFI was its slighting of older films (``Forrest Gump''
and ``Fargo'' but not ``The Lady Eve'' or ``Top Hat''?). The
leading criticism of the Modern Library was its being top-heavy
with pre-1945 novels (John O'Hara's ``Appointment in Samarra'' and
Erskine Caldwell's ``Tobacco Road'' but not Evelyn Waugh's ``Sword
of Honour'' or Thomas Pynchon's ``Gravity's Rainbow''?).
</P>
<P>
   As this century's foremost vehicles for narrative expression,
movies and novels share a common storytelling bond, and the degree
of cross-fertilization between the AFI and Modern Library lists is
considerable. Thirty-eight of the AFI-cited films are derived from
novels _ and six of them are in the Modern Library 100: Anthony
Burgess's ``A Clockwork Orange,'' Dashiell Hammett's ``The Maltese
Falcon,'' James Jones's ``From Here to Eternity,'' John Steinbeck's
``The Grapes of Wrath,'' ``Apocalypse Now'' (based on Joseph
Conrad's ``Heart of Darkness''), and ``A Place in the Sun'' (based
on Theodore Dreiser's ``An American Tragedy'').
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the Modern Library list can seem at times like a
Merchant-Ivory prospectus. From it have come at least 57 feature
films, as well as nine television movies or miniseries and one
full-length cartoon (of George Orwell's ``Animal Farm'').
Furthermore, of the 73 novelists on the list, no fewer than 16
tried their hand at screenwriting.
</P>
<P>
   The unlikeliest is Vladimir Nabokov, commissioned by director
Stanley Kubrick to adapt his own ``Lolita'' (No.5 on the Modern
Library list). Nabokov turned in an epic scenario of 400 pages _
the rule of thumb for screenwriters is one page equals one minute
of screen time _ which Kubrick then politely ignored, though it's
Nabokov who's credited with the script. That credit earned him an
Academy Award nomination for best adapted screenplay. Twelve years
later he had the final word, publishing the script as a book.
</P>
<P>
   Burgess also ran afoul of Kubrick. Besides the director's
adaptation of ``A Clockwork Orange,'' the two collaborated on a
script about Napoleon that never went into production.
</P>
<P>
   Both F. Scott Fitzgerald and Aldous Huxley were contract writers
at MGM in the late '30s and early '40s. As a Warner Bros. contract
writer, William Faulkner got to adapt the work of a fellow Top 100
novelist, Ernest Hemingway (``To Have and Have Not''), and
collaborated on what is surely the best screen adaptation by anyone
on the list, ``The Big Sleep.'' (Raymond Chandler's novel is not on
the Modern Library list. Far less excusable is the absence of
Howard Hawks's film from its AFI counterpart.) As for Hemingway, he
wrote the screenplay for a 1937 documentary, ``The Spanish Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Any prize for best original screenplay by a Modern Library
author belongs to Graham Greene for ``The Third Man'' (No.57 on the
AFI list). A close second would be Thornton Wilder, who wrote
``Shadow of a Doubt'' for Alfred Hitchcock in 1942. Two years
later, Hitchcock drew on the services of John Steinbeck for
``Lifeboat.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Mailer's screenwriting experience led to his novel ``The
Deer Park.'' That didn't make the list (``The Naked and the Dead''
did), but there is one Hollywood novel cited by the Modern Library:
Nathanael West's ``The Day of the Locust'' (No.73). West was a
contract writer at RKO in the '30s. As for Richard Wright, he not
only adapted but played the lead in the 1950 screen version of
``Native Son'' (No.20 on the Modern Library list).
</P>
<P>
   Other Modern Library Top 100 members who dabbled at the screen
trade include Hammett, O'Hara, Joseph Heller, James M. Cain,
William Kennedy, and John Fowles.
</P>
<P>
   Besides ``Ambersons,'' there are at least eight novels that
would appear to have gotten on the Modern Library list by
piggybacking on the reputation of their movie versions: ``A
Clockwork Orange,'' ``The Maltese Falcon,'' ``From Here to
Eternity,'' all of which are on the AFI list, and Robert Penn
Warren's ``All the King's Men'' (winner of the best picture Oscar
in 1949), Cain's ``The Postman Always Rings Twice'' (there have
been three film adapatations), Muriel Spark's ``The Prime of Miss
Jean Brodie'' (Maggie Smith's performance in the title role won her
the best actress Oscar in 1969), E.M. Forster's ``A Room With a
View,'' and James Dickey's ``Deliverance'' There's also Robert
Graves's ``I, Claudius,'' which surely owes its place at No.14 to
the superb BBC miniseries that ran on PBS 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, it's a sad commentary on the cultural standing of
the novel that, at most, only one movie could be said to have
gotten on the AFI list because of its literary cachet, William
Wyler's 1939 adaptation of Emily Bronte's ``Wuthering Heights.''
Even then, parsing its selection is more problematic than with the
movie-aided novels: It's hard to dismiss the merits of the film
that Laurence Olivier, who plays Heathcliff, credited with teaching
him how to be a movie actor.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's long been a truism that trashy novels make for
better movies than serious novels do. What the former excel at,
plot and energy, play to the movies' strengths; and what they don't
do well, prose style and characterization, either never make it to
the screen or the power of the image more than compensates for.
With a great novel, so much has to get left out when a film version
is made that the result is almost always a disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   By no means is this a statistically accurate sampling, but the
justified obscurity of the film adaptations of the top three Modern
Library titles _ James Joyce's ``Ulysses'' (No.1) and ``A Portrait
of the Artist as a Young Man'' (No.3), and Fitzgerald's ``The Great
Gatsby'' (No.2) _ certainly bear this out. By contrast, the
top-ranking novel adaptation on the AFI list, ``The Godfather''
(No.3), comes from a book that one can safely assume was never
considered by the Modern Library.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of the mystery of art that trash of one sort can be
transformed into genius of another, and vice versa. Oblivious to
that mystery, the AFI and Modern Library lists have more than their
share of vice, but they sure don't have any versa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
