<HEADLINE>
`SUB DOWN' A CLUNKER; SAYLES'S `GUNS' ON TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES:  &UR; ``Sub Down''  &LR; _ Way down. Alec Baldwin stars in
this clunker that drowns in techno-babble. This story of a nuclear
sub stuck in the Arctic originally aired on the USA network.
Directed by Alan Smithee (which means that the actual director was
so embarassed by the film he or she requested his or her name be
removed from the credits), it's a sinker.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Men With Guns''  &LR; _ Writer-director John Sayles continues to
cut his way through the cinematic landscape with this story of
innocent Latin Americans caught in a violent political cross-fire.
While Sayles's films remain politically sophisticated, his
characters have become much more complex over his 30-year career.
And this is one of his best.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Four Little Girls'' &LR;  _ Spike Lee's documentary on the four
young girls who were murdered in the Baptist church bombing in
Alabama on Sept. 15, 1963, is a moving story that gives complexity
and life to their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``North Shore Fish'' &LR;  _ This TV adaptation of Israel Horovitz's
Gloucester-based play loses its local flavor in the translation.
Aside from a fine performance from Mercedes Ruehl, it looks as if
everyone was in a hurry to finish when they should have been slowly
searching for nuances. Tony Danza, in the leading role, seems
utterly unsuitable.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Pocahontas II: Journey to a New World''  &LR; _ This
direct-to-video sequel to ``Pocahontas'' has some amusing moments
as Pocahontas searches for love.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMING ATTRACTIONS:  &UR; Sept. 1:  &LR; ``Titanic,'' ``Dream for an
Insomniac,'' ``Absolutely Fabulous Moments,'' ``Barney's Great
Adventure: The Movie,'' ``Star Trek: The Next Generation,'' ``The
Spooktacular New Adventures of Casper,'' ``Leviathan,'' ``Child's
Play,'' ``Breeders,'' ``The Vicar of Dibley,'' ``Phantasm.'' &UR; Sept.
8:  &LR; ``Primary Colors,'' ``A Call to Remember,'' ``Children of the
Noisy Village,'' ``The Spree,'' ``I Love You ... Don't Touch Me.''
 &UR; Sept. 15:  &LR; ``Lady and the Tramp,'' ``He Got Game,' ``Deep
Rising,'' ``Hush,'' ``Rhapsody in August,'' ``Eat, Drink, Man,
Woman,'' ``Buffy, the Vampire Slayer,'' ``Suicide Kings,'' ``Man
With the Gun,'' ``To Live.''  &UR; Sept. 22: `` &LR; Addams Family Reunion,''
``Happy Together,'' ``Nightwatch,'' ``Fallen Angels.''  &UR; Sept. 29:
 &LR; ``The Object of My Affection,'' ``The Song of Songs,'' ``The
Trial,'' ``Milo,'' ``Two Girls and a Guy,'' ``The Devil Is a
Woman,'' ``Chinese Box,'' ``The Flame of New Orleans,'' ``Paulie.''
 &UR; Oct. 6 &LR; : ``Lost in Space.''  &UR; Oct. 13: &LR;  ``The Big One,'' ``Black
Dog,'' ``I Got the Hook Up.''  &UR; Oct. 20 &LR; : ``Chitty Chitty Bang
Bang,'' ``Red Corner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
