<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-CRITICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD NEWS TRAVELS FAST ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Retailers beware. On the Internet, everybody will know if your
product is a dog.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is turning disgruntled shoppers into fearless
consumer advocates. Consumers can create or tap into a host of
``anti-sites,'' Web sites where &UR;  &LR;  customers can share complaints
about cheesy products and lousy service with an audience of
millions.
</P>
<P>
   Visit the Yahoo Internet search service and run a search using
the words ``consumer opinion.'' You will find dozens of sites built
by ordinary people who want to denounce _ or occasionally praise _
a particular product. For fast food-phobics, there is the ``I Hate
McDonald's'' page. An angry airline passenger offers the ``Untied
Airlines'' page _ targeted at United Airlines. The boycott against
the Walt Disney Co.'s ``anti-Christian'' policies is backed by a
number of sites, while others support the company. And this does
not count another popular Internet service _ the Usenet, a system
of public bulletin boards or ``newsgroups'' devoted to thousands of
different topics. Usenet visitors routinely post messages slamming
companies that have left them unsatisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the best-known consumer watchdog in cyberspace keeps
his eye on the &UR;  &LR; Internet's most powerful company, &UR;  &LR;  America Online.
</P>
<P>
   David Cassel, a 34-year-old freelance writer in Berkeley,
Calif., was amusing himself in an AOL chat room in 1994, when a
fellow chatter used a four-letter word. Shortly thereafter, the
offending chatter was electronically silenced by AOL.
</P>
<P>
   That casual act of censorship turned Cassel from an on-line
neophyte to a crusading avenger dedicated to exposing the evil of
AOL and all its works. He started AOL Watch, a Web site which,
according to Cassel, gets as many as 1,000 visitors a day. He also
claims 32,000 people receive regular AOL Watch newsletters via
electronic mail.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that when Cassel speaks, people listen. He
reported last year that AOL planned to sell the phone numbers of
its 12 million users to outside firms for marketing purposes. The
story made headlines nationwide and forced the company to abandon
the plan. ``Who knows how much money they would have made off
that,'' Cassel said, ``and who knows how many people would have
suffered?''
</P>
<P>
   The lesson of David Cassel has not been lost on corporations,
which is good news for James Alexander. The former television
production worker runs eWatch, a New York firm that keeps track of
what Internet users say about various businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Over 600 firms have employed eWatch. The company uses ``software
agents,'' software that automatically scans thousands of Web pages
and Usenet newsgroups in search of words and phrases related to the
client companies. All relevant material is then examined by
editors, who write up a daily report for the client.
</P>
<P>
   The company does not attempt to contact disgruntled consumers.
``We're just a listening post,'' Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   He said some of the gripes are actually planted by cunning
investors hoping to spread false information to depress the value
of a company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   But when customers complain about real problems, eWatch reports
can provide client companies early warning about product
shortcomings that need fixing. Said Alexander: ``We are improving
customer service, without a doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But most of the credit goes to angry consumers who
have begun using the Internet to broadcast their gripes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980824.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9082 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      08-24 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG WIDOW NEEDS HELP WITH FINANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am a recently (and very suddenly) widowed 34-year-old
woman, and I am pregnant with our first child. I am about to
receive a $500,000 life insurance payoff, and need help investing
it wisely. I have $32,000 in IRAs invested in mutual funds, plus
$60,000 in a taxable mutual fund account, plus $15,000 bank
savings. When the baby is born I will receive $700 a month in
Social Security benefits. I need $4,000 a month to pay the mortgage
and other bills.
</P>
<P>
   S.C., San Diego
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Please accept my consolations for your loss. But at least you
should be able to develop a portfolio that will minimize financial
worries.
</P>
<P>
   If you consider your monthly requirement of $3,300 relative to
the insurance settlement, you would need a 7.92 percent return on
your portfolio to supply the cash without invading the principal.
In today's market, that's a pretty steep target. But if you add in
the $60,000 that's now in a taxable mutual fund, the required yield
falls to 7.07 percent, which is a more workable number.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest you build a yield-oriented portfolio similar to what I
frequently suggest for retirees _ one dominated by Ginnie Mae
holdings, which will yield about 6.5 percent in the current market,
but with additional holdings at the further ends of the risk
spectrum: short-term bonds at the most conservative, and high-yield
(or junk) bonds at the most aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, if you put half of this money in a Ginnie Mae
fund, you could expect a yield of about 6.5 percent, bringing in
$18,200 a year. A 25 percent position in a short-term bond fund
would yield you about 5.8 percent in the current market, adding a
further $8,120. And a junk bond fund would yield you 8.4 percent,
bringing in $11,700 _ bringing you up to a total of $38,020 _
pretty close to the $39,600 you feel you need.
</P>
<P>
   If it's important that you not invade the principal, you might
tweak the formula a bit, putting a third into the junk bond fund
and only a sixth into short-term bonds. This would bring the
combined yield up to $40,292.
</P>
<P>
   There are two potential problems with this approach.
</P>
<P>
   First, since you would be drawing all of the yield, you could
not expect any growth in principal. That means you would be prey to
the effects of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Second, a portfolio such as I have outlined tends to work well
over the long haul, but it also can be quite volatile over the
short haul. Therefore, if you expect that you are likely to need
more in emergency savings than the $15,000 you listed, you should
hold such an amount aside.
</P>
<P>
   The returns on a bond fund can be wrecked if you get into
circumstances that require a sale of shares at a time that
coincides with one of the periodic droops in the bond market.
</P>
<P>
   This you should put no more into such a portfolio than you are
confident will remain there for a decade, and preferably longer.
</P>
<P>
   Most fund families offer funds in all of the categories I
suggested, but you should limit your research to those that charge
no sales loads _ fund families such as Fidelity and Vanguard, to
cite the largest. This isn't because I am dead set against load
funds in general, but because I am against them when it comes to
fixed-income funds.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to take the more cautious route I outlined above,
you'd might pay a sales charge of 4 percent _ and that would
represent more than half of the first year's anticipated yield.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't feel qualified to select funds, I suggest you seek
out a financial adviser, insisting that you will pay only a
one-time flat fee, and that the selection be limited to no-load
funds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have $35,000. I'm 56 years old and want to retire soon.
Where can I put the money to keep it multiplying quickly and
safely?
</P>
<P>
   G.C., Massena, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, we have to start with the basic reality, which is this:
The greater the potential for quick growth in an investment, the
less safe the investment will be. But a second rule is this: The
longer your investment time frame is, the higher the risk you
should be willing to assume.
</P>
<P>
   If you are planning to retire within five years, and if you
expect to use the income this money can produce to augment other
funds in retirement, this is short-term money. It shouldn't be in
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   So rather than seek high principal growth, you might instead
choose a more conservative path _ investing it now in the kind of
vehicle you'll be using once you actually retire.
</P>
<P>
   Although her situation is different from yours, you might adopt
a portfolio such as the one suggested for S.C. in the letter above
_ mostly GNMA funds, balanced at opposite ends of the risk spectrum
by short-term and high-yield bonds.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to put your money in a portfolio such as this and
let it grow for five years, reinvesting all returns, the account
would reach $49,089 after 60 months, based on a projected 7 percent
return.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't expect to retire that soon, or if you believe you
can let this pool of money grow beyond your retirement date, you
might want to consider something a bit more aggressive, such as a
balanced fund. These are funds that divide their investments
between the stock and bond markets, typically with about 60 percent
of the portfolio in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Good examples are Vanguard Balanced Index fund and Fidelity
Puritan. But remember, in exchange for a higher potential for gain
there's also a higher risk of losses, and such investments would be
appropriate only if you are willing to leave the money alone for
eight to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
