<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PATRIOTS RUNNING GAME, PAIN, FEW GAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ When the Patriots wisely decided they couldn't
afford to match the New York Jets' $36 million offer to running
back Curtis Martin last winter they kept saying ``you can always
find a running back.''
</P>
<P>
   What they forgot to mention is that doesn't mean you can always
find a running game.
</P>
<P>
   With two weeks to go before the regular season opens in Denver,
that search continues with barely a hint that there is any such
thing in Foxborough. Not since the pre-Martin days of Marion Butts
have the Patriots struggled as much to move the ball on the ground
as they have this summer and to say it is a concern would be to
understate the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't much there, was there?'' Patriots coach Pete
Carroll conceded after his team needed 42 carries to produce 120
yards on the ground Saturday night against the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sedrick (Shaw) made some plays for us and was trying to pound
it up in there for us. He was playing his heart out, but we wish we
knew a lot more about Robert (Edwards). Obviously, we're not there
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   In Edwards's case he hasn't been there at all. The No. 1 draft
choice would have been noticed more often in Smithfield, R.I., if
he'd been in the witness protection program. A nagging groin injury
has limited him to six carries, all in the exhibition opener
against the 49ers. Since then Edwards has worn an assortment of
bandages and occasionally tried to practice, seldom lasting long.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, as the Redskins game approached, Carroll said it
would be Robert Edwards Week, but one aborted effort at practice
ended Robert Edwards Week with six days to go, which brings him to
Saturday's game with the Eagles. That final exhibition is supposed
to be Robert Edwards Night, a week perhaps being too much to ask of
him for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Fact of the matter is, if Edwards can come in and show some
signs that he can run the ball at a clip better than the present
2.8 yards a carry the team is averaging, no one will care what he
did the rest of the week. But there is an eerily familiar quality
to things this summer in Foxborough, both for Edwards and the
Patriots, and it is alarming.
</P>
<P>
   The former Georgia running back spent much of his college career
the way he has this summer ... in street clothes. One injury after
another (ankle, shoulder, knee, what else is left?) slowed him when
he was with the Bulldogs, although in those moments when they got
to hand him the ball he reminded many of Herschel Walker, which in
Georgia is quite a comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is in the pros and the pattern has been the same and
anyone who is honest with himself has to wonder if this is just the
way it's going to be. If that's the case, it means no one is going
to forget Martin any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Without Edwards, the Runners Shaw (Sedrick and Harold) have
carried the bulk of the load and frankly they haven't carried it
very far. Sedrick has rushed 52 times for 156 yards, averaging 3
yards a carry. He has run hard, without question. He just hasn't
run far.
</P>
<P>
   Harold, meanwhile, has carried 51 times for 131 yards, a
2.6-yard average. To refresh a memory Patriot fans rather would
forget, in the last year before Martin arrived Butts averaged 2.9
yards a carry and was run out of town on a rail.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the Patriots organization have insisted that as long as
the running back position produces 1,200 yards all will be well.
Those people are wrong because with Butts in 1994 the Patriots
rushed for 1,332 yards and suffered dearly for their inadequacies.
</P>
<P>
   Martin arrived the next season and ran for 1,487 yards and 15
touchdowns and averaged 4 yards a carry. In 1996, he ran for 1,152
yards, scored 14 touchdowns, and averaged 3.6 yards a carry. Last
season, an injury-plagued Martin produced 1,160 yards and averaged
4.2 yards a rush. What you need to understand is that the
difference between 2.8 yards and 4.2 yards is more than 1.4 yards.
</P>
<P>
   It is the difference between making the playoffs and not making
the playoffs. It is the difference between keeping your quarterback
in one piece and having him throw so much he goes down under an
avalanche of pass rushers and gets up a different guy.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the post-Curtis Martin Era.
</P>
<P>
   Without Edwards, the running game has produced 375 yards on 134
carries this summer, an average of 2.8 yards a carry. Some
apologists for what has been going on have argued that the problems
have been primarily ones of blocking schemes and efforts to try an
assortment of things and an emphasis on getting the passing game
down first, but no one can dispute what the Patriots tried to do
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Although Drew Bledsoe threw better than he had all season, the
Patriots tried to run the ball and they gained 120 yards on the
ground, which is the kind of number that can fool you.
</P>
<P>
   Taken at face value one could conclude the running game was
working with a number like that, but the fact is it took 42 tries
to gain that yardage. That's like saying you scored 20 points in a
basketball game without pointing out you needed 40 shots to do it.
That's too many tries for too little production.
</P>
<P>
   The last two games the talk has been that the running game was
improving, yet the facts are against Dallas the Patriots averaged
2.8 yards a carry on 36 runs and Saturday night it was 2.9 on 42.
Does the name Marion Butts ring a bell?
</P>
<P>
   One bright spot in all of this is that the Runners Shaw have
produced few of the negative yards Martin used to in his search for
longer gains. They have, almost without fail, managed to go forward
with the ball when handed it. If they could go, say, 2 yards
farther with it on average they'd be stars and the Patriots'
offense would have nothing to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   But they haven't and it is time to figure out why. Saturday
night it appeared the offensive line had supplied its backs with
several opportunities to break some long gains but they never got
through the hole. They got to the hole and got the minimum the play
should have produced but little more. Leonard Russell used to be
the master of that when he was running here. It's why he's not
running anywhere any more.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Edwards will change all that. Maybe he has the extra step
to get through those holes before they close. Maybe he has the
elusiveness to make tacklers miss, which the Runners Shaw
apparently do not, and the power to run over them if they don't.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps filling this hole will be as simple as getting Edwards
healthy, because those few who actually have seen him run when he's
healthy claim there's a distinct difference between him and New
England's other backs. Unfortunately, up to now the only difference
has been the other backs have been playing.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the regular season opener only 14 days away, even the
ultimate optimist had to concede that the time has grown too short
for short runs and absent runners any longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I've said this before, but Robert's got to play this
week,'' Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   If he does, let's hope he reminds you of Curtis Martin and not
Marion Butts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
