<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9090 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS &LR;      08-24 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY DO VOLCANOES ERUPT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Why do volcanoes erupt?
</P>
<P>
   L.W., Peabody, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There are two kinds of volcanic eruptions: the ones that
peacefully go ``blurp'' and the ones that explosively go ``blam.''
First, an explanation of the quiet kind.
</P>
<P>
   Miles below Earth's surface, conditions are hot enough to get
rocks moving, however slowly _ in most places, less than an inch a
year. But down in the 1,700-mile-thick mantle layer, things are
definitely not standing still.
</P>
<P>
   The mantle rock is solid. Immense pressures from the weight of
the rock overhead keep everything from melting, the way pressure
keeps hot water from boiling and turning into steam.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Grove, a volcanologist at Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, says hotter chunks of rock move upward. As they rise,
there is less and less rock overhead, and the pressure decreases.
When it becomes low enough, the rocks can finally melt into what is
called magma.
</P>
<P>
   Like oil in water, magma is less dense than the solid rock
surrounding it, so it starts to float to the surface. There aren't
any cracks down in the mantle, so it must travel along the
microscopic edges of the grains of minerals in the mantle rock,
kind of like water rising through a tightly-packed sponge.
</P>
<P>
   When it nears the Earth's surface, or crust (which is about 20
miles thick,) the magma pushes up and through cracks, oozing onto
the surface, where we call it lava. The result is the quieter
volcanic eruption, the kind often produced by undersea volcanoes,
which account for about 80 percent of the 200 or so volcanos
erupting on the Earth every day. It's how Kilauea and Mauna Loa
erupt in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   But there's another way that magma forms, Grove explains, which
explains why some volcanoes ooze and some explode.
</P>
<P>
   Earth's surface contains two kinds of crust: Continental crust
is the land that we live on, and oceanic crust is the seafloor. The
crust is broken into huge sections, called tectonic plates, that
are moving around. In some places, where the edge of the oceanic
crust hits the edge of the continental crust straight-on, it dives
under the continental crust, which is made of lighter rocks.
</P>
<P>
   As the oceanic crust moves deep into the mantle, it takes water
with it, embedded in the molecules of the rock. In the mantle, the
tremendous heat and pressure change the molecular structure of the
crust, which releases the water. It rises into the solid mantle
rock, lowering its melting temperature and causing the rock to
melt. Now, molten and less dense than the solid rock around it, the
magma starts to rise.
</P>
<P>
   But this type of magma is carrying molecules of water. At first,
the water molecules don't turn to vapor because of the pressure
they're under. But when the magma/water mix penetrates the crust
and nears the surface, the pressure is reduced. That lets the water
evaporate into steam bubbles, like the bubbles of gas in a soda
bottle that you don't see until you relieve the pressure by
removing the cap.
</P>
<P>
   As more and more gas is released from the magma, the pressure
underground builds; it's like shaking a bottle of soda with the cap
still on. Finally the pressure underground becomes greater than the
rocks can hold back, and KABOOM; You get a violent eruption with
huge clouds of ash and flying chunks of rock.
</P>
<P>
   Why don't these eruptions glow the way lava rivers do? The rocks
and ash are certainly hot, between 1,800 and 2,000 degrees
Fahrenheit. But because that material mixes with water and air as
it spews out, it's cooler than the red rivers of lava that pour out
of non-explosive volcanoes. Those flows glow because they're even
hotter, around 2,500 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
