u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CAVES-MARS-BOS &LR;      08-24 1684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CAVES-MARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARTH'S CAVES MAY YIELD CLUES TO MARS LIFE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. _ Some scientists hope to learn about the
possibility of life on Mars by studying a Martian meteorite; some
concentrate on plans for robotic missions to search for life on the
red planet itself.
</P>
<P>
   But biologist Penny Boston and others have been looking down
below to learn what's up above. They have been researching the
possibility of Martian life by crawling through the dank, slimy
passageways of caverns deep below the deserts of New Mexico and the
jungles of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   It's gruelling work. Boston and her colleagues had to learn to
be spelunkers and technical climbers in order to explore some of
the most inhospitable cave environments known _ which may resemble
environments that could exist on Mars.
</P>
<P>
   In week-long treks through Lechuguilla Cave in Carlsbad, N.M, _
the deepest cave known in the United States _ Boston at times had
to inch along on her belly through passages that were far too small
even to crawl through. She was covered with slime and filth from
the microbes that coated the walls and floors of the cave, and
sweating profusely in the 100 percent humidity. She encountered
chambers where sulfuric acid dripped from above, concentrated
enough to cause severe skin burns. In a cave in Mexico called Villa
Luz, she contracted a severe eye infection from bacteria growing on
the wall, and had a close escape when the cave suddenly filled with
potentially lethal carbon monoxide gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's so much fun!'' she declares without a trace of irony.
The danger and the conditions, she says, are more than compensated
for by the beauty of underground chambers decorated by spectacular
crystalline formations and colorful deposits, and by the thrill of
discovery. ``I love this cave,'' she says of Lechuguilla. ``It
really is like being on another planet... There are places under
there that just bring tears to your eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   What Boston and other cave researchers have discovered
underground is a host of previously unknown microbial species and
ecosystems that may play a vital role in humanity's quest to learn
about the possibility of life on Mars _ and, in the process, add to
the knowledge about life's origins and evolution on Earth. There
may possibly be tangible earthly benefits as well, including new
disease-fighting agents.
</P>
<P>
   Most biologists say the surface of Mars, bathed in lethal
ultraviolet radiation from the sun and with air thinner than in
most vacuum chambers on Earth, couldn't possibly support any kind
of life as we know it. But what about beneath the surface?
</P>
<P>
   Boston, who is scientific director of a Boulder-based company
called Complex Systems Research, said it was only after years of
studying the possibility of Martian life that she thought about
seeking life inside caves. ``Where you have a surface, you also
have a subsurface, and it may be very different,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Mars, that difference might be crucial: Under the surface,
creatures might find a habitat protected from radiation, meteorite
impacts, and freezing cold, and perhaps blessed with liquid water
that cannot exist on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Most people think, as Boston did before she began her research,
that caves are relatively rare formations, and therefore not likely
to be found on other worlds or play a significant role in
supporting life there. Not so. On Earth, Boston said, caves are
ubiquitous, formed through a variety of processes _ most of which
almost certainly could have taken place on Mars as well.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to predict exactly what we may find someday on Mars,
she said, except that ``there will be cavities, and they will have
contents. And there may well be remnants of life, remnant
populations of microorganisms.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 70 percent of caves on Earth _ some estimate as many as
95 percent _ have no natural openings, and the vast majority remain
undiscovered.
</P>
<P>
   Lechuguilla was one of these. A pit leading to its opening had
been blocked by a rockfall, sealing off its intricate labyrinth of
passageways from the outside _ possibly for millions of years. It
was not until 1986 that a group of explorers broke through the
rubble and entered the pristine cave for the first time. Since
then, they have mapped 95 miles of passageways _ and a comparable
amount may still remain unexplored.
</P>
<P>
   Though they weren't obvious at first, the explorers found living
organisms _ none larger than microbes _ thriving in this
sealed-off, totally dark environment. Biologists have been
struggling ever since to figure out exactly where they came from
and what keeps them alive, in the absence of any trace of the
photosynthesis that lies at the base of all food chains on Earth's
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is that allows these microscopic creatures to make a
living deep below the surface, they are likely to be among the very
few organisms on Earth that would be capable of living on Mars
today, despite that planet's harsh conditions. They are a perfect
test case for learning how to detect signs of life on our sister
planet.
</P>
<P>
   And geologists have been startled to learn, just in the last few
years, just how crucial microbial life can be in a variety of
geological processes, changing the shapes and even the mineralogy
of many formations that had been thought to have formed by chemical
reactions. Learning to recognize geological formations that can
form only in the presence of life could end up providing key tools
for detecting the past presence of life on other worlds, including
Mars.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there are odd cave formations that have long been
known by cavers but are only now being identified as products of
living microbes. Stalactite-like formations with a rubbery
consistency, called ``snottites'' by the colorful cave
afficionados, sometimes form loops and complex woven-looking shapes
hanging from the cave ceiling. Boston and her colleagues, including
Diana Northup of the University of New Mexico, have found that
these formations contain rich communities of bacteria _ and
probably would never form without them.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, beautiful arrays of ``cave pearls'' grow on many cave
floors. Like real pearls, these perfect spheres build up one layer
at a time as they naturally rotate in place, in this case created
by the dripping of mineral-rich water from above. But why don't
they just form the more typical towering stalagmites growing up
from the floor?
</P>
<P>
   Boston thinks it's because they become coated with a microbial
slime, which acts as a lubricant and allows the pearls to rotate
each time a droplet strikes, instead of remaining fixed in place
and simply growing upward. To test the theory, she has sterilized
some of the still-growing pearls, to see if the microbe-free ones
begin to grow differently from their neighbors. It's a long-term
test, because the pearls grow very slowly; it may take years to be
able to detect the results.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many other questions the biologists have yet to answer
is how living organisms got inside the caves in the first place.
While Lechuguilla is believed to have been almost completely sealed
off from the outside world for millions of years, there apparently
have been occasional openings that have allowed small animals to
crawl inside. Boston's group, for example, found the skeleton of a
civet cat that apparently curled up in a crevice and died in the
cave about 20,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not how the microbes that thrive in the cave got
there, Boston said. DNA analysis of some of the microbes shows that
they are so distantly related to any known organisms on Earth that
they must have been isolated from other living things for millions
of years, evolving underground to adapt to their exotic
environment. Within the cave, she found, pools just a few hundred
feet apart contain entirely different arrays of living organisms,
with no more than 20 percent in common from one to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Boston thinks it's likely the original population of microbes
that spawned the ecosystems found today may predate the caves
themselves. Now that researchers have discovered living microbes
inside the bedrock in deeply-drilled holes, that suggests a seed
population of microbial life may exist virtually everywhere in the
Earth's crust. As soon as a cavity opens up in the rock, as a
result of water eating its way through or earthquakes or impacts
opening up fissures, these microbes may begin to grow and evolve to
take advantage of the new environment.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that different ponds inside a cave have different
chemical conditions and support different organisms also makes them
ripe for experiments that could be relevant to searching for life
on Mars: What is the minimum size of an ecosystem that can function
and survive for long periods? If, as many scientists now suspect,
life may have gotten started on Mars during a brief period of
warmer, wetter conditions soon after the planet's formation, could
some living organisms have survived in small, isolated
micro-environments such as underground lakes or caves?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are deeper questions here that the cave will help to
elucidate,'' Boston said.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, it may become possible to study a truly sealed-off cave
in pristine conditions, without bringing anything in or out while
doing the research. But that's not possible with present
technology. The research teams take as many precautions as they can
to minimize their impact on the cave: staying on narrow marked
trails whenever possible, laying out mylar groundsheets under their
campsites, eating over plastic bags to catch any crumbs, and
carrying back out everything they bring in _ including bagged and
bottled human wastes.
</P>
<P>
   But they can't help bringing in some outside organisms _
complicating the task of analyzing the cave's native life. The work
they've been doing for the last 10 years, Boston said, ``is really
just practice for someday doing a completely non-invasive study of
a cave that's completely sealed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
