<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-COMPULSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL CLINTON AND THE PSYCHOLOGY OF RISK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've learned a lot about President Clinton this past week. We
now know he did something ``inappropriate'' with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky. We know he says he regrets it _ but has a
hard time saying ``I'm sorry.'' And we know his wife says she
forgives him. But what we don't know is: Why did he do it? What
compelled a smart man _ and Clinton is described as one of the
smartest presidents in history _ to risk all for a fling with a
former intern not much older than his daughter?
</P>
<P>
   Focus writer Matthew Brelis talked last week to psychiatrists
and psychologists in an attempt to get some insight into Clinton's
motivations. Here is what he found.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Renshon, a professor of political science and a
psychoanalyst at the City University of New York. Renshon is the
author of ``High Hopes: The Clinton Presidency and the Politics of
Ambition.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton is a man who throughout his life has never wanted to
be bound by ordinary conventions that you and I adhere to. He wants
what he wants, when he wants, and feels entitled to get it. ... And
he is very smart, very able. He not only has a history of doing
anything he wants, but of getting away with it. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``His charm is really a manipulative charm. It makes use of and
uses people. ... When you know he lied, the thing that stands out
is when the news first broke there was a Cabinet meeting going on
and he sent Madeleine Albright, Donna Shalala out there and asked
them to make statements to the press. He sent them out knowing they
would say things that were not true. Did he care? No. What was most
important was Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe he essentially got it (his sense of entitlement)
from his childhood with his mother. ... She was very smart as well,
and an unusual lady. She became a nurse, then a nurse
anesthesiologist, and started her own private practice many years
ago in a small Southern town, which is quite a set of
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a woman who liked to drink, to go out nightclubbing,
and she liked men. She liked to party. She gave Bill the first idea
that you do not need to conform to convention. .. In the hospital
where she worked, it came to be known that when the horse racing
came around, no one would schedule patients for her. In a
profession where you tend to people's needs, or going out and
having fun with cronies, she chose the latter. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``If you grow up in a house like this, you pick up
self-indulgence. Bill picked it up and he was smart enough to carry
it off.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aubrey Immelman, associate professor of psychology, St. John's
University, Col-legeville, Minn. Immelman's specialty is political
psychology. His analysis of Clinton's personality will be published
this fall in Leadership Quarterly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``After a systematic analysis of biographical materials, I
concluded that President Clinton's personality was an amalgam of
`asserting' and `outgoing' patterns. ... He may commit errors of
judgment stemming from a combination of strong ambition, a sense of
entitlement, and inflated self-confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The asserting-outgoing personality is highly ambitious and
self-promoting, driven by a need to achieve fame and public
recognition. A distinctive feature of this personality composite is
an erotic orientation. For these personalities, sexual prowess
serves to enhance self-worth.
</P>
<P>
   These individuals may have an indifferent conscience and
aloofness to the truth, which, if brought to their attention, is
likely to elicit nonchalant innocence. ... Although they may leave
a trail of broken promises and outrageous acts, including sexual
excesses, their disregard for the truth and their talent for
exploitation and deception are rarely hostile or malicious in
intent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Although their sexual indiscretions may be purely
opportunistic, one may hypothesize, on theoretical grounds, that
these episodes are correlated with periods of uncertainty, deflated
self-confidence, or crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   (Asked about Clinton's address to the nation Monday, in which
the president was, by some accounts, too defiant and sufficiently
apologetic:)
</P>
<P>
   ``When their confidence is shaken, the feigned tranquillity and
cool imperturbability of these personalities may briefly give way
to self-bolstering rage or remorseful shame. In the case of
President Clinton, this dynamic may account for the perplexing
disjuncture between remorse and shame on the one hand, and
self-righteous indignation on the other.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Hermann is a psychologist and professor of political
science at Ohio State University. She is a member of the
International Society of Political Psychologists.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason may be the compartmentalization that Clinton has
often engaged in over time, and the fight he has for himself to
keep down spontaneity and impulsiveness that is himself. One
worries about this compartmentalization. ... The question is, can
you separate two lives? Can you behave as a very intellecutual,
empathetic president who enjoys thinking about policies and
initiatives, but be very constrained, with people watching you all
the time? When does the spontaneity that is the individual really
come out?
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, we have seen this growing phenomenon in the male
community of people around his age, and I wonder if Bill Clinton is
representative of the phenomenon of the male in a midlife crisis.
... He is going to be through with the presidency with a lot of
life left, and maybe he was seeking youth and the trophy wives in
our society. As he said, `When I was 16 I acted like I was 40.' And
now, he is acting like he is 16.''
</P>
<P>
   (Asked about the tone of Clinton's address to the nation,
Hermann said it relates to his compartmentalization.)
</P>
<P>
   ``When he is caught, which person is caught? The person who is
steadfast, upright, and intellectual? He can deny it, see it as not
real. Only when his hand is forced does he have to face there is
another part of him.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert Weiss is the founder and clinical director of the Sexual
Recovery Institute in Los Angeles. He is a clinical social worker
and addiction specialist, and a board member of the National
Council for Sex Addiction and Compulsivity. (He spoke generally
about behavior such as Clinton's, not specifically about the
president.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I have not met the president and not done an
assessment on him, so I can't speak to the specific issue. But
there are a lot of factors with the kinds of folks we see who who
come in for treatment for addictive or compulsive sexual behavior
that is similar to this.
</P>
<P>
   ``They repetitively engage in sexual behavior that clearly has a
detrimental effect on their career, their family, and they
disregard those potential consequences or previous consequences.
Those are signposts of an addictive disorder. ... Clearly he has a
sexual problem; whether it is addictive or not, I cannot speak to
the specific nature. But I can say the pattern of behavior we are
getting information about is very similar to men we see here for
sexual addiction treament.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone grows up in a family where there is alcohol,
abuse, or violence, they learn how to speak in half-truths, to
manage reality in order not to get hit, or to protect a family
member. You are not only likely to see them act out, but also to be
completely incapable of being clear and honest for fear of
reprobation or abandonment. It is an adaptive mechanism created to
survive a difficult set of circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My real sadness ... is that if the president really has this
issue ... he is not going to get the understanding, support, and
direction he needs (as compared with) if he had, say, a drinking
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Rogoff, a Newton, Mass. psychiatrist and psychoanlyst
practicing since 1971. (Rogoff spoke generally about people who
take risks, not about Clinton specifically.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two possibilities. One is they do it because of the
risk, in a mechanism that is called counter-phobic. If you are
afraid of heights, you take up sky-diving. There is a need to prove
to everyone and to one's self that they are not afraid. But in a
sexual situation, I don't think that applies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other possibility is that they are heedless of the risk
because they are following a compulsion. In cases like that, you
tend to see more than one piece of behavior. You see previous
behavior that is similar. And even if they got into trouble, they
continue to do it. The reason for the compulsion? You really need
to know the individual, and it is often the coming together of very
complex matters. I have seen this in many cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who have compulsions who act in a certain way
to satisfy an internal need. But I would not want to take a stab at
determining what that need is unless I met the person. If someone
is aware of the risks, they might choose to ignore them, or, in one
way or another, convince themselves that they will not get caught.
But all of that is after the fact if you are dealing with some
internal compulsion. Whether Bill Clinton fits that picture or not,
I don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
