<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9098 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CHEMICALS-FUEL-BO     08-24 1470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CHEMICALS-FUEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEED BAG TO FUEL THE FAMILY CAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Someday soon, you might be filling up your car with fuel made
in part from from paper-mill sludge, oat hulls, and corn stalks,
thanks to a Princeton University researcher.
</P>
<P>
   Research on the environmental advantages of the new alternative
fuel, which the US Energy Department is considering endorsing for
general use as soon as next month, is expected to be one of the
marquee projects presented this week as 14,000 members of the
American Chemical Society hold their semiannual national meeting in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not snake oil,'' said Stephen F. Paul, a top Princeton
plasma physicist who also researches nuclear fusion. He often fills
up the tank of his own Ford Taurus with batches of fuel he makes
from agricultural trash.
</P>
<P>
   Anything that contains carbohydrates _ corn cobs, wood,
newsprint, vegetables, grass _ can be turned into a fuel additive
through a high-pressure process that uses sulfuric or other acids
to create a key hydrocarbon component of the fuel, which is called
MTHF, or or methyltetrahydrofuran.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate product also includes ethanol, a type of alcohol,
and natural gas in liquid form. Paul, who has licensed his patented
fuel to Manhattan-based Pure Energy Corp., a startup company formed
to develop ``engineered'' motor fuels and additives, believes the
product can be made for 60 to 90 cents a gallon wholesale.
</P>
<P>
   At current prices, which have been unusually low for several
years and are expected to stay low barring a Mideast catastrophe,
that represents a 5 to 60 percent premium over conventional
gasoline. The national wholesale weighted average price &UR;  &LR; this month
was calculated at 59.4 cents per gallon by the Lundberg Survey
industry publication.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Energy Department's assistant secretary for
energy efficiency and renewable energy, Dan Reicher, said: ``With
our nation's increasing reliance on imported oil, it is important
that we develop and use clean, domestically abundant, renewable
alternative fuels, such as the P-series fuels,'' which get their
name from their Princeton birthplace (and which might invite a
``put a Princeton Tiger in your tank'' ad tagline).
</P>
<P>
   Reicher estimated that ``P-series fuels have the potential to
displace approximately 1 billion gallons of gasoline by 2005'' _
out of the estimated 120 billion gallons used by the United States
in a typical year.
</P>
<P>
   On July 28, the department formally proposed adding Paul's
patented fuel to the list of approved alternative fuels, which
currently includes ethanol, methanol, compressed natural gas,
propane, and electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Under recent federal and state rules, owners of large fleets of
cars _ such as taxi companies, utilities, and government agencies _
are being required over the next five years to buy increasing
numbers of vehicles that can use alternatives to gasoline. Some
officials predict that by 1999, five million ``alt fuel'' cars,
trucks, and buses will have to be purchased.
</P>
<P>
   Gallon for gallon, Paul's fuel is estimated to be 92 percent as
powerful as gasoline, an imperceptible difference to most drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Research he has prepared for the Chemical Society meeting
indicates it produces 4 percent less carbon dioxide per mile
travelled, up to 50 percent less unburned hydrocarbon (a key
component of eye-and lung-irritating smog), 20 percent less carbon
monoxide, and dramatically less toxic benzene.
</P>
<P>
   And Paul asserts that those numbers understate his fuel's
potential for reducing production of carbon dioxide, which many
scientists contend will or is already causing global temperatures
to rise.
</P>
<P>
   On average, it takes about five barrels of petroleum to extract,
produce, and distribute four barrels of gasoline. By using less
fuel and reclaiming carbon dioxide from organic materials that
would otherwise waft into the air, Paul asserts, his fuel could
produce up to 50 percent less ``greenhouse gas'' than gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   While Paul uses corn and oat byproducts in his blend, a
Waltham-based company called Biofine has worked out a process to
produce the key MTHF additive from paper mill sludge, newspapers or
even municipal trash.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I know, it's the only technology that's a
commercially viable product that can produce'' the additive,
company president Stephen Fitzpatrick said last week.
</P>
<P>
   From the cellulose in a ton of paper, Fitzpatrick's process can
generate about a quarter-ton of the key component in P-series fuel,
the MTHF, which can also be used separately as an additive in
gasoline-ethanol mixes.
</P>
<P>
   Though the fuel has a sort of medicinal smell before it burns,
and emits an odor like a generously poured whiskey sour before a
car's catalytic converter kicks in, Paul says once a car is
running, ``You can put your nose up against the tailpipe, and it
smells just like a teapot bubbling. You can't smell a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all its advantages, Paul is the first to acknowledge:
``It isn't that wonderful. It costs too much. I can't make it cheap
enough.'' With gas prices dipping below $1 a gallon in many places,
Paul said it would be a hard sell to offer his fuel for perhaps
$1.50 at retail _ even if some environmentally-minded drivers might
accept the cost premium.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had another oil crunch or Saddam started acting up again
or we had a really cold winter and not enough fuel around, it
might'' gain a market, Paul said. But ``it's not the answer to
everybody's wishes, because it's not really solving a problem that
exists. Today, there's plenty of gas.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pure Energy president Merrick Andlinger said earlier this
year that ``we expect to be cost-competitive with gasoline'' even
without using available &UR;  &LR; tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   Some supporters think P-series might gain a foothold in Europe,
where steep taxes drive up the cost of gasoline to $3 or $4 a
gallon and ``green'' sentiment is stronger than in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Trask, a senior regulatory analyst with the American
Petroleum Institute, the main industry lobby, said his group was
``still reviewing'' the proposal to list Paul's fuel as a
recognized alternative fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, however, it opposes any special tax deals or the many
existing mandates on fleets to buy cars that run on alternatives to
gasoline. ``As long as alternative fuels compete on a level playing
field, they will find their appropriate place in the market,''
Trask said.
</P>
<P>
   One drawback is that only vehicles with ``flexible fuel''
engines _ which have sensors that determine the fuel being
introduced and adjust the air-to-fuel ratio _ can burn P-series
fuel. Chrysler and Ford have begun to make these engines standard
equipment on some models, including the Dodge Caravan and Ford
Ranger pickup, and options on several other &UR;  &LR; models.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two years, an estimated 250,000 flexible-fuel
vehicles that can burn gasoline, ethanol, methanol, or mixes are
expected to hit the road, Energy Department officials estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Chemical Market Reporter, an industry publication, cited
predictions by engineers earlier this year that Paul's fuel ``could
capture just 2 or 3 percent'' of the gasoline market ``and make a
lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   The society's president, Paul H. L. Walter, a 1956 Massachusetts
Institute of Technology graduate who spent seven years as a
Du &UR;  &LR; Pont Corp. researcher before a 29-year career as a Skidmore
University chemistry professor, said that ``even I am overwhelmed''
by the range of the 6,700 papers being presented.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that we've seen in our last decade and a
half is the movement of chemistry away from the core areas to
having a lot more of the work done at the boundaries of chemistry
and biology or chemistry and physics,'' said Walter, a former
president of the American Association of University Professors.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Paul's, papers scheduled to be presented included
research on ways to improve the colon-cancer-preventing potential
of wheat bran, implantation of nerve growth factors to repair brain
cells, and use of chemicals that give citrus fruit their bitter
aftertaste to fight cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Other important papers scheduled to come out later this week
include research on transmission of carcinogens by expectant
mothers who smoke to their fetuses, an engineered dietary fat
substitute, and use of a protein in snake venom to fight breast
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is chemistry today, but it would not have been chemistry
when I was at MIT,'' Walter said in an interview. ``What's happened
in the last decade or so has been a vast improvement in diagnostic
technology that's allowing us to solve problems we used to not even
know existed. We're able to do things we were never able to do
before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
