<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9099 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-DIABETES-BOS &LR;      08-24 1462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DIABETES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE NEW MEDICAL TOOLS, DIABETES RATES ARE SOARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIE C. SANCHEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When 12-year-old Jake Dunigan's lab tests revealed a gene marker
for diabetes and evidence that his body was beginning to destroy
its ability to produce insulin, no one was surprised. Just
devastated.
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes has been plaguing generations of Dunigans, striking
young and old in the Londonderry, N.H., family.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to save some of the insulin-producing beta cells in
Jake's pancreas, his father, Jay _ who also suffers from diabetes _
enrolled Jake in a clinical trial of a pioneering prevention
technique at Boston's Joslin Diabetes Center. Researchers hope that
massive doses of insulin given orally, or injections of small
amounts, will trick the bodies of high-risk individuals like Jake
into tolerating the cells that make insulin, the hormone the body
needs to metabolize sugar, which otherwise are attacked by the
body's immune system.
</P>
<P>
   But even as researchers at Joslin _ which is celebrating its
centennial as America's first diabetes center _ and elsewhere are
making inroads on this and other fronts, more and more Americans
are being stricken with diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   In 40 years, the toll has risen six-fold, reaching 16 million in
1997, according to the US Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention (CDC). Only about two thirds have actually been
diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   Another 21 million Americans with impaired blood sugar
metabolism have a 50-to-75 percent chance of developing diabetes.
The cost of treating the disease and its complications had soared
to $100 billion by 1997, up from $5 billion in 1975, according to
congressional reports.
</P>
<P>
   Type I, or juvenile-onset diabetes, the type that Jay and Jake
Dunigan have, affects fewer than than 10 percent of all diabetics,
or about 2 million Americans. For reasons that remain poorly
understood, their immune systems make antibodies that destroy the
cells that make insulin.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of those afflicted, mainly adults and older
people, have type II diabetes. Their bodies gradually become
resistant to insulin, prompting cells in the pancreas to step up
production until they become exhausted and the insulin supply
dwindles, making them gradually dependent on outside sources.
</P>
<P>
   Americans 65 and older account for one quarter of the increase
of new type II cases since 1980, CDC reports show. And about 90
percent of all type IIs are obese. Because age and obesity increase
the risk, diabetes poses an enormous public health threat to an
America growing grayer and heavier each year.
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes affects nearly every organ system. It's a leading cause
of blindness, fatal kidney disease, amputations, and disability.
It's a principal cause of birth defects and infant mortality. And
diabetics are at increased risk for stroke, heart disease, and
nerve damage.
</P>
<P>
   While genetics plays the key role in rendering individuals
susceptible, it is lifestyle that actually triggers the vast
majority of type II cases.
</P>
<P>
   Studies show the rates of the disease in American men of white
European descent are about double those of their European
counterparts. These differences within the same racial group are
likely caused by the American lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   CDC studies also show that diabetes rates among American
minorities are two to three times higher than among American
whites. Native Americans have the highest rates, followed by
Hispanics, blacks, and Asians. These differences among racial
groups are likely the result of genetic differences in
susceptibility, researcheers say.
</P>
<P>
   One intriguing study presented at the American Diabetes
Association meeting in Boston last year illustrates the intertwined
roles of genetics and environment.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists studied two tribes of Pima Indians who live on either
side of the border between Arizona and Mexico. They are genetically
related but dramatically separated by culture and lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Pimas live on a reservation 30 miles south of Phoenix
with electricity, running water, televisions, and cars. Their diet
is heavy in fatty, processed food. Many are unemployed and most who
work have sedentary jobs. Most are obese. The rate of diabetes is
38.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican Pimas live in the Sierra Madre mountains, without
running water or electricity and few modern conveniences. Their
jobs require heavy physical labor. Their traditional diet is very
low in fat and includes lots of beans, tortillas, and fresh salsa.
Few are overweight. The diabetes rate is 6.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results illustrate the importance of environmental factors
in preventing the development of both type II diabetes and obesity
in people who presumably carry a genetic susceptiblity to these
conditions,'' said study author Caroline Fox of the National
Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Some researchers theorize that genes for diabetes once protected
against starvation. But in times of plenty, those genes cause
chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter-gatherers were at nature's mercy 100,000 years ago. Dr.
Barry Sears, a biochemist and nutrition specialist, writes in his
book, ``The Zone,'' that our genes were well-suited to our
ancestors' diets: rich in the fresh fruits, nuts, seeds and lean
meat.
</P>
<P>
   About 10,000 years ago, the cultivation of milk and grains
began. Our bodies have done little to adapt to the changing diet,
however, and few populations can properly digest the new foods.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 75 percent of Americans cannot properly digest
carbohydrates such as grains, rice, breads, and pastas, reports Dr.
Gerald Reaven, a Stanford University endocrinologist. To metabolize
those foods, the body's insulin spikes to levels that stay high for
abnormally long periods. Over time, this can lead to obesity and
insulin resistance, which in turn are risk factors for diabetes and
heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   The American diet today is high in processed carbohydrates made
from grains, as well as refined sugar, and low in fresh fruits,
seeds, and vegetables. Alcohol also contributes to obesity and to
problems with liver function, which help trigger diabetes if
certain genes are present.
</P>
<P>
   The Dunigans carry genes for both types of diabetes. ``I suspect
it was just bad luck,'' said Dr. Gordon Weir, head of the beta cell
transplant unit. ``A type I family married into a type II family.''
</P>
<P>
   But progress is being made on several fronts. New research
spurred by patient advocacy groups and the Clinton administration's
commitment _ more than $2.4 billion over five years _ has produced
an array of alternative drugs, novel methods of insulin delivery,
new genetic maps and tantalizing clues that may someday point to a
cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future, we will train cells to be pancreases,''
predicts Dr. Stanley Mirsky, a diabetologist at Mt. Sinai Hospital
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In experiments at the Joslin, Weir is attempting to find ways to
improve the lives of patients by giving them transplants of healthy
insulin-producing cells. He has raised the proportion of those able
to be taken off insulin completely from 10 percent to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is the scarce supply of human pancreas donors, but
researchers think that may eventually be resolved with the use of
cells from fetal pigs. In addition, special coatings are being
developed to protect transplanted cells from attack by the immune
system.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, Dr. Gary Ruvkin of Massachusetts General Hospital
suggests, a test will be able to reveal the exact genetic mutations
in a person, and there will be a precisely targeted drug to block
the effects of the defective gene that is causing the type of
diabetes that person has.
</P>
<P>
   To better treat today's patients, the National Institute of
Health is running a five-year trial of ways to permanently alter
patients' lifestyle and to measure the effect of drugs that help
regulate blood sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Success in managing the disease lies in tight control of blood
glucose levels, a strategy that has been shown to reduce
complications up to 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That means testing eight to 12 times daily with a finger prick
and glucose meter, injecting insulin five times or more, sometimes
using both established and newer drugs _ all to hold blood sugar
close to normal levels. Managing the disease is a major part of a
diabetics's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my life,'' said Jay Dunigan, who was recently fitted
with an insulin pump the size of a beeper that continously releases
insulin and allows extra doses before meals at the push of a
button. ``And it's a good life.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he thought of the changes already showing up in young
Jake Dunigan, his eyes misted over. ``It just blows me away that my
son might get it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
