<HEADER>
A9102 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-AGENDA-BOS &LR;      08-24 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AGENDA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S TROUBLES STYMIE HIS PLANS FOR PUBLIC POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was a policy blitz like none other, a rapid-fire
unveiling of initiatives on child-care expansion, school
reconstruction, a teacher-recruitment campaign, and Medicare reform
_ all designed to define the Clinton presidency in its second term.
</P>
<P>
   That was in the second week of January. For the past seven
months, since allegations were first raised about President
Clinton's affair with Monica S. Lewinsky, the White House policy
agenda has sat dormant on Capitol Hill, the hidden victim,
according to some Democrats and analysts, of the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after Clinton's widely criticized confession and speech a
week ago, his policy fortunes before Congress are expected to
worsen, analysts said. And when independent counsel Kenneth W.
Starr issues his report on the Lewinsky and Whitewater inquiries
this autumn, lawmakers will be consumed by Clinton's past and
future, not by his current domestic proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he will get very little cooperation in the Congress from
Republicans, and less than before from the Democrats,'' said Erwin
Hargrove, a professor of political science at Vanderbilt University
in Nashville. ``How can he ask people to stand behind him when they
lack a respect for him? It's an intangible, but it matters.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Clinton's path to success in Congress would have
been difficult even without the Lewinsky affair, given that both
houses remain under Republican control. But in contrast, in 1996,
another election year, the White House and the Republican
congressional leadership compromised on welfare changes, a minimum
wage increase, and an expansion of health care coverage.
</P>
<P>
   This year, stalled or lost on the Clinton agenda are a $21.7
billion proposal designed to make child care more affordable, a
$12.4 billion program to hire 100,000 teachers to reduce class
sizes in lower grades to 18 students, and a $22 billion program to
repair decaying schools.
</P>
<P>
   Stalled, too, are Clinton's proposals to strengthen Social
Security and Medicare, and enact a plan to overhaul health
maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides blame not the president, but the Republican
leadership for what has been perhaps their most dismal legislative
year since Clinton was elected in 1992. Even Clinton chided
lawmakers for their abbreviated schedule this year, joking in a
comedy routine at the White House correspondents' dinner in April,
``This is a Congress with nothing to do and no time to do it in.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration advisers said the most conservative elements of
the Republican Party have prevented Clinton from achieving a goal
of bipartisanship that he touted in his 1997 inaugural address.
Those conservatives, advisers argued, have caused mainstream
Republicans to do little for the past year, hoping to avoid
negative attention before the 1998 midterm elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a difficult year, but that has more to do with
the inner workings of a Republican caucus than with anything we
could do,'' said Ann Lewis, the White House communications
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``The single biggest disappointment of the year has been the
pace of the Congress and their apparent unwillingness to make any
policy decisions,'' Lewis said. ``I attribute that to the fact that
the decisions their right-wing members want to make would insult
everyone else, so they are trying to solve that by doing as little
as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic lawmakers and their top aides had hoped that the
Congress could return to questions of policy once Clinton testified
before the federal grand jury investigating the Lewinsky
allegations and addressed the public.
</P>
<P>
   But in his speech, Clinton lashed back at Starr and offered no
explicit apology for his transgression and lies. Many Democrats at
the highest levels were left stunned and fearful of what else the
Starr report might contain. Some aides said they no longer are
focusing on Clinton's program, but on his viability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that this has happened, there is a different aura,'' said
a senior aide to one Democratic congressional leader. ``It is more
heavy on the minds of the members that there is more there there,
and that the report could be more significant than we thought.''
</P>
<P>
   At a minimum, Democrats are frustrated that Clinton's actions _
his extramarital affair with Lewinsky and his seven-month denial of
the relationship _ have allowed Republicans to effectively avoid
developing a policy agenda of their own. The news media, and to
some extent the public, have been consumed by Clinton's actions and
have paid little attention to public-policy initiatives, the
members said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many instances the Republican leadership would rather see
the focus on the president and is using this an an excuse,'' said
Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Lowell Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Republicans repeatedly criticized Clinton's
proposals as too costly, and have largely ignored them since. Some
key Republicans have offered scaled-down alternatives to such plans
as the teacher hirings, but even those have received little support
in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nation has been preoccupied by the president's personal
problems,'' said Tim Fitzpatrick, a spokesman for the Republican
National Committee. ``The Republicans have tried to move their own
agenda, but President Clinton continues to try to beat up on Ken
Starr and now the Congress has to turn its attention to the
president's legal problems.''
</P>
<P>
   White House aides, lawmakers, and analysts said it remains to be
seen how Clinton might regain an air of authority on public policy.
In the wake of last week's admissions, some fear a credibility gap
_ the term first used to describe President Johnson's predicament
when he espoused Vietnam War policies that many in the Congress and
the country did not believe to be true.
</P>
<P>
   The credibility gap widened during President Nixon's second term
and the onslaught of Watergate, eventually crippling his
presidency. In Clinton's case, though, leading scholars have
questioned whether the public would envision such a gap over issues
of sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very important, credibility,'' said Richard Neustadt, a
historian of the presidency from Harvard University. ``In some
issues, foreign and domestic, to believe the president is telling
it like it is is crucial for public morale, for faith, for
action.''
</P>
<P>
   But Neustadt added: ``Maybe this is just a different category,
where lying about sex is different, and you can't create a
credibility gap when you lie about sex. It is crummy, but it may
not be serious in the way the other things came to be serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton aides still are uncertain about his next steps to regain
a place of policy prominence. The missile strikes against suspected
terrorist sites in Sudan and Afghanistan last week helped, aides
privately said, in that Clinton acted decisively in the public
realm and did not need congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Clinton will leave for a whirlwind tour through
Moscow, Northern Ireland, and the Republic of Ireland, providing
another opportunity to appear presidential while leaving some of
the controversy behind. After that, he and his aides probably will
have to address the findings in the Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short term, he should lower his profile, spend time
with this family, reflect on where he is and how he wants to deal
with this,'' said David Gergen, Clinton's former White House
strategist. ``He has to deal with the national psychology as well
as the politics of this. That's a different challenge from what
he's dealt with in the past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
