<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9104 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-MUSEUMS-CHANGE-2N     08-24 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-MUSEUMS-CHANGE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... West Wing escalator.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rembrandt, it turns out, has been reclassified as an Early
Modernist. At least, he's in the small upstairs gallery usually
devoted to early 20th century work. Two years ago, European
paintings curator George Shackelford gave the Rembrandt ``Artist in
His Studio'' the star status it merits, moving it from an obscure
corridor wall to its own free-standing case plunked in the center
of the Sidney and Esther Rabb Gallery. You couldn't miss it.
</P>
<P>
   To make way for ``Monet,'' ``Artist in His Studio'' has now been
moved again. So have other 17th-century Dutch paintings, including
``Old Man in Prayer,'' which was a Rembrandt when I was growing up
but was downgraded to ``pupil of'' some years ago. The other day
its label read ``Rembrandt'' once more. I was glad. I love this
exquisite painting whose theme is reflection _ reflected light,
reflected thoughts. It's a great painting no matter who did it, and
of course it shouldn't matter whether it's a Rembrandt or a John
Doe. But the concept of the individual artist-genius has so taken
hold that it does matter _ not only to the painting's monetary
value, but to its hold on our hearts. It turns out, though, that
the painting hadn't been reinstated at all: The MFA computers were
just temporarily incapable of printing out a label that said
``Rembrandt, Pupil of.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubism, meanwhile, has moved two rooms farther on: It's now in
the big Impressionist gallery that is probably the most popular
place in the whole museum. At the moment, it's also the most
startling place. Picasso meets Monet. The violently shattered
images of the former with the sweetly dissolving ones of the
latter. Imagine.
</P>
<P>
   New pairing of paintings affects how you see them, how each one
hits your eye. One new couple in the big gallery is Kirchner's
``Reclining Nude'' and Van Gogh's ``Lullaby: Madame Augustine
Roulin Rocking a Cradle.'' The skin of both ladies is citrusy.
``Madame Roulin always looked jaundiced,'' observes MFA research
assistant Deanna Griffin. ``But next to the Kirchner she's
especially yellow-green.''
</P>
<P>
   Picasso's ``Portrait of a Woman'' now hangs next to Matisse's
``Carmelina.'' The pairing encourages you to seek out the ``Woman''
who hovers in the background of the fractured planes of the
Picasso, and to notice how somber and sculptural the figure in the
Matisse is _ and how earthy its palette for a painter whose name is
synonymous with color that sings.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Monets still ensconced in the room is ``La
Japonaise,'' the artist's 1876 portrait of his wife, set against a
wall of fans and giddily swirling around in a Japanese kimono
embroidered with a Samurai warrior who looks about to leap off the
skirt. It's Monet's comment on the obsession with things Japanese
among fashionable French of the time. As the label hints, it's also
comical. Camille Monet was really a brunette, but here she's a
blonde: Her husband had her wear a wig, perhaps to highlight the
silliness of a westerner playing at being Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   ``La Japonaise'' prompts thoughts of the intriguing
Monet-Japan-Boston triangle. Japanese collectors were right there
with Bostonians in buying Monets early on, when the paint was
virtually still wet. Bostonians also bought quantities of superb
Japanese Buddhist art. In April, Boston's MFA opens its
years-in-the-making Japanese branch, attached to a hotel in Nagoya,
and one of the first shows there will be French landscapes from the
MFA collections. The museum is currently holding Wednesday-evening
Japanese lessons, to prepare curators who'll be commuting.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``La Japonaise,'' Millet's ``The Sower'' and Sargent's
``The Daughters of Edward Darley Boit'' are MFA signatures. Unlike
``La Japonaise,'' the Millet and Sargent are now off view, to the
disappointment of tourists who expect to see them on the MFA walls.
The Millet has gone to Paris to be in a show at the Musee d'Orsay.
The ``Boit Brats,'' as they're affectionately called, are preparing
to depart for London, where they'll be in a big Sargent
retrospective opening at the Tate in October.
</P>
<P>
   But don't book a ticket to Heathrow. The Sargent show comes to
the MFA next June. At the same time, the Gardner Museum mounts a
companion exhibition, ``Sargent: The Late Landscapes,'' which will
go in the museum's temporary exhibition space, currently serving a
more mercantile function. During the summer tourist season, it's an
extension of the gift shop. For a small museum that already charges
a big admission ($10 for adults) this encroachment of commerce on
curatorial turf is sad.
</P>
<P>
   The Gardner exhibition will show a side of Sargent less well
known than his famously flattering portraits of aristocrats, even a
Sargent influenced by Monet's late landscapes. If that's still not
enough Sargent for you, the MFA is currently restoring its great
mural cycle by the artist, a project scheduled for completion by
the opening of the show. There are also important Sargent murals at
Harvard and the Boston Public Library. After Monet Mania, we're in
for a Sargent Spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
