<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9108 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-CHAMBERMAID-BOS     08-24 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CHAMBERMAID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOATING ANOTHER TITANIC LOVE STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two young, attractive people from different backgrounds find a
romance which blossoms in the shadow of an extraordinary luxury
liner. Their love _ so perfect, so pure _ is brutally interrupted
when the ship, on its madien voyage, meets a tragic end in the icy
waters of the North Atlantic in April 1912.
</P>
<P>
   This may all sound familiar, but this isn't ``Titanic,'' James
Cameron's Oscar-sweeping 1997 romantic epic. There's no Rose or
Jack, no fabulous jewel necklace, no band playing ``Nearer My God
to Thee,'' as doomed passengers clasp their hands in a final,
desperate prayer.
</P>
<P>
   The film is ``The Chambermaid,'' a dizzyingly romantic story
about a coal worker who has an affair with a maid the night before
she is set to sail on the ill-fated Titanic. It is, to be sure, a
love story, but it is also a tale of the blurred lines between
fantasy and reality, and how the shared recollections of one man
changes his life as well as the lives of those around him. The
film's original title, ``The Chambermaid on the Titanic,'' was
changed at the end of last week in time for its nationwide release
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think the word, `Titanic' is almost the property
of James Cameron,'' joked Aitana Sanchez Gijon, who portrays Marie,
the chambermaid, in the film. She was recently in Boston, along
with costar Oliver Martinez, and writer-director Bigas Luna to
promote the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to know this is not the Titanic story or a
remake,'' she said. ``We have the Titanic as a context, but this is
a completely different thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is less about the Titanic than the liberating and
fanciful nature of love. Horty (Martinez) wins a contest of
strength at the foundry where he works. His prize is a trip to
Southampton, England to watch the launch of the Titanic. Since
there is only one ticket, he makes the trip without his wife Zoe
(Romane Bohringer).
</P>
<P>
   After he checks into his hotel, he meets Marie (Gijon), a
beautiful maid with nowhere to stay. Although there's an instant
mutual attraction, Horty is at first reluctant to allow her to stay
in his room. He gives her his bed, but soon she invites him to
share it with her. By morning, Marie is gone. Left only with a
picture hastily snapped by a photographer, Horty is unsure whether
he and Marie spent a romantic night together, or if the passion
lived only in his dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Once he hears of the Titanic's demise, Horty tells his friends
about Marie. With each telling, the story becomes more elaborate
and passionate, with Horty and Marie making love within the opulent
rooms of the fabled ship.
</P>
<P>
   The story begins as Horty's revenge against Zoe, who Horty
believes is having an affair with his boss. But Horty's motivations
run far deeper, Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film is about various subjects like love, hatred and
lying. But it's also about the artistic dimension hidden within
everyone,'' he said. Born in France, he answered questions in his
native language through a translator, and in English.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the idea of a worker having cultural standards and
artistic standards within him,'' Martinez said. ``When he takes his
trip (to see the Titanic), he discovers another part of life, and
he becoms a different man. This was an initiation for Horty, and
going through this helps him figured out things within him.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the novel by Didier Decoin, Luna, who adapted the film
with Cuca Canals, said he identifies with Horty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a creator also, as Horty becomes a creator with his
story. I'm a storyteller, so I relate very well to Horty. It's a
movie which tells how creation starts, the mechanism of creation,
which is what happens to Horty,'' he said. ``It's something which
fascinates me, the limits between reality and imagination. The
Titanic is the symbol of a century, a particular life slipping
away. And after the ship goes down, after our reality disappers,
what we will have left and what we help us survive is imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, for me, as an artist,'' Luna said, ``the question becomes
which is more important _ what you think and how you live or what
you desire?''
</P>
<P>
   Playing the object of Horty's desire was a formidable task for
Gijon, a stunning Italian-born actress raised in Spain. Marie, she
said, had to be as a much flesh-and-blood woman as a fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first read the script and I talked to Bigas, I told him
I loved the story, I loved the character, but I was worried because
it was challenge,'' she said ``The character could be just an
image, a symbol, and I didn't want that. She needed to be a real
woman. On one side she needs to be an ideal woman for Horty since
he's the one who tells the story, and we see her through his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the hand, she must be real,'' Gijon said. ``You should be
able to almost touch her. If not, the story has no soul.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's ending is open to interpretation, another aspect
which attracted Luna to the story. Whether Horty's story of passion
with a chambermaid is true is almost besides the point, Luna said.
Depending on personal experience, each audience member can draw
their own conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end, it doesn't matter whether the story happened or
not,'' Gijon said. ``The point is sometimes fantasy and imagination
is better than reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Luna, ``In some ways, we're showing the mechanism of love
_ how love starts, how love is related to imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working with the film, I arrived at the conclusion that love
is an intellectual creation, something we invent,'' he said. ``It's
one of the best inventions of human nature _ we have religion, we
have culture, and we have love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
