<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9110 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-PREVIN-ART-BOS &LR;      08-24 1690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-PREVIN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDRE PREVIN'S FIRST OPERA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENOX, Mass. _ Andre Previn waited until he was 69 to write his
first opera, ``A Streetcar Named Desire.'' The San Francisco Opera
will present the premiere of Previn's version of Tennessee
Williams's play next month. Soprano Renee Fleming has already
recorded one of Blanche Dubois's arias, ``I Want Magic!,'' with
James Levine on a London/Decca CD scheduled for release next month.
In the music you can hear the heat, the mugginess, Blanche's
desperation, and her special grace. Deutsche Grammophon plans to
record the opera live in San Francisco for release before the end
of the year, and ``Great Performances'' is taping it for
television.
</P>
<P>
   Previn is a late bloomer in opera, but his case is not unique;
at 89, Elliott Carter has just completed his own first opera.
Previn has composed music most of his life, starting out in films
(``Elmer Gantry'' may be his best original score); in 1969 he wrote
a Broadway show for Katharine Hepburn, ``Coco.'' But his first
famous concert work didn't arrive until 1976, ``Every Good Boy
Deserves Favour,'' a play for actors and orchestra that he wrote in
collaboration with Tom Stoppard. Since then Previn has composed a
piano concerto, which the Boston Symphony has programmed for next
season, and a large body of chamber music, vocal music, and works
for solo instruments. He has enjoyed the process of creating
``Streetcar'' so much that he's already at work planning the next
opera.
</P>
<P>
   Recently Previn took some time over tea near Tanglewood to talk
about ``Streetcar''; he had conducted a Boston Symphony concert the
night before and was about to start rehearsals for a concert with
the Tanglewood Music Center Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Previn has admired Tennessee Williams's play for years, but
never particularly thought of it as a subject for an opera, or for
himself. ``I read the play when it came out in 1947, but I didn't
see it until a London production which must have been in the late
'50s sometime; Claire Bloom was Blanche, and she was
transcendentally wonderful. Of course, I saw the movie with Marlon
Brando and Vivian Leigh, and a Broadway revival with Jessica Lange.
I saw a TV version with Ann-Margret, and she wasn't bad. I think
`Streetcar' is one of the great American plays. It is intensely
touching, yet parts of it are also very funny. One of my theater
friends still says that the first production was the best-directed
new play ever.''
</P>
<P>
   How the opera came to him ``is not much of an anecdote,'' Previn
says. ``Lofi Mansouri, who runs the San Francisco Opera, called me
near the end of 1994, and asked me if I wanted to write an opera.
`Just abstractly?' I asked him. He said, `No _ would you like to
write ``A Streetcar Named Desire''?' I said `Yes.' I was instantly
crazy about the idea, and why shouldn't I be?''
</P>
<P>
   Some time went into making the appropriate arrangements with the
Williams estate and into finding an appropriate librettist. The
choice fell on Philip Littell, who had written the text for an
earlier opera premiered in San Francisco, Conrad Susa's ``Les
liaisons dangereuses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was also anxious to settle on a cast,'' Previn says. ``Like
Benjamin Britten, I have written all my music with specific
performers in mind. Renee Fleming was a given for Blanche.
Paradoxically, all three of the other principals I had first seen
in Britten operas: Rodney Gilfrey, who sings Stanley, I saw as
Billy Budd; Elizabeth Futral I saw in `A Midsummer Night's Dream';
and Anthony Dean Griffey, who will be Mitch, I saw in `Peter
Grimes' here at Tanglewood. Colin Graham, the director, of course
directed most of the premieres of the later Britten operas. Renee
did me a most unusually flattering favor when I told her I was
about to write `Streetcar.' `Would you be interested?' I asked her.
`I'll do it,'' she replied. `I've heard your music; just do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Littell's job was primarily one of condensing and cutting;
nearly every word in the libretto comes from the play. ``The play
is four hours long,'' Previn says. ``If I had tried to set all of
it, it would have been as long as Messiaen's `St. Francis of
Assisi'! Philip was way ahead of me. We talked in advance about
where the arias would come, and he was very accommodating, but I
didn't start until he was finished. Philip, Colin, and I had
conversations about our perceptions of Blanche. For me she is
totally sympathetic. Philip may not be quite so sympathetic; he
finds her morally censorable. I think the play is exclusively about
Blanche, and not really about Stanley so much; it took Brando to
make us think it was. Talk about a life _ Blanche's life was
preordained _ she is a sad, doomed, vulnerable woman; that's why
she's so riveting. Those are the qualities Claire Bloom brought out
so brilliantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Previn admits he was concerned about the famous rape scene.
```What are you going to show?' I asked Colin. He told me the stage
would be completely blacked out, and that he wanted two minutes of
music. I said, `Colin, you can't rape Blanche in two minutes; give
me between four and five!'''
</P>
<P>
   Previn says he wasn't intimidated by the famous lines in
``Streetcar'' _ even people whose memory for details of the plot is
hazy remember lines like ``I have always depended on the kindness
of strangers,'' ``We've had this date with each other from the
beginning,'' ``I want magic!,'' and even ``Stell-lahhhh!'' This
last line is the only one Previn did not set to music. ``There is
no way to have that sung without getting a laugh. Dietrich
Fischer-Dieskau himself, standing at the foot of those stairs,
couldn't control the audience. Philip wanted me to set it to music,
but I said, `It can't be done.'''
</P>
<P>
   Previn says the musical language in ``Streetcar'' is
``reasonably tough.'' ``This ain't `Susannah'; I don't think you
can be ingratiating all the time in this story. But I have always
been in favor of music with a tonal center, although I think some
of the composers today have turned the clock backwards too far. The
aria `I Want Magic!' is an exception. I thought at that point it
would be wise to retreat into something absolutely unreal in terms
of today's music.''
</P>
<P>
   The aria appears in the context of a duet between Blanche and
her mismatched suitor Mitch. ``He's lost for a set of different
reasons from hers, but both of them are so desperately lonely that
they keep hoping to find what they need in each other, although
both of them must know better _ he's completely wrong for her, this
sad and fragile mama's boy. Even when Tennessee Williams wrote
characters he was alienated from, he infused them with something
that makes you sorry for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years Previn has conducted an eclectic but limited
operatic repertory _ works of Mozart, Britten, Walton, Ravel,
Johann Strauss. ``Coming up there are quite a lot _ Korngold's `Die
tote Stadt,' Stravinsky's `The Rake's Progress,' Strauss's
`Daphne,' and Lehar's `The Merry Widow.''' He says his operatic
heroes in this century are Britten in England and Samuel Barber in
this country. ``I like that kind of musical vocabulary. In Ben's
work, I like the unfailing sense of drama, the sheer theatricality.
I think `The Turn of the Screw' is genuinely scary; it's the
scariest opera I know. In Barber, what I find so appealing is that
nonstop lyricism of his. Just when his music seems to be veering
towards the simplistic, he will throw a surprise at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Previn argues that his work for the movies and Broadway doesn't
really feed into ``Streetcar.'' ```Coco' was written for a great
personality, but she is not a singing personality. When Danielle
Darrieux came in to replace Katharine Hepburn, she sang like a
dream, and the show closed immediately, but Alan Jay Lerner and I
realized for the first time that we had written a musical. But
there's a difference between writing a musical and writing an opera
_ in a musical, almost nothing is developed; it's just a series of
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of musical references in Williams's play, and
Blanche sings ``Paper Moon'' in the bathtub. ``Music added a
dimension to what was essentially a nonmusical play. But those
specific references which worked so well in the play would set up
interference in the opera. I also made a conscious decision not to
use specific references to New Orleans jazz music for the same
reason that if I were writing an opera about Russia I wouldn't
necessarily want to introduce a balalaika. Of course, I've heard
and played a lot of jazz in my lifetime, so people are bound to say
that there is a jazz influence in the harmonies or the rhythmic
patterns. I like to quote Aaron Copland, who replied to questions
about jazz in his work by saying, `I didn't grow up in a vacuum.' I
didn't set out to write a jazz-influenced score, but I didn't set
out not to do it either.''
</P>
<P>
   Previn says he composed the score in order. ``I didn't have much
of a floor plan, although I marked the things that would obviously
be arias or duets. I also made the decision to stick very closely
to the speech patterns _ I don't like elongations and stretching of
syllables. Renee says her part is taxing, but that it was easy to
memorize because the rhythms of the music are the same as the
rhythms you would use if you were speaking the lines. All along the
way I had to stick by musical decisions I had made, decisions that
had long-lasting consequences. I knew when I was writing music that
I would need to use again in the opera.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The appeal of opera to me,'' Previn says, ``is the combination
of music and drama _ this is irresistible, the collaboration of
voice and orchestra. And opera is the one place left in the theater
where the composer has the last word! Luckily I've got a lot of
elaborate plans _ Lofti was nice enough to say, `You pick 'em and
we'll do 'em.' I'm trying to make up for lost time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
