<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9115 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-ZOMBIES-BOS &LR;      08-24 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ZOMBIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZOMBIE'S ROCK REMAINS A HORROR SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rob Zombie has this theory. It's sort of like ``everything you
really need to know you learned in kindergarten,'' but with a
twist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everything that you will later enjoy in life will
somehow form by the time you are about 6,'' says Zombie. ``Like big
sports fanatics who will mortgage their homes to go to baseball
games. That's obviously an obsession left over from being a kid.
The worst thing is the people who give them up. Then they just
wander around for the next 60 years and go `How come life seems so
boring?''' Of course, he notes, so-called normal people ``put a lot
of effort into trying to make you feel embarrassed for enjoying
your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Zombie's life is not boring, he thoroughly enjoys himself, and
he's proud to wear his childhood/adult obsessions on his sleeve.
And face. And all over the music he's created with his band White
Zombie and now on a solo CD called ``Hellbilly Deluxe,'' out
Tuesday. Zombie and his band _ guitarist Riggs, bassist Blasko, and
drummer Tempesta _ will begin a tour in October, with a probable
date at the Orpheum around Halloween. (Zombie was originally slated
to be part of the Korn-helmed Family Values tour, which kicks off
in Worcester, Mass. Sept. 23, but he pulled out in order to do his
own thing and a longer set.)
</P>
<P>
   Zombie's groove-centered, techno-hard rock remains a horror
show. Some of the song titles on the new album: ``Call of the
Zombie,'' ``Superbeast,'' ``Dragula'' ``Spookshow Baby,'' ``How to
Make a Monster,'' and ``Meet the Creeper.''
</P>
<P>
   You can guess how the young Zombie grew up. ```Creature Double
Feature' on Channel 56 (Boston)!'' he crows. (Yes, the Zombie
family _ though his parents use another surname _ grew up in these
environs. Rob's younger brother is Spider of Powerman 5000.)
Zombie's formative years were spent watching ``Frankenstein,''
``King Kong,'' ``Destroy All Monsters.'' He particularly dug the
creepy Hammer Films ``Dracula'' series starring Christopher Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Zombie isn't trying for horror movie effect in his music _
``not,'' he says, ``in the sense that I'm ever trying to do
something shocking per se. But if it comes off that way, it's fine.
But it's never the goal. You want to get across a vibe. I'm really
into the old Universal (films) where it's all about the atmosphere.
Nothing's actually happening, but you get the vibe.''
</P>
<P>
   Zombie, who has had five Grammy nominations, has sold millions
of albums, but he had nothing to do with his band's most recent
accomplishment. Nevertheless, he takes pride in the fact that White
Zombie's ``Thunder Kiss '95'' was played continuously at maximum
volume on a loop outside the Barbra Streisand-James Brolin wedding
reception in order to drive the assembled press crazy and keep them
at bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I pulled that off; a lot of work went into that,'' he
deadpans.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if Babs had really wanted to decimate the press
corps, she would have dug deeper into the White Zombie catalog. The
New York-based band began during the early 1980s and made a
godawful punk/art/noise racket, practically unlistenable to anyone
outside that circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was practically unlistenable to anyone's ears,''
offers Zombie. Our sound ``was just an evolution. We were a total
garage band, a bunch of people who started a band, who couldn't
play, or who knew how to play just enough. It wasn't ever like we
were trying to do one thing and then another. It was just that we
weren't good enough to be able to do what we wanted to do. So every
record is different in a more advanced way. I don't think bands
should just say `Oh this is what we do and we're going to do it
'til we drop dead.' You know, you can get better at something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was definitely a turning point, but I don't know what
the turning point was. For us, musically, I'm not sure. But for us
as a band in the industry, the turning point was when bands like
Jane's Addiction and Soundgarden were getting signed. I remember
those bands from the club level. And all of a sudden it was like
having a band, could be worth (something).''
</P>
<P>
   White Zombie made its major label debut with ``La Sexorcisto:
Devil Music Vol. 1'' in 1991. It went double platinum. Then came
``Astro-Creep: 2000.'' Also double platinum. Then came a bunch of
collaborations and soundtrack songs, and, most spectacularly, the
garish Beavis-goes-to-hell fantasy sequence in ``Beavis and
Butt-head Do America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hellbilly Deluxe'' bears Rob's name but has obvious
connections to the White Zombie sound. ``I don't know if it's
different at all from White Zombie,'' he says. ``White Zombie was
my band for 13 years. I think it may be different because it's
produced better and different musicians are playing that bring a
different flair to it.''
</P>
<P>
   So is White Zombie _ pardon the pun _ dead?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' says Zombie. ``We just kind of took a year off and in
that year I got bored. I wanted to keep working, and this project
started as a little time-killer that snowballed into a full-blown
thing. So it's not something I just walk away from. I have to see
it through to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Zombie has long been a fan of Alice Cooper and KISS,
shock-rockers from the '70s, who are now his friends and peers.
Cooper, of course, presented his Alice as character created by the
artist _ a separate entity and ego-monster. Zombie says, of his
rock self, ``I don't think of it as a character at all. It's just
me; it blows up your personality. I see it in rehearsal, when the
adrenaline starts pumping. It's like an athlete or something. It's
the same guy, he doesn't create a character, but when he gets on
the field he's pumped up. It's like a super version of your
off-stage personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Onstage and off, Zombie is a man with an X in the middle of his
forehead, a fashion statement made famous by celebrity killer
madman Charles Manson. (Before there was Marilyn Manson, there was
Charles.) Is Manson cool?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think cool is the right word,'' says Zombie, who was
but 4 years old when Manson declared Helter Skelter on Sharon Tate,
the LaBianca family, and others in 1969. ``I do think he's very
interesting. People always go, `That's sick' but how can you deny
what a bizarre story that is? I mean, it's not funny to the
families. But it's like the O.J. thing. The media creates another
persona with this person and he becomes famous. Why are you seeing
him on TV? You forget it's because they murdered someone. Manson
starts to seem like some standup comic when you're watching him.
The media is to blame. They keep sticking him on TV and somehow
find a way to make him entertaining.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
