<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEFT STROKE BY CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- In at least one sense _ the best sense _ there was
indeed a link between last week's cruise missile attacks on Osama
bin Laden's terrorism infrastructure and President Clinton's
ability to hold on to his office amid scandal.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning _ while the rubble from the horrors in Kenya
and Tanzania was still smoldering _ the president's foreign policy
advisers put Congress's four top leaders in the loop of their
decision-making; Newt Gingrich and Trent Lott, in short, were on
the ground floor.
</P>
<P>
   That was wise politics on the merits, particularly because the
missile attacks represent an important change to a no-sanctuary,
antiterrorism policy that involves as many risks as potential
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But it was also prescient and wise scandal politics.
</P>
<P>
   From the first intelligence information about the origin of the
embassy bombs on Aug. 7 through the first discussions of a military
response to the actual plans, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
and Clinton's national security adviser, Sandy Berger, kept the
tight circle _ including Democrats Tom Daschle and Dick Gephardt _
up to date right up through the night before the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Because they could see the plans evolving and the policy
changing, they were in position to not only support Clinton when
the attacks began, but to vouch for the legitimacy of his decisions
in the face of a few ugly, ad hominem but, under the circumstances,
inevitable questions from journalistic and political harpies.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Gingrich even saw to it that one of his political
associates, Rich Galen, sent a blast-fax to conservative talk radio
hosts urging them to lay off the president on the missile strikes,
and making sure they knew of Gingrich's strong support.
</P>
<P>
   That's the same Rich Galen, by the way, who is openly urging
Republican congressional candidates to try to take political
advantage of the president's sex scandal in their television
advertising this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Those Republican politicians who had the sense to check with
their leaders before reacting on Thursday were able to avoid
embarrassment _ Jesse Helms, for example, and especially Orrin
Hatch, whose endorsement bordered on the gushy and was all the more
interesting given his intense anger at the president's remarks
after his grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Those who didn't check and reacted in negative haste made fools
of themselves as they spent most of the following 12 hours walking
back from their initial statements _ notably the normally stable
Senator Dan Coats of Indiana and publicity hound Arlen Specter.
</P>
<P>
   None of this means that any of the fundamentals of scandal
politics have changed. It is a truism that there isn't a president
deservedly in a very tight spot who has ever derived anything more
than brief advantage from some policy move or emergency that serves
to remind people that he is still president. The fundamental things
always apply as time goes by.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, however, the missile strikes came smack in the
middle of the national sorting out that commenced with Clinton's de
facto admission that he had lied to the public and to his family
and friends ever since January about his relationship with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The effect has been to defuse at least some of the tension and
intense emotion of the initial reaction among partisans and the
media and to reinforce the less hotheaded and more supportive
feelings of the country at large.
</P>
<P>
   The short-term effect will also be to solidify the astonishing
disconnect between those in public life who like to think of
themselves as opinion leaders and the people who find this notion
of opinion leadership hilarious as well as pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important _ for those screaming prematurely for
resignation or impeachment _ the effect should be to remind one and
all that the removal of an elected president not only requires
clear and convincing proof of a serious crime but also a clear and
convincing mandate from the public before any formal proceedings
can have legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, another effect of the deft execution of an important
security policy change will provide some additional cover for the
delicate repair work Clinton and his family are engaged in on
Martha's Vineyard. Whatever happens next will begin with his
family's emergence from seclusion with its own judgment about how
to carry on.
</P>
<P>
   We can wait, believe it or not, and the military response to a
murderer named bin Laden has made it easier.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
