<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S MESSAGE TO STARR IS ALSO THE PEOPLE'S: ENOUGH! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When President Clinton gave his brief address to the nation
Monday night, he knew exactly whom he was speaking to _ and they
listened with approval.
</P>
<P>
   He certainly wasn't speaking to Republicans, who bristled when
he defiantly criticized Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr. And he
wasn't speaking to GOP or Democratic insiders _ those who would
later say he didn't offer sufficient apology for his inappropriate
relatioship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   And he certainly wasn't speaking to the newspaper publishers and
editorialists, who have criticized his presidency and now call on
him to resign because of his sexual relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   No, he was speaking to the millions of voters who twice elected
him, flaws and all, and who, throughout Starr's investigation,
continue to give him high approval ratings for his job performance.
</P>
<P>
   The president's speech resonated with these voters. They agreed
with his criticism of Starr and disagreed with the road Starr's
investigation had taken _ from Whitewater ``to my staff and
friends, then into my private life.'' They also agree with
Clinton's view that the investigation by the independent counsel
(he did not use Starr's name) ``has gone on too long, cost too
much, and hurt too many people.'' The polls, which represent the
bulk of the electorate, made it clear that they want this
investigation to end, not in the next few months but today.
</P>
<P>
   And, as the polls reflect, he connected with women voters when
he said that ``this matter is between me, the two people I love the
most _ my wife and my daughter _ and our God'' and that ``it's
nobody's business but ours.''
</P>
<P>
   In a dig at Starr, Clinton told his audience, ``It is time to
stop the pursuit of personal destruction and the prying into
private lives and get on with our national life.''
</P>
<P>
   As the polls reflect, most of the electorate share this view,
which explains why Clinton's job approval at week's end remained in
the 60 percent range, while Starr's remained below 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This does not mean that the majority approves of Clinton's
relationship with a White House intern. Rather, the electorate
feels that this is a private matter between Clinton and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's ratings continue to be abysmally low because the
majority of voters see him as a right-wing Republican partisan out
to destroy the president, even if it means prying into his private
life.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is a key reason why Clinton continues to have
high approval ratings even after he admitted that he lied when he
denied having a relationship with Lewisnky.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for Clinton's continued good standing with voters is
the way Hillary Rodham Clinton has, for whatever reason, stood by
her husband through the thick and thin of this sordid Starr
inquisition. Traditional housewives who once scorned her now
support her for supporting her husband during his ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   With the president's approval rating so high, and Starr's so
law, some lawyers and prosecutors familiar with grand jury
proceedings felt that Clinton never should have gone before that
jury at all. By doing so, they argued, he would likely fall into
the perjury trap that Starr has set for him. Starr, they further
argue, could use Clinton's own testimony to show that he originally
lied about having an affair with Lewisnky, suggesting he perjured
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Some Clinton critics argue that if Clinton were president or
chairman of a private corporation and was found to have had an
affair with a young intern, he would probably be forced by his
board of directors to resign. But in Clinton's case, the
circumstances are different. He is an elected, not an appointed,
president.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Congress is not an appointed board of directors,
but an assemblage of officials elected by a clear majority of
voters. Those voters say they do not want Clinton impeached, nor do
they want him to resign.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Congress is acutely aware of how hard it would be to
try to impeach a president with an approval rating as high as
Clinton's. Even with the a GOP-majority Congress, such a move would
likely fail. It is more likely that Congress could reprimand or
censure Clinton _ but even then members of Congress would have to
be careful not to infuriate the Clinton-backing public.
</P>
<P>
   To his backers, Clinton is the president who deserves some
credit for a strong economy, as well as his domestic and
international accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Some predicted that when details of Lewinsky's sexual affair
with Clinton was leaked to the media, the effect would be so
damaging that even the president's backers would demand that he
resign. However, it now seems that releasing such information could
backfire on Starr, given the public's clear wish not to know the
details of a private sexual affair.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton told the nation Monday of the independent counsel's
excesses, his words were also meant as a message to Starr and the
GOP. It is the same message the nation's populace has been sending
to Starr and his GOP supporters for the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope that, before this sleazy investigation goes any
further, they finally get it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
