<SLUG> BC-EMAIL-BATTLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT, LOTUS STEP UP BATTLE FOR CORPORATE E-MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fight between Microsoft Corp. and Lotus Development Corp. to
dominate the market for corporate electronic mail is starting to
get ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Lotus last week attacked Microsoft for making ``reckless and
inaccurate'' claims about its momentum in the fast-growing market
for messaging software.
</P>
<P>
   In a memo posted on its World Wide Web site, Lotus accused
Microsoft of playing ``PR games'' in pronouncing its Exchange
software as the ``leading messaging platform.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, the Redmond, Wash.-based software giant
touted new market research that shows Exchange outsold Lotus' rival
product, Notes, for the second quarter in a row.
</P>
<P>
   According to an industry newsletter, Electronic Mail &AMP; Messaging
Systems, Microsoft sold 3.55 million licenses for Exchange in the
second quarter, while Lotus sold 3.1 million Notes licenses. In the
first quarter, Microsoft sold 3.05 million copies of Exchange,
compared with 2.7 million copies of Notes sold by Lotus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's way too early in the game to declare victory, but what
this is telling us is that the playing field has shifted
dramatically, and we're the ones with the momentum,'' said Stan
Sorensen, lead product manager for Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   But Lotus points out that the figures reported by the newsletter
are actually estimates provided by the vendors themselves, and
because Microsoft counts users differently, the data is skewered in
Microsoft's favor.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Mark Leavitt, an analyst who tracks the messaging
industry for International Data Corp. of Framingham, Mass., said
the sales numbers both companies provide to the newsletter are
inflated by software licenses that are shipped to customers in a
bundle with other products but aren't necessarily used.
</P>
<P>
   IDC is still compiling market share data for the first half of
1998, but Leavitt said it's clear that after discounting for those
copies of Exchange and Notes that are sold in a bundle but aren't
actually used, the gap between the two rivals will be much smaller,
perhaps about 200,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   The tenacity both companies have displayed in their battle for
market share underscores the potential payoff in the booming market
for groupware _ software that lets distant employees not only send
e-mail but also collaborate on a single project or document.
Analysts predict it will be a $20 billion industry by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Lotus, based in Cambridge, Mass., created the market nine years
ago with its introduction of Notes and has seen its sales zoom
since the company was acquired in 1995 by deep-pocketed
International Business Machines Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Lotus still has a commanding lead, but after just two years on
the market, Microsoft Exchange is gaining fast. It has about 16.6
million users, compared with about 25.1 million Notes users, said
Eric Arnum, editor of Electronic Mail &AMP; Messaging Systems.
</P>
<P>
   But Arnum said that some of Microsoft's recent sales momentum
may be due to the fact that Exchange is at the peak of its product
cycle, while the current version of Lotus Notes is about to be
replaced. He said Lotus will probably pick up momentum later in the
year after the next generation of Notes software debuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are talking about two top teams here,'' he said.
``Inevitably, each quarter, one is going to come out ahead. I think
these two companies are going to pace each other not only this
year, but next year as well.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``It's a two-horse race,'' agreed Lotus spokesman Paul
Labelle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
