<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9127 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      08-24 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENSON PUSHING HIS WAY TO THE FRONT OF THE PACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ It may be too soon to tell just how good Damon
Denson, the Patriots' left offensive guard from Michigan, is, but
in almost three quarters Saturday night against the Redskins,
Denson may have made a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Damon played very well, really holding his own and then some
out there,'' said coach Pete Carroll after New England's 20-17
exhibition victory at Jack Kent Cooke Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Denson, a fourth-round 1997 draft pick and one of the
compensation picks the Patriots received from the Jets in the Bill
Parcells matter, has made some progress but has been bothered by
nagging injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, the Patriots put him into the fire against two
of the best interior linemen in the NFL _ Dana Stubblefield and Dan
Wilkinson _ and Denson not only protected quarterback Drew Bledsoe
well, but he moved Stubblefield and Wilkinson off the line well,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty tough, but I think I held my own,'' said Denson.
</P>
<P>
   Denson, who is 6 feet 3 inches and weighs 300 pounds, has huge
legs. The Patriots worked with him in the offseason on improving
his mobility and quickness, and that work seems to have paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Denson entered the game with about eight minutes remaining in
the second quarter in place of Max Lane and played next to Bruce
Armstrong for a while. But Armstrong then was replaced at left
tackle by Lane, who wound up playing a lot there, a sign the
Patriots are making contingency plans in case Armstrong's leg,
which has a stress fracture, sidelines him.
</P>
<P>
   If last night was a preview of life without Armstrong, the
Patriots came out of it all right, because Denson performed well
and Lane also did a credible job. Denson made some nice blocks near
the goal line, although he was called for holding once.
</P>
<P>
   There were some other interesting developments in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran free agent Brian Stablein hasn't been involved much in
the offense throughout the exhibition season. Saturday night he got
very little action as a wide receiver. While it appears Stablein
will make the team based on the $500,000 signing bonus he received
on a three-year, $3 million deal, the Patriots sure are acting like
they may keep Anthony Ladd, a second-year free agent from the
University of Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   It appears the coaching staff will keep six receivers, with
Stablein No. 6, but over the past few weeks, Carroll and others
have been praising Ladd, who had three catches for 23 yards against
the Redskins. Ladd has superb speed and is a deep threat, while
Stablein is considered more of a possession receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Stablein was signed over Indianapolis teammate Sean Dawkins as
insurance in case the team found a taker for Vincent Brisby. That
didn't happen, and the Patriots began camp with both.
</P>
<P>
   Old reliable Troy Brown continues to make big plays, his 37-yard
catch over the middle during the Patriots' 99-yard scoring drive in
the third quarter a perfect example, so he's not about to
relinquish his role.
</P>
<P>
   It may be Stablein hasn't seen much action because the team
already knows what he can do.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' running backs got the tough yardage they weren't
gaining in the regular season a year ago. Sedrick and Harold Shaw
did nice jobs. But what was lacking is the big gain that Curtis
Martin was so good at. Sedrick Shaw ran hard all night but still
hasn't been able to break into the open field.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll plans on giving the ball to Robert Edwards Saturday
night against Philadelphia, providing the No. 1 pick's groin is
better. Even if Edwards has a big game, the Patriots will start the
season with a running back-by-committee situation until someone
establishes himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to sit and dwell on the situation,'' said
Sedrick Shaw. ``I'm just trying to get better every time out. I
play football, and I think I'll be playing football somewhere. This
career doesn't last very long so you go out and give it everything
every week. That's been my approach.''
</P>
<P>
   There was one breakdown in the defensive secondary, when Kato
Serwanga and Lawyer Milloy seemed confused on coverage of Leslie
Shepherd in the third quarter. The play went for a 48-yard
touchdown, Washington's first score of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said it was a mistake the team could learn from, but it
also pointed out a possible problem with depth. Serwanga was the
nickel back on the play, a spot that usually would go to a veteran
like Steve Israel (knee) or Steve Lofton (shoulder).
</P>
<P>
   As Carroll will utilize Edwards Saturday night, it also should
be the Tebucky Jones Show at right cornerback. Jones has missed the
last two games with a sore toe, and although the rookie from
Syracuse wanted to play Saturday night, he hadn't practiced during
the week and Carroll held him back.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there has never been a cheaper shot than the punch to
the groin Redskins tight end Stephen Alexander laid on Patriots
rookie defensive end Greg Spires in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander and Spires had been battling hard, and Spires had been
getting the best of it.
</P>
<P>
   Spires had a sack at the end of the game, got close to the
quarterback several other times, and forced several bad throws.
</P>
<P>
   He was used as a third-down pass rusher with the first team, and
that will continue to be his role.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
