   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ANALYSIS (Paris) _ Victor Chernomyrdin returns as
Russia's prime minister in a more powerful personal position than
he was before President Boris Yeltsin fired him five months ago. In
the midst of a financial crisis, Yeltsin ``humiliated himself'' by
recalling the man he fired in a Cabinet shuffle, one analyst says.
By BERNARD D. KAPLAN. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ As cries mount for President
Clinton's censure or resignation, Vice President Al Gore remains
fiercely loyal to his mentor, counting on his own clean personal
life to distance himself from the Monica Lewinsky affair. Actually,
Gore has little choice but to stand by Clinton; any change in their
partnership now would be seen as a betrayal not likely to sit well
with voters. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
