<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-DION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DION IS A DREAM IN WORLD-TOUR LAUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Call it the coronation of Celine _ and who would argue
after Friday's spectacular performance at the FleetCenter? Celine
Dion, better known as just Celine to the millions of fans who
scooped up the ``Titanic'' soundtrack, opened her world tour with a
high-tech, in-the-round show (on a heart-shaped stage, no less)
that sent a sold-out crowd of 18,300 fans into complete rapture.
</P>
<P>
   It was glitzy but glitch-free. She had told the crowd there
might be ``mistakes,'' but none were visible. And Dion stayed
genuine even amid a lighting grid the size of a spaceship and a
series of video duets with Barbra Streisand and the Bee Gees that
threatened to get hokey. OK, maybe they did, but were still saved
by her utter sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   ``New shoes, new clothes, new hair!'' exclaimed Dion, whose
long, tangly hair weave nearly went to her waist, though she pulled
it back Kate Winslet-like for a thrilling encore of ``Titanic'' hit
``My Heart Will Go On,'' for which she also wore an Edwardian ball
gown and sang from a white railing as though she were on the
Titanic's bow. No sentimentality was spared, but it was an
effective moment of pop theater and the crowd loved it. She kept
the crowd waiting until the end to hear it, but it sent everyone
home in a state of smiling grace.
</P>
<P>
   This was an upbeat, entertaining show that focused on Dion's
last album, ``Let's Talk About Love,'' and was enhanced by some
personal (and unrecorded) favorites that allowed her personality to
rise above the show-biz effects.
</P>
<P>
   These favorites came via an acoustic medley in which she
gathered her musicians around her at the center of the stage, as
she sat on a hydraulically lifted swivel chair. She mesmerized with
delicate rendering of Roberta Flack's ``The First Time Ever I Saw
Your Face,'' soothed with the Beatles' ``Because,'' touched hearts
with Eric Clapton's ``Tears in Heaven,'' and woke up the romantics
in the house with Frank Sinatra's ``All the Way,'' describing it as
the favorite ``couple'' song between her and her husband/manager
Rene Angelil, who watched nervously from the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of nerves, Dion said, ``I'm so nervous tonight because
this is the first show.'' She had reason to worry, as camera crews
from all over the US and Canada filmed her every move on the first
couple of songs, before being ushered away. Those first two songs
were the album title track ``Let's Talk About Love'' (augmented by
a talented chorus from the W.H. Lincoln School in Brookline) and
``Declaration of Love.'' Yes, the word love was in both titles,
hinting at the direction to come.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese violinist Taro Hasake came out for a bravura ``To Love
You More'' (there's that word again), followed shortly by Dion
singing ``Tell Him'' with a video image of Streisand. Then came two
French songs (led by ``S'il Suffisait Qu'on S'Aime,'' translated
``If It Were Enough that We Love Each Other,'' she said), before
she improvised beautifully on Eric Carmen's ``All by Myself.'' She
joked that she was hardly by herself, because 50 people were
working under the in-the-round stage.
</P>
<P>
   The overwrought portion of the show came on a Bee Gees medley of
``Staying Alive/You Should Be Dancing,'' with Dion, in only her
first costume change (Diana Ross would have had eight by then),
prancing in a creamy white suit like John Travolta. It was fun, but
it would have been nice to hear some of Dion's earlier hits (where
was ``The Power of Love'' and ``If You Asked Me To''?) instead of
these cover tunes.
</P>
<P>
   For pure entertainment, however, this was a volcanic triumph.
Dion thanked Boston fans for ``being lucky charm people''; this was
the third time she's opened a world tour here. This was the
biggest, for Queen Celine now reigns.
</P>
</TEXT>
