A9151 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-24 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTEAD OF PITCHING, THINK COMPOSTING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mail brought questions about compost this week. How is it
beneficial, and how can we make this special material in our home
gardens?
</P>
<P>
   Compost is an excellent form of organic matter to add to the
soil in your garden. You can buy bags of compost from your garden
center, or build a simple compost bin or pile in your back yard.
</P>
<P>
   Compost is a mixture of organic matter such as grass clippings,
leaves, pine needles, bark and kitchen scraps (including eggshells,
coffee grounds and vegetables, but excluding meats). All these are
readily available around many households. When the circus comes to
town, my husband likes to bring home elephant poop in large,
extra-heavy plastic bags. He then works the manure into his compost
system. It's good stuff.
</P>
<P>
   We try to use a good mix of greens and browns in making compost.
Greens _ fresh plant parts and kitchen scraps _ are sources of
nitrogen and protein. Browns _ straw and fallen leaves _ are carbon
sources. Manure is a great source of protein. The end result when
these several ingredients break down is a crumbly, dark material
that is loaded with macro- and micronutrients. We spread this
around beds like a mulch. We work it into soil in new beds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
IDEAL SOIL AMENDMENT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Compost is the ideal soil amendment _ it not only increases
nutrients, it also improves the soil texture. It loosens tight,
heavy clays, allowing greater movement of water, air and roots. It
tightens loose, sandy soils so that roots will have a better chance
to absorb water and nutrients. Compost encourages beneficial soil
organisms that in turn wage war on disease organisms.
</P>
<P>
   Our compost system is in a rear corner of our garden, accessible
but camouflaged by large shrubs such as eleagnus and azaleas and
near a water spigot. It is a system of three bins _ one to collect
organic ingredients, another for cooking compost, the third
containing finished compost. Our rectangular bins are low, about
thigh-high, and made of landscape timbers. Side timbers are laid on
top of end timbers to allow maximum air circulation. The timbers
were our only costs. All the materials used in making the compost
are free _ even the elephant poop.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of pushing food scraps down a disposal, we put coffee
grounds, eggshells and vegetable leftovers in a plastic bucket with
a lid, then transfer this goop to the pile every day or two.
Leaves, grass clippings and other plant parts are mixed in. By
recycling garden wastes, we avoid sending useful materials to the
landfill and we use a lot fewer plastic bags.
</P>
<P>
   Once your bin is built (you can buy compost bins or tumblers),
pile alternate layers of organic matter and soil in the receptacle.
Start with about six inches of organic matter, then add an inch of
soil. The soil is beneficial because it contains microorganisms
that help break down the organic matter. Continue this layering,
watering each layer until the pile is about four feet high. Create
a bowl in the center of the pile and add water.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
COOK AND TURN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As decomposition takes place, the center will heat up and kill
any traces of disease. Turn the compost pile with a fork or shovel,
shifting undecayed matter to the center so that it can cook. The
compost is finished when the pile no longer generates heat.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the compost at least once a week and you may have a
finished product in a month. If you turn it only once a month,
you'll have to wait about three months. If you find the pile is
cooking too slowly, add nitrogen in the form of grass clippings,
kitchen scraps, manure, blood meal, cottonseed meal and/or alfalfa
meal.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need an elaborate system to compost. You can use a
plastic garbage can with holes drilled in the bottom and sides for
aeration. Elevate the can on bricks or some stable base to ensure
good aeration. Garbage-can composting is handy if you have small
amounts of material to compost. Just layer organic matter and soil,
and add a little water. Stir from time to time and you'll
eventually have compost.
</P>
<P>
   One reader asked about composting in a large plastic bag. This
easy method is anaerobic _ oxygen-deprived _ and you'll notice an
odor if you open the bag before the ingredients are decomposed.
Collect kitchen and garden scraps in a bag, add a couple of quarts
of water, shake to moisten the ingredients, seal and you'll have
compost in a few months. Roll the bag around from time to time to
encourage quicker decomposition.
</P>
<P>
   You can make great leaf mold, nature's compost, by simply
bagging leaves, adding a little water and waiting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston 77210. The bulk of mail prevents
individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
