<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORRESPONDENCE AT BOILING POINT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ During my years as a baseball writer, August was often
referred to as the ``dog days'' of a long, arduous season.
</P>
<P>
   Seems sports and travel have much in common. Except in this
instance, some folks are urging my banishment to the doghouse.
</P>
<P>
   The volume of heated correspondence always increases this time
of year. It's understandable: We've sweated through too many
100-degree afternoons; we're weary from getting the kids off to
school; and our much-anticipated vacation is history, with the only
reminders a photograph album and a hefty stack of credit-card
bills.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BRISTLING ABOUT B&AMP;BS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several readers, including a few Texas bed-and-breakfast
operators, are especially hot under the collar _ not from the
weather but from my recent suggestion that a first-rate B&AMP;B owes
its guests a full, freshly prepared breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   One traveler labeled me an elitist who doesn't appreciate small,
hospitable lodgings that offer tiny cereal boxes and a carton of
milk, available to suit the guest's schedule _ not the agenda of
the host and cook.
</P>
<P>
   Another correspondent, Cynthia Smith, owner of Smith's Tin House
B&AMP;B in Johnson City, was kinder but equally pointed in her
constructive criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Smith wrote: ``All bed-and-breakfasts are not `owner-on-premise'
and traditional. I was very disappointed in your view of Hill
Country bed-and-breakfasts that were not in a position to serve a
hot breakfast. How in Sam Hill do you figure that we, in a private
guest house, aka bed-and-breakfast establishment, could host a
steaming hot gourmet breakfast when most of us don't even have a
working stove in the kitchen?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we do leave a handwritten note. And yes, breakfast does
get nuked or zapped in the microwave. But I assure that what is
getting nuked is homemade and wonderful. We even inquire if our
guests have special dietary wishes. (We provide) fresh fruit,
sometimes wine and snacks. Our home-cooked goods, albeit
`yesterday's,' is something we pride ourselves on in our group of
owners in Johnson City.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, let me say that I also heard from more than a handful of
readers _ and B&AMP;B owners _ who applauded my position. One
Fredericksburg innkeeper corresponded, too, to say that she _ like
several peers _ now offers guests the option of a hot breakfast
served formally at an established time or a pre-prepared meal
available in the room at any hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-five percent choose the hot meal,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I respect that every traveler has individual likes and
dislikes. I'll concede, too, that one innkeeper's ``pre-prepared''
breakfast _ not the day-old goodies I microwaved, though _ may
prove tastier than another's hot-off-the-stove concoction. Given
her obvious passion, I'll wager that Cynthia Smith's Tin House B&AMP;B
serves up a scrumptious feast. And I've visited some idyllic one-
and two-room hideaways in the Hill Country where raiding the
refrigerator for sweet rolls, fruit and juice serves as the perfect
morning pick-me-up.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Donna Mittel, proprietor of Gstehaus Schmidt
reservations service in Fredericksburg, suggests that one of that
area's prime assets involves the wide range of lodging choices
offered visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone calls for a reservation and has never stayed with
us before, we ask, `Are you wanting to stay in a traditional
bed-and-breakfast or a guest house?''' Mittel wrote. ``If they do
not know the difference, we educate them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of our guests actually prefer a guest house, because a
guest house offers complete privacy, rest and relaxation,'' Mittel
continued. ``If they want to get out of bed at 10 o'clock, drink
coffee in their pajamas and enjoy breakfast on the front porch,
they are able to do this without another thought or call from their
hosts. In our business, there is an option for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Well said. And I know Gstehaus Schmidt as a dedicated
professional service that helps each individual match his or her
tastes to just the right property. My concern isn't with the
guest-house concept to which Mittel refers. I just question if all
travelers _ and dare I say some innkeepers? _ easily connote
fine-line differences in industry-applied terminology such as
``traditional B&AMP;B,'' ``guest house,'' ``country inn'' and
``historical home.'' I'm still shaking my head over a call from a
well-intentioned woman whose son had just departed for college and
who asked, ``What do I need to do to turn his room into a B&AMP;B?''
</P>
<P>
   Guests have a right to know what they are getting in return for
their hard-earned money. And if they want, and expect, to feast on
a box of cereal and carton of milk in their jammies, that's fine
with me. Been there. Done that.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, well, I'll soon be out of the pen. Dog days are almost over.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1411EDT &QL; 
