<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DIANA-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YEAR LATER, DIANA'S STORY STILL SURPRISES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  ``The Day Diana Died''; By Christopher Andersen; (Morrow, $27) 
 
By CLIFFORD PUGH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A dearth of new information hasn't stopped a flood of new books
coinciding with the first anniversary of the car accident that
killed the Princess of Wales.
</P>
<P>
   The one that is likely to get the most attention is this
meticulous account by Christopher Andersen, a former senior editor
for People magazine and the author of such celebrity tomes as
``Jackie After Jack'' and ``Madonna Unauthorized.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Day Diana Died,'' which reads like a long People article,
covers familiar ground in tracing the princess' final days leading
up to the Aug. 31, 1997, automobile crash in a Paris tunnel that
also killed her companion, Dodi Fayed, and driver, Henri Paul.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen concludes that the crash was caused by Paul, who was
drunk, and that Diana most likely would have survived if she'd been
wearing her seat belt.
</P>
<P>
   But he adds to such familiar information a number of gossipy
revelations in which Diana lovers will revel.
</P>
<P>
   If his disclosures are to be believed, Queen Elizabeth II was a
coldhearted monarch who remained clueless about how deeply moved
her subjects were by the death of her former daughter-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Upon receiving word of Diana's death, the queen demanded that
any royal jewels in the princess' possession be returned
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   She also insisted that her grandsons, William and Harry, attend
a church service just four hours after learning of their mother's
death. When, at the queen's orders, no mention of Diana's death was
made at the service, Harry turned to Prince Charles and whispered,
``Are you sure Mummy is dead?''
</P>
<P>
   The queen relented and addressed the nation several days later
after Charles had issued an ultimatum: If she didn't, he would
publicly apologize for her callous behavior.
</P>
<P>
   While the queen comes across as a villain, Charles is portrayed
as a hero. According to Andersen, Charles seemed truly stunned by
Diana's death and wept openly when he heard the news. He
immediately sent her favorite flowers _ white lilies _ to the
hospital room and called to request that her gold earrings be put
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diana always likes to wear her earrings in public,'' he said,
still speaking of his ex-wife in the present tense.
</P>
<P>
   Against his mother's wishes, he flew to Paris with Diana's
sisters to accompany her body to England, and he spent much of the
following week circumventing the queen in order to present a public
funeral that would pay proper tribute to his ex-wife.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to Diana's death, no item is too trivial or
ghoulish to report. Andersen reveals that her coffin featured a
window above her face and that her body was returned to England in
a dress borrowed from the wife of the British ambassador to France
because Mohammed Fayed, the father of her lover, had already had
her belongings in Paris packed and shipped out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   A large chunk of Andersen's breezy 270-page book is a rehash of
Diana's life before that fateful day. Those looking for new
information can browse the 21-page first chapter for details that
are then amplified toward the end of the book.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Clifford Pugh, a Houston Chronicle reporter, met Princess Diana
while covering her visit to Washington, D.C., in 1985. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1412EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980824.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9164 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-CHILDREN-REVIEW-     08-24 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CHILDREN-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STINKY CHEESE' MEN TRY THEIR HAND AT CLEVER, WISE FABLES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JANE P. MARSHALL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A grasshopper conveniently forgets hoework. A gullible frog
buys skateboard shoes advertised on television. A duckbilled
platypus and a BeefSmakStik argue about attributes.
</P>
<P>
   You know these characters. Maybe they sit next to you at work.
Or live in your house. Or squat in the branches of your family
tree.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Scieszka and Lane Smith, the dynamic duo that produced
``Math Curse'' and ``The Stinky Cheese Man and Other Fairly Stupid
Tales,'' have moved on to fables with ``Squids Will Be Squids,
Fresh Morals, Beastly Fables'' (Viking, $17.99).
</P>
<P>
   Fables, they say, are merely rude gossip and bad jokes about
``bossy, sneaky, funny, annoying, dim-bulb people.'' Except change
the people to animals and add a moral to make the jokes and gossip
socially redeeming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stinky Cheese Man'' is a kids book. Kids love it. They get it.
Parents don't. ``I'm so tired of reading that book over and over
and over,'' more that one parent has said.
</P>
<P>
   The ultraclever and sneaky ``Math Curse'' makes any other book
or game that declares ``math is fun and important'' seem drier than
a Texas pasture in August.
</P>
<P>
   The big question: Could the dynamic duo outdo themselves again?
</P>
<P>
   The answer: Yes. YEs. YES.
</P>
<P>
   The new book presents 18 fables for ages 49-630 (in dog years).
These are read-aloud stories, mostly because they are so funny you
can't keep them to yourself. And you can't read just one.
</P>
<P>
   Scieszka writes for children, but there is a fable for President
Clinton (``Little Walrus''), another for a brother, although of
course it has nothing to do with him. This is more Dilbert than
Dilbert. More Thurber than Thurber. Monty Python with a heart for
children. Real chicken soup for what's ailing, whether a timid soul
or a grouchy grimace.
</P>
<P>
   This guy knows kids. In fact, he's probably a kid himself. Could
an adult brain really come up with Spanking Head? Or a talking
larva? Or an argument between Toast and Froot Loops? Or a moral
like, ``Everyone knows frogs can't skateboard, but it's kind of sad
that they believe everything they see on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Scieszka's words are masterful in their cleverness and wisdom,
rich and thick like swimming in fudge.
</P>
<P>
   Is Scieszka really this funny and clever and awesomely
entertaining?
</P>
<P>
   We asked his 14-year-daughter, Casey. Fourteen-year-old
daughters know the truth about parents. And they tell.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, said Casey from her home in Brooklyn, N.Y. Her father is
indeed funny.
</P>
<P>
   No, he doesn't embarrass her in front of friends. Pause. ``Maybe
it's that I don't find what he does embarrassing,'' she said. ``My
friends don't mind being around him.''
</P>
<P>
   She likes her dad's new book. ``Straw and Matches'' is her
favorite fable.
</P>
<P>
   Lane Smith draws Casey's favorite and the other sparse tales _
the squid and the self-centered slug, the termite and the
misunderstood wasp _ with the gusts of eccentricity equal to
Scieszka's. This is craziness with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   Molly Leach gets a small-type credit as the book's designer. She
is likely the one who makes it soup. She's also married to Lane
Smith. She must be patient as well as talented.
</P>
<P>
   These fables are all about truth, selfishness, thoughtfulness,
vanity and more. Kids will get them. Some adults will too. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Squids'' is a lesson in social behavior, ``Home Run'' is a
lesson on an American icon. Aug. 16 was the 50th anniversary of
Babe Ruth's death. ``Home Run: The Story of Babe Ruth'' (Harcourt
Brace, $16) celebrates the man and the game of baseball with
simplicity and dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Burleigh's words are poetic _ ``He is the Babe. He has
always loved this game. This baseball. But what he does not know
yet is this: He will change the game he loves. Forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful. Burleigh lovingly smashes one into the stands with
this book.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wimmer's illustrations _ joyful, Norman Rockwell-like and
full of compassion and power _ are oil on canvas.
</P>
<P>
   Details and facts of George Herman Ruth's life and career don't
clutter the narrative. They are told, one on each page, via
vintage-style baseball cards. One explains how Ruth got the
nickname, another how he was famous for leaving $100 tips when he
was on road trips.
</P>
<P>
   Recommended age is 6-10. Or anybody who loves baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten Queens, Portraits of Women of Power'' (Dutton, $24.99) is
a beautifully produced 134-page book that shows how powerful women
pushed civility on civilization from the 5th century B.C. to the
18th century.
</P>
<P>
   Portraits are a mixture of women known mostly through folk
legends, and some who are unfamiliar. Author Milton Meltzer
explained how he chose the women: ``These are not women who were
called queens because they happened to marry a king and had little
or nothing to say about ruling the country. ... Most ruled in their
own right. ... Or if they sat on thrones beside kings, they had as
much or more to say about governing than their husbands.''
</P>
<P>
   He also explained the difficulty of writing stories about people
who lived thousands of years ago. He had to rely on archaeological
evidence and sources like shrines and coins as he shifted through
legends.
</P>
<P>
   The stories are told clearly and are filled with interesting
details, a history textbook better told. None of the 10 women lived
in peaceful, untroubled times.
</P>
<P>
   The paintings, by Bethanne Andersen. are beautiful and give an
aura of storybook instead of history book.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 queens are: Esther, Cleopatra, Boudicca, Zenobia, Eleanor
of Aquitaine, Isabel of Spain, Elizabeth I, Christina of Sweden,
Maria Theresa and Catherine the Great.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten Queens'' is an inspired idea that should help equalize the
telling of history, which is usually done from the male point of
view.
</P>
<P>
   While these are three distinctly different books, each is a
stepladder for a child to be a bit stronger and a bit braver. And,
in the case of ``Squids,'' giggling all the way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
