<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: The problem with superpowers
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's such a bother being a great power and leader of the free
world sometimes you wonder if it's worth it. Terrorists bomb two of
our embassies, killing hundreds. We retaliate. The administration
swears we nailed a chemical weapons plant in Sudan and a terrorist
camp in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner does the last piece of shrapnel fall and most
Americans are feeling better about being a great power than a few
politicians say it's ``Wag the Dog'' all over again. The whole
thing, they say, has the odor of a counter-Lewinsky love triangle.
Then they say maybe it doesn't, but Bill Clinton made us think it
did.
</P>
<P>
   They demonstrate something fierce in the streets of Kabul. The
Sudanese say we hit the only darned pharmaceutical plant in the
whole country. For both notoriously oppressive governments, getting
bombed is the most popular thing they've ever done. Television
crews, not knowing what to believe, stumble through the rubble and
take pictures of whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, we're keeping mum, presumably protecting secrets.
This is the problem of being a superpower. It makes you act and
sound like one, sending in cruise missiles, making enigmatic
statements that sound funny both here and abroad. Terrorism is at
least by half a propaganda war. We should know that by now and
should have a few skills.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
