<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICE OF PUBLIC OFFICE IS LOSS OF SOME PRIVACY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Let's face it, folks. We have a boring governor.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about his college days, but most of the headlines
that George W. Bush has been producing out of Austin have been real
snoozers, compared to what we have been reading from Washington
about another prominent leader.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to mid-life hanky-panky, Gov. Bush is no President
Clinton, and Texans of all political persuasions can be thankful
for that.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton was simmering in the Monica Lewinsky scandal last
week, Bush was promoting the character issue back in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   He repeated some of his favorite themes _ abstinence before
marriage for young people and personal responsibility for all. And
he said the president's ``not appropriate'' relationship with a
White House intern and Clinton's lies about it had helped solidify
character as a political issue.
</P>
<P>
   The governor is right. Character is a legitimate political
concern. Although public officials, even presidents, are entitled
to some privacy, their constituents also are entitled to expect
those lives to be guided by a moral compass that doesn't seem to be
in need of constant repair.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said it was ``up to the American people to determine''
where to draw the line between a candidate's public and private
life.
</P>
<P>
   Again, his statement is correct. Although the media are
frequently accused of excess in reporting on the personal lives of
public figures _ and sometimes the complaints are legitimate _ it
ultimately is up to readers and viewers _ the public _ to determine
what is important or relevant and what is not.
</P>
<P>
   Many elected officials and people seeking elected office are
quick to accuse the media of being intrusive, but they would have
us forget that they are also attempting to intrude on our lives
when they offer themselves for public office.
</P>
<P>
   Giving up a lot of their privacy is a price they must pay for
public service because the quality of that service can be affected
to a large extent by their personal views and experiences, family
backgrounds and business connections.
</P>
<P>
   As the son of a former president, Bush should know this better
than most people. But he sometimes displays a touchiness that makes
one wonder how much confidence he really has in the voters' ability
to decide what information is important about a public figure.
</P>
<P>
   The governor was noticeably unhappy as Houston Chronicle
reporter R.G. Ratcliffe was completing a story, published last
week, about profitable dealings that some of Bush's former business
associates have had with state government.
</P>
<P>
   There was no evidence, as the article pointed out, that Bush had
intervened on his friends' behalf or that he even knew they were
doing business with the state. But Bush apparently feared that the
article would suggest unseemly insider dealings or paint him
guilty, by association, of using government to help his friends.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Bush's detractors will pounce on any opportunity to
criticize him, and the story's headline may find its way into a
campaign ad for Garry Mauro, the governor's Democratic re-election
challenger. But that kind of reaction to publicity comes with the
territory for an elected official.
</P>
<P>
   Many readers probably didn't consider the business dealings
unethical, and there wasn't any evidence of illegal activity. But
the deals certainly were interesting, and that's why they were
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The state's teacher retirement system, for example, sold three
office buildings to a real estate company owned by a wealthy,
former business partner and major financial contributor to the
governor, losing $44 million on one of the sales.
</P>
<P>
   And the state's education trust funds have invested almost $20
million in the same real estate company since Bush became governor.
</P>
<P>
   Does the public have an interest in knowing how the governor's
friends are faring in their business dealings with state
government? You bet they do.
</P>
<P>
   An even truer test of Bush's willingness to let the public be
the judge will come if he, as expected, wins re-election and wages
his own campaign for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Every aspect of his life _ including the ``young and
irresponsible'' days that he admits to in his younger years _ will
be examined and re-examined by thousands of reporters, whose
standard for what constitutes news may not match his own.
</P>
<P>
   Buckle up, governor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
