<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOURMONEY8/24-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD INVESTMENTS START AT THE TOP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you're picking stocks it's easy to get the numbers on the
company's revenues and profits.
</P>
<P>
   What's hard is evaluating whether the executives running the
company are any good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of management is a very important fundamental
factor in the success of any company,'' said Lynn Bernard Jr.,
executive vice president of global investment strategies at
Pinnacle Management &AMP; Trust Co. in Houston, a money management
firm. ``Sometimes, that can be a deciding factor to invest in that
particular company vs. its competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, you want leaders who can deliver results and make
money for the company. The key is how it gets there.
</P>
<P>
   If you know employees of a company you're considering investing
in, talk to them about how the company treats its most important
asset _ its workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management is two simple pieces: You have to make money and
you have to keep people motivated,'' said Greg Nakanishi, managing
partner of GN Resources in Kingwood, a management consulting firm.
``If you are just a slave driver and not treating people with
respect, people will leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, sound the warning bells if you see a management that's
giving too many excuses for why it consistently misses earnings
targets. After all, how many times can you blame El Nio for losses?
</P>
<P>
   ``If they keep giving excuses, then as an investor, you really
have to question the investment attractiveness of a company that
does that,'' Bernard said.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a list of signs that point to weak management from
Nakanishi and other observers who regularly evaluate companies as a
potential investment:
</P>
<P>
   The company isn't consistently making money.
</P>
<P>
   That may suggest a team that's not focused on what it takes to
produce steady results. If the management team is new to a company,
study the managers' track records.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much movement today in management, you want to make
sure that the people coming in to key management positions have a
good track record where they have been,'' Bernard said.
</P>
<P>
   The key executives can't solve problems.
</P>
<P>
   Look for managers who have been able to take a product that was
limping along and improve it by adjusting the price or the way it's
made or fix a flaw that has hurt sales, said Claude Cody, a senior
portfolio manager at Aim Management Group in Houston, a mutual fund
firm.
</P>
<P>
   The top executives don't know where they want to take the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have they created a vision for what they're trying to create
for the organization, like, `We want to become the most admired
company in the industry,' '' Nakanishi said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has a blurred sense of the corporate culture it
wants to create.
</P>
<P>
   Do its managers say they want to foster an innovative atmosphere
that encourages creativity or do they want to be purely
results-oriented?
</P>
<P>
   The management is so focused on making money that it kills
employee incentive.
</P>
<P>
   A focus on the numbers isn't bad. However, with poor managers,
``they focus on those almost exclusively to the detriment of
building the kind of organization where people want to contribute
their time, their expertise, their talent,'' Nakanishi said.
</P>
<P>
   The people at the top aren't well-grounded in their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people don't have an understanding of the industry, it
sometimes is difficult to build credibility in the organization,''
Nakanishi said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's leaders have frayed relationships with crucial
players in its industry.
</P>
<P>
   You want a management team that avoids regular public disputes
with bankers, customers, suppliers and regulatory agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The head honchos haven't set financial boundaries, such as how
much debt the company will shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should have well-stated para- &QL; 
meters around their financial structure, so you're financially
prudent,'' Nakanishi said.
</P>
<P>
   The management doesn't listen to different points of view.
</P>
<P>
   This is a key skill at the upper echelons of management. You
want managers who are able to pull together different ideas to
create a sound strategy for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you want to see top managers who work well together,
solving the turf wars that exist in any organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have a cohesive management team at the top or do you
have fragmented management?'' Bernard asked.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To voice comments, telephone 713-220-2000 and dial in code 1003.
Send e-mail to pamela.yip at chron.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
