<P>
   MOROCCO-MINBARS (Marrakesh, Morocco) _ Not long ago the imam at
the Casbah mosque agreed to show me his ancient minbar _ minbars
are decorated wooden staircases on wheels from which the imam
addresses the congregation during Friday worship. The idea was to
compare it to the 12th-century minbar from the Kutubiyya mosque
here, which conservators from the Metropolitan Museum of Art have
lately restored and installed to justified local fanfare, in the
remains of the city's immense Badi Palace. The smaller Casbah
minbar is great, too _ though a wreck _ and is still in use. So
however they compare esthetically, the two minbars have now become
fundamentally different kinds of objects and reflect different
approaches to treasured objects from the past. By Michael
Kimmelman.
</P>
