<HEADER>
A9198 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-FELLOW-LADN     08-24 1865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-FELLOW-LADN </SLUG>
 
Mouse House taps geniuses for ideas 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Danny Hillis once invented a computer a thousand
times faster than anything on the planet. Alan Kay created the
world's first notebook computer back when most of the machines
still filled a room.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Minsky has been a seminal figure in artificial
intelligence research, trying to teach computers how to think. And
Seymour Papert, another AI pioneer, has done groundbreaking work
understanding how children learn.
</P>
<P>
   They're hall of famers in the world of computers, big-science
big-timers that any high-tech company would love to have on its
team.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, these brains work for the Big Mouse,
brainstorming for one of the world's largest media companies,
fortifying Walt Disney's already formidable Imagineers with an
extra dose of IQ as they create new theme-park attractions, movies,
television shows, computer titles and Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   They're Disney Fellows, part of a program started three years
ago with the hiring of Hillis, whose astonishing breadth of
interests and accomplishments by age 40 would be really annoying if
he weren't so damned nice.
</P>
<P>
   Kay, who built the Dynabook computer in the early '70s while
still at Xerox's groundbreaking Palo Alto Research Center, came
after spending 13 years as a fellow at Apple Computer.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Papert and Minsky, two Massachusetts Institute of
Technology powerhouses whose work has shaped our understanding of
how humans learn and how computers can be taught.
</P>
<P>
   Working with a media giant instead of a computer king has been a
radical change of corporate culture, something Hillis said he was
ready to do after years working in the more empirical, linear world
of engineers and programmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge change _ in a lot of dimensions,'' Hillis said.
``But I'm very glad I did it. I wanted to learn new stuff, and I've
done that in spades here. I've gone from trying to understand
reality to trying to escape reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Hillis, Kay is glad to have made the jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very different kind of environment than a Silicon
Valley computer company,'' said Kay. ``Computer companies just
don't get that it's all about media. Disney is now a media company,
and a lot of its destiny has to do with computer(-based)
representations.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the entertainment world is much more interesting,
Hillis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, people are very into aesthetic perception, storytelling,
emotion,'' Hillis said. ``There's much more initiative, more gut
feel.''
</P>
<P>
   In the world of engineering, he added, ``Emotion never gets
talked about, except as a weird sort of behavioral anomaly. When I
first came here, it confused me. I could not figure out how you
could be successful with such sloppy thinking. Now I'm getting that
new perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Hillis said, he understands that it's not sloppy thinking.
Very different from what he knew, but not sloppy.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the ``science'' of entertainment is a series of highly
educated guesses about what works for people. And understanding
that science has been undergirding his work the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the Fellows said the great part about working at
Disney is they get to think hard about how people will play in the
future, and they help make that happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a little bit like Edison's lab; we're playing around
with what you could do,'' Hillis said. ``But the real analogy is
when Disney was creating animation and they discovered the rules of
physics don't apply: `Hey, the body can squish.' But the stuff
we're doing now will look very quaint three years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Minsky likens the Disney R&AMP;D work to the way MIT's famous Media
Lab and Artificial Intelligence Lab work. The feeling of
exploration, of serious play and playful work, are keys to powerful
creativity, he said, but aren't often available to researchers
around the world these days.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Kotkin, a senior fellow at the Pepperdine Institute for
Public Policy, said the Fellows program is an example of the larger
media and technology convergence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of scholar-in-residence program is very smart,''
Kotkin said. ``Long-term thinking in Hollywood is not common. But
Disney is so much more than just a film company.''
</P>
<P>
   Kay and Hillis are based in the Disney R&AMP;D skunk works sprawling
across a west Glendale industrial park, while Papert and Minsky
remain at MIT as Disney ``associate fellows.'' When needed, the
associate fellows come to Disney's Southern California operations
to advise on specific projects, Minsky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go there whenever somebody has an interesting problem,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fellows laud the major resources they have available at
Disney, starting with the many great, if anonymous minds that
support them in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   While they are easily the best-known people in Disney's
long-secretive R&AMP;D hierarchy, the Fellows work collegially with
each other, their own teams of researchers and other groups
throughout the company, often to help tweak particularly
troublesome details.
</P>
<P>
   They tend to be modest about their own contributions as well.
For instance, in talking about a recent theme-park ride that he
worked on, Minsky said he helped on 1 percent of the project. The
everyday brilliance of Disney's Imagineers did the rest, and they
should get the credit, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring Papert and Minsky as associate fellows is ``brilliant,''
said Aaron Goldberg, executive vice president of Ziff-Davis Market
Intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, there's no way in a million years that Disney could hire
away someone like Minsky or Papert,'' Goldberg said. ``Who's going
to leave (jobs like they have at) MIT? But this lets them tap into
what those minds are working on.''
</P>
<P>
   Minsky likens the atmosphere at Disney's R&AMP;D operations to what
MIT used to be ``before all the students grew up and became
professors. You can get an idea and do something with it in a
weekend. It's both a different environment and a flashback to those
golden days in the 1960s when nothing seemed impossible and no one
cared what you did.''
</P>
<P>
   The ringmaster of this particularly lively circus is Bran
Ferren, Disney's executive vice president for creative technology
and research and development.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my jobs at the company is to think about the future of
the entertainment business and Disney's place in it,'' said Ferren,
whose Easthampton, N.Y., research lab was absorbed by Disney a few
years back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion is the business of storytelling and creating
characters is going to be moving more and more in the direction
where technology will have a significant effect,'' said Ferren.
``At the highest level, we want to be able to identify and bring
into the company the best of the best, the most creative minds out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferren is a strapping man of imposing girth, twinkling eyes and
a graying red beard. Altogether, he reminds one of Santa Claus in
his salad days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bran Ferren is just this great, insane toymaker,'' said Paul
Saffo, executive director of the Institute for the Future, a
Silicon Valley think tank. ``He's brilliant. He's always moving.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ferren and the Fellows routinely zap back and forth
between the two coasts and Disney's five R&AMP;D facilities. They're
like electrons, zooming about the continent in a haze of energy and
ideas, difficult to pin down in one spot, their own private
metaphor for Heisenberg's uncertainty principle.
</P>
<P>
   And like electrons zooming around a nucleus of big ideas, the
Fellows have been flying around each other since the 1960s, thanks
to MIT.
</P>
<P>
   Papert and Minsky have been at the school for decades and have
known Hillis since he was an undergraduate there. Papert's work
helped inspire Kay's explorations of new computing systems. And
when Kay was briefly an MIT professor, he hired a teen-age Hillis
to work in his lab.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the four work with the rest of Disney's 140-person research
and development unit to help create a variety of projects. But
revealing details is something the ever-secretive Disney executives
can only partially allow for fear of giving away not-quite-ready
ideas to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Hillis will allow &UR;  &LR; that he's working on a ``dinosaur-related''
project, along with numerous Internet and computing-related
projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic, top-level notion is there's a fundamental change in
the medium going into the home: Now you can talk back to it,''
Hillis said.
</P>
<P>
   Kay _ stumpy, shaggy and still vigorously youthful at 58 _ has
spent his time creating educational computer titles based on a
powerful new object-oriented programming language he helped create
called Squeak.
</P>
<P>
   Kay shows some of his team's Squeak-based ``children's authoring
system'' that will soon be on Disney's Internet site for kids.
</P>
<P>
   With it, students can create simple software ``machines''
illustrating gas pressure, gravity and epidemiology. A nimble
``paint'' program creates objects that can be manipulated,
animated, even linked to each other with a powerful, simple
programming system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disney is doing a lot of thinking about education,'' Kay said.
``What is an interesting route toward something that is good for
kids, and what would it be like if you put the Disney brand on it?
What I want to do is help kids think better than adults do today.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also is using Papert's work to answer questions
about education, said Ferren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Papert is thinking about how to weave the educational process
into what we do,'' Ferren said. ``How do you teach? How do you make
richer educational experiences?''
</P>
<P>
   Imagineering president Kenneth Wong calls the Fellows program an
experiment for Disney.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are some of the most unique minds in fields that are
very interesting to us,'' Wong said. ``But they're free-roaming. We
bring them in and let them match up with their interests. These are
great fertilizer, great provocateurs.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for Disney is to take the Fellows' ideas and make
them into moneymaking ventures. All of them work on projects that
have a chance of becoming real in the next decade, Wong said,
though not without a lot of effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``What these guys generally propose (is) very hard, not
intellectually but technically,'' Wong said. ``Anything that
doesn't seem impossible is sort of boring to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The other challenge, Wong said, is the prodigious and
wide-ranging nature of the Fellows' brains and interests,
particularly as the company considers whether to expand the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Hillis, for instance, edits a math journal in his spare time,
owns his own firetruck and closely follows evolutionary biology
theory, in part because of its potential impacts on creating
computer code that evolves and improves itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power and thinking of these individuals is pretty
prodigious and has a vastly disproportionate mindshare, if you
will,'' Wong said. ``It's more a question of balancing the
intellectual firepower with the ability of the organization to
contextualize these days. These are a very special breed of
thoroughbreds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
