<DOCNO> NYT19980824.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9203 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER-MEDICAL-LADN     08-24 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-MEDICAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIND OVER CANCER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEESUN WEE 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Chad Warrick of Canyon Country knew his
girlfriend had a doctor's appointment that morning four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The couple downplayed the visit. Probably nothing major.
Routine. Heather Clelland was, after all, only 24.
</P>
<P>
   But when Chad checked his voice mail during his lunch break, he
went into shock. Test results positive. Breast cancer. He
understood that much, despite Heather's crying.
</P>
<P>
   He abandoned the Lego pirates display he had been assembling
inside a toy store, hopped into his car and rushed to Heather's
Canyon Country home.
</P>
<P>
   As the speedometer hovered over 80 miles per hour, he thought,
``We're just starting our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Heather was still crying when Chad rushed inside and hugged her.
``We've got to go on a drive. We've just got to get away,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   So they drove. Where they went, they don't remember. It didn't
matter. The point was they were escaping, if only for a bit, by
moving, going _ going anywhere. As the road rolled underneath them,
he consoled his future wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is going to be OK. We're not going to let this
thing get us. We're going to get through this together.'' He
sounded more confident than he actually was, he would confess
later.
</P>
<P>
   In the unfinished story of breast cancer, the young couple
represent a mere blip _ if that. Heather is among an estimated
180,000 American women who are diagnosed with breast cancer
annually.
</P>
<P>
   But Heather's experience is difficult to ignore. She found a
grape-sized lump in her right breast when she was young and
healthy. And she's a woman with no family history of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, her physicians have no definitive explanations for
why Heather developed cancer. ``Believe me, I asked,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her test results serve as a stark reminder that this disease
knows no boundaries. And despite ongoing research on inherited
breast cancer, chemotherapy before surgery, experimental drugs and
machines claiming to more accurately detect the disease, Heather
reminds women that cancer remains unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of worrying about cancer, worry about finding it
early,'' Heather says. ``If you're a woman, you're at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, Heather is self-assured and well-spoken.
Her poise and good looks would make a beauty queen envious. She
even looked cute when chemotherapy made her hair fall out and her
scalp was reduced to a peachlike fuzz. But Heather hasn't always
been so poised and articulate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, she always thought of herself not as good as other
people,'' Chad said. It took fighting breast cancer and educating
others about it to push her out of her shell.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1994 diagnosis, Heather has undergone a lumpectomy and
within the past month a mastectomy. It has been difficult for the
self-described control freak.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if it comes back?'' she wondered aloud to Chad. They
thought about the children they eventually want to have and
Heather's family members who may be at risk for cancer, too _
especially Heather's twin sister.
</P>
<P>
   An identical twin has roughly double the risk of getting breast
cancer, said Thomas Mack, director of the Division of Epidemiology
at the University of Southern California School of Medicine. He
also leads the California Twin Program that studies diseases among
twins.
</P>
<P>
   For now, her sister, Dawn Poirier, has shown no evidence of the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Heather and Chad endured the dark times. As Heather puts it, she
lives hopefully, not hopelessly. Family support and humor help too.
</P>
<P>
   Just before Heather's mastectomy in July, her mother and sister
scrawled ``Hasta La Vista, Boobie!'' above her chest. Heather's
family teases her when she complains of fatigue. ``Cancer,
schmancer,'' her sister jokes. Earlier this month, they threw
Heather a recovery party.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's your time to go, it's your time to go,'' Heather said.
``You can't live life wondering and waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long after Heather and Chad, now both 29, fell in love
that their medical roller coaster began. Ironically, the first turn
centered on Chad _ not Heather.
</P>
<P>
   When the two first began dating, Chad, a fly-fishing fan, seemed
to adore the outdoors. ``Let's go sit out on the patio. It's so
beautiful out,'' he suggested. ``How romantic,'' Heather thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all actuality, I couldn't breathe,'' said Chad, who has
been battling asthma since he was a child.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Chad's asthma, which had been dormant for years,
flared into a life-threatening condition. The episode landed him in
a hospital for a week.
</P>
<P>
   Heather leaned toward Chad and said, ``You've got to take care
of yourself because I want you to be around.''
</P>
<P>
   The following year around Easter, it was Heather's turn.
</P>
<P>
   She was taking a shower, getting ready for a date with Chad,
when she felt the lump.
</P>
<P>
   ``The instant I felt it, all the air was sucked out of me and
down the drain. It took my breath away,'' Heather recalled. ``My
first thought was, `Oh my God. This feels bad'.''
</P>
<P>
   But Heather let her age dissuade her from seeking a physician
immediately _ something she now lectures women against as a
volunteer for the American Cancer Society in the Santa Clarita
Valley. She chastised herself for thinking she could even have
breast cancer so young. Statistics seemed to support her doubts.
</P>
<P>
   Of the estimated 180,000 breast cancer cases recorded annually,
about 600 involve women age 30 and under, said Diane Blum,
executive director of Cancer Care Inc., a New York-based nonprofit
organization offering education and support.
</P>
<P>
   Heather felt uncomfortable investigating the lump. ``I convinced
myself it was nothing,'' she said. Her mother eventually ordered
her to visit a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   The physician initially thought Heather had a fibroid tumor. No
big deal. But test results two weeks later confirmed otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just looked stunned. He said, `I have a bit of bad news.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he proceeded to tell me what happens next, choices I
needed to make. ... I wasn't listening. I was crying.''
</P>
<P>
   She walked out of the office to a nearby pay phone. She called
her mother, sister and Chad.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks later, Heather had a lumpectomy. Chemotherapy followed.
</P>
<P>
   It was during her recovery, those days she spent clad in
pajamas, sometimes suffering from extreme nausea, that Chad came
over bearing roses _ and a velvet ring box shaped like a rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking like utter crap,'' she recalled. They married
two years later, in March 1996 _ enough time for Heather's hair to
grow back.
</P>
<P>
   Then earlier this year, a routine checkup revealed cancer had
returned to the same spot. The first diagnosis had been shocking.
This time, they were mad.
</P>
<P>
   ``When is some good stuff going to happen to us?'' Chad
wondered. ``We're good people.''
</P>
<P>
   But anger gave way to the reality of Heather's condition.
Positive thoughts in mind, they proceeded with a mastectomy
followed by reconstructive surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Heather returned to work at a podiatrist's
office. She'll continue speaking publicly about breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Heather urges women not to assume youth or no family history of
the disease means immunity. About 80 percent of all breast cancer
diagnoses have no track record. She lectures women to perform
breast self-exams _ not rely on finding a lump accidentally as she
did. ``I didn't know what a breast exam was.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Heather pauses at her past lack of insight, she doesn't
regret passing on the mastectomy first. The lumpectomy was the
right decision then, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Heather and Chad focus on the future. Although she
won't know for years if she has been cured, for now, she's
cancer-free. Sure the couple worries about a recurrence. But they
push thoughts of ``what if'' aside. ``Mastery of fear but not
absence of fear,'' Heather says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to be healthy, have a house and some kids. I'm a
pretty simple person, and I know Heather is, too,'' Chad said. ``We
just want a normal life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
