<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9207 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     08-24 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THIS, AT LEAST, COMMANDER IN CHIEF MERITS OUR SUPPORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You won't hear me criticizing President Clinton's decision to
order missile attacks against terrorist facilities in retaliation
for the bombing of U.S. embassies in East Africa. I've been
screaming for years that he should do something like this.
</P>
<P>
   But I can see where some people might be skeptical. I can see
where some might suspect Clinton of a ``Wag the Dog'' scenario.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't seen this ``Wag the Dog'' movie, but they say it's
about a president who diverts public attention from a White House
sex scandal by staging a phony war against Albania. Inquiring minds
want to know: Did Clinton order military action Thursday just to
distract us from Monica Lewinsky and lurid tales of sex in the Oval
Office?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton-backers called such suggestions ``silly'' _ among other
things. The language used by Democratic Sen. Joe Biden of Delaware
wasn't the worst you'll hear from a member of Congress, but I won't
repeat it in a family newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The problem here is that the commander in chief who ordered the
missile strikes has little or no credibility after admitting to
seven months of baldfaced lies about his relationship with
Lewinsky. Who can believe anything he says about anything?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, is it really so silly to suspect a ``Wag the Dog'' con
job by a president who brought in a Hollywood producer to coach him
for his infamous wag-the-finger scam: ``I did not have sexual
relations with that woman ...''?
</P>
<P>
   When a president sets fire to his own credibility, he has to
live with the mistrust that ensues.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I don't give the ``Wag the Dog'' theory much
credence. I'd be more inclined to believe that Clinton dreamed up
the missile attacks as an excuse to interrupt that family vacation
he's been on with his wife and daughter. I'd rather confront
wild-eyed terrorists any day than do battle with an angry Hillary.
</P>
<P>
   All skepticism aside, it doesn't matter what motivated the
president to strike the terrorists. It was the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   The United States too often endures attacks by terrorists and
does nothing to retaliate. In this case, the missile strikes were
said to be both retaliatory and preemptive because the United
States had reason to believe that the terrorists involved were
planning future attacks against America.
</P>
<P>
   The world's lone remaining superpower _ and the favorite target
of international terrorists _ must take the lead in combating
terrorism. If that means periodically launching military strikes
against nations or groups that harbor and sponsor terrorists, so be
it.
</P>
<P>
   And the president of the United States has the authority to
initiate such military action _ whenever and wherever it is needed.
It's a responsibility he had shirked for too long before Thursday's
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Scandal or no scandal, the American people should hope that
Clinton's decision signaled a new willingness to act boldly in the
face of provocation by terrorists. These are vile, ruthless killers
who are emboldened by the perception that their mortal enemy, the
United States, is cowering in fear and is helpless in the face of
their vicious atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   Terrorists feed on the fear that their brutality engenders in
its victims. It inspires them to ever-escalating acts of murder and
mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   Firm and expeditious U.S. action is the only thing these killers
understand. That Clinton was willing and able to take such action
despite his predicament conveys an important message to terrorists
around the world: Do not assume that political turmoil will prevent
this country from doing what it must to maintain its security.
</P>
<P>
   There can be no doubt that Clinton's penchant for deception has
created a serious gulf of distrust between him and large numbers of
Americans. As long as it exists _ and that may be for as long as he
is president _ this distrust will prompt questions about his
motives when he exercises his responsibilities as commander in
chief.
</P>
<P>
   But he is still the president. He deserves our support when he
lives up to the title.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
