<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9232 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NINA-SIMONE-SPI &LR;      08-24 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NINA-SIMONE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NINA SIMONE BRINGS ELEGANCE AND ANGER TO HER PERFORMANE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERTA PENN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It is a rare sight in the '90s, a 65-year-old woman
dressed in a glittering evening gown with her fist raised in the
black-power salute. Few people could pull off such a seemingly
mixed statement before a crowd of 3,000 and not be laughed off the
stage. But singer and pianist Nina Simone did it and not only
commanded respect, but also received a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   That picture of sparkling-clad Simone with her fist in the air
before the roaring applause of the Friday night crowd at the
Seattle Pier reveals her essence as a blend of elegance and anger,
upper-class sophistication and working-class political
consciousness. She has been the High Priestess of Soul to '60s
jet-setters and intellectuals, and now their offspring, and used
this status to make demands for equality and justice.
</P>
<P>
   The price Simone has paid for balancing revolution with standing
ovations has been bouts with mental illness, a suicide attempt and,
at times, poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Simone began her hour-and-40-minute set with several gospel
tunes, shouting like the preacher's daughter that she is. Some were
delivered seated at the piano, accompanied by longtime band leader
and multi-instrumentalist Al Schackman, percussionist Leopoldo
Fleming and drummer Paul Robinson. Others were done a cappella with
band members singing harmony. At first Simone's voice sounded
ragged, gruff, but it was coming from her soul.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she hit ``Sinnerman,'' Simone's voice was gaining
elasticity, and she started to expand her repertory by covering the
Beatles' ``Here Comes the Sun.'' On the sexy Afro blues of ``See
Line Woman,'' Simone danced sensuously with only percussion
accompanying her tale of seductive women.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional roller coaster of ``I Loves You, Porgy,''
(Simone's first single and first chart maker) was followed by the
swinging standard ``Exactly Like You,'' and then her best-known
tune, ``Sugar in My Bowl,'' which she delivered as a sultry
come-on. After a few puffs from a cigarette Simone had her
attendant bring on stage, she asked the crowd if they wanted to
hear her now-classic '60s protest song ``Mississippi Goddam!''
which she said she had sung at the birthday of the ``finest man on
the planet,'' Nelson Mandela. As it was a house full of High
Priestess worshipers who had come from as far away as Switzerland
to see her only North America appearance, they not only wanted to
hear her shout about racism, they joined in the refrain.
</P>
<P>
   The ferocity of ``Mississippi Goddam'' gave way to the soft
vulnerability in Jacques Brel's ``Ne Me Quitte Pas.'' Simone ended
the set with a vengeance, giving the Brecht/Weil-penned ``Pirate
Jenny'' the hardness inherent in the lyrics, but seldom is it sung
with such frightening glee. For an encore, she did ``My Baby Just
Cares for Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the dark velvet voice that Simone used to wrap around a
song in the '50s and '60s has been taken by age, it has been
replaced with a Kinte cloth that swaddles her singing in the
history and spiritualism of African American culture. It is a
one-of-a-kind voice, and most of those who saw Simone's show at the
Pier will not quickly forget it.
</P>
<P>
   The opening set of free jazz by the Art Ensemble of Chicago was
not well-received, used as background for socializing by the crowd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
