<HEADLINE>
SHAKESPEARE'S WORKS TRANSCEND EVEN DELIVERY BY SITCOM STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFREY ERIC JENKINS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Here we go again.
</P>
<P>
   That's what first came to mind when it was announced that
Oscar-winner Helen Hunt (``As Good As It Gets'') would star in
Shakespeare's ``Twelfth Night, or What You Will'' at the Vivian
Beaumont Theater in Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on the heels of Alec Baldwin and Angela Bassett's
disappointing performances in ``Macbeth,'' at the Joseph Papp
Public Theater in March, Hunt's planned portrayal of Viola set
critical teeth on edge.
</P>
<P>
   Could the sitcom star turned lauded film actor continue
ascending professional heights? Or would the elevated language of
Stratford's Bard prove too tough a task? For many years, American
actors have taken an oft-deserved rap for being unable to ``speak
the speech'' and still make the plays come to life.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Twelfth Night,'' which runs through next weekend, Hunt and
her British director, Nicholas Hytner, have the advantage of
working on one of the theater's finest comedies. A tale of
emotional loss and romantic love, the play hinges on confusion
caused when the shipwrecked Viola assumes a man's identity.
</P>
<P>
   After befriending the passionate Duke Orsino (Paul Rudd), the
disguised Viola is asked to carry the duke's message of love to
Olivia (Kyra Sedgwick). Mourning her late brother, Olivia spurns
the advances of the duke but takes a fancy to Viola. To complicate
matters further, Viola herself begins to fall in love with the
duke.
</P>
<P>
   Interspersed with this intricate love triangle are delightful
comic scenes between the play's clowns, Sir Toby Belch (Brian
Murray) and Sir Andrew Aguecheek (Max Wright). Murray and Wright's
exquisite characterizations often reduce the audience to extended
fits of laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Exotically designed by Bob Crowley (sets), Catherine Zuber
(costumes) and Natasha Katz (lighting), this ``Twelfth Night'' is a
warming pleasure from start to finish _ including when the actors
splash in the onstage pool. Hytner's production accentuates the
strengths of the actors while (mostly) disguising the flaws.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt manages her role nicely. Jamie Buchman _ Hunt's character
on television's ``Mad About You'' _ occasionally peeks through but
those moments are few and her emotional honesty is admirable.
</P>
<P>
   Among the leads, only Rudd fails to match his character's drive.
It's as if he is performing in a different version of the play.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, since it's summer in New York City, ``Twelfth Night''
isn't the only of the Bard's works on the boards.
</P>
<P>
   As it has since 1962, the New York Shakespeare Festival has made
the outdoor Delacorte Theater in Central Park its summer home. This
year's Shakespeare offering is the little-seen ``Cymbeline.''
Little-seen, that is, except for this year when the Royal
Shakespeare Company also staged a version at the Brooklyn Academy
of Music.
</P>
<P>
   In director Andrei Serban's Central Park production (through
Aug. 30), a storyteller (George Morfogen) reads a tale to a child
(Jacob Smith) that weaves a complex account of King Cymbeline in
the time of the Romans. As darkness falls in the park, the
storyteller's words bring the characters to life and the banishment
of Imogen's (Stephanie Roth Haberle) husband, Posthumus (Michael
Hall), begins the romantic saga.
</P>
<P>
   Serban keeps the child involved with the intricate action - here
he peers through the trees, there he prompts a character - to
remind us that this story is a fantasia from a fertile imagination.
And it's just as well, ``Cymbeline'' is filled with classic
fairy-tale devices such as an orphaned child, an evil stepmother,
kidnapped children, powerful potions and long-lost siblings. It is
a story of a world locked in chaos and of how order may arise from
the dispensation of mercy, if not of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Set designer Mark Wendland's grassy knoll surrounded by a moat
features an elegant stand of trees and a small circle of fine sand,
which tie the setting to the park's bucolic natural backdrop even
as it makes us think of exotic places. Marina Draghici's costumes
evoke Arabian nights with her modified turbans and shoes with
pointy-toes curling skyward.
</P>
<P>
   In the Royal Shakespeare Company's production, director Adrian
Noble and his designers gave ``Cymbeline'' a decidedly Asian feel
that stylistically landed somewhere between Japan and China. Noble,
too, began with a storyteller - in the text one gentleman tells
another of the Cymbeline story and Posthumus' banishment. But the
opening scene was more ritualized with hooded actors hunkered
around the storyteller's fire. As each character was introduced,
the actor stood and whisked off his or her cape.
</P>
<P>
   Where Serban has mined the open-hearted humor of the fantastic
``Cymbeline'' plot, Noble's production possessed a coolness
enhanced by the dark palette of color and Anthony Ward's abstractly
formal scene design.
</P>
<P>
   And what of the actors? How do the Americans fare when compared
with their British counterparts? Pretty well, in this instance.
However, Stephanie Roth Haberle, who is an imposing presence as
Imogen in Serban's park version, might have been an interesting
alternative to diminutive Joanne Pearce in the RSC production.
</P>
<P>
   In the Central Park production, Liev Schreiber is a
fascinatingly sympathetic villain as Iachimo. Even as he lurks
about the sleeping Imogen's bed, trying to gather information that
will falsely convince her husband of her infidelity, Schreiber's
innate warmth is oddly seductive. As a result, Imogen's resistance
of Iachimo's wiles is all the more impressive.
</P>
<P>
   But in ``Cymbeline,'' the story is all and the actors are merely
servants to telling it clearly. Although both directors highlighted
comedic aspects of the play, Serban's production in Central Park is
superior for the way that the entire creative team manages to tell
the tale in an engaging and entertaining way.
</P>
<P>
   More successful than Noble's ``Cymbeline'' were the other two
Shakespeare plays produced by the Royal Shakespeare Company during
its residency in Brooklyn. ``Hamlet'' and ``Henry VIII'' provided
keen insights to disparate works by the man from Stratford.
</P>
<P>
   Director Matthew Warchus skipped the politics in ``Hamlet'' and
went straight for the Oedipal jugular. His production opened with a
brief black and white film that plays young Hamlet's memories of a
snow-filled winter romp with his father and his dog. As the film
rolled, Hamlet (Alex Jennings) mournfully emptied an urn filled
with ashes. All of the Shakespearean intrigues dealing with
Fortinbras and Norway were stripped away, laying bare the troubling
story of murder and incestuous marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The wiry Jennings was a bundle of raw nerves as he hurtled from
one emotional explosion to the next. Was the character mad, or
merely feigning madness? Probably a bit of both.
</P>
<P>
   Susannah York as Gertrude, David Ryall as Polonius and Derbhle
Crotty as the mad, onanistic Ophelia all made solid contributions
to Warchus' plan. Unfortunately, the concept was undermined by key
performers who seemed unable to release themselves completely to
it.
</P>
<P>
   It was jarring to attend ``Henry VIII'' in the week following
verbal attacks and threats of violence aimed at playwright Terrence
McNally for his coming play, ``Corpus Christi.'' Shakespeare's
duplicitous Cardinal Wolsey drank heavily, fondled young women and
encouraged general debauchery among revelers at a party in his
home. The cardinal later repented. But it was tantalizing to think
of how this Catholic libertinism might be received these days by
certain watchdogs of morality. Wolsey was human and had human
failings. The author of ``Henry VIII'' made the cardinal a genuine
and ultimately sympathetic character - even if some of the
``facts'' are inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   Could this type of work be staged as a new play today? Perhaps,
if it managed to hew to the dominant political culture - as this
play did when it was written.
</P>
<P>
   What is it that continues to draw artists and audiences to
Shakespeare after nearly 400 years? Lovely poetry spoken
exceedingly well doesn't hurt his appeal. But it isn't simply
euphonious combinations of words that keep us coming back.
</P>
<P>
   It's the stories. Brimming with blind passions, grand desires,
humiliating retributions and occasional happy endings, Shakespeare
is eternally here and now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
