<SLUG> BC-INTERVIEW-JENKINS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWN AND OUT IN BEVERLY HILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ How do you cope when you're a motherless teenage girl
in full-bore puberty and you're cursed with a poor, dysfunctional,
male-dominant family that is lacking in sympathy and nurturing
skills?
</P>
<P>
   Especially when that family is more focused on dodging the
landlord in the middle of the night _ all just within the city
limits of that exclusive, rich, movie-star fairy-tale turf called
Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   You avenge your childhood demons by making a movie, of course.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what Tamara Jenkins did.
</P>
<P>
   She's the thirtysomething writer and director of ``Slums of
Beverly Hills,'' which opens Friday at several Seattle area
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Using a Guggenheim grant and funding from the Sundance Institute
and Fox Searchlight Pictures, she spent a year purging her soul by
writing a script. It evolved into a dramatic diary about growing up
``in the '70s without a mom.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie is unusual in its frank and humorous portrayal of how
its adolescent protagonist, Vivian, played by a suitably
``unfinished and gawky'' Natasha Lyonne, deals with her budding
body.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins says she had ``no guidance through the minefield of
adolescence, nor do I have an agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   The director settles into a chair at Seattle's Hotel Monaco
looking very comfortable with her adult body. She's chic,
well-dressed and funny and sucks on an iced coffee, complaining
about the chill from the hotel air-conditioning on a rare Seattle
summer day that promises to hit 80 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was interested in telling a story I'd be interested in
seeing, mainly,'' she says. ``The representation of adolescent
girls is always something that gets on my nerves in movies.
Especially those issues of physicality and coming of physical age
and dealing with the equipment one gets in life. I wanted to deal
with that material in a non-fetishy, non-sexualized way and I hoped
there would be other people interested in putting themselves in
those shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, there were. ``Slums of Beverly Hills'' stars, besides
newcomer Lyonne, film veterans Alan Arkin, Rita Moreno, Carl Reiner
and Jessica Walter, as well as younger actors Marisa Tomei and
Kevin Corrigan. It's about a white-trash family that slinks from
apartment to apartment on the outskirts of Beverly Hills, looking
for the big score and eating at Sizzler when the chips finally come
in.
</P>
<P>
   The R-rated movie features a few wild moments _ most notably a
dance with a vibrator _ and more references to the mystery of
female anatomy and biology than any other recent film.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins says she purposefully made her movie with these
anatomical wonders in mind because ``the whole world is a male
dominant place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we make movies is male dominant; our producers were men,
as were the crew. It was a little microcosm of the real world and
most of them were really great. I ended up having a brotherly
relationship with many of them.''
</P>
<P>
   She says she's had a few ``weird reactions'' to the flagrant
budding female sexuality in the film. Someone felt repelled and
said, ``oooh, all that female grossness.'' She says she also got
hit with an ``oh, you're only interested in breaking taboos''
speech.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if that's true, Jenkins pauses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those reactions frighten me,'' she says. ``As women, we put
ourselves in the shoes of male protagonists everyday. We
transgender no matter what fiction ride we're taking _ movies,
books, plays _ and engage ourselves in things like Hamlet's
dilemma. So I think it would be very painful to believe men
couldn't develop those same muscles and allow themselves to go on a
ride in the shoes of a female, teenage protagonist.''
</P>
<P>
   But she insists she's not intentionally trying to foment a
screen revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason `Slums of Beverly Hills' might be
taboo-breaking is because it's unusual to see movies that deal with
a woman's body in this sort of way. I'm not on a feminist mission,
I just want to explore the female condition. I'm a woman, my
point-of-view is specific and I think it will inform everything I
do as a filmmaker. Even if I write a story with a male lead, it
will be informed by my female experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The movies are the other peripheral character in her film. There
are nods to the out-of-reach glamour of Rodeo Drive and musicals
like ``Guys and Dolls.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jenkins says the only films she remembers were TV movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never had money for the cinema. But I remember bad, raunchy
TV fare. I worshiped `Born Innocent' with Linda Blair. I was
perversely fascinated with it and later, `The Exorcist.' I liked
girls-gone-bad themes, which I'm still intrigued by.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't see great cinema until I was an adult and I
educated myself.'' She sighs. ``I was a weird girl. I was an
outcast but managed to weasel my way in. Like the character in the
film, I lived in an environment where I didn't really belong. Now,
I can wiggle through different scenes, and I'm OK with being
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Her unusual approach obviously made no difference to her strong
cast. The combination of old and new actors ``only enhanced the
film,'' though, she gushes, ``Alan Arkin was a little intimidating
because of his veteran status as well as the fact that he was
playing a variation on my father. My anxiety would swell up like a
virus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was so grateful he agreed to do the movie. And I think
his relationship with Natasha was compelling and exciting.
Sometimes, as a filmmaker, you wind up being a chemist or
matchmaker, imagining how your actors will mix, because you never
see them together until you've cast the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With Alan and Natasha, they had a great rapport and they
worked together really well. I think he responded to her and it
became the perfect father/daughter relationship. He was a mentor.''
</P>
<P>
   So where did Jenkins find Lyonne, her screen self-image?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I auditioned a bunch of girls for the role in New York and
Los Angeles,'' she notes. ``But 90 percent of the young actresses
who walked through the door looked finished. They weren't
adolescent even though they were only between 16 and 20. I needed
the role to be inhabited by someone in an unfinished state. I could
have never imagined being as poised and ladylike as a teenager as
the actresses I saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Natasha was feral and had a sense of humor about herself,
which most people don't have at a young age. She's real and manic
and gawky. She's also beautiful with an animal instinct. She throws
herself around. She's not a finished person in the best sense of
the word.''
</P>
<P>
   And how did Jenkins find the experience of purging the past on a
big screen?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' she says with a smile. ``A film becomes a weird thing
unto itself. When you're mining personal experience and
transforming it into fiction, there's a weird mutation process that
occurs. You have to let go of fact and allow the fiction to simply
be. It's a weird chemical thing. You let go of something you know
and it becomes its own entity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making a film is a strange act of trying to control and
surrender at the same time. But I think anyone who makes a movie
feels that way. Right afterward everyone feels stressed and
horrified and says, `I'm never doing that again!'
</P>
<P>
   ``But, then we start getting itchy and weird and want to go out
and fix all the mistakes we made the first time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone else says they never want to do it again,'' she
sighs, ``but I do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
