 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of TUESDAY, Aug.
25.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867. And be sure to look for other stories from our partners:
Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst
Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona Republic, Kansas
City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San
Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-WAGERS (Undated) _ Scientists are carrying on a noble
tradition, wagering on the outcome of scientific questions, and
that practice seems as pervasive in labs, observatories and
supercomputer centers as pools on college basketball tournaments
are in office parks and machine shops. The tradition was already
alive when titans like Johannes Kepler and Isaac Newton were
setting the foundations of modern science _ and making bets. This
century's savants have ponied up on everything from the properties
of matter's tiniest building blocks to the fate of the entire
universe. By James Glanz. (2280 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANCIENT-AMERICANS (Puerto Montt, Chile) _ Near Monte Verde,
Chile, the site of the oldest known human habitation, archeologists
have discovered a green knoll that may hold clues to human life
even 12,500 years earlier. By John Noble Wilford. (1270 words)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STACKING-ORANGES (Undated) _ Thomas Hales, a professor of
mathematics at the University of Michigan, announced a solution
this month to a problem that had plagued mathematicians for almost
four centuries _ which is the best way to stack oranges? It turns
out that the classic arrangement used by greengrocers around the
world is undoubtedly the most efficient way to stack oranges. While
they reached their conclusion via experience and intuition, Hales
spent 10 years developing a complex 250-page argument, which relies
on 3 gigabytes of computer files. By Simon Singh. (1625 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MONARCH-BUTTERFLIES (Undate) _ High in the mountains of
central Mexico, monarch butterflies arrive by the millions each
winter to take refuge, their black and orange wings festooning
stands of towering fir trees. But conservationists have grown
increasingly concerned about these butterflies as these small
patches of forest, some of which were set aside as preserves,
compete with the needs of the residents around them. Now
conservationists are trying to help the butterflies by helping the
residents. Last month, 40,000 trees were planted in an effort to
save the fragile habitat where monarchs congregate after their long
flight south from the eastern United States and Canada. By Carol
Yoon. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENDER-BIAS (New York) _ Virginia Valian, a professor of
psychology and linguistics at Hunter College, normally studies how
children learn language, but years ago she came across an academic
monograph that demonstrated how the same professional credentials
are evaluated differently depending on whether they are possessed
by a man or a woman _ with the woman being the loser. A
conversation with her. By Natalie Angier. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STALKING (Undated) _ Every year, millions of Americans are
the victims of stalkers. A recent national study by the Justice
Department revealed that an estimated one million women and 400,000
men are plagued by unrelenting pursuers who harass, terrorize and
may even kill their intended victims or anyone else deemed to be in
the way of a stalker's desired goal. The extent of the stalking
problem and its potential for growth through computer networks has
astonished even the most astute researchers in the field and
prompted a strident call for stronger laws. By Jane E. Brody. (2000
words)
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STALKING-COPE (Undated) _ Though stalking is often
glamorized in movies and sitcoms, in real life it is anything but.
For most victims, it is a waking nightmare characterized by
constant fear and hypervigilance that triggers lasting emotional
distress and sometimes results in bodily injury or even death.
Authorities discuss ways of dealing with stalkers. By Jane E.
Brody. (1225 words)
</P>
<P>
   Eds, SCI-STALKING-COPE will also serve as this week's Personal
Health column. We will file it a second time to some points as
BRODY-HEALTH, with its usual lifestyle (``l'') code.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ The All-in-Wonder Pro from ATI
Technologies, as the name implies, brings together television,
video and graphics. It also is forcing people to rethink the
potential of the television. By Rob Fixmer. (1360 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Locating the geographical centers. (300
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Science shorts: The supply of truffles
apparently all but dried up 10 years ago; expanding universe;
mercury poisoning. (750 words)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-WATCH (Undated) _ Although women trying to conceive have
long been warned against heavy drinking, a new study suggests that
even moderate alcohol intake can impede conception. (550 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MOROCCO-MINBAR (Marrakesh, Morocco) _ Not long ago the imam at
the Casbah mosque agreed to show me his ancient minbar _ minbars
are decorated wooden staircases on wheels from which the imam
addresses the congregation during Friday worship. The idea was to
compare it to the 12th-century minbar from the Kutubiyya mosque
here, which conservators from the Metropolitan Museum of Art have
lately restored and installed to justified local fanfare, in the
remains of the city's immense Badi Palace. The smaller Casbah
minbar is great, too _ though a wreck _ and is still in use. So
however they compare esthetically, the two minbars have now become
fundamentally different kinds of objects and reflect different
approaches to treasured objects from the past. By Michael
Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   LUCERNE-MUSIC-FEST (Lucerne, Switzerland) _ Arts Abroad: The
International Music Festival in Lucerne. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   RESERVATION-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Reservation Road,'' by
John Burnham Schwartz (Schwartz). Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SACKS-REVIEW (Undated) _ On PBS, ``Oliver Sacks: The Mind
Traveler.'' By Caryn James.
