A9284 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EGYPT-EXHIBIT-AZR &LR;      08-24 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPT-EXHIBIT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERN WORLD RELISHES EGYPTIAN RELICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. - The Nile used to flood Egypt every year. Egypt
itself will flood Phoenix this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Splendors of Ancient Egypt'' is an immense exhibit coming
to the Phoenix Art Museum for an Oct. 4-March 28 run. The traveling
show of about 200 pieces of ancient art has visited St. Petersburg,
Fla.; Houston; Detroit; and Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   In Portland, where the show ended last week, to be packed up and
trucked to Phoenix, it took over the museum and washed into every
corner and closet, filling them up with mummy cases, bas-reliefs
and canopic jars.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is very little of our own collection up right now,''
explained Asian-art curator Donald Jenkins, the on-site coordinator
for the show in Portland. ``To show this exhibition, we had to take
things down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Portland Art Museum is the oldest in the Northwest and one
of the oldest in the West. Founded in 1892, the museum now inhabits
a stately stone building that looks something like a miniature
National Gallery of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Its atrium served both as an introduction to Egypt and as a
giant waiting room, where crowds of people stood in line to get
individual cassette recorders with an ``accoustiguide'' tour
narrated by Kathleen Turner.
</P>
<P>
   And the crowds have been huge.
</P>
<P>
   A final count has not yet been completed, but Jenkins predicted
it would wind up in the 350,000-370,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   It will prove to be the second most popular in the museum's
history, after ``The Imperial Tombs of China,'' which attracted
450,000 visitors in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins said that he wondered, as many have, why Egyptian art is
so popular. The world it lived in is 5,000 years old, and you might
think the interest in the objects would be archaeological rather
than aesthetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the humanity of it,'' Jenkins said. ``That was
eye-opening for me in this exhibition. I always thought, like most
people, of the very rigid sculptures, the impassive faces, that
there was not much individuality. But when you actually go through
this exhibition, time and time again, you really see something that
strikes home and that underscores the humanity of these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins singles out such pieces as the fragment of a head of
Senwesret III, from about 1850 B.C. There is not much remaining but
the eyes and brow under a headdress. Yet, despite our expectation
that all Egyptian figures are pretty much interchangeable,
Senwesret expresses personality. There is care, worry, even a
little fatigue showing on the finely modeled forehead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so telling,'' Jenkins said. ``And it's only that one
little part of the head.''
</P>
<P>
   The public can relate to the art because they see people doing
very human things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them are mysterious,'' Jenkins said. ``There are
lion-headed goddesses and all that hieroglyphic writing. And that
has its own fascination.
</P>
<P>
   ``But intermingled with that is this very human kind of thing:
those wooden models of people in the granary or plowing the field,
or the wife who puts her arm around her husband's shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, there is the limestone relief of the deified King
Tuthmosis I.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we feel the humans are stylized because of the
curious stance, head-on view of the shoulders, but the face in
profile, with the eyes twisted straight. But if you come close to
it, and look at it in detail, the sensitivity of the rendering
around the nose and eyes, and it is hard to believe it is carved.
It almost looks like it is impressed in clay, it is so refined.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the King Tut show in 1976 _ the first blockbuster of the
new era of museum exhibits _ that reawakened America's fascination
with Egyptian history and art. Since then, all shows of Egyptian
artifacts have been compared to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people have asked, `How does this compare with King
Tut?','' Jenkins said, ``we tell them you can hardly compare them.
King Tut was an extraordinary set of objects, but all from one
tomb, and a tomb that had never been broken into, whereas most
Egyptian art comes from tombs that have been ransacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, this exhibition has a scope that is
phenomenal and that Tut couldn't match. It contains pieces from
Predynastic Egypt right down to Roman and Coptic times, and in the
midst are masterpieces by anyone's standards.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
