<HEADER>
A9291 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-SHOPPING-ART     08-24 1720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-SHOPPING-ART-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMERS HIT THE INTERNET FOR BARGAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eliminates graphic)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joseph Vigneau knew exactly what he wanted: a 1998 Volkswagen
Passat with a V-6 engine, silver paint, and black leather interior.
It's a &UR;  &LR;  vehicle that is &UR;  &LR;  hard to find on this side of the
Atlantic. But the Massachusetts software consultant knew exactly
where to look &UR;  &LR; _ the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Using his laptop computer, Vigneau discovered how much a car
dealer pays the factory for a new Passat; the information is
available at no charge on line. He also read on-line auto magazines
and messages from Volkswagen owners in Europe to get opinions on
the car. And he began e-mailing Volkswagen dealers in search of the
best price.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of pounding the pavement, Vigneau did nearly all his
research while sitting at a keyboard. He ended up paying $1,000
below sticker price for a hard-to-get car. ``By having the amount
of information that I did, from car review sites, to people's
personal experiences ... I knew enough so I wouldn't be taken for a
ride,'' Vigneau said.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with streams of product information available on the
Internet, Vigneau and millions of other on-line consumers are
rewriting the rules of retailing.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of electronic shopping, information is power.
Businesses, consumer groups, and individuals publish vast amounts
of data about thousands of products _ data that shoppers can obtain
at the click of a mouse. Information that was once the private
possession of industry insiders is at the fingertips of any
consumer who cares to look. The results include better deals,
greater convenience, and retailers scurrying to preserve their
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers have always benefited from the ignorance of their
customers. Sellers can pad their earnings by concealing the true
cost of goods they sell. They can withhold information about the
quality of merchandise. And sellers can count on the consumer's
limited patience, his unwillingness to visit one more store or buy
one more consumer-education magazine. But Internet shoppers can
overcome these barriers.
</P>
<P>
   According to Forrester Research &UR;  &LR; Inc. in Cambridge, Mass., 5
percent of North American households bought something on line last
year, spending $2.4 billion. The number of on-line shoppers is
expected to double this year.
</P>
<P>
   The dollars spent on line only hint at the importance of
Internet shopping. The surge of Internet shoppers is turning
retailing upside down. For example, Portland, Ore.-based Egghead
Inc. stunned the retail world in February when it closed its 40
stores. The company changed its name to Egghead.com Inc. and began
selling products exclusively over the Internet or by telephone
order.
</P>
<P>
   Still, traditional bricks-and-mortar retailers will not go away
entirely. Consider Joseph Vigneau and his new Volkswagen Passat.
While he shopped for his car on the Internet, he actually made the
purchase at a traditional auto dealer. With products like cars,
many consumers still will want to see and test the wares.
</P>
<P>
   But shoppers still are finding money-saving information on line.
In order to attract visitors to their retail Web sites, companies
like bookseller Amazon.com or travel agents like
Travelocity &UR;  &LR; publish huge amounts of information that is free to
all visitors, even if they don't make a purchase. In addition,
Internet access services like America Online or Yahoo provide free
consumer information to boost the number of visitors to their
advertiser-supported Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Car dealers have been among the first to feel the effects of
Internet shopping. Detailed information about cars is plentiful on
the World Wide Web. For example, Edmund Publications Corp. of
Beverly Hills, Calif., publishes its new- and used-car guides on
the Web with prices, product reviews, and comments from car owners.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than resist the enlightened consumer, many car dealers
are joining organizations like Autobytel.com Inc., an on-line
buying system that helps direct customers to nearby &UR;  &LR;  dealerships
that have exactly the car they want.
</P>
<P>
   A visitor to the Autobytel site can type in exactly the car he
wants, starting with a base model and adding options. The system
provides the invoice price _ the cost of the car to the dealer _
and shows the consumer how to calculate additional factors like
destination charges and rebates. A visitor can get similar
information for hundreds of new and used cars. Once he makes a
choice, the buyer can type in his contact information and request a
bid from the nearest car dealer in the Autobytel network.
</P>
<P>
   Autobytel president Mark Lorimer says that it is a good deal for
the seller as well as the buyer, because the system automates so
much of the selling process. Lorimer says it costs a dealer about
$1,260 to sell the average new car. Selling through Autobytel
lowers that cost to around $400. That means more savings for
consumers and higher profits for dealers. Lorimer estimates that
the nation's 2,700 Autobytel dealers sell between 20,000 and 25,000
cars a month using the on-line approach.
</P>
<P>
   But some auto dealers find they don't have to share their
profits with a firm like Autobytel in order to reach customers on
the Internet. Smith Volkswagen in East Providence, R.I., where
Vigneau bought his Passat, created its own Web site. And it's
working. The company gets 100 to 200 e-mail inquiries a day from
Web shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get Thailand, places in North Africa, Western Europe, South
America, pretty much everywhere,'' said Smith salesman Phil Teves.
The dealership gets so many long-distance queries because of its
reputation for being able to acquire hard-to-get models like the
silver Passat. Teves said 20 to 50 percent of the dealership's
monthly new-car sales come from Internet shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most visitors to retail Web sites buy nothing. But
many of them collect information &UR;  &LR;  for use at stores in the real
world.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with Jeff Bezos, founder of Amazon.com, the
electronic bookstore that is probably the Internet's best-known
retailer. ``One of the pieces of feedback we get is that for some
people, they find the book they want to buy, or the CD, and they
print it out on a sheet of paper and take it to the clerk'' at a
store, Bezos said.
</P>
<P>
   Some visitors write and apologize for not buying from Amazon.
Said Bezos, ``We send them back mail saying, `Don't worry about
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Amazon.com spent millions on its huge database of
books and music recordings to attract paying customers from around
the world. But it costs the company nothing extra when visitors
just browse. Those browsers could turn into buyers one day.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses and organizations are jumping into the market for
on-line consumer information. Consumer Reports magazine has rolled
out a Web site that aims to build on the magazine's reputation for
reliable, honest product reviews. In keeping with the Consumer
Reports tradition, there is not a trace of advertising. That means
visitors must pay for the service, but the price is just $2.95 a
month or $24 a year. Thomas Falconer, manager of the site, said
140,000 people have signed up.
</P>
<P>
   There are also for-profit consumer information services on the
Internet, which support themselves through advertising. The most
interesting of these feature ``shopbots'' _ software that lets a
visitor search for a product at several Internet retailers. A
number of these shopbots are available through the major Internet
gateways &UR;  &LR;  _ sites like Yahoo or Lycos _ visited daily by millions
of users.
</P>
<P>
   The Yahoo search service has a section devoted to on-line
shopping. Visitors can locate hundreds of sources for a variety of
consumer goods, and compare prices and features. For instance, a
visitor looking for a computer priced between $1,000 and $2,000
gets 365 suggestions culled from several on-line electronics shops.
The user can order the products over the 'Net, or use the
information as a guide when shopping in a store.
</P>
<P>
   The Compare.Net service takes this concept even further. The
site includes product reviews, side-by-side comparisons, and links
to Usenet message boards where consumers discuss their experiences
with similar products.
</P>
<P>
   This last feature is one of the most significant changes the
Internet has brought to retailing. Until now, consumer
word-of-mouth usually traveled as far as the back fence or the
office water cooler. Today, many turn to the Usenet, a set of
thousands of electronic bulletin boards or ``newsgroups.'' There
are a couple of newsgroups for general consumer issues, but many
more that focus on specialized interests like cars, computers, home
electronics, and other topics. And people are not shy about
relating their experiences with the products they buy.
</P>
<P>
   David Dologite, 25, a Boston project manager, routinely visits
the Usenet before making major purchases, to see how others have
fared. ``I've found the newsgroups to be useful in getting a sense
of what the customer service is like for various companies,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The DejaNews search service maintains an archive of old Usenet
messages that can easily be searched using key words, such as the
name of a particular product.
</P>
<P>
   Many consumers sign on to the Internet in search of
bargain-basement prices. Indeed, Amazon.com and other Internet
retailers have used the lure of sharply discounted prices to draw
customers. But on the whole, it is not clear that goods purchased
on line are much cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   While much is made of cut-rate book prices, the discounts are
sharply reduced when shipping costs are added. And travelers
searching for cheap air fares can find them just as readily with a
phone call as they can on the Internet. &UR;  &LR; Many other products on the
Internet _ computers for instance _ cost about the same as at a
discount electronics store.
</P>
<P>
   But for many consumers, finding exactly the right product _ say,
a silver Volkswagen with black leather interior _ is more important
than getting the lowest price. For these people, the Internet is on
its way to becoming the first place to look.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
