<DOCNO> NYT19980824.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9333 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-VINEYARD-NAT     08-24 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-VINEYARD-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        MARTHA'S VINEYARD LEADERS: PRESIDENT CLINTON CAN YOU HELP US
WITH ...
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Mark D. Preston  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Aug. 24 -- If Martha's Vineyard lawmakers could meet
with President Clinton, they would tell him they need Washington's
help with a number of issues ranging from an inadequate
transportation system to overly stringent fishing regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a whole menu of ideas and items that we could use on
Martha's Vineyard,'' said U.S. Rep. William Delahunt, D-Quincy, who
represents the island.
</P>
<P>
   Delahunt said he wants people to know Martha's Vineyard is more
than a ``wealthy playground for the rich and famous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I represent are the hard-working people trying to
eke out a living,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main problems Martha's Vineyard faces is that the
federal government allocates its money without factoring into the
equation the island's part-time residents for such things as
highway construction, said Charles Clifford, executive director of
the Martha's Vineyard Commission, the island's regional planning
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Dukes County, which encompasses Martha's Vineyard, has only
about 14,000 permanent residents. But with the likes of Clinton,
Hollywood stars and sun-starved tourists, the summer population
balloons to about 102,000, a spokesman for the Martha's Vineyard
Chamber of Commerce said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, for example, Dukes County received $53.7 million from
the federal government, the lion's share coming in the form of
Social Security and other pension benefits paid to residents. By
contrast, Franklin County in western Massachusetts, with a
population of 71,000, took in $272.7 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Clinton's affection for the island -- this is the fourth
summer holiday he has vacationed with his family on Martha's
Vineyard -- Clifford said the president has ``done nothing to
understand its needs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You could probably count on one hand and have four fingers
left over how much in federal dollars we have received since
(Clinton) has been coming here,'' Clifford said.
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokeswoman said President Clinton, too, shares
their concerns about these and other issues that are affecting
communities across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But the federal dollars that Martha's Vineyard, as well as other
communities across the country, seek are overseen more by Congress
than the president.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton is expected to hobnob with Hollywood celebrities
and the nation's elite over the next two weeks, local leaders said
they have no plans to meet with him.
</P>
<P>
   But if local lawmakers did meet with Clinton, most said they
would ask for his assistance in obtaining federal money to improve
the island's transportation system. State Rep. Steve Turkington,
D-Falmouth, describes Martha's Vineyard's roads during the summer
months as ``parking lots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't many other places that have worse traffic in the
summer,'' Turkington said. ``Just try driving into Edgartown,
Vineyard Haven or Oak Bluffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Rappaport, a local attorney and chairman of the Woods Hole,
Martha's Vineyard and Nantucket Steamship Authority -- which
oversees the operation of the ferries between the islands and the
mainland -- said the traffic congestion on Martha's Vineyard has
gotten increasingly worse over the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a major expansion of the public transit system,''
Rappaport said, adding that the current public and private bus
systems are not meeting the demands of visiting tourists during the
summer months.
</P>
<P>
   Rappaport said he would like to see the federal government fund
a program that would allow Martha's Vineyard to use a fleet of
buses during the peak summer months. During the winter months,
those same buses could be used by a ski resort community, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many island leaders are also concerned that future budget cuts
could close the Menemsha Coast Guard Station, although Delahunt
said there are no plans to shut it down this year. But he warned
that a shrinking Coast Guard budget puts the station at risk in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Goff, chairman of the Chilmark Board of Selectmen, said
the federal government needs to change how it regulates the
commercial fishing industry because current policies are hurting
local fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to reform and make better the fishing regulations,''
she said. ``I think the fishermen are looking for a little more
understanding so they can make a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Morgan, a 74-year-old semi-retired Menemsha fisherman,
said the federal government needs to relax its catch quotas this
year on summer flounder and striped bass. Morgan also said that if
the U.S. is going to allow Canadian-caught swordfish to be sold on
Cape Cod, then our northern neighbors ``should allow us to fish in
the eastern part of the Georgia Banks.''
</P>
<P>
   As Martha's Vineyard copes with the increasing growth boom that
is eating up its remaining landscape, island leaders are attempting
to preserve as much open space for future generations. In fact,
Rappaport said that 2 percent of every real estate transaction is
set aside in a land bank.
</P>
<P>
   A land bank is a designated fund designed for the sole purpose
of helping communities purchase land for preservation.
</P>
<P>
   Turkington said he would like to see the federal government
``step up'' with some money and help the state and local
governments pay for preserving the island's open space.
</P>
<P>
   But not all Martha's Vineyard residents are looking for federal
money allocations earmarked specifically for the island. Chris
Burns, a well-known media consultant and former Washington Post
executive, said the best thing Clinton can do to help the island is
to make the federal government more responsive and user-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should walk on the beach, take a deep breath and figure
out how to give us a better federal government,'' Burns said would
be his advice to the president. ``A government that is more
reasonable, more civilized and more focused on what the country
needs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1546EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
