<SLUG> BC-SHOCKCOLLAR1-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZAP! ZEKE II BECOMES A MODEL CANINE CITIZEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS ROPP  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Looking back, shock was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Everything about this Airedale pup had been a jolt: the barking,
the jumping, the biting, the nasty little things he did with his
snout.
</P>
<P>
   Zeke II was 7 weeks old when I purchased him from a private
breeder in Glendale. Soon came the smash-mouth realization that I
had bought Damian's hound from hell. Every moment of every day, the
new dog tested us. If he wasn't eating my guitar strap, he was
running laps around the kitchen with dish towels stuck between his
teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Zeke II was a dog from ``Seinfeld's'' bizarro world. ``No''
meant ``yes.'' ``Down'' meant ``up.'' ``Come'' meant ``catch me if
you can.''
</P>
<P>
   The cats were so nervous they refused to walk on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   When Zeke II was 6 months old, I sent him off to doggy boot camp
for serious obedience training. Five weeks later, he returned with
the trainer's trenchant observation: He's a real handful, isn't he?
</P>
<P>
   After a second stint at doggy boot camp with little improvement,
I came to the sad realization that Zeke II's options were running
out. I kept telling myself he was just a pup and deserving of some
slack. But he was a pup expanding ominously. Every day, he grew
larger and stronger and more obstreperous.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne was no longer able to control him. I had slightly better
success.
</P>
<P>
   As a last resort, I purchased a shock collar. Let me make it
clear to all you animal lovers (like myself) that this WAS a last
resort. I didn't know much about shock collars, other than that
they sounded barbaric and I never imagined using one.
</P>
<P>
   But then, I never imagined a dog like Zeke II.
</P>
<P>
   Shock collars, also known as remote trainers, usually consist of
a simple snap-on nylon collar with a receiver in the middle that
resembles a pager. The other part, the transmitter, looks like a TV
remote. Both transmitter and receiver operate on a 9-volt battery.
</P>
<P>
   My transmitter came with three buttons: one for programming the
severity of shock (ranging from 1 to 8), a warning button and a
shock button. The warning button delivers an audio signal when the
dog commits a heinous act, such as chewing on the cat. If he
continues the heinous act, the negative behavior is corrected with
a quick, low-level shock, which also emits the same audio signal up
to a range of 100 feet.
</P>
<P>
   (The manufacturer claims that the lower-level shocks feel like
the charge from carpet static electricity and recommends that
owners try the shock collars on themselves first to reassure
themselves that the charge is not too severe. I did and, at level
3, found it to be somewhat more potent than static electricity _
more like a mild shock from an electrical short.)
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that the dog eventually will associate negative
behavior with the warning sound so he won't need a shock
correction.
</P>
<P>
   All this was in my remote-trainer booklet and instructional
videotape, which I reviewed a half-dozen times to make sure I was
going to do it correctly. But in truth, I had no idea what to
expect.
</P>
<P>
   The moment Zeke II received his first correction was a moment
that forever altered all our lives.
</P>
<P>
   It was a Saturday, late morning. Zeke II was being even more
recalcitrant than usual, alternately barking aggressively, biting
and ripping apart ``No Bad Dogs,'' one of several books he had
snatched from the bookshelf.
</P>
<P>
   We could have corrected Zeke II for any number of problems, but
the remote-trainer manual advised to focus on one misbehavior at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   We focused on cat chasing. From the onset, Zeke II had it in for
Soledad, a stray we had taken in a few years earlier. And sure
enough, it wasn't more than five minutes after we activated the
trainer that the terrier terror began.
</P>
<P>
   As Soledad stepped through the pet door, Zeke II made his move
for her.
</P>
<P>
   The scene unfolded in slow-mo. As always, I told him ``No.'' And
as always, he ignored the command and continued cat bound. I
pressed the warning button on the transmitter, activating a red
pulsating light and a warning tone from the collar.
</P>
<P>
   Zeke II ignored that, also.
</P>
<P>
   Soledad executed an escape maneuver, bounding skillfully from
couch to television to piano. Zeke II compensated and pursued.
</P>
<P>
   My thumb slid up to the correction button. Zeke II may have shot
the sheriff, but he did not shoot the deputy.
</P>
<P>
   One press and the dog fiend froze in mid-molest.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 20 minutes, Zeke II slipped into a peculiar stupor,
eyes focused on nothing in particular, a strapping Airedale youth
reduced to an oversize hood ornament.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know where Zeke II went during those 20 minutes, but I'm
convinced a transference occurred. When he came back around, he was
not the same dog. It was as if the personality of the surly, skanky
Zeke II had been electrically exorcised and replaced with the
sweet, gentle spirit of the deceased Zeke I.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that may be a stretch. But consider this: After that first
correction (and only a few more), Zeke II mysteriously began to
obey commands, the barking stopped, the aggression ceased, and we
can now even leave him alone in the house.
</P>
<P>
   To me, it's a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not advocating the use of shock collars. I suspect that
every dog in every situation reacts differently. I'm also guessing
that Zeke II's substantial obedience training contributed to our
positive experience with the remote trainer. A couple of months
have passed, and there has been no relapse. In fact, I no longer
use the collar except for off-leash training outdoors. And he
always responds to the warning tone _ even when a rabbit jumps out
of the brush 10 feet in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Zeke II has become a model dog citizen. We're happy.
He's happy. The cats have returned to the floor. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1548EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
