<DOCNO> NYT19980824.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9342 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOCKCOLLAR2-AZR &LR;      08-24 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOCKCOLLAR2-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOCK COLLARS UNLEASH CONTROVERSY AMONG EXPERTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS ROPP  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Shock collars, as you might expect, are not
universally embraced. The Arizona Humane Society finds them
particularly objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hate them,'' said the society's Kim Hicks. ``We're opposed to
anything that causes pain to animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Luper, owner of the Greater Phoenix Dog Training Academy,
uses the motto, ``Never never hit your dog.'' Luper said you can
add to that, ``Never shock your dog either.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time I've used them is for poison-proofing or
snake-proofing,'' Luper said.
</P>
<P>
   Shock collars are commonly used to teach dogs to stay clear of
snakes. They're also used in the training of retrievers and other
hunting dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Luper said shock collars should not be used as a substitute for
more in-depth, general obedience training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the dog's main motivation to listen should be
anticipation of the praise and affection that he'll receive for
listening,'' Luper said. ``I don't like the idea of a dog listening
because he's afraid of the shock he'll get if he doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Luper said that in the hands of an inexperienced dog trainer, a
device such as a shock collar can become traumatic to the dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``True, a shock collar can provide a correction at a distance,''
Luper said. ``But if you want a dog to come and you don't use the
collar correctly, it can have the reverse effect. If you use the
shock when he's running away from you, he just might run away
faster.''
</P>
<P>
   If your dog doesn't come when you call him, Luper said, you
should work on modifying your relationship with your pet instead of
just shocking him for not coming.
</P>
<P>
   Some breeds, according to Luper, don't respond well to shock,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pit bulls are virtually immune to pain,'' Luper said.
``Rottweilers are also less sensitive to pain than other breeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Luper said that although he doesn't have firsthand experience,
he has heard good things about devices that use audio or smell
corrections, such as citronella spray, in place of shock.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix area animal psychologist Kay Cox, a k a the Pet
Counselor, said that she has used shock collars and that they can
be an effective training device for some dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dog with an attitude needs tough love,'' Cox said. ``You
have to find the right combination of whatever it takes to make
that animal recognize you as the leader in order to communicate
with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox said the more traditional choke-chain and leash-training
methods can also be painful if done incorrectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of trainers train completely wrong,'' Cox said. ``A
good, hard yank with a leash hurts. You do that, you aren't
teaching them; you're controlling them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox said a key to using a shock collar is to leave it on the dog
for a few days before activating it so the dog doesn't associate
the correction with the trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``A shock collar works because it doesn't have to do with you,''
Cox said. ``Because there isn't a leash between you and the dog,
there is no one the dog can be resentful of when the correction is
made. It's like God strikes him. It can definitely wake up some
dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cox, too, concedes that shock collars are not necessary in
most situations. She estimates that only about 1 percent of pups
under 8 weeks old demonstrate the kind of aggression and dominance
that may eventually merit such non-traditional training methods.
</P>
<P>
   Veterinarian Mark Trueblood of Apollo Animal Hospital in
Glendale, Ariz., said he does not hesitate to recommend using
remote trainers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a situation where a dog is a problem barker and
you've tried other methods, using a no-bark collar is certainly a
better alternative than taking the dog to the pound or having it
euthanized.''
</P>
<P>
   Trueblood said he is not aware of any physical damage caused by
remote trainers if used correctly. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
