<HEADLINE>
MORE DEVICES FOR PETS` BAD HABITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS ROPP  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - A slew of other electronic devices is available to
curb a variety of pet problems.
</P>
<P>
   - Bark control collars: When your dog barks, a warning beep
sounds. If your dog continues to bark, a mild static shock is
emitted. The collar senses vibrations in your dog's throat that
happen only during barking. Costs around $50.
</P>
<P>
   Also available are bark collars that use high-frequency sound
pulses rather than shock corrections. Cost around $40.
</P>
<P>
   Citronella bark-control collars are now available. Citronella is
a plant with aromatic oils used to repel insects. Dogs don't like
this lemony scent, so each time your dog barks, a brisk yet
harmless citronella spray is released. Costs around $130.
</P>
<P>
   - Outdoor containment systems: These vary, depending on the size
of your dog (or cat) and the amount of area that needs coverage.
Basically, there's a transmitter that plugs into a standard
electrical outlet and emits radio signals that travel along an
underground wire. A receiver on your pet's collar picks up the
radio signals and alerts him as he nears the underground boundary.
If he crosses the boundary he receives a mild correction similar to
a static shock.
</P>
<P>
   A containment system sold by Radio Fence operates on the
citronella spray principle rather than shock. Costs range between
$150 and $250.
</P>
<P>
   - Indoor containment systems: Place a small, disk-shaped
transmitter near the area you want to protect. Then adjust the
range from 2 to 20 feet. Your cat or dog wears a receiver collar.
If he gets too close to the forbidden area, a warning beep sounds.
If he continues to approach, a mild correction is given. If you
have multiple pets, only the one you want to keep from a given area
wears the collar. Designed to keep pets away from plants, furniture
and even other pets. Costs around $80; a citronella version costs
about $170.
</P>
<P>
   - Mats: These give off a mild correction when dogs or cats touch
them. Normally, mats are placed on rugs or on furniture that pets
are slowly ruining. Also a good deterrent to cats who spend far too
much time under the bird cage. Cost about $57.
</P>
<P>
   - Hand-held trainers: These are small, hand-held audio devices
designed for correcting the misbehavior of dogs and cats. There are
usually two buttons: One gives of a positive tone for reward and an
ultrasonic tone for correction. These devices have been used by
mail carriers and meter readers to deter unwanted advances from
neighborhood dogs. Cost about $30.
</P>
<P>
   - Pest deterrents: Speakers broadcast high-decibel ultrasonic
sounds to discourage rabbits, birds, rodents or the neighbor's cat.
Cost about $60.
</P>
<P>
   - Electronic flea comb: The manufacturer claims that 97 percent
of fleas are killed within 24 hours of combing your dog with this
New Age grooming device. Costs about $20.
</P>
<P>
   Where to find these products:
</P>
<P>
   - Radio Fence in Punta Gorda, Fla., is a large supplier of
remote-training devices. Call up its Web page at www.radiofence.com
or phone 800-941-4200.
</P>
<P>
   - Check the Yellow Pages under ``Pet.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
