<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-UNIFORMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS UNIFORM TREND SPREADS, SCHOOLS OUTGROW KILTS AND KHAKIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Wisconsin, New York)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL LOPEZ  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ After nearly 10 years of wearing a plaid kilt,
long-sleeve white Oxford shirt and navy blue blazer, you would
think that 16-year-old Andrea Ogden would have had just about
enough of her uniform at the private Doane Stuart School in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   But Ogden has seen the uniform change through those years,
giving her more options, like the choice of wearing a polo shirt, a
sweat shirt embossed with the school's logo, even khaki shorts on
hot days. The blazer and blackwatch-plaid kilt are reserved for
formal occasions, like ``chapels,'' or memorial services, at Doane
Stuart, set in a serene Romanesque building of dark wood and leaded
glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more freedom in the uniform,'' said Ogden, a senior.
``When I was in third grade, girls were not allowed to wear khaki
pants.''
</P>
<P>
   True, private schools tinker with uniforms, and more public,
particularly city schools, are adopting uniform policies to lessen
peer pressure about fashion and to instill a serious, disciplined
atmosphere, administrators hope. That trend is opening up a whole
new market for designers and retailers.
</P>
<P>
   But today's array of decidedly casual khaki, navy and white
represent only a subtle evolution from the stiff, plaid jumpers and
starched white shirts that baby boomers wore.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can go back to those scratchy uniforms to what we see
today, there is a major change. I think safe, is the perfect
word,'' said Joanne Arbuckle, a children's wear expert and
assistant professor at Fashion Institute of Technology in New York.
Last spring, she led a charge of 24 young, fresh-minded FIT
students who wanted to test the parameters of the school uniform by
designing its future look.
</P>
<P>
   The result? Think faux-fur trimmed coats and anorak jackets in
bright orange Ultrasuede, the fabric invented by Halston; think
striped bike shorts for girls and iridescent blue vinyl pants for
boys. Think, too, washable, colorful and about as far away from
preppy as you can get.
</P>
<P>
   Ogden takes one look at these designs and immediately comments,
``I would love it. I think they're great. It's not the same old,
same old uniform,'' a remark she qualifies by saying that such
dramatic looks lessen the chance of their broad acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   The boys' uniform, consisting of khaki pants, polos, oxfords,
and blue sweaters or blazer, is fine for Jake Erwin, a 14-year-old
Doane Stuart ninth-grader, if a bit hot during chapel services.
Plainer styles may be a better sell, but, ``then again, it would
probably be impossible to wear a uniform everyone would like.''
</P>
<P>
   Arbuckle and her students note that these slightly over-the-top
designs and fabrics were intended to be futuristic, and for the
runway, not the current market. The students, completing a two-year
degree with a specialty in children's clothing, unveiled their
designs in May at a runway show and related museum exhibit this
summer. Those garments will be shown again at upcoming trade shows.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the message inherent in these daring clothes asks people
to consider the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically opening peoples' eyes, that uniforms don't have
to look like uniforms,'' said Joellyn R. Marshall, 24, whose
designs and academic work won the critic's award. Marshall,
coincidentally,is now a design apprentice in children's sleepwear
at Lands' End, a Dodgeville, Wis., catalog clothing company that
last year introduced a school uniform catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Arbuckle did not conceive of FIT's uniform study in a vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, public schools are turning to the uniform as a way
to enhance school image, curtail peer pressure, instill discipline,
and, in some cases, bolster safety in neighborhoods with gangs who
identify themselves by certain colors.
</P>
<P>
   A February survey of 958 public elementary and middle schools
found that about one-quarter were either considering or had already
begun a school uniform policy, according to the National
Association of Elementary School Principals. The poll was supported
by Lands' End.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton in his 1996 State of the Union and subsequent
speeches, has endorsed the concept as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lands' End last year began a school uniform catalog at the
request of customers, said Christine Hess, the catalog's manager.
</P>
<P>
   The company could easily adapt its regular children's line to
uniform designs, said Hess, who gave the example of transforming
cotton chino pants to a cotton/polyester blend for durability.
</P>
<P>
   Full of crew neck sweaters in navy or evergreen, mesh polos and
twill ``skorts,'' a combination of skirt and shorts, the catalog is
dictated by customer requests, Hess said.
</P>
<P>
   All of this stress on the comfort and casualness of uniforms
leads to a question about their look: should they be fashionable?
After all, schools are adopting uniforms in part, because they hope
to lessen competition.
</P>
<P>
   But Arbuckle, the FIT professor, believes designers will have to
create uniforms with more fashion sense as more schools adopt
policies and students weigh in on those requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, you have the school board and administrators who want to
cut down on the competition and want more discipline. What we were
trying to say is, you can have the discipline, you certainly can
cut down on the competition, but the kids can be happy, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
