<SLUG> BC-FAGAN-KIDNAP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SIGNS OF THAW IN FAGAN CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The handwritten letters, composed in the ``very
touching'' tone of a forgotten friend, have gone unanswered. So,
too, have pleas by Barbara Kurth for a reunion with her two grown
daughters, whom she last saw before their father allegedly
kidnapped them in October 1979.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides in the Stephen Fagan kidnapping case remain as far
apart as they were last April, when Fagan was arrested. With the
matter scheduled for a pretrial hearing in Middlesex Superior Court
Tuesday, sources on both sides report the criminal case is still
forging ahead. No plea agreement is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Continuation of the standoff at this point seems to portend a
highly publicized, contentious trial late this year or in early
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting it to proceed,'' said Peter Kurth, the brother
of Barbara Kurth, ``and we're expecting it to be very dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Fagan was arrested April 16 in Palm Beach, Fla., at one of
several homes in which he has lived since his departure from
Massachusetts nearly two decades ago. Before his arrest, he was
known by his alias, Dr. William Martin.
</P>
<P>
   His daughters, raised as Rachel and Lisa Martin, were living in
New York and California at the time of their father's arrest. The
family reconvened in Massachusetts for Fagan's arraignment on April
21, and during a chaotic week of interviews and meetings, the
daughters stood firmly behind Fagan's contention that he was a
loving parent who spirited them away at ages 2 and 5 to protect
them from their mother, whom he characterized as a neglectful
alcoholic.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a public appeal from Barbara Kurth, in which she said
she had ``always loved them,'' the daughters said they would not
speak to their mother until the case against their father was
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   More than four months later, neither daughter appears to have
budged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbara has written the girls a couple of times, my mother has
written them; (the letters) were all registered and signed for,''
Peter Kurth said. ``But they certainly haven't replied.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacob Atwood, an attorney for Barbara Kurth, described the
correspondence as ``very touching, candid letters that always end
up saying, `I love you.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the girls believe that their father will go to jail if
they have any contact with her,'' Atwood said. ``That's what they
said, at least initially.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwood described their iciness as ``a little bit of bait,'' a
tactic designed to lure their mother into requesting a plea
agreement. But Atwood said that a plea bargain is ultimately the
decision of Middlesex prosecutors, not his client.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Egbert, the attorney for Fagan, confirmed that no plea
agreement has been reached with prosecutors in District Attorney
Thomas F. Reilly's office. But he refused to say whether any
letters had been sent to his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Barbara is discussing things, that's her business,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Egbert also said that Fagan is not planning to attend this
week's court hearing, at which the trial date may be set.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1612EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
