<DOCNO> NYT19980824.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9459 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-0825-     08-24 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-0825-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANALYSIS: CRISIS SIGNALS THE BEGINNING OF YELTSIN'S END
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-STREETS-0825; RUSSIA-Q&AMP;A-0825.
 &HT;    EDs: With optional add beginning at 900 words.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's current political and economic mayhem means
the twilight for Boris Yeltsin, political analysts said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The political obituary of the tenacious Yeltsin, 67, has been
written and erased before. But perhaps never has Yeltsin done so
much to compose it himself as he has in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   His abrupt firing of the government Sunday was widely viewed
here as capitulation to forces increasingly beyond the aging
president's control: Russia's powerful tycoons, a still untamed
post-Soviet economy and a troublesome opposition parliament led by
the Communists.
</P>
<P>
   In uncharacteristic form, Yeltsin stooped Monday to acknowledge
the presidential mettle of another Russian.
</P>
<P>
   In televised remarks, Yeltsin stated that acting Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin may be the best candidate to succeed him when
Yeltsin's presidential term expires in 2000. He also promised to
give Chernomyrdin extraordinary autonomy to run the government.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Yeltsin forewarned not only the end of his
presidency, but the democratic vision he embodied seven years ago
as the Soviet Union collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Yeltsin bowing out. And it's the end of any meaningful
attempt in this country for reform in the near future. It's sad
really. It's a surrender,'' said Al Breach of the Russian-European
Center for Economic Policy.
</P>
<P>
   As Chernomyrdin, 60, an uncharismatic moderate, sets out to form
a new government amid economic chaos, there are signs that Yeltsin
has agreed to give up considerable powers to him and other Russian
political factions.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist speaker of the Duma, the lower house of
parliament, said political parties had agreed with Chernomyrdin to
devise plans for a new government formed on an unprecedented
``coalition basis'' -- possibly giving some senior posts to the
Communists and allowing them a hand in setting the economic agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Chernomyrdin is considered the favorite of a small
band of influential tycoons who control much of Russia's industry,
banking and media -- financial interests who have opposed economic
reforms in the past and are now threatened by the country's
deepening financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's selection of Chernomyrdin, whom he fired five months
ago, appears to be in accord with these business magnates who
helped re-elect the president during a tough campaign in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the ``oligarchy,'' they have lobbied in recent weeks
for the return of Chernomyrdin in the hopes that he will use state
money to prop up their faltering banks, many of which are on the
verge of failure and owe billions of dollars to Western lenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``For these oligarchs, the pain of true reform was like a death
sentence for their banks and investment houses. So, they made a
deal,'' said political analyst Sergei Kolmakov.
</P>
<P>
   Two prominent economic reformers close to Yeltsin, Anatoly
Chubais and Boris Nemtsov, apparently will not be part of the new
government. They were favorites of Western officials and
personified the economic thinking believed necessary to deliver a
free-market economy.
</P>
<P>
   Nemtsov, a deputy prime minister, announced his resignation on
Monday and offered a bitter assessment on Russian television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is all too difficult to carry out any reforms . . . in the
conditions of such an ugly market, where competition is
non-existent, monopolies are rampant, where rules are few,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Yeltsin went on national television in
video-taped remarks to explain his latest government overhaul,
replacing young reformer Sergei Kiriyenko after only five months on
the job. And why he was reappointing Chernomyrdin, whom he faulted
in March for failing to seek needed economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin said Chernomyrdin possess ``decency, honesty, and
thoroughness,'' adding: ``I think these qualities will be the
decisive argument in the presidential elections.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments provoked widespread speculation in Moscow that
Yeltsin may resign before the end of his term, though Yeltsin has
confounded such predictions many times in the past. ``Early
elections are necessary ... If Chernomyrdin wins the approval of
the Duma, he becomes the real master of the state and Yeltsin
becomes more of a figurehead in the background,'' said Kolmakov.
</P>
<P>
   Under the constitution, Chernomyrdin would become acting
president if Yeltsin resigned or could not serve for health
reasons, and an election would be held in three months.
</P>
<P>
   Despite talk of a coalition government, the Communist Party
appeared ready to exploit the turmoil. It called on Yeltsin to
recall Chernomyrdin's nomination. The Duma announced it would not
convene to consider the government overhaul until next week at the
earliest, just as President Bill Clinton is scheduled to arrive for
a summit with Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as Yeltsin remains in power, no reshuffling will lead
the country out of crisis,'' said Gennady Zyuganov, the Communist
Party leader.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin earned his global reputation as the champion of
democracy, who jumped atop the tanks during the communist
hardliners' unsuccessful coup attempt in August 1991 and hastened
the demise of the Soviet Union later that year.
</P>
<P>
   Heart problems, a thirst for vodka and Kremlin intrigues have
taken their toll. He appeared stilted in his brief video-taped
appearance Monday.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add begins.)
</P>
<P>
   It has been an embarrassing month. Russia's financial markets
continued to tumble even as Yeltsin pursued his summer vacation in
isolation in the country's far north.
</P>
<P>
   Dismally low in opinion polls for the past year, Yeltsin emerged
last week when the financial crisis forced him to abandon his
leading achievement since his reelection in 1996: low inflation and
a stable ruble.
</P>
<P>
   On August 17, the government allowed the national currency to
drift on markets as high as 9.5 to the dollar -- in effect, a
34-percent devaluation. The new policy was a dramatic shift for the
government, which determined it could no longer afford to spend
billions of dollars of its hard-currency reserves to prop up the
ruble and place Russia deeper in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, parliament began impeachment proceedings against
Yeltsin, which Zyuganov said Monday would continue. He said the
Duma would agree to approve Chernomyrdin only if he promised
radical changes in economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   So, Yeltsin may have indicated Monday that he is prepared to
throw in the towel, but the fight is still raging. Unfortunately,
for one of the remarkable figures of this century, there are few
Russians left in his corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If another coup attempt happened now, I don't think people
would go into the street to defend Boris Nikolaiovitch (Yeltsin),''
said Yevgeny Bogdonov, a newspaper editor in the city of Kemerovo.
``Not here.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
