<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9463 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-STREET-0825-CO     08-24 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-STREET-0825-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIANS FEEL HELPLESS AND HOPELESS AMID CRISIS
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-POLITICS-0825.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES AND JULIA SHARGORODSKA 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Rioters have not stormed the Kremlin in outrage over
the sliding value of the ruble, the slow and steady rise of
consumer prices or the latest bewildering shake-up of the
government.
</P>
<P>
   There are not tanks in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, for most Russians life goes grimly on in Moscow and
elsewhere with little evidence of the shock from last week's
devaluation of the ruble and Sunday's firing of the government.
</P>
<P>
   All too familiar with economic troubles and political turnovers
since the Soviet Union collapsed in 1991, many Russians are
care-worn but ultimately resigned to a life of flirting with
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I'm worried. You can never relax very long in our
country. There is no stability,'' said Dennis Golubkov, 28, manager
of a music shop in Moscow. ``But what can we do?''
</P>
<P>
   Most Russians are insulated from the economic crisis by their
own poverty. The average Russian salary is only about $200 a month
and there is virtually no credit -- no home mortgages, car loans,
few credit cards. A recent government estimate said 77 percent of
the 147 million living in Russia have no savings.
</P>
<P>
   They also are dubious that Sunday's government overhaul
reappointing Viktor Chernomyrdin as prime minister will improve
their lives, coming as it did from Boris Yeltsin, a president they
stopped trusting long ago.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest sentiment on the street is suspicion of
politicians and their promises. For months amid the financial
turmoil, millions of workers have gone without their full pay. At
the beginning of this month, Russian workers alone, were owed $11
billion in back-wages and pension monies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general opinion is, 'It's all the same for us who is in
power. But what really matters is whether they pay our salaries or
not,''' said Vladimir Oshchenko, deputy editor of the major daily
in Vladivostok, in Russia's far east.
</P>
<P>
   Polls shows that Russians, who have a short history of
democracy, feel little connection to their government and no power
to compel it to change. Cynicism is the leading ideology.
</P>
<P>
   ``In America, if you knock, something will be done. Here, you
knock but there is no response. During the Soviet period, no matter
how badly we lived, the government took care of us in the sense
that, for example, prices were stable. Now we have to fend for
ourselves,'' said Viktor Kapranov, a 67-year-old metal worker in
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The worst could still come, as the now ex-Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko warned in a candid speech to parliament on Friday. Banks
are expected to fail. Consumer prices could soar. The ruble, which
has devalued slightly on the currency markets, could yet crash.
</P>
<P>
   Aman Tuleyev, governor of the coal-rich Kemerovo region in
southern Russia, warned that the mix of social, economic and
political instability could lead to a ``social explosion.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has given Chernomyrdin the task to assemble a new
government and study the issues at a time when Russia should be
coping with its deep financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the one thing the new government has going for it is the
profound apathy in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   In Vorkuta, in Russia's far north, Roman Yuniter, editor with
the newspaper ``Zapolyuriya,'' said two issues are on the minds of
people in the region: ``We only want to get our pay on time, and we
pray that it does not start snowing in August.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
