<SLUG> BC-DELTA25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta-UAL alliance stumbles over board seat issue
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta and United airlines trumpeted their planned
alliance last spring as a major strategic move that would marry the
two giant carriers' route systems and create ``the wave of the
aviation future.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that wave could be reduced to a ripple.
</P>
<P>
   The two airlines will have to live with a scaled-down alliance _
with joint frequent flier benefits but no ability to book
passengers on each other's flights _ unless Atlanta-based Delta and
its pilots union can make peace.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Delta's directors rejected a union demand for a
voting seat on the board in return for a contract change that would
allow the airline to code-share, or sell seats on United flights as
if they were its own.
</P>
<P>
   The union had demanded the board seat last spring as a
prerequisite to changing the contract, which prohibits code-sharing
with another big domestic airline. The company, which announced the
alliance in April, agreed to study the demand and respond this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   After being told of the rejection by Delta Chief Executive Leo
Mullin and non-executive board Chairman Gerald Grinstein, union
leaders last week ordered a committee studying the needed contract
change to stop its work.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Giambusso, the just-elected chairman of the Delta unit
of the Air Line Pilots Association, said the Delta board's
``resistance to having an employee as a full voting member of the
Delta board ... exceeded their desire to go forward with the United
alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless the impasse is broken, Delta and United can only proceed
with frequent flier elements of their alliance. On Sept. 1, they'll
begin allowing fliers on either carrier the option of accruing
miles in either carrier's program.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the very near future we will make some announcements
regarding joint redemption,'' said Delta spokeswoman Laura Gillig.
</P>
<P>
   Frequent flier cooperation alone will produce some strategic
gains. Passengers who usually fly Chicago-based United to Asia or
the western United States, where it's strongest, should be more
likely to use Delta elsewhere so they can accrue United mileage.
</P>
<P>
   But code-sharing _ a more direct way of creating cross-loyalties
between passengers of the two airlines _ has always been seen as
the heart of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that the lion's share of the strategic and
financial benefits accrue from code-sharing,'' said analyst Tom
Longman of Arnhold &AMP; S. Bliechroeder.
</P>
<P>
   The United-Delta deal was in part a competitive response to a
similar deal announced last winter between Northwest and
Continental.
</P>
<P>
   But the Northwest-Continental partnership hasn't taken effect,
Northwest is mired in labor woes of its own, and federal regulators
have yet to signal their stance on major airline alliances
generally.
</P>
<P>
   So the urgency behind the Delta-United deal has waned for the
moment, said PaineWebber analyst Samuel Buttrick. That could
contribute to Delta's unwillingness to give in on the pilot demand.
</P>
<P>
   As for the union's stance, Buttrick said he's puzzled. Board
seat or no, he said, the union can extract job security assurances
and pay boosts when the new contract language is negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an economic matter, the contract change gives the pilots
all the leverage they need,'' Buttrick said. And with just one vote
on an 11-member board, the union wouldn't be able to sway corporate
policy, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Karen McGuffey, spokeswoman for Delta's ALPA group, said the
issue isn't about voting power, but rather an equal and ongoing
voice in deliberations that will affect pilot careers. As the
alliance evolves it could lead to joint decisions about which
carrier adds or drops routes in different areas, and that would
affect both the number and type of Delta pilot jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize being one of 11 votes on the board is not going to
affect change,'' McGuffey said. ``The issue to us is one of
participation. Being a full member of the board provides access,
and that's what's critical. As the alliance moves ahead, there are
going to be decisions that affect pilot careers, and we want to
participate in that process.''
</P>
<P>
   McGuffey also said there is a question of equity.
</P>
<P>
   United's pilots union has a voting seat on parent UAL Corp.'s
board of directors. That seat was granted as part of a 1994
employee buyout in which workers gained a 55 percent stake in the
company. Delta's pilots, by contrast, have a single-digit stake in
the company. Their union is allowed to appoint a board
representative, but that member can't vote and isn't privy to all
matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of the four parties involved (the two companies and two pilots
unions), we are the only one that doesn't have a full voice at the
table,'' McGuffey said.
</P>
<P>
   ALPA made it ``crystal clear'' to Delta management last spring
the board seat was a threshold condition to any contract change,
according to union leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin, in a memo to workers last week, said the board gave the
union demand ``serious study'' but rejected it to preserve its
independence from special interest considerations. He added he
hoped union leaders, who meet at the end of this month, will
reconsider their position.
</P>
<P>
   Delta spokesman Bill Berry said the board consulted with both
legal experts and major shareholders. ``Many (shareholders) have
stated positions on board composition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Giambusso, in a letter to pilots, said the decision reflects
``our board's and management's inability to conduct business in a
non-paternalistic manner.''
</P>
<P>
   How does United view the snag? ``We think code-sharing is quite
important, and we're hopeful Delta can work out the issues with
their pilots,'' said spokesman Joe Hopkins. ``There is value in
what we are doing with the frequent flier programs ... but we would
like to go further with the rest of the alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   If code-sharing dies, speculation about other strategic moves by
Delta will likely be rekindled _ especially given that, prior to
the United alliance, Mullin had tried to buy Continental.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down the road,'' said analyst Longman, ``if Delta isn't
involved in a code-share with United, it's still going to be
looking for some form of partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
