<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9553 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROPER-RUSSIA25-COX     08-24 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROPER-RUSSIA25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia-based Roper ready to bear storm in Russia
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Officials at Georgia-based Roper Industries say they
are sufficiently protected to weather Russia's latest economic
storm but might have a harder time winning new business there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Russia and there is more risk and more uncertainty
than there is in most other markets in the world,'' said Martin
Headley, Roper's vice president and chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has been good to Roper, a company based in Bogart, near
Athens, GA, that makes analytical instruments and industrial pumps
and valves.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian company Gazprom, one of the world's largest energy
companies, is also Roper's biggest customer, bringing in $40
million in annual revenue. That's expected to equal 10 percent of
Roper's sales this year. The money has helped to fuel a number of
Roper's acquisitions in other markets. Roper has been doing
business with Gazprom since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   As it usually does with other international customers, Roper
requires payment from Gazprom in dollars. That is particularly
important in Russia, Headley said, where exchange rates for the
ruble have had wild swings.
</P>
<P>
   Roper's chief financial officer says his company is insulated
from Russia's economic troubles because Gazprom's payments are in
dollars and because the work centers on revenue from Gazprom's
business in Europe. Roper sells Gazprom compression controls, which
allow the pipelines to operate at higher pressure, thus handle an
increased flow of natural gas to markets in Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Roper does not expect the devaluation of the Russian ruble to
affect it in the short to medium term, Headley said.
</P>
<P>
   But coupled with the Russian economy's broader difficulties, the
currency problems do make it more difficult for Roper to generate
new business there, Headley said. Roper has contracts with other
Russian businesses to supply equipment _ if they have enough money
to pay Roper with dollars. None has, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Headley said it is difficult to gauge how Russia's economic
problems might affect Gazprom in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Gazprom sells much of its natural gas to Russian markets, but it
also has significant business outside the country, Headley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it ought to have some strength independent of the
Russian economy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-08-21-98 2208E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
