<HEADER>
A9556 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-GAME25-COX     08-24 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-GAME25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Video games capture pros' moves, hearts
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miami Fusion defender Cle Kooiman was a starter for the United
States in World Cup '94. But while the real U.S. team stumbled,
Kooiman's computer-generated twin went on to greater soccer glory
in Electronic Art's new video game, World Cup 98.
</P>
<P>
   That's Kooiman doing the video victory dance after the World
Cup's winning goal is scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did (that scene) once and it took me 10 minutes to calm
down,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Kooiman did that victory dance _ along with dribbling, tackling
and running _ at an Electronic Arts laboratory in Vancouver last
December. Console computer sports games require human movement if
the video players are to move realistically. The process is called
motion capture.
</P>
<P>
   Kooiman wore a stifling hot, black, rubbery body suit that
looked like it was covered with dozens of ping pong balls. He
played soccer in a dark, empty room as cameras and computers
captured his movements.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic Arts is the biggest player in the $6.6 billion video
game industry. EA Sports games for PC, PlayStation and Nintendo 64
systems cost between $40 and $60. The games feature brand-name
announcers such as Fox NFL's John Madden and in-stadium music from
groups such as Chumbawamba. And the teams are made up of real
players.
</P>
<P>
   World Cup 98 features 1,600 players that have 850 movements.
</P>
<P>
   Motion capture began about four years ago when video games began
featuring 3-D players. EA, which has been creating software since
1982, has a permanent studio that features a sod ``playing'' field
and $20 million in motion capture equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Companies such as EA don't look for marquee names for motion
capture but instead seek players who can act and can quickly
understand the process, says World Cup '98 producer Marc Aubanel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cle jumped right out as an absolute, right guy, a natural born
ham,'' says Aubanel. ``He can imagine anything that happens on the
pitch (field) and re-create it in the studio. Of all the soccer
players we've worked with, he's the most charismatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Aubanel says it's not yet feasible for computers to create
accurate human movement for video games. That's why EA, based in
San Mateo, California, seek pros such as Kooiman.
</P>
<P>
   After he was picked, Kooiman wasn't sure he could finish the
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very first day I honestly didn't think I could make it
through seven days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long process. It takes 40 minutes to hook you up in the
suit and then you start sweating like crazy,'' he recounts. ``You
do one sequence at a time, like pass the ball at a 45 degree angle.
If you don't do it right, you do it again. You can do six, seven,
eight takes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it can take the computers three to four minutes to set up
again. If a (soccer) ball hits a camera it can take an
hour-and-a-half to reconfigure it. You do this for about 10 hours a
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Golfer Tiger Woods has been playing video games for years and
knew exactly what new wrinkles he wanted when EA signed him for a
game due in the fall. For one, Woods wanted his game to play faster
than the competitors. You'll be able to play 18 holes of Tiger
Woods 99 in 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Video games are played in every Major League Baseball clubhouse,
including the Florida Marlins. Cliff Floyd, the Marlins left
fielder, plays out a whole video game season. His mid-season report
is that his video Marlins are way behind the Atlanta Braves. Sound
familiar?
</P>
<P>
   ``It relaxes me,'' says Floyd, who adds that playing baseball
for a living isn't necessarily a video advantage. ``Playing the
game puts you in the position you think you know what you're doing
and when you don't . . . whoops.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Miami Dolphins take video games on the road to ease
hotel room boredom. When wide receiver Lamar Thomas plays EA's John
Madden NFL 98, he likes to put NFL players he doesn't like on
``sorry'' teams so he can trash them.
</P>
<P>
   It can also be disconcerting when he's playing and the video
Lamar Thomas drops a pass. ``First I get mad at myself and then I
remember to get mad at the guy who made the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Kooiman admits when he plays World Cup 98 the game doesn't last
very long. He sets out to get a red card ejection for a violent
foul as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's me doing the rant against the referee,'' he says, ``I
just love seeing it.''
</P>
<P>
   REAL PROS TAKE THE FIELD IN VIDEO GAMES
</P>
<P>
   All EA sports video games use real athletes for motion capture.
When the Dolphins' Lamar Thomas' computer alter ego catches a pass
on Madden NFL 98, the movements were supplied by former San
Francisco '49ers receiver John Taylor. Linebackers Gary Plummer
(49ers) and Ken Harvey (Washington Redskins) also did motion
capture for the game.
</P>
<P>
   For EA's NCAA March Madness 98 women's basketball, Kate Starbird
of the Seattle Reign and former Florida Atlantic star Yolanda
Griffith, now with the Long Beach StingRays, did the motion
capture.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Duncan, the NBA's 1997 Rookie of the Year with the San
Antonio Spurs, was picked for men's movements for the same game.
</P>
<P>
   Boxers Sugar Ray Leonard and Oscar de la Hoya are the movement
models for EA's Knockout Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Players doing motion capture for NHL 99 include goalkeeper John
Vanbiesbrouck and center Mike Sillinger, both with the Philadelphia
Flyers, along with Vancouver Canucks players Markus Naslund,
Mattias Ohlund and Donald Brashear.
</P>
<P>
   Antoine Walker, from the Boston Celtics, is involved in NBA Live
99 . For NBA Live 98, the Miami Heat's Tim Hardaway and Mitch
Richmond of the Sacramento Kings supplied motion.
</P>
<P>
   To complement Kooiman's work for EA's World Cup games, other
Major League Soccer specialists were used, including D.C. United's
Roy Lassiter (shooting), Dallas Burn's Mark Dodd (goalkeeping) and
Kansas City Wizards Preki (trick dribbling).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
