<P>
   COKE-WENDYS _ How did Coke pull off the Wendy's coup? Wendy's
announced it would exclusively use Coke products. This in the face
of Pepsi's effort to make inroads into the fountain sales market.
What is Wendy's market share, what is effect on Pepsi, revenue to
Coke, etc.? (Gramig, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DELL-INTELCHIP _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Dell Computer Corp. will use
versions of Intel Corp.'s low-cost Celeron chip in some computers.
Don't expect Dell prices to dip below the $1,000 mark, however.
(Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TEX-BANKWOES _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The record profits for banks in
Texas look good, but lurking around the corner is an alarming drop
in the net interest margin, or spread as it's called. Sheshunoff's
managing director for community banking warns of a first-quarter
decline, to the lowest net interest margin in five years. (Golz,
Austin American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   ROPER-RUSSIA _ ATLANTA _ Officials at Georgia-based Roper
Industries say they are sufficiently protected to weather Russia's
latest economic storm but might have a harder time winning new
business there. But Russia has been good to Roper, a company based
in Bogart, near Athens, GA, that makes analytical instruments and
industrial pumps and valves. (Kempner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA _ ATLANTA _ Delta and United airlines trumpeted their
planned alliance last spring as a major strategic move that would
marry the two giant carriers' route systems and create ``the wave
of the aviation future.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that wave could be reduced to a ripple. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOMEOWNER _ ATLANTA _ Homeownership may soon be more than just a
dream to some Georgia residents. More than two dozen people are
participating in an innovative program designed to open the door to
homeownership. The IDA (the individual development account) Home
Ownership Program is similar to incentive-based savings programs
across the country and is at work in three metro Atlanta
neighborhoods. (Poole, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ When he spoke on the Monica Lewinsky
matter last week, President Clinton insisted that his private life
should remain private. Unfortunately, what the president did behind
closed doors with a former White House intern does directly involve
all of us and our wallets. (Geewax, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
(k, f)
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ The stock market is down sharply for the last few
weeks, and so are the much-loved index mutual funds that promise _
and mostly deliver _ the same returns as the indices they mimic.
(Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER-WATCH _ This is a big time of year for college students
and prepaid phone cards. Tens of thousands of students are
returning to class, and many are carrying prepaid cards with them.
The prepaid cards are very convenient but, for some of the
students, they may also serve as their No. 1 consumer lesson:
caveat emptor, let the buyer beware. (Tharpe, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT-BLOCK _ Credit card blocking: Do you know what it is?
Probably not, unless you are a seasoned traveler. But if it happens
to you unexpectedly, you might be embarrassed _ and may get mad.
(Tharpe, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BANKER-DEAD _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Robert E. Harris, president and
chief executive of the Texas Bankers Association, the largest and
oldest state banking organization in the nation, was found dead of
a heart attack Friday, August 21, in Madison, Wis. (Golz, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
