<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SCANDAL PUTS GORE ON THE GRIDDLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c. 1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As cries mount for President Clinton's resignation
or censure, Vice President Al Gore remains fiercely loyal to his
mentor despite some ominous implications for his own political
future.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been mocked for insisting he is still proud to serve
with Clinton and thinks of Clinton as a great president. Some
pundits even suggest that Gore damaged his own chances of being
elected president by being so uncritical of behavior no one else
defends.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Gore, as the Democratic heir apparent, has little
choice but to stand by the president. After nearly six years of a
close personal and political partnership, it would be neither in
Gore's nature nor his interest to waiver now.
</P>
<P>
   Like the legendary British Prime Minister Winston Churchill,
Gore understands the basic principle of loyal public service.
Churchill, once asked to turn against the Crown, stoutly replied,
``I have taken the king's shilling. I am the king's man.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats facing re-election in November are
nervously sidling away from their discredited president. But Gore's
fate is inextricably tied to Clinton's. A vice president's proper
role is to be an honorable team player, not a selfish opportunist
willing to pile on a pal when he's down.
</P>
<P>
   There will come a time after the fall elections when Gore will
have to move beyond Clinton's shadow to establish a separate
identity as a presidential candidate, on character as well as
global issues. But that time has not yet come.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's own clean family life partially insulates him from the
widespread public disgust voters register toward the president's
tawdry dalliance with Monica Lewinsky. And so far Clinton's
continuing high job-approval ratings _ in the 60 percent range _
have further spared Gore from a deadly undertow that could bring
down not only Clinton but everyone associated with him.
</P>
<P>
   In a Los Angeles Times poll last week, 73 percent of those
surveyed said the Clinton sex scandal would have no effect on their
vote for Gore in the 2000 presidential contest. Other polls show
that Gore's job-approval ratings have remained slightly over 50
percent during the entire scandal, at roughly the same level they
were before the scandal broke.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how much Gore's job-approval ratings are buoyed by
Clinton's and how much they are due to a definably favorable public
image of his own. Some polls do indicate a majority of voters see
Gore as more honest and trustworthy than Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But vice presidents traditionally benefit, or suffer, from the
fortunes of the presidents in whose shadow they labor. And Gore
does have problems, although they are still in embryonic form.
</P>
<P>
   There is, for instance, the freshness factor. If voters are sick
of Clinton's misbehavior, they may simply want to get rid of the
whole Democratic shebang, including the fellow endlessly
photographed at Clinton's side. No matter how uninformed they may
have been thus far about Gore's personality, he's a familiar figure
visibly identified with an administration that is wearing out its
welcome.
</P>
<P>
   And there is the lingering 1996 Democratic campaign fund-raising
controversy. Although congressional probes into potential
wrongdoing proved nothing materially wrong with Gore's role, a
White House memorandum recently turned up by Justice Department
investigators suggests that some of Gore's telephone solicitations
may have violated federal campaign finance laws after all.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, who had previously absolved Gore of
wrongdoing, is now examining the issue of whether a special counsel
should be appointed to look into his fund-raising activities. Under
Republican pressure, Reno also is reconsidering whether to approve
a special counsel for the entire 1996 Clinton-Gore campaign
financing operation.
</P>
<P>
   Any controversy that keeps alive the fund-raising issue is bound
to hurt Gore.
</P>
<P>
   His biggest gaffe remains his effort to explain away his
fund-raising calls by saying ``no controlling legal authority''
forbade them. He sounded as legalistically evasive as Clinton and
just as deceptive. Nor did he seem forthcoming about the nature of
a Buddhist temple fund-raiser, which he originally described as
``community outreach.''
</P>
<P>
   He is once again raising campaign money by the carload, but he
is highly vulnerable to further partisan scrutiny in this area.
</P>
<P>
   The closer he gets to the throne room, in fact, the fatter a
target he becomes for political arrows from others who would like
to be president as well.
</P>
<P>
   As a discreet vice president of greater indirect influence than
his predecessors but with little real power, Gore has been able to
maintain a low profile with relatively little controversy.
</P>
<P>
   But all that changes dramatically if Clinton is censured by
Congress and becomes unable to function effectively as president,
making both himself and his vice president look like failures. Or
if Clinton resigns and Gore becomes the incumbent president,
burdened with the previous administration's record and no electoral
base of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment is the least likely scenario, given that the House
Judiciary Committee may not be able to publicly take up the task,
if at all, until next spring. The next presidential election could
be practically upon us by the time Clinton faced imminent danger of
being ousted that way.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Gore would have no control over the major
events shaping his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe political satirist Mark Russell has the ultimate ironic
answer to Gore's fate. ``Bill Clinton is so slick,'' Russell jokes,
``they'll impeach Gore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
