<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK TRUFFLES: VIVA VARIETY  
 PRE-COLUMBIAN ULCERS  
 EXPANDING UNIVERSE  
 FLAWED MERCURY MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Md.)  (js) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   That culinary delicacy, the black truffle, may be relatively
rare and expensive these days, but pity the poor cave man: the
supply appears to have all but shriveled up around 10,000 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   That is the hypothesis of a trio of researchers (from France,
naturally) who studied black truffles with an eye to understanding
why they vary in flavor and aroma. In a brief article in Nature,
they report that the fungi, which are found among tree roots, show
almost no genetic variation across the species. This contrasts
sharply with burgundy and summer truffles, which vary greatly.
</P>
<P>
   Genetic sameness can often be linked to a population bottleneck,
an event that kills most of a species, leaving a relative handful
of specimens (and a correspondingly small gene pool) to carry on.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the other two varieties, the black truffle ripens in
winter, and can be killed by a cold snap. The researchers theorize
that the truffle's population bottleneck came in the last Ice Age _
that cold snap of epochal proportions, which ended about 100
centuries ago _ when European forests were greatly reduced.
</P>
<P>
   They conclude that differences in the perfume and taste of black
truffles are probably due to environmental conditions and suggest
further research to identify the specific influences. Well,
somebody has to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-Columbian Ulcers
</P>
<P>
   While shedding tears for the truffleless cave men of Europe,
save some sympathy for the mountain dwellers of pre-Columbian South
America. Some of them, it turns out, may have had stomach ulcers.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Pelayo Correa, a pathologist at Louisiana State University,
detected antigens for Helicobacter pylori, the bacteria at the root
of peptic ulcers, in stool samples from Andean mummies. Correa used
a new test designed to detect infection in living people, but it
proved effective in remains that were up to 1,800 years old. His
findings are the earliest evidence of H.pylori infection in humans.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding Universe
</P>
<P>
   Current thinking that there is not enough mass in the universe
to stop it from expanding forever has received support from the
seemingly paradoxical discovery of a huge mass in space: a cluster
of thousands of galaxies containing trillions of stars.
</P>
<P>
   The cluster, found by Megan Donahue and others at the Space
Telescope Science Institute in Baltimore, is 8 billion light-years
from earth. In addition to its great mass, it is incredibly hot _
the gas between galaxies is calculated to be 300 million degrees
Fahrenheit. The presence of such a massive cluster so far away, and
thus so far back in time, suggests that the cluster did most of its
accumulating when the universe was relatively young, and has since
slowed its growth.
</P>
<P>
   This finding runs counter to the theory of a dense universe that
could eventually collapse upon itself. If there was a lot of mass
around to be accumulated, clusters of galaxies would grow
continuously, and the most massive ones would have been growing
longest. It would be highly unlikely to find one so early in time.
</P>
<P>
   But a cluster that has grown relatively quickly and then slowed
supports the opposite idea, that the universe is relatively
lightweight, without the critical mass that would allow clusters to
grow steadily or prevent its own eternal expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Flawed Mercury Measure Mercury, the element, not the planet, is
one of the world's great environmental poisons. It accumulates in
the food chain, starting in plankton and building up through ever
larger sea creatures to wind up in humans, where it is toxic to the
nervous system. The amount of mercury from industrial processes and
the burning of coal and solid waste has long been a concern.
</P>
<P>
   Now U.S. and French researchers have shown that one important
barometer of mercury pollution, measurements of the amount of the
metal found in the Greenland ice cap in the 1970s, was too high.
Where tests of snow samples two decades ago found mercury
concentrations as high as 800 parts per trillion, the new studies,
of samples from 1949 to 1989, found concentrations below two parts
per trillion. Apparently the older testing methods contaminated the
samples.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
