<HEADER>
A9570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESERVATION-BOOK-REVI     08-24 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESERVATION-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RESERVATION ROAD': COMPELLING READING, DESPITE ITS JERRY-BUILT
PLOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(lh) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cover of John Burnham Schwartz's new novel, ``Reservation
Road,'' depicting a country gas station, is reminiscent, in a crude
way, of Edward Hopper's famous 1940 painting ``Gas.'' There is
something lonely and haunted about the picture, a sense of
isolation, even impending menace.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does the gas station in the painting play a pivotal
role in this psychological thriller _ it is the place where
10-year-old Josh Learner is struck and killed by a hit-and-run
driver _ but the painting's mood of brooding loss also underscores
the novel's haunting evocation of the precariousness of ordinary
life.
</P>
<P>
   What happens in the opening pages of ``Reservation Road'' is
this: The Learners are returning from a concert to their home in
upstate Connecticut when they stop at a local gas station. A
speeding car suddenly careers around a bend, striking Josh, who is
standing at the side of the road. He is killed instantly, but the
car continues on its way as Josh's father, Ethan, tries, in vain,
to give chase. The remainder of the novel is devoted to chronicling
the emotional fallout of this awful accident on both the Learner
family, and on Dwight Arno, the hit-and-run driver responsible for
Josh's death.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Reservation Road'' marks a huge departure in subject
matter and tone from Schwartz's first novel, ``Bicycle Days''
(1989) _ a comic Bildungsroman about a young American trying to
begin a new life in Japan _ the two novels share an emotional
density of experience and a writerly concern with language and
domestic detail. In fact, it is Schwartz's authoritative depiction
of his characters' inner lives _ their efforts to come to terms
with Josh's death and their own feelings of guilt, anger and grief
_ that makes this novel so compelling to read, despite its somewhat
jerry-built plot.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting back and forth between the voices of Ethan Learner and
Dwight Arno, Schwartz meticulously depicts the immediate aftermath
of Josh's death. The Learners' stunned disbelief that ``one minute
there is a boy, a life thrumming with possibilities, and the next
there are marked cars and strangers in uniform and the fractured
whirling lights.'' And Dwight's equally stunned realization that in
a brief second he has become a murderer, the inadvertent thief of a
child's life, a boy the same age as his son, Sam.
</P>
<P>
   While Dwight toys with the idea of allowing himself to be caught
by the police, he knows, as a lawyer, that his own dubious past
will probably be held against him: Years before, when his wife Ruth
announced that she was leaving him, he attacked her with his fists,
and broke the jaw of Sam, who was trying to keep his parents apart.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight tells Sam, who was asleep in the car when the accident
occurred, that they hit a dog on their way home, and he puts the
car, with a tell-tale bit of Josh's jacket caught on its smashed
right headlight, into the garage and shuts the door.
</P>
<P>
   The Learners' lives, meanwhile, have shattered into a before and
after. Ethan, who teaches English at a small New England college,
vacillates between rage at the police for not doing more to catch
the man who killed his son, and sharp, aching grief, as he replays
memories of his son in his head. Grace Learner has sunk into a
state of anguished numbness, unable to work and unable to forgive
her husband, whom she blames for failing to keep Josh safe. As for
their 8-year old daughter, Emma, she blames herself for her
brother's death. After all, she reasons, she was the one who
insisted on stopping at the gas station (to use the bathroom) in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in lyrical, carefully hammered prose, Schwartz does a
sensitive job of showing us the mathematics of loss as they apply
to both the Learners and to Dwight, a man depicted not as your
usual villain, but as an unlucky, frustrated individual devoted to
his son and eager to make up to him all the hurt he has already
inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to orchestrating the thrillerlike aspects of this
novel, however, Schwartz is decidedly clumsier. Though
``Reservation Road'' is highly suspenseful, its author's efforts to
put Dwight and Ethan on a collision course often feel highly
synthetic. He repeatedly makes portentous references to Dwight's
violent temper, and he occasionally has Ethan step out of character
to utter such theatrical remarks as ``I was a hard wronged man with
a mission'' or ``without hope, the need to punish is the one true
religion.''
</P>
<P>
   As the novel speeds toward its melodramatic conclusion, the
coincidences, too, begin to proliferate: it just so happens that
Dwight's ex-wife is Emma's music teacher, and it just so happens
that Ethan runs into Sam, who tells him about the night his
father's car hit a dog. No doubt we are meant to believe that such
uncanny events could easily happen in a small town, but as
delineated in ``Reservation Road'' they feel hokey and contrived
and in retrospect they cast a small but lingering shadow over what
is otherwise a powerful and affecting novel.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `RESERVATION ROAD'
</P>
<P>
   By John Burnham Schwartz
</P>
<P>
   292 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
