u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SACKS-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-24 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SACKS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OLIVER SACKS: THE MIND TRAVELER': ON BEING HUMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Wash.)  (Eds: Broadcast notes at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only Oliver Sacks would have the wit to alert readers of
``Seeing Voices'' (one of his early books, about the deaf) that the
footnotes are ``mental or imaginative excursions, to be taken, or
avoided, as the reader-traveler chooses.'' Those footnotes are
mini-essays, always worth the detour. More to the point, no one has
better defined Sacks' writing. A neurologist and dazzling essayist,
he creates travelogues of the best sort: forays into the human mind
and personality.
</P>
<P>
   In the PBS series ``Oliver Sacks: The Mind Traveler,'' he turns
to a different form. Yet these absorbing documentaries remain
imaginative excursions. Sacks takes viewer-travelers along as he
examines the peculiar, sometimes magical-seeming ways in which the
brain works.
</P>
<P>
   The four-part series begins Tuesday night with ``The Ragin'
Cajun,'' about a man with Usher's syndrome, a condition in which
people are born deaf and become progressively blind from
adolescence. On the next three Tuesdays Sacks goes to a Pacific
atoll where part of the population is born colorblind, visits a
talented autistic painter and meets an 8-year-old girl with
Williams syndrome, in which a flair for social skills and music
coexists with limited ability to deal with numbers.
</P>
<P>
   On screen, Sacks is a genial, curious guide, with his Santa
Claus beard, precise British accent and large supply of T-shirts
and hats from the New York Botanical Garden. These are
straightforward documentaries, with no visual flash-and-dazzle.
They are not poetic and not nearly as philosophical as his
deservedly best-selling books (including ``An Anthropologist on
Mars'').
</P>
<P>
   His literary qualities are replaced by the close-up experience
of meeting the people he examines. It would seem off-base to call
them subjects. Sacks always views them not merely as case studies
but as individuals with winning personalities, whose differences
from the rest of us shed light on the essence of what it means to
be human.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's episode focuses on Danny, the chef in a Seattle
restaurant called the Ragin' Cajun. He was born in a Louisiana
county with a high incidence of Usher's syndrome, a result of
isolation and inbreeding going back so many generations that his
parents were unaware of those factors.
</P>
<P>
   Danny and several friends, all of whom use sign language
eloquently, have moved to Seattle, where there are better services
and acceptance of the deaf and blind. In this ``migration,'' Sacks
finds ``a portrait of a community.'' And though he examines the
physiology of Usher's, the condition is equally important for what
it tells him about the fierce need to communicate. As they lose
their ability to see, adults with Usher's syndrome are in danger of
losing their native language. Yet they learn to feel the hand
motions of signing and even to discern emotion according to the
tension in the speaker's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Danny is the perfect Sacks subject: At 35 he is a smiling,
good-looking man with a ponytail. But he now has tunnel vision, and
in 10 years will most likely be blind. As in Sacks' books, there is
no condescension or sentimentality in his attitude. But there may
be an element of self-fulfilling prophecy in his choice of
examples, as he focuses on people who are flourishing and
accomplished in at least one direction, however limited they may be
in others.
</P>
<P>
   That is also true of ``Rage for Order,'' the third episode and
one of the best, about a 37-year-old autistic woman named Jessy.
She lives with her parents, a physicist and a writer. We meet her
when two of her paintings are put on display at the National Arts
Club in Manhattan. The canvases depict houses and skies with a
hyperreal flatness and a distinct sense of pastel, rainbow colors.
</P>
<P>
   Jessy has obsessions that help her order her world: she has been
fixated on refrigerators and on bank fees for using ATMs. And she
has an elaborate system for painting suns, in which the number of
rays are good or bad, and colors equal foods. She has created rice
suns and licorice suns, whose colors have no relation to the actual
foods.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at her painting of a night sky filled with accurately
rendered constellations, Sacks says, ``For a minute I was tempted
to equate these dark vacuums with some inner empty state that was
Jessy's, but the force of her presence discouraged such an easy way
out.'' Instead, he asks unanswerable questions: ``How much is Jessy
the product of her autism? How much has she been shaped by her
parents?'' He wonders, ``Who is Jessy?'' The episode, as he
suggests, is a display of her fascinating, engaging personality.
</P>
<P>
   With one exception, this series does not echo published
material. Next week's episode presents the journey that is the
basis of Sacks' most recent book, ``The Island of the Colorblind.''
Knut Nordby, a Norwegian scientist born colorblind, accompanies
Sacks to Pingelap, where one in 12 people share his condition. This
episode leads to the not-exceptional conclusion that different
cultures have different standards of normalcy.
</P>
<P>
   And it includes the series' oddest segment, in which Sacks
becomes obsessed with finding the perfect indigo, a color he once
experienced in a mild drug-induced state in the '60s. His search
makes the point that color comes from the mind as well as the eye,
and hints at crosscurrents in the series. Sacks' search suggests
his own rage for order, so different from Jessy's yet so
fundamentally part of the human psyche.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `OLIVER SACKS: THE MIND TRAVELER'
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday at 9 p.m. ET on PBS (Channel 13 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Robin Brightwell, executive producer; Chris Rawlence, producer
and director; William Grant, executive in charge. A production of
Channel 13/WNET and the BBC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
