<P>
   N A T I O N A L &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FIGHTER-MARINES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The joint strike fighter program, which is supposed
to produce a new aircraft that can be adapted for the Air Force,
Marines and Navy, has picked up new flak on its radar. The Marine
Corps has told the defense titans competing to build the aircraft _
Lockheed Martin and Boeing _ that current designs are not
satisfactory. The Marines Corps expects its version of the plane to
replace the AV-8B Harrier II, a fighter that can take off and land
vertically. By MICHAEL D. TOWLE. Story will move in ``w''
Washington category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BIBLE-SINAI SITE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GRAPEVINE, Texas _ Colorado adventurer Bob Cornuke and his
partner, Larry Williams, were stunned by what they saw on the Saudi
Arabian mountain that they believe is the true Mount Sinai. The duo
had forged a letter, crawled under wire fences in the sizzling
desert and eluded soldiers at a nearby Saudi military outpost _ all
for this moment. They were awed by what Cornuke said was the
``unnaturally scorched'' peak of Jabal al Lawz. According to the
Bible, fire rained down when God delivered to Moses the two stone
tablets containing the Ten Commandments. By SUSAN GILL VARDON.
Story will move in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STARR-TEXAS ROOTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ To understand the drive and perseverance of
Kenneth Starr _ whose investigation of presidential improprieties
has delved too deeply, taken too long and cost too much, according
to many polls _ you have to examine his Texas roots, friends say. A
glimpse of Starr's formative years presents a picture that meshes
little with the White House's portrayal of him as a relentless, if
not brutal, and politically motivated inquisitor. By BARRY
SHLACHTER. Story has moved in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCANDALS-TRUTH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Two columnists from The Boston Globe resign under
allegations of fabricating stories. A major news network (CNN) and
newsmagazine (Time) jointly retract a story. The president of the
United States confesses on national television that he ``misled''
the American people about his relationship with a former White
House intern. Truth, it seems, is taking a beating. By MATTHEW
BRADY. Story will move in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEXUAL ABUSE-BISHOPS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ The nation's 60 million Roman Catholics continue to be
embarrassed by revelations of priests accused of sexual abuse of
minors. But despite major efforts by U.S. Catholic bishops to
address the problem, it doesn't seem to be going away. By JIM
JONES. Story will move in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
