<HEADLINE>
A HINT OF THE EXOTIC FOR FALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is a chapter in the fall fashion story devoted
to romance, to exotic embroideries and patterns inspired by foreign
cultures. The resulting clothing has an ethnic feeling but is never
a literal interpretation of a country's mode of dress. It's a
refreshing alternative to the new season's daily uniform of sweater
and pants.
</P>
<P>
   There's a hint of India in the subtle trimming on shift dresses
by Tocca (starting at $250) and a bohemian attitude to the printed
silk scarves trimmed with velvet and fringe from Voyage (starting
at $550) at Bergdorf Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   Saks Fifth Avenue has dresses with Indian-inspired embroidery by
Plenty ($135), Anna Pia ($295), Laundry by Shelli Segal ($130) and
Vivienne Tam (from $215).
</P>
<P>
   Mexican accents at Neiman Marcus include what Tracy Feith calls
``fiesta'' skirts in silky crinkled fabrics with beads and fringe
($200 to $225). Neiman Marcus also has Ms. Tam's Day of the Dead
T-shirt and sleeveless dress, with skeleton motifs ($165 to $255).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
