<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9590 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     08-24 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV30-(700)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VACATION RECIPE: STUDY COOKING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 30) 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's one thing to seek good food on vacation. Increasingly
though, cookbooks are replacing guidebooks as travelers take to the
stove.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of merely spending a few nights at a farmhouse inn in
Tuscany, or ensconced in a charming village in Provence and dining
in the local cafes, travelers are signing up for cooking classes in
these places. In the 1998 edition of ``The Guide to Cooking
Schools,'' published by Shaw Guides of New York ($19.95), there
were 270 vacation cooking courses listed, triple the number in
1989, when the guide was first published. (Although the guide does
not evaluate the schools, it is an excellent source of information;
it is also available, regularly updated, on the Web, at
www.shawguides.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Options now range from a few demonstrations by chefs on a cruise
ship to intensive experiences, including the opportunity to do some
heavy lifting in a Michelin three-star kitchen in France. There are
courses given by celebrity cooks, and serious technical courses in
established schools like the Cordon Bleu in Paris. The cost of most
programs is in the $2,000 range for five to seven days, not
including transportation.
</P>
<P>
   There are more programs in the cities and countryside of France
and Italy than elsewhere, but you can often choose your destination
first, then find a course. Cooking vacations can now be arranged in
more than two dozen countries, several as far-flung as Brazil,
Oman, Thailand and Japan, where Elizabeth Andoh teaches one- to
four-session courses in home-style cooking in Tokyo. Visits to many
American vacation spots like New England, Hawaii and the California
wine country can also be combined with cooking classes.
</P>
<P>
   Vacation is the critical term. A basic requirement is a
well-equipped kitchen with an overhead mirror, but the setting and
locale are significant factors. Some courses are held in
particularly alluring settings in the midst of historical and
cultural attractions. Provence, where Patricia Wells teaches in her
beautifully restored 18th-century farmhouse, is one such example.
Another is Lorenza de'Medici's school at Badia a Coltibuono, a
beautiful residence and winery in a former monastery near Siena.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of where you visit, selecting a program featuring the
local cuisine will enhance the experience. Larraine Stroman of
Dallas, who took the course at the Domaine de la Fontaine in the
lovely small Provencal town of L'Isle-sur-la-Sorgue, said, ``It was
a great way to learn about regional foods,'' even though she
admitted that she began to tire of eggplant recipes after a week.
Jane Butel's course in Albuquerque takes students through the vast
range of chilies, from tame to inflammatory.
</P>
<P>
   Taking cooking classes is also a good way to meet people who
share interests, making them ideal for single travelers. Of course,
many couples take them together.
</P>
<P>
   The best courses are hands on, not merely demonstrations, and
they vary in intensity. Some involve cooking all day, while others
offer side trips, visits to markets and free time.
</P>
<P>
   Ask about the level of instruction, class size, and whether each
student has a work station. Request sample recipes. If the
instructor has written a cookbook, buy it for a better idea of the
teacher's approach. Though the idea of taking classes given by
well-known chefs may sound exciting, bear in mind that professional
chefs are often not the best teachers, nor are their recipes always
easy to replicate at home. Ask for names of students to contact for
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Another consideration is the time of year a course is offered.
Many courses are excuses to fill hotels and inns during the off
season. Do you really want to go on a cooking vacation in Hawaii in
August or one near Yosemite National Park in March? On the other
hand, fall _ white truffle season _ would be an added enticement
for northern Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Though some courses can be reserved on fairly short notice,
those with well-known cooks and authors, like Marcella Hazan and
Giuliano Bugialli, tend to be booked months, even years, in
advance. But they have waiting lists. And people cancel.
</P>
<P>
   Before signing up, determine what kind of lodging is available
and whether it's included in the price. Are all meals and any side
trips part of the program? Does the school accommodate noncooking
companions, or if not, what kind of lodging can be arranged nearby?
Will you be met at an airport or train station? Do you need a car?
Are credit cards accepted?
</P>
<P>
   And if you plan to take your own knives to the school _ some
prefer it _ check them in your luggage or give them, well-wrapped,
to airline personnel so they won't be confiscated. You'll get them
back when the flight lands.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of schools in the United States and abroad:
</P>
<P>
   A La Bonne Cocotte: A few years ago Lydie Marshall, a veteran
Manhattan cooking instructor, began giving her course from April to
October at her home in France, a small chateau in Nyons, near
Avignon. Students in the intimate (maximum of eight), hands-on
classes can be assured of learning to cook delicious French food
that they will be able to reproduce at home. The five-day course is
$1,500, including lodging in the chateau _ there are three doubles
and two single rooms. For information: (212) 675-7736; from April
through October: (33-4) 75.26.45.31, fax (33-4) 75.26.09.31.
</P>
<P>
   The Apple Farm: Sally and Don Schmitt, the former owners of The
French Laundry, an esteemed restaurant in Yountville, Calif., in
the Napa Valley, have joined forces with their daughter and
son-in-law, Karen and Tim Bates. Their new headquarters is a
working organic farm and orchard in Philo, Calif., in Mendocino
County. Hands-on weekend cooking classes are held in a large
country-style kitchen 10 to 12 times throughout the year. The cost
is $200, including all meals but no accommodations; phone and fax
(707) 895-2461.
</P>
<P>
   Ballymaloe Cookery School: Darina Allen, whose in-laws own
Ballymaloe, a lovely estate in the south of Ireland near Cork, has
developed what was a sideline into a full-time occupation. Many of
the courses are for professionals, but there are a few one-week and
weekend classes for amateurs from April to mid-July; specialized
topics range from baking Irish breads to preparing seafood. There
are visits to markets, cheesemakers and a whisky distillery.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Schwartz of East Hampton, N.Y., who took a three-day
course last spring, said she especially liked the fact that she and
her husband, Robert, were the only Americans in the class of about
40. ``It was worth it for the experience of being more than just a
tourist,'' she said. Costs range from about $300 for a weekend
course, not including accommodations, to about $2,925 for a week,
with lodging at luxurious Ballymaloe House. Contact Tim Allen,
(353-21) 646-785, fax (353-21) 646-909.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking With Friends in Franc: Perhaps some of Julia Child's
magic will rub off. This course is given at Domaine de Bramafam
near Grasse in the south of France, the property that Ms. Child and
Simone Beck once owned. The course is run by Kathie Alex, whose
mentor was Ms. Beck. The cost is $1,850 for six days, including
rooms in private houses on the grounds. For information: Jackson &AMP;
Company, Boston, (617) 350-3837, fax (617) 247-6149.
</P>
<P>
   Cuisine International: This Dallas company is the American
booking agent for many of the better-known programs in Italy,
France and other countries. Judy Ebrey, the owner, researches the
courses she handles carefully, making her company a reliable
resource. Among those she offers are the Villa Table, Ms.
de'Medici's school in Italy; the World of Regaliali, Anna Tasca
Lanza's excellent program in central Sicily; Mas de Cornud in
St.-Remy-de-Provence, France; French cooking at Raymond Blanc's
luxurious Manoir aux Quat'Saisons near Oxford, England, which
includes rooms at the Manoir; and lively classes by Yara Castro
Roberts at her Brazilian Academy of Cooking in Ouro Preto, about
140 miles north of Rio de Janiero. Call (214) 373-1161, fax (214)
373-1162.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliano Bugialli's Cooking in Florence: Among the acknowledged
experts, Giuliano Bugialli has been conducting weeklong classes in
Italy for 25 years. Recently, his scope has broadened beyond
Tuscany to include trips to other parts of Italy. His regular
classes are in a newly equipped villa in the Chianti region, in
September and at Christmas. Most programs are $3,500, including
lodging and all meals, $2,700 for those not taking classes; (212)
813-9552, fax (212) 486-5518.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Butel's Cooking School: Vibrant Southwestern cooking is the
specialty of Ms. Butel, an experienced teacher who runs her program
at La Posada de Albuquerque, a lovely, historic hotel in the old
part of Albuquerque. Weekend and one-week classes are $695 and
$1,695, including accommodations and most meals; (800) 472-8229,
fax (505) 243-8297.
</P>
<P>
   John C. Campbell Folk School: Established in 1925, this school,
on a 380-acre campus in Brasstown, in the mountains of western
North Carolina, specializes in courses in crafts and folk music but
has weeklong and weekend classes in gathering and preparing wild
foods. A more elaborate teaching kitchen, including a wood-fired
oven, is under construction. Weeklong classes are $258, plus $223
to $300 for rooms _ ranging from dormitories to doubles with
private bath _ and family-style meals. There is also camping ($48
for tents and $76 for recreational vehicles), with meals extra;
(800) 365-5724, fax (704) 837-8637.
</P>
<P>
   La Cucina al Focolare: Based in Boulder, Colo., the school has
run a popular program in San Donato in Fronzano, in Tuscany, for
six years, and now has a program in Tellaro, a fishing village in
Liguria, where an intensive class in seafood is taught by a
French-trained chef, Angelo Cabani. The cost for either course is
$2,250 to $3,200 depending on accommodations; (800) 988-2851, fax
(303) 440-8598.
</P>
<P>
   La Cuisine de Provence: In L'Isle-sur-la-Sorgue, Domaine de la
Fontaine receives students for weeklong hands-on classes taught by
Jean-Claude Aubertin in October and in April. There is considerable
emphasis placed on the region's history and tradition. The fee,
including meals, excursions and lodging, is $2,195, and $1,995 for
a noncooking companion. This company also runs two schools in
Tuscany, L'Amore di Cucina Italiana and a strictly kosher school,
La Cucina Kasher in Toscana, conducted under rabbinical
supervision, in spring and fall. For information, contact Inland
Services, (212) 687-9898.
</P>
<P>
   La Varenne at the Greenbrier: As cooking schools in resorts go,
this one, taught by Anne Willan at the vast, historic property in
White Sulfur Springs, W.Va., is one of the most serious. Though
most of the instruction is demonstration in a comfortable,
extremely well-equipped classroom, students have the opportunity to
participate in the preparation for an extra fee. The five-day
program is $2,000 plus tax, including lodging, meals and use of the
hotel's recreational facilities. Contact Riki Senn (800) 228-5049,
fax (304) 536-7893.
</P>
<P>
   L'Ecole des Chefs: This is a new program of five- or six-day
working apprenticeships for nonprofessionals in 17 Michelin two-
and three-star restaurants in France, including seven in Paris, a
pastry shop and a catering service. Knowledge of French is not
required. Some culinary experience is recommended, a detailed
application must be completed and acceptance is not guaranteed. The
price is $1,950 in a two-star restaurant, $2,450 in a three-star,
including meals but not lodging or air fare; (610) 469-2500, fax
(610) 469-0272.
</P>
<P>
   Thai Cooking School at the Oriental, Bangkok: What do you do on
a steamy morning in Bangkok when the thought of bucking the traffic
is too daunting? You can ferry across the Chao Phraya from the
elegant Oriental Hotel to a complex of white and green buildings,
one of which houses a well-run, beautifully presented program of
authentic Thai home cooking. First, students learn the ingredients,
then move to to cooking. Single sessions are $120, and there is a
Sunday-to-Thursday program for $2,928 a person ($3,576 a couple),
double occupancy, including a room at the Oriental, daily
breakfast, one dinner and a massage; (800) 526-6566.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
