s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$AVD30-NYT     08-24 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$AVD30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL Q&AMP;A: SEARCHING FOR NESSIE; MAUI DAY HIKES; CASTLES IN
CATALONIA  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 30) 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SUZANNE MacNEILLE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My 12-year-old son is obsessed with the Loch Ness monster, so
I have decided to take him to the source next month. Can you
provide information on what Nessie-themed tours or sites there are
in Drumnadrochit, Scotland? _ Sam Payne, Newport, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   A: It has been described as resembling everything from a dragon
to a giant sturgeon, but whatever it may or may not be, Nessie, the
legendary inhabitant of Loch Ness, attracts tens of thousands of
tourists each year. Many of the monster sightings have been near
your destination, the tiny village of Drumnadrochit on the northern
side of the lake, about 15 miles from Inverness in the Scottish
Highlands. That is where you'll find the greatest concentration of
Loch Ness monster sites, as well as shops selling everything from
stuffed Nessies to refrigerator monster magnets.
</P>
<P>
   Local historians say the first recorded sighting of the beast
was by the Christian missionary St. Columba in 565. In 1886 the
Inverness Courier noted the ``local tradition of a strange fish in
the Loch.'' Some 50 years later newspapers throughout Britain
carried reports of a surging mass of water in the center of the
23-mile-long loch created by an enormous animal rolling and
plunging. One of the most recent sightings was reported on June 1,
following 11 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, high-tech investigations involving submarines,
sonar and underwater video cameras have neither proved nor
disproved Nessie's existence.
</P>
<P>
   In Drumnadrochit, you'll find two major exhibitions on the lake
and the monster. At the Official Loch Ness Monster Exhibition,
which is housed in a former Victorian hotel in the center of
Drumnadrochit, a 40-minute presentation uses video, photographs,
music, narration and dramatic lighting to describe the geology,
history and legends surrounding the 800-foot-deep lake, whose basin
was carved out by glaciers some 300 million years ago; it is the
largest body of fresh water in Britain. Ample time is devoted to
the myths surrounding Nessie and the various attempts to locate
her. Exhibits include the John Murray, a sonar research vessel used
in search of the monster in the 1970s. The center is open from 9:30
a.m. to 8:30 p.m.; admission is $7.60 (figured at a rate of 59
pence to the dollar), $4.25 for children. From late October to next
spring, the center will be partly closed for renovations.
Information: (44-1456) 450573.
</P>
<P>
   Next door is the Original Loch Ness Visitor Center, where you
can view another multimedia presentation, as well as photographs of
the creature (probably faked, a spokesman for the center says).
Admission is $6, $4.65 for children. The center is part of the Loch
Ness Lodge Hotel, a 350-year-old 60-room inn with modern double
rooms available for $119, including breakfast. Information and
reservations: (44-1456) 450342, fax (44-1456) 450429.
</P>
<P>
   The winding one-mile-wide lake, rimmed by forested hills and
glens, is an attraction in itself. Among the sightseeing cruises
available is an hourlong trip on the Deepscan research vessel,
which carries up to 12 people and departs hourly in the spring,
summer and fall from 10:30 a.m. through 5 p.m. Besides learning
about the Nessie legend from well-informed guides, you'll pass the
imposing ruins of the 500-year-old Urquhart Castle; about two miles
southeast of Drumnadrochit, it is open to visitors (admission is
$6). The cost of the cruise is $13.50; $8.50 for children. The trip
can be booked at both exhibition sites mentioned above.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, contact the Highlands of Scotland Tourist
Board, Post Office Box 9, Dunoon, Argyll PA23 8QQ; (44-1997)
421160.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm looking for companies offering guided day hikes on Maui.
Can you help? _ Susan Wolff, New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A: Here are two possibilities:
</P>
<P>
   Hike Maui has a variety of half-day and full-day hikes on the
island; most are described as moderate hikes, meaning they are
suitable for people in reasonable physical shape. Prices range from
$75 to $115 and include snacks and sandwiches. Participants are
transported by van to trail heads; during the trip _ which,
depending on the itinerary, could last up to two hours _ guides
lecture on the geology, flora and fauna of the volcanic island. For
example, a seven-hour three-mile hike along the arid coastline
above La Perouse Bay costs $90, $70 for children 15 and under.
Snorkeling equipment is included. Information: (808) 879-5270, fax
(808) 876-0308.
</P>
<P>
   Soul Journeys to Paradise, which organizes kayaking, driving and
hiking trips, has a Haleakala Hiking tour that lasts six to eight
hours and covers eight miles. Participants start at an altitude of
8,000 feet and hike into the Haleakala Crater. The cost is $79 and
includes transportation to the trail, lunch and snacks.
Information: (888) 232-3601 or (888) 345-7685.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you know of a Spanish organization that offers tours to a
group of private castles in Catalonia? _ Janice P. Mincks, New
York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A: You're probably thinking of the Castle Cultural Foundation of
Catalonia, a relatively new foundation committed to preserving 77
privately owned castles, most of them in the region of Catalonia in
eastern Spain. Only four of the castles are open throughout the
year (except in August), although the owners of the majority of the
castles will participate in the second annual ``open door'' visit
on Sept. 27, when free guided tours are scheduled at 11 a.m., 12:30
a.m., 4 p.m. and 5:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Among the four that are open year round is the 11th-century
Montsonis Castle, in the village of the same name, 36 miles
northeast of the provincial capital of Lerida. The idea for the
foundation was conceived in 1991 by the castle's owner, Baron
Carlos Montoliu. His 30-room palace is five stories tall and has a
former prison and a secret escape passageway. Montoliu, a corn and
alfalfa farmer, lives there with his family.
</P>
<P>
   Montclar Castle, about 15 minutes away, and two castles in the
nearby towns of Florejachs and Pallargas, also share the same
year-round schedule of guided tours, which are on Sundays at 11
a.m. and 12:30 p.m. Admission is $3.30 for each. Group visits are
held on other days, by appointment; individuals may be able to join
the groups by contacting the foundation's office in Montsonis, at
(34-973) 402 045, fax (34-973) 400 735.
</P>
</TEXT>
