<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: POSTAL HEROES; SAINTLY CANDIDATE; AZNAVOUR TOUR;
AIR-CONDITIONING EXHIBIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stamp of Approval
</P>
<P>
   The words are: Postal Service. The question is: What sort of
image do they conjure up? Those who answered ``heroic'' are on top
of today's news. Plans are in progress to broadcast a
made-for-television movie starring Louis Gossett Jr. and Jonathan
Silverman as a couple of intrepid postal inspectors tracking down a
mail bomber. The film, ``The Inspectors,'' is to be shown on the
Showtime cable network on Sept. 20. The little-known 2,200-member
investigative arm of the U.S. Postal Service traces its origins to
Benjamin Franklin and combats mail fraud, child pornography and
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Artist's Soul
</P>
<P>
   He was a great architect. Was he also a saint? The subject is
Antonio Gaudi, the Spanish modernist perhaps best known for the
towers and spires of his vast and still unfinished Sagrada Familia
Cathedral in Barcelona, Spain. Now comes word that the archbishop
of Barcelona, Ricard-Maria Cardinal Carles, with the support of the
bishops of Catalonia, has proposed the beatification of Gaudi, who
was born in 1852, spent the last 40 years of his life working on
the cathedral and died in a tram accident in 1926.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly letter, the cardinal wrote of the known and
generally unknown areas of the architect's life. ``One of these
aspects,'' he said, ``is Gaudi's intimate and spiritual life.''
</P>
<P>
   Road Trip
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ People who like to mark their calendars with special
events may want to record that 74-year-old singer, actor, composer
and songwriter Charles Aznavour is bound for Broadway, not to
overlook Los Angeles. From Oct. 21 to Nov. 3, the entertainer, who
became prominent in the 1950s with his emotional chansons and
starring roles in films like Truffaut's ``Shoot the Piano Player,''
will play 12 performances at the Marquis Theater in New York. From
Nov. 18 to 22, he'll be at the Wilshire Theater in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Space Trip
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's hot. But figuratively speaking, stay cool. For those
who are patient, the place that beckons the overheated next year is
the National Building Museum in Washington. Beginning May 1 and
continuing into the next millennium (well, Jan. 2, 2000, to be
precise), the museum will mount a major exhibition titled ``Stay
Cool! Air-Conditioning in America.'' Trumpeted as the first major
show to explore the transformative power of air-conditioning and
its impact on architecture, interior design and the way Americans
live, work and play, the exhibition will feature a series of
pertinent environments.
</P>
<P>
   These include a 1920s movie theater where millions of Americans
were introduced to air-conditioning; a centrally air-conditioned
1960s suburban living room, and an inflatable structure supported
by its own air-conditioning that will feature projects by
visionaries like Buckminster Fuller and Frank Lloyd Wright.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
