<HEADLINE>
HOYT C. HOTTEL, MIT RESEARCHER AND WEAPONS DEVELOPER; AT 95 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hoyt Clarke Hottel, a specialist on fuel and combustion who
helped develop the incendiary bomb and the flame-thrower during
World War II, died of pancreatic cancer last Tuesday in his home in
Winchester, Mass. He was 95.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hottel, a member of the faculty at Massachusetts Institute
of Technology for 40 years and director of the school's fuel
research laboratory for 35 years, was awarded a Presidential Medal
of Merit, the nation's highest civilian honor, for his
contributions to the bomb's development.
</P>
<P>
   At a chemical engineering dinner in 1992, Mr. Hottel, who was
nearly 90 at the time, poked fun at his tendency to procrastinate
by quoting pianist Victor Borge, ``Plan to die young and keep
planning,'' he said, ``just put off the act as long as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   An only child, he was born in Salem, Ind. He recalled watching
Halley's comet from his family's back yard on April 21, 1910, the
day Mark Twain died. At the time, he said, ``I thought I never
would see Halley again because it would be about 76 years.'' He
did, of course, in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hottel, who completed high school at the age of 15,
graduated from the University of Indiana and earned a master's
degree in chemical engineering at MIT in 1928, the year he joined
the school's faculty. He retired in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, when MIT instituted a Hoyt C. Hottel lecture series,
Mr. Hottel delivered the inaugural address. A chair in chemical
engineering was endowed in his name at the school in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, he helped develop the M-69 incendiary bomb,
which was used extensively in Europe and Japan. The device was
tested on a meticulously-constructed village of 32 Japanese-style
homes and 16 sturdy German-style dwellings constructed at the
Dugway Proving Grounds in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hottel visited Japan in 1961. ``They are a warm, gracious
and friendly people,'' he said in a story published in the Boston
Herald on July 1, 1962. ``They are a nation of high culture and
intellectual depth. One can't help having regrets about the way
things were and what had to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1984 he was among the 55 scientists from 13 countries who
volunteered to visit the Soviet Union as ``good-faith witnesses''
to guarantee the return of ailing dissident Yelena Bonner, if she
were allowed to leave the Soviet Union for medical treatment in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves three daughters, Lois H. Wood of Lebanon, N.H.;
Barbara H. Willis of Severna Park, Md., and Elizabeth H. Barrett of
San Diego; a son, Hoyt Jr., who is known as ``Clarke,'' of
Mattapoisett, Mass.; 10 grandchildren and 18 great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1748EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980824.0312 </DOCNO>
