<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MALARIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO BATTLES MALARIA EPIDEMIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Already devastated by forest fires and drought,
Mexico is struggling to slow a Malaria epidemic that has struck
more than 10,000 people in the southeastern state of Oaxaca, health
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Alvarez Peralta, an epidemiologist for the Pan American
World Health Organization, says an unusual combination of El
Nino-related drought followed by heavy rains along Oaxaca's coast
has caused the anopheles mosquito population _ which carries the
malaria virus _ there to explode.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, Oaxaca officials report 10,500 cases of
malaria _ compared to 565 cases all of last year. However, there
has been no reports of any deaths due to the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a situation that no one can ignore,'' Alvarez says.
</P>
<P>
   While the popular coastal towns of Huatulco and Puerto Escondido
have been affected, the U.S. Embassy here has not issued any
specific health advisory for people traveling to the areas.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez says curbing the malaria epidemic will hinge on
controlling the mosquitoes that carry the diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public health authorities there are now on a preventive
offensive, and I am sure that they will soon have things under
control,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But authorities in Oaxaca _ one of Mexico's poorest states _
admit that most of the state's funds have been used to fight
hundreds of forest fires sparked by a severe drought this Spring.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this year's epidemic, the number of cases remains low
compared to outbreaks of the disease 20 years ago, Alvarez says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to count more than 100,000 cases of malaria every
year,'' he says. ``They are really doing a very good job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
