<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Aug. 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 2 P.M. Monday, powerful hurricane Bonnie was located about
600 miles southeast of Savannah, Ga., moving slowly northwestward
at five miles per hour. Packing winds of over 100 miles per hour,
Bonnie is expected to continue its drift toward the Carolina coast
Tuesday. The only notable effects from the intense hurricane will
be unusually high surf along the Southeast coastline. Ten-foot
waves will cause dangerous rip currents and limited beach erosion
near the time of high tide. If Bonnie impacts the U.S mainland, it
would not be until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Intervals of clouds and sunshine will cover the Northeast
Tuesday. Clusters of potent thunderstorms will erupt from the Ohio
Valley to New England as a flow of sultry air intercepts an
approaching cold front. A few of these storms will contain hail and
damaging wind gusts. These thunderstorms will press east, reaching
the northern Middle Atlantic Coast toward evening. Isolated
thunderstorms will also form near the western boundary of the front
from Indiana to the northern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure and its sinking air currents will suppress clouds
over much of the Southeast, including Florida. Beneath ample
sunshine, daytime temperatures will reach the middle and upper 90s.
</P>
<P>
   Severe flooding will continue to plague portions of
south-central Texas Tuesday where the remnant moisture from
Tropical Storm Charley had led to at least four deaths since last
weekend. Elsewhere, onshore breezes will promote clouds near the
Northwest coast while abundant sunshine and seasonable warmth
covers California.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Agitating Bonnie
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Bonnie weakened slightly Monday as the mammoth storm
stalled north of the Bahamas. Bonnie's weakening was self-induced.
While floundering over the same seas for hours, Bonnie's winds
agitated the upper layers of the ocean, causing warm surface water
to sink and cooler water to rise from the depths. In turn, cooler
waters decreased the rate of evaporation, lessening the amount of
water vapor injected into the atmosphere. Because hurricanes derive
fuel from heat released when water vapor condenses into cloud
drops, a reduction in the available fuel caused Bonnie to weaken.
</P>
</TEXT>
