<SLUG> BC-BIBLE-SINAISITE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO EXPLORER USES BIBLE AS GUIDE TO FIND `TRUE' MOUNT SINAI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SUSAN GILL VARDON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAPEVINE, Texas _ Colorado adventurer Bob Cornuke and his
partner, Larry Williams, were stunned by what they saw on the Saudi
Arabian mountain that they believe is the true Mount Sinai.
</P>
<P>
   The duo had forged a letter, crawled under wire fences in the
sizzling desert and eluded soldiers at a nearby Saudi military
outpost _ all for this moment.
</P>
<P>
   They were awed by what Cornuke said was the ``unnaturally
scorched'' peak of Jabal al Lawz. According to the Bible, fire
rained down when God delivered to Moses the two stone tablets
containing the Ten Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   The two also found what was left of a 30-foot-high stone altar
with renderings of a cow, which Cornuke believes is the altar where
Israelites worshipped the image of the golden calf in rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   ``What blew me away was that everything was there that the Bible
talked about, and I didn't expect that,'' Cornuke, 47, told members
of First Baptist Church of Grapevine on Sunday. ``I thought, `This
is either Mount Sinai or the movie set that they had abandoned.'''
</P>
<P>
   To a rapt audience of hundreds, Cornuke described and played a
videotape of his quest to use the Old Testament as a road map to
find the sacred Mount Sinai. He also talked about the discovery of
an underwater land bridge, or reef, in the Red Sea that he and
Williams theorize the Israelites might have used to cross the water
during their exodus from Egypt 3,400 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That trek to Saudi Arabia in 1988 is the subject of the book
``The Gold of Exodus: The Discovery of the True Mount Sinai,'' by
Howard Blum. Rob Reiner has optioned the book for a film. Cornuke
is writing a book describing the ``Christian, inspirational'' side
of the story.
</P>
<P>
   Cornuke said that many biblical scholars are critical of his
findings, but he said no one has confronted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scholars are upset at me because they say, `How can this yahoo
go find this stuff when we have been looking for hundreds of years
and haven't found it?''' he said. ``I look at it from an
investigator's eyes, and I look at it as if the Bible is true. It's
a wide-open field for investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornuke, who was a police officer and SWAT team member for nine
years in Costa Mesa, Calif., moved to Colorado in the early 1980s
to escape the congestion and pressures. It was there that this
married father of four children met his mentor, former astronaut
Jim Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Irwin was preparing for a trip to Turkey to search
for Noah's Ark on Mount Ararat, but he had gotten word that Kurdish
terrorists knew of his plans and were going to kidnap him to
advance their cause, Cornuke said.
</P>
<P>
   So Irwin asked Cornuke to come along to provide protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I knew about Moses at that time was that he
looked like Charlton Heston,'' Cornuke said. ``I didn't know that
much about the Bible. I was a kind of now-and-then churchgoer.''
</P>
<P>
   But Irwin's enthusiasm was contagious, and Cornuke went on to
found the Bible Archaeology, Search and Exploration Institute in
Colorado Springs, Colo. He has followed the Exodus route of Moses,
dived into the Red Sea in search of the pharaoh's chariots and
searched for the Lost Ark of the Covenant _ which carried the Ten
Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   Cornuke and Williams, a two-time Republican congressional
candidate in Montana, left for Saudi Arabia on the assumption that
Mount Sinai was not in the Sinai peninsula, as tradition holds, but
in the ancient land of Midian, in Saudi Arabia. Williams bankrolled
the trip.
</P>
<P>
   They also were looking for artifacts _ gold and gems that the
Israelites had taken with them when they fled Egypt. Two years
before, a friend of Williams' had discovered a gold bracelet near
the mountain but was arrested, tried and asked to leave the country
_ without the bracelet.
</P>
<P>
   The kingdom of Saudi Arabia prohibits foreign archaeologists
from the country. Cornuke and Williams got around that by forging a
letter from a Saudi official to get visas.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the one thing I regret out of this whole story,''
Cornuke said of the forgery. ``At the time, I was so full of
adventure and full of myself. I just figured I'd be like Mission
Impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   When they reached their goal _ the Jabal al Lawz mountain _ they
learned that it is the site of a top-secret Saudi military
operation, with armed guards and missile launch areas.
</P>
<P>
   So for their nighttime excursion up the mountain, they used
night-vision binoculars. They crawled under a fence, eluded guards
and scaled up the mountain. They returned home soon after that.
</P>
<P>
   Cornuke said he has returned to Saudi Arabia several times but
would not elaborate. He worries, though, that the recent terrorist
bombings and the United States response will make it more difficult
for archaeologists to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to mess up everything,'' he said. ``It really will.
And it was tough before.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the Rev. Rick Lineberger donned a distinctly
unblemished Indiana Jones-type fedora in Cornuke's honor at the
conclusion of the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was great,'' Lineberger said after the
presentation. ``I think it will stimulate our people to study the
Scripture even more.''
</P>
<P>
   Melodee Gruber, 28, who stopped to chat with Cornuke before
leaving the church, was ``very impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's comforting to hear validation of your faith in a
skeptical world,'' the Irving resident said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
