<SLUG> BC-BARD-MUSIC-FESTIVAL-ART-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCHAIKOVSKY MADE FRESH? YES, DESPITE PSYCHOBABBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(lh) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANNANDALE-ON-HUDSON, N.Y. _ Tchaikovsky needs to be rescued from
his own enormous popularity.
</P>
<P>
   That seemed to be the overriding theme of the ninth annual Bard
Music Festival, which concluded Sunday with a substantive
orchestral program at the outdoor festival tent on the Bard College
campus, conducted by Leon Botstein.
</P>
<P>
   Botstein, who is also the president of Bard College, is an
insightful and engaging thinker who has made these annual festivals
a forum for re-examining the work of composers like Dvorak,
Schumann and Bartok, to name three, whom we think we already know
about. This summer's festival, called ``Tchaikovsky and His
World,'' was typically generous, offering 10 concerts (including a
concert performance of his seldom-heard opera ``The Maid of
Orleans''), each preceded by a lecture, as well as four panel
discussions and a screening of Soviet-era film versions of
Tchaikovsky ballets, over two weekends. Botstein shared the duties
as artistic director with another musician-philosopher, cellist
Robert Martin, who is also the dean of graduate studies at Bard.
</P>
<P>
   A recurring premise behind this festival was the idea that there
is a disconnection between Tchaikovsky's music, which has always
been beloved by audiences, and the treatment it has received from
many musicians, critics and scholars. Too often he has been
regarded as an ``adolescent passion you outgrow,'' in the words of
scholar Harlow Robinson, who spoke at Saturday morning's panel on
the critical assessment of Tchaikovsky as a composer.
</P>
<P>
   This premise seems outdated. It is true that, in the mid-20th
century, when most composers were trying to outdo one another in
cutting-edge modernity, Tchaikovsky was disdained in some circles;
his emotionalism was not the flavor of the times. Significantly,
several of the put-downs of Tchaikovsky's music cited during that
panel came from voices of the 1940s, like Wanda Landowska's barb
that Tchaikovsky ``cries louder than any suffering could justify.''
</P>
<P>
   But more recently, with the coming of neo-Romanticism in
contemporary music, and the cessation of hostilities between tonal
and atonal composers, Tchaikovsky has been viewed as a striking,
skillful and original master who can not be blamed for the
overexposure much of his music is subjected to. The best thing
about the Bard Festival is the way it found to present the music in
interesting programs that made you hear it afresh.
</P>
<P>
   That said, one could object that the philosophical, historical
and, especially, psychological contexts surroundings these works
were emphasized at the expense of strictly musical issues. For
example, on Sunday morning, in a lecture prior to a delightful
program of works written for children, all sorts of explanations
for Tchaikovsky's emotional attachment to children, and the idea of
childhood, were advanced _ for example, that as a tormented
homosexual, Tchaikovsky was entranced by the prepubescent innocence
of children.
</P>
<P>
   But could it not have been that Tchaikovsky the musician, much
like Bach, Schumann, Bartok and others, was simply interested in
the challenge, which it is, of writing music for children? Don't
most people simply like children? That certainly seemed true during
this concert of piano works performed entirely by talented
youngsters, several of them just 8 years old, and, most
interestingly, by Sarah and Susan Wang, 14-year-old twin sisters
who played an arrangement of ``The Nutcracker'' Suite for two
pianos. Their performance completely fulfilled the festival's goal
of making you hear familiar music freshly: take away the orchestral
colors from ``The Nutcracker'' and you hear what inventive, exotic,
structurally succinct music this is.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
