<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9654 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARD-MUSIC-FESTIVAL-A     08-24 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARD-MUSIC-FESTIVAL-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ANNANDALE-ON-HUDSON, N.Y.: that is.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In terms of examining Tchaikovsky's works from a strictly
musical perspective, nothing during this past weekend was as
interesting as a topic raised by composer Richard Wilson during
Saturday morning's panel. Addressing the charge that Tchaikovsky's
music is flawed by a penchant for repetition, he contrasted
recordings of three sections of the last movement of the violin
concerto: In one, an older performance by Nathan Milstein, the
music was played with familiar cuts that were sanctioned by
violinist Leopold Auer, to whom the work was dedicated; in the
other, a recent recording by Maxim Vengerov, the original uncut
version was performed.
</P>
<P>
   This provoked a heated discussion: Are Tchaikovsky's repetitions
incantatory, relentless or just careless? The uncut version was
indisputably stronger: It made the asymmetries of the phrase
structure seem crazier, more startling. But it was a lively debate,
culminating with some psychobabble from musicologist Henry
Zajaczkowski, who, relating Tchaikovsky's rhythmic repetitions to
his homosexual distress, described the phenomenon as ``suppressive
compulsive release.''
</P>
<P>
   The two main musical events were the concerts by Botstein with
the Bard Festival Orchestra (essentially the American Symphony
Orchestra, which Botstein also directs). Botstein has strengths and
weaknesses as a conductor. Large-scale matters, like the overall
shape and sweep of a piece, are well attended to. But finer points
of nuance, balance, incisive rhythmic detail and careful phrasing
are lacking.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the conditions he must work in are not ideal. These
musicians are excellent, but they cannot hear one another well in
this outdoor festival tent. And these formidable programs required
more preparation time for even a technical whiz of a conductor than
the limited amount available.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the programs were satisfying. It's not often that one has
a chance to hear Tchaikovsky's opera on Joan of Arc. Conceived
rather in the style of a French grand opera, the work is a bit
overblown and structurally messy, but it teems with musical ideas
and passion. Botstein assembled a strong cast of singers, mostly
from Russian companies, topped by Makvala Kasrashvili, who brought
her cool, gleaming soprano voice and fervor to the role of Joan, as
well as impressive soprano Oksana Krovytska, tenor Oleg Kulko and
baritone Vladimir Redkin in other roles.
</P>
<P>
   The final concert Sunday, titled ``Literature and Music,''
included three of Tchaikovsky's dramatic orchestra works inspired
by classic literary sources: ``The Tempest'' (Shakespeare),
``Francesca da Rimini'' (Dante) and the hourlong ``Manfred''
Symphony (Byron). This was a formidable program, and the
performances were inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the festival's emphasis on making literary connections
seemed out of proportion. Neither in any lecture nor the program
notes was it ever mentioned that, for example, in the final
movement of the ``Manfred'' Symphony there is a quite elaborate and
exciting episode in fugue, and that the work ends with a consoling
chorale. Surely, having these wholly musical matters pointed out
might have helped listeners to appreciate the greatness of this
work. There were times when one wished for a musician less
intellectually endowed but with the technical chops to arrive on
the scene and straighten up some things.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was an involving concert. Botstein and his players put
themselves out admirably, and the program, the whole festival in
fact, sent you home with vivid musical memories and much to think
about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
