</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-Q&AMP;A-0825-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA IN TURMOIL: WHAT DOES IT ALL MEAN?
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-POLITICS-0825.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin's unexpected
sacking of the government on Sunday -- the second time in five
months -- has once again focused the world's attention on the
former superpower and its wily, unpredictable president. A looming
financial crisis and potential political meltdown has Americans
once again asking what it all means. Cox Newspapers Washington
correspondent Eunice Moscoso put that and other questions to
Professor Harley Balzer, director of the Center for Eurasian,
Russian and East European Studies at Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
   Question: What does Yeltsin's decision mean to the U.S.
politically, considering that many Western nations supported ousted
pro-reformist Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: On a whole range of issues that are the most important
things for us, it doesn't change very much. (Newly named -- and
former -- Prime Minister Viktor) Chernomyrdin had a good
relationship with (Vice President Al) Gore. There is a whole raft
of security issues, non-proliferation issues, environmental
agreements that I'm sure are still going to be major agenda items
at the summit, when Clinton goes over there next week. The problem
is that the United States and International Monetary Fund (IMF)
agreement to economic policies had been very much dependent on our
confidence in Kiriyenko, and this group of reformers, and that's
now up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does it mean for the U.S., militarily, considering
Russia's nuclear capability?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't think it presents much of a military threat as long
as the country doesn't fall apart. Our worry is not that Russia is
going to attack us. Our worry is either that they are going to
support the bad guys -_ the Saddam Hussein's of the world -_
although it's not in their interest to go too far in that
direction. An even more serious threat would be if things really
get out of hand in Russia, if the economy gets even worse or if
central controls become even more lax then they already are. Then
we could see both hardware and personnel getting out of the
country, and that could be a very serious problem.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will recent events in Russia have economic consequences for
the U.S.?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not on a national scale. There are individual companies, of
course, that are going to be affected by this. But remember that
the Russian economy is roughly the size of the Netherlands. We've
been getting this mirror-imaging of people reporting the Russian
stock index everyday as if it were the Dow Jones stock index. Less
than one percent of all Russians own stock, and the total
capitalization of the Russian stock market is only 1 or 2 percent
of the country's gross national product (GDP). It's not a
particularly significant economic indicator. It's a
misrepresentation. You don't have millions of Russians sitting
around everyday watching their stock market average, and thinking
that it affects them in any meaningful way.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How concerned should the U.S. be that many of Russia's banks
could go bankrupt?
</P>
<P>
   A: That should concern us. First of all, it depends which banks.
I don't think that the Russian government is going to let the major
ones go. My concern with Chernomyrdin would be that he won't let
any of them go. There are a bunch of Russian banks that ought to
fail. There are way too many banks in Russia and a lot of them
aren't real banks. They are simply money-laundering operations . .
. that allow individuals to loot companies that they've privatized,
or they're a way that people can conduct financial manipulations
and pyramid schemes. A lot of them have been making bad loans that
they know are bad. They just assume the government will never allow
them to be called into account. Maybe (Chernomyrdin) is coming back
a changed man, but his policy previously was nobody gets hurt --
you support all of these idiotic, uneconomic practices because
after all, we have to protect the people.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If Russia isn't able to pay back several billion dollars it
owes to Western lenders, will that hurt the U.S. economy?
</P>
<P>
   A: Most of the Western investors used this last ($22.6 billion)
IMF bailout to run for cover. I don't think there is any massive
exposure. Most of what they've borrowed at this point are IMF kind
of loans, and those are generally long-term. It's nothing compared
to what default in a European country or Japan would be for the
United States. The more serious concern is if there is significant
bank failure, and failure to payback loans, and that the contagion
could spread to other central European countries. If it becomes a
serious regional crisis, if it begins to affect Estonia, Poland,
Hungary, Czech Republic, than the Germans will start taking a
serious hit and that has ripple effects.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happens if the ruble drops even more, leading to severe
inflation and social unrest? A: That's not likely to happen
overnight. The real danger is probably somewhere three months to a
year away if inflation does build. It could produce political
instability. It doesn't have to, but it could.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How will these events affect the upcoming summit between
Yeltsin and President Clinton? Will the economy be the main topic
of conversation?
</P>
<P>
   A: There isn't a whole lot they can do about the economics and
therefore, the non-proliferation and environmental issues are
likely to take center stage in their talks.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it politically risky for Clinton to come to the summit
considering Yeltsin's condemnation last week of U.S. air strikes in
Afghanistan and Sudan?
</P>
<P>
   A: I read that more as ``my friend Bill didn't call me and talk
to me about it. Why weren't we included?'' They are much too
interested in good relations with us. Somebody will informally tell
the Clinton people that they're sorry -- that you really should
have warned us. I think they'll patch it over because it's in
everybody's interest.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it possible that Clinton could be the U.S. president to
lose Russia back to the Communists?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't think so -_ not back to the Communists. The
Communists are still the biggest party in the country because there
are no other parties. But Gennady Zyuganov, the Communist Party
leader, has not shown any inclination to make himself a social
democrat with a broader appeal. The Communists really seem to have
peaked at somewhere between 30 and 40 percent in a two-way race.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If it's not an economic force like, say Japan or Germany, why
is Russia so important to the United States?
</P>
<P>
   A: Because they still have between 10,000 and 20,000 nuclear
weapons. Because they occupy an enormous chunk of real estate in a
very dangerous neighborhood. Because they are the key to the
security and the successful economic and political transformation
of all the countries on their borders.
</P>
<P>
   And, because they're a country of 150 million people with one of
the better education systems in the world; and if they actually
could pull off a successful transition, it would take them a very
short period of time to become a net contributor to solving the
problems of the countries that are really in desperate
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that doesn't seem to be happening.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
