<HEADLINE>
BIRMINGHAM SYMPHONY: CONDUCTOR'S FAREWELL IN MUSIC HE LOVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALZBURG, Austria _ Simon Rattle will soon come to the end of
his 18-year tenure as music director of the City of Birmingham
Symphony. The final concerts will, quite properly, be given in the
orchestra's hometown, for the audience that has supported this
remarkable partnership. As for the wider world, the farewells took
place at the Salzburg Festival over the weekend, with a performance
of Szymanowski's opera ``King Roger'' and the last concert in a
cycle of the Beethoven symphonies interlaced with contemporary
British music.
</P>
<P>
   Rattle has always been disinclined to play music he does not
love, and here he loved exuberantly. Szymanowski's score _ a grand
arabesque that evokes the opulence and sensuality of medieval
Sicily by piling Scriabin's yearning on top of Ravel's glitter,
Byzantine chanting and orientalism a la Russe _ belongs near the
center of one of the chambers of his capacious heart, and gained
from its place there. The three acts, given without intermission,
moved sinuously upward from climax to climax, bolstered by
exceptional playing from the Birmingham musicians: forthright,
lustrous, virtuoso. Languor and ornament were consistently vivified
by passion and drive.
</P>
<P>
   In the title role, Thomas Hampson was magnificent. As he came
onto the stage he was almost unrecognizable, already sunk into his
character, which, as he sang, became that of a monarch and a
lonely, fearful individual. Resolution and command were in his
voice along with hollowness and a sense of dread. Bearing
responsibility for that dread was the exciting erotic appeal
embodied in the singing of Elzbieta Smytka as Roger's queen,
Roxana, and of Ryszard Minkewicz as the Shepherd, who arrives in
Palermo spreading a new religion of abandonment to natural forces.
Ms. Smytka was radiant and sure in her hymns to the night;
Minkewicz had a thrilling and chilling wildness to him, a raw vocal
beauty. Excellent, too, were Philip Langridge as Roger's alter ego,
the supple, voluble Edrisi, and Robert Gierlach as the sonorous
Archbishop.
</P>
<P>
   But rarest of all was the vivid contribution made by the City of
Birmingham Symphony Chorus, both in ``King Roger'' on Sunday and in
Beethoven's Ninth Symphony the previous night. They made an
exciting sound: frank, strong, completely engaged. In the
Szymanowski they filled the set built into the Felsenreitschule for
Messiaen's ``Saint Francis'': adults right across the wide
platform, girls in the first act inside the skeleton of a wooden
cathedral to one side. In the Beethoven, given in the Grosses
Festspielhaus, they sang by heart, and fully from the heart.
</P>
<P>
   The Beethoven was altogether a revelation. Played with the
basses in a line above and behind the rest of the orchestra, it
stood on firm feet. It also had the benefits of the transparency
and engagement that have characterized the Birmingham orchestra's
association with Rattle: the transparency with which the
conductor's gestures and ideas are realized as sound, and the sense
of responsibility the conductor and all his fellow musicians exude,
of responsibility to one another, to the music, to the moment at
hand.
</P>
<P>
   With its thought herded and sweeping in zigzag strokes, the
performance was as far as possible from the traditional long-lined
approach, and the Ninth Symphony became vigorous, rough and young
again, its features fresh, right from the lovely, almost
vibrato-free cello pedal revealed near the start of the first
movement to the skyrocket of tone immediately before Willard White
dramatically enacted the bass' intervention in the finale.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison Birtwistle's ``Triumph of Time'' thoroughly justified
being placed alongside one of music's noble monuments. With grainy
rocks of sound in its tutti sections and beautiful playing from
solo English horn, French horns and percussion, it was a monument
itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
