<HEADLINE>
NEW ENERGY CHIEF SAYS GLOBAL WARMING SHOULD BE U.S. PRIORITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Energy Secretary Bill Richardson vowed Monday to
focus the nation's attention on decreasing pollutants that are
blamed for global climate changes and the gradual warming of the
planet's atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The former American ambassador to the United Nations, who took
over the Energy Department on Monday, said the agency had ``really
been outgunned'' in the push to reduce greenhouse gases. ``We have
to do better.''
</P>
<P>
   The pledge to curb emissions comes in response to warnings from
some scientists that the increase in greenhouse gases is causing
global temperatures to slowly rise. Greenhouse gases are mostly
carbon dioxide and other pollutants that are released with the
burning of fossil fuels such as coal and oil.
</P>
<P>
   These scientists fear that unless emissions are controlled, the
polar ice caps will melt, swamping coastal areas and many islands.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said one of his priorities as secretary would be to
keep Congress and the public informed by being ``the lead agency on
global climate change.''
</P>
<P>
   In December, the United States signed the so-called Kyoto
Protocol, an international accord that would require industrial
nations to reduce emissions of carbon dioxide and other
heat-trapping gases by 2012.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement faces opposition in Congress, where critics fear
it would be too taxing to American businesses. Opponents of the
protocol also want developing countries to be included in the
required cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, a globe-trotting former representative from New
Mexico, replaced Federico Pena as energy secretary and is the
highest-ranking Hispanic in the government. He was confirmed by the
Senate on July 31 for the Cabinet post.
</P>
<P>
   In Richardson's new role, he will oversee a department that
concentrates on oil and gas production policies; energy technology;
scientific research for energy conservation; and the regulation of
nuclear power and waste.
</P>
<P>
   America's growing dependence upon foreign oil is also of
concern, Richardson said, and he said he wants to direct more
department resources toward reducing American dependence on fossil
fuels.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old department should be ``committed to renewables
(and) alternative sources of energy,'' including solar energy and
wind power, Richardson added.
</P>
<P>
   There are many positive programs at work in the agency, he told
the packed Energy Department auditorium, but there are
``significant challenges,'' including the dangers of nuclear
proliferation and storage of nuclear waste.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson will wear dual hats as secretary and ambassador until
Richard Holbrooke replaces him at the United Nations in September,
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
