<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 30)  
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; PHONES OVERTAKE CRIME IN RIO TOURIST POLL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   After years of a combined effort by state and municipal police
to fight street violence in Rio de Janeiro, results are beginning
to show. Crime is down and tourism is up _ now telephones are the
biggest problem.
</P>
<P>
   According to a poll recently released by Embratur, Brazil's
government tourism agency, Rio's telephone system is the most
frequent source of visitor complaints. Filth, inefficient public
transportation and lack of tourist signs follow in that order.
</P>
<P>
   The poll surveyed foreign tourists at Rio's international
airport in 1997 over a four-month period.
</P>
<P>
   Street violence came in fifth, down from first in recent years.
Tourist officials attribute the drop in the crime rate _ 20 percent
in the last two years _ to a 24-hour police patrol in Copacabana,
Ipanema and Leblon, and a police station in Leblon specially
designated to attend to tourists who are victims of crime. They say
this may be the main reason for the steady growth of tourism in
Rio.
</P>
<P>
   The number of foreign visitors jumped from 378,000 in 1993 to
1.1 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one third of Rio's visitors are business travelers, for
whom the telephone is crucial. Connections often break off in
mid-conversation, crossed lines and static are common, getting a
dial tone can be a lengthy ordeal, and operators are often not
available.
</P>
<P>
   The expectation that service would improve after the
privatization last month of the state-owned telephone company,
Telebras, has quickly faded. Soon after the sale, a spokesman for
the Brazilian consortium that bought the Rio division said that
improvements should not be expected for at least two years.
</P>
<P>
   _ MERY GALANTERNICK.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FARNSWORTH MUSEUM ADDS WYETH GALLERIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Celebrating its 50th year, the Farnsworth Art Museum in
Rockland, Me., has just opened its Center for the Wyeth Family in
Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The new $10 million addition includes galleries in a converted
church and a study center and gallery in the new wing. They will
house 4,500 objects, including 75 major paintings and hundreds of
watercolors, drawings, photographs and archival materials, given by
Andrew and Betsy Wyeth, son and daughter-in-law of the American
illustrator N.C. Wyeth.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the area since the 1920s, N.C., Andrew and his son,
Jamie, have drawn on the rugged coastline, scenic islands, diverse
landscape and resilient residents of the area for inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   The Farnsworth's featured exhibition, through Nov. 8, is
``Wondrous Strange: Pyle, Wyeth, Wyeth and Wyeth,'' which uses 105
works to trace the influence of Howard Pyle, the illustrator who
was N.C.'s teacher, on N.C., Andrew and Jamie Wyeth. The exhibition
travels to the Delaware Art Museum in Wilmington on Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Farnsworth is open daily through Oct. 12, after which it is
closed on Monday. Admission is $9, $8 for seniors, $5 for students
18 and older and free for children ($8, $7 and $4 after Oct. 12).
Information: (207) 596-6457.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEPHEN MAY.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A NEW HOTEL RISES NEXT TO OLD FAITHFUL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The new $19 million Old Faithful Snow Lodge in Yellowstone
National Park recently completed its first stage of construction,
and 52 of 100 planned guest rooms, along with the restaurant and
lounge, have opened.
</P>
<P>
   Built in the rustic style of early 20th century national park
lodges, the new lodge is a short walk from the Old Faithful geyser.
All the pine and cedar heavy timbers used in the construction were
recycled from older buildings. The lodge features exterior log
columns and a cedar shingle roof, hardwood floors and a two-story
lobby fireplace. All guest rooms in the new lodge have private
baths.
</P>
<P>
   The new lodge replaces a two-story motel-style building that was
built in the 1960s as a dormitory for park employees.
</P>
<P>
   Construction is expected to be completed next May, including 48
more guest rooms, another restaurant and a ski store.
</P>
<P>
   The Old Faithful Snow Lodge and the Mammoth Hot Springs Hotel at
the north entrance are the only properties in Yellowstone open
year-round.
</P>
<P>
   Double rooms at the Snow Lodge are $121 a night. The lodge is
operated by Amfac Parks and Resorts Company in Denver. Information
and reservations are available at (307) 344-7311 or
www.ynp-lodges.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 50-YEAR-OLD ENGLISH RACE COURSE REOPENS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   One of the most famous sports-car racing courses in the world,
Goodwood Motor Circuit near Chichester, England, will officially
reopen Sept. 18 to 20, looking much as it did when it made its
debut 50 years earlier _ right down to the cars and many of the
drivers of the era.
</P>
<P>
   In Goodwood's heyday, such legends as Jim Clark of Scotland and
Stirling Moss of England competed there. It held its first event on
Sept. 18, 1948, using the perimeter roads of a wartime air base,
and will now be used exclusively for exhibition races featuring
historic sports cars, motorcycles and Formula One cars from the
1950s and 60s.
</P>
<P>
   The increasing danger that accompanied faster cars was one of
the reasons Goodwood was retired as an active track in the late
1960s. ( Moss crashed there in 1962, suffering injuries that forced
him to retire.) The 2.4-mile circuit was not modernized, but that
is now one of its charms: a chance to relive the days when bold
drivers raced Ferraris and Jaguars on tracks surrounded by hay
bales and cornfields (organizers plan to have cart horses finishing
the corn harvest within sight of the track, just as in the old
days).
</P>
<P>
   Along with flyovers by World War II Spitfires, one of the
weekend's highlights will be an exhibition race on Sept. 20
featuring Moss and the former world champions Phil Hill of the
United States and Sir Jack Brabham of Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Advance-purchase tickets are $85 for the weekend, $17 Friday to
$34 Sunday; at the gate, it's $25.50 Friday to $59 Sunday. Call
(44-1243) 755055.
</P>
<P>
   The track is about 90 minutes south of London by car. It can be
reached by taking the A3 to Milford and the A283 to Petworth, then
the A285 to Halnaker, and following the signs from there.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOSEPH SIANO.
</P>
</TEXT>
