<HEADER>
A9662 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT     08-24 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URBAN BUSH WOMEN: CHARTING LIVES PUBLIC AND PRIVATE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BECKET, Mass. _ The three dances presented by Jawole Willa Jo
Zollar's Urban Bush Women here on Sunday in the Doris Duke Studio
Theater at the Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival were a record of
public and private histories. That record began in the present,
looped back to the past and caught up with the present, with
extraordinary poignancy, humor and immediacy.
</P>
<P>
   The evening opened with ``Self-Portrait,'' created last year by
Ms. Zollar, Steven Kent and the dancers, with a text by Carl
Hancock Rux that was spoken by Ms. Zollar. ``Self-Portrait'' is a
tour de force on several levels. The dance chronicles a rehearsal,
an often unconvincing genre. ``Self-Portrait'' is also
simultaneously solemn and self-mocking, with a blessedly un-ironic
humor. Ms. Zollar, a famously demanding choreographer, takes a hard
but infectiously empathetic look at her behavior and how it can
affect even committed performers. And the Urban Bush Women are
committed, triple-threat performers who dance, sing and act with a
sometimes searing sense of truthfulness.
</P>
<P>
   The company moves on to the dancers' spiritual lives in
``Transitions,'' which ends with a group passage that suggests a
resolution of all that has come before. Maria Earle, majestically
imposing with an air of charming innocence, winds through the piece
like a motif, drawing the others along to music by Michael
Wimberly, the group's genial, coolly impassioned percussionist.
``Like Self-Portrait,'' the dance was created with Kent, a
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hands Singing Song,'' the program's premiere, looks as if it
hasn't yet settled into itself entirely yet. But it quickly picks
up speed and authority as it examines the role of the hands in the
everyday lives and history of black Americans. ``Hands Singing
Song'' is set to a hymn by Bernice Johnson Reagon and instrumental
music by Wimberly that catches the mood of each section and even of
individual dancers with breathtaking simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Love's costumes similarly enhance the piece. And the
performances are powerful, especially those of Kristin McDonald, so
delicately sensual in the section ``My Female Hand,'' and Christine
King in ``Hands Singing Hallelujah.'' But this is ultimately Ms.
Zollar's achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Reading from an interview with the poet Abiodun Oyewole, she
creates a glancing portrait of black American culture and history.
Hands push at invisible boundaries, embrace and shove others away
and signal power, sometimes comically. Masturbation is explored in
the tastefully explicit and imaginatively staged ``My Female
Hand.'' Ms. King recalls the firm but gentle hands of her
grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Hand to Fist'' manages to chronicle the social battles of
today and to sing of those often-forgotten battlers in a time when
the idealism of the 1960s seems lost forever.
</P>
<P>
   The litany is at times doctrinaire. But Ms. Zollar bravely steps
out of line, in a coolly dismissive era, as someone who has not
forgotten and who still believes in the possibility of change for
the better.
</P>
<P>
   J. Russell Sandifer designed the lighting. The choir robes were
by Stefani Mar. The company was completed by Diedre Nyota Dawkins,
Michelle Dorant, Francine Sheffield and Carolina Garcia, an
irresistibly cheerful, charging little dynamo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
