<HEADER>
A9666 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIGHTER-MARINES-TEX     08-24 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIGHTER-MARINES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINES FIND FAULT WITH DESIGN OF JOINT STRIKE FIGHTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL D. TOWLE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The joint strike fighter program, which is supposed
to produce a new aircraft that can be adapted for the Air Force,
Marines and Navy, has picked up new flak on its radar.
</P>
<P>
   The Marine Corps has told the defense titans competing to build
the aircraft _ Lockheed Martin and Boeing _ that current designs
are not satisfactory. The Marines Corps expects its version of the
plane to replace the AV-8B Harrier II, a fighter that can take off
and land vertically.
</P>
<P>
   Brig. Gen. Bruce Byrum, the Marines' assistant deputy chief of
staff for aviation, said the service has told both companies they
will have to do better to meet Marine goals for the Harrier
replacement, which is expected to become operational in 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Byrum said the Marines want an aircraft that is lighter, has
more maneuverability and greater range and can carry more weapons
than the aircraft depicted in models and designs presented by the
two contractors.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the Marines have been looking at the models that
Boeing and Lockheed are developing and that neither design meets
all the requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some areas of concern which dealt with maneuverability,
range, stow (weapons storage) and, in particular, the vertical
landing capability,'' Byrum said.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Hayden, a Lockheed spokeswoman in Fort Worth, said the
company was ``somewhat surprised'' by Byrum's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   She said that Lockheed has ``great faith'' in its JSF entry and
that the company believes its aircraft will be ``fully compliant''
with the needs of all three services.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to remember that the design is still being refined,''
she said. ``There are some things that will be improved upon.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives declined to respond to phone messages.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the Marines' problems could be a natural byproduct
of trying to produce three different aircraft from a common design.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lockheed and Boeing are still in the early stages of
developing all three fighters and have yet to produce prototypes
beyond so-called paper airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the strengths in our design,'' Hayden said. ``It
is flexible enough to accommodate the changes, rather than a fixed
design. Having dealt with the F-16 and over 110 variations of that
aircraft, we felt it important to do the same (develop a flexible
design) for the next multirole fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   All three variants of the fighters to be produced in the joint
strike fighter program will have distinctly different performance
characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   But they are to be built from a common design and manufactured
on a single assembly line.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon contract for the planes is expected to be worth
more than $250 billion. The Pentagon will determine in 2001 which
firm will produce the fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin has said it intends to produce most of the plane
at its factory in west Fort Worth, so winning the contract is
considered essential for the long-term future of the plant.
</P>
<P>
   The program is also vital for the Marines.
</P>
<P>
   Military analysts say that any problems in fielding a Harrier
replacement _ expected to cost $35 million per plane _ could
undermine the Marines' role in providing close air support for
forces on the ground. In turn, that could reduce the Marines'
overall role in military aviation.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, key lawmakers believe the services in the JSF
program must do everything possible to control costs because the
planes will come on line about the same time as the F-22 Raptor, a
21st century air-superiority fighter for the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., chairman of a House National Security
Committee subcommittee that examines tactical aviation, said the
Marines recognize that the JSF program has to be carefully watched
for cost overruns, often caused by last-minute design changes.
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, that the JSF may become the target of
Pentagon budget cutters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Marines are now facing up to the fact that you cannot do
three new tactical aviation programs with the current budget'' he
said. ``The last time I checked, we were doing $2.7 billion on
tac-air a year. The (General Accounting Office) said it would cost
$14 billion a year to build the programs the administration has on
the books. And that is within a defense budget that continues to
decrease at a dramatic rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Navy has gone to the wall for the F/A-18E/F and they have
won,'' he added. ``The F-22 has already begun to develop its own
constituency. The joint strike fighter is basically out there as a
concept. Unfortunately, it is the only replacement the Marine Corps
has for the Harrier.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force plans to buy about 2,000 of its JSF variant, which
will, like the F-16, perform as a multirole fighter.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy will buy about 300 aircraft to fill its needs for a
strike aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines will use the Harrier replacement in close air
support, backing up troops in enemy territory.
</P>
<P>
   The Harrier replacement is being designed to take off and land
vertically, or to take off and land more traditionally on runways.
It is intended to operate from land bases and naval vessels. It can
be used in a fighter or attack role and can escort helicopters,
conduct close combat air support and attack enemy ground-to-air
defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Byrum said the Marines are compiling written requirements that
will explain to both contractors what performance standards they
want in the aircraft. If the plane doesn't meet those standards,
the Marines could look elsewhere to replace the Harrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we have a lot of confidence that we will get to a
good solution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is important to us,'' he said. ``It would be hard for us
to walk away. We are dedicated to it. We see a lot of positive
aspects to the program, as far the three services are all partners,
as well as the U.K. The commonality of support will make it less
costly for us over the years. We do need a replacement for the
Harrier.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
