<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9682 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCANDALS-TRUTH-TEX     08-24 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCANDALS-TRUTH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDALS HAVE PUT TRUTH TO THE TEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATTHEW BRADY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two columnists from The Boston Globe resign under allegations of
fabricating stories. A major news network (CNN) and newsmagazine
(Time) jointly retract a story. The president of the United States
confesses on national television that he ``misled'' the American
people about his relationship with a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Truth, it seems, is taking a beating.
</P>
<P>
   Some say it is a sign of the times, calling President Clinton's
debacle simply a ``snapshot'' of decaying morality in America.
</P>
<P>
   Others say it is difficult to prove that society is less honest
now than before.
</P>
<P>
   Every decade has had its disgrace _ from the McCarthyism of the
1950s, the Pentagon Papers of the 1960s and Watergate in the 1970s
to the savings and loan and Iran-Contra scandals of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like easy answers,'' said Timothy E. O'Connell, professor of
pastoral studies at Loyola University in Chicago and author of
several books on ethics. ``I don't luxuriate in all the ambiguity,
but I think there is a lot of it there. If we ignore it, we betray
the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little ambiguity surrounding Clinton's revelation. But
there is plenty of ambivalence.
</P>
<P>
   People don't seem to care.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's approval rating dipped but remained high after the
admission, which creates a type of moral ambiguity. Does it matter
what he did? Should he be punished? How?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's between the God he and the woman he sleeps with,''
said Ervin Kingsbury, 61, an Arlington, Texas, resident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say to him, `Bill, go to your wife, go to your
minister, straighten these things out and then, in the words of
Christ, I would say, `Go, sin no more,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But others would like to tell Clinton, ``Go, and don't come
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Eppstein, a political consultant based in Fort Worth, said
that out of respect for the country and the office, Clinton should
resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he has done is disgrace the office, the highest office in
our country. Then he lied about it. Now, what we are seeing is the
cover-up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eppstein praised the example of former Speaker of the House Jim
Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Awash in allegations of ethics violations regarding profits from
a book he had written, Wright resigned as speaker in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, who is now a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram,
wrote later that he could have disproved the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at what cost to the institution, the country and the
well-being of my family?'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Eppstein said that Clinton's refusal to resign is a ``selfish
act.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton cares more about himself than he does about the
United States of America,'' Eppstein said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell said he is not worried about Clinton dragging down the
American public or the White House.
</P>
<P>
   It has weathered numerous indiscretions by other presidents.
</P>
<P>
   But he is concerned about the influence of the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this moment, I don't know that anybody is going to be
terribly anxious to imitate Clinton,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more nervous about them imitating all the pundits and
commentators, who all look well-scrubbed but who are also
manipulative,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The resignations of The Boston Globe columnists Patricia Smith
and Mike Barnicle, plus the retraction of a story by Time and CNN
about the use of the nerve gas sarin during the Vietnam War haven't
helped the media's image.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media's agenda is an interesting hour,'' O'Connell said.
``They want controversy. In a certain sense, Jerry Springer just
does it more blatantly than `Meet the Press.'''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connell recalled the time he was asked to sit on a panel for a
Chicago TV program. The topic was abortion.
</P>
<P>
   He was to be the virulent Catholic anti-abortionist. A
Protestant was to provide an opposing viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   But 10 minutes into the program, the two ``opponents'' ended up
agreeing on the basic issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The producers were furious,'' he said. ``Their agenda is not
evil, but their agenda is to catch stuff, to give it clarity, to
create controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes media harmful is the lack of counteractive forces in
people's lives, O'Connell said.
</P>
<P>
   In ancient days, people would stand in the village square and
listen to village news or proclamations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were standing together and they could elbow each other
and say, `That's baloney' or `What do you think about that?,''' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   People got the ``top down'' communication and at the same time
``lateral assessment'' communication, O'Connell said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the lateral communication has disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sit one by one in our living rooms. If I don't agree with
the person on TV, my first instinct is to presume I'm wrong, and I
don't have anybody to check it with,'' he said. ``We are not all
sitting around the same bonfire anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   His advice for Americans is to seek a sense of community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk about what you read,'' O'Connell said. ``Talk about what
you see. We are never going to undo the media. It's done.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
