<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TO AUCTION BILLS AND 2-YEAR NOTE THIS WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury securities were mixed Monday, with the price
of the 30-year bond down for the first time in four days as the
dollar fell against the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar declined amid speculation that the Japanese
government was ready to take action in the currency market when
necessary to bolster the value of the yen by selling dollars.
</P>
<P>
   A weak dollar would make dollar-denominated investments like
U.S. government securities less attractive to foreign investors,
who have been supporting the recent rally in the bond market by
seeking the safety of bonds as stock markets overseas tumble.
Foreign investors also hope to gain when they convert their dollar
returns to other currencies.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year bond was down 14/32, to 100 19/32. The yield, which
moves in the opposite direction from the price, rose to 5.46
percent, from 5.43 percent on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Traders point out that with yields at historic lows, it is
becoming harder to get investors to buy Treasury securities. Buying
is not expected to increase until investors get more signs of
sustained weakness in the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor in bond pricing Monday was the turbulence in the
stock market, which has been a leading factor in the decline of
nearly a quarter of a percentage point in bond yields in the last
couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pugliese, senior vice president and director of the
fixed-income department at J.W. Genesis Financial Corp. in Boca
Raton, Fla., described the market environment as not for the faint
hearted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we are seeing and getting inverse reactions to the stock
market _ when stocks go up, the bond market goes down; when stocks
go down, bonds go up,'' he said. ``I believe we are fully priced,
so the only impetus at this juncture would be if we had a further
flight to quality by investors thinking the stock market will get
hammered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we are pretty much in a trading range, and with
global events so compelling, I doubt any one of this week's
economic reports will have much of an impact on prices.''
</P>
<P>
   The market will get reports Tuesday on consumer confidence in
August and existing-home sales in July. On Wednesday, durable goods
orders for July will be announced, and personal income figures for
July will be released on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, in when-issued trading ahead of Wednesday's $15
billion auction of two-year Treasury notes, the securities are
being offered at a price to yield 5.19 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
