A9722 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEXUALABUSE-BISHOPS-8     08-24 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEXUALABUSE-BISHOPS-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEXUAL ABUSE LEGACY PLAGUES U.S. BISHOPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's 60 million Roman Catholics continue to be
embarrassed by revelations of priests accused of sexual abuse of
minors. But despite major efforts by U.S. Catholic bishops to
address the problem, it doesn't seem to be going away.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the furor died down this summer over a Dallas case in
which a jury awarded $30.9 million to 11 men sexually abused as
boys by a priest, reports surfaced that a former Fort Worth priest
had been accused of sexual misconduct in his native state of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The dark shadow of sex abuse reached into four small parishes
west of Fort Worth on Aug. 16 when the weekly sermon was replaced
with pleas to parishioners to report any known sexual abuse by the
former Fort Worth priest, the Rev. Thomas Teczar.
</P>
<P>
   Such episodes in the past five years have provided a wake-up
call for the nation's 300 Catholic bishops, said Sister Mary Ann
Walsh of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, bishops dealt with this like it was a moral
failing; now they realize it is a mental illness,'' said Walsh, a
spokeswoman for U.S. bishops.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Walsh said, an accused priest would confess his
sins, go off to a retreat and engage in serious prayer, and the
bishop thought he would be fit to go back to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they realize there is a high danger of recidivism in the
cases of sexual abuse,'' Walsh said. ``It is very difficult to get
a re-assignment if a priest is found to have had a serious
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Joseph P. Delaney said the Fort Worth diocese is part of
the movement to be more diligent in dealing with sexual abuse
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have prided ourselves during the last several years in
responding very forthrightly to any hint of any kind of
impropriety,'' he said at a recent news conference about Teczar.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth diocese officials had not received any complaints
related to Teczar by late last week. Reports can be made by calling
the Catholic Center at (817) 560-3300.
</P>
<P>
   Allegations of priests sexually abusing children began making
headlines more than a decade ago. The Chicago-based Survivors
Network of Persons Abused by Priests (SNAP) estimates from various
sources that more than 800 men have been removed from priestly
duties in the past 10 years because of sex abuse complaints.
</P>
<P>
   More than a half-billion dollars has been paid in civil
judgments, out-of-court settlements and attorneys fees, the
organization estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Frank Maniscalco, a spokesman for U.S. Catholic
bishops, said the church's calculation is similar. From anecdotal
evidence, it estimates that about 1,000 priests have been accused
of child sex abuse in the past decade. That is 1 percent of the
100,000 U.S. clergy who served during that time.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Catholic bishops, Maniscalco said, have been dealing
forthrightly with the t2K+V- &QC; U!
</P>
<P>
   The committee's recommendations call for: responding quickly to
allegations; removing the suspected offender from ministerial
duties; reporting the violation to civil authorities; cooperating
with the investigation; reaching out to victims and their families
and making the matter public while respecting privacy rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth diocese had to deal with the issue again recently
after published reports that Delaney accepted Teczar into the
diocese 10 years ago, even though the priest's Massachusetts
diocese had suspended him.
</P>
<P>
   Delaney said that in retrospect, he regrets accepting Teczar,
who served in the Fort Worth diocese from 1988 to 1993. No
accusations of sexual abuse were made against Teczar while he was
in North Texas. Delaney said he did not know of several past
accusations that had been made in Teczar's home diocese.
</P>
<P>
   Teczar lives in Dudley, Mass., and has been on administrative
leave from duties as a priest since he left Texas. He faces a civil
suit in Massachusetts filed by David Lewcon, 44, who contends that
Teczar sexually abused him repeatedly in 1971 and 1972 when Teczar
was assigned to St. Mary's Church in Uxbridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Teczar and his attorney did not respond Friday to messages left
on their telephone answering systems.
</P>
<P>
   Delaney said he had received some good recommendations about
Teczar before accepting him, but he also knew that the priest had
gone through a year of therapy after church authorities
investigated a complaint that he had provided alcohol to a youth in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, two years after Teczar came to Texas, Delaney said, he
learned from Massachusetts church authorities that Teczar had been
charged and convicted of a misdemeanor concerning the alcohol
complaint. The victim also accused Teczar of seeking sexual favors
in the alcohol incident, Delaney said, but Teczar denied it and no
sex abuse charges were brought.
</P>
<P>
   Stricter guidelines adopted by the 28-county Diocese of Fort
Worth in the past five years require incoming priests to go through
extensive psychological screening and serve as associate pastors
before getting a permanent position.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the diocese's 105 priests come from within the diocese
or from worldwide missionary orders such as the Franciscans, who
come with high recommendations from their superiors, Delaney said.
The missionary priests are also carefully screened, the bishop
noted.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, the U.S. bishops' spokeswoman, said Catholic bishops who
accept or recommend priests for an assignment have tough judgments
to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bishop may review a priest's record carefully, but nothing
is 100 &LR; %HW.cent,'' she said. ``It is just like a doctor who tells
you that you are in good health, and then you die of a heart attack
the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishops also have a problem in being open about sexual abuse
complaints, she said, because many victims don't want such matters
to become public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Protecting the victim is the first concern,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Jenkins, author of the book ``Pedophiles and Priests:
Anatomy of a Contemporary Crisis,'' said sex abuse of minors is a
problem in all church groups. But it gets more attention in the
Catholic Church because of the church's high profile and because
priests are unmarried.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say the problem of sex abuse is related to the
church's system of mandatory celibacy, although church authorities
strongly dispute that.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in the church hierarchy will even concede that there is
a problem with celibacy,'' said Jason Berry of New Orleans, author
of ``Lead Us Not Into Temptation: Catholic Priests and the Sexual
Abuse of Children.''
</P>
<P>
   Church authorities often cite studies indicating that most cases
of child sexual abuse occur within heterosexual families, Berry
noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree that celibacy does not cause men to molest children
any more than marriage can be blamed for incest,'' Berry said.
``But celibacy creates a climate of sexual denial that can
contribute to sexual abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
