<HEADER>
A9725 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN25-COX     08-24 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Late-game heroics by Lopez, Jones gives Atlanta win over L.A.
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If good teams are determined by winning games they
should have lost, the Atlanta Braves must be pretty high in
baseball's pecking order.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves won a game they should have lost on Monday. For the
seventh time this season, Atlanta won after trailing in the eighth
inning, a neat trick that concluded a 5-2 homestand and sent the
woebegone Los Angeles Dodgers home to wonder why they ever left.
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez and Andruw Jones beat L.A. 4-3 with back-to-back
homers off closer Jeff Shaw, who has blown six saves this season
but surely not one like this.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Braves tackle the final challenge remaining on the
schedule, a five-game run during the next nine days with the NL
Central-leading Houston Astros, another possible playoff opponent
who hosts Atlanta tonight for a two-game set.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're packing them in down there now,'' manager Bobby Cox
said, ``and then, of course, they got the (Mark) McGwire thing
going on in St. Louis (where the Braves go for a weekend series).
So it's going to be a fun trip.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be hard to top the 10-minute trip that was Monday's
eighth-inning, when Tom Glavine watched his shutout blown on a Gary
Sheffield RBI single and Eric Karros' two-run homer. L.A. lefty
Brian Bohanon had held the Braves to just five singles, and his 3-0
lead looked padlocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't real happy with the turn of the events, and I was
pretty much sitting there counting on getting a loss,'' said
Glavine, who improved to 17-5. ``But the guys turned it around with
a huge eighth inning. For me, you go through the full spectrum of
emotion, but for the team, this is a great win.''
</P>
<P>
   After Bohanon issued a one-out walk, Dodgers manager Glenn
Hoffman brought in Shaw, who has posted a 1.61 ERA since coming to
L.A. from Cincinnati. The move was not an entirely successful one.
Andres Galarraga singled on the first pitch to put two men on, and
two pitches later, Lopez broke up a 4-for-27 slide with his 26th
homer, the 100th of his career, to tie the game, 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw him in L.A, and he handled us pretty good over there,''
Lopez said. ``You figure one day is for you, and the next day has
got to be for us. He made some pitches that I believe were
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones had to work for his, fouling off five pitches before Shaw
threw an inside fastball that he pulled for his 22nd homer and his
second in two games. Jones finished the homestand 11-for-27 (.407)
with nine runs scored and a pair of stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been putting the ball in play,'' Jones said. ``No matter
where the pitch is, inside or down the middle, there's a way to put
it play. If it comes to my strength, I'm going to go ahead and use
my power.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
