<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maryland: Slight hope for improvement _ but not much
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE PARK, Md. _ Maryland coach Ron Vanderlinden compares his
Maryland football team to a 1969 Chevrolet Impala once owned by his
grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a car with no power steering, no power brakes and no
power period,'' the second-year coach said. ``It was a chore to
drive, and I think our Maryland program is like that. But there
will come a time when we'll become an automatic and have power, and
all the coaching staff will have to do is steer it and give it
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   O.K., so the former Northwestern assistant would probably flunk
Analogy 101, but it's tough to find something to say about a team
that finished 2-9 last season and probably was even worse than its
record.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderlinden is the coach who was introduced at halftime of a
December Maryland basketball game after his hiring in 1996 and
promised the 14,500 in attendance that they wouldn't be spending
any more Christmas holidays at home, that they'd be going to bowl
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised that the talent level wasn't a little
higher,'' Vanderlinden said about his first Terp team. ``I was
surprised how good this conference was.''
</P>
<P>
   The Terps could be better this year, although probably not by
much. The positives include linebackers Kendall Ogle and Eric
Barton, who finished No. 2 and No. 3 in the ACC in tackles last
year, and tailback LaMont Jordan, who gained 689 yards as a
freshman.
</P>
<P>
   The negatives include a group of seven quarterbacks, none with
have any appreciable experience; an offensive unit with only one
senior; a defensive line that returns only one starter; and a
secondary green in three of four spots.
</P>
<P>
   But don't suggest to Vanderlinden that this might be a
rebuilding year. ``I'm going to play the best players, and I'm
going to do my damnedest to win every game,'' he said. ``I realize
where we're at in terms of mental attitude and the problems we have
to overcome, but I'll be doggone if I'm going to write off the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps junior quarterback Ken Mastrole can answer the
quarterback questions. The 6-3, 225-pound junior has ``distanced
himself from the pack,'' Vanderlinden said. Mastrole played in
seven games in '97 and hit seven of 19 passes for 83 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Terps lone senior offensive lineman, 6-7, 299-pound John
Feugill, promises that Maryland will be better up front. ``Our
offensive line last year, we had five individuals,'' Feugill said.
``There was no chemistry there. When things went wrong, there was
nothing said. The team has a new attitude this year. The offense is
so much more competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan may be the Terps' ace in the hole. The 5-11, 214-pounder
has the talent to be one of the ACC's best, especially for a guy
who doesn't like to get hit. ``I hate contact,'' Jordan says.
''People ask me, 'Why are you playing running back,' and I tell
them I have no idea. I think because I don't like contact it's made
me a better player. I try to avoid it, but when it's inevitable, I
like to give it instead of taking it. We're going to be better. . .
. I've seen holes in practice I've never seen before. You can tell
if your offensive line is jelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Maryland's strong point last year might be its undoing this
time. The defense is inexperienced and lacks depth. ``This league
is defense-oriented,'' linebacker Barton said. ``I've never seen
bigger people run faster than in this conference.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly why the Terps might be in for an exceptionally
long year.
</P>
<P>
   Coming Wednesday: Virginia
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
