<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-PROTENNIS-NOTES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inside Pro Tennis: Atlanta bypassed by big names
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Anna Kournikova and Steffi Graf were to make their
Atlanta debuts this week. Instead, the two superstars are playing
in the Pilot Pen International Women's Championships in New Haven,
Conn. That's the tournament formerly known as the U.S. Women's
Hardcourt Championships, the flop that was supposed to be Atlanta's
regular stop on the Corel WTA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's tournament, which returned women's pro tennis to
Atlanta for the first time in 14 years, was an attendance bust at
Stone Mountain Park, with only two sessions _ Monica Seles' one and
only match and the Lindsay Davenport-Sandrine Testud final _
attracting more than 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big loss for the city of Atlanta, particularly with
the depth and quality of women's players today,'' said Sheila
Cronkright, the executive director of the Georgia Tennis
Association. She also winced at the lost prospect of Kournikova
playing Graf in a quarterfinal here Thursday night. ``That would've
been huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a four-year contract with the USTA and Stone Mountain,
the local group that managed the event, International Sports and
Entertainment Strategies (ISES), requested out of the lease. The
USTA granted the request because Butch Buchholtz, owner of the
Lipton Championships in Key Biscayne, Fla., and one of the game's
top promoters, was pitching to take the U.S. Open warm-up to
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The Pilot Pen, which began Monday with Kournikova as the evening
attraction, has three things the U.S. Women's Hardcourts didn't
have: a title sponsor, clever marketing and low ticket prices.
</P>
<P>
   For $125, a fan can see every match this week through the final.
For $15 Monday, spectators were entitled to half the first round,
matches that included Kournikova, Mary Joe Fernandez and Amanda
Coetzer.
</P>
<P>
   At the USTA Women's Hardcourts, ticket prices averaged $10 more
per ticket and granted admission to only half as many matches.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras mulling Davis Cup
</P>
<P>
   Pete Sampras says he'll decide by next week if he'll play in
next month's Davis Cup semifinal against Italy in Indianapolis.
Andre Agassi won't play. Sampras skipped the first two rounds this
year for the second-straight year. If Sampras says no, captain Tom
Gullikson probably would go with Vince Spadea, who's up to a
career-high No. 42 after beating Agassi and Richard Krajicek
earlier this month. Loyalty to the team and past heroics will keep
Jim Courier in the lineup, although his ranking is No. 68.
</P>
<P>
   This week in tennis history
</P>
<P>
   This week is the 25th anniversary of the first computer rankings
in men's professional tennis. Ilie Nastase was the first No. 1
player and kept the spot for 40 weeks before John Newcombe
supplanted him. After Newcombe's eight-week reign ended on July 29,
1974, Jimmy Connors held No. 1 for 160 weeks consecutively, still a
record. There have been 100 top-10 players from 25 countries,
including Atlanta residents Mikael Pernfors and Tom Gorman, who
each peaked at No. 10. Only 14 players have been No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis on TV
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports Net will televise the ATP Tour's Hamlet Cup from Long
Island on Saturday at 1 p.m. and 7 p.m. (semifinals) and Sunday at
2 p.m. (final). Marcelo Rios and Patrick Rafter are the top seeds.
Best potential early match is Rafter against Goran Ivanisevic in
the quarters. ... CBS will televise Saturday's 2 p.m. final of the
Pilot Pen women's tournament. Top seeds are Davenport and Jana
Novotna. Best potential early match is Kournikova versus Graf in
the quarterfinals. ... Luke and Murphy Jensen will host the second
episode of Topspin, the USTA's new tennis show targeted at a young
audience. It airs Sunday at 1:30 on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Loose points
</P>
<P>
   Sampras on his second-round defeat by Leander Paes last week:
``Playing three weeks in a row has taken its toll emotionally.''
... Seles on winning the du Maurier Open: ``I've played
five-straight weeks, and I'm worn down. I'll arrange my schedule
next year so that won't happen again (leading up to the U.S.
Open).'' ... Rios on losing in the third round in Indianapolis to
Byron Black: ``I was playing so bad I never felt I was going to
win.'' ... Graf on losing to Magui Serna in the third round in
Montreal: ``I have no consistency in my game at all right now.''
... Martina Hingis hasn't won a tournament since the Italian Open
in early May. ... Yevgeny Kafelnikov, who's fallen out of the top
10, withdrew from the Long Island event this week and doesn't sound
up to the U.S. Open, either. Last week in New Haven, Russia's
all-time top player noted that he plays more matches than anyone
else on the ATP Tour and said, ``I'm burned out. ... I have no
motivation to go on right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
