<HEADLINE>
SEXUAL ABUSE LEGACY PLAGUES U.S. BISHOPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's 60 million Roman Catholics continue to be
embarrassed by revelations of priests accused of sexual abuse of
minors. But despite major efforts by U.S. Catholic bishops to
address the problem, it doesn't seem to be going away.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the furor died down this summer over a Dallas case in
which a jury awarded $30.9 million to 11 men sexually abused as
boys by a priest, reports surfaced that a former Fort Worth priest
had been accused of sexual misconduct in his native state of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The dark shadow of sex abuse reached into four small parishes
west of Fort Worth on Aug. 16 when the weekly sermon was replaced
with pleas to parishioners to report any known sexual abuse by the
former Fort Worth priest, the Rev. Thomas Teczar.
</P>
<P>
   Such episodes in the past five years have provided a wake-up
call for the nation's 300 Catholic bishops, said Sister Mary Ann
Walsh of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, bishops dealt with this like it was a moral
failing; now they realize it is a mental illness,'' said Walsh, a
spokeswoman for U.S. bishops.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Walsh said, an accused priest would confess his
sins, go off to a retreat and engage in serious prayer, and the
bishop thought he would be fit to go back to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they realize there is a high danger of recidivism in the
cases of sexual abuse,'' Walsh said. ``It is very difficult to get
a re-assignment if a priest is found to have had a serious
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Joseph P. Delaney said the Fort Worth diocese is part of
the movement to be more diligent in dealing with sexual abuse
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have prided ourselves during the last several years in
responding very forthrightly to any hint of any kind of
impropriety,'' he said at a recent news conference about Teczar.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth diocese officials had not received any complaints
related to Teczar by late last week. Reports can be made by calling
the Catholic Center at (817) 560-3300.
</P>
<P>
   Allegations of priests sexually abusing children began making
headlines more than a decade ago. The Chicago-based Survivors
Network of Persons Abused by Priests (SNAP) estimates from various
sources that more than 800 men have been removed from priestly
duties in the past 10 years because of sex abuse complaints.
</P>
<P>
   More than a half-billion dollars has been paid in civil
judgments, out-of-court settlements and attorneys fees, the
organization estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Frank Maniscalco, a spokesman for U.S. Catholic
bishops, said the church's calculation is similar. From anecdotal
evidence, it estimates that about 1,000 priests have been accused
of child sex abuse in the past decade. That is 1 percent of the
100,000 U.S. clergy who served during that time.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Catholic bishops, Maniscalco said, have been dealing
forthrightly with the problem through educational programs and
special task forces that have recommended prompt action against sex
offenders among the clergy.
</P>
<P>
   Bishops have also made it harder for priests with records of
sexual abuse to move from diocese to diocese.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Fort Worth diocese spokesman Jeff Hensley said the
diocese is increasingly wary of accepting priests from other
dioceses and very few such transfers are made now. Applicants must
have an unqualified recommendation from their bishop attesting to
their good character and lack of any record of wrongdoing,
including sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates for victims of sex abuse are skeptical _ if not
cynical _ about the bishops' efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all window dressing,'' said David Clohessy, national
director of the Survivors Network, who says he was abused by a
priest.
</P>
<P>
   Most bishops, he contends, are still trying to protect fellow
clergy and the church's image by bringing problems to light only
when backed into a corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've spent ... more energy on the problem in recent
years,'' said Clohessy. ``But their focus is on damage control and
maintaining secrecy rather than preventing abuse and healing of
those abused.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``As long as that remains their priority, you are
going to hear about case after case after case.''
</P>
<P>
   Maniscalco said the problems keep arising because victims are
periodically coming forward to report sex abuse that occurred many
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are playing catch-up in dealing with 30 years of cases,''
he said. ``I don't know what more the bishops can do to address
this.''
</P>
<P>
   All 194 dioceses in the United States now have strict policies
dealing with sex abuse, partially based on recommended guidelines
from a Bishops' Ad Hoc Committee on Sex Abuse established in 1993
to help them deal with the problem.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
