<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS _ MOSCOW _ Russia's political and economic chaos
marks the beginning of the end for Boris Yeltsin, analysts said
Monday. The Russian president also said as much in televised
remarks Monday when he suggested that acting Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin may be the best candidate to succeed him when his
presidential term expires in 2000. Yeltsin's political obituary has
been written and erased before. But Yeltsin's abrupt firing of the
government Sunday was widely viewed here as capitulation to forces
beyond the wily president's control. An analysis. (Holmes, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-STREETS _ MOSCOW _ Most Russians are insulated from the
economic crisis by their own poverty. Most also are dubious that
Sunday's government overhaul will improve their lives, coming as it
did from a president they stopped trusting long ago. A look at how
average Russians are coping with their country's latest upheaval.
(Holmes/Shargorodska, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-Q&AMP;A _ WASHINGTON _ A question-and-answer session with an
expert on Russia about what the turmoil in the former superpower
means going forward. (Moscoso, Cox News Service). ETA: 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   COX-CLINTON-MEDIA _ WASHINGTON _ With the Internet and talk
radio abuzz with rumors of kinky sex in the Oval Office,
increasingly graphic accounts of the relationship between President
Clinton and Monica Lewinsky are making their way into the
mainstream news media. ``Standards are in the toilet and not just
in the White House,'' said Larry Sabato, a professor who teaches
about politics and the media at the University of Virginia. (Dart,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE _ Hurricane Bonnie ambled toward the Southeast coast
today, prompting residents from Florida to North Carolina to stock
up on emergency supplies and tune in to weather reports. PBP
tracking map shows Bonnie making a direct hit on Wrightsville
Beach, N.C., at 6 a.m. Wednesday. (Manuel/Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE-RIPTIDES _ Rip tides and heavy surf driven by Hurricane
Bonnie churned the Atlantic from Florida to New Jersey, claiming
the lives of at least two swimmers and leaving scores more turning
to lifeguards to make it safely to the beach. Rip tides were blamed
for the deaths Sunday of a 25-year-old man in South Carolina and a
24-year-old man in Delaware. Thirty people were rescued in Carolina
Beach, N.C., and 100 were saved in Atlantic City, N.J. A look at
the phenomenon of riptides. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE-FLORIDA _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Hurricane Bonnie should
be due east of here about 500 miles at 8 p.m. Monday, sparing South
Florida unless it does a spectacular, unexpected left turn, which
the National Hurricane Center never discounts. Still plodding along
at 5-6 mph to the NW but should pick up speed Tuesday. Meanwhile,
tropical depression 4 formed today farther east and south of where
Bonnie formed last Wednesday and should be a tropical storm by
Monday nite. NHC said it looks impressive and should be 600 miles
east of Guadaloupe by Thursday. (Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE-SAVANNAH _ SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Coastal Georgians prepare for
Hurricane Bonnie. (Davis, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE-NC _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Checking with marinas on any
preparations. State officials meet Tuesday to assess the threat.
(Greenville Daily Reflector)
</P>
<P>
   TEX-FLOODS _ Sixteen people are dead and some 20 are missing as
the remnants of Tropical Storm Charley pound the border cities of
Del Rio and Ciudad Acuna. (Harmon/Shah/Haurwitz/Gamino, Austin
American-Statesman) ETA: 8 Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   TEX-FLOODS-CHARLEY _ A sider explaining Charley's path, how it
stalled, what caused devastating flooding. (Haurwitz/Allison,
Austin American-Statesman) ETA: 7 Eastern. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   TEX-FLOODS-HISTORY _ A look at some of the worst floods in
</P>
<P>
   Texas history. (Kelly/Coffey/Gamboa, Austin American-Statesman)
ETA: 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   TEX-BUSH _ Gov. George W. Bush takes his presidential
noncandidacy to South Carolina Tuesday, one of the early primary
states, where 1996 GOP nominee Bob Dole jumpstarted his candidacy
after lackluster performances in Iowa and New Hampshire. Although
Bush is helping friend and Republican Gov. David Beasley raise
money, the visit _ Bush's second in as many years _ fuels
speculation for 2000. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman) National
and political wire.
</P>
<P>
   UT-LAWSCHOOL-DATA _ AUSTIN, Texas _ UT Law School is expected to
release enrollment data today showing its racial breakdowns in this
second year of Hopwood. Checking to see if Tech or Univ. of Houston
have figures as well. Also will mention Berkeley data. (Roser,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-SCHOOLFUNDING _ Hearings open on the state's school funding
actions. Opening arguments and witnesses from the state, which gets
to go first. House Speaker JoAnn Davidson could testify today.
(Miller, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   STUNT _ ``The Last Marshal'' films the car crash off Lake Worth
pier. (McCabe, Palm Beach Post) WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   BERRIES-PROSTATE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Florida Marine Patrol
officers arrested two Indiantown men for picking palmetto berries
at Jonathan Dickinson State Park. The two had 80 lbs. of berries in
their car, on which charges were based, and another 250 lbs. in
their trunk. The berries are sold at 16 cents to $1 per lb. to
pharmaceutical companies, which use them to make a medication to
treat prostate problems. (Swartz, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
