A9739 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     08-24 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNER'S DISORGANIZED SON-IN-LAW CAUSES CHAOS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves Mondays
in the ``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box
260057, Encino, Calif. 91426 or by electronic mail to
LloydOnJobaol.com. Names will be withheld upon request.) 
By KEN LLOYD  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Q. I report to the vice president of the company.
He is creative and intelligent, but totally unorganized. Several of
us always have to scramble to complete projects that he delegates
at the last minute. Unfortunately, he is the owner's son-in-law. Do
you have any suggestions? M.R.
</P>
<P>
   A. There is no management guideline allowing owners' sons-in-law
to be totally unorganized. In reality, many owners are not exactly
ecstatic when their employed relatives throw the support staff into
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Your working relationship with the vice president will obviously
influence the approach that you take in this situation, but
regardless, the only way to deal with this matter is to discuss it
with him.
</P>
<P>
   Putting aside the family ties, it is important to note that the
vice president's style is not highly atypical of creative people,
as they often tend to be rather uninterested in plans and
schedules. During a noncrisis period, you and several of your
associates should meet with the vice president and indicate that
you have some ideas to help the department work more effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Give him specific examples of projects that could have been
handled more successfully if there had been more planning and
advance notice. You can even provide him with information on some
of the user-friendly day-timing and scheduling systems that are
available. Some actually have a creative flair, and these should be
particularly appealing to him.
</P>
<P>
   If the company owner has any interest in increasing the
likelihood of putting success in succession planning, this can be a
very important step.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I thought I was in line to be promoted into a management
position, and I was shocked when the promotion went to one of the
most incompetent people in our department. My manager said it was a
hard decision, but there will be other opportunities in the future
and I should ``stick around.'' What do you think? S.T. &QL; 
A. Being advised by management to ``stick around'' is not exactly
useful data when it comes to career planning. The fact is that you
expected a promotion, and management decided that someone else was
more qualified. Management can tell you anything about the
promotion possibilities, but nothing speaks louder than the
decisions they make.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the job went to a person who is less competent, but this
person may be more competent than you think. After all, he or she
is certainly competent when it comes to knowing how to get
promoted.
</P>
<P>
   At this point you should consider having a candid career-related
discussion with your manager, focusing specifically on your
near-term and longer-term objectives, and the realistic
opportunities that exist within the company. If there are growth
plans, educational programs, varied internal career paths, it may
be worthwhile to ``stick around.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there should be some timetables associated with this.
After all, having benchmark dates is an important aspect of
goal-setting. If the message continues to be to ``stick around,''
be careful or you may get stuck.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will soon be looking for work. I am a hard worker, and I
have good references. I get terrible headaches when I am around
people who wear perfume, scented powders, etc. At my last job,
everyone agreed not to wear scents and it worked just fine, but I
had to quit the previous job because of headaches from the
perfumes. Should I tell a prospective employer about this when I am
applying or after an offer has been made? A.C. &QL; 
A. If the first words out of your mouth are that you cannot work in
environments where people wear scents, that will not make much
sense. Although employers are expected to make reasonable
accommodations in these situations, such an approach may still hurt
your chances of obtaining the job before you have had any chance at
all. At the same time, this does not mean that you should conceal
this type of disability.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, you should bring it out when the employer asks you if
there are any factors that can interfere with your ability to
handle the work during the required work hours, or as a response to
an open-ended question in which you are describing your work style
or job objectives.
</P>
<P>
   At such a point in the screening process, the employer will
already know that you are a hard worker with solid references. You
can also mention the kinds of reasonable accommodations that
previous employers have made to help you be fully productive.
</P>
<P>
   In this tight labor market, it is difficult to find excellent
employees. Having the troops show real restraint when applying
colognes and powders is not too high a price to pay. In fact, many
employees would probably regard this change as a breath of fresh
air.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
