<HEADLINE>
FRIENDS, ASSOCIATES SAY BIN LADEN FAMILY SPURNED TERROR SUSPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUZANNE HOHOLIK and TRAVIS E. POLING  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Terror suspect Osama bin Laden had an older
half-brother who lived and worked in Central Texas until his death
in a 1988 ultralight aircraft crash.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and associates of Salem bin Laden say his family
disowned Osama bin Laden as the younger man's politics and world
view turned militantly anti-American. While other family members
cultivated ties to the United States, the radical son took a
different path.
</P>
<P>
   Salem bin Laden was the eldest son of a wealthy Saudi Arabian
businessman who amassed his fortune in the construction business.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, Salem bin Laden's love of flying was transformed into
another business venture, Binladen Aviation, which was incorporated
in Austin and was dissolved shortly after his death at 42. His
connection to Texas began in 1973 when the young Saudi Arabian
businessman came seeking a pilot for the family airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Auerbach worked for Salem bin Laden for years, first as a
private pilot in Saudi Arabia and later as an aviation manager for
his company in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was great. He always treated me well,'' Auerbach said. ``In
fact, I was probably a father figure to him. He was very kind and
always took care of me. He came over here all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Auerbach said he never met Osama bin Laden, who is accused by
the United States of financing terrorist activities, including the
recent bombings of two American embassies in Africa. Last week,
President Clinton ordered retaliatory missile strikes against
targets in Afghanistan and the Sudan associated with Osama bin
Laden.
</P>
<P>
   As Osama bin Laden became a player in the world of radical
Islamic fundamentalism, Salem and the rest of the bin Laden family
``disowned'' and refused to talk to him, Auerbach was told.
</P>
<P>
   That assessment of the family rift was echoed by Charles
Schwartz, a Houston lawyer who represented the bin Laden estate in
a 1991 lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio attorney Wayne Fagan represented Salem from 1982
until his death in 1988. He said Osama always was considered the
``black sheep of the family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard all of this, it just made me sick,'' Fagan said,
referring to the allegations that Osama bin Laden was linked to the
embassy bombings. ``Salem, God bless him, is turning over in his
grave. The family, they agonized over (Osama bin Laden) and outcast
him from the family since the early '80s.''
</P>
<P>
   Auerbach's links to the bin Laden family have faded, but he
fondly recalls how he went to work for the head of the family,
Muhammad bin Laden, then Salem.
</P>
<P>
   Auerbach worked in Saudi Arabia as a contract pilot with Trans
World Airlines in the 1960s, when he was hired to fly the elder bin
Laden's private plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``His father had bought an airplane and used it in the
business,'' he said. ``He contracted with the airlines ... they had
hired a pilot and he didn't show up, so I filled in.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad died in an aircraft crash in 1967. It wasn't until 1973
that the family was able to buy another plane. That's when Salem,
the eldest of 20 sons, went looking for a pilot, Auerbach said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to the States and found me because I had flown for his
father,'' Auerbach said. ``He came here to find me and took me back
to Saudi Arabia.''
</P>
<P>
   Fagan said the bin Laden family is very respected
internationally and Salem worked hard to earn that reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very carefree and a very fun-loving person, truly a man
of the world,'' he said. ``He was highly respected in Saudi Arabia
and so is his family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
