<HEADER>
A9750 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCOY-COLUMN25-COX     08-24 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCOY-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sosa an afterthought in recent Maris chase _ but he shouldn't be
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Sammy Sosa isn't exactly Brand X. He isn't generic.
He isn't some cheap
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire knock-off. It just seems that way.
</P>
<P>
   This is The Year of Big Mac and for most of this season Sosa has
been a tag-a-long. If Sosa did what he is doing in any other year,
the nation's baseball attention would be focused squarely on him.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the very large shadow of McGwire blots out Sosa.
Headlines scream, ``McGwire Homers, So Does Sosa.''
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps that is as it should be. Sosa was Sammy-come-lately
this year. McGwire started fast and at one point led Sosa in the
home run race, 27-13. But Sosa hit 20 home runs in June and joined
McGwire in dogging the ghost of Roger Maris.
</P>
<P>
   Still, fans don't clamor to see Sosa take batting practice.
Sosa's home runs aren't measured with odometers, as are McGwire's.
But, as Cincinnati Reds manager Jack McKeon points out, ``They all
count the same. McGwire doesn't get anything more for hitting one
475 feet than Sosa does hitting one 340 feet.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no furor over Sosa's visit to Cinergy Field with the
Chicago Cubs tonight and Wednesday as there was for McGwire's stop.
No requests for special seats in the left-field upper deck red
level.
</P>
<P>
   To McKeon, it makes no difference. McGwire, Sosa. Sosa, McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   And his attitude hasn't changed about pitching to both. Just
because the Reds are wallowing in the muck of last place doesn't
mean Sosa can expect any favors in the form of fat, juicy pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win all the games we play against Chicago and St. Louis
and they both break the record (61 homers), I don't give a damn,''
McKeon says. ``How about some integrity in the game? Do we want to
win or see them break records? I'd like to see both do it. I'd like
us to win and for them to break the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the fans will be booing me again,'' McKeon said,
referring to boos in Cinergy when McGwire was walked. ``We'll pitch
to Sosa as much as possible, just as we do McGwire. We've had
pretty good success getting Sosa out, but we won't let him beat us
if the game is on the line. We will walk him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds and Cubs have played only three games and McKeon's
memory is a bit off. In those three games in Cinergy, Sosa was 5
for 12 (.417) with a home run, four RBI (three on the home run) one
intentional walk and four strikeouts. Sosa's home run off
Cincinnati's Scott Sullivan was, though, uh, McGwire-like _ an
explosion into the green seats in straight-away center.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire hasn't been nearly as destructive on the Reds _ 2 for
13, no homers, no RBI, 11 walks (five intentional), two strikeouts
and one hit-by-pitch.
</P>
<P>
   There are major differences in the two.
</P>
<P>
   While McGwire would like to put his hands over his face to avoid
the cameras, Sosa likes to mug and enjoys the attention.
</P>
<P>
   After Sosa dispatches another one over the fence, he thumps his
chest, blows a kiss and holds up the ``V'' sign. The kiss and
pounding of his chest are for his mother back in the Dominican
Republic, to let her know she is in his heart. The ``V'' is for
deceased broadcaster Harry Caray.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's home-run trot is pure vanilla, as boring as 10-mile
walks around a running track, but that's McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   At the plate, McGwire is as disciplined as a Marine drill
sergeant. He wouldn't swing at a bad pitch if the catcher held a
Glock 21 to his head, which is why he has 31 more walks than
anybody else in the league, 137 to the 106 for runner-up Barry
Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa is likely to go after something not only outside the strike
zone, but outside the area code. He isn't in the Top Ten in walks
(58, 11 intentional).
</P>
<P>
   That's why pitching coach Don Gullett and McKeon believe Sosa
can be negated.
</P>
<P>
   ``If either one is hot, you don't want to face either one,''
McKeon said. ``What they are doing is great for baseball, selling a
lot of tickets and creating great interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa will be facing left-hander Dennis Reyes tonight and
right-hander Brett Tomko Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes says he is up and ready to face Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to work Sosa outside, then come in strong,'' Reyes said.
``You can't put the ball in the same place all the time or he'll
hit one off you, for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomko believes facing Sosa is the same as facing McGwire, or any
other power-laden behemoth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't approach them any differently than any other power
hitters in the league,'' Tomko said. ``You have one objective. .
.get them out. If you give it up, you give it up. And you tip your
cap.''
</P>
<P>
   What advice for the two?
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how to get him out,'' Gullett said. ``It's a matter of
making pitches. Home runs usually are the result of mistakes (53
mistakes to McGwire, 51 mistakes to Sosa).''
</P>
<P>
   The consensus is that Sosa finds it difficult to lay off high,
inside fastballs on his hands. And he doesn't like to walk, so
there is a plan for when he has three balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll chase the ball in the dirt if he has three balls on
him,'' Reds third-base coach Harry Dunlop said. ``Throw it in the
dirt or over his head and he'll chase it. Just make sure it is in
the dirt or over his head or you might injure your neck when you
snap it to catch a glimpse of the ball leaving the yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Then you can watch Sosa thump his chest, blow a kiss, hold up
the ``V'' and see if he gained any ground on Big Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
