<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE AFTER THE WHITE HOUSE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Sunday Times of London reported over the weekend that
 &UR; Hillary Clinton  &LR; is thinking about working at the United Nations
after her husband's second term is over.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Times, Secretary of State  &UR; Madeleine Albright &LR; 
has discussed the prospects of a position for the first lady with
Secretary-General  &UR; Kofi Annan &LR; . Mrs. Clinton is said to be
interested in working with refugees or on human rights issues.
</P>
<P>
   The White House refused to comment on the story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE TO THE LOVELORN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, despite the best of possible intentions, and some
pretty nifty gifts, too _ books of poetry and T-shirts and power
ties _ things just don't work out. But what are a guy and a gal to
do (after testifying)?
</P>
<P>
   Remember, you are not alone. Whatever you've done, someone else
has been there, done that. Twist magazine includes a first-person
account: ``Sometimes we'll be kissing and things will get pretty
hot and heavy, and he'll say, Do you want to? And I'll just be
like, No, not now. He doesn't get mad about it. ... We've been
doing plenty of other stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   All About You magazine advises the guy that if the girl
``spreads gossip about you,'' it's not a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   Teen magazine advises the girl who's just broken up with her
boyfriend: ``Use dating downtime to focus on your studies, get
organized, deepen friendships and generally go for your goals with
renewed fervor. Look at the bright side: You're free to hang with
the girls all night, and you can flirt your fanny off whenever you
want.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STILL IN THE LOOP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; George &LR;  and  &UR; Charlotte Mailliard Shultz &LR;  were to celebrate
their anniversary last Thursday with a day of culture that included
a personal tour by curator  &UR; Renee Dreyfus &LR;  of the ``Ancient Gold _
The Wealth of the Thracians'' show at San Francisco's Palace of the
Legion of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   But late last Wednesday, the day before the United States bombed
Sudan and Afghanistan, former Secretary of State Shultz postponed
the Thursday festivities. Informed about the bombing on Wednesday,
he knew he'd be busy all day Thursday providing knowledgeable TV
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It was  &UR; Chelsea Clinton &LR;  who asked that  &UR; Jesse Jackson &LR;  come to
the White House last week, reports U.S. News &AMP; World Report. The
first daughter thinks that Jackson has forged a connection
``between the spiritual and political worlds,'' a White House
adviser told the magazine, ``and Chelsea is a very spiritual
person.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROLLING PEBBLE GETS MARRIED &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Angela Richards &LR;  did get married last week, at her father
 &UR; Keith Richards &LR; ' home outside London. Keith gave away his daughter,
who walked down the aisle to a recording of the Stones' song
``Angie.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Richards and  &UR; Ron Woods  &LR; made some music, neither
 &UR; Mick Jagger &LR;  nor  &UR; Charlie Watts &LR;  was there, which was probably a
result of their tax problems. If the two had entered England,
reported the Chicago Sun-Times, ``it would have cost them a ton of
cash.''
</P>
<P>
   Jagger's wife,  &UR; Jerry Hall &LR; , and their children were there, as
well as  &UR; Kate Moss  &LR; and onetime Jagger girlfriend  &UR; Marianne &LR; 
 &UR; Faithfull &LR; , who said the wedding was ``magical.''
</P>
<P>
   (Brides magazine advises prospective brides and grooms to do
everything in their power to encourage wedding guests to mail gifts
rather than bring them to the reception, where ``there's the
potential for theft and for cards to become detached.'')
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely tired of playing those loser roles. Unless
they're really, really funny.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jerry Stiller, who appears in ``There's Something About Mary''
and ``Your Friends and Neighbors,'' in W.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1850EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
