<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9768 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT &LR;      08-24 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., N.Y.)  (js) 
 BY ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Diego Della Valle doesn't believe in standing still.
Della Valle, the owner of J.P. Tod's , whose Italian-made shoes and
bags have in the last couple of years leapt into the high-status
category, is expanding his business on several fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Not content with the four Tod's stores selling all of the
company's products in this country (in Los Angeles, Miami,
Manhasset and Manhattan), he is opening 22 in-store boutiques just
for his handbags starting next month at Bergdorf Goodman, Neiman
Marcus and Saks Fifth Avenue. They will be designed to look like
his own stores, with glass, stainless steel and the same calfskin
used for the handbags, said Claudio Castiglioni, the chief
executive of J.P. Tod's in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which also has 23 J.P. Tod's shops in Europe and
four in Asia, introduced a striking new advertising campaign in the
September issues of fashion magazines, featuring twin images of the
model Yasmin Le Bon on a dark background with her accessories in
shadow. Close-ups of the shoes or bags are on the facing page.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Della Valle has added styles like boots, ballet
flats and sandals to the classic driving shoes that put his company
on the fashion map. And he is planning to open boutiques next year
for his casual Hogan's line in Manhattan and Los Angeles. Although
there are 10 Hogan's boutiques in Europe, the line was introduced
in this country only last spring, at Bergdorf Goodman, and is now
the fastest-growing segment of the business, with 20 more stores
set to open next year in Europe and a line of men's shoes to come.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan's is part of the company's strategy to appeal to a
younger, hipper customer than the establishment types who favor
Tod's. The Hogan shoes sell for $165 to $295; the Tod's range from
$245 to $1,700.
</P>
<P>
   To fuel the company's expansion, a $46 million complex has been
built in Italy near the city of Ancona, with 350 employees devoted
solely to research and design.
</P>
<P>
   There are also three company-owned factories where the shoes,
bags, belts and small leather goods are made. Annual retail sales
are now at $400 million and have been increasing by 20 percent to
25 percent a year, Castiglioni said.
</P>
<P>
   Kamali's `Celebrity' Service
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Norma Kamali has only one store, at 11 East 56th St.,
where her ready-to-wear, swimwear and athletic clothing are sold.
But she is also finding new ways to expand her business. In
addition to a Web site (www.omo-norma-kamali.com), where users
anywhere in the world can find her designs, Ms. Kamali is offering
a shop-at-home service.
</P>
<P>
   Working from a customer profile obtained through e-mail or a
telephone interview, a Kamali personal shopper sends a selection of
clothes by Federal Express to the client, who can try them on at
her leisure, keep what she wants and return the rest. What she buys
is then charged to her credit card. Ms. Kamali calls the service
``Shop Like a Celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been shipping things to our celebrity clients that way
for 10 or 15 years,'' she said. ``Our staff is used to working that
way. Then I thought that was really crazy. Why just celebrities? I
would like that service for myself, so I thought we'd try it first
with our tried-and-true clients. A lot of our European clients we
see once or twice a year, so we started with them. Then the sales
people in my shop said a lot of their Manhattan customers were
asking if we would send things to their offices.''
</P>
<P>
   She continued: ``It's been a slow increasing, increasing,
increasing way of doing business, but in the last two years it's
become very important. It's part of the way we interact with the
client. We train our staff to get the right information. It's not
just a shot in the dark. Some clients we haven't ever seen in the
store.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers have to pay for shipping, but it costs a lot less than
a plane ticket. Or possibly even a taxi.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1851EDT &QL; 
