<HEADER>
A9773 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPAIN-HOTELS-450&AMP;ADD-     08-24 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-HOTELS-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPANISH HOTEL COMPANIES ARE GOING GLOBAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By AL GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ A quickening battle in the domestic hotel market
and increasing competition from abroad have sent traditional
family-run Spanish hotel companies scrambling to ensure their
future, with nearly a billion dollars already committed to new
investments.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of the changes came earlier this month, when the
family-owned Barcelo Empresas agreed to sell controlling stakes in
its only two properties in the United States: the Radisson Barcelo
hotels in Washington, D.C., and Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The buyer is a consortium being formed by Barcelo, a tour and
hotel company on the island of Majorca; Argentaria, a major Madrid
bank, and Fomento de Construcciones y Contratas, or FCC, one of
Spain's largest construction companies. Barcelo will retain its
core businesses but is pledging the stakes in its U.S. properties,
which the consortium says are worth $48 million, as its ticket to
join the new enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium plans to invest $600 million to buy or build
hotels in the next two years in Spain and abroad, and to bolster
Barcelo's current management of 44 hotels in nine countries,
including the two Radissons operated under franchise, to about 80.
</P>
<P>
   After a generation of slow growth, several Spanish families that
started with one hotel, like Barcelo in 1962, and nudged up to
mid-size companies are now bracing for tougher global competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need more capital to grow more quickly,'' said Jesus
Garcia de Ponga, head of Argentaria's principal real estate
division. ``If not, other groups will capture the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, four family-controlled Spanish companies _
Barcelo, Occidental Hoteles, Riu Hoteles and Sol Melia _ plan to
add to their combined total of 103 hotels in the Caribbean and
Latin America, where expanding tourism and relatively low operating
costs have beckoned with 20 percent returns on investment.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the companies have invested in hotels just across the
Mediterranean in Morocco and Tunisia. And all are on guard against
foreign challengers, like Britain's Bass PLC and its Holiday Inns,
which are poised to enlarge their small presence in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   France, the United States and Spain itself ranked in that order
as the world's top three tourist destinations in 1997, according to
the World Tourism Organization, which is based in Madrid. But
competitive tour pricing that now makes it almost as easy for
Europeans to vacation in the Caribbean as on Spain's beaches has
changed the rules for Spain's fragmented hotel market, where small
owners still predominate.
</P>
<P>
   ``For survival, you need hotels in a lot of different places''
with coordinated reservations systems, Garcia de Ponga said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last May, Occidental Hoteles, a Madrid chain, announced plans
with Spain's largest savings bank, La Caixa, to invest $320 million
to build eight resort hotels in the Dominican Republic, Mexico and
Spain's Canary Islands by 2001. They will be added to Occidental's
current management of 54 hotels in eight nations.
</P>
<P>
   The mid-size companies are dwarfed by Spain's largest family-run
hotel company, Sol Melia. It started in Majorca in the 1950s and
now manages 245 hotels with 60,000 rooms in 25 nations.
</P>
<P>
   While Occidental and Barcelo are talking about selling shares on
the Madrid Stock Exchange, Sol Melia was the first Spanish hotel
company to list, in 1996, raising $275 million from the sale of a
45 percent equity stake. This year, a related real estate company,
Melia Inversiones Americanas, based in Amsterdam, Netherlands, was
listed separately on the Madrid bourse. It owns six hotels in the
Caribbean and Latin America, all managed by Sol Melia, and is
building four more in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Only one other Spanish hotel firm, HN Hoteles, is traded in
Madrid, although indirectly, as the largest asset of the Spanish
hotel and beverage group Cofir. Last year, Cofir bought out NH's 66
hotels in Spain from its founder, Antonio Catalan, who has since
started another hotel group, called AC.
</P>
<P>
   Most Spanish hotel families still shy away from public listings
because they ``fear they'll lose control by trading on the
market,'' said Fernando Rosello, an analyst with Credit Lyonnais
Securities in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking other formulas, Riu Hoteles, a Majorca firm that manages
75 hotels in six nations, including one in Miami and another in
Orlando, Fla., continues its 22-year alliance with the large tour
operator Touristik Union International of Hanover, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Grupo Hosteleria Unida, based in Barcelona, aims within five
years to double its current portfolio of 200 hotels through
franchising, which requires less capital risk.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidation in the hotel sector is growing steadily, starting
at the top. Chains are involved in just 20 percent of Spain's 5,780
hotels, but they run 55 percent of the 766 premium four- and
five-star establishments.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign chains manage less than 1 percent of Spain's hotels, but
some have big expansion plans. Bass, which has two Holiday Inns, a
Crowne Plaza, two Intercontinentals and a Holiday Inn Express in
Spain, will invest $30 million by 2001 for five more Holiday Inn
Express budget hotels in Spain. The French group Accor, with 12
hotels in Spain, including its upscale Novotel and Sofitel brands,
will build 50 Ibis and 30 Formule I hotels, its budget brands,
within five years.
</P>
<P>
   At the high end of the Spanish market is Starwood Hotels and
Resorts Inc., based in White Plains, N.Y. Earlier this year, it
acquired ITT/Sheraton, which operates five luxury hotels in Spain,
including the 440-room Palace Hotel in Madrid near the Prado.
</P>
<P>
   The $42 million renovation of the Palace, completed last
December, has paid off with increased business conferences and more
guests from abroad, said John H. Henderson, the hotel's general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   But foreign companies shopping for hotel deals in Spain, he
added, have balked because a lot of the properties are outdated and
would require costly overhauls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entry format needs to be a new build or an acquisition
which would require a major rehabilitation,'' Henderson said.
``That's why many haven't come in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
