</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLAIBORNE-SUIT-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DISMISSES WORKERS' COMPLAINTS AGAINST LIZ CLAIBORNE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge in Manhattan has thrown out all
claims contained in a lawsuit against garment manufacturer Liz
Claiborne, which was accused of improperly conspiring with union
leaders to betray the interests of workers at a Brooklyn sweater
factory. But the judge refused to dismiss two of the workers' key
complaints against the union.
</P>
<P>
   The opinion, released Aug. 18 by Judge Harold Baer in Manhattan,
came in response to motions by Claiborne and the Union of
Needletrades, Industrial and Textile Employees, known as Unite,
which had sought to have the case dismissed in its entirety.
Although the judge refused to eliminate two claims against the
union, he noted that ``undoubtedly it will be difficult for the
plaintiffs to ultimately prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Unite, Jo-Ann Mort, said Baer's ruling came
``at an early stage of the judicial process,'' before the union had
an opportunity to submit evidence on its behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident that the case will be dismissed completely on
summary judgment, after we have had an opportunity to submit
evidence,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual lawsuit was filed last fall by employees of
Mademoiselle Knitwear Inc. in Brooklyn, once a showcase of
union-management cooperation but now in bankruptcy amid a tangle of
angry litigation.
</P>
<P>
   The workers asserted that Liz Claiborne had reneged on a
commitment to order a substantial volume of sweaters from
Mademoiselle, and that the union had improperly agreed to settle an
arbitration case aimed at enforcing that commitment. In exchange
for the settlement, the workers charged, Claiborne agreed to pay
the union approximately $20 million over three years, none of which
would benefit the workers.
</P>
<P>
   Because Baer dismissed all of the workers' claims against
Claiborne, those accusations ``must be considered thoroughly
discredited,'' said Roberta S. Karp, Claiborne's general counsel.
Having also won an earlier trademark infringement case against
Mademoiselle, she said, the company was confident that it would
also win a separate lawsuit pending against it by Mademoiselle.
</P>
<P>
   Baer also dismissed the portions of the complaint that accused
the union of accepting what the workers termed ``a bribe'' from
Claiborne in exchange for settling the arbitration claims. Federal
labor laws limit the enforcement of union anti-bribery provisions
to government prosecutors, not to private plaintiffs, the judge
ruled. He added that the matter was being referred to the Manhattan
District Attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Karp said the payment was legitimately made under the terms
of Claiborne's contract with the union and the prosecutor's office
``has been aware for over a year of the allegations the court
referred, and it has taken no action.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Baer also dismissed all claims against the specific local, Local
155, that represented workers at Mademoiselle, because it had
played no role in the arbitration dispute or its settlement. The
arbitration had been undertaken on behalf of Mademoiselle workers
by another union local, Local 23-25, with support from the parent
union.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge rejected arguments by Unite and Local 23-25 that
their indirect relationship with the Mademoiselle workers barred
any claims against them for not fairly representing those workers.
``The actions attributed to Unite and Local 23-25 in initiating,
conducting and settling the arbitration claims'' provided
sufficient grounds for the workers to assert in court that they had
not been fairly represented, Baer ruled.
</P>
<P>
   To prevail, he noted, the workers will have to show that the
union's settlement of the arbitration claims against Claiborne was
``arbitrary, discriminatory, or in bad faith'' _ a very difficult
hurdle, he added. ``Nonetheless, at this stage of litigation, the
plaintiffs should be allowed to proceed,'' he ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Rhine, the lawyer for the Mademoiselle workers, said he
was encouraged by the ruling, and was confident that the remaining
claims in the complaint would move forward to trial next spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
