<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIE-RIPTIDES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Riptides part of the dangerous hurricane package
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Of all the dangers that swimmers and waders face at
the beach, rip currents - also called riptides or undertows - are
the most dangerous, say lifeguards and coastal geologists.
</P>
<P>
   And as Hurricane Bonnie spins and surges in the Atlantic, the
danger of the deadly current has increased at many East Coast
beaches. Rip currents believed to be spawned by Bonnie this weekend
claimed the lives of a 25-year-old North Charleston, S.C., man
vacationing at Surfside Beach, S.C., and a 24-year-old man at
Rehobeth Beach, Del.
</P>
<P>
   Several others had near misses. At Neptune Beach, Fla.,
lifeguards rescued two young boys who were dragged out to sea while
standing in knee-deep water. Lifeguards also reported 30 rescues in
Carolina Beach, N.C., and 100 in Atlantic City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities at several East Coast beaches on Monday were
allowing only ankle-deep wading in the surf because of the
currents. ``Certainly the danger of rip currents intensifies with a
storm,'' says Duke University coastal geologist Orrin Pilkey. A
person caught in a rip current will quickly be pulled under or
swept out to sea. Even the strongest swimmers may be unable to
fight it, say water safety experts.
</P>
<P>
   A rip current occurs near a break in a sand bar when water
pushed onto the beach by offshore storms or strong winds escapes
into the sea through the break. As they funnel out to sea, the rip
currents gain force, fan out into a mushrooming slough and then
dissipate. The process continues as more water tunnels through the
sand.
</P>
<P>
   Storms like Hurricane Bonnie create bigger waves, which dump
more water onto the beach and result in greater volumes of water
escaping back into the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Areas with piers, jetties or sand bars are especially prone to
rip currents and should be avoided, says Pilkey.
</P>
<P>
   If you get caught in a rip current, don't fight it, water safety
experts advise. Try to stay calm and afloat by letting the current
carry you away from shore until it begins to dissipate. Swim
parallel to shore until the current weakens, then head back in.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Lifesaving Association estimates that more than 36,000
swimmers were rescued from rip currents in 1997. Florida officials
say that an average 23 persons have died from rip currents per year
in Florida since 1989. No figures are available for Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
