A9778 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-WENDYS-COX     08-24 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-WENDYS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another victory for Coke as fast-food chain signs on for 10
years
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Pepsico, fighting desperately to gain market share,
has lost another round in the cola wars to Atlanta-based Coca-Cola,
which has snared pouring rights with Wendy's International for the
next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Terms were not disclosed for the 10-year contract, which
Wendy's, the nation's third-largest hamburger chain behind
McDonald's and Burger King, awarded to Coca-Cola without inviting
Pepsico to the bidding table.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 2 soft-drink company said it was prepared to offer more
lucrative terms for the account _ and remains willing to do so even
though Coca-Cola and Wendy's have already inked the deal. But
Pepsi's comments were too little, too late, for Wendy's.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't a bidding war,'' said Denny Lynch, a spokesman for
the Dublin, Ohio-based restaurant chain. ``Coca-Cola has invested
heavily in learning our business and assembling an account team
that numbers more than 50 people. That's a partnership. Coke has
earned our business.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy's already pours Coke products in 85 percent of its 4,600
U.S. restaurants and all 600 of its international locations,
through contracts going back to the mid-1980s. Pepsi brands are
served by between 700 and 800 U.S. franchisees, but will be phased
out of those locations as contracts expire in the next few years,
Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   Having a system-wide soft drink supplier will help Wendy's make
better use of its advertising budget, which will get an estimated
$133 million infusion from Coca-Cola over the life of the contract.
Coca-Cola plans to fork over $42 million for Wendy's national
advertising in the first year, plus 32 cents for every gallon of
soft drink syrup the chain buys during the remaining nine years,
according to a letter to franchisees from Gordon F. Teter, Wendy's
chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   That cash contribution will surely have strings attached,
requiring Wendy's to showcase Coca-Cola products in its
advertising, said Dennis Lombardi, executive vice president of
Technomic, a food service consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke isn't going to give a check for $130 million to just let
Dave Thomas do more commercials,'' Lombardi said. ``To some degree,
that's part of Coca-Cola's advertising campaign, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Pirko, a New York beverage consultant, said Coca-Cola's win
signals that its fountain soft drink business is better run than
Pepsi's.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a flat-out offer to simply pay more for the account isn't
enough, that tells you there are some distinct differences. Coke is
simply the preferred brand,'' said Pirko. ``And if Pepsi was
willing to do anything to buy the business, they'd probably be
accused of predatory pricing and literally cashing in.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico filed a federal anti-trust suit against Coca-Cola May 7,
charging that it uses unfair trade practices to dominate the $15
billion U.S. fountain market. Coca-Cola argued in court last week
that the suit should be dismissed, and a ruling on that issue is
expected any day.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts estimate Coca-Cola has two-thirds of the U.S.
fountain business, compared with Pepsi's estimated 24 percent.
Coca-Cola has a 43.9 percent total share of the U.S. carbonated
soft drink market, and a 49.7 percent global share. Pepsi's U.S.
market-share is 30.9 percent, and it has a 20.3 percent share
world-wide.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
