<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY DISMISSES SUHARTO'S SON-IN-LAW, A TOP GENERAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.C., Ga.)   (jw) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ The Indonesian military, pressing ahead
with a risky housecleaning that has involved exhuming bodies and
investigating high-ranking officers, Monday discharged a son-in-law
of former President Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   One of Suharto's most aggressive and feared generals, the
son-in-law, Lt. Gen. Prabowo Subianto, symbolized for many people
the repressive nature of the country's military.
</P>
<P>
   The former chief of the special forces, known as Kopassus, which
gained a reputation for efficiency and brutality, Prabowo has been
implicated in the abduction and torture of political dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing Prabowo's discharge, the armed forces chief, Gen.
Wiranto, said Prabowo, 47, could still face a court-martial as more
evidence emerges about the abduction of more than two dozen
dissidents earlier this year. At least 14 are still missing and are
feared dead.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups say Prabowo could also be implicated in
other acts of brutality, including instigating the riots, arson and
rape last May that precipitated Suharto's downfall.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's announcement day was criticized for not going far
enough by a group representing the families of the missing
dissidents. Their statement illustrated the public pressure and
scrutiny that, for the first time in decades, has put the military
_ known by its Indonesian acronym, ABRI _ on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that decision, ABRI showed no willingness to
substantially or institutionally correct its repressive policies,
which include the act of kidnapping,'' said the group's leader,
Munir, who like many Indonesians uses only one name.
</P>
<P>
   Wiranto said his decision was made ``without any pressure from
any side or person and it is clearly in the interest of ABRI and
that of the nation and the state.'' He said dismissal was a harsh
punishment for a high-ranking officer.
</P>
<P>
   Since Suharto was forced from office three months ago, the
military has embarked on a painful self-analysis under the harsh
eye of a newly liberated press.
</P>
<P>
   Two soldiers have been sentenced to prison for their part in the
killings of four student demonstrators that touched off the
citywide rioting in mid-May. But human rights groups say
higher-ranking culprits remain unpunished.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of soldiers have been withdrawn from the disputed
territory of East Timor, where the military is implicated in
widespread killings and brutality. And in the island province of
Aceh, scores of bones of people believed to have been executed by
the army in a 1989 insurgency were exhumed during the weekend from
a mass grave.
</P>
<P>
   A separate government investigation is under way into the riots
in May in which 1,200 people died and thousands of buildings were
burned, vandalized and looted.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups have gathered evidence that much of the
damage was coordinated by organized groups, and Prabowo is expected
to be questioned about a possible military role in the destruction,
which also included attacks on Chinese-owned businesses and the
rapes of scores of ethnic Chinese women.
</P>
<P>
   Wiranto has stated his commitment to reform and his allegiance
to the new government of President B.J. Habibie. But the shape of
these reforms is still being debated within the military.
</P>
<P>
   Wiranto moved quickly to consolidate his grip on the military
immediately after Suharto's resignation. Within hours, he had
removed Prabowo from his command of troops and assigned him to head
a military academy.
</P>
<P>
   Wiranto, like Habibie, was a close associate of Suharto. But
both men have been leading the way into a more open post-Suharto
era with pledges of democracy and human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Prabowo, who is married to Suharto's second daughter, reacted
furiously, and Habibie said the general accosted him at his home,
forcing Habibie to take shelter for the night in a safe house.
Suharto and his family, meanwhile, retired to their homes in
Jakarta, where they remain, out of the public eye, reportedly
angling to secure their wealth from public investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Wiranto also announced the demotion Monday of two of Prabowo's
allies, Maj. Gen. Muchdi Purwopranjono _ who succeeded Prabowo as
head of the special forces _ and Col. Chairawan, who was in charge
of the unit's intelligence unit.
</P>
<P>
   Ten lower-ranking officers from the unit face trial in a
military court in connection with the kidnappings.
</P>
<P>
   The actions follow an investigation by a tribunal of seven
generals known as an ``honor council,'' during which Prabowo was
reported to have admitted responsibility for the abductions, saying
he had misinterpreted orders from above.
</P>
<P>
   Wiranto said the investigation showed that the special forces
unit was involved in the abductions, under orders to ``uncover
several movements then considered radical and jeopardizing
government programs and public security.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambitious and aggressive, Prabowo aroused the resentment of many
of his fellow officers with his quick rise through the ranks, to
become the youngest general in the history of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   He trained in the United States at the Special Forces school in
Fort Bragg, N.C., and at the advanced infantry school in Fort
Benning, Ga., and was known as a professional, if rough-edged,
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Wiranto said Monday that Prabowo's military career is over. ``He
will not be active any more within the armed forces,'' Wiranto
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
