<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9781 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MERRILL-SEC-BOS &LR;      08-24 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-SEC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL TO PAY $2 MILLION TO SETTLE ORANGE COUNTY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. agreed Monday to pay a $2 million fine
levied by the nation's top securities regulator to settle charges
that it led Orange County, Calif. into the biggest municipal
bankruptcy in US history.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, with the Securities and Exchange Commission,
ends an expensive and closely watched saga for the nation's largest
brokerage, which agreed in June to pay a hefty $437.1 million to
the southern California county to resolve $2 billion in damage
claims.
</P>
<P>
   It also brings into the home stretch a raft of SEC probes into
companies and officials involved in the county's 1994 financial
collapse. ``Although there may be additional enforcement action,
the bulk of our investigations and probes related to the Orange
County case is finished,'' said Elaine M. Cacheris, director of the
SEC's Pacific regional office.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch has been under a cloud since mid-1994, when it
sold Orange County $875 million in risky, interest-sensitive
securities that soured into a shocking $1.6 billion loss when
interest rates rose later that year.
</P>
<P>
   The financial crisis led Orange County, just south of Los
Angeles, to declare bankruptcy in December 1994, and made
derivatives, a complex form of security that is lucrative for the
companies that sell them, a dirty word. It also cast a pall over
Merrill Lynch, which officials accused of not providing necessary
information to county officials and investment bankers about the
derivative-linked bonds it was underwriting for Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   While among the larger fines ever levied by the SEC for
unintentional fraudulent conduct, the penalty did not require the
Wall Street investment behemoth to admit wrongdoing. Instead, the
settlement reproached Merrill Lynch for lax disclosure about its
investment strategy for the county's investment pools. In 1995
Merrill Lynch paid $12 million to various Massachusetts authorities
to settle charges of irregularities in its municipal-bond work for
the Bay State.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that in an era of rapid consolidation in the
financial services industry, Merrill Lynch had desperately wanted
to put the debacle behind and move on. ``They had been spending
millions on this and wanted it out of their hair,'' said a New York
banking analyst who declined to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``As far as the government is concerned, the case
against Merrill is closed, and this (the civil penalty) was a slap
on the wrist.'' The SEC settlement did not name Michael Stamenson,
the whiz-kid Merrill Lynch broker in San Francisco who carried out
the ill-fated securities sales.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch nudged up 13/16 to close at 84 15/16 on the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange County saga may be over for Merrill Lynch, which
played the largest role in the episode, but it is not finished for
the California municipality. The nation's fifth-largest county has
so far recovered around $739 million via lawsuits against banks,
brokerages, accountants, and law firms that helped sell the
ill-fated securities. The county has since gotten back on its feet
financially.
</P>
<P>
   Outstanding cases include an SEC lawsuit against Minneapolis
investment firm Dain Rauscher Corp. charging fraud in selling $1
billion in Orange County notes.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch's June settlement with the county came one month
after CS First Boston agreed to pay $52.5 million. Last month,
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. and Nomura Securities, the
Japanese brokerage, settled for $117.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC, the securities industry watchdog, reached its own
settlement with CS First Boston in January. An investigation by law
enforcers into former Orange County treasurer Robert Citron led to
his conviction in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
