</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MEDIA25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEDIA FACES QUANDARY OVER GRAPHIC DETAILS OF WHITE HOUSE SEX
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the Internet and talk radio abuzz with rumors
of kinky sex in the Oval Office, increasingly graphic accounts of
the relationship between President Clinton and Monica Lewinsky are
making their way into the mainstream news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Standards are in the toilet, and not just in the White
House,'' said Larry Sabato, a professor who teaches about politics
and the media at the University of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Salacious reports sometimes percolate up through the tabloid
press and online sites such as the Drudge Report, and often are
first printed in general circulation newspapers abroad. When they
reach a critical mass, American newspaper editors and TV producers
feel pressured to deal with the story, explained Sabato, who
criticized the practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The justification is that 'our readers expect us to explain
what's already out there','' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sabato noted that one rumor about an unusual act involving
Clinton and Lewinsky was sweeping the country on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where it originated,'' he said, saying he had
received dozens of phone calls and e-mails about the report. ``It
could be a top-down rumor.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports of ``unusual'' sexual activities in the Clinton scandal
are not appearing just in the non-traditional media.
</P>
<P>
   ``More rude shocks await. Mrs. Clinton, the U.S. Congress and,
ultimately, the American people may learn the details of the sexual
relationship between the president and the former intern _ more,
perhaps than anyone wants to know,'' Newsweek magazine reports in
this week's edition.
</P>
<P>
   Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's report to Congress ``will
include graphic vignettes of sexual encounters in the president's
small study off the Oval Office,'' Newsweek said. ``Starr is known
to believe that the public will be deeply offended by some of the
kinkier details. 'When people read his report, they'll want to
throw up,' said a knowledgeable source.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's edition of the Hotline, an electronic insider's guide
to politics, contained a roundup of media reports of sex acts.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotline reported that radio talk show host and former
Republican political strategist Mary Matalin appeared on NBC's
``Meet the Press'' and urged Clinton to resign before Starr's
report goes to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know inside the Beltway what's in that report,'' she
said. ``And I don't think (Clinton) wants his family to know any
more about what's in that report, or the country needs to hear any
more about tissue, dresses, cigars, ties and anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, NBC correspondent Lisa Myers reported that Lewinsky
had told the grand jury that ``the sex was mutual, involved unusual
practices and included the president touching her in very intimate
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the serious charges facing Clinton involve perjury and
obstruction of justice, it is impossible to report the story
without delving into the relationship. And Clinton has helped
legitimize the detailed coverage by engaging in semantics over what
constitutes sexual relations.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post has not held back any relevant facts, said
Executive Editor Len Downie, but has been careful in its use of
language _ using the phrase ``DNA material'' or other euphemisms
rather than the word ``semen,'' for instance. The Post, as well as
The New York Times, did report the body parts that Lewinsky told
the grand jury the president fondled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The information that our readers should know about the
president of the United States, we're going to publish,'' said
Downie. ``We'll try to do it tastefully.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
