<SLUG> BC-CHEMISTS-COOKIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEMISTS PROMISE HEALTHY COOKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They're the words you've been waiting to hear: Go
ahead, eat that cookie _ it's good for your heart.
</P>
<P>
   You may not have to wait much longer. Cookies, cakes, and other
treats that are beneficial for health are not on the market yet,
but food chemists said Monday they may be available within about a
year. They will be made with a fat substitute derived from oats
that not only may reduce calories, but also may help lower
cholesterol levels.
</P>
<P>
   George E. Inglett, a scientist with the US Department of
Agriculture, said the new fat substitute he developed is the first
such additive that meets federal standards for being advertised as
beneficial for the heart.
</P>
<P>
   The additive &UR;  &LR; will be sold under the name Nu-Trim, said Inglett,
and all proceeds from its sale will go to the federal government,
which funded the research.
</P>
<P>
   The additive is more effective at lowering both total
cholesterol and the ``bad'' form of cholesterol, or LDL, than
natural oatmeal or barley, said Wallace Yokoyama, a scientist at
the USDA research center in Albany, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   That is because the processing involved, which removes most of
the cellulose material from the oats' husk, makes it easier for the
body to absorb the beneficial chemicals, called beta-glucans, from
the oats, Yokoyama said. In his laboratory studies, he said,
Nu-Trim lowered cholesterol levels in rats by 27 percent,
substantially more than unprocessed oats did. And LDL cholesterol
was reduced by 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The processing, Inglett said, involves ``taking out the coarse
stuff that makes (oats) tough, rough, and gritty and hard to add to
other products.''
</P>
<P>
   Inglett, of the USDA's Agricultural Research Service in Peoria,
Ill., said that it is not yet clear how beta-glucans lower
cholesterol, but tests have clearly shown their effectiveness. He
said a manufacturer must file a formal petition before the FDA
approves the product, but since it is derived entirely from oats it
should qualify as a ``generally recognized as safe'' product.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a new ingredient,'' Inglett said. ``People have been
eating oatmeal since Adam and Eve.''
</P>
<P>
   Inglett has spent the last 10 years working on deriving fat
substitutes from oats and barley, and two of his earlier products,
called Oatrim and Z-Trim, are either on the market or in the
process of being licensed. But this is the first product of his
research that actually provides positive health benefits in
addition to lowering fat intake.
</P>
<P>
   David Busken, a representative of Oak State Products, which
makes cookies that are sold under various manufacturers labels,
said his company has tried the product and found it could be used
to produce a low-fat cookie with the smooth consistency of treats
that contain at least three times the fat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
