<P>
   RUSSIA-CURRENCY (Moscow) One middle-aged woman wiped a tear from
her eye as she emerged from the MOST Bank a block from Red Square,
having just found that Russia's currency crisis had prevented her
from withdrawing savings. At a nearby subway entrance, an old woman
leaned heavy against the railing, carrying two weighty bags filled
with bootleg beer that she would soon sell for a few rubles' profit
to well-off visitors. The ``new'' Russia was replete with such
scenes last week, as devaluation of the ruble threatened to send up
prices once more and lower a standard of living that has already
plummeted through the 1990's. Nearly seven years after the Soviet
Union's fall, ordinary Russians are embittered at their president
and at a government dominated by a new class of bosses. They see
the poverty of pensioners while watching the massive consumption
habits of their country's nouveau rich.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (story will move in the ``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-BRITISH-AIRWAYS (Undated) British Airways is expected to
announce a $2.7 billion order for 59 short-haul Airbus planes, with
options that could bring the overall order to as much as $11
billion. While Boeing also will land an order for 17 Boeing 777s
worth $2.67 billion, the Airbus order is significant in that it's
the first time British Airways has ordered anything but a Boeing
jet. We have off-the record confirmation that the Airbus orders
will be announce tomorrow, and that British Prime Minister Tony
Blair will be on hand. Boeing order may come later.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
