<HEADER>
A9803 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUCK-COX     08-24 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUCK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Life's just ducky _ even though she's really a he
 &HT;    By Bette Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_This is the story of a woman _ and her duck.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Carolyn Wallace, and the duck, Ethel, live in a large
red brick house with Carolyn's husband, Nathan, another duck,
Ricky, and a white Maltese dog named Arthur Deco.
</P>
<P>
   But we digress.
</P>
<P>
   You're probably wondering: Ethel? Ricky? Where are Lucy and
Fred?
</P>
<P>
   There never was a Fred, but there used to be a Lucy until she
got eaten by a hawk in front of Ricky, an act that so traumatized
Ricky, he stood in the Wallaces' basement for 10 months staring
into a corner. (He's fine now, but mean! Which is where Ethel comes
in, but more about this later.)
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, this story really began two years ago at a 92nd birthday
party for Carolyn's grandmother. Carolyn's uncle Albert, who owns a
farm in Ellijay, Georgia, said he knew some people who were selling
ducklings.
</P>
<P>
   Like Marcel Proust's redolent madeleines, the word ``duck,''
says Carolyn, opened a cache of fond memories of her favorite
childhood pet, a particularly affectionate mallard named Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   ``And without thinking,'' she says, ``I sprung from my chair and
said, `Yes!'''
</P>
<P>
   Nathan, not nearly as excited about the idea as Carolyn, began
pondering how to dissuade his wife of two years from becoming a
duck owner. Within minutes he had a plan _ he'd just say no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going home after the party, just as I figured she would,
Carolyn asked me if we could have ducks,'' recalls Nathan, 30. ``I
said no. And the next day we had ducks.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward nine months: The hawk eats Lucy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Afterward, Ricky just wasn't the same bird,'' says Carolyn,
36.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the couple didn't know what to do about the grieving
Ricky. Like swans and other waterfowl, ducks mate for life. And
Ricky, well, he loved Lucy. Then Carolyn saw an ad for ducklings in
a newspaper. Enter Ricky's new mate, Ethel.
</P>
<P>
   But Ethel turned out to be male. Ricky attacked him.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling sorry for Ethel, Carolyn, who still refers to the fowl
as a she (don't ask), took the little duckling under her wing. And
on top of a towel, especially when they watch TV together _ Ethel
isn't totally housebroken yet.
</P>
<P>
   It's been six months since Ethel came to roost at the Wallaces'
home. And life is good. Ethel has his own little plastic pool to
swim in, eats spinach by the handful and entertains the
neighborhood children. Ethel particularly likes to sit in Carolyn's
lap while she drives around town, running errands. He even has gone
to work with Carolyn and Nathan at a family paper supply business.
</P>
<P>
   ``People point at her and say, `Is that a duck?''' Carolyn says
with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Well, as the saying goes, if it walks like a duck and quacks
like a duck ...
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
