<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9806 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOVELESS-COX     08-24 1419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOVELESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Loveless embrassed about being in the spotlight
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patty Loveless doesn't like talking about herself, which is an
interesting dilemma for someone who is famous.
</P>
<P>
   After selling millions of albums and racking up a mantle-full of
awards, the country singer still seems a little embarrassed of the
spotlight, kind of like the shy valedictorian forced to pose for
pictures after the commencement speech. When she talks about her
near-two decade career in country music, she calls it ``The Patty
Loveless Thing,'' as if she's referring to someone else who's
onstage and tossing back a mane of red hair and posing for album
covers in Armani.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a while for her to relax in an interview, but
eventually she lets he guard down to laugh and admit the ``real''
Patty Loveless cleans her own house, washes her own clothes, buys
her own groceries, and drives a Toyota.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to wear both hats. I have to be onstage and be Patty
Loveless, and there are times I'm able to break down and just be
Patty, wife and homemaker,'' she says, calling from a sound check
just before a show in Indianapolis. ``When I'm offstage, I want to
be in blue jeans and real casual clothes, which throws people off.
People come up to me and say 'you almost look like Patty Loveless'.
It's hard to pinpoint me or pick me out, and I prefer to be that
way. I like to be treated as just another person.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's this authenticity that makes Loveless perhaps the
best singer in country music today.
</P>
<P>
   When she rolls into Atlanta's Fox Theatre Wednesday night, the
41-year-old entertainer will unleash songs that have proven to be
the answer to the traditionalist's prayer _ ``lead us not into
temptation'' of pop. While Nashville has spent most of the '90s
signing acts that look and sound like commercial lightweights,
Loveless has never deviated from the mockingbird-pure sound she
honed singing Loretta Lynn tunes when she was a kid growing up in
Pikeville, Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patty is the last of the breed that got signed because of her
talent, and not because of how she looks on a album cover or how
she struts around onstage,'' says country disc jockey Rhubarb Jones
of Y-106.7. `` I actually go out and buy her records, mainly
because I love her voice and her choice of material. She has a hurt
in her voice, a genuine honest ache.''
</P>
<P>
   Loveless' ability to wring the guts out of a tune has earned her
a jukebox full of hits: ``Timber (I'm Falling In Love),''
``Chains,'' ``I'm That Kind of Girl,'' ``Jealous Bone,'' ``The
Nights Too Long,'' ``You Can Feel Bad,'' ``I Try To Think About
Elvis,'' ``Blame It On Your Heart,'' and ``How Can I Help You Say
Goodbye.'' Though first signed to a recording contract in 1985,
Loveless didn't become a power player in the industry until a
decade later, when her album, ``When Fallen Angeles Fly,'' was
named the Country Music Association's album of the year. The
following two years, she walked away with the trophy for female
vocalist of the year, then nabbed a Grammy last February for
country album of the year for her current release, ``Long Stretch
of Lonesome.'' She's nominated for four awards at the upcoming CMA
ceremonies on Sept. 23.
</P>
<P>
   But like a pair of sensible shoes, Loveless has perhaps never
been fully credited for her long and consistent contribution. While
critically acclaimed, ``Lonesome'' hasn't produced the No. 1
singles she's used to. The album's duet between Loveless and George
Jones, ``You Don't Seem To Miss Me,'' was perhaps the most powerful
collaboration to come out of a Nashville studio in years, yet was
shunned by some country stations as being ``too country.'' Imagine
that.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Benson, executive director of the CMA, thinks Loveless will
transcend the current choppy waters of Music City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patty Loveless is a timeless artist,'' he says. ``She's gonna
have the enduring power of some of her forebears like Tammy
Wynette, Dolly Parton and Loretta Lynn _ people where the
credibility and depth of talent will transcend all that's going on
now.''
</P>
<P>
   When dissecting Loveless's sound and success, many in the
industry point to her partner/producer/husband, Emory Gordy, Jr. A
native Atlantan, Gordy has been a fixture on the music scene for
years. Back in his Georgia days in the '60s, he played with the
Classics IV, and even co-wrote the hit ``Traces'' with Buddy Buie .
After heading to Music City, he played bass in several bands,
including the penultimate ?? experience of touring with Elvis
Presley. Along the way, Gordy earned a reputation as a musician's
musician, and wound up playing with Loveless. The two fell in love
and were married, which formed the beginning of what is one of
Nashville's richest creative pairings.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '90s, Gordy, 51, began producing his wife's music,
sheparding her into a more mature and compelling sound. Loveless
material began exploring complex, adult themes, starting with the
hit ``If My Heart Had Windows.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always involved, and ninety percent of the time he's
right,'' Loveless says of Gordy. ``He's just amazing, he blows me
away. I think he's a genius, but he always takes the back seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordy has been instrumental in helping Loveless with one of the
most difficult tasks a vocalist faces: selecting material. For
example, he found the Gary Scruggs/Tony Arata tune ``Long Stretch
of Lonesome,'' which Loveless
</P>
<P>
   says is the perfect example of the type of lyric-driven song she
craves: ``Where the memories that haunt me/are gonna someday be my
friend/when that long stretch of lonesome/comes to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   Says the CMA's Benson: ``Emory is a great partner for her in
helping her pick those songs, and managing to get her to deliver
what he thinks is the best Patty Loveless performance in that song.
The songs they have been able to find for her records are just
incredible. She's one of those people who can take a song and make
it more than it is through her vocal interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   Loveless's tunes are often dark and brooding, choking on the
heartache of loss. She says much of the mood of the last album came
from ``the year from hell,'' which is what she calls 1996. That was
the year an older sister died of emphysema, and Gordy went into the
hospital with pancreatitis.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, she was drawn to songs ``that moved me in some kind
of way. I want my songs to move people, whether they're going
through a bad situation or something that makes them feel good
about life. We all go through the same things.''
</P>
<P>
   Loveless says she is drawn to simplicity _ ``we tend to forget
that simple is very good. A song doesn't have to have a bunch of
fancy lyrics, just say things that are subtle that get to the heart
of things we have all felt.''
</P>
<P>
   Loveless spends most days on the road, on the bus, traveling
from one show to another. She and Gordy rarely have time to visit
the lakehouse they own in Dallas, Ga., although she recalls how
they spent their last visit to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rode around and took in all the old places he used to
play,'' she says. ``There's something about Atlanta that I love. It
makes me feel like part of him. He has a whole lotta family there.
I hope some day we can make it our home.
</P>
<P>
   A Snapshot of Patty Loveless
</P>
<P>
   -- Age: 41
</P>
<P>
   -- Hometown: Pikeville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   -- Influences: A distant cousin of Loretta Lynn, Loveless grew
up to the sounds of traditional country music. One of her first
professional jobs was as the ``girl singer'' with the Wilburn
Brothers. She says a short stint as a rocker in a cover band in the
late '70s helped her with her range and phrasing.
</P>
<P>
   -- The name: At 19, Loveless married drummer Terry Lovelace. The
marriage didn't last, but she kept _ and altered _ his name.
</P>
<P>
   -- Married to: Her producer, Emory Gordy, Jr.
</P>
<P>
   -- What a year: In February, she was nominated for three 1998
Grammy Awards for country album of the year (``Long Stretch of
Lonesome''), best country female performance (``The Trouble With
the Truth''), and best country vocal collaboration (``You Don't
Seem to Miss Me'' with George Jones). The Academy of Country Music
also named her top female vocalist. On Sept. 23, she's up for four
Country Music Association awards.
</P>
<P>
   -- Favorite movie: ``Contact,'' because _ like the heroine in
the film _ Loveless maintains a ham radio license.
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
