<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    George spotlights women in latest issue
 &HT;    By Don O'Braint
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What do a vampire slayer, a birth control activist, and a
cybersex editrix have in common? They're all women, for one thing.
For another, they're on George ($2.95) magazine's list of the ``20
Most Fascinating Women in Politics.'' Guest contributors including
Bob Dole, Lindy Boggs and Dennis Rodman (yes, Dennis Rodman) offer
their views on Sarah Michelle Gellar (Buffy the Vampire Slayer),
Jane Fonda (activist) and Lisa Palac (cyber siren). Others include
Hillary Rodham Clinton, Venus Williams, Mary Bono, Judge Norma
Holloway Johnson, Tina Brown and Monica Lewinsky. Ronald Reagan's
daughter Patti Davis speculates why the former White House intern's
15 minutes of fame have lasted for months. ``We don't care that a
young woman is apparently being manipulated by every man in her
life,'' Davis writes. ``We watch her like we watch a soap opera.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in George, Rosalynn Carter makes the list of the ``Top 10
Most Forceful First Ladies,'' and excerpts from a new book, ``Empty
Without You,'' details the love affair of another first lady _
Eleanor Roosevelt _ and the cigar-smoking journalist Lorena Hickok.
</P>
<P>
   DOING AFTER DI: A year after Princess Diana's death, People
($2.79) revisits the royal family and others to find out how their
lives have changed. The young princes are thriving, Charles and his
mother seem more human, and Camilla Parker-Bowles can now enter
through the front door. And what of Di's brother, Charles Spencer?
Apparently his finest moment was his eloquent eulogy. The British
public no longer has a taste for the man known as Champagne
Charlie, particularly after an acrimonious divorce.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEWSWEEKLIES: Sometimes the best-laid plans go awry.
Immediately following President Clinton's sort of mea culpa last
Monday, Time ($2.95) rushed to press with a special midweek
edition. Unfortunately, the magazine missed the other big story of
the week: the U.S. missile strike on terrorist strongholds in
Afghanistan and Sudan. Newsweek ($2.95), following its usual
schedule, scores a bull's-eye with a detailed article on the attack
and the U.S. war on terrorism. Meanwhile, back at the White House,
Newsweek reports that Hillary Rodham Clinton was said to have been
furious at her husband's ``foolishness'' with Monica Lewinsky. So
were some of the celebrity experts Newsweek polled about the
president's speech. ``The whole thing was pitiful to watch,'' says
Atlanta's Dr. Frank Pittman. Feminist author Camille Paglia agreed.
``I am completely disgusted,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ALLY AND THE FAMILY: In a 556-page issue as heavy as a fat
feline, Harper's Bazaar ($3) manages to wedge a fluffy but
entertaining article on Calista Flockhart between the fashion and
fragrance ads. Cute and flaky as lawyer Ally McBeal, the poster
girl for postfeminism talks about the choices she faces in her
career and private life. One of them is related to the dancing
cyberbaby that appears on the show occasionally. And, in a
companion article, James Servin writes about how TV newswomen such
as Hannah Storm and Katie Couric view themselves as style-setters.
It's not enough to be good, Servin says _ they have to look good.
And that means no more helmet hair.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD ADVICE: In a truly educational article, Life ($3.99) asks
dozens of Americans from Tony Bennett to Frank McCourt to name the
best or worst thing they learned in school. The most valuable
lessons pertain to life skills rather than names and dates of
historical events. Sam Pickering, the model for the teacher in
``Dead Poets Society,'' recalls his terrible record as an athlete.
``I struck out seven straight times when I played baseball. Sports
taught me that my days were going to be ordinary, and instead of
dreaming about the extraordinary and faraway, I learned to
appreciate, and love, the familial and the neighborly.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
