<SLUG> BC-TITANIC-SOUNDTRACK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Second Titantic soundtrack proves that ``My Heart Will Go On''
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``Titanic'' sails again today _ only this time it's not the
ship, the Oscar-winning movie or the home video. It's ``Back to
Titanic,'' the followup to the first soundtrack, which Sony Music
says has worldwide sales of 25 million CDs and cassettes.
</P>
<P>
   The album contains music conducted by James Horner, who won two
Academy Awards for his ``Titanic'' score, and the radio-mix version
of Celine Dion's hit ``My Heart Will Go On,'' which features
dialogue between the film's Jack Dawson (Leonard DiCaprio) and Rose
DeWitt Bukater (Kate Winslet). Also included are two takes of
``Nearer My God to Thee'' and some Irish dance music.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Paramount Video, which has announced plans to ship 20
million copies of the ``Titanic'' video to retailers Sept. 1, Sony
won't say how many copies of the soundtrack are going to stores.
Calvin Thorbourne, a manager at a HMV Music in Atlanta, said the
store will have ``a lot'' of copies of ``Back to Titanic.'' HMV
will sell CDs for $13.99 and cassettes for $10.99. The Best Buy on
U.S. 41 in Atlanta says the CD will be $11.99, the cassette $9.99.
</P>
<P>
   Just how much demand there will be is the question. ``I have no
idea what to predict,'' said Geoff Mayfield, Billboard's Los
Angeles-based pop chart expert. ``The 'Titanic' sequel has a better
shot than most followup soundtrack albums. But people who bought
the first album already have an aural souvenir of the movie, so
will they buy the second?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
