<SLUG> BC-TV-CHARMED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doherty plays another modern witch
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new fall TV season has stars from past series who are
starting over with new characters and shows. This week, we're
taking a look at five of them.
</P>
<P>
   -- Who: Shannen Doherty
</P>
<P>
   -- Best known as: Brenda Walsh, one of the original teens of
``Beverly Hills, 90210.'' A vixen on-screen with a reputation
offscreen as troubled and a troublemaker, Doherty left in 1994 amid
``I Hate Brenda'' clubs and much bad press.
</P>
<P>
   -- Next known as: Prue Halliwell, one of a trio of reluctant
witches who are also sisters in the campy WB drama ``Charmed,''
which debuts Oct. 7 after ``Dawson's Creek.'' (Holly Marie Combs of
``Picket Fences'' and Alyssa Milano co-star.)
</P>
<P>
   -- Dramatic stretch: This time she's literally a witch.
</P>
<P>
   -- Between shows: Did a bunch of TV movies, ranging from ``The
Margaret Mitchell Story'' to cheesy erotica such as ``Blindfold.''
Also did the feature film ``Mallrats.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Behind the scenes: Aaron Spelling, who produces ``90210'' and
``Charmed,'' says he talked to Doherty about returning to ``90210''
this season, but she wanted a new show. She says she still might do
a guest shot as Brenda on some unscheduled finale episode.
</P>
<P>
   -- Looking back: One line in the pilot has been getting laughs:
when Doherty says, ``You made me a witch,'' and Combs replies,
``You were born one.'' ``It was definitely not a play on my image
at all,'' Doherty says. ``Unfortunately, there are quite a few
journalists who refuse to be more imaginative and go with something
else. And if they choose to stick me with that, then that's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Why she's back: ``Oh, maybe the weekly paycheck,'' she jokes.
``I once joked that there are film snobs and that I was going to be
a TV snob that would only do TV.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Preparing for the role: ``I did in fact go out and I bought
about 10 books on witchcraft. I walked in and said, `OK, I need
everything you've got on witchcraft.' I'm sure that somebody at a
bookstore thinks I'm just a complete freak.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Coming Wednesday: Jerry Stiller
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
