<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia's capital filling in for ``The Big Easy''
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Metro Atlanta isn't exactly New Orleans but that won't stop TNT
from making a movie there with Andre Braugher starting next month
that's set in Lousiana's biggest city.
</P>
<P>
   The cable network is scouting locations in metro Atlanta for
``Passing Glory,'' based on a true story about a young black priest
who challenges segregationist conventions in New Orleans by
organizing a basketball game between an undefeated black team and
an all-white prep school squad.
</P>
<P>
   Braugher, an Emmy nominee this year for his final season on
NBC's ``Homicide: Life on the Street,'' will portray Father Paul
Verrett.
</P>
<P>
   The film's producers is a heady list of big-name celebs,
including Quincy Jones and Earvin ``Magic'' Johnson. Directing will
be Steve James (``Hoop Dreams,'' ``Prefontaine'').
</P>
<P>
   Filming is tentatively scheduled to start Sept. 22 and will
likely last from five to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
