<HEADLINE>
IRAQ AND U.S. HARDEN DEMANDS IN U.N. WEAPONS STANDOFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The United States and Iraq hardened their
positions Monday over Baghdad's decision to end cooperation with
weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britain have begun pressing for an end to
periodic sanctions reviews, which would have the effect of keeping
Iraq permanently under a crushing embargo ``until they're back on
the reservation,'' a Western diplomat said. The last review was in
April; the next is scheduled for October.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq insists on a more friendly inspection system and perhaps
another visit, or at least a new initiative, from Secretary-General
Kofi Annan, bypassing the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   The new statements of resolve _ stopping well short of any kind
of military threat on Washington's part _ followed a report to the
Security Council on Monday morning by Annan's special envoy to Iraq
on his unsuccessful attempt last week to persuade the Iraqi
government to resume cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The envoy, Prakash Shah, an Indian diplomat, told the council
members that in two essentially perfunctory meetings with Iraqi
officials in Baghdad earlier this month he had been told that the
United Nations was offering nothing new and therefore there was
nothing to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Burleigh, the deputy U.S. representative said that Shah
``basically said to the council that he's gotten nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. position is that we will be consulting this week,
looking toward a council resolution on Iraq,'' Burleigh said.
``We're suggesting the suspension of sanctions reviews until Iraq
comes back into cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   Nizar Hamdoon, Iraq's representative to the United Nations, said
Baghdad still wants a new body of inspectors to replace the
existing U.N. Special Commission, known as Unscom, which is
responsible for dismantling biological and chemical weapons,
missile systems, and the means to produce them. Iraq has also
stopped cooperating with the International Atomic Energy Agency,
which monitors nuclear developments.
</P>
<P>
   Hamdoon also did not rule out shutting down all future technical
monitoring and surveillance of Iraq in addition to ending surprise
visits by U.N. inspectors, which were terminated on Aug. 5. He said
all options remained open to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have stopped all cooperation with Unscom,'' Hamdoon told
reporters, ``and we are waiting the genuine move on the council's
part to address Iraq's concerns.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Most important is the restructuring of Unscom as a body,''
Hamdoon said. ``Unless this restructuring takes place, Iraq finds
it very difficult _ almost impossible _ to have any meaningful
cooperation with Unscom.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamdoon's pitch to bring the secretary general into direct
negotiations with Iraq again is meeting a cooler reception from
Annan's aides this time, diplomats said. He reached an agreement
with Iraq at meetings there in February, averting a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, which was not enthusiastic about the involvement of
the secretary general earlier this year, now seems intent on
keeping him in the forefront of the debate with Iraq, some council
members say. Iraq has violated its agreement with Annan as well as
Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   Another trip to Baghdad by Annan has been discussed only in
general and preliminary terms, diplomats say. Iraq has not invited
him.
</P>
<P>
   In the Security Council, Iraq is growing more isolated,
diplomats said Monday. More countries are demanding that Iraq
resume cooperation before there can be any effort to re-examine
sanctions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
