<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-PAKISTAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTAN SAYS U.S. MISSILE LANDED THERE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: ATTACK-RDP, ATTACK-SUDAN, ATTACK-U.N.) 
(mk) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ An unexploded American missile, believed
to be a stray from last week's attack on suspected guerrilla
training centers in Afghanistan, has been found in a remote area of
Pakistan, the Pakistani Foreign Ministry said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   This proves that Pakistani airspace was violated during the
missile barrage, the ministry said in a statement, adding that a
formal complaint would be made to the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   The government's accusation seemed to confirm earlier reports
that a missile had been found Saturday near Kharan, in a sparsely
inhabited area of the Baluchistan desert.
</P>
<P>
   Panic-stricken villagers discovered the long object lodged in
the sand and informed local authorities, press reports said, and a
precautionary evacuation was ordered.
</P>
<P>
   The missile was handed over to the military, the Foreign
Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   American officials here had little to say about the allegation.
``The government of Pakistan brought this story to our attention,
and we are looking into it,'' said Richard Hoagland, spokesman for
the American Embassy here.
</P>
<P>
   If the missile did indeed come down within Pakistan, it gives
the government another opportunity to express its indignation about
the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the attack on the camps in Afghanistan, Pakistan had
said that a missile had fallen within its soil, killing several
people. To Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's embarrassment, this charge
was then deemed incorrect and had to be withdrawn. Sharif fired his
intelligence chief for passing along the faulty information.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Pakistan's protests about the American attack have been
delicately measured, attempting to mollify its angry citizens while
at the same time not distancing itself unnecessarily from the
United States, whose influence might be needed to help Pakistan out
of its economic crisis. The country is close to defaulting on
billions of dollars in international loans.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's quandary, partly resulting from economic sanctions
imposed after Pakistan tested nuclear weapons in May, was addressed
in an editorial in Monday's issue of the newspaper Dawn: ``We know
that the United States has a major role to play in any softening or
lifting of sanctions, and yet we now find ourselves in a position
where we cannot in any stretch of diplomatic cleverness condone the
U.S. moves against Afghanistan and Sudan.''
</P>
<P>
   The country is rife with conflicting rumors: that the government
had advance knowledge of the attack and betrayed its allies in
Afghanistan; that the government tipped off the main target, Osama
bin Laden, who is accused by the United States of financing
terrorist attacks, thus saving his life, and that the government
actually attempted to finger bin Laden and pinpoint his
whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Islamic militants here have insisted that Pakistan was a willing
helpmate for the United States' attack in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   One group, the Jammat-I-Islami, has charged that, in preparation
for the attack, American warships breached Pakistani waters in the
Arabian Sea and that the Pakistani navy chose to ignore this
menacing military presence.
</P>
<P>
   But just as the Foreign Ministry was complaining Monday about
American violations of Pakistani airspace, the Defense Ministry
dismissed any notion of American encroachment in its seas, saying
the warships were ``well clear'' of its territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that national interests not be compromised by
making wild statements,'' said a Defense Ministry spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In Afghanistan, the Taliban leader, Mohammad Omar, continued
what has become a running commentary on the behavior of his
country's guest, bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   Omar was quoted by the Afghan Islamic Press as saying that bin
Laden had contritely accepted Omar's rebukes of the day before,
promising to make no more threats against the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked him to refrain from such activities and Osama bin
Laden has accepted our advice and promised to abide by it,'' said
Omar, according to the Pakistan-based news agency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
