<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9817 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-GERMANY-510&AMP;AD     08-24 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-GERMANY-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY FINDS RUSSIA'S PROBLEMS ESPECIALLY WORRISOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: RUSSIA-SHAKEUP, RUSSIA-VOICES, RUSSIA-POWER,
RUSSIA-U.S.)  
(js) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ As Russia staggers through its financial
crisis, few countries are watching with more anxiety than Germany.
</P>
<P>
   German banks are by far the biggest lenders to Russia, with
about $30 billion in outstanding loans. The German government has
guaranteed repayment of most of that money, and stands to lose
billions if the loans go completely sour.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the economic concerns, Germans worry about the political
fallout. Having fought Russia in both world wars and having been
trapped for decades at the epicenter of the cold war, many Germans
are deeply troubled by prospects of a Russian meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main concern of the government is on the political side,''
said Per Fischer, vice president of Commerzbank in charge of
lending to Russia. ``We cannot let Russia, a superpower so near to
Germany, fall deeper and deeper into crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   German political and business leaders did what they could Monday
to calm the markets and the public. Gunter Rexrodt, minister of
economics, quickly announced that the government would continue
guaranteeing loans to Russia as long as Russia carries out the
reforms it has promised the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have a strong interest in a sustained stabilization of
the situation in Russia,'' Rexrodt said. He quickly endorsed the
``experience and recognition'' of Viktor Chernomyrdin, who was
re-appointed as Russian prime minister after having been dismissed
in March.
</P>
<P>
   But others were grim. Jurgen Stark, a senior official in the
German Finance Ministry who is becoming a director of the central
bank, warned Monday that the crises in Russia and Asia had
increased the risks of a global crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a phase in which the global financial system is
highly vulnerable to a crisis,'' Stark said, adding that they could
present the ``greatest challenge of the last 70 years.''
</P>
<P>
   German banks have played an important role in Russia for many
years, but that role grew considerably after the Berlin wall fell
in 1990. As Communism collapsed throughout Central Europe and the
Soviet Union, German manufacturers turned eastward to capitalize on
their central geographic position as well as their ability to
supply the material and equipment for rebuilding those countries.
</P>
<P>
   German banks provided the financing for German exports to Russia
as well as for investment in development projects. And the German
government, primarily through an export-promotion agency called
Hermes, guaranteed the vast majority of the debt.
</P>
<P>
   According to the German Ministry of Economics, Hermes is
guaranteeing more than $30 billion in debt to Russian projects.
Although the Russian government has imposed a 90-day moratorium on
repayment of foreign debts, it has said it will continue to honor
government debt.
</P>
<P>
   Over the long term, industry analysts believe the Russian loans
could have a negative impact on the German budget. But many of the
loans don't come due for years and no one knows how many of them
may go into default.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The uncertainty undercut the German stock market last week,
particularly bank stocks like Deutsche Bank and Commerzbank. But
the banks insist they are fairly secure because the government is
backing so many of the loans. Deutsche Bank has said its
``exposure'' to Russian loans is about $750 million and Commerzbank
has said its exposure exceeds $100 million. But bank executives say
they have already taken loan-loss provisions for about half that
amount.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this long record of support, there was a suggestion
Monday that Germany might have done more to avert the current
crisis. Stanley Fischer, the deputy managing director of the
International Monetary Fund in Washington, told the newspaper
Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung that Russia's problems might have
been mitigated if Chancellor Helmut Kohl had lobbied fellow
European leaders forcefully to supply aid last week.
</P>
<P>
   Otto Hauser, the German government spokesman, said those remarks
were baseless.
</P>
<P>
   For many years Kohl had political as well as economic reasons to
support relations with Russia. It was Mikhail Gorbachev who let it
be known that Russia would not block the reunification of Germany,
a moral debt that Kohl highlighted on Sunday as he talked about the
reunification of Germany in a campaign speech.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, German bankers and government officials found
themselves scrambling just to find someone to talk to in Moscow.
Monday was supposed to be the day that Russian government leaders
sat down with Western banks, led by Deutsche Bank and J.P. Morgan,
to discuss a restructuring of payment on Russian bonds.
</P>
<P>
   But bankers said it was impossible even to begin discussions,
because Russia didn't have a real government in place. The Russians
were represented by the deputy chairman of the Russian central
bank, and European banks generally sent local representatives
rather than top executives from their headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer, of Commerzbank, said German bankers were worried about
an absence of capable financial managers in Russia and had even
contemplated offering to lend Russia some of their own experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main concern is that the Russians find the necessary
managerial skills,'' he said. ``We feel the Russians are lacking,
to a certain extent, the competence and the good people to manage
the massive problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, European political leaders divided their time Monday
between insisting that Russia follow through on its economic
reforms and declaring that the Russian crisis would have no severe
impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian crisis will have no decisive impact on European
growth,'' asserted Jacques Santer, president of the European
Commission, speaking at a symposium in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl spoke with Yeltsin over the weekend, aides told reporters
in Bonn, and told him that he had to follow through on reforms. The
most important reform is the tax system, which has become
increasingly incapable of collecting taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But in a frank admission of the limits to outside pressure,
German Finance Minister Theo Waigel said Monday that Western
governments would ultimately have to deal with whomever ends up in
power in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe it makes any sense for us to get mixed up in
creating the Russia government,'' Waigel told German news agencies
Monday. ``We have to work together with the people that are
named.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
