<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOB INFORMANT INVOKES FIFTH AMENDMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Repeatedly confronted on the witness stand with an FBI
paper trail detailing his years informing on the Mafia _ including
dinner meetings with mob bosses in the North End and a personal
introduction to the head of the Patriarca crime family _ Stephen
Flemmi had a ready response.
</P>
<P>
   He took the Fifth.
</P>
<P>
   In his third day of testimony in US District Court, Flemmi
invoked his right against self-incrimination more than 70 times,
refusing even to admit to the inside information he'd given his FBI
handler, H. Paul Rico, in series of informant reports filed by Rico
in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi, who helped the FBI bug mob hangouts and dismantle the
Mafia hierarchy during three decades of sporadic informing, refused
to acknowledge his dealings with the crime family he infiltrated,
and would not talk about his role in several murders, dating to the
late 1960s, with which he is currently charged.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a wide-ranging racketeering indictment that charges
him with four killings and accuses his Winter Hill Gang with a
decades-long conspiracy with the Mafia, Flemmi wouldn't say
anything too incriminating _ even though federal prosecutors
promised it wouldn't be used against him when Flemmi is tried on
those charges, which stem from a series of indictments in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Only reluctantly did Flemmi admit to running a gambling and
loansharking operation in Boston's Roxbury section in the 1960s;
``It was a way of life in them days,'' he said. But he preferred to
portray himself as someone ``mainly involved in real estate.''
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi dodged questions from federal prosecutor Fred M. Wyshak
Jr. about his early contact with Rico, and was evasive about Rico's
rationale for asking him to visit the North End. ``He wouldn't send
me down there to play whist,'' said Flemmi.
</P>
<P>
   ``They trusted you because of the level of criminal activity
that you were involved in with them?'' Wyshak asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's correct,'' Flemmi replied.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi refused to answer questions about the murders of brothers
Edward Bennett, Walter Bennett and William F. Bennett, who were
killed within months of each other during a gangland war in 1967,
or the murder of Richard Grasso that same year.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi was more talkative, however, about the core claim
underlying pretrial hearings before US District Judge Mark L. Wolf:
that he was promised immunity from prosecution in exchange for
information he provided the FBI on the Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never convicted for anything in the '60s _ nothing _ and
I was involved in criminal acts,'' Flemmi said during nearly four
hours of cross-examination by Wyshak.
</P>
<P>
   Asked specifically what Rico did to keep him out of jail, Flemmi
answered, ``He never really spelled it out for me who he would go
to. I just expected it. ... I was looking for results, I got the
results I was looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi claims he escaped prosecution because of his deal with
the FBI and is asking Wolf to throw out the 1995 indictments
charging him, his fugitive criminal partner James ``Whitey''
Bulger, New England Mafia boss Francis P. Salemme and two others
with a decades-long criminal conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   A string of present and former FBI agents and supervisors,
including Rico, &UR;  &LR; has denied that Bulger and Flemmi were given
permission to commit any crime short of murder, as Flemmi contends.
The government argues that even if rogue agents made such a promise
it would not be legally enforceable.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi claims that when he returned to Boston in 1974, after
five years on the run from charges that he bombed the car of a
Boston attorney, Rico got a fugitive warrant dropped and helped him
get released on bail. Flemmi was never tried for the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Rico, now retired from the FBI, testified in January that he
never engineered Flemmi's surrender or played any role in getting
the charges against him dismissed. He also denied tipping Flemmi
off to the car-bombing indictment so he could flee.
</P>
<P>
   But Rico also acknowledged that the FBI never launched an
investigation into Flemmi's criminal activities, even after he
reported to them that he had severely beaten a man.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
