BBO-HOMERS (Los Angeles) _ Baseball has had an understandable
fascination with the pursuit of its home run record this season.
Questions of ``if'' have begun to give way to ``when.'' Unlike some
other hitting standards in baseball _ Ted Williams' .400-plus
average, Hack Wilson's 190 RBI _ the direct assault on Roger Maris'
61 home runs has generated a sense of inevitability. And raised the
bar in baseball. It wouldn't be startling if St. Louis' Mark
McGwire finished with 60 home runs this year only to have the
Chicago Cubs' Sammy Sosa whack 62 next year. Or to have McGwire get
63 this year and have Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr. put up 61 next
year. ``After McGwire and them finish this year,'' said former
Cincinnati and Detroit manager Sparky Anderson, ``I think the
standard will be set there, and somebody's got to be 55 or 60 every
year. I don't believe we'll ever have the top dog under 55. It's
just there... Twenty years from now, it could be 60 every year.'' &QL; 
By Eric Noland. (Will move on the ``s'' sports file.)
