STRIP PINGPONG (Peoria, Ariz.) - Two Peoria firefighters, a male
and female, have been reprimanded by the city for playing strip
pingpong while on duty, but some firefighters complain the pair
should have been fired. They accuse the city of granting special
treatment to the female, Jacqueline Verdone, who pocketed a $68,250
settlement earlier this year after complaining she was secretly
videotaped while changing her clothes at a fire station, an
allegation that cost a fire captain his job. By BRENT WHITING.
Story moved in the ``A`` category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CENSUS (Undated) - A controversial method of taking the next census
was struck down by a federal court panel Monday, a move that could
have a significant impact in Arizona, which lost an additional
congressional seat, and millions in federal funding, to undercounts
of minorities in the last decennial census. The Census Bureau is
likely to appeal. By ADRIANNE FLYNN. Story will move in the ``A``
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FALCON (Undated) - After 28 years, the peregrine falcon, the
world's fastest bird, is being removed from the endangered species
list on Tuesday. The bird has more breeding pairs in Arizona than
any other state. ``The first peregrine falcon that I ever saw was
in 1968 in Marble Canyon (Arizona),'' Interior Secretary Brice
Babbitt, the former Arizona governor, said Monday. ``We spent a
long time looking at that bird because they were almost gone.'' By
JEFF BARKER. Story will move in the ``A`` category. &QL; 
