 &QL; 
SHOCKCOLLAR1
</P>
<P>
   (Undated) - Everything about this Airedale pup had been a jolt:
the barking, the jumping, the biting, the nasty little things he
did with his snout. Zeke II was 7 weeks old when I purchased him.
Soon came the smash-mouth realization that I had bought Damian's
hound from hell. As a last resort, I purchased a shock collar. Let
me make it clear to all you animal lovers (like myself) that this
WAS a last resort. I didn't know much about shock collars, other
than that they sounded barbaric and I never imagined using one. But
then, I never imagined a dog like Zeke II. With
</P>
<P>
   SHOCKCOLLAR2, 3, 4. By TOM ROPP. Stories moved in the ``L''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
COMPUTER COLUMN (Undated) - We'd be in a world o' hurt if God had
used a PC for creation!
</P>
<P>
   That's all I can conclude after collecting entries for the past
couple of weeks in our latest contest. Readers were asked to send
in examples of how things would be if God had used a PC to create
things.
</P>
<P>
   First place went to Steve Hrovat, who sent in several great
examples.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite was: ``Having a baby is considered a slow, painful
process by many. This was done out of God's frustration at having
to download an entire universe on a 2400-baud modem. It was a slow,
painful process. He figured he'd make `downloading' a baby an
equally painful process so people realize what he went through.''
By DAVID HOYE. Story moved in the ``F`` category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
EGYPT-EXHIBIT (Portland, Ore.) - The Nile used to flood Egypt every
year. Egypt itself will flood Phoenix this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Splendors of Ancient Egypt'' is an immense exhibit coming
to the Phoenix Art Museum for an Oct. 4-March 28 run. The traveling
show of about 200 pieces of ancient art has visited St. Petersburg,
Fla.; Houston; Detroit; and Portland, Ore. By RICHARD NILSEN. Story
moved in the ``E`` category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
