<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-DISPUTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURER SAYS STOREOWNER WON'T BE ALLOWED TO COLLECT BONUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Treasurer Joseph D. Malone vowed Monday that variety
store Nick Havan, who claimed ownership of a $21 million winning
lottery ticket, will not get his lottery license back or collect a
standard bonus from the state for selling a jackpot winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I have anything to say about it, we will work to
prevent Mr. Havan from turning back on his lottery machine or
collecting the $25,000 commission,'' the Massachusetts official
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Laurence Johnson, Havan's lawyer, said Monday he has a suit
pending in Superior Court seeking payment of the $25,000
commission. He declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Malone's pledge came as he handed a $704,597 check to Paraskeve
Kantges, the 72-year-old Watertown woman who was ruled the winner
of the Mass Millions jackpot. The check is the first of 20 annual
payments that will be issued to the widow.
</P>
<P>
   Malone also presented Kantges with a second check Monday for
$25,501, the amount of interest earned on her winnings while the
dispute was pending.
</P>
<P>
   She was formally declared the winner last week after Havan
withdrew his claim to the jackpot when Kantges agreed to give him
part of her winnings.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Havan and Kantges agreed to ``apportion'' the prize
but keep the details secret. A source familiar with the settlement
said Havan will receive $1 million to drop his claim, which could
have dragged on for years in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the very beginning, it has been clear to me that Mrs.
Kantges has been telling the truth and it's nice that good things
happen to honest people,'' Malone said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   When the dispute erupted in February, Malone accused Havan of
``lying shamelessly'' and said the store owner was trying to
defraud Kantges.
</P>
<P>
   Kantges said she phoned in the winning Mass Millions bet to
Havan at Coolidge Provisions &UR;  &LR; in Watertown on Feb. 5, along with 95
other bets. But when she went to pick up her tickets at the store
the next day, the winning ticket was not among the pile.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Havan insisted he bought the winning ticket himself after
Kantges changed her mind and canceled the bet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The Lottery Commission declared Kantges the winner, after
retired Superior Court Judge Robert Steadman, who heard the
evidence in the case, recommended that they do so.
</P>
<P>
   Kantges has records showing that she has played the winning
combination, &UR;  &LR; 4-6-10-16-19-25, for years. She said the number
signifies her birth, at 4 a.m. on the sixth day of the week Oct.
16, 1925. She says she never canceled the winning bet.
</P>
<P>
   Steadman told the commission it should reject the claim of a
third person, Sonya Bardakjian of Watertown, and award Kantges the
jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Bardakjian, the third claimant, gave the same story as
Kantges. She said she phoned in a bet with the winning number to
Coolidge Provisions along with 36 other bets Feb. 5, and the next
day Havan gave her all the tickets except the winning one.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  But Steadman said a review of Bardakjian's bets established
that she never played the winning number.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
