<SLUG> BC-STRIP-PING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREFIGHTERS DISCIPLINED FOR STRIP PING PONG SESSION 
</HEADLINE>
 PONG-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY BRENT WHITING  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. - Two firefighters, a male and female, have been
reprimanded by Peoria for playing ``strip Ping Pong'' at a Peoria
fire station.
</P>
<P>
   The firefighters, Mario Bravo and Jackie Verdone, were the focus
of a heavily edited investigative report that was released Monday
by City Attorney Steve Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the written reprimands, some Peoria firefighters
complained that Fire Chief Mike Fusco should have handed pink slips
to the pair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody else would have been fired,'' said one firefighter,
who asked that his name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   However, Fusco said he took the steps that were appropriate,
saying he did what was reasonable under the facts of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as firefighters wanting more, we're not going to be
intimidated by vigilante tactics,'' he said. ``I have not been
contacted by any firefighter in the field about the level of
discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusco said no special favors were granted to Verdone, 37, who
rocked the Peoria Fire Department last year by complaining she was
secretly videotaped while changing her clothes in a dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   Her allegation led to the resignation of Jerry Franzmeier, a
Peoria fire captain accused of sparking the scandal by setting up
the camera.
</P>
<P>
   Verdone had stripped down to her panties and bra before she
discovered the camera, according to a lawsuit that Verdone filed
against Franzmeier earlier this year, seeking $1.5 million in
damages.
</P>
<P>
   She later agreed to drop the action after Franzmeier and his
lawyer, Tom Crowe, filed court papers accusing her of defamation,
according to documents in Maricopa County Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago, Verdone was paid $68,250 by Peoria to settle a
civil-rights grievance filed against the city over the camera
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's investigative report said that while on duty earlier
this year, Bravo and Verdone engaged in a round of table tennis in
which the loser of a point or game agreed to remove an item of
clothing.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't strip down to their underwear, but their conduct
warranted disciplinary action under city regulations, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators failed to reach a conclusion on another allegation
accusing Bravo and Verdone of engaging in ``phone sex'' while on
duty at a fire station.
</P>
<P>
   They were accused of using their personal cellular telephones to
engage in sexually explicit talk with each other while in different
rooms at the station, but the report said the allegation could not
be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Verdone, who joined the Fire Department in May 1996, refused to
discuss the matter when reached on her cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no comment and that is my official comment,'' Verdone
said. ``And I don't want to be bothered with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Bravo, a 14-month Peoria employee, could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tellef, a Fire Department spokesman, said he understands
how firefighters may be unhappy about the reprimands, but added,
``The matter is essentially over.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
