A9834 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-MFSPRO-BOS &LR;      08-24 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-MFSPRO-BOS </SLUG>
  
 POZZI SERVES SANTORO AN UNEXPECTED DEFEAt  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ You're never too old to be on a tennis court,
or so it seems. Take Gianluca Pozzi of Italy. He makes a habit of
defying the odds and rankings.
</P>
<P>
   The unseeded Pozzi, 33, did that Monday with a first-round
victory over sixth-seeded Fabrice Santoro that got the weeklong MFS
Pro Championship off to a rousing start. Pozzi, ranked No. 62 and
the oldest player on the ATP Tour, had little trouble in a 6-2, 6-2
victory at Longwood Cricket Club.
</P>
<P>
   There were other significant casualties on day one, not the
least of which was Vince Spadea, the No. 8 seed, who withdrew at
the last minute because of an injured right wrist. That opened the
door for ``Lucky Loser'' Steven Campbell, who had lost in the
qualifying round but was reinstated to fill Spadea's vacancy.
Campbell lasted only long enough to lose in straight sets to
teen-ager Xavier Malisse, 6-3, 6-1. Malisse, ranked 411th, was
playing in his third career match as a pro.
</P>
<P>
   Third-seeded Cedric Pioline survived his opener, beating Adrian
Voinea, 6-4, 6-0. Big guns Michael Chang and Karol Kucera make
their debut today.
</P>
<P>
   Pozzi didn't play like a 33-year-old. He patrolled the baselines
and returned most of Santoro's deep volleys. When Santoro tried to
chip and charge, he couldn't execute and Pozzi took advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll play as long as I feel good,'' said Pozzi, ``and as long
as I'm in the rankings. I'm not looking towards the senior tour. I
can't get there for a couple of years. You have to be 35.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've faced highly ranked players before, and even beat some of
them in important matches. It's not like I'm ranked in the
hundreds. In 1993, I beat both Ivan Lendl and Andrei Medvedev. This
year I beat Marcelo Rios in Great Britian.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 13 years on the tour, Pozzi has seen America's best, but
he hasn't always found a way to win. He is 0-4 against Pete
Sampras, 0-2 against Jim Courier, and 0-1 against Andre Agassi. But
on any given day ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I played a solid match today,'' said Pozzi. ``I stayed quite
deep and didn't make as many mistakes. That's what I have to do. I
know I'm getting older and I see a lot of young players around.
Experience doesn't always help. But you keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   Santoro wasn't happy with his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to go to the net on hardcourt,'' he said. ``But today I
wasn't good enough to play an aggressive game. I was very slow on
the court. No energy. I had trouble making a point because I had no
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Pioline, a wild-card entry, made quick work of Voinea in a
morning match. The first question asked didn't concern his victory
but his appearance in this tournament as a last-minute entry. In
the MFS Pro field, only Kucera (9) and Jonas Bjorkman (12) are
ranked higher than Pioline (17).
</P>
<P>
   ``With the US Open coming up, I came here rather than take a
week off,'' said Pioline. ``I called Friday morning and asked if
there might be a spot. There was, thankfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to play sets and get ready for the Open. In Cincinnati
and Indianapolis, I lost each time in the second round. I think I
can play very good. But sometimes I have bad results. I need to be
more consistent during the year and play some very good
tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   One qualifier who did well was Sebastien Grosjean, who
eliminated John van Lottum, 6-2, 6-0. In the closest match of the
day, Kenneth Carlsen beat Jerome Golmard, 3-6, 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1930EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
