<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9846 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEARNNG-SHARES-BOS &LR;      08-24 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARNNG-SHARES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING CO. SHARES OFF 16 PERCENT ON SALES REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been a rough ride for shareholders of The Learning Co.
lately.
</P>
<P>
   The Cambridge, Mass. educational software company's stock has
been on a roller-coaster over the past week, and Monday, it plunged
again. This time, shares were down 16 percent as investors fretted
over news of a modest sales slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   Learning Co. stock fell 3 5/8 to 19 3/8, as 2.39 million shares
traded hands, more than three times its three-month daily average.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts such as Stephen Fleming of BancAmerica Robertson
Stephens, said the market overreacted Monday, partly as a result of
some confusion last week over whether the company would be able to
collect on unpaid bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``With last week's confusion, a lot of people have got The
Learning Co. under a magnifying glass,'' said Fleming.
</P>
<P>
   So when new figures from PC Data, a Reston, Va.-based market
research firm, showed a slight drop in The Learning Co.'s market
share, investors panicked, he said.
</P>
<P>
   PC Data said retail software sales declined to $328.1 million in
July from $442.0 million a month earlier, and Learning Co.'s share
of the market, in terms of dollars, fell to 5.9 percent from 6.1
percent. Measured in units sold, Learning Co.'s share fell by a
similar margin, from 10.6 percent to 10.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the educational software category, where The Learning Co. is
dominant, its share slipped from 32.2 percent to 31.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very minor negative development,'' Fleming said,
noting that July is traditionally a slow month for software sales
and The Learning Co. didn't introduce any major new products during
the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Extrapolating the results from one month, after six
consecutive months of very strong performances, would be foolish,
particularly because July is the weakest month of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Getgood, a Learning Co. spokeswoman, declined to comment
on Monday's stock activity, but noted that the company is headed
into the strongest sales periods of the year, the back-to-school
and holiday seasons. ``We have a lot of great new titles ahead,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming said he believes The Learning Co. was ``unduly
punished'' because of confusion last week that caused the stock to
gyrate wildly.
</P>
<P>
   Learning Co. shares plunged 20 percent last Wednesday after an
analyst apparently misinterpreted a Securities and Exchange
Commission filing and raised questions about the status of the
company's accounts receivables _ or bills outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   The stock rose 17 percent the next day after company officials
allayed concerns about the accounting issue.
</P>
<P>
   Learning Co.'s shares tripled to a 52-week high of 32 3/8 on
July 16 from a year earlier, before falling during the last month.
</P>
<P>
   The Learning Co., which makes Reader Rabbit and other
educational software, has announced plans to buy Broderbund
Software Inc., maker of the popular puzzle game Myst and the Carmen
Sandiego line of educational software, for $417 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
