<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9853 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNNI-HOLLAND-COX     08-24 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNNI-HOLLAND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNNI to leave Amsterdam system
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Turner Broadcasting System has decided to pull the
international edition of CNN from an Amsterdam cable operator
rather than pay it high fees for carrying the programming.
</P>
<P>
   It's a first for Turner Broadcasting but company representatives
said they felt they had no choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conditions for renewal are so disproportionate with those
negotiated with every other cable and satellite platform operator
anywhere in the world that we had no option but to withdraw the CNN
International service,'' said Phil Kent, president of TBS
International, which markets the channel.
</P>
<P>
   The channel, called CNNI, is a version of Atlanta-based CNN
marketed in Europe, Asia and the Middle East. It has 140 million
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   CNNI has been in Amsterdam for more than a decade and has
developed a devoted following, said a company spokesman Nigel
Pritchard in London. The channel had some 500,000 subscribers in
the Netherlands, representing about 8.3 percent of the country's 6
million cable TV households.
</P>
<P>
   CNNI has been in the Netherlands for years without incident. But
that changed when Amsterdam cable operator A2000, owned by United
International Holdings Inc.'s United Pan-Europe Communications NV
and MediaOne International, began charging all its programmers.
</P>
<P>
   A2000 has argued it has no choice but to charge programmers
because the Amsterdam City Council refuses to let it raise
subscriber rates.
</P>
<P>
   Under A2000's rate schedule, CNNI would have to pay $357,000
annually. That represents a stark reversal for the channel. It has
been carried without charge. And in most countries worldwide,
including the United States, cable operators pay to carry
programming.
</P>
<P>
   That A2000 would ask for payment instead is ``a very rare
occurrence,'' said a CNNI spokesman in London.
</P>
<P>
   CNNI is not alone in leaving A2000. MTV Europe, a unit of the
New York-based music channel, left the cable operator this summer
in a dispute over fees.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting will pay to keep a Dutch version of its
Cartoon Network on A2000. Also staying will be the company's TNT
channel, which is part of a premium package exempted from fees.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
