<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9858 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARDUOUS-VACATIONS-2TA     08-24 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARDUOUS-VACATIONS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE INDIANA JONESES RELAX WITH HARD WORK, ADVENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICKI HADDOCK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Picture your dream vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's trekking across Zimbabwe scouting for piles of
elephant dung, then meticulously tabulating the thousands of
pea-size camel-thorn seeds within each pile of poop _ all to better
determine how elephants spread plant life across a savanna.
</P>
<P>
   Or you might prefer excavating the grounds of czarist Russia's
answer to Versailles, the Catherine Palace: shoveling and rolling
away huge clumps of dirt to investigate rumors of underground
passageways and buried sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe you would favor the sweltering swamps of French Guiana,
where you would slog through low waters in thick rubber waders,
surrounded by a droning cacophony of tropical insects and fortified
only by your daily feast of fried Spam. Your fantasy is not
complete until you net your quarry, an 18-inch-long giant leech.
</P>
<P>
   If ``vacations'' like these sound as enticing as a spinal tap,
count yourself among the Americans who opt for the beach,
Disneyland or a Carnival Cruise.
</P>
<P>
   But if you feel an inexplicable attraction to the adventurous,
you're a candidate to join the tens of thousands of Americans
annually who volunteer their vacation time for what they believe to
be a righteous cause: be it constructing a library in Kenya,
unearthing dinosaur fossils in Montana or conducting a research
census of humpback whales in California's Monterey Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are participants uncompensated for their efforts _ they
actually pay a pricely sum for the privilege of working like crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Nonprofit organizations such as the University of California's
Research Expeditions Program, Earthwatch Institute and the Oceanic
Society charge $500 to $2,500 per person to participate in a
volunteer vacation _ and that doesn't include travel costs.
</P>
<P>
   So why do it?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's probably no good way to explain the `why' of it to
most people,'' admitted retired school psychologist Betty Spicher
of Campbell, Calif., as she laundered her clothes for the third
time, hoping to extract the grime gathered on the St. Petersburg
dig of the Catherine Palace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been so tired or done such heavy physical labor day
after day. And I said to myself, `Wouldn't my friends laugh to see
me, paying big bucks to roll dirt balls?''' she said. ``But it
opens up new facets of your personality and your being. You get to
know yourselves in ways you hadn't before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just more meaningful to me than Club Med.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We give people the chance to fulfill a dream, to actually live
another life,'' said Jean Colvin, founder and director of UC's
Research Expeditions.
</P>
<P>
   While pure wanderlust has propelled the growth of scores of tour
companies touting ``thrill travel,'' volunteer vacationers insist
that thrills for the sake of thrills are not enough. They want an
exotic adventure that also contributes to the community or the
planet.
</P>
<P>
   Participants, who range in age from 16 to 91, tend to be
well-educated and well-traveled but come from all walks of life.
Their motivations are uniquely personal.
</P>
<P>
   Many volunteer vacationers echo the desire to better the world _
not minding that their tax-deductible payment helps underwrite the
costs of research, tools and other expenses beyond food and
lodging.
</P>
<P>
   They also desire to leave behind the daily routines of a desk
job and briefly become more than a frustrated armchair
paleontologist, archaeologist or anthropologist.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana Jones would find a soul mate in Marstin Tallant. During
the school year, Tallant teaches biology to prep students at the
Branson School in Ross, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   But when school's out, his own field education begins.
</P>
<P>
   There was an expedition to Costa Rica, where his team tagged and
observed a certain type of pepper plant to explore its symbiotic
relationship with a small genus of tiny ants. Another was to Kenya,
where his team made camp in mud-and-wattle houses and went to work
before daybreak helping a graduate student monitor the behavior
patterns of the yellow-shouldered widow bird.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was back to Costa Rica, on a project to capture and
identify scores of grasshoppers by genus and species. The long-term
goal: to build a diversity database environmentalists can use to
fend off development on sensitive land.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trips gave me an idea of the excitement of research work,
but also the tedious nature of it,'' Tallant said. ``It was
thrilling to be in Kenya up close to see the birds come in and
bathe in the morning dew ... and then just when you started to
think, `Oh, God, I gotta go watch another widow bird,' we'd take a
break and head to town to have a beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallant has returned to his classroom with piles of photos,
connections that allowed him to arrange exchange programs, and a
reservoir of tales guaranteed to snare his students' attention.
</P>
<P>
   The final common allure for volunteer vacationers is the
possibility of making history.
</P>
<P>
   University Research teams in Egypt supported the archaeological
survey of the Luxor area that led to the famed discovery of the
Ramses tomb.
</P>
<P>
   Anita Benedict of Sacramento got her $1,500 worth out of an
Earthwatch expedition to Montana when she helped uncover possibly
the largest specimen of a tyrannosaur ever unearthed.
</P>
<P>
   Trevor McNeil of San Francisco didn't uncover any
precedent-setting finds on his Earthwatch expedition to Belize this
summer, but he is awe-struck by having excavated a human skeleton
from a Mayan village.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 16 _ that seems to be the age when they let you risk your
life,'' McNeil said with a wry grin. ``Not many 16-year-olds can
say they found and held in their hands the skeleton of somebody who
walked the Earth 500 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Volunteer vacation trips are not without critics. Occasionally
participants themselves rebel against primitive conditions and what
they considered a ``boot camp'' mentality.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say they try to avoid mismatches by spelling out
conditions well in advance.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   The University Research registration questionnaire, for example,
asks would-be participants to relate their reactions to humidity,
ability to eat unusual food, allergies to grass, dust and smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers tolerate the inexperience of an amateur crew in
exchange for the funding they provide and the enthusiasm they
bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may spend the first day out seasick, and they may not
know much of anything about whales going into this, but they learn
a lot and help us in the process,'' said marine biologist Nancy
Blake as she led Oceanic Society volunteers on a clipper ship
excursion to survey whales and dolphins in Monterey Bay. ``They
make a lot of valuable scientific work possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some environmentalists worry that certain expeditions may
be done more for the employment of the researcher and the
entertainment of participants than to further science. Organizers
and participants insist they take care to ensure that does not
occur.
</P>
<P>
   Bea Ogden, 17, of San Francisco had second thoughts this summer
after she arrived in Crete on an Earthwatch project to study wild
agrimi goats.
</P>
<P>
   What prompted her doubts was not the sweltering heat, not the 20
pounds of cucumbers and tomatoes she was required to add to her
50-pound backpack for the slippery 6 1/2-hour hike down to the
Samaria Gorge _ not even the grueling work of grabbing, straddling
and blindfolding the goats while researchers extracted DNA samples
and tagged them.
</P>
<P>
   But when passing tourists spooked a female goat in the corral,
sending her into a frenzy that culminated in a fatal heart attack,
Odgen said, ``that made me question why I was there.''
</P>
<P>
   She reaffirmed her commitment to the project (researchers
stopped using that corral) after concluding that the study to map
the agrimi's DNA was the best hope for earning them classification
as a subspecies eligible for protection by the Greek government.
Without that, the agrimi may be lost forever to inbreeding with
domesticated goats.
</P>
<P>
   ``These animals really have no other hope besides us,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not all volunteer vacations are arduous _ some involve counting
wildflowers in the Rocky Mountains or photographing public
sculpture in Venice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the ultimate question is, what separates people who do
these sorts of vacations from those who don't? And I firmly believe
it all comes down to an inner need,'' said Susan Gerke, a San
Rafael oil painter just back from an excursion to China to record
an otherwise undocumented ritual Buddhist music of a tribe known as
the Dai.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who do this are really seeking, searching for
something more than the ordinary life around us. We want to connect
with the world, as opposed to just observing it. And the Dai have
such a beautiful way of life, it would be a horrible loss to lose
that culture. There is so much we could learn from them ...
</P>
<P>
   ``You go on a trip like this thinking you're going to help
someone,'' Gerke said, ``and you come back having received so much
more than you ever gave ...''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
