<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves Notebook: Lockhart looking to return after hiatus
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The schedule works in Keith Lockhart's favor.
</P>
<P>
   With the Braves in a stretch of three opposing left-handed
starters in a row _ including Houston's Mike Hampton tonight _
Lockhart has able to rest a strained right hamstring sustained
Saturday. With inactivity the best therapy, Lockhart will not be
called upon to start again until the Braves face Sean Bergman in
Houston Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no big deal,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``We could bring
up Marty (Malloy, the Class AAA Richmond shortstop) in a heartbeat
but they say it'll be okay.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart sustained the injury in Saturday's fifth inning, when
he was running from second on a grounder to third by Greg Colbrunn.
Lockhart left his feet to get around L.A. third baseman Adrian
Beltre, and ``it just felt like a cramp,'' he said. ``They're
telling me it was way better than running full out and doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   While the rest helps, there is a downside; Tony Graffanino's
game has fallen off. The right-handed second baseman who has
started 52 games to Lockhart's 79, is in the middle of a 4-for-35
(.114) slump that has dropped his average to .220. Cox let him hit
lead-off Monday, given his performance record against Los Angeles
starter Brian Bohanon (4-for-4 lifetime with a homer). But
Graffanino went 0-for-5 with four strikeouts. In both the seventh
and eighth, he came to the plate with runners in scoring position
and took strike three.
</P>
<P>
   It has gone even worse in the field, where he committed his
fifth error in four starts, ranging deep in the hole to get to a
Eric Young grounder in the ninth and then dropping it. Graffanino
now has 11 errors, which ties him with Chipper Jones for the team
lead. But Jones' 11 have come in 340 total chances. Graffanino's
came in 285.
</P>
<P>
   Graffanino's fielding percentage dipped to .952, compared to
Lockhart's .984.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz good for Wednesday
</P>
<P>
   After a strong off-day session in the bullpen Monday, John
Smoltz pronounced himself fit to make his next start in Houston
Wednesday. Smoltz, who has won seven in a row, questioned over the
weekend whether it was time to skip a start to give his elbow a
break, but Monday's work was strong enough to persuade him
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Introducing the Big Unit
</P>
<P>
   The Braves will not see Randy Johnson, the newest Astro, on
their short two-night stand in Houston. But if the Astros stick
with their rotation after their off-day Thursday, Johnson will
pitch against the Braves on Sept. 2 at Turner Field. There is a
reason the club would like to face him, just to get an idea of what
it would be like if the Braves and Astros meet in the postseason.
Or maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a nice story,'' Cox said. ``But he might not throw
the same against us now (that) he would later. It doesn't make any
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Saving grace
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Ligtenberg's 23rd save Monday gave him 17-straight
conversions, dating to May 27. Since the All-Star break, he has
thrown 19 1/2 scoreless innings while allowing just six hits and
striking out 18.
</P>
<P>
   The trio of Ligtenberg, left-hander John Rocker and set-up man
Rudy Seanez have had an excellent August, posting a 1.75 ERA. The
three have struck out 30 while allowing 13 hits in 25 1/3 innings
in August.
</P>
<P>
   Every day
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones is the only Brave to appear in all 131 games this
season and has started in a team-high 130. He missed a June 19
start because of illness and made a pinch-hitting appearance but
otherwise has played in every inning except the ninth of a May
6victory over Los Angeles. That field time will not last, he has
already been informed, once the September call-ups and Richmond
third baseman Wes Helms arrives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like (to play every game), and Bobby knows that,'' Jones
said. ``'I'd just like some time off at the end of the game, like
the seventh or the eighth, give me a chance to come in and sit in
the whirlpool.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
