<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lopez breaks HR drought
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Javy Lopez wasn't thinking home run.
</P>
<P>
   That would have been unreasonable for someone who hadn't hit one
in his last 39 at-bats, whose batting average for the past 10 games
before an eighth-inning at-bat Monday afternoon was a meek .143
(6-42).
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons I hadn't hit a home run was because I was
looking for it,'' the Braves catcher admitted. ``It's hard not to
think about it when you're at the plate. Every time I go up, I look
at home plate and see home run. When I'm not looking for it, I
guess I hit better.''
</P>
<P>
   So with two runners on, one out in the eighth and the Braves
trailing 3-0 to the Dodgers, Lopez tied the score with a home run.
Andruw Jones followed with a home run to win it.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 11th time this season the Braves have hit
back-to-back homers. They may have to add that stat to the record
book. In 1997 and again in '96, the team did it six times.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez has been in on six of the back-to-backs, and this one was
special: It was the 100th homer of Lopez's five-year major-league
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I didn't even know it was the 100th one,'' Lopez
said. ``All I know is I hit it at the right time. That was the
perfect situation for me to hit a home run, tie the game, and
Andruw takes care of the rest. Now that I know that it's a hundred
home runs, I'm kind of happy.''
</P>
<P>
   So are Earl and Ann Smith of Knoxville. They were sitting out in
left field when the Lopez homer flew over them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bounced once behind me and I caught it,'' said Earl Smith,
a switchman for the Norfolk Southern Railroad. ``Javy's her
favorite player. I would have been in the doghouse if I hadn't gone
after it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Smiths didn't get to keep the souvenir for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sent somebody down and said that Javy wanted the ball,''
Earl Smith said. They posed for pictures with Lopez after the game,
then swapped the milestone home-run ball for two autographed balls,
a signed bat and four tickets to a future game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky to get the ball,'' Lopez said. ``I know I've been
struggling the last couple of weeks. I knew sooner or later I was
going to come out of it. What a perfect chance to hit it. I've been
thinking that one at-bat probably was going to help me get out of
it, and hopefully this was the at bat I was looking for.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 1946EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
