<HEADER>
A9864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRBUS-BRITISH-AIR-57     08-24 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRBUS-BRITISH-AIR-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD NEWS FOR BOEING FROM BRITISH AIRWAYS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wash.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ British Airways, in a blow to the Boeing Co., is expected
to announce its first purchase from the rival Airbus Industrie,
awarding a contract this week for as many as 259 medium-range,
single-aisle planes worth $11 billion, according to managers at one
of the companies.
</P>
<P>
   The order, if all options are exercised, would be the largest
awarded to Airbus by any European carrier, as well as British
Airways' first break with Boeing, its main supplier.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways, which is the largest European carrier, is also
negotiating to buy long-haul Boeing 777 jets. The combined
purchases are expected to represent the basis of an overhaul of the
British carrier's routes, which will emphasize point-to-point
flights, rather than using feeder aircraft to bring passengers to
major hubs, like Heathrow, London's principal airport.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, British Airways is expected to order 59 planes in the
Airbus A320 family, with options for as many as 200 more. The value
of the orders reflects the list price of the planes, but airlines
usually receive a discount on large and long-term agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The order _ which could be announced as early as Tuesday, when
Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain is to visit Airbus
headquarters in Toulouse, France _ would be especially welcome to
Airbus at a time when the Asian economic crisis has taken a toll.
The big Asian carriers had been the mainstay of its business in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing had no immediate comment on the report, but
airline-industry analysts called the decision a defeat for Boeing
in its effort to sell an updated version of its 737. It was the
second major European victory for Airbus this year; in February
Iberia, the Spanish airline, decided to order as many as 76
medium-haul jets worth $4 billion from Airbus, instead of the 737.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this segment, Airbus has put not only its foot in the door,
but its whole leg,'' said Raymond Neidl of Furman Selz in New York.
``It's a big loss for Boeing.''
</P>
<P>
   Although neither company would confirm the reports, rumors had
circulated for some time that British Airways would place its first
order with Airbus, because of the European consortium's aggressive
pricing and its political access. British Airways said in February
that it would ask Boeing and Airbus for bids for short-haul planes
to replace aging ones for regional European subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, British Airways executives said they wanted to buy
about 30 medium-range planes, worth about $975 million, with
options on 70 more, which would have taken the order up to roughly
$3.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The much larger order appears to reflect the rapid pace of
deregulation in Europe, and the challenge posed by heightened
competition, both from strengthened mainstream carriers, like
Lufthansa, and from newer, no-frills airlines. Earlier this year,
British Airways joined the no-frills battle, with a low-fare
affiliate called Go.
</P>
<P>
   The Airbus family of single-aisle A320s, which began chipping
away at Boeing's 737 about a decade ago, comprises the A320, which
carries as many as 150 passengers; the A319, with up to 126
passengers, and the A321, which also carries up to 150.
</P>
<P>
   If British Airways takes delivery of all 259 planes, Airbus
would be likely to outstrip Boeing as the carrier's leading
provider of aircraft. British Airways has about 350 planes in its
fleet.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, it appeared that Boeing would not be a total loser.
Earlier this month, Robert Ayling, British Airways' chief
executive, said the carrier would also order long-haul, wide-bodied
jets to meet its future needs as airline deregulation progresses in
Europe, and many industry experts expect it to choose Boeing's 777.
In the past, British Airways has mainly flown Boeing 747s, 757s,
767s and 777s.
</P>
<P>
   The driving forces behind the British fleet overhaul are moves
by Europe's airlines to deregulation, and British Airways' proposed
alliance with American Airlines. Under conditions set by the
European Commission for the alliance with American, an AMR Corp.
unit, British Airways will have to rely heavily on wide-bodied
planes like the 777 for point-to-point flights, while the
short-haul Airbus fleet will be used on domestic British and
European routes.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus is working to transform itself from a consortium of four
European aircraft makers _ Aerospatiale of France, Daimler-Benz
Aerospace, British Aerospace PLC and Construcciones Aeronauticas of
Spain _ into a single corporation that would be a linchpin of a
restructured European aerospace and arms industry.
</P>
<P>
   In July, giving in to British and German pressure, France
announced it would relinquish full government control of
Aerospatiale, the nation's largest aerospace company, by selling a
big stake to Groupe Lagardere and offering shares on the stock
market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
