A9865 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIGHWAY-DEATHS-ART-47     08-24 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHWAY-DEATHS-ART-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGURES ON TRAFFIC DEATHS SHOW PROGRESS ON DRUNKEN DRIVING
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic on auto fatality rates is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New figures on traffic deaths, released Monday by federal safety
regulators, showed that campaigns against drunken driving are
producing some success even as the overall number of deaths on the
nation's roads remains stubbornly high.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol-related traffic deaths in the United States dropped by
1,029 last year, a 6 percent decrease from 1996. But the overall
number of traffic deaths was virtually unchanged as 931 more people
were killed in crashes that did not involve alcohol, a 3.7 percent
increase, according to statistics released Monday by the National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration, which is part of the
Transportation Department.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic deaths involving alcohol plunged in the 1980s but had
been showing signs of leveling off until the release of Monday's
data. Alcohol was involved in only 38.6 percent of all traffic
deaths last year, the lowest percentage since the federal
Government began keeping records in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Karolyn Nunnallee, president of Mothers Against Drunk Driving,
said that the decrease in 1997 appeared to reflect a public
reaction to the Princess of Wales' death in a car crash on Aug. 31
last year, and to a long-running fight in Congress over whether to
require states to lower the minimum level of alcohol in blood at
which a driver is considered legally drunk.
</P>
<P>
   Tests after the crash that killed Diana found that her driver
had consumed several times the quantity of alcohol necessary to be
considered drunk in the United States. Congress ended up passing
legislation recently that gives extra highway construction money to
states with lower alcohol minimums but does not require states to
adopt such rules.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater attributed last year's
decrease in alcohol-related deaths to a steady toughening of state
laws against drunken driving and growing public awareness of the
problem. The statistics on alcohol-related deaths include drunk
pedestrians who are hit by automobiles, as well as drunken drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in deaths not involving alcohol has proved troublesome
for safety experts. Dr. Ricardo Martinez, the highway safety
agency's administrator, said there were more fatal crashes in
daytime, when alcohol is seldom a factor. The increase probably
signals that Americans are driving farther each year because of the
strong economy, Martinez said Monday in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's report estimated that the number of Americans killed
for every 100 million miles driven had been steady at about 1.7
since 1992, after falling steeply for decades before then.
</P>
<P>
   The safety agency said that the number of traffic deaths
involving alcohol had fallen to 16,189 last year. The number of
traffic deaths that did not involve alcohol rose to 25,778, leaving
a drop of 98 in the total number of deaths, to 41,967.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Federal regulators have been increasingly worried in recent
months that more deaths might be result from soaring sales over the
last several years of so-called light trucks. These include sport
utility vehicles and pickup trucks, which roll over more often.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's report found that 36 percent of the sport utility
vehicles involved in fatal crashes last year had rolled over,
compared with 24 percent of pickups, 20 percent of vans and 15
percent of cars. The agency also released separate statistics
showing that light trucks were involved in an unusually large and
growing number of fatal, two-vehicle collisions last year, although
most of the deaths occurred in the cars they hit.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said that the very different designs of cars and light
trucks were a subject of regulatory concern, but that his agency
was looking at data from many years rather than drawing conclusions
from a single year's statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is an emerging trend that we want to get ahead of the
curve on,'' said Martinez, a former emergency room physician.
</P>
</TEXT>
