<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANG ON THE COMEBACK COURT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ It hasn't been a good year for the boys from
Hoboken. Sinatra, the singer, died. Chang, the strings player, has
taken a big slide on the charts. At least Michael Chang has a shot
at a comeback, which he hopes begins with this week's gig at a
Chestnut Hill club called Longwood.
</P>
<P>
   This is outdoor work, the MFS Pro Championships, at the leafy
corner of Hammond and Route 9, and Chang has been engaged as the
featured entertainer, with 31 other guys doing the backup chores.
He is the high-priced name for the big room, seating 7,500, not a
lounge act even though declining from No. 2 in the business to No.
22, and trying to stop a free-fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my best days are ahead,'' says Chang. Like his Hoboken
predecessor, Frank Sinatra, he got outta there at an early age and
made his rep all over the planet. Such places as Paris, New York,
London, Melbourne. Especially Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at Longwood, where international strings concerts have
taken place since 1890, hope those ``best days'' commence Tuesday
night when Chang makes his Boston debut in the company of a
24-year-old Romanian named Andrei Pavel. Pavel shouldn't be on the
same green hard-rock stage with Chang, you might say, since his
chart listing is No. 75.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the beauty of tennis. You put two guys on a court,
shooting at each other at 25 paces, and the better one may go down.
Ask Pete Sampras. He's been drilled this year by three lesser
lights who were on the property Monday _ Ramon Delgado, Karol
Kucera, and Fabrice Santoro _ and several others, including Chang.
</P>
<P>
   It happens, and it's been happening to Chang with greater
frequency in 1998 than either he or the promoters at Longwood would
care to think about. You can understand why he'll have a cheering
section in the officials stand upon learning that Chang collects
$200,000 whether he lands in Jail or on Baltic Avenue. That's a
guarantee merely for showing his face in our town, monopolizing the
cash that the MFS Pro parcels out to lure a better type of
entertainer.
</P>
<P>
   Chang is a million-dollar baby ($16,557,647 in official prize
money at last count), and you don't find them any more in a
five-and-ten store. Ever since he astounded the sporting world by
winning the French Open as a currency-green 17-year-old in 1989,
Chang has risen in ranking and esteem _ and asking prices, possibly
exceeding his prize money.
</P>
<P>
   Such up-front transactions are within the rules of the ATP Tour
for some tournaments (not the majors), the MFS one of them. When
Longwood made the deal early in the year, Chang, a top-10 resident
for six straight years, had slipped only a notch, to No. 3. He
seemed a very good buy then, and maybe will turn out to be,
although injuries (ankle, wrist, knee) have jammed him up.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kramer, a founder of the Association of Tennis
Professionals a quarter-century ago, preached against guarantees,
feeling that money should be earned as in golf _ only by
performing. I agree, but it didn't work. Too many promoters were on
the prowl, with monetary inducements to corral ticket-selling
somebodies for their diversions. Agents twisted their arms and
wallets. ``Announced prize money'' became only the tip of the
mother lode.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm fully fit now,'' says Chang. Arriving on a 24-11
record, and no tourneys won, he's trying to break out of his first
bare-cupboard season since he started amassing 31 career titles in
1988. ``Boston is what I need right now as I head for the US Open.
I'm getting my confidence back.''
</P>
<P>
   Although I disapprove of guarantees because too often eminenzas
_ Sampras and Andri among them _ have taken the money and
not run enough, Chang is a different case. Chang does not know how
to play tennis without leading with his heart.
</P>
<P>
   He is the greatest runner and retriever the game has known. He
resuscitates points that had long been pronounced dead, extends
them as though he were pulling taffy, and finally wins them. He
never met a tennis ball that he didn't stalk like Inspector Javert
hounding Jean Valjean, making his foes feel like one of Les
Miserables.
</P>
<P>
   He treats each point like an Olympic marathon _ except for him
it's a sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Chang is the Napoleon of tennis, the little guy who outsmarts
and outhustles the enemy and conquers big countries. Though he's
but 26, his odometer may reveal too much mileage, too many battles
of attrition. Chang doesn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   And when you watch him, you think of townsman Sinatra declaring,
``You make me feel so young ... runnin' across the meadow ...
pickin' up lots of forget-me-nots ...'' Plus pickin' up lots of
forget-it shots.
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra made his big comeback as the soldier Maggio in ``From
Here to Eternity.'' Perhaps Chang's will begin Tuesday night,
because he has no intention of not running from here to eternity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
