<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERS-MARKETPLACE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: BAD TIDINGS WHEN THE SHOPPING STARTS DROPPING
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They've shopped, and they've shopped. Now are they
starting to drop?
</P>
<P>
   The marathoner of the moment, as far as Wall Street is
concerned, is the American consumer, one of two prime movers behind
the booming economy of the last four years. Shop-happy consumers
brought the nation out of the recession back in 1991 and, together
with corporations investing in capital equipment, have kept gross
domestic product growth perking far longer than in any other
economic cycle. These same free-spending consumers are needed to
snatch up foreign goods and pull the world's faltering companies
back from the brink.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, there are signs that the marathoner may be tiring.
And since capital spending by corporations is also declining, a
prolonged weakness among consumers could add insult to an already
injured stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Straws in the wind on consumer spending come from surveys
conducted by International Strategy and Investment, a brokerage
firm in New York specializing in economic research. Every week, the
firm surveys almost 100 companies, including retailers, auto
dealers, manufacturers, home builders and banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting indications that consumer spending is starting
to soften,'' said Jason Trennert, firm vice president. ``We're not
counting the consumer out. And no question, lower interest rates
are going to provide a fairly strong backdrop for consumer
spending. But some of the headwinds on the economy are starting to
affect consumer spending.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts at ISI often identify significant economic trends well
ahead of the rest of Wall Street. For instance, the firm spotted
the Asia debacle and warned of its consequences in the spring of
1997, when most Wall Street firms still considered the Asian
economies a picture of health. Ed Hyman, a founder of the firm, has
been named the top-ranking economist by Institutional Investor
magazine for 18 consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent data from ISI show the lowest reading on overall
economic strength since January, an indication that the economy is
cooling. The index, in which 100 represents strong growth, stood at
48.8 as of Aug. 21, down from 50.3 in July and 55.9 in May. The ISI
numbers are not seasonally adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found a whiff of weakness in consumer spending at
retailers and auto dealers. For two weeks now, retail sales have
slowed at the six large, national retail chains interviewed by ISI.
The weakness was broad based, showing up at both a discounter and a
department store chain. ISI's retailer index fell to 39.6 last
week, down from a reading of 54 in May.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers reported strong sales in the first week of August,
giving hope for a bang-up back-to-school season. But the sales
growth fizzled; subsequent weeks have been dismal.
</P>
<P>
   ISI sees a similar trend in auto sales. Although new-car sales
rose slightly last week, Japanese and luxury models were
responsible. Many dealers in the survey reported significantly
fewer car shoppers on their floors, Jennert said. ``A couple of
weeks ago they thought inventory problems were behind slow sales,
but now they say floor traffic is off,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   What the consumer does is important because consumption accounts
for two-thirds of the gross domestic product and because a host of
weak countries are counting on Americans to buy their goods while
Asians and others cannot. Most forecasters expect that growth in
consumer spending will drop from the 6 percent reported earlier
this year to about 3 percent by year-end. If this number turns out
to be too optimistic, the economy will feel the pain.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Further clues to the shopper's mindset come Tuesday when the
Conference Board releases its consumer confidence figures. On
Friday, the University of Michigan publishes its confidence report.
In early August, the Michigan sentiment figures showed only a
slight decline from the previous month.
</P>
<P>
   Trennert wonders if the consumer pullback that his firm is
beginning to see is a result of the summer squalls in the stock
market. Are consumers spending less because many of them have lost
money, at least on paper?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our work has shown a strong correlation between retail sales
and the performance of stocks,'' Trennert said. ``Stocks tend to
lead by about four weeks. Every time we've seen the stock market
move up or down signficantly, the moves tend to influence consumer
spending.'' Since the value of the average stock portfolio is
probably down anywhere from 10 percent to 25 percent from the
highs, it would not be surprising if consumers reined in their
spending a bit.
</P>
<P>
   One thing consumers still have going for them, of course, is
declining interest rates. With Treasury yields near historic lows,
home-mortgage refinancings will put additional income in consumers'
pockets. So even if stocks continue to drift lower, American
investors will have some good news to balance out the bad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
