A9874 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANAM-103-HNS &LR;      08-24 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAM-103-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT TELLS LIBYA TURN OVER SUSPECTS TO NETHERLANDS OR FACE MORE
SANCTIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright presented
Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi with a ``take it or leave it
proposition'' Monday, warning him to turn over two men charged in
the 1988 bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 for trial in the Netherlands
or face further international sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The warning came as Albright and British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook announced simultaneously that the United States and Britain
have agreed to a previous proposal by Libya that the men suspected
of blowing up the Pan Am airliner over Lockerbie, Scotland, be
tried at The Hague in the Netherlands under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement marked a dramatic change in the 10-year-old
U.S.-British position that the two Libyans would have to be tried
either in the United States or Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Libya has refused all demands to expedite the men to face
charges, insisting that any trial would have to be held in a
neutral third country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Libya has repeatedly stated its readiness to deliver the
suspects for trial by a Scottish court sitting in a third country.
We now challenge Libya to turn promises into deeds,'' Albright said
at the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan the U.S. and the U.K. are putting forward is a
take-it-or-leave-it proposition. It is not subject to negotiation
or change, nor should it be subject to additional foot-dragging or
delay,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan for a trial in the Netherlands has been brought up from
time to time ever since the two men were indicted in the United
States and in Britain on charges of murdering all 259 people aboard
the Boeing 747 and 11 others, who were killed on the ground by
falling debris from the explosion. An exhaustive investigation
linked the bombing to a Libyan intelligence officer and a Libyan
airlines manager in Malta, both of whom are believed to have been
agents of Gadhafi's government at the time.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, Cook said that United Nations Secretary General Kofi
Annan has been asked to help arrange the extradition of the
Libyans, who were identified as Abdel Basset Ali Megrahi and Lamen
Khalifa Fhimah. There was no response Monday from Gadhafi on
whether he would allow the men to be transferred to the custody of
Dutch authorities at The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as they are handed over for trial, we will support
action in the (U.N.) Security Council to suspend the international
sanctions against Libya,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright raised the possibility of a tightening of international
sanctions, including an international oil embargo against Libya.
</P>
<P>
   The United States banned U.S. imports of Libyan oil years ago
but has not been able to persuade many other countries to go along.
</P>
<P>
   Albright also hinted at further action aimed at achieving
``accountability'' for the brutal bombing, noting that the United
States had demonstrated its determination to seek justice for
terrorist attacks with the military action last Thursday against
suspected terrorist targets in Afghanistan and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way or the other, terrorists must answer for their crimes.
As the events of recent days illustrate, America is determined to
see that perpetrators of terrorism past are brought to account, to
respond swiftly and firmly to present acts of terror, and to deter
and prevent such crimes in the future,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe that to the families of Pan Am 103, to other victims of
terror, to all Americans and to decent and law-abiding people
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the announcement, Albright spoke with relatives of the
victims in the Pan Am bombing. She said most seemed willing to
accept a trial in The Hague conducted by a panel of Scottish
judges.
</P>
<P>
   Some relatives called the U.S.-British decision ``a very
positive step.'' But others said they were upset about the
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary Wolfe, who lost a stepson in the Flight 103 explosion,
told CNN that Libya will never turn over the men, despite what it
has said in the past about holding the trial in neutral location.
</P>
<P>
   She said the agreement will lead to nothing except ``another
kick in the face from Gadhafi.'' Wolfe also expressed doubts about
the effectiveness of sanctions, noting that many U.S. allies are
ignoring them anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time that this country look at unilateral ways of getting
(the Libyans) to trial,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
