<HEADER>
A9875 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-GORDON-BOS     08-24 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-GORDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Tom Gordon needs five saves to break Jeff Reardon's
club record for saves in a season set by the bearded one in 1991,
when he saved 40 games, and the record could fall on the nine-game
Red Sox homestand that opens Tuesday night in Fenway Park against
the Oakland A's.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has eight saves in nine chances against the A's and the
two teams that follow Oakland into Fenway Park, the Anaheim Angels
and Seattle Mariners. His only blown save this season came against
the A's on April 14, but he eventually won that game and has saved
33 straight since then, the longest current streak in the major
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon leads the American League in saves with 36, five behind
the major-league leader, the Padres' Trevor Hoffman, younger
brother of former Sox shortstop Glenn Hoffman, who now manages the
Dodgers. He also has a 6-3 record and 2.81 ERA, but take away the
21 games (15 runs in 23 1/3 innings) in which he pitched that were
nonsave situations, and Gordon's ERA becomes a microscopic 1.09.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a September collapse, Gordon is on track to have the
greatest season by a Red Sox reliever since 1964, when the man out
of the bullpen didn't point at the heavens in thanksgiving, as
Gordon does after every save, but thrust two giant arms overhead in
triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Radatz did that for the first time the day he struck out
Mickey Mantle, Roger Maris and Elston Howard of the Yankees on 10
pitches with the bases loaded and nobody out in the ninth inning.
That became the calling card of ``The Monster,'' as the 6-foot-6,
240-pound Radatz would become known.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been very impressed with Gordon, he's been very good,''
Radatz said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at relief pitchers, I do compare guys to those
back in my day--Stu Miller, Hoyt (Wilhelm), Johnny Wyatt, a couple
of other guys. The table is set a lot differently today for
relievers; it's easier to get a save.
</P>
<P>
   ``But from the beginning of the season, to me Tom Gordon has
been successful for one reason more than any other: He wanted the
job. It wasn't like he was going to try it. You either want it or
you don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he got a little tired of the mediocrity he had had as a
starter. He knew he wasn't going to be the No. 1 starter. Maybe he
had the feeling he could be the No. 1 man in the bullpen, the
savior. It was something he really wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Gordon, Radatz, a college star at Michigan State, was a
starter, until Johnny Pesky made him reliever in 1961, the year
before he broke into the majors. Radatz had his doubts about the
switch, but as a rookie in 1962, he was American League relief
pitcher of the year, with a 9-6 record and 24 saves. A year later,
he was an All-Star and in 1964, he had the season of his career:
16-9 record, 29 saves, a 2.29 ERA and 181 strikeouts in 157
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in Kansas City, Royals closer Jeff Montgomery, who
broke into the big leagues with Gordon, said that he learned a
valuable lesson from former Royals closer Dan Quisenberry. ``Quiz
told me the best thing a closer can have is a very short memory,''
Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   Radatz laughed in agreement. ``I don't know if my line was
original or not,'' he said, ``but what I always said was, `What are
they going to do if I give up a home run, take me to jail?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest problem was that there were so many doubleheaders.
If you screwed up in the first game, you still came out for the
second game, when what I wanted to do was go for a cold one.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has pitched as many as three innings just once this
season, more than one inning on just 14 occasions. Radatz, of
course, pitched in the era before the micromanaging of bullpens,
and the age of specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were on call from the seventh inning on,'' Radatz said. ``I
had a setup man, though they weren't called that back then, and
that was Jack Lamabe. Jack had nine wins that year ('64). He'd come
into the game in the fifth or sixth, and if he was pitching well,
they would leave him in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Radatz recalled blowing a save against the Yankees in the
seventh inning of one game in Yankee Stadium. ``Marshall Bridges
and I were out there until the 17th inning,'' Radatz said. ``We won
it in the 17th when Bob Tillman tripled, and that was the only park
he could have tripled in, and Billy Gardner, who was hitting for
me, squeezed him home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated to blow saves. I'd go up to a starter and say, `I'm
sorry.' But Bill Monboquette pulled me aside and said, `Listen,
you're going to save a lot of wins for me that I wouldn't have
gotten, so don't worry about it. Nobody else in here is.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has been used on back-to-back dates 13 times this season,
including the Aug. 18 split doubleheader against the Rangers in
which he saved both the matinee and evening affairs. He has pitched
three days in a row just once this season.
</P>
<P>
   Pesky, who managed the Red Sox in 1964, wasn't as shy about
using Radatz day after day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This story sounds almost fictitious,'' Radatz said, ``but
after Johnny pitched me six or seven days in a row, he told me not
to come to the ballpark. `If you do,' he said, `I might be tempted
to use you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched the first three innings at home on TV in Milton, and
then I told my wife, `I can't watch this, I'm going to the
ballpark.' I got there in the sixth, and Johnny used me in the
13th, and we won the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to be the only guy in baseball history to win a game
after watching the first three innings at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Radatz recalled pitching 6 2/3 innings on a Sunday against
Baltimore, then going to Detroit the next day for a makeup game.
``Johnny looked at me and said, `Can you give me an inning?' I went
into the game in the seventh, and I pitched until the 16th. Fifteen
and two-thirds innings in 24 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Radatz, who does sports radio and TV, has not spoken with Gordon
this season. He's only been to the ballpark a handful of times,
preferring to watch most games on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it looks like he's tightened up his curveball a lot, to
the point where it works almost like a slider,'' Radatz said. ``In
the past, when he'd get beat, 80 percent of the time it was on a
hanger.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he has a lot better fastball than I think he thought he
had. And he throws it for strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Radatz never had another season like '64. The following season,
1965, he was 9-11 with 22 saves, and in 1966, he was traded to the
Cleveland Indians for Don McMahon and Lee Stange, two pitchers who
played vital roles in the Impossible Dream season of '67. Stange
won eight games for the Sox en route to a pennant, while McMahon
was traded to the White Sox for Jerry Adair, the Mike Benjamin of
his day.
</P>
<P>
   By 1969, Radatz was out of baseball, his career ending at the
age of 32 with the original Montreal Expos expansion team.
Interestingly, despite a workload that would be considered criminal
by today's standards, Radatz's career wasn't curtailed by arm
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had arm problems,'' he said. ``I had control trouble.
I went to spring training with the Cubs in 1968, and I walked six
guys on 24 straight pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of wildness is reminiscent of the struggles Braves
closer Mark Wohlers is now enduring. But Radatz, on the
recommendation of catcher Randy Hundley, who once had trouble
throwing the ball back to the pitcher, overcame his problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to a psychiatrist who hypnotized me,'' Radatz said,
``and doggone if it didn't work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980824.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9877 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSUS-2000-NYT &LR;      08-24 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-2000-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT BARS `SAMPLING' METHOD IN NEXT CENSUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.Y)  (Eds: See also CENSUS-SAMPLING) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal court ruled unanimously Monday that the
Census Bureau's plans to use statistical sampling to supplement the
2000 census violated federal law.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was welcomed by congressional Republicans, who
contended sampling would lead to new sets of errors and be subject
to political manipulation. But it dismayed Democrats, who thought
the system would count minority voters missed under recent censuses
and that counting them would produce new congressional and
legislative districts likely to vote Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   The special three-judge panel, specifically charged by Congress
with hearing census issues, ruled that the scheme was not permitted
under the 1957 and 1976 laws that govern how the census is to be
conducted. The unanimous decision stressed that the court found no
need to decide whether sampling was constitutional because the
ordinary federal law already barred its approach.
</P>
<P>
   The decision can be appealed directly to the Supreme Court, and
the Clinton administration is expected to do so. The three-judge
panel was composed of Judge Douglas Ginsburg, an appellate court
judge, and Judge Royce Lamberth, a district court judge, both
appointed by President Reagan, and Judge Ricardo Urbina, who was
named by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The panel issued an injunction Monday prohibiting the Census
Bureau from using any form of statistical sampling in the next
census. In the meantime, however, the ruling is expected to provide
ammunition to the Republicans who have been waging a protracted
political and legislative battle against sampling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this gets the adminis's attention,'' said Rep.
Dan Miller, R-Fla., chairman of the House Subcommittee on the
Census. ``This is a unanimous decision _ one judge appointed by
Clinton. The wise thing to do is put all their resources into a
full enumeration.''
</P>
<P>
   But proponents of sampling said Monday they stil hoped for a
favorable decision from the Supreme Court. ``Ultimately, it will be
before the Supreme Court,'' said Rep. Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y.
``Nothing has really changed. The nation needs an accurate count,
that includes everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau had counted on using sampling to avoid a
repetition of the 1990 census, which missed more than 8 million and
counted about 4 million either twice or in the wrong place. The
Census Bureau's planned methodology is loosely similar to that of
public opinion polls in that it extrapolates information about the
population from partial data.
</P>
<P>
   But the bureau's plans are far more sophisticated than polls.
They involve using traditional methods to count everyone in 90 per
cent of the households in a census tract _ a neighborhood of about
1,700 dwellings. Data from the 90 per cent would be used to
determine the number and characteristics of the remaining 10 per
cent, and a further adjustment of the population would be made on
the basis of a survey made up of 750,000 households.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's decision was particularly galling to representatives of
minoritiy groups that make up a disproportionate share of those
missed by traditional head-counting methods. ``It's inexplicable. I
don't understand it,'' said Eric Rodriguez, senior policy analyst
with the National Council of La Raza, a Hispanic advocacy
organization. ``We had an undercount of five per cent of the Latino
population in 1990. If this ruling is upheld we have no reason to
expect anything but a five per cent undercount this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's ruling turned on an interpretation of two seemingly
contradictory provisions in the Census Acts of 1957 and 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The 1957 act said that ``except for the determination of
population for apportionment purposes,'' the secretary of Commerce
``may, where he deems it appropriate, authorize the use of the
statistical method known as sampling.'' The wording codified the
practice of sending the census long form _ the questionnaire that
asks about items such as how many bathrooms one has in one's home _
to one in every six households.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, Congress changed the language of the law, saying that
except for purposes of reapportionment, the Commerce secretary
``shall'' authorize the use of sampling.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyers had argued that by by changing the
wording to make sampling mandatory, rather than optional, Congress
had effectively removed the prohibition against it for
reapportionment purposes. Further they argued that in 1976 Congress
added amendments _ Section 141 _ to the act that directed the
commerce secretary to conduct a census every 10 years ``in such
form and content as he may determine, including the use of sampling
procedures and special surveys.''
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's ruling, written by Lamberth, the three-judge panel
disagreed with the Justice Department's line of reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though defendants' interpretation of the except/shall sentence
structure is proper in some instances, the court finds it to be
strained and incorrect when applied to the amended section 195,''
he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Lamberth stressed the importance of the census to the balance of
power in Congress between parties and between states, and said it
was hard to imagine that Congress would change the rules without
explicitly saying so. He quoted from then Justice Rehnquist in a
1980 decision:
</P>
<P>
   ``In a case where the construction of legislative language such
as this makes so sweeping and so relatively unorthodox a change as
that made here, I think judges as well as detectives may take into
consideration the fact that a watchdog did not bark in the night.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit that produced Monday's ruling was brought by Speaker
Newt Gingrich, who during bargaining over the spending bill that
covered the Census Bureau last November won administration
agreement to allow general tax revenues to pay for the litigation,
a deal that enraged many House Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bought him the gun and said, `shoot me,''' said a
Democratic staffer who asked not to be identified, ''and the court
did.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the White House was confident that the court would
rule that Gingrich lacked standing to bring the suit since he could
not show how the Census Bureau's plans would cause a specific
injury to the House. White House lawyers were also confident that
the court would decide that because the administration and the
House Republicans were still haggling over the issue, the case was
not yet `'ripe'' for a court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's ruling went against the administration on both counts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
