<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-REJECT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATISTICAL ACCOUNTING SUPPLEMENT TO CENSUS RULED UNCONSTITUTIONAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal court on Monday struck down President
Clinton's plan to use a statistical accounting method to supplement
the traditional head count of the U.S. population in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In ruling Clinton's proposal unconstitutional, the U.S. District
Court here handed a victory to the Republican-controlled House,
which sought a court order invalidating the president's plan.
Republicans fear a statistically enhanced census would increase
population figures for minorities, a traditionally strong
Democratic voting bloc.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department, which conducts the count through its
Census Bureau, tried to defend Clinton's plan as the most effective
way to get an accurate figure for the U.S. population. The
department said as many as 8 million people, including 66,748 in
Houston, were not counted in the 1990 census.
</P>
<P>
   However, House Republicans successfully countered that the
Constitution's call for an ``actual enumeration'' of the U.S.
population every 10 years requires a head count and prohibits other
calculations.
</P>
<P>
   The battle before the district court was both legal and
political, with the fate of congressional seats and federal funds
for communities hanging in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Congress relies on census data for apportioning the 435 seats in
the House. In addition, the U.S. government uses the data in
deciding where to distribute federal funds for social welfare
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The administration could appeal the decision directly to the
Supreme Court. The Commerce Department had no comment, saying the
case was still under review.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's nominee to head the Census Bureau, New York social
scientist Kenneth Prewitt, said in June that statistical sampling
yields the most accurate population data by accounting for people
census takers might miss. Prewitt said then that, if the courts
prohibit the use of statistical sampling, he would still press
ahead to ``conduct the most accurate and cost-effective census
possible'' within the legal constraint.
</P>
<P>
   The top Democrat in the House, Minority Leader Richard Gephardt
of Missouri, said he was ``disappointed'' by the court's decision
and expressed his hope that the Supreme Court would reverse the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the Census Bureau's plan will guarantee a fair and
accurate count,'' Gephardt said. ``If its plan is not implemented,
nearly 6 million plus people will disappear for all practical
purposes when a host of government decisions based on the 2000
Census are made.''
</P>
<P>
   However, several Republicans who joined the lawsuit against the
Commerce Department hailed the court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come for the Clinton administration to abandon
their population polling plan,'' said Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla. ``I
have said all along that their plan is too complicated, unreliable
and untrustworthy. Now sampling has been found to be illegal.
Congress will not allow the Clinton administration to waste $4
billion on an illegal census scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. J. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., called the court's decision a
``huge blow to the political handlers at the White House'' and
questioned the accuracy of statistical samples. ``People need to be
counted, not guessed,'' Hastert said.
</P>
<P>
   In its unanimous, 71-page decision, the three-judge panel cited
the constitutional requirement for a census every 10 years as well
as the federal Census Act in concluding that U.S. law calls for a
head count of the population. The act, which Congress passed in
1957 and amended in 1976, limits the Commerce Department's use of
statistical sampling to the gathering of population information not
related to the decennial census, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   The three judges also went to great lengths to say the
Constitution's call for a separation of powers between the
legislative and executive branches of government does not prohibit
Congress from suing the Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   House members have a legally protected interest in ensuring that
they receive constitutionally valid information about the U.S.
population every 10 years, the court said in rejecting the Commerce
Department's separation of powers argument. Valid census data
enables Congress to apportion the House's 435 seats properly, with
each seat representing about 500,000 people, the court added.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is apparent that a legislative body has a judicially
cognizable interest in matters affecting its composition,''
District Judge Royce Lamberth wrote in the court's decision. ``And,
most critically, if the executive's interpretation of the statute
is, in fact, contrary to the law or the Constitution, the most
directly affected entity is the institution of the House of
Representatives, because of its mandatory duty to apportion
representatives based upon a lawful and constitutional decennial
census, and because of its ... interest in its lawful
composition.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Lamberth's opinion were U.S. District Judge Ricardo
Urbina, a Clinton appointee, and Judge Douglas Ginsburg of the U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia. Lamberth and
Ginsburg were appointed by President Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   The participation of an appellate judge in a three-member
district-court panel enables the losing party in a case between
governmental branches to appeal the decision directly to the
Supreme Court under federal law. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
