<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9888 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STRATEGY-710&AMP;     08-24 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STRATEGY-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AIDES DEBATE WHETHER OUTSIDER NEEDED TO BLUNT STARR
REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With President Clinton's worries shifting from the
grand jury room to Capitol Hill, his senior aides are considering
proposing that he hire an outside expert to help blunt any
Congressional inquiry into a report by independent prosecutor
Kenneth Starr, White House officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The move is one of several measures debated inside the White
House over the last week, as Clinton's political strategists
searched for ways to help him rebuild public confidence, retain the
support of Congressional Democrats and begin to campaign again for
his policy goals.
</P>
<P>
   Other options that were under discussion have been set aside, at
least for now, White House aides said. Some of Clinton's friends
and advisers have been pressing him to give another, less formal
public address about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky, after
sharp criticism, even within the White House, that his speech last
Monday was not apologetic enough.
</P>
<P>
   But White House officials say that the president is unlikely to
do that. Instead, they expect him to address the matter again when
he travels to Russia next week. He is planning to hold a joint
press conference with President Boris Yeltsin, and is certain to be
asked about Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been said by friends to be worried about the
critical reviews of his previous speech. But his aides say they
have taken heart from public surveys showing that most Americans
continue to approve of the job he has done. To encourage that point
of view, they have been planning for him to interrupt his Martha's
Vineyard vacation this week to hold at least one public event,
probably on the subject of crime.
</P>
<P>
   Despite criticism in Washington, White House officials said,
they have not detected any public desire for a fuller apology. One
White House adviser said that Clinton had received several letters
of support and encouragement from Congressional Democrats and
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton has come under heavy fire from Republicans and some
Democrats on Capitol Hill. His aides are worried that his existing
legal team does not have the expertise to handle potential
impeachment hearings. Many of them have complained that David
Kendall, the president's private lawyer, has not paid enough
attention to the politics of his legal predicament.
</P>
<P>
   But one senior Administration official said that any new faces
would not supplant Kendall. ``We've known for some time that as
this thing entered a new phase, we would want to supplement
Kendall's team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One outside lawyer familiar with the White House planning said,
``The Congressional beast is different than the independent counsel
or your typical criminal investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House has apparently not yet approached anyone for the
job.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is preparing a report for Congress on his investigation
into Clinton's relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, a former intern. He
may also address other subjects he has examined during his
four-year investigation, which originally focused on the Clintons'
Whitewater real estate deal.
</P>
<P>
   Among the sorts of issues a new adviser might be expected to
decide is what protected information the White House should release
in advance of any hearings, to defuse revelations that might
otherwise be bombshells. That is a technique the White House has
used repeatedly during such Congressional investigations as the
inquiry into donations during the 1996 campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall and members of the White House Counsel's office have
been reluctant to release any information about the president. Just
last week, they infuriated other White House advisers by refusing
to disclose a request by prosecutors that Clinton supply a sample
of his genetic material. Prosecutors want to determine if a dress
belonging to Ms. Lewinsky was stained during a sexual encounter
with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, Kendall met with White House chief of staff
Erskine Bowles and other White House officials to discuss their
concerns, in what was described by participants as a tense meeting.
</P>
<P>
   One ally of the president's who is knowledgeable about White
House deliberations said that he was concerned that any new
outsider would be stymied by the existing team. ``You cannot have
this current structure and bring someone in,'' he said. ``It's the
mindset, and that's what's got to change now.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   White House officials have reached out in recent days to
numerous Democratic political strategists, as they try to devise a
plan to secure Clinton's political standing. One fundamental issue
they have been discussing is what the president's posture should be
as Congress takes up legislation on the budget, education, and
health care.
</P>
<P>
   Some White House advisers said that Clinton's political
interests might be best served by compromising with Republicans, to
demonstrate that he can still get things done despite the furor
over Ms. Lewinsky. But that may not be an option, they said,
because House Democrats might prefer confrontation, to sharpen
their differences with Republicans going into the fall campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   With the possibility of impeachment hearings hanging over his
head, Clinton cannot afford to alienate Democrats in the House,
said one adviser who has been consulted by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't afford to to blow up the Democratic caucus with the
kind of compromise he's prepared to reach,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
