<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIBUNE-TV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Meredith sees growth in purchase of Atlanta affiliate
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Meredith Corp. is better known for magazines than
television stations. But that may change now that the company has
agreed to purchase Atlanta's WGNX.
</P>
<P>
   ``This acquisition represents a unique strategic opportunity for
Meredith,'' said William T. Kerr, the company's chairman and chief
executive. ``A chance to acquire a station in a top 10 market is
rare, let alone in one of the nation's fastest growing television
markets.''
</P>
<P>
   While not among the biggest players in television, Meredith has
other strengths. The Des Moines, Iowa-based company publishes 21
magazines. Its holdings include such popular titles as Better Homes
&AMP; Gardens, Ladies' Home Journal, Family Money and Crayola Kids.
With nearly 8 million subscribers, Better Homes &AMP; Gardens is the
third largest magazine after Reader's Digest and National
Geographic.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison to its magazine holdings, TV stations are a small
part of Meredith's business. The company owns 11 stations, four of
which are CBS affiliates like WGNX. None of the 11 is in a top 10
market.
</P>
<P>
   These stations generated $156.4 million in revenue last year, or
about 18 percent of the company's total of $885.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Among Meredith's stations are KPHO in Phoenix, WOFL in Orlando,
KPDX in Portland, Ore., KCTV in Kansas City, Mo., WSMV in Nashville
and KVVU in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Meredith's stake in television is small compared to that of a
company like Tribune which owns 18 stations that generated $1.1
billion in revenue last year. That represents about half of the
company's total revenues of $2.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Under Kerr's leadership, Meredith has been upping its TV
holdings. It bought four stations in 1997 for $375 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company is exploring creating TV programming based on its
magazines. It launched ``Better Homes &AMP; Gardens,'' a syndicated
show, last year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
