<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9896 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARNEYS-ART-550(2TAKE     08-24 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNEYS-ART-550(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWING THE BUSINESS AND SHRINKING THE ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Ill., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Imagine, if you can, a shopper wandering into Barneys
New York, walking past the Gucci bags and the glittering John
Galliano gowns to cozy up to a size 14 designer suit. A clerk comes
running over and offers to help her with the garment, fits her for
some shirts to match and then orders up three more suits in that
size.
</P>
<P>
   Clothes for the larger-than-skinny? Solicitous service? Barneys?
</P>
<P>
   Barneys, the luxury retailer with a reputation for snootiness
that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection more than two years
ago, is not about about to turn into a Lord &AMP; Taylor, catering to
the masses. But it has undergone enormous business changes in the
last six months, some designed to alter its image subtly but many
of them invisible to its usual customers, who still come for the
one-of-a-kind necklaces and designer suits.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Barneys is making a transition from a clothing art
gallery _ creative but unprofitable _ to a more traditional
retailer, with all the disciplines, back-office controls and
service standards that the rest of the industry tries to apply.
</P>
<P>
   Removed from daily responsibilities as part of the
reorganization of Barney's Inc., the company that owns the stores,
are the Pressman brothers, Bob and Gene, who once ran it as
co-chief executives. Both remain involved, though, with generous
consulting contracts.
</P>
<P>
   In their place, Thomas Shull, the company's new chief executive,
is doing everything he can to get more customers in the door, from
rewarding them for using the Barneys credit card to training clerks
to be nicer to browsers who don't look like models.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly Barney's, which intends to emerge from bankruptcy
sometime this fall with the help of a plan put together by its
creditors, needed a new business plan to make its stores more
profitable and to generate growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barneys is still a huge destination for a wealthy, hip
customer,'' said Faye Landes, a retail analyst at Salomon Smith
Barney. ``Layering on some business traditions should help them
return to profitability, as long as they don't kill the goose that
laid the golden egg.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in reorganizing, Barneys is faced with a special
challenge: how to apply the business practices standard in the
retail industry while at the same time preventing itself from
becoming like the stores that are standard in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   It has always been the special merchandise and creative displays
that have set Barneys apart from the retailing mainstream. The
store carries many brands and styles that are not easily available
elsewhere, in everything from dresses to men's shirts to perfumes
to vases.
</P>
<P>
   And while other stores place millions of dresses and shirts on
round racks and leave it to shoppers to unearth the goods, Barneys
displays everything in a spare, attractive way with whimsical
mannequins, unusual fixtures and the occasional original work of
art.
</P>
<P>
   But adding a hint of business strategies from Macy's, where he
was executive vice president for two years, Shull insists that none
of the creativity will be hurt. ``We believe strongly that there is
not a dichotomy between creativity and discipline,'' he said in an
interview. ``Clearly we have been world-class in terms of
merchandise. Now we want to elevate the company to the level of our
brand.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the store in returning to its roots.
</P>
<P>
   Barneys was founded as an off-price men's suit business in 1927
by Barney Pressman, who paid for the lease of his store on Seventh
Avenue and 17th Street by hocking his wife's engagement ring.
</P>
<P>
   Things began to change in the 1950s, when Barney's son Fred
became active in the business, adding a high-end touch to what
traditionally had been a sort of Loehmann's for men. Fred
introduced Giorgio Armani and other designers from such fashion
centers as Milan, Italy, and London's Savile Row to American
consumers. His penchant for counting threads on ties and arranging
shirts just so on a display table took the store far from its
roots.
</P>
<P>
   Bob and Gene, Fred's sons, joined the company in the 1970s, and
in the 1980s, the family began to open stores around the country
with the help of the Isetan Co. of Japan. The chain's eventual
bankruptcy resulted in part from a fight between the Pressman
family and Isetan over who actually owned stores on Madison Avenue
and in Chicago and Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Much had changed since the company tried to move beyond the
original store that Barney Pressman opened on 17th Street, whose
doors were shuttered last summer. The women's businesses never ran
quite as smoothly as the men's. Half of the 14 big anchor stores
failed, and the survivors, including those in Los Angeles and
Chicago, have needed serious rethinking to accommodate regional
tastes. The company now runs seven Barneys and 13 outlet stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically,'' said Shull, ``Barneys had taken a New York store
and placed it in other cities without really appreciating the needs
and wants by market.''
</P>
<P>
   Setting up stores with a regional focus means much more than
making sure there are more wool sweaters in stock in New York than
in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kalenderian, general merchandise manager for the men's
department, said he was surprised, for instance, to find that in
Los Angeles men tend to buy more luxury robes and silk pajamas,
largely because they wear them outdoors, whereas in New York, those
are mostly Christmas items.
</P>
<P>
   There were similar discrepancies throughout the store. Jewelry
fashioned from leather cord sells well on Madison Avenue but runs
cold in Beverly Hills. Los Angeles longed for more colorful
garments. The Chicago store needed more size 10s.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Pressman supposedly once proclaimed, ``I don't want fat
people shopping in this store,'' and Barneys has always had a
reputation for carrying nothing bigger than a size 6 on its women's
floors. While that is an exaggeration, larger sizes are hard to
find, with the result that many baby boomer shoppers leave the
store empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the Barneys mystique is that it is a little
intimidating to shop here,'' Shull said. ``We have to minimize that
and increase the warmth of the experience. If you walk into the
store and you're a size 14 and there is limited merchandise, that
is not warmth.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of that intimidation came from the sales staff. Known for
being chilly and snobbish, Barneys clerks became the model for
parodies of the rude New Yorker. That too, is coming to an end,
Shull said. He said better training of sales clerks and more
involvement of merchants on the sales floor will help to make
Barneys more welcoming.
</P>
<P>
   The new mantra _ ``customers are guests in our home'' _ is
borrowed not from Neiman Marcus, the leader in customer service
among luxury retailers, but from Target, the discount store owned
by the Dayton Hudson Corp., which for years has referred to
shoppers as ``guests.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting into shoppers' hearts _ in a profitable way _ is also
part of the game plan. Barneys is launching a customer loyalty
program, similar to one offered by Saks Fifth Avenue and Neiman
Marcus, which enables big spenders to get rebates at the end of the
year in the form of gift certificates.
</P>
<P>
   The program rewards shoppers who spend $3,000 to $4,999 on the
store's credit card each year with a 3 percent gift rebate, with
much higher rates for bigger spenders.
</P>
<P>
   Barneys has never really tried to leverage its credit-card
business before; only 15 percent of its shoppers use its card,
compared with rates closer to 50 percent at Neiman Marcus and Saks.
What's more, Barneys plans to mine the data base provided by credit
card use to improve its sometimes-scattered marketing strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Shull also wants to expand the company's private-label line to
25 percent of sales from 17 percent now, and to add co-branded
lines with companies like Battistoni, an Italian maker of men's
clothing. He believes those lines also have potential for
wholesaling to other retailers abroad, the company's best global
growth possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Shull's efforts have already helped the bottom line. For the
fiscal year ended July 31, the company earned somewhere around $17
million before taxes and professional costs associated with the
bankruptcy costs, compared with a loss of $2 million in the same
period last year. In the same period, sales dipped to $343 million
from $361 million.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bob Pressman said he is in favor of the reorganization
plan. ``I am totally supportive of Tom and his team,'' Pressman
said. ``I look forward to a close relationship to his team now and
in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the cost-cutting is behind the company now. Clothing
allowances have been eliminated for executives, staffing has been
cut in Los Angeles and suppliers have started to kick in for
advertising costs. So now, the company is faced with trying to make
the top line grow.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is sold. ``They are just too expensive,'' said
Barry Bryant, managing director of R&AMP;R Capital Group Inc., a
boutique investment bank. ``How many people can pay $140 for a
sport shirt? The retail concepts that are the most successful are
the ones that deliver more fashion value than the price they're
charging.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Pressmans are now largely disengaged from the
business, Judy Collinson, the general merchandise manager for
women's; Simon Doonan, the company's valuable creative director,
and Kalenderian have all been with the company for well over 10
years. Each is a disciple of one Pressman or another; in Ms.
Collinson's case, it's Bonnie, Gene's wife, who left the company
this week to work for Polo Ralph Lauren.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is not to wipe out the Pressman legacy, but to
eliminate the troublesome parts of it, particularly the reckless
spending and family infighting that marked the company's recent
financial past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in cleaning house,'' said Shull. ``The people
who built this company should inherit it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
