<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS ARE OPTIMISTIC, BUT CAUTIOUS, ABOUT RUSSIA
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investors around the globe were cautious, though
optimistic, on Monday in light of the latest moves by Russia to
reverse its recent economic slide.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, stocks ended mixed as investors expressed some
skepticism that Russian President Boris Yeltsin's moves to dismiss
the country's five-month-old cabinet and reinstate the former prime
minister would stem its economic free fall.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, moves by acting Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko
allowing the Russian ruble to devalue and the country to default on
$40 billion of government debt, sent world equity markets reeling.
Russia's slide, and expectations that a currency devaluation in
Venezuela was next, ignited fears that the financial crises
enveloping Asia's emerging markets was spreading to other
developing regions.
</P>
<P>
   And while Russia's benchmark equity index rose more than 5
percent, most of the gains were limited to big energy companies and
utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Even though U.S. investors were relatively calm, they were
showing growing signs of cautiousness, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 32.96 points, to 8,566.61,
but increases in three stocks _ Merck, American Express and
Wal-Mart Stores _ accounted for the bulk of the gains.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index added 6.90 points, closing
at 1,088.14, while the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index fell
6.79 points, to 1,790.82 _ led by declines in Tellabs, Worldcom,
Oracle and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, the benchmark Nikkei index of 225 issues fell 2.03
percent. Hong Kong's Hang Seng index increased 4.2 percent, propped
up by continued government buying of blue-chip shares. Stock
indexes in Singapore, Taiwan and the Philippines were lower.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks closed higher in London for the first time in three days,
rising 1.4 percent, and German investors pushed that benchmark
index up 1.2 percent, as a belief that previous declines may have
been overdone pulled investors into the market.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico and Venezuela were little changed, but markets in Brazil
and Chile fell more than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're seeing a global re-evaluation of assets,'' said
Anthony Conroy, a managing director at Bankers Trust Global
Investment Management.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should still be concerned about Russia and Latin America,''
he said, adding that Hong Kong could fall again once the government
ends its buying spree.
</P>
<P>
   Since world stock markets may continue to be volatile, investors
should remain cautious, he advised.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, buying on the dips is going to be the wrong
thing to do,'' because markets may continue falling, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent decline in stock prices and with Treasury
bond yields at their lowest levels in more than 20 years, Douglas
Cliggott, the chief investment strategist at J.P. Morgan, is
reluctant to buy shares.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations that corporate earnings will be lackluster through
the end of the year and increasing volatility, characterized by
global market gyrations, mean investors are not going to be
compensated for the added risk of buying stocks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Abby Joseph Cohen, co-chairwoman of the investment policy
committee at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Company, called investor concerns
about the impact of global economic problems on American corporate
earnings and the perceived increased riskiness of U.S. stocks
``overdone.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, global investor attention has focused on Russia,
Brazil and Venezuela, Ms. Cohen wrote in a market commentary. Most
of those countries, however, are relatively small and have only
limited trade impact on the United States, she argued. Less than 1
percent of the total U.S. exports flow to Russia; exports to
Venezuela equal about 1 percent, while total exports to Brazil are
about 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the S&AMP;P 500 is currently 5 percent to 8
percent undervalued,'' Ms. Cohen wrote, adding that she contends
the Dow could hit 9,300 by the end of the year and the S&AMP;P 500
could increase to 1,150.
</P>
<P>
   Still clients of some mutual fund firms, like the Vanguard
Group, are growing slightly more cautious, as evidenced by a
moderate pickup in inquiries about and cash flows into money market
mutual funds, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   During the last three weeks, investor requests for information
about money market funds has increased, said John Woerth, a
spokesman. Flows into money market funds in August are expected to
top the $900 million that entered the funds in July, he said. And
recently, flows into equity mutual funds have been slowing a bit,
he added.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
