<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POWER-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S POWER-HUNGRY TYCOONS WELCOME CHERNOMYRDIN APPOINTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: RUSSIA-SHAKEUP, RUSSIA-VOICES, RUSSIA-U.S.,
RUSSIA-GERMANY)  
(js) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ It doesn't take much to spark a rumor in Moscow these
days, as governments and policies are flipped around like flapjacks
on a griddle.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough for Boris Berezovsky, a 51-year-old
multi-billionaire financier with an unquenchable political
appetite, to be ``sighted in the vicinity of the office of the head
of government'' Monday to prompt a headline in an evening newspaper
Monday night and a new round of talk about the master intriguer's
possible return to power.
</P>
<P>
   In March, when President Boris Yeltsin last switched
governments, Berezovsky, who months before had been ousted as
secretary of Russia's Security Council, was put further out on the
sidelines with a job at the Commonwealth of Independent States,
which has its headquarters in Minsk, the capital of Belarus.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Berezovsky wins a post in Russia's new government is
still not certain, but it is not improbable given his close ties to
Viktor Chernomyrdin, a figure whose power base includes both
Russia's old ``red'' establishment and its new monied elite.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, who first came to government as the head of
Gazprom, Russia's giant gas company, has much in common with the
small coterie of financiers and corporate magnates who in the last
few years have accumulated enormous wealth by mixing politics and
business.
</P>
<P>
   These men _ known here as the oligarchs _ are widely seen as the
beneficiaries of the returnrnomyrdin, who is expected to
lend a sympathetic ear to their complaints about his predecessor's
tough tax collection and tight money policies.
</P>
<P>
   They own oil companies, newspapers, television stations, and
metal factories but, above all, they own Russia's major private
banks _ many of which have been caught dangerously short by
Russia's current financial crisis. Many profited from Russia's
privatization program by buying state assets on the cheap, and
leveraging them to get access to state credits.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky, however, is not a banker, but a deal maker whose
power derives from the fortune he has made buying and trading
assets of former state-owned oil, automobile, airline and
television companies. Another key asset is his friendly relations
with the Yeltsin family, in particular the president's daughter
Tatyana Dyachenko, who serves as her father's image maker and
political adviser.
</P>
<P>
   In this crisis, Berezovsky is seen to be taking advantage of a
power vacuum to propel himself back to the center of power. Some
analysts note that he himself may be the primary source of rumors
of his pending comeback. Like other oligarchs, he hopes to
influence Russia's next presidential elections in 2000, and has
kept a line open not only to Chernomyrdin but also to Alexander
Lebed, the former general and aspiring presidential candidate who
is now governor of a Siberian region.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The political ambitions of Russia's other oligarchs are more
muted, and more directly tied to their business interests, whether
it be oil or media. As chairman of the Media-Most holding company,
Vladimir Gusinsky, 45-year-old founder and former chairman of MOST
bank, controls a newspaper, a magazine and a network of private
television stations.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Potanin, the 37-year-old chairman of Uneximbank, is a
member of the board of directors of the Sidanko oil company, and
the Norilsk Nickel joint stock company.
</P>
<P>
   But with Russia's banking system still teetering on the edge of
collapse, attention this week is focused primarily on Russia's
major bankers - including Alexander Smolensky, chairman of
SBS-Agro, and Vladimir Vinogradov, president of Inkombank, two
banks that engaged in aggressive trading in Russian treasury bills
and in foreign loans secured with Russian bonds as collateral.
</P>
<P>
   When the value of Russian bonds fell in recent weeks, the banks'
foreign creditors demanded payment - causing several banks earlier
this month to default on payments.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as part of its anti-crisis program, the government of
ex-prime minister Sergei Kiriyenko imposed a 90-day moratorium on
Russian commercial debt, a move that amounted to a short-term
bail-out for the banks. Some banks have sought more help from the
government, both in the form of credits and guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   According to some analysts, even the Chernomyrdin government may
be powerless to prevent the failure of one or more Russian banks.
An attempt by the Central Bank of Russia to form a pool of 12
leading Russian banks, banded together to share debts and protect
private depositors, is already cracking under the strain of the
crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
