<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9916 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-BONNIE-ART-     08-24 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-BONNIE-ART-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COASTAL RESIDENTS KEEP ANXIOUS EYE ON SLOW-MOVING HURRICANE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Surfers rejoiced Monday while anxious coastal
residents from Florida to Virginia kept a wary eye on Hurricane
Bonnie, a sluggish but powerful Atlantic storm that is confounding
forecasters with a wobbling track toward the southeastern United
States.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 p.m., the National Weather Service declared a hurricane
watch from Savannah, Ga., to the border between North Carolina and
Virginia, meaning that hurricane conditions were possible anywhere
along that 450-mile stretch within the next 36 hours. But because
the hurricane was moving so slowly _ about 5 miles per hour in a
generally northwestern direction _ hurricane trackers had great
difficulty predicting where, when, or even if the storm would come
ashore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel terrible because we know we've got all these people
hanging on and we're not being able to be very definitive for
them,'' said Jerry Jarrell, director of the National Hurricane
Center in Miami. ``And there's no quick end in sight. It may be
Wednesday before we get a landfall, or even later if it doesn't
start moving a little faster.''
</P>
<P>
   By Monday afternoon, the hurricane was sliding past the
northeastern side of the Bahamas. The center of the 400-mile-wide
storm was about 640 miles southeast of Savannah and about the same
distance south of Wilmington, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Maximum winds reached 115 miles per hour, placing the storm
within Category 3 on the Saffir-Simpson hurricane scale. By
comparison, Hurricane Andrew, which devastated South Florida in
1992, carried winds of 145 miles per hour, while Hurricane Hugo,
which struck Charleston, S.C., in 1989, had sustained winds of 135
miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrell said that Hurricane Bonnie's size and strength ``makes
this hurricane a potential disaster sitting out there waiting to
fall on somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the Eastern Seaboard, emergencyment teams began to
dust off plans for evacuating barrier islands and for housing
people with nowhere to go. In South Carolina, which harbors painful
memories of Hugo, Gov. David Beasley placed 1,000 members of the
National Guard on alert and asked them to move to their armories.
</P>
<P>
   But in most places, sunny skies and light winds provided at
least a temporary sense of reassurance, if not complacency.
</P>
<P>
   Surfers enjoyed a day blessed with 6-foot waves, with some
skipping their first day of school and braving swells well after
nightfall. On Hilton Head Island, S.C., Nanci Polk-Weckhorst, the
owner of Nan-Seas Custom Canvas and Surf Shop, found herself torn
between the heightened demand for surfboards and her own desire to
ride the waves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our problem is we all want to be out surfing so the shop's
been closed a lot of the time,'' Ms. Polk-Weckhorst said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Buxton, N.C., on Hatteras Island, John R. Hooper, the owner
of the Lighthouse View Motel, said surfers ``are having a blast.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the hurricane's path was so uncertain, relatively few
coastal property owners were taking protective measures like
boarding and taping windows. Nancy Y. Peacock, a closet designer in
Neptune Beach, Fla., near Jacksonville, spent $300 on 20 sheets of
plywood, but left them piled in her driveway for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't usually have hurricanes in Jacksonville,'' Ms.
Peacock said. ``But I thought, as an added good luck charm, if we
buy all this stuff it will certainly not hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrell said his current forecast called for the hurricane to
land on the Outer Banks of North Carolina on Wednesday or Thursday.
But he said he had ``low confidence'' in that prediction.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, he said, is the hurricane's lethargic pace makes it
susceptible to relatively minor atmospheric forces. ``If you think
about a ball that's moving very fast, it's harder to change its
direction or to stop it,'' he said. ``But if it's moving very
slowly, it's fairly easy to change its direction or stop it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it moves sharp, closer to west, then it goes into north
Florida,'' Jarrell said. ``If it moves almost straight north, it
goes into the Outer Banks. That's a horribly wide zone to be
talking about, but unfortunately that's sort of where we are at the
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Powerful riptides, possibly generated by the hurricane's
offshore winds, were blamed for the drowning deaths on Sunday of a
24-year-old man in Delaware and a 25-year-old man in South
Carolina. Some 100 people were rescued from the dangerous surf in
Atlantic City, N.J., on Sunday, and 30 were saved in Carolina
Beach, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlantic City Monday, as elsewhere along the coast,
lifeguards restricted bathers to waist-deep water and few swimmers
found themselves in trouble, said Robert Levy, that city's beach
patrol director.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
