<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTRONAUTS-NASA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATOR, 46, RETURNS TO ASTRONAUT CORP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Idaho third-grade teacher Barbara Morgan is back in line, albeit
a long one, for a trip to space.
</P>
<P>
   The 46-year-old educator was one of 31 people from seven
countries and from backgrounds as varied as medicine, engineering
and the military who gathered Monday at the Johnson Space Center as
members of NASA's latest class of astronaut candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan gained notoriety more than a dozen years ago as the
backup to Christa McAuliffe, the New Hampshire schoolteacher who
perished with six others in the explosion of the shuttle
Challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the space agency announced an end to its
lengthy deliberations over whether Morgan, the mother of two young
boys, would get the opportunity to fly. Morgan would, NASA
administrator Dan Goldin decided in January, but only after
qualifying as a full-fledged NASA mission specialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure glad I'm here,'' beamed Morgan, who is eligible
because NASA has decided to include teachers in the list of
professions eligible to become astronauts. ``Training with this
class and having education fully integrated like this is a big and
important step. I'm glad to be part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   As McAuliffe and Morgan prepared for their much heralded mission
in the mid-1980s they were considered ``payload specialists,''
professionals invited by NASA to fly in space because their
expertise was needed for a particular mission. They did not intend
to make a career of spaceflight.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, like her colleagues, faces a year of instruction before
she is eligible for a flight assignment. Once eligible for flight,
most mission specialists are assigned to ground-based
responsibilities for a year or two before they are named to a
flight crew. The training for a specific mission can take another
year.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan intends to weave her passion for education with an
opportunity to help assemble the new U.S.-led international space
station or to conduct scientific research in space. At the same
time, she plans to remain a liaison between the nation's educators
and the space agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education is really important to NASA, and it's certainly
important to our country,'' said Morgan, who left a third-grade
classroom in McCall, Idaho, to join NASA full time. ``All of these
folks are here because of a good educational system. We are all
here to learn and work together.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,600 U.S. citizens applied to NASA for a slot in the
astronaut corps. Less than 5 percent qualified for an interview,
and only 25 were hired.
</P>
<P>
   The new class was expanded by six to include astronauts from
France, Italy, Germany, Canada and Brazil. Eight Houston-area
professionals are among the new class: Patricia Hilliard, 35, of
Seabrook; Gary C. Johnson, 44, of Friendswood; Clayton Anderson,
39, of League City; Timothy Creamer, 38, of League City; Gregory
Chamitoff, 36, of Houston; Michael Fossum, 40, of Houston; Steven
Swanson, 37, of Friendswood; and Douglas Wheelock, 37, of Seabrook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm absolute thrilled to be a part of this program, with the
space station around the corner,'' said Hilliard, a NASA flight
surgeon. ``I think that provides a stepping stone for future
exploration.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been flying air planes for over 20 years,'' said Johnson,
a former military aviator who serves as a research pilot and chief
of maintenance for the NASA aircraft based at Ellington Field.
``This is the best flying job in the universe.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
