<SLUG> BC-CYANIDE-LETTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCER PATIENT ARRESTED IN PLOT TO MAIL SODIUM CYANIDE PACKETS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)   (jw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A woman stricken with cancer who lives in a van
was arrested here on Sunday in what authorities said was a plot to
mail packets of sodium cyanide to at least 100 people, including
medical professionals and a dozen or more New York residents, by
disguising the contents as nutritional supplements.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Kathryn Schoonover, 50, was seen by a witness in the
lobby of a post office in Marina del Rey on Sunday afternoon
wearing protective gloves and filling the packets from a container
marked as poison, Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department and
postal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The witness, who was getting mail from a post office box, went
outside and called authorities, who found the woman in a van parked
in front of the post office. At least 100 envelopes, containing
about a teaspoon each of sodium cyanide and a health supplement
brochure, had not been mailed.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schoonover, who appeared bald and gaunt in a photograph on
television news programs, was booked on suspicion of attempted
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Sodium cyanide can be lethal in doses as small as a few
milligrams, said Brent Ekins, the director of the division of the
California Poison Control System in Fresno. People who ingest it
often collapse, vomit, suffer convulsions and seizures and pass
out, Ekins said, and they can die within minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff's department said detectives had confirmed that four
people on the list, New York residents, have received similar
correspondence from Ms. Schoonover in the last two months, though
it was unclear if those envelopes contained poison. Some intended
recipients contacted by authorities knew who she was, while others
had no recollection.
</P>
<P>
   Officials declined to identify the recipients or the witness.
Ms. Schoonover denied to investigators that she had previously
mailed out any pamphlets and did not offer an explanation for
having envelopes with poison in them. Officials said anyone who had
received such a package should contact a postal inspector.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators worked through the night into Monday reaching
people on the mailing list, many of whom are medical profession.
Bob Killeen, a sheriff's deputy, said detectives were trying to
determine whether those professionals, including physicians and
people who draw blood, had treated Ms. Schoonover.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what the common thread yet is,'' Killeen said.
``It may be some place where she was treated, we don't know. Our
investigators are working like mad to try and get in contact with
people. It's really quite chaotic. It's a very difficult case.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officers from West Covina, an eastern suburb of Los
Angeles, were on the list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
