<HEADER>
A9922 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-DRUG-COX     08-24 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-DRUG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Over-the-counter drug causes quite a stir in sports circles
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Monday, Mark McGwire took a rest. The same could not be said
of the controversy rippling throughout the sports world regarding
his use of an over-the-counter drug.
</P>
<P>
   The substance is Androstenedione, a container of which was
spotted in the St. Louis slugger's locker last week by a reporter.
His story touched off a firestorm over McGwire's consumption of the
drug, which is banned by many major sports organizations because a
segment of the medical community considers it about as close as you
can get on the hormone chain to illegal anabolic steroids.
</P>
<P>
   While McGwire sat in the dugout during the Cardinals' rainout in
Pittsburgh:
</P>
<P>
   _ Baseball commissioner Bud Selig spent the day soliciting
opinions from medical experts on the drug.
</P>
<P>
   _ Many American athletes involved in Olympic sports phoned the
U.S. Olympic Committee's drug hotline to ask why they cannot ingest
it.
</P>
<P>
   _ An NCAA official expressed concern that its use is growing on
the college level.
</P>
<P>
   _ Health and nutrition retail stores reported inquiries from
curious customers about its availability.
</P>
<P>
   As McGwire closes in on one of sports' most revered records _
the single-season home run mark of 61 _ the little pills he
swallows to raise testosterone levels in his body and thus increase
strength has drawn attention to the inconsistent approach toward
drugs among athletics organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Most Olympic sport federations test for numerous drugs not only
at major events but also in spot out-of-competition situations. The
NCAA tests athletes out of season and at post-season events. The
NFL tests for steroids at the start of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball, like the NBA, forbids only some illegal
``street'' drugs. In both cases, drug policies are determined in
conjunction with the players association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any change will have to be approved by the union,'' Selig
said. ``This is a collective bargaining matter.''
</P>
<P>
   A league spokesman said Selig received varied opinions on the
potential risks of Androstenedione and hopes to bring his findings
soon to the players union.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic world's position is clear. Billie Marseilles-Berge,
a USOC pharmacist, said Androstenedione has been on the
International Olympic Committee's banned list ``forever,'' but not
until last year did athletes begin asking about the status of its
various brand-name supplements. Swimmers from the former East
Germany previously had been known to rely on the drug to improve
performance, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Marseilles-Berge said research generally supports claims that
the drug raises levels of testosterone, the body's primary
muscle-building hormone. As a result, it is forbidden under IOC
drug guidelines, even if it enables the body to create more of a
natural substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you bake a cake and you add one cake mix, it'll make you a
regular size cake,'' she said. ``If you go out and take five cake
mixes, you're going to have a really big cake. Well, the analogy
here is they're adding in more cake mixes.''
</P>
<P>
   The substance is under scrutiny from the Food and Drug
Administration because it is advertised to double or triple the
production of testosterone.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are curious,'' Marseilles-Berge said. ``The
big question is, why are they allowing it in baseball. Most of my
guys know you can't use it.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL prohibited the substance in December 1996. Dr. John
Lombardo, the league's adviser on steroids, cited the anabolic
steroid qualities of the drug and the fact that no studies have
been conducted on side effects.
</P>
<P>
   The recent suspensions of Georgia Tech tight ends Chris Myers
and Mike Lillie after positive tests for the drug illustrated its
presence on the college level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's catching on because it's accessible,'' said Cindy Thomas,
the NCAA's assistant director of sports science. ``Athletes find
it's there and they can get their hands on it. It does increase
performance, increases strength and size ... and that catches on.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not expensive, either. One form of the drug costs $50-$60
for 120 pills, about a 30-day supply for the recommended dosage of
four to six pills a day. Another form costs $20-$40 for 80
capsules.
</P>
<P>
   GNC stores, a national chain, does not stock Androstenedione
because, as local franchise owner Mark Leavitt said Monday, ``it's
too much related to steroids.''
</P>
<P>
   But other stores with the drug on their shelves indicated the
publicity has triggered calls. Greg Hynson, owner of Super
Nutrition in Marietta, Ga., said he bemoans the negative hoopla
over the product, and indicated he believes it's a safe and
effective supplement. Hynson says taking a capsule prior to working
out temporarily raises one's testosterone level by ''about 100
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   ''You basically get a small spike for a duration of three or
four hours,'' Hynson said. ''When testosterone levels are raised,
you're going to have greater nitrogen retention. And with higher
nitrogen levels, you can recover faster from any workout.
</P>
<P>
   ''It does make you stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Some experts are hesitant about recommending hormone supplements
in amounts above what the body would naturally produce. Dr. William
Regelson, author of ``The Super Hormone Promise: Nature's Answer to
Aging'' and an oncologist at Medical College of Virginia in
Richmond, advocates using supplements only at replacement levels as
the hormones begin to decline around age 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``Athletes are using these supplements beyond what is needed to
prevent decline,'' he said. ``There should be a word of caution in
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents also claim Androstenedione can aide sexual
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fish writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. AJC staff writers Amanda Husted, I.J. Rosenberg and Len
Pasquarelli contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
