<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves on deck: Houston Astros
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ When: Tonight and Wednesday at 8:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: TBS will telecast tonight's game, Fox Sports South will
telecast Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Probable starting pitchers: Today, RHP Kevin Millwood (14-7,
4.35; first appearance vs. Astros) vs. LHP Mike Hampton (9-6, 3.87;
2-6, 3.66 lifetime vs. Braves). Wednesday, RHP John Smoltz (12-2,
3.44; 13-12, 3.12 lifetime vs. Astros) vs. RHP Sean Bergman (11-6,
3.44; 1-2, 7.11 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   _ Series history: Atlanta leads the all-time series 277-275 but
is 7-8 at the Astrodome dating back to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   _ Past meetings: The Braves split a four-game series in Houston
May 15-18. A two-homer performance by Eddie Perez decided the first
game, before Astros starters Shane Reynolds and Sean Bergman
limited Atlanta to three earned run over the next two games. Tom
Glavine salvaged the split with seven innings of shutout work in a
4-0 win in the fourth game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Astros leaders: Ave.: Craig Biggio (.327); HR Moises Alou
(38); RBI Alou (115); SB Craig Biggio (41). W Shane Reynolds (16);
ERA Randy Johnson (1.46). Saves Billy Wagner (24). Strikeouts
Reynolds (167).
</P>
<P>
   _ Quickly: The Astros are coming off a 6-2 road trip that just
concluded with a three-game sweep in Chicago. Houston's NL Central
lead over the Cubs, which was 3-1/2 games when the month began, is
up to a season-high 10-1/2. After going 53-34 (.609) before the
All-Star break, Houston is 29-16 (.644) since. . . . The current
82-50 record is the best 132-game record in Houston history. With
two more victories, the team can match t season win total. .
. . The club has already set a franchise record for homers,
surpassing the 138-mark over the weekend, the old mark set in 1993.
The Astros have hit 13 homers in their last six games alone. . . .
Houston is leading the league in runs (738), RBI (680), stolen
bases (132) and on-base percentage (.357). They trail only Colorado
in hits, average and doubles. . . . The team ERA (3.64) is third
lowest in the league. Only the Braves have walked fewer batters. .
. . Hampton, tonight's starter, has just one victory in his last 11
starts. Seven of those games have been no-decisions. He is 1-3
since coming off the DL July 3 (strained groin). While his ERA has
remained respectable, Hampton has been hit consistently during this
span, having given up 76 hits in his last 60 innings. The Braves
beat him 4-0 May 18, when the bottom of the Atlanta order was
6-for-13 and drove in three runs. . . . On the DL: RHP Chris Holt
(shoulder surgery), RHP Ramon Garcia (right elbow ligament strain),
RHP Jose Cabrera (sore right shoulder), INF Jack Howell (broken
left hamate bone).
</P>
<P>
   Who's hot: OF Moises Alou was 12-for-33 (.363) on the road trip
and has homered in eight of his last 18 games. 2B Craig Biggio has
four homers in his last three games and is second in the league
with 41 stolen bases. 3B Sean Berry has seven hits in his last 13
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Who's not: OF Derek Bell went 6-for-31 (.194) on the road trip.
INF Tim Bogar is hitless in 15 at-bats, during which time his wife
gave birth to their second child. 1B Jeff Bagwell has one hit in
his last eight at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
