</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BENGALS-MATHIAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mathias walks tall, makes big noise in NFL
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Amidst the glittering array of major college stars
stands the NFL's version of the underdog ``Rudy'' _ 5-foot-10,
180-pound Ric Mathias from NCAA Division III University of
Wisconsin-La Crosse.
</P>
<P>
   Intimidated? Not at all. Eager to show he belongs in the NFL?
Absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   All the undrafted rookie cornerback did in the Bengals' 33-19
victory over Detroit was commit two crimes _ one that aided the
enemy and another that sealed the win.
</P>
<P>
   Flagged for fair-catch interference when he bumped Detroit's
Terry Fair while trying to down a punt inside Detroit's 5-yard
line, Mathias made up for it by intercepting a Chris Dittoe pass
and racing 67 yards for a touchdown with 34 seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   Mathias' last-minute heroics may not be enough to make the team.
That's why he's sweating out today's seven cuts as NFL rosters get
reduced to 60.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking every play like it's my last play,'' Mathias said.
``I'm enjoying the people I'm around. I'm very, very grateful to be
in this situation and I just don't want to take anything for
granted.''
</P>
<P>
   What isn't subject to debate is his intensity, desire and
lightning quickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like his guts, determination, quickness, speed and
toughness,'' said Jim Lippincott, the Bengals director of
pro/college personnel. ``The kid has a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL teams are always hunting talent. So when the Bengals got a
call from UW-La Crosse coach Roger Harring regarding Mathias, they
figured: Why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't expecting very much,'' Lippincott said. ``What we
got was something pretty commendable. Ric plays the game the way
it's meant to be played _ 100 miles an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathias knows he fighting tremendous odds with his size and
inexperience. But when skeptics say, ``You can't,'' he says, ``I
can.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from a small school, you're not expected to make it to
this level,'' he said. ``You see these guys on TV and you just
dream of playing with them someday. Now all of a sudden it's come
true. You have to understand you're here and you can't get caught
up in all the hoopla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not intimidated by these guys as far as their speed and
strength. It's just a matter of getting to know who I've got to
respect and how many steps I've got to give certain receivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathias admits the complexity of the Bengals 3-4 defense with
all the checks, formations and responsibilities is ``a lot more
mentally taxing'' than college. But he's adjusting well.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are pulling for me to see if I can hang on,'' he said.
``I just want to make the most of my opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Chick Ludwig writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
