</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SAFETY-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO NAME COUNCIL TO OVERSEE FOOD SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (mk) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will appoint a high-level council
to oversee food safety in the United States, an activity now
performed separately by a dozen agencies, a senior White House
official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The official said Clinton would sign an executive order on
Tuesday establishing the council, which would have the
responsibility of coordinating enforcement, research and
educational activities but would not have the authority to do any
of those things on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Although the United States is generally regarded as having one
of the safest food supplies in the world, there are frequent
outbreaks of illnesses, many of them fatal, caused by harmful
substances in food. In recent years a strain of bacteria known as
E. coli 0157:H7 has caused many illnesses and deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The government until recently has shown little leadership in
dealing with illnesses caused by unwholesome food. There is a
patchwork of weak state agencies as well as a federal bureaucracy
that focused more on reacting to outbreaks than on preventing them.
The new executive order places emphasis on prevention.
</P>
<P>
   In a report issued last week by the Institute of Research and
the National Research Council, two groups that advise the
government on science, the number of deaths caused by food-borne
organisms was estimated at 9,000 a year, a figure that uted
by the food industry as too high.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the panel that produced the report, Dr. John
Bailar III of the University of Chicago, said, ``The United States
has some of the attributes of an effective food safety system, but
it lacks a central authority and is hampered by old laws that don't
allow flexible responses to today's threats.''
</P>
<P>
   The organizations, arms of the National Academy of Science,
called in its report for the appointment of one individual to
oversee food safety, a ``czar'' in current government argot.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the president will name a troika to lead the new
council, which is not expected to require any new federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will appoint three co-chairmen of what will be called
the President's Council on Food Safety. They will be the secretary
of Agriculture, the secretary of Health and Human Services and the
assistant to the president for science and technology.
</P>
<P>
   Serving as members of the council will be the secretary of
Commerce, the director of the Office of Management and Budget, the
administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency, the assistant
to the president for domestic policy and the director of the
National Partnership for Reinventing Government.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of consumer and industry organizations, who had not
yet seen the final order, praised its overall thrust, but with some
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Smith DeWaal, director of food safety at the Center for
Science in the Public Interest, a consumer group, lamented the
choice of a three-headed council over a strong individual as
recommended in the scientists' report.
</P>
<P>
   But she added: ``We think that this is acceptable as a temporary
measure, a first step. The report clearly found weaknesses in how
we currently inspect food. This is modestly better.''
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Willard, the spokesman of the National Food Processors
Association, said the appointment of the council ``seems to be
moving in the right direction.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The industry official was pleased that the program would not be
led by a single person. ``When you have a czar, that would probably
create a new bureaucracy,'' he said. ``It is important to keep
politics out of food safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House official said Congress would not be asked to
provide additional federal money to run the council.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why the president was creating the council by
executive order instead of asking Congress to institute it with
legislation, she answered: ``When the law allows us to put in place
a mechanism with an executive order, we are going to act to achieve
our objectives. Current law does allow us to put it in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Left unsaid was the likelihood that the Republican-controlled
Congress would have refused to pass legislation creating the
council.
</P>
<P>
   Rahm Emanuel, a senior adviser to President Clinton, said Monday
that the creation of the council was an important part in Clinton's
efforts to make food safety a high priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the system has been unchanged since Teddy Roosevelt
put it in place,'' Emanuel said. ``It's another chapter in the
president's efforts to modernize the nation's food safety system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
