<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9944 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BONNIE-COX     08-24 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bonnie flirting, keeps coast guessing
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt and Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WRIGHTSVILLE BEACH, N.C. _ With Hurricane Bonnie at least a day
away, surfers Monday rode the churning, dangerously powerful waves
next to a pier badly damaged two years ago by Hurricanes Bertha and
Fran.
</P>
<P>
   The landmark Johnnie Mercer's Fishing Pier and other businesses
along this narrow beach town have recovered from Bertha and Fran,
but residents have not forgotten the wreckage caused by the
back-to-back hurricanes _ North Carolina's most costly natural
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will leave if Bonnie is headed this way,'' said Eric
Knowles, 27, manager of Johnnie Mercer's pier, which lost 320 of
its 740 feet when Bertha barrelled up the Cape Fear River on July
12, 1996, and Fran followed on Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Thick pilings that supported the end of the pier snapped off in
the storms. As reminders of the hurricanes' fury, the ragged
timbers still stick out of the blueish green water.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the North Carolina coast would take its third direct hit
in two years remained frustratingly uncertain Monday night, as
Bonnie, with sustained winds of 115 mph, moved erratically in the
Atlantic some 600 miles off the Florida coast, menacing the whole
Southern seaboard.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service issued a hurricane watch Monday for
an area stretching from Savannah to the North Carolina/Virginia
border. Forecasters said Bonnie could make landfall Wednesday
morning _ or not at all, possibly turning north and skirting the
area.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Bonnie's erratic movement, no areas had been
evacuated Monday, and vacationers continued to frolic along the
beaches.
</P>
<P>
   At Wrightsville Beach, officials said Monday that a possible
evacuation was at leay away, but many property owners picked
up decals that would allow them to return to the island in the
event it is closed to the general public.
</P>
<P>
   On the Georgia coast, emergency officials and residents were on
hold as Bonnie stalled and wobbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the coastal counties are just sitting around waiting for
her to make up her mind,'' said Becky Tindall, assistant to Glynn
County Emergency Management Director Ed Abel.
</P>
<P>
   Abel said the Wal-Mart in Brunswick was stripped of D-cell
batteries over the weekend as residents laid in extra flashlight
batteries, bottled water, nonperishible foods and other essentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's just hurry up and wait,'' he said. ``It's too
early to evacuate. But as close as this storm is, if it picks up
speed and comes toward us, we'll all be moving and moving
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   On St. Simons Island, residents and vacationers enjoyed a
windless, sunshiny day, despite the fact that high surf advisories
covered the length of the Georgia coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ocean looked just like it always does when I rode past the
pier,'' said Gordon Strother, co-owner of J.C. Strother &AMP; Co., the
island's oldest hardware store near the beach. ``I'm looking out
the window at the oak trees right now and you can barely see the
leaves moving.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Palmer, a plywood salesman from Savannah, said plywood
sales were brisk Monday. In South Carolina, where the memories of
Hurricane Hugo's 135 mph winds remain vivid after nine years, Gov.
David Beasley ordered 1,300 National Guardsmen to coastal armories
in case they are needed to direct evacuations.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, many coastal communities still show evidence
of the long recovery from the 1996 hurricanes. At the northern end
of Wrightsville Beach, an inlet washes against sandbags protecting
Shell Island Resort, a high-rise that closed for nine months of
repairs after Hurricane Fran.
</P>
<P>
   At a cost of $2 million, a beach renourishment project pumped
900,000 cubic yards of sand onto the beach. But a dearth of dunes
leaves some waterfront homes vulnerable to high water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are as ready as we can be ready,'' said Wrightsville Beach
Mayor Avery Roberts, 72, at the town hall on Sea Water Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing near Shell Island Resort, Daniel Goff, 20, said he had
stocked up on water, canned tuna and beer and had stored his
20-foot boat.
</P>
<P>
   Even though a violent wave broke his surfboard in half Monday,
Goff said, ``I am going to stay. I'm just waiting to pick up a new
surfboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
