<HEADER>
A9951 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-SCHOOLFUNDING-CO     08-24 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-SCHOOLFUNDING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Emotions tense as hearing on schools, taxes opens
 &HT;    By Tim Miller
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW LEXINGTON, Ohio _ The state of Ohio and a coalition of local
school districts squared off in a southeastern Ohio courtroom
Monday during a sometimes tense hearing that saw the state
solicitor quote Communist Karl Marx to support property taxes for
schools and the schools' attorney deride the General Assembly's
funding fix.
</P>
<P>
   The courtroom drama was a new starting point for a 7-year-old
legal case in which a coalition of Ohio school districts has been
trying to force the state to adopt a new funding mechanism that
provides every student with a ``thorough and efficient'' education
as required by the state constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio Coalition for Equity &AMP; Adequacy of School Funding won
its case on March 24, 1997 when the Ohio Supreme Court ordered a
new funding formula. In the following 17 months, the General
Assembly has taken numerous steps it says solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The new trial before Judge Linton D. Lewis Jr. of the Perry
County Common Pleas Court is to determine the validity of that
claim. Lewis issued the original ruling in 1994, finding the system
unconstitutional because its relies too heavily on local property
taxes and thus property-poor districts cannot adequately fund their
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The first day featured opening arguments followed by nearly five
hours of testimony and cross-examination of House Speaker Jo Ann
Davidson, R-Reynoldsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Both she and State Solicitor Jeffrey Sutton said the Legislature
has pumped millionsof additional dollars into primary and
secondary education, has developed a new funding subsidy of $4,063
per pupil, and is providing additional millions for school
renovation and construction.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton said the changes reduce the reliance on property taxes
and redistribute tax dollars across the state. He said the high
court did not demand that property taxes be scrapped and that it
would not be feasible to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karl Marx could not have identified a fairer way of
distributing wealth,' Sutton said. ``I can't believe the voters
want us to get rid of that linchpin of our system.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nicholas Pittner, coalition attorney, said legislative
leaders have ``fallen woefully short'' of a systemic overhaul of
the funding formula. ``What was then is now. We haven't fixed it.
It is a house of cards that will collapse under close scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson appeared testy at times under cross-examination from
coalition attorney Quintin Lindsmith, who suggested that the
Legislature made the situation worse by enacting new mandates on
schools only to see voters defeat a state sales tax hike that many
believed was to be ufund the new formula.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson denied that the tax hike was directly linked to the
school reforms and said money from other revenue sources will be
available to pay for the changes.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time Monday, coalition leaders put their price tag
on the cost of an adequate education.
</P>
<P>
   If the case as expected goes back to the Supreme Court, Pittner
said the schools would ask for an order forcing the state to
gu $5,051 per student. Assuming a 50-50 split between with
local school districts, the new figure would add more than $1
billion to the $5.2 billion the state now spends annually on public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition also wants the state to pay the entire cost of
transportation and special education. And ultimately if the schools
have their way, a court-appointed overseer would determine the cost
of an adequate education and a way to pay for it, Pittner said.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Miller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
