<SLUG> BC-MA-HERALD-REDESIGN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TABLOID HERALD FIELDS REDESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Some Boston Herald readers blinked when they saw it,
confusing the newly colorized tabloid with USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   Others never saw the paper at all, or at least not until well
after the morning commute, because of a production foul-up that
delayed delivery for hours in some cases and nearly melted down the
newspaper's central switchboard with readers' calls.
</P>
<P>
   When the ink had dried on Monday's much-heralded, $10 million
Herald redesign, though, most agreed that the effort was both
splashy and historic. Splashy in the sense that the paper's snazzy
new packaging was a certified eye-grabber, and historic in the
sense that, for better or for worse, an era in local newspapering
was officially McPapered over and done with.
</P>
<P>
   Or, HUB TABLOID BIDS FANS ADIEU.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is the Herald's doing what all local TV stations and
newsmagazines are doing, and that's giving readers what the focus
groups say they want,'' said Northeastern journalism professor
Charles Fountain. ``Whether this means USA Today without the
national weather map or USA Today with an attitude remains to be
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston Business Journal editor Jay Fitzgerald pronounced the
redesign ``very, very good _ as close as you can get to a home run
with a redesign, and I've redesigned a few papers myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming from Chicago, where the tabloid Sun Times underwent a
similar redesign in the '90s, Fitzgerald said he recognizes the
gamble being undertaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always that fear of alienating old-time loyal readers,
and I can see some saying, `Oh, the Herald is going too upscale,'''
Fitzgerald said. ``But the paper clearly needs more suburban
readers. And frankly I'm mostly hearing positive things so far.''
</P>
<P>
   New England Adweek editor Judy Warner noted a richer mix of
national advertisers in Monday's Herald, a hopeful sign for the
market's No. 2 newspaper, but not necessarily a guarantee of future
profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the crisis of confidence in journalism today, including
local journalism, the redesign could not have come at a better time
for the Herald,'' said Warner. ``But something may still be lost
here. Will the Herald take itself too seriously? That remains to be
seen. If they wind up losing readers, they'll probably tweak the
new design and go back to their old tricks.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's tricks had some readers out trying to track down a copy
of the paper before lunch hour. Malfunctioning presses and problems
with the equipment that folds the paper led to an embarrassingly
late roll-out that prompted hundreds of complaints from impatient
readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing was horrible, especially considering the time and
effort spent on promotion,'' acknowledged Gwen Gage, Herald vice
president for promotion.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gage, the Herald printed 375,000 copies of Monday's
paper, 50,000 more than the usual press run. While some areas west
and north of the city were unaffected by the production delays, the
downtown area _ the heart of the paper's readership _ was hardest
hit. Many newsstand customers simply assumed the paper had sold
out, unaware that it had yet to arrive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
