<HEADLINE>
WHILE CRONY CAPITALISTS THRIVE, MANY RUSSIANS FACE BLEAK FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A middle-aged woman wipes away a tear as she emerges
from the MOST Bank a block from Red Square. She just learned that
Russia's currency crisis had prevented her from withdrawing
savings.
</P>
<P>
   At a subway entrance, an old woman leans heavily against the
railing, burdened by two bags stuffed with bootleg beer that she
would sell for a few rubles' profit _ survival money for someone
whose pension works out to about $40 a month.
</P>
<P>
   These are scenes from the ``new'' Russia. With the ruble
devalued, prices will go up once more, further lowering a standard
of living that has plummeted through the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly seven years after the Soviet Union's fall, many Russians
feel powerless. They are embittered at their president and deeply
cynical about a government in which corrupt Communist bosses have
been replaced by crony capitalists _ sometimes the very same
people.
</P>
<P>
   They see poverty of pensioners intensify while the new rich
consume conspicuously. Last week, after the ruble was allowed to
free-fall, customers found themselves unable to withdraw savings
from MOST, one of the city's major commercial banks. Its major
owner, Vladimir Gusinsky, was vacationing at his home in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Russia, there is no change. Any real change must still come
in the future,'' said Irina Gorvich, an elderly architect who
helped restore the Great Palace in Pavlovsk near St. Petersburg
after it was looted and burned by German occupiers in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The crony capitalism of today ``is not much different from the
old Communist Party,'' added Alexey Naimoosheen, 23, a medical
student from Ufa in the Ural Mountains, who was visiting his sister
in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Naimoosheen sees President Boris Yeltsin as nothing more than
the party boss he was for most of his adult life. ``He is
Communist, he was Communist. We need somebody else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll found that only 4 percent of Russians would back a
Yeltsin re-election bid in 2000. It's not hard to see why. Russia's
``misery index'' figures shoot off the chart.
</P>
<P>
   The male life expectancy in Russia has declined since 1987 from
65 to 57 years. An estimated 75 percent of the population lives at
or below the subsistence level. The once-buoyant stock market has
dropped more than 75 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Such figures do not even factor in the way average Russians get
beaten down by the system, or fleeced in various scams. One
incident recently took place in St. Petersburg, a city that lost an
estimated 1.1 million people as German troops tried to starve it
into submission during a 900-day World War II siege.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a bank that opened a fund for veterans, promising
tremendous profits. In a year or so, the bank collapsed,'' said
Father Alexander Tkachenko, a Russian Orthodox priest who works at
St. Nicholas's Cathedral in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian court system refused to order owners of the defunct
bank to pay back any of the investors' money. The veterans appealed
to the St. Petersburg city government. The mayor promised to redeem
their investment out of public funds. Instead of taxes going for
good roads and medical care _ two critical needs of the city _ ``we
end up helping banks solve their problems,'' Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the Soviet era came the term ``blat,'' which roughly
translates as influence or clout. While Communism has been
consigned to the dust bin of history, ``blat'' still rules Russia.
</P>
<P>
   A new generation of oligarchs was allowed to buy state assets
cheaply. The result has been creation of economic empires like
Gazprom, which controls one-third of the world's natural gas
reserves and accounts for about 5 percent of Russia's economy.
</P>
<P>
   It is Russia's largest taxpayer, but Gazprom ``does not pay
nearly the taxes that it should,'' author David Remnick noted in
his book ``Resurrection: The Struggle for a new Russia.'' Recently,
government tax authorities put a lien on Gazprom assets until a
deal for higher taxes was worked out.
</P>
<P>
   The last oil and gas minister of the Soviet Union, Viktor
Chernomyrdin, became head of Gazprom when it was privatized. The
job reportedly made him one of Russia's richest men.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin was named in 1993 as Russia's prime minister, and
served five years. On Sunday, four months after firing him, Yeltsin
reinstated the industrialist-technocrat as head of government.
Gazprom stock rose 24 percent on news of Chernomyrdin's
reinstatement.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the government cannot pay salaries to the millions of
people who still work for it.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Kisselev, an obstetrician-gynecologist in St. Petersburg,
has not been paid in two months. She does receive income from
private patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blat'' operates in ways large and small. The omni-present
security force at the Intourist Hotel in downtown Moscow is known
to harass ordinary Russians when they enter. Last week, however,
prostitutes brazenly plied their trade in the hotel's bars, casino
and elevator landing. A man appearing to be a pimp sat in the lobby
bar, frequently rising to huddle with security men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nouveau Russians!'' snapped an engineer in Pavlovsk as he
passed a mammoth new house near his city's famous 19th century
palace.
</P>
<P>
   The country's new rich do not hesitate to show off their wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prominent businessmen and pop-stars, famous politicians and
diplomats are frequent guests of our Club. Join us and feel
yourself part of St. Petersburg's high life!'' says a brochure for
the posh Taleon Club, located in a restored mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Once though a metal detector, guests partake of caviar and
sturgeon in a restaurant where the tab can equal two months' wages
for an average Russian.
</P>
<P>
   They can gamble at the club's two casinos advertised as
``comparable only to ... Monte Carlo.'' Fine cognacs and cigars are
available in the Cigar Salon. Guests can work off such consumption
in the fitness room, and recover in a sauna and spa-pool.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, in the Alexander Nevsky Montastery by the gates of a
cemetery in which Dostoevsky and Tchaikovsky lie buried, an elderly
man in a threadbare suit approached a visiting American. His name
was Viktor. He was begging, in perfect English.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am an Orthodox refuge from Azerbaijan,'' Viktor said,
referring to a Muslim former Soviet republic by the Caspian Sea.
Once a teacher, he now lives in a tiny city flat, without a
vegetable garden or children to help him get by on his tiny
pension.
</P>
<P>
   Feodor Ivanovich, 85, fought the Nazis and was wounded twice.
Portions of three fingers are missing on his left hand, but he
still crafts icon frames. He, too, is an Orthodox believer and has
watched with joy the reopening of a church in Pavlovsk where he
first worshiped more than 60 years ago. It was long used as a
repair facility for Red Army tanks. While Ivanovich can again hear
the word of God, he knows that many fellow veterans are not getting
enough to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if life is better in the new Russia, Ivanovich stroked his
chin and replied: ``It is a very difficult question. Some people
think in Soviet times, it was better than now.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Russia has genuine adherents, mainly among young people
who sense opportunities in capitalism and have the skills to be
part of a global marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``For someone young and speaking a foreign language, it is no
problem,'' said Nina Novikova, 23, a recent university graduate who
is going to work in Moscow before pursuing post-graduate studies.
</P>
<P>
   There is an array of once-scarce products, and a climate of free
cultural expression in which one can find a Kurt Cobain calendar
for sale at the new World War II memorial on a hill above Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are silly,'' said Lena, an 18-year-old university
student, when asked about people who believe life was better under
Communism.
</P>
<P>
   The view was different, however, among older people lined up at
banks, and among Russians who live away from the bustle of Moscow
and St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been hungry all their life long. Now they are
getting angry,'' said Father Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   Naimoosheen, whose grandfather was Jewish, is thinking of
leaving Ufa and emigrating to Israel or Germany. He is, slowly,
building up a stash of precious American dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a real life,'' he said. ``You can have a real life in
Moscow and St. Petersburg, if you have a job and can live there.
You can have a real life in other countries. But for many people,
in many Russian places, there is no real life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
