<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE LAND BUY IN N.M. WOULD BE BIGGEST IN QUARTER CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic and photo are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEMEZ SPRINGS, N.M. _ In what would be the largest purchase of
private land by the U.S. Forest Service in at least a quarter
century, Congress and the Clinton administration are forging a
consensus to buy the Baca Ranch, a 95,000-acre expanse of alpine
meadows and fir-covered mountains so emblematic of the West that it
has served as backdrop for Stetson hat advertisements and Marlboro
man billboards.
</P>
<P>
   For Hollywood directors, Madison Avenue advertisers or the rare
invited guest, the appeal of the isolated greensward, cupped in the
walls of an ancient volcano, is often the same. The Baca ranch
imparts a rare sense of discovery. Driving on Route 4 over a dark
and winding mountain pass, the visitor suddenly emerges into a
``Lost Horizon'' world of hot springs, trout streams, and meadows
of wildflowers where cattle and the state's largest elk herd graze
side by side.
</P>
<P>
   But the same sense of wide-open Western independence evoked by
the vistas has prevented the sale of the land for years. And the
deal to buy the ranch, which has been owned by one family for
almost 40 years, is as much about attitudes toward public land as
it is about money.
</P>
<P>
   Tton administration has long supported buying the ranch,
which has been called ``the hole in the donut,'' because it is a
privately owned island surrounded on all sides by the Santa Fe
National Forest. Last February on a visit to New Mexico, President
Clinton even had Air Force One make a detour to fly over the ranch
for a better view of its dominant feature _ a 15-mile-wide crater
of the dormant volcano.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, noting that almost one third of New Mexico is
already owned by the federal government, have long opposed further
purchases. But in August, Republican sentiment began shifting
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Under legislation drafted by Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., the
Baca would be a separate unit of the National Forest system, owned
by the U.S. Forest Service, but managed by a trust, comprised of
members appointed by the president. This board would be charged
with responding to local wishes and making the park economically
self-sustaining.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Domenici's bill would tie an agreement to purchase
the Baca to legislation intended to speed sales of land owned by
the Bureau of Land Management that the agency has decided it does
not need.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, particularly those in Western states, are eager to
free up more federal land for private development.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici said that the sale of the such land could increase
support among Western senators for his legislation, to be
introduced early next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we could get set aside this fall $20 to $40 million,''
Domenici said, ``money that says to the owners we are going to do
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the owners, the Dunigans, an oil family from
Abilene, Texas, expressed interest in selling the ranch in 1980,
the price was $55 million. Competition for the land between the
National Park Service and the National Forest Service, as well as
the death of the family patriarch, James Patrick Dunigan, squelched
that deal.
</P>
<P>
   Although new appraisals have not been completed, the 1998 price
could easily be twice as high.
</P>
<P>
   Driving the price, and public interest, is tremendous population
growth in Santa Fe and Albuquerque, the state's two largest cities,
which are about 90 minutes by car from the Baca Ranch. In 1915,
when Woodrow Wilson first considered buying the Baca, recreational
tourism was an embryonic activity. Now, more than 3 million people
visit the Santa Fe National Forest every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Baca could be the Rocky Mountain National Park for the new
Santa Fe-Albuquerque megapolis,'' said Roger Kennedy, a former
National Park Service director who lives in Santa Fe, referring to
the Colorado park that draws visitors from Denver and Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who ran the National Park Service until 1996, said
acquisition of the Baca was similar to the purchase of land for
national parks at the start of the cent   ``It's the largest piece of unviolate land anywhere near a major
city,'' he said. ``Everything else that size is either very remote
or very ugly. This is beautiful and close.''
</P>
<P>
   The Baca began to approach its present form about one million
years ago, when two massive explosions blew the top off a volcano
here, sending 100 cubic miles of ash and lava into the air, some of
it reaching what is now Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   In modern times, Indians from the Santa Clara and Jemez pueblos
hunted the area in the summer. In 1860, Congress settled a land
dispute by giving the area to heirs of Luis Maria Cabeza de Vaca, a
Mexican sheep rancher. From 1926 to 1962, the ranch was owned by
the Bond family, who first grazed sheep, then cattle on the land.
Separately, a timber company heavily logged about half of the
forest area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a smaller kind of Yellowstone, with a number of hot spots
in the streams,'' Frank Bond, a Santa Fe lawyer, said, recalling
childhood summers spent on the remote ranch. ``Because it has a
much more temperate climate that the rest of the Rockies, it has a
greater number of bird species.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, red-tailed hawks could be seen circling
over meadows, looking for prairie dogs that popped in and out of
their holes. Grouse, mourning doves, flickers and bluebirds abound
in this private reserve, which ranges from grasslands and aspens in
the valleys to spruce and fir at high elevations, up to 11,000
feet.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, James Patrick Dunigan bought the ranch for $2.5 million
and instituted a gentler management hand. Through expensive court
battles, he ended the timber lease and stopped most of the logging.
Dunigan died in 1980, in the midst of negotiations to sell the
ranch to the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   His heirs have maintained his management pattern, avoiding
overgrazing and logging largely for the health of the forest.
Giving priority to the elk, which were reintroduced after World War
II, the ranch now maintains about two elk for every cow - about
7,000 elk and 3,000 cows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally have always thought we have been here as
caretakers,'' Anne Dunigan Wilson, Dunigan's widow, said on a
recent visit to a fieldstone hunting lodge her husband had built
here.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Dunigan, one of her sons, said that the family has set a
December deadline for Congress to show serious intent to buy the
property.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are offering the government and the American people the
first opportunity to buy the property,'' said Dunigan, a private
investor based in Dallas. ``This is clearly one of the most
desirable trophy ranches.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
