u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEDERAL-PARK-ART-2NDT     08-24 0290
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEDERAL-PARK-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 JEMEZ SPRINGS, N.M.: trophy ranches.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Local county zoning allows for houses to be built on lots here
as small as three quarters of an acre. With demand growing from New
Mexico's city dwellers for second homes in the mountains, the
threat is real.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mobile homes with skirts around them _ that's the specter
now,'' said Dave Simon, regional director of the National Parks and
Conservation Association, a Washington-based parks support group.
As he bounced in a van along a ranch road, he added: ``There is
constant pressures on ranchers up here to develop. The best places
up here would be cherrypicked for development.''
</P>
<P>
   The threat of development has caused many conservationists to
rally behind the new bipartisan efforts to preserve the area.
However, environmentalists and the Clinton administration insist
that any management board be charged with placing conservation
values over economic values in running the ranch as a park.
</P>
<P>
   ``The resource values of this property must come first,'' Katie
McGinty, chairman of the White House Council on Environmental
Quality, wrote after visiting here in July. ``The trustees may not
sacrifice those values in an effort to make the property
financially self sufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   While staffers for Republican and Democratic congressmen work to
hammer out mutually acceptable legislative language by Labor Day,
negotiations are spurred by the thought of the Baca being sold to
real estate developers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would hate to see it divided up and sold off,'' said Sen.
Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M., and a longtime advocate of public ownership
of the Baca. ``I think prospects are good that we can go ahead when
Congress reconvenes in September.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
