<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVO-COACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RONGEN BOOTED, ZENGA NAMED REVOLUTION COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Last year, Walter Zenga rescued the Revolution with
spectacular performances in goal as they qualified for the MLS
playoffs. Now, the Revolution are counting on Zenga to lead them
again, this time as coach.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga was named interim coach of the Revolution Monday,
replacing Thomas Rongen, who had come under criticism after a 5-1
loss to Los Angeles Saturday solidified the team's position in last
place. Zenga, 38, was honored at halftime of the match, and offered
the position afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``This happened very quickly, it was not in the works before
Saturday's game,'' general manager Brian O'Donovan said. ``We have
always said that the only reason we would make a change is if there
was an alternative that justified making such a change. There
weren't really a lot of good alternatives that would give us what
we hoped to achieve. But Walter was here, and at dinner before the
game he expressed interest in coming back to the Revolution,
whether as a player or in management.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that in mind, after the game Saturday I told him there
was an opportunity to come here as interim coach, if he was
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga, 38, is a legendary figure in Europe, where he performed
for 20 years, making his name with Internazionale Milano and the
Italian national team. He has been exploring new opportunities, and
seemed to genuinely enjoy his experience with the Revolution last
year. But he underwent knee surgery during the season and announced
his retirement in December, then returned to Milan to work in
management with Inter and in the media, along with fiancee Hoara
Borselli, an aspiring actress.
</P>
<P>
   Before coming to the US, Zenga had hoped to have one last chance
with a big-time club. He contacted former national team teammate
GianLuca Vialli, who was playing in England. But former Chelsea
coach Ruud Gullit, later to be replaced as player-coach by Vialli,
rejected him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every move we make at this stage is a bold move,'' O'Donovan
said. ``It's true he hasn't coached a team, but neither had Vialli
or Gullit. In that sense, Larry Bird hadn't been a coach. There are
a lot of coaches with track records who have gone by the wayside.
Experience isn't always the most important of criteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it's taking a chance. Everything we do, every player
we take, is a chance, a judgment call. But we have every confidence
it will work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga, who likely becomes the most famous coach in the history
of Boston-area sports, is expected to return Thursday to prepare
the team for Sunday's visit to Miami. The Revolution, with 20
points in 26 matches, trail the Fusion by 6 points with six matches
remaining for the final playoff spot in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's expected of him is to bring stability to the team, and
to hopefully make a run at the playoffs,'' O'Donovan said. ``We
still have a lot of hopes for making the playoffs but there are
also longer-term issues we've got to consider for the Revolution.
Walter will not be judged solely on making the playoffs. He has to
decide if he likes coaching, if he is suited to coaching. This
gives him a chance to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   Cesidio (Sid) Mazzola, formerly owner and coach of the Boston
Bolts in the American Professional Soccer League, and goalkeeper
coach Pete Simonini will be Zenga's assistants. Assistants Renato
Capobianco and Rich Williams also resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Rongen, MLS coach of the year in 1996 in Tampa, rebuilt the
Revolution after taking over from Frank Stapleton. The Revolution
earned 29 points in their first 19 games under Rongen, but began
floundering when Zenga departed for knee surgery. They have earned
just 29 points in the last 39 games, and dissension has become
apparent recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thomas is a great coach and I virtually guarantee he will be
coaching in the MLS and have success in the MLS,'' O'Donovan said.
``The only reality here is that the job was not getting done. We
will have many postmortems to see what contributed to us not doing
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
