<HEADER>
A9972 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-FLOODING-ART-42     08-24 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-FLOODING-ART-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS FLOODING LEAVES 16 DEAD, AND MORE THAN 60 MISSING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ The sputtering remains of Tropical Storm
Charley had pushed 200 miles up the Rio Grande Valley from the Gulf
of Mexico before stalling early Monday and dumping more than a foot
of rain on South Texas and northern Mexico, turning drought-baked
arroyos into gushing drain spouts and leaving at least 16 people
dead and more than 60 missing.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest loss of life and the fiercest flooding came about
145 miles west of San Antonio, in the remote desert town of Del Rio
and just acroborder in Acuna, Mexico. The rains had begun
early Sunday, and the flooding started shortly after midnight,
residents said, at one point sending a 5-foot wave down the San
Felipe Creek that washed away some 50 homes. Smaller creeks and
arroyos on the north side of town also flooded. By 4 a.m.,
two-thirds of Del Rio was under water.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flood just came,'' said Eddie Eskew, 72, the senior pastor
at Grace Community Church in Del Rio's San Felipe section.
``There's this whole section here with mobile homes. It came right
through there and washed them all out. Three people were killed,
two I knew. There were four people in one mobile home. Two of them
swam away, and two stayed behind and they died. The water took that
mobile home off its foundation and across Amistad Boulevard and
slammed it through a brick wall and into a house.''
</P>
<P>
   Border Patrol officers, national guardsmen, local constables,
paramedics, firefighters, almost everyone in a uniform, worked
throughout the day Monday, rescuing people from roofs, treetops and
water-logged hillocks. The water had scattered cars, masonry,
asphalt and all manner of debris around the scrubby, cactus-filled
flood plain.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush sent 150 guardsmen, 28 trucks and nine
helicopters into the area following pleas from local officials, and
the dull thud of helicopter blades could be heard all afternoon as
the search continued for those still missing.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Del Rio said Monday night that they had six
confirmed deaths, including a Border Patrol trainee who had gone to
search for relatives, but they cautioned that at least 50 people
were still missing and that the death toll was likely to rise.
About 17.5 inches of rain fell on Del Rio between 8 a.m. Sunday and
8 a.m. Monday. The previous record had been 8.8 inches of rain,
which fell on Del Rio on June 13, 1935.
</P>
<P>
   ``Highway 90 East had 5 feet of water ovand-new bridge we
just built,'' Askew said. ``Highway 90 West had 2 feet of water
crossing it out by the Wal-Mart, about a mile and a half from
downtown. It's unreal.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Meanwhile, across the border, at least five teen-agers were
killed while trying to cross the swollen Rio Vacas using a length
of rope as a guide. The youths had worked as grocery baggers at a
local supermarket. Two others were still missing, as was an entire
family from a nearby neighborhood, Mexican officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Mena, a spokesman for the Coahuila provincial government
said that 20 homes had been destroyed in Acuna and dozens more made
uninhabitable by the rising waters, leaving some 2,700 people
homeless. All but 200 of them were living in makeshift shelters in
Acuna, Mena said, while the rest had fled south or moved in with
friends or relatives.
</P>
<P>
   At its height, the flood had left 6 feet of water on downtown
Acuna, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those flooded out of their homes in Del Rio, more than 500
people by late Monday afternoon, were scattered among four
shelters. Red Cross and Salvation Army officials were staffing the
shelters and passing out bottled water to the hundreds of
households left without drinkable water.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that the floods had damaged the city's water
system, allowing sewage to seep into it and making most tap water
unfit to drink.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, four Mexican immigrants, including a 2-year-old and a
4-year-old, were drowned when their pickup truck, carrying 18
people, tried to make its way across a swollen stream in Real
County, northwest of San Antonio in the heart of the Texas Hill
Country. The fast moving waters swept the truck away, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   And a 65-year-old man had a heart attack and died Monday while
being evacuated in Uvalde, Texas, where the Frio River had
overflowed its banks.
</P>
<P>
   In South Texas, virtually every major river had spilled its
banks at least some, including the Llano, the Frio, the Sabinal and
the Nueces. In the hardest hit areas, almost every creekbed, every
depression, every low-lying crossroads was under water on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Weather officials had expected Charley, which hit the Texas
coast on Friday and Saturday and was downgraded from a tropical
storm to a tropical depression, to continue to diminish as it moved
inland and into western Mexico on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The remnants of the system moved into the Del Rio area and
basically became nearly stationery, and it produced the very heavy
rainfall in parts of southern Texas in the past 25 hours,'' said
David Imy, a meteorologist at the Storm Prediction Center in
Norman, Okla. ``The problem when you have a system such as this is
that it picked up moisture over the gulf. These systems will
produce heavy rain wherever they go, but the problem here is that
it sat over basically the same area for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The storm stalled over Uvalde, Kinney and Val Verde counties. At
its height, it dumped 4 inches of water per our on parts of the
region, before moving slowly back to the east.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing kind of hit us by surprise,'' said Ben Patterson, a
spokesman for the Texas Division of Emergency Management. ``The
first call we had was around 12:45 this morning, basically asking
us if we knew about the flood. We didn't, so we opened up the
operations center.''
</P>
<P>
   The water was making its way back to the gulf of Mexico Monday,
a great swell almost a mile in width moving slowly down the Rio
Grande, cresting in Eagle Pass Sunday night and expected to hit
Laredo sometime on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Eagle Pass said they were expecting the water
overnight to move into the downtown area, and hundreds of residents
were evacuated. In Piedras Negras, Mexico, across the Rio Grande,
300 residents were evacuated, and the water was just beginning to
seep into city streets at 7 p.m., Mena said.
</P>
<P>
   While emergency officials in Eagle Pass struggled to evacuate
and hold back the surge, officials in Laredo were meeting into the
evening to assess the threat of the danger approaching them.
</P>
<P>
   Officials were concerned not only about those still missing but
about panicked residents who may try to escape. An automobile can
be swept away by less than 2-feet of moving water, Patterson said,
and many of the low-crossings in rural areas around Del Rio and
Eagle Pass were flooded out.
</P>
<P>
   Further scattered showers and thunderstorms were predicted for
South Texas on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Texas and Oklahoma had been in the grips of the worst drought
the region had seen since the early 1950s, and the rains brought to
the region by Chad been expected to ease some of the
drought's effects. It did, officials said, but at a heavy cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 2.8 inches of rain in Del Rio in the first seven months
of the year,'' Askew said. ``We've been praying for rain, but we
didn't pray for this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
