<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNBEAM-STRATEGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNBEAM OUTLINES NEW PLAN TO SAVE ITSELF
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN.: Fla.)  (jw) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunbeam Corp., the troubled appliance maker, Monday outlined a
strategy for fixing itself, scrapping the plan begun by its former
chairman and chief executive, Albert Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it would decentralize its operations, keep open
some plants scheduled for closing and retain some businesses it had
planned to sell. The company also put in place a new management
team.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions come two months after Jerry Levin, a turnaround
specialist, was brought in to replace Dunlap. The plan calls for
the maker of Oster and Sunbeam blenders, irons and electric
blankets to be organized into a corporate group and three operating
groups: outdoor leisure products, household products and
international. Those units will be run out of 17 regional
headquarters and have separate management teams and research and
development divisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In contrast to the prior management's approach, we are
decentralizing operations while maintaining central support,''
Levin told analysts in a conference call. Dunlap closed regional
offices when he arrived at Sunbeam in July 1996 in favor of running
the business from a central location to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam, based in Delray Beach, Fla., also scaled back a plan
that Dunlap announced in May calling for reducing the company's
work force by 40 percent _ or about 6,400 workers. The company said
three plants scheduled to be closed would be shut, but four others
would remain open. It will also retain two businesses that Dunlap
had put on the block: the Eastpak backpack division and the
Powermate compressor business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we still have much to do in the short term to
stabilize Sunbeam's business,'' Levin said, ``our strategic focus
is on growth.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sunbeam's poor performance lately has caused frustrated
investors to send its stock tumbling from its high of $52, the
initial reaction to Monday's announcements, which came after the
market closed, was favorable. Shares of Sunbeam rose as high as $10
in after-hours trading, up from the close of $8.8125 in the regular
session.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a first step,'' said William Steele, an
analyst who follows the company for Buckingham Research. ``It
establishes where they stand and what they are going to be working
on.'' He said the company still had strong brands, good
distribution and now a capable and focused leadership.
</P>
<P>
   But until management releases more specifics about Sunbeam's
financial position, ``it is very hard to value the company, which I
think is ultimately what we are trying to do here,'' Steele added.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam said it would no longer pay its quarterly dividend of
one cent a share and it put in place a management team that is
heavy on executives who worked with Levin at Coleman Products.
</P>
<P>
   When Dunlap was let go by a board that said it had lost faith in
his leadership, Levin was handpicked to run Sunbeam by Ronald
Perelman, who sold Coleman to Sunbeam in March, making him one of
Sunbeam's largest shareholders. Levin had run Coleman, the camping
products company, and also had led Revlon Inc., which Perelman's
holding company controls.
</P>
<P>
   When he took over, Levin promised that he would quickly work to
stop Sunbeam's hemorrhaging and would put in place the people to
return it to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more than 30 executive changes he announced Monday was
the naming of Paul Shapiro, a former vice president and general
counsel at Coleman, to be executive vice president and chief
administrative officer, stepping into a post Dunlap had been
looking to fill. Also, Bobby Jenkins became executive vice
president and chief financial officer, replacing Russell Kersh, who
was Dunlap's most trusted lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The management group has extensive experience in
consumer-focused businesses, which will be central to Sunbeam's
strategy, particularly as it increases its emphasis on brand
building and marketing,'' Levin said. But the new team and game
plan come as Sunbeam has been losing money, its inventory is
extremely bloated and the validity of its recent financial results
are in question.
</P>
<P>
   The company has turned in a disappointing performance all year,
including posting a $44.6 million loss in the first quarter. It is
also being investigated by the Securities and Exchange Commission
for possible accounting irregularities and says it will have to
restate its financial results for last year and possibly 1996 and
the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Some shareholders have filed lawsuits against the company and
Dunlap, saying they were misled about Sunbeam's financial health,
accusations the company and Dunlap deny.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
