<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9987 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTACK-TALIBAN-ART-30     08-24 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-TALIBAN-ART-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBTS GROW THAT TALIBAN WOULD HAND OVER TERRORIST LEADER TO THE
U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: ATTACK-RDP, ATTACK-SUDAN, ATTACK-PAKISTAN)  
(ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By STEVE LeVINE and RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PESHAWAR, Pakistan _ With Osama bin Laden having apparently
survived the barrage of missiles rained down on his stronghold
across the border in Afghanistan, the United States still has the
problem of how to get its hands on the man it considers the No. 1
terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility that has been floated is for the United States
to negotiate with the Taliban, the Islamic movement that controls
most of Afghanistan, to surrender bin Laden _ perhaps in exchange
for several million dollars in aid or even diplomatic recognition.
</P>
<P>
   But diplomats who have dealt with the Taliban doubt that
anything could come of such negotiations, particularly with the
Taliban's anger over Thursday's attack.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the Taliban have repeatedly failed to keep promises
to U. N. agencies and Western governments _ promises to stop the
opium trade, to form a broad-based government and to ease its
restrictions on women.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats and experts say the Taliban will not relinquish bin
Laden largely because of his relationship to Mohammad Omar, the
``supreme'' leader of the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
   Omar, 39, is rarely heard from or seen in public, keeping
company mostly with a small group of Taliban subordinates. Bin
Laden is one of the few individuals outside this group whom Omar
has permitted to become close to him.
</P>
<P>
   Economically destitute and considered a renegade movement by
much of the world, the Taliban have few sources of income besides
bin Laden. Chief among them has been opium. Western diplomats said
this week that the opium production in areas it controls was
increasing.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days, Omar has demonstrated his loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will never hand Osama over to anyone,'' Omar said last
week. ``We will protect him with our blood at all cost.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Both men were part of the mujahedeen movement, which wa
against the Soviet Union during its military intervention in
Afghanistan from 1979 to 1989. But they did not meet then.
</P>
<P>
   Omar is said to have fought with a moderate faction and emerged
from the war a virtual unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden, who inherited a fortune that his father earned
building roads in Saudi Arabia, commanded a unit of volunteers
under the nom de guerre Abu Abdullah, and he earned a reputation
for being courageous and charismatic. His unit captured the
southeastern Afghan city of Khost. He lost the toes on his left
foot in combat.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after the 1989 Soviet withdrawal, bin Laden, who was
not welcome in his native Saudi Arabia because of his support for
militants, moved to Sudan and lived in a spacious, well-guarded
home on a dusty road in the capital, Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
   It was in Sudan that bin Laden, along with building roads,
reportedly began to finance militant Islamic movements and assaults
against governments he opposed. In 1993, he reportedly sent his
operatives into Somalia to attack the U.S.-led peacekeeping
mission.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from the United States and Saudi Arabia, Sudan
deported him, along with other alleged terrorists, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden returned to Afghanistan, which was racked by civil
war. The mujahedeen leaders ensconced in Kabul, the capital, were
fighting among themselves. And a new group had emerged _ the
Taliban, whose core fighters came out of Saudi-financed religious
schools in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   In two years, the Taliban had risen to capture the entire south
and most of the west of Afghanistan. But the Taliban's military
drive stalled when its financial resources had all but dried up,
</P>
<P>
   Pakistani intelligence officers, who were backinaliban,
introduced the Taliban leaders to a new, wealthy friend _ bin
Laden. He gave $3 million to the movement, said Afghans and
diplomats familiar with the transaction, a sum that could go a long
way in the poor nation.
</P>
<P>
   With the money in hand, the Taliban and their Pakistani allies
began a round of visits to important militia commanders in eastern
Afghanistan. These local leaders were plied with cash, and many
agreed to ally themselves with the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
   In a sweep in September 1996, the Taliban rushed north with
little resistance, capturing Jalalabad. Ten days later, Kabul fell.
</P>
<P>
   Omar's gratitude to bin Laden was quickly apparent. Bin Laden,
his three wives and a 160-member coterie shifted south to Kandahar.
The two men were often seen together, and an enormous house was
built for bin Laden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
