<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME COMPANIES ASK US TO BACK OFF IN TRUST SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many technology firms support the federal government's antitrust
campaign against software giant &UR;  &LR;  Microsoft Corp. and processor
titan Intel Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Many, but not all.
</P>
<P>
   The antitrust efforts have brought dissension within the
computer industry, and led to the creation of new industry groups
that are urging the government to back off.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday in Washington, a new organization called Technology
Access Action Coalition, is joining the fray on the side of Intel
and Microsoft. It plans a press conference to announce its
position. TAAC includes executives from computer retailer CompUSA
Inc. and system integrator Corporate Software &AMP; Technology Inc. of
Norwood, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, over 200 software and hardware firms have joined the
Association for Competitive Technology, a group formed last year to
oppose consumer advocate Ralph Nader's call for antitrust action
against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ACT cofounder Ted Johnson is chief technology officer of Visio
Corp., a Seattle firm that makes technical drawing software.
Johnson is in a delicate position. He's also on the board of the
Software Publishers Association, a major group that has condemned
Microsoft's business practices and supports a federal antitrust
suit against the company. But Johnson vehemently opposes the suit.
``I don't know why we've decided to punish success,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most ACT members are small firms, but the roster includes
Symantec Corp., a leading maker of anti-virus software, as well as
Emerson Electric Co., a manufacturer of electrical components.
Microsoft, a long-time member of SPA, has also joined ACT as well.
</P>
<P>
   SPA president Ken Wasch admitted that disputes over Microsoft
have had a divisive effect inside his organization. ``In any
important public policy issue, you don't have unanimity of
opinion,'' said Wasch. ``Microsoft is SPA's largest member ... We
agree with Microsoft on so many issues. The antitrust case is not
one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ACT's executive director Jonathan Zuck denied that Microsoft
is pulling the strings at his organization. He said that the
software titan joined two months after the group was founded, and
does not have a seat on the ACT board. Zuck also said that he
didn't know how much of the organization's financing comes from
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ACT and TAAC were created in response to aggressive efforts at
the US Justice Department and the Federal Trade Commission to apply
antitrust law to the computer industry. Next month, the Justice
Department and Microsoft will square off in court in a major
antitrust case. The government alleges, among other things, that
Microsoft bundles new features like Internet browsing into its
Windows operating system in order to crush smaller competitors,
such as browser-maker Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The trade commission, meanwhile, is going after Intel &UR;  &LR; for
refusing to share technical specifications of its Pentium
microprocessors with certain companies. The commission argues that
Intel is using its dominance in the microchip industry to freeze
out possible rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FTC case against Intel starts to raise serious issues
about intellectual property rights,'' said ATC's Zuck, who believes
that Intel has a right to deny its product information to whomever
it chooses.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of ACT and TAAC reflects a controversy inside the
computer industry over the value of government intervention.
Computer companies have generally adopted a laissez-faire approach,
urging that government regulation of their activities be kept to a
minimum. But the growing market power of Microsoft and Intel have
led many companies to do an about-face and urge stronger
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, firms like Visio &UR;  &LR; have done well by riding on
Microsoft's coattails, designing their products to work well with
Microsoft operating systems. Such firms are content to co-exist
with their giant neighbor and don't want the government to rock the
boat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 2132EDT &QL; 
