<HEADER>
A0003 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-VINEYARD-BOS &LR;      08-24 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VINEYARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS ENJOY SEPARATE LUNCHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ President Clinton and his wife, cloistered in
their borrowed compound for much of their vacation, ventured out to
separate lunches Monday _ each of them visiting with a group of
friends.
</P>
<P>
   That simple social decision set off yet another raft of
speculation, as reporters and observers immediately pointed at
their separate engagements as a signal of the seriousness of their
latest marital rift. The White House, oddly, did little to defuse
such speculation.
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Mike McCurry said last week that the
couple was spending time alone as part of a healing process in the
wake of Clinton's admission that he carried on an extramarital
affair with Monica Lewinsky, a former intern fresh out of college
at the time of their relationship. Monday, McCurry added, to
laughter in the makeshift briefing room, ``I stand by my prior
assessment. With each day, we are getting more more confident in
that insight.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had lunch Monday with his longtime confidant Vernon
Jordan, dining at Jordan's Chilmark house on a menu that featured
Icelandic salmon, asparagus, potatoes and pie. Hillary Rodham
Clinton boarded a boat in Edgartown Harbor with friend Kelly Day
and a collection of female companions, White House officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton remained silent to reporters coming and going from
lunch. Afterward, he stopped at Alley's General Store in West
Tisbury _ a favorite shopping haunt _ on his way home. He sipped a
cup of coffee and told the establishment's general manager, Jack
MacKay, ``I really like your store.''
</P>
<P>
   Observers described Clinton as looking ``forlorn,'' ``worn,''
and subdued. He talked with an 11-year-old boy in one of the store
aisles, and the boy's mother, Meghan Staffell, was overheard
saying, ``That was a really good speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked later by a reporter which speech she was referring to,
Staffell said, ``The second one,'' meaning his Oval Office address
explaining the missile launch against terrorists in Sudan and
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   As the Clintons dedicated themselves to their personal lives,
White House national security officials are becoming increasingly
confident that last Thursday's strike on a suspected Afghanistan
terrorist camp was successful. Clinton received a telephone
briefing on the damage Monday morning from his ranking security
aide, Samuel (Sandy) Berger.
</P>
<P>
   ``With each passing day we are growing more confident in the
preliminary assessment that we gave as to the damage assessment,''
said McCurry. Last week, Berger said the damage inflicted by US
Tomahawk missiles was ``moderate to heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Clinton still planned to visit Russia next week,
even in light of Russian President Boris Yeltsin dismanting his
government over the weekend. Clinton and Yeltsin will likely talk
about the Russian economy and the future of nuclear weapons
disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a reminder of the volatility that exists in Russian
domestic politics,'' said McCurry. ``We've known for a long time
that President Yeltsin faces a very complicated internal dynamic.
He deals with that. That's really between him and the Russian
people. But the work we do has to be cognizant of the fact that it
is a complicated environment in which President Yeltsin pursues
policies.''
</P>
<P>
   But policy aside, all eyes are on Clinton for a hint of mood and
progress in his personal life. On vacation, the president has yet
to pick up a golf club. In year's past, he has golfed more rather
than less with Jordan, who is now a central grand jury  in
the Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday afternoon, with the Clintons again hunkered down in
their house, the White House announced that they would not be
venturing forth again for the day or night.
</P>
<P>
   Some White House officials continue to search for a venue for
Clinton to appear at a political event off the island and raise his
public profile. Some aides have been bantering about the
possibility of venturing a rally in Boston on Thursday, but no
plans have been set. A few strategists believe it is crucial for
Clinton to make an appearance after what was widely believed to be
a failed speech last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The White House was discussing the possibility of a Boston trip
as early as Tuesday, but the day passed without any action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to intrude on their privacy, but they are
spending time together, doing all the things that I've been telling
you about,'' said McCurry. ``They've been talking, they've been
relaxing, they've been reading, they've been walking, and they've
been dealing with what is a personal private matter.''
</P>
<P>
   At Alley's, Clinton seemed buoyed after he shook hands with
about 40 people in a rope line. He seemed especially happy after
MacKay gave him a canvas bag filled with gifts, including an
oversized dog biscuit. Clinton pulled the treat from the bag and
said, ``You're going to make me a hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Most aides said Clinton would not give another address on his
affair, but would look for another appropriate opportunity to
address it and possibly offer an explicit apology. One idea: a
question at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Washington, White House chief of staff Erskine Bowles
told aides to quit griping about the president's political
fortunes. ``Enough whining. Get back to work,'' he was quoted as
saying in a senior staff meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 2139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980824.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0004 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BONNIE-FLORIDA-COX     08-24 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIE-FLORIDA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For now, Florida seems safe as Bonnie begins to move
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Hurricane Bonnie, running in place since
Saturday like a jogger at a red light, began plodding forward again
Monday, passing by Palm Beach County and the Treasure Coast with
barely a ripple of surf.
</P>
<P>
   The 400-mile-wide storm was headed northwest but forecasters
were uncertain whether it would threaten South Carolina, North
Carolina and Virginia with its 115-mph winds or turn northeast and
churn out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 p.m. Monday, officials issued a hurricane watch from
Savannah, Ga. through the North Carolina-Virginia border, meaning
hurricane conditions are possible by Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's quite a range of forecast tracks. The larger models
are forecasting a turn to the east but the others are pointing to
South and North Carolina,'' said forecaster Andrew Shashy of the
National Hurricane Center in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unusual. We frequently have this problem,'' he said.
How quickly Bonnie turns depends on the strength of a mid-level low
pressure trough over the eastern United States.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 p.m. Monday, Bonnie was located near latitude 26.3 north,
longitude 72.9 west, about 450 miles due east of Palm Beach. It was
moving northwest at 6 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane center still estimated a 2 percent chance the
storm could U-turn and strike Palm Beach County by midday Thursday,
a 3 percent chance for the Treasure Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the mid-Atlantic Ocean, another storm rapidly
intensified from a depression to Tropical Storm Danielle. At 5 p.m.
Monday, the storm, with 40 mph winds, was located near latitude
14.4 north, longitude 38.8 west, about 1,400 miles east of the
Lesser Antilles. It was moving west-northwest at 21 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks pretty impressive on the satellite imagery,'' Shashy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie was expected to remain a Category 3 hurricane through
today, capable of causing severe coastal flooding and serious
damage to homes and other buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane-force winds extended 85 miles from the center and
tropical storm winds reached 230 miles out, mainly to the northeast
and northwest.
</P>
<P>
   A heavydvisory was in effect from the Jupiter Inlet north
to Cape Hatteras, N.C., but Bonnie disappointed any surfers hoping
for a day of big waves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surf is 1 to 2 feet, like (Sunday). It's real quiet. No
riptides,'' said Nate Nevid, a beach patrol lieutenant for Palm
Beach County beaches from Singer Island to Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   Reports were similar from Boca Raton to Fort Pierce. ``With the
storm south of us, the swells run up against the Bahama bank and
are broken up,'' said National Weather Service meteorologist Robert
Molleda.
</P>
<P>
   As Bonnie moves north, ``swells should start working their way
down the coast. It should start sometime (Tuesday), Wednesday for
sure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, 7-foot swells were reported off Cape Canaveral
and surfers were delighted with 6-foot waves in Virginia Beach,
Va., where the East Coast Surfing Championship is scheduled this
weekend. ``Surfers always wish for a hurricane. We love 'em,''
championship director Paul West said.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Virginia and some coastal communities elsewhere
banned swimming because of rip tides, strong currents near the
beaches that were blamed for two drownings over the weekend in
South Carolina and Delaware. Hundreds of bathers had to be rescued
at New Jersey beaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were getting sucked out left and right,'' said Margate
Beach, N.J., lifeguard Mike Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina Gov. David Beasley told 1,000 National Guardsmen
to get ready in case the storm takes aim at that state's coast.
Officials estimated there were 125,000 tourists in the state's
beach towns. Almost a decade ago, South Carolina was battered by
Hurricane Hugo.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County emergency management officials and American
Red Cross volunteers were prepared to head north to help out in
storm-threatened areas, said Manny Papandreas, the county's
emergency operations coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   With the threat of Bonnie past, South Florida water managers
began filling up coastal canals Monday that had been lowered late
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Tim O'Meilia writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. This report was supplemented with information from Post wire
services.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
