<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0008 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANAM-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      08-24 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAM-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLIGHT 103 FAMILIES DISTRESSED BY TRIAL PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w, a, i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ten years after terrorists killed her husband and
269 others in the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103, Eleanor Bright
winced at a compromise the United States and Britain announced
Monday in an attempt to bring the suspects to trial.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, addressing Libyan leader Moammar Khadafy's
request that two Libyans charged in the bombing be tried in a
neutral country, became public just days after the United States
unleashed its military might in retaliation for recent terrorist
bombings in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Under the US-British proposal, the suspects would be tried by a
Scottish court sitting in the Netherlands. The Libyan foreign
minister told the United Nations in January that his government
would accept Scottish judges.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Many relatives of the Pan Am 103 bombing victims want the
suspects tried in the United States or Scotland, where the bombing
occurred. And several wondered aloud Monday how the United States
could appear to compromise with alleged terrorists in Libya less
than a week after US raids on suspected terrorist sites effectively
declared war on terrorism around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very distressing,'' Bright said Monday of the US
attacks last week in Sudan and Afghanistan. ``It made all of us
feel as if our loved ones' lives weren't important enough,'' she
said by telephone from Little Cranberry Island off Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Bright's husband, Nicholas, a manager for Boston-based Bain &AMP;
Co., was among 189 Americans who died in the explosion over
Lockerbie, Scotland, four days before Christmas in 1988. Seventy
other people on board were killed, as were 11 in Lockerbie.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest chapter of the Pan Am 103 explosion _ the most
deadly terrorist attack ever on American civilians _ Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright outlined the compromise plan in a
conference call Monday with Bright and 22 other relatives of the
bombing victims.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, which drew mixed reactions among the
families, United Nations sanctions against Libya will be lifted if
Khadafy accepts the offer from the United States and Britain to
allow the suspects to be tried in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Khadafy has refused since the suspects were indicted in 1991 to
deliver them to the United States or Scotland, insisting they would
not receive a fair trial in either place.
</P>
<P>
   With few other diplomatic alternatives, the Clinton
administration decided ``to call the Libyan government's bluff,''
Albright told reporters after speaking to the family
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate response from Libya.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy, who has urged tougher sanctions on
Libya to try to force Khadafy to turn over the suspects, reserved
judgment on the change in strategy. ``This is a new proposal, which
is in its early stages, and I want to study it carefully,'' he
said. ``If it is truly air-tight and will at long last bring to
justice those responsible for this heinous act, then it should move
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Several relatives of the bombing victims also reserved judgment.
``It's clear to me that if Libya has not cooperated by now, they
never will,'' said Lestra Carpe Benello, of Hanover, N.H., a
retired physician whose 24-year-old son, Julian, died in the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Julian Benello, a graduate of Phillips Exeter Academy and Yale
University, was working toward a doctoral degree at Cambridge
University when he died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm cognizant of why it would be best to have the trial here
or in Scotland,'' his mother said. ``But what we need is a trial,
and I believe nothing further will happen as things stand now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bright, whose son, Nick, was a year old when the bomb exploded,
said she worries about the United States stepping onto a ``slippery
slope'' by appearing to bargain with Khadafy. And she urged the
United States to push for an oil embargo against Libya if he
rejects this offer. The administration said Monday it would seek to
tighten UN sanctions and add unilateral measures if there is a
rejection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 2142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980824.0456 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0012 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANAM-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      08-24 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAM-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLIGHT 103 FAMILIES DISTRESSED BY TRIAL PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w, a, i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
