   Bright, whose son, Nick, was a year old when the bomb exploded,
said she worries about the United States stepping onto a ``slippery
slope'' by appearing to bargain with Khadafy. And she urged the
United States to push for an oil embargo against Libya if he
rejects this offer. The administration said Monday it would seek to
tighten UN sanctions and add unilateral measures if there is a
rejection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
