<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 California Bans New Taxes On Net Business   By Jamie Beckett  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
California yesterday banned new state and local taxes on Internet
access and purchases for three years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's only fitting that the state that showed America how to
surf _ and surf the Internet _ should also lead the policy debate
about how to keep the Internet a vibrant avenue for growth and
opportunity,'' Governor Pete Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson signed the California Internet Tax Freedom Act into law
at a ceremony in San Jose a Systems, a leading networking
company that does a lot of business online.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado passed legislation similar to California's in May. Two
other states, New York and New Jersey, limit taxes on Internet
services and transactions. In those states, the limits came about
through executive orders by state tax officials.
</P>
<P>
   The state law mirrors a federal proposal backed by President
Clinton. Passed by the House of Representatives, it is expected to
go before the Senate in September.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters consider such laws essential to maintaining the
growth of the Internet, which is still a relatively young business.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The California Internet Tax Freedom Act, introduced by
Assemblyman Ted Lempert, D-Palo Alto, bars special taxes on
Internet commerce, treating it the same as mail-order or catalog
sales. Californians pay state sales tax on products bought over the
Internet only if the seller has a store, factory or other
``physical presence'' in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crucial legislation for California because this is home
to the Internet industry, and it's been so important to our
economic growth,'' Lempert said. ``Having a lot of folks trying to
tax the Internet could impede its growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The law, which takes effect January 1, prohibits new taxes on
Internet access and on the telephone lines used to hook up to the
Internet. The bill does not affect any existing tax. Local
governments would still be able to collect utility user taxes on
basic cable television, telephone and cellular phone service, even
if the lines are used for Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   The League of California Cities, city governments and other
opponents had argued against an earlier version of the law that
would have curbed local taxes on cable TV companies and utility
use.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been another step in our dwindling revenue
base,'' said Dwight Stenbakken, legislative director of the League
of California Cities.
</P>
<P>
   Amendments to the bill that won over the League protected local
governments' &UR;  &LR; existing taxing authority and ensured the tax
moratorium would be temporary.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the bill had strong support in Silicon Valley
and throughout the high-technology industry. Netscape, Apple
Computer, Microsoft and Netcom were among a group that lobbied for
the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Th{Qyidea is to have jobs grow in California rather than
burden the industry with regulation and taxes and have them grow
some other place,'' said Teresa Casazza, executive director for
state public policy for the American Electronics Association in
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet and Net commerce is an emerging business that has
resulted in new technology and economic opportunities in every
state,'' said John Hough, a spokesman for Egghead.com in Portland,
Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (the United States) have the chance to be the global leader
in Internet commerce,'' he said. ``It would be best if government
at all levels gives it a chance to develop before imposing
regulations and taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Egghead closed its remaining 80 retail stores in February to
move its business operations to the Web.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
