<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Cisco Using TV Ads to Outdo Lucent in Battle of Network Stars   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Are you ready?
<TEXT>
<P>
   That's what Cisco Systems asks in a new television ad campaign
that debuted last night on local news shows.
</P>
<P>
   The ads put a human face on a company that's a hit on Wall
Street but not exactly a household word. The network equipment
vendor is the latest high-tech firm to use television ads to build
a brand name with consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Created by Goldberg Moser O'Neill of San Francisco, the ads are
designed to let consumers know that Cisco hardware provides the
plumbing for much of the fast-growing Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesperson Doug Wills said Cisco will buy ad time on talk
shows and prime-time television. On the surface, the campaign is
designed to help Cisco launch a new family of consumer products _
high-speed modems and other geek gear _ that it will build and
co-market with manufacturers like Sony and Matsushita.
</P>
<P>
   But Cisco has ambitions that transcend the network niche. A
second, if unspoken, purpose of the campaign is to help Cisco play
catchup in a battle for name recognition with one of its newer
rivals, Lucent Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent, which includes the former Bell Labs, is a top maker of
the hardware used to route telephone traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Once, the phone network and the Internet were separate, but new
technology makes it possible and desirable to route phone and data
traffic over the same equipment.
</P>
<P>
   That means Cisco, the data-networking giant, and Lucent, the
Godzilla of voice, are increasingly bumping heads.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent began its own television-branding campaign last year
after it was spun off from AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lucent's $26 billion in annual revenues dwarfs Cisco's
$9 billion take, Cisco chief executive John Chambers wasn't
overawed by the size of his rival when he briefed reporters in May
about the consumer ad campaign and other topics.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Lucent an ``old economy'' company, Chambers said: ``It
will be interesting to see which cultures win, the old economy or
the new economy cultures'' like Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Size and number of people are not necessarily
strengths.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the TV ad wars, dollars do seem to matter.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it's just a coincidence that Lucent spent $26 million
on its TV image ads, while Cisco is saying privately that's it's
willing to drop up to $30 million for prime-time exposure in North
America alone.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Web-apalooza: &LR;  There's been a whole lot of socializing in the
Web community of late.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday evening, for instance, the inaugural meeting of
San Francisco Women on the Web  &LR; (www.sfwow.org) &LR;  drew a crowd of
several dozen to the Macromedia Building in San Francisco.
Organizers Valerie Hoecke, of the San Francisco Web design firm
Fire Engine Red, and Cyd Harrell, of Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., said
some 300 women have already joined SFWow's mailing list, which
targets women whose jobs revolve around the Web.
</P>
<P>
   And both (or should we say all genders) are invited to the
Transmission Theatre in San Francisco tomorrow night for the
Geekapalooza, a party put on by the Bay Area chapters &UR;  &LR; of the
Association of Internet Professionals.
</P>
<P>
   You still may be able to get $7 advance tickets (check
 &LR; www.geekapalooza.com) &LR; , but if you're too late, what the heck: Dye
your hple and spend $10 to get a ticket at the door.
</P>
<P>
   The 'Palooza will air an eight-minute trailer of ``GirlGeeks?,''
a documentary-in-the-making that its producers _ne Hanna and
Peter Crosby of Sausalito _ hope to get on the air next April in
conjunction with ``Take our Daughters to Work Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, ``GirlGeeks?'' has focused on better-known women like
industry analyst Esther Dyson, Marimba chief executive Kim Polese,
network industry executive Judy Estrin (now of Cisco) and Katrina
(tres decolletage) Garnett of CrossWorlds.
</P>
<P>
   But the producers plan to set up a camera at the 'Palooza to ask
women in the tech field their feelings about working in a
male-dominated arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole purpose of the documentary is to find out how women
view this (geek) label,'' Hanna said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the women already filmed, the attitudes range from
Polese's pride in wearing the label, to Estrin's comment that after
being named ``geek of the week'' in a Silicon Valley publication,
her mother sent her a dictionary entry that identified a geek as
``a carnival performer who rips the heads off chickens.''
</P>
<P>
   Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by
phone (650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail (abate(at
sign)sfgate.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
