<HEADER>
A0034 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOCKERBIE-TRIAL-ART-5     08-24 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKERBIE-TRIAL-ART-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TO ASK WIDER LIBYA BAN IF LOCKERBIE TRIAL IS REFUSED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(lh) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If Libya refuses an offer to try two Libyan
suspects in The Hague, Netherlands, for the 1988 bombing of Pan Am
flight 103, the United States will press the United Nations to
extend sanctions on Libya to include an oil embargo, a senior U.S.
official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook of Britain confirmed in simultaneous announcements
Monday that they were willing for the Libyans to be tried in a
third country, but by Scottish judges under Scottish law. They had
previously insisted that the trial take place in the United Kingdom
or the United States.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials called the offer, which is close to a proposal
made by Libya, ``nonnegotiable'' and said Libya must respond
quickly by handing over the suspects. Otherwise, they said, the
offer will be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate response from the Libyan leader, Moammar
Gadhafi, but the Arab League, seeming to speak for Libya, welcomed
the proposal cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   In Cairo, Egypt, the league secretary general, Esmat
Abdel-Meguid, said Monday: ``Libya and the Arab League are in
agreement in principle, but we need to know the details, in
particular whether there are any conditions. If this proposal
conforms with the Arab and Libyan offer for a Scottish panel of
judges to try them at The Hague in accordance with Scottish law,
this would be the beginning of the solution to the crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan, who was asked by the United
States and Britain to notify Libya of the details of the proposal
and to handle the extradition of the suspects, endorsed the idea.
</P>
<P>
   The plane blew up over Lockerbie, Scotland, in December 1988,
killing 259 people on the aircraft _ including 189 Americans _ and
11 on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We note that Libya has repeatedly stated its readiness to
deliver the suspects for trial by a Scottish court sitting in a
third country,'' Ms. Albright said. ``We now challenge Libya to
turn promises into deeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Albright said the plan ``is not subject to negotiation or
change, nor should it be subject to additional foot dragging or
delay.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Libya fails to hand over the suspects, who have been named as
Abdel Basset Ali Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah, Washington will
seek an expansion of U.N. sanctions to include sales of Libyan oil,
a State Department official added, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But other officials said they considered an international oil
embargo unlikely. They said, though, that a Libyan refusal would at
least make it difficult for the United Nations to ease the
sanctions it imposed in 1992 on Libya for refusing to hand over the
suspects, who are believed to be Libyan intelligence agents.
</P>
<P>
   If the suspects are handed over, both the United States and
Britain will support action in the Security Council to suspend the
international sanctions against Libya, which include a ban on
flights to and from the country. But U.S. unilateral sanctions
against Libya for being what it considers a ``state sponsor of
terrorism'' will continue, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Libya has repeatedly broken the ban on flights, sending token
flights to Mecca in Saudi Arabia for the annual Muslim pilgrimage.
Foreign dignitaries, including President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt
last month and President Idriss Deby of Chad Monday, have started
flying to and from Tripoli, the Libyan capital, instead of
traveling by road.
</P>
<P>
   Libya has not made any recent announcements on the proposal for
a trial in a third country, but the lawyer for the suspects,
Ibrahim Legwell, said last month they would accept a trial in The
Hague ``if the conditions for a fair trial are provided.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Legwell's conditions included an international
panel of judges, which the United States and Britain have rejected.
But the Libyan Foreign Minister Omar Mustafa Muntasser, said
explicitly in a letter to the United Nations in January that the
judges could be Scottish.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, the suspects could have to serve up to 30 years in
a Scottish prison, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright and National Security Adviser Sandy Berger told the
families of those who died in the Pan Am bombing about the decision
in a conference call Monday morning. ``These families don't all
agree on the proper strategy for achieving accountability in this
case,'' Albright said. ``But they all agree that the delays in
bringing the suspects to trial have gone on for far too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Cohen of Cape May Court House, N.J., whose daughter,
Theodora, died in the explosion and crash, said she was very upset
about the outcome. ``Today has been a day which has been, in a
sense, a victory for Gadhafi and the terrorists,'' Mrs. Cohen said
in a telephone interview. ``This sets a bad precedent. If
terrorists out-wait us, do they now have a right to decide where to
be tried? I don't think the administration has really thought
through the long-term implications of this.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials in contact with all the families said a majority
of them favored the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Johnson of Greensburg, Pa., said in an interview Monday
that he, his wife, Carole, and the board members of the group,
Survivors of Pan Am 103, supported the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt this might allow us to get justice and get
off-center,'' he said. ``This still meets with what we can live
with. With everything that's happened, we need to take the
initiative, and this will force Gadhafi to make a decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
