<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0037 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNBEAM-COX     08-24 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNBEAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sunbeam redesigns comeback
 &HT;    By Julie Waresh
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ Sunbeam Corp.'s latest turnaround strategy
calls for abandoning cost-cutting plans former Chairman Al Dunlap
put in place before he was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive Officer Jerry Levin said Monday he will keep
open four of the eight plants Dunlap sought to close, delay the
closing of one and retain two businesses that were slated to be
sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plants are being kept open,'' Levin said, ``to ensure a
high level of quality and customer service, as well as a
consistency of supply.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin, who spoke to Wall Street analysts after the market
claid discussion of Sunbeam's financial performance would
have to wait until the company restates its results by the end of
September.
</P>
<P>
   The troubled appliance maker, whose accounting practices are
under investigation by the Securities and Exchange Commission, has
said it will issue new numbers for 1997, the first quarter of 1998
and possibly all of 1996 as well.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam also faces the difficult task of selling off bloated
inventories. Levin said he expects it will take 18 months to clear
warehouses of excess grills through outlet sales and special
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenges we face in the near term are significant,''
Levin said. ``But they are more than offset by the upside of our
businesses _ the consumer is still buying our products.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have been waiting to hear from Levin since he took the
helm at Sunbeam in June, several days after the board fired Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-July Levin had assembled a new management team made up
primarily of executives who worked for him at Coleman Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certainly much more optimistic now, given the management
team in place, than I have been in the last 12 months,'' said
William Steele, an analyst with New York-based Buckingham Research
Group.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, Steele has no plans to change his neutral outlook
on the stock, which he has rated a ``market performer.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin, who ran Coleman until Sunbeam bought the camping products
maker in March, was brought in by financier Ronald Perelman, who
became Sunbeam's second largest stockholder when he sold the
company his Coleman shares.
</P>
<P>
   The part-time Palm Beach resident will become the appliance
maker's largest investor if he exercises warrants he received this
month to buy 23 million additional shares at $7 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam issued the warrants as part of a settlement to avoid a
lawsuit from Perelman, who has seen the value Sunbeam
investment plummet.
</P>
<P>
   The billionaire investor got a 14 percent stake in Sunbeam in
March, when the stock (NYSE: SOC) was trading above $40 a share. It
closed Monday at $8.81, up 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   To keep employees happy, Levin said the company will allow them
to trade in stock options set at exercise prices higher than $10
share for fewer options at Perelman's price of $7 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Levin said his options are set at exercise prices of $7, $10.50
and $14 a share. In addition, he said Sunbeam will no longer pay
shareholders a quarterly dividend of a penny a share.
</P>
<P>
   Levin attributed much of Sunbeam's problems to poor customer
service and a lack of communication between Sunbeam's sales and
manufacturing divisions, both of which reported directly to Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   ``As things would change with customers, the word literally
never made it to the manufacturing floor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Levin plans to pull back from the centralization
Dunlap had planned and give each of the company's three business
units _ outdoor leisure, household products and international _
more control and accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Levin said the company will keep open plants in Maize, Kan.;
Pocola, Okla.; Aurora, Ill.; and Acuna, Mexico. The closing of a
plant in Mexico City will be delayed three months, until December.
Sunbeam also will retain Coleman's Eastpak outdoor products
division and its Powermate compressor business, which were to be
sold.
</P>
<P>
   Levin eased analysts' concerns about the company's liquidity,
saying Sunbeam has $300 million available in cash and credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no intention of going bankrupt,'' Levin said. ``It's
in nobody's interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Waresh writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
