<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0038 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-BANKWOES-COX     08-24 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-BANKWOES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Banks facing difficult times
 &HT;    By Earl Golz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ After three years of record profits, Texas banks
may be headed for some turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings were still good for the state's 855 banks in the first
quarter 1998, according to the latest figures from Austin-based
bank research company Sheshunoff Information Services Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But banks' net interest margins _ the difference between what
banks charge for loans and what they pay for deposits _ took a
nosedive during the quarter, according to Sheshunoff.
</P>
<P>
   Banks typically derive most of their profits from two sources,
fee income and interest income. The declining interest income could
be a harbinger for lower profits, said Bob Colvin, Sheshunoff's
managing director of community banking.
</P>
<P>
   ``This indication of weakness may point to more difficult times
ahead,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The net interest margin at Texas banks dropped 40 basis points,
from 4.43 percent to 4.03 percent, in the first quarter from the
fourth quarter 1997, according to Sheshunoff.
</P>
<P>
   The margin is the lowest in the last five years, Colvin said. It
continues a steady quarterly decline since the second quarter of
1997, when Texas banks reported their third straight record
earnings at $2.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The net interest margin has declined since,'' Colvin said.
``While it was steady most of last year in the 4.40 percent to 4.50
percent range, it looks as if we have moved to another range.
</P>
<P>
   The 40 basis point decline was even greater than the decline of
33 basis points for all banks in the nation in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in interest spreads is indicative of banks'
increasing reliance on fees for everything from checking accounts
to use of tellers.
</P>
<P>
   But with more competition, some doubt whether banks can continue
to raise fees to offset the declines in interest income.
</P>
<P>
   ``With more competition, and shrinking margins, can these fees
continue to rise at a pace to offset any future declines in the net
interest margin?'' Colvin asked. ``Only time will tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Banking Commissioner Catherine Ghiglieri agreed that banks
are ``under a lot of pressure to reduce fees.''
</P>
<P>
   Bankers also have a ``sense of urgency trying to book loans and
they are squeezing their margins down to almost nothing,''
Ghiglieri said. ``They are not leaving any room for any costs they
may incur in the future in terms of collection or any kind of cost
of care. So it is a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   As mergers and acquisitions give larger banks in Texas a larger
share of the market, pricing policies will have a depressing effect
on the rest of on the rest of the banking industry, said Steve
Scurlock, senior vice president of the Independent Bankers
Association of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been hearing from our community banks that some of the
larger banks are doing some fairly aggressive pricing on some
lending,'' Scurlock said. ``I guess they feel like they can make up
for a loss in spread, or net interest margin, by volume.''
</P>
<P>
   Rates on loans and long term investments rates have inched
downward as deposit rates stayed steady, said Hartland Bank
Chairman David Hartman, partly the result of heightened competition
between banks. ``It's basically the state of the monetary market
and increased competition,'' said Hartman. ``Banking is always most
profitable when there is a steep yield curve, and short term rates
are low and long term rates are high.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving into the exact opposite situation right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Earl Golz writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 2200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980824.0476 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0039 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UT-LAWSCHOOL-DATA-COX     08-24 1591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UT-LAWSCHOOL-DATA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT Law School's challenge: an open door to power
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For a fifth of its 115-year history, the
University of Texas School of Law has been able to call a former
student by the title governor.
</P>
<P>
   The school could have claimed a sixth Texas governor, but it
rejected George W. Bush about 30 years ago because it contended his
grades from Yale weren't good enough. Today, Bush works with 16 UT
law graduates in the Legislature. Another five sit in Congress.
Eighty-three call courts to order. And plenty of others practice at
prominent firms.
</P>
<P>
   UT ranks 10th nationally in producing managing partners, or
heads, of major law firms. It's in the top 20 schools turning out
graduates hired by the nation's 100 largest firms. Two recent
graduates clerk for U.S. Supreme Court justices, a career door
opener like no other.
</P>
<P>
   While the legal profession is often a gateway to power in
society, a pedigree from a premier law school such as UT helps turn
the key.
</P>
<P>
   But black and Hispanic access to the Law School _ along with its
innate connection to power _ is eroding at a time when the Hispanic
population is swelling and the Anglo population is expected to fall
below 50 percent in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Despite monumental recruiting efforts, some Texas law school
deans are bracing for a second fall of enrolling fewer blacks and
Hispanics than their schools had in 1996 because of a federal court
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   UT opens Wednesday for a second year of grappling with the
Hopwood ruling, which stopped Texas colleges from considering race
when selecting students, awarding scholarships and providing other
services. The ruling has been hailed by some as a victory over
reverse discrimination and decried by others as a tragic return to
segregation.
</P>
<P>
   Hopwood has cast a lingering spotlight on the UT Law School, not
only because the lawsuit originated there, but because of the
school's standing in Texas. No other state law school has as many
graduates in the courts, Congress or state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   But only in the past 30 years have the gates to the state's
biggest and highest-ranked law school truly opened to blacks and
Hispanics. It took a court order in 1950 for the UT Law School to
admit its first black. Several decades later, it became known for
graduating more blacks and Hispanics combined than any law school
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Today, seven of the 16 UT law graduates in the Legislature are
black or Hispanic. Many other minority graduates are judges,
community leaders, mayors and council members.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Pen(tilde)a, a UT law graduate and president of the
State Bar of Texas, says that because the face of Texas is
changing, the Law School should reflect that diver
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, ``you're going to have a situation where over 50
percent of the population in Texas is minority and 10 percent of
the attorney population is minority,'' he said. ``You're talking
about a societal problem everyone has an interest in.''
</P>
<P>
   UT Law School Dean Mike Sharlot said people lose faith in public
institutions when they don't see people like themselves in power.
The justice system is especially vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no other country in the world that has turned a
greater variety of disputes over to the justice system to
resolve,'' Sharlot said. ``Our justice system depends ultimately on
most people in society accepting its decisions as legitimate.'' The
UT Law School has played a key role in shaping the Texas justice
system.
</P>
<P>
   From 1940 until 1988, all seven chief state justices were UT
graduates, according to Michael Widener, the school's archivist and
rare books librarian.
</P>
<P>
   On the Law School's 100th anniversary in 1983, the
American-Statesman reported that nearly half of the state's sitting
appellate judges were UT law graduates. Alumni that year also
included the chief justice of the Texas Supreme Court, four
associate justices, a third of the state's senators, the attorney
general and the secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   When Hopwood was argued in federal district court in Austin, UT
law graduates were intimately involved, from the presiding judge,
Sam Sparks, to lawyers on both sides. They included Vinson &AMP;
Elkins' managing partner Harry Reasoner, who defended UT, and
Steven Smith, who filed the lawsuit on behalf of four white
applicants who claimed reverse discrimination when denied admission
to UT in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The four applicants won, and Hopwood is being appealed for a
second time to the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New
Orleans, where seven of the 21 judges are UT law graduates.
</P>
<P>
   UT, like flagship law schools in some other states, has a
national reputation for grooming leaders, said Jim Vaseleck,
associate counsel to the Law School Admission Council, which
administers the Law School Admission Test and provides other
services. ``I've heard the road to the Statehouse goes right
through the UT Law School,'' Vaseleck said.
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Canales has worn a path between the Statehouse and UT
since 1992, first at the LBJ School of Public Affairs and then as a
law student. He started as a volunteer for state Rep. Irma Rangel,
D-Kingsville, chairwoman of the House Higher Education Committee,
in 1989. By 1995, he was her paid chief of staff. He left that fall
to enroll in law school and graduated last May.
</P>
<P>
   The competition to get in was fierce, Canales said, not just
because of the school's prestige but because of its low tuition.
</P>
<P>
   With 475 students entering last fall and about the same this
fall, more than six applicants are turned away for every one who
wins a place.
</P>
<P>
   While Canales, 29, awaits his bar exam results, he is monitoring
hearings at the Capitol, educating himself on an array of issues.
His goal is to be elected to the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Canales, a former migrant farm worker who headed the
Chicano/Hispanic Law Students Association at UT, is considering
lobbying or consulting work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have this legislative bug in me I can't get rid of,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Rodney Ellis, a Houston Democrat and an African
American, also went to the LBJ School and then to the UT Law
School. Harvard had been his top choice, but he thought his law
exam score wasn't high enough, so he didn't apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look back on it, I am much better off having gone to
the University of Texas rather than Harvard,'' Ellis, 44, said.
``I've lived my life in Texas, and the contacts I made . . . have
been invaluable.'' He mentioned Dallas Mayor Ron Kirk and several
other high-powered lawyers as examples from his 1979 graduating
class. As an investment banker, Ellis sometimes finds himself
working on deals with fellow alumni.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being at the premier law school in the state opened doors for
me in ways I never could have predicted,'' he said. ``It was like
being part of a fraternity.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Henry Cuellar of Laredo, also a UT law graduate,
wants to see the Law School return to the days of high minority
enrollments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legislature is going to encourage the UT Law School and
the other professional schools to do as much as they can to
diversify,'' he said. ``If they don't move fast enhere will
be moves by the Legislature to take appropriate actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Texas Tech Law Dean W. Frank Newton is helping Rangel
craft proposals for lawmakers to consider when they convene in
January. One is designed to stem what Newton called a ``brain
drain'' of talent to other states. It would create a scholarship
fund so that Texas can counter offers from out-of-state law
schools.
</P>
<P>
   There are no data on how many students leave Texas for law
school elsewhere and what happens to them, but the vast majority of
lawyers educated in Texas stay. Last year, 87 percent were working
in the state, the highest percentage in the nation, according to
the National Association for Law Placement.
</P>
<P>
   Another legislative proposal, Newton said, would give law school
applicants with subpar LSAT scores a chance to enroll if they
perform well during a summer program.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. David Sibley, a leading Republican from Waco who has
sponsored legislation to end racial considerations in education,
government contracting and employment,says that while he supports
diversity he does not want the courts to overturn Hopwood. ``I just
don't believe in curing racial discrimination with racial
discrimination,'' said Sibley, who has a Baylor law degree.
</P>
<P>
   UT law professor Lino Graglia, who triggered a furor last year
when he made remarks about the cultures and academic performance of
blacks and Hispanics, agrees. ``Knowing everyone got in the same
way is better than having 40 that might not have gotten in like
everybody else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Minorities with lower scores and grades are better off going to
less competitive schools where they can succeed, Graglia said. He
acknowledged that most beneficiaries of affirmative action at UT
graduated and eventually passed the bar. But using race casts
suspicions on all minorities, and that is devastating to race
relations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Newton said it will be far more devastating if Texas fails to
significantly boost minority access to the legal pon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a creeping crisis, and creeping crises are hard to get
people's attention,'' he said. ``But the longer you let it go, the
harder it is to fix.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Roser writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
