<HEADER>
A0043 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-JOBS-COX     08-24 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-JOBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas techies outnumber oilers
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's official: nerds and geeks outnumber
wildcatters and roughnecks in the Lone Star state.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the presence of two of the world's biggest personal
computer makers _ Compaq in Houston and Dell in Round Rock _
oil-and-gas still packs a bigger economic punch than high-tech. In
a study released Monday, the state Comptrollers office said the
number of high-tech jobs in Texas surpassed those in the
oil-and-gas industry for the first time in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That trend is sure to continue, said Comptroller John Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``High technology has emerged as one of the main engines of
economic growth in the state,'' said Comptroller John Sharp.
``There are strong signals that our high-tech industry will become
even more dominant in the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, oil-and-gas accounted for 11 percent of the state's
economic output, while high-tech accounted for 8 percent, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of jobs, however, high tech will continue to grow
beyond oil-and-gas. The report says jobs in the five core high-tech
businesses will pass 500,000 this year year, compared to 453,599 in
oil-and-gas.
</P>
<P>
   The core businesses are: semiconductors and computers;
communications, biotechnology, defense and electrical and
electronics equipment. Sharp released the study at a press
conference at the University of Texas at Dallas. The data also are
published in the comptroller's latest Fiscal Notes newsletter. It
is available online at
http://www.window.texas.gov/comptrol/fnotes/fnhome.html.
</P>
<P>
   When two related employment areas _ technical services and
``technology-intensive manufacturing'' _ are added, then Texas
high-tech employment swells to 781,000, or about 10 percent of the
state's work force.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech workers are far better paid than the typical Texas
worker, with an average annual salary of $48,000 compared with
$28,000 for all workers, but the benefits of the high-tech
explosion in the state are, for the most part, limited to the
state's largest metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of them are in Dallas-Fort Worth and Houston,
while another 16 percent are in Austin and San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Texas Triangle of Dallas-Forth Worth, Houston, Austin and
San Antonio are the primary beneficiaries'' of high-tech growth,
said Bernard Weinstein, director of the Center for Economic
Development at the University of North Texas. ``It's not getting
spread out to the hinterlands of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein noted that three areas tied to petroleum and
petrochemicals, Beaumont, Odessa-Midland and Galveston-Texas City,
have high jobless rates of 7.7, 5.8 and 7.1 percent respectively.
By comparison, two high-tech centers, Dallas and Austin, have
jobless rates of 3.5 and 2.9 percent. High-tech has been gaining on
the oil-and-gas industry in Texas for some time. But the
comptroller's study said that the high-tech core industries gained
more than 51,000 jobs between 1994 and 1996 to top the 454,000 jobs
statewide and surpassed Texas' oil-and-gas employment for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   If Texas can keep training workers, high-tech jobs should keep
growing in the state, Sharp said. His office projects Texas will
add 51,000 high-tech industrial jobs in the next four years. Sharp
warned that the state must continue to train more workers for
high-technology jobs or risk having its job growth slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the computer power in Texas cannot match the brain power
of our young people,'' Sharp said. ``We have to do all we can to
create a technically skilled workforce to meet industry's demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Ladendorf writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
