<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0050 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SURFER-FASHION-ART-70     08-24 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURFER-FASHION-ART-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURF'S UP (SO IS BUSINESS) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By AMY M. SPINDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COSTA MESA, Calif. _ Basically, the deal to bring Australia's
Quiksilver professional surfer board shorts to the United States
and to start a U.S. company was sealed in 1976 when a champion
surfer exhibited his passion for them at a dinner with their
inventor by grabbing a doily and eating it. And another surfer,
today a key executive in Quiksilver, now the biggest surf-wear
company in the country, got his first job there after he exhibited
his passion for the board shorts by breaking into a warehouse and
stealing a stack of them.
</P>
<P>
   So if it's 10 a.m. on the coast, and the waves are perfect and
there are babes at the beach and the breeze is like a bath, it
would be hard to take Quiksilver seriously if its surfer-executives
were at their desks. Even if it is a nearly $250 million public
company, opening its first New York store the following day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the waves are good because the guys are all gone,''
sighed Amy Patrick, who handles press relations for Quiksilver,
when there are company types around for the press to have relations
with. ``The girls finally had to learn how to surf.''
</P>
<P>
   Surfing is the company's business, so there's nothing really to
apologize for. Which is why Danny Kwock, the executive vice
president in charge of Quiksilver's new lines, didn't, after
ignoring his office pager all morning last Tuesday while he was in
the water. ``If I do that, and some CEO of the board is scolding
me, we're in trouble,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quiksilver opened its New York store last Wednesday in the midst
of one of the waves of mass popularity surfing seems to have every
decade or so, this time swelling among the fashionable. It isn't
just that the company's board shorts _ which are designed to fit,
stay on and be comfortable during grueling surfing events _ haveed designers like Anna Sui. James Danzinger recently
exhibited Don James' classic surfing photographs; Bruce Weber
bought some. Professional surfers are regularly showing up in
fashion shoots. The former Beach Boy Brian Wilson is releasing a
new album, and VH1 is broadcasting documentaries about the Beach
Boys, and about Jan and Dean. NBC is producing a new surfing
television show.
</P>
<P>
   And quietly learning to surf is the new chic activity for
trendsetters like Dewey Nicks, the fashion photographer, and Tom
Sachs, the cool conceptual artist. All of which means absolutely
nothing to teen-age girls who have made Quiksilver's Roxy one of
the most successful teen clothing lines on the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important piece of Quiksilver's business from a
growth standpoint is they seem to have cornered the women's surf
market,'' said James Palczynski, a vice president of research who
specializes in the youth market at Ladenburg Thalmann, a New York
investment bank. ``Roxy is really on fire right now. They were the
first to market a women's surf line, and women's surf could be as
large a category as young men's.''
</P>
<P>
   With 11 stores now in the United States, 17 in Mexico and 27 in
Europe, Quiksilver could be positioned as a sort of blond Benetton
with a tan and a better body. But while most big-name designers and
mass-market stores have invented lifestyle myths with slick
marketing, there is a real lifestyle beneath the Quiksilver logo:
the surfer life. The company has walked the line between being a
company with gear for Kelly Slater, the five-time surfing world
champion and Pamela Anderson's current boyfriend, and being a
company with gear for guys who will only get as close to Pamela
Anderson as the poster in their gym locker.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have not only the brand, but a history in involvement in
the sport which gives it real legitimacy,'' Palczynski said. ``And
what we know about teen-agers is they're interested in legitimacy.
They're very media savvy.'' And Quiksilver has been savvy at using
that media. So much so that it's difficult to tell which came
first, the women's surf movement or Roxy. Certainly whatever
fledgling feminist surf scene was growing was aided by the images
Roxy has used for seven years to promote its women's clothes: tan,
confident, leggy surfer girls like the Beach Boys might have sung
about.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   The real lives of surf team members sponsored by Quiksilver and
Roxy are so cool that they might have been invented by MTV, a hip
real world instead of a faked real world. During high surf-contest
season, Roxy's surfers share a house in Newport Beach, Calif., that
Quiksilver pays for, with as many of the nearly 100 male surfers as
the house can accommodate. That is, when the surfers aren't
competing in Australia, Japan, Indonesia, South Africa, Brazil,
Peru, Uruguay, Tahiti, Portugal, Spain or Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Lissa Zwahlen, who designs the Roxy collection, has only to go
to the warehouse attached to the company offices, where there is a
half-pipe for skating, Ping-Pong tables, and a putting green, to
get a look at the surfer team kids, who treat the place as their
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   And there are plenty of former surfers on staff. Eric Diamond,
who designs the company's high-tech board shorts, was sponsored by
Quiksilver when he was 13. He was raised on the Hawaiian island of
Maui by surfer parents, and had a cameo as a toddler in the Jimi
Hendrix movie ``Rainbow Bridge.'' All of which has helped keep him
close to the pro surfers. ``It's like designing a racing car and
drivers are telling you how it's running,'' he said. ``Like they'll
say some fabric gave them a rash.''
</P>
<P>
   And Kwock was the best surfer in the neighborhood when he stole
those Quiksilver board shorts in 1976, at 15. ``We were poor kids
from the 'hood, and couldn't afford them,'' he said. ``It was
status.'' Instead of punishing him, Jeff Hakman, the surfer so
passionate about getting the rights to sell Quiksilvers in America
that he ate a doily, and Robert McKnight, who is now the chairman
of the company, hired him as their first team rider. ``They were
stoked,'' Kwock said. ``They needed a surfer to sponsor. I thought
I was going to jail, but they put me to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Hakman had borrowed his first pair of Quiksilvers from a fellow
surfer in 1975 and never gave them back. His doily-eating dinner
with the board shorts' Australian inventor, Alan Green, ended with
him getting the rights to license the name and product in America.
</P>
<P>
   By supporting surfers (like the four-time women's world champion
Lisa Anderson, who gets a six-figure salary), sponsoring contests
and dressing up-and-coming athletes, Quiksilver is gambling that
its core constituency won't mind so much when a guy with a beer gut
who lives 500 miles from the nearest whitecap brands himself a
Quiksilver man.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a diminished credibility factor in every stage of the
way,'' Kwock said. ``From the moment you start to print 10 pairs of
shorts you lose cool people. It's part of the game you play. The
ultra-creative people who discover people, that's their job. They
discover. The very coolest ones, at the very bottom, are gone
already.'' It's a balance as tricky as, well, surfing.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Quiksilver, we were paranoid from day one that we never
lose our roots,'' said Randy Hild, the head of the Roxy division,
who was there on Tuesday morning, but planning to surf at lunch.
``The day we have a surf shop drop our line because we've sold out
is the day we've lost our soul. Not that we spend frivolously, but
we don't hesitate with promotion ideas from surf shops. Then we're
quietly building the other world.'' The other world, of course, is
their shops and department stores.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, Kwock said, is for Quiksilver to do for surfing what
Ralph Lauren did for polo. ``He took polo as a vehicle and turned
it into an East Coast lifestyle,'' he added. ``Our quest is whether
surfing can be that West Coast lifestyle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
