<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INVESTORS MIXED ON MOVES BY RUSSIAN GOVERNMENT
</P>
<P>
   Investors around the globe took a cautiously optimistic view of
the latest moves by Russia to reverse its recent economic slide. On
Wall Street, stocks ended mixed, with the Dow Jones industrial
average rising 32.96 points, to 8,566.61. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index added 6.96 points, to 1,088.14, while the Nasdaq
composite index fell 6.79 points, to 1,790.82.
</P>
<P>
   Markets around the world were mixed. Russia's benchmark equity
index rose 5.67 percent. In Japan, the benchmark Nikkei index of
225 issues fell 2.03 percent. Hong Kong's Hang Seng index increased
4.2 percent. Markets in Brazil and Chile fell more than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Top Yeltsin officials promised to share power with the
Communist-dominated Parliament that has sought to frustrate the
nation's economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   German banks, the biggest lenders to Russia, with about $30
billion in outstanding loans, are carefully watching the crisis in
Russia. The German Government has guaranteed repayment of most of
that money, and stands to lose billions if the loans go sour.
</P>
<P>
   MERRILL LYNCH SETTLES WITH SEC
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch has agreed to pay $2 million to settle Securities
and Exchange Commission charges that it failed to tell buyers of
Orange County, Calif., bonds important information it knew about
the county's precarious financial condition.
</P>
<P>
   HICKS, MUSE IN $250 MILLION DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, Muse, Tate &AMP; Furst is acquiring a 62 percent stake in
Coho Energy, an oil exploration and production company with
properties mostly in Mississippi and Oklahoma, for $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMERS MAY BE CLOSING WALLETS
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are starting to slow their spending at retailers and
auto dealers, according to a survey by a a brokerage firm
specializing in economic research. Gretchen Morgenson: Market
Place.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHROP TO REDUCE WORK FORCE
</P>
<P>
   Northrop Grumman is cutting its work force by 15 percent by the
end of 2000. Most of the job cuts will be in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   WENDY'S RENEWS COKE CONTRACT
</P>
<P>
   Wendy's International has renewed its soft-drink contract with
Coca-Cola for 10 years, forcing franchises that served Pepsico's
drinks to switch.
</P>
<P>
   A NEW DRUG FOR CROHN'S DISEASE
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration approved the first drug
specifically for Crohn's disease, an often debilitating bowel
ailment. The drug, infliximab, will be marketed under the brand
name Remicade by its maker, Centocor of Malverne, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   HYUNDAI AND UNION SETTLE STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   Workers for Hyundai Motor played soccer while waiting for the
settlement that was reached yesterday, ending a strike that
crippled South Korea's largest auto maker. Hyundai and the union
have agreed to cut 277 jobs, only one-sixth the number sought by
management. The outcome illustrated how hard it was for South
Korean companies to dismiss workers.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE DISMISSES PART OF LAWSUIT
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge has thrown out portions of a lawsuit accusing
the clothing manufacturer Liz Claiborne of improperly conspiring
with union leaders to betray the interests of workers at a Brooklyn
sweater factory. But the judge refused to dismiss two of the
workers' complaints against the union.
</P>
<P>
   SPANISH HOTELS TO STAY COMPETITIVE
</P>
<P>
   Family-run Spanish hotel companies are selling stakes in their
properties to gain capital and stay competitive.
</P>
<P>
   30-YEAR BOND YIELD RISES TO 5.46 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond jumped to 5.46 percent,
from 5.43 percent on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
