<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-FLOODING-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS FLOODING LEAVES 16 DEAD, AND MORE THAN 60 MISSING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Adds further details and corrects spelling of ``Eskew.'')  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lh) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The sputtering remains of Tropical Storm Charley
pushed 200 miles up the Rio Grande Valley from the Gulf of Mexico
before stalling early Monday and dumping more than a foot of rain
on South Texas and northern Mexico, turning drought-baked arroyos
into gushing drain spouts and leaving at least 16 people dead and
more than 60 missing.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest loss of life and the fiercest flooding came about
145 miles west of San Antonio, in the remote desert town of Del Rio
and just across the border in Acuna, Mexico. The rains began early
Sunday, and the flooding started shortly after midnight, at one
point sending a 5-foot wave down the San Felipe Creek that washed
away some 50 homes, residents said.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller creeks and arroyos on the north side of town also
flooded. By 4 a.m., two-thirds of Del Rio was under water.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Garcia, a spokesman for the Del Rio police department,
said the wall of water that rushed down the normally docile creek
was caused by a buildup of branches and debris further upstream
that created a dam that finally burst.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flood just came,'' said the Rev. Eddie Eskew, 72, the
senior pastor at Grace Community Church in Del Rio's San Felipe
neighborhood. ``There's this whole section here with mobile homes.
It came right through there and washed them all out. Three people
were killed, two I knew. There were four people in one mobile home.
Two of them swam away, and two stayed behind and they died. The
water took that mobile home off its foundation and across Amistad
Boulevard and slammed it through a brick wall and into a house.''
</P>
<P>
   Border Patrol officers, national guardsmen, local constables,
paramedics, firefighters and almost everyone in a uniform, worked
throughout the day rescuing people from roofs, treetops and
water-logged hillocks. The water scattered cars, masonry, asphalt
and other debris around the scrubby, cactus-filled flood plain.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush sent 150 guardsmen, 28 trucks and nine
helicopters into the area following pleas from local officials.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Del Rio said Monday night that they had six
confirmed deaths, including a Border Patrol trainee who had gone to
search for relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The dead officer, David Pyatte, had been with the Border Patrol
for less than a year, said Patty Mancha, a spokeswoman for the
patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Officials cautioned that in addition to the dead, at least 50
people were missing and that the death toll was likely to rise.
</P>
<P>
   About 17.5 inches of rain fell on Del Rio between 8 a.m. Sunday
and 8 a.m. Monday. The previous record had been 8.8 inches of rain,
which fell on Del Rio on June 13, 1935.
</P>
<P>
   ``Highway 90 East had 5 feet of water over a brand-new bridge we
just built,'' Eskew said. ``Highway 90 West had 2 feet of water
crossing it out by the Wal-Mart, about a mile and a half from
downtown. It's unreal.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
