</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980824.0490 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0062 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-FLOODING-ART-1S     08-24 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-FLOODING-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SAN ANTONIO: It's unreal.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Meanwhile, across the border, at least five teen-agers were
killed while trying to cross the swollen Rio Vacas using a length
of rope as a guide. The youths had worked as grocery baggers at a
local supermarket. Two others were still missing, as was an entire
family from a nearby neighborhood, Mexican officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Mena, a spokesman for the Coahuila provincial government,
said that 20 homes had been destroyed in Acuna and that dozens more
made uninhabitable by the rising waters, leaving some 2,700 people
homeless. All but 200 of them were living in makeshift shelters in
Acuna, Mena said, while the rest had fled south or moved in with
friends or relatives.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the flood, downtown Ciudad Acuna was under 6
feet of water, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The more than 500 people flooded out of their homes in Del Rio
were scattered among four shelters. Red Cross and Salvation Army
officials were staffing the shelters and passing out bottled water
to the hundreds of households left without drinkable water.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that the floods had damaged the city's water
system, allowing sewage to seep into it and making most tap water
unfit to drink.
</P>
<P>
   The water level of the nearby Amistad Reservoir, which had
fallen 15 feet in recent years, surged 35 feet in one day.
</P>
<P>
   The storm knocked out power to about 5,000 of Del Rio's 34,000
residents. Almost all of the southern half of the city had received
some flooding, and there were pockets of flooding in the northern
half of town, as well.
</P>
<P>
   At nearby Laughlin Air Force Base, two of the three runways were
under water, and the third was being reserved for emergency
flights.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, four Mexican immigrants, including a 2-year-old and a
4-year-old, were drowned when their pickup truck, carrying 18
people, tried to make its way across a swollen stream in Real
County, northwest of San Antonio in the heart of the Texas Hill
Country. The fast-moving waters just swept the truck away,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   And a 65-year-old man had a heart attack and died Monday while
being evacuated in Uvalde County, where the Frio River had
overflowed its banks.
</P>
<P>
   In South Texas, virtually every major river spilled over its
banks Monday, including the Llano, the Frio, the Sabinal and the
Nueces. In the hardest-hit areas, almost every depression and
low-lying crossroads was under water.
</P>
<P>
   Weather officials had expected Charley, which hit the Texas
coast on Friday and Saturday and was downgraded from a tropical
storm to a tropical depression, to continue to diminish as it moved
inland and into western Mexico on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The remnants of the system moved into the Del Rio area and
basically became nearly stationery and it produced the very heavy
rainfall in parts of southern Texas in the past 25 hours,'' said
David Imy, a meteorologist at the Storm Prediction Center in
Norman, Okla. ``The problem when you have a system such as this is
that it picked up moisture over the Gulf. These systems will
produce heavy rain wherever they go, but the problem here is that
it sat over basically the same area for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The storm stalled over Uvalde, Kinney and Val Verde counties and
at its height dumped four inches of water per hour on parts of the
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing kind of hit us by surprise,'' said Ben Patterson, a
spokesman for the Texas Division of Emergency Management. ``The
first call we had was around 12:45 this morning, basically asking
us if we knew about the flood. We didn't, so we opened up the
operations center.''
</P>
<P>
   The water was making its way back to the Gulf of Mexico Monday,
a great swell almost a mile in width that was moving slowly down
the Rio Grande, cresting in Eagle Pass Monday night and heading for
Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Eagle Pass, expecting the water to move into the
downtown area overnight, evacuated hundreds of residents. In
Piedras Negras, the Mexican city across the Rio Grande, 300
residents were evacuated and the water was just beginning to seep
into city streets at 7 p.m., Mena said.
</P>
<P>
   While emergency officials in Eagle Pass struggled to evacuate,
officials in Laredo were meeting into the evening to assess the
threat approaching them.
</P>
<P>
   Further scattered showers and thunderstorms were predicted for
South Texas on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Texas and Oklahoma had been in the grips of the worst drought
the region had seen since at least the early 1950s, and the rains
brought by Charley had been expected to ease some of the drought's
effects. It did, officials said, but at a heavy cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 2.8 inches of rain in Del Rio in the first seven months
of the year,'' Eskew said. ``We've been praying for rain, but we
didn't pray for this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
