NYT-08-24-98 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980824.0491 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0063 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-BUSH-COX     08-24 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-BUSH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush trip stirs speculation on his candidacy
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As he campaigns for re-election, Gov. George W.
Bush has steered wide of overtly presidential states like Iowa and
New Hampshire. But when he visits South Carolina today , Bush will
invite a new wave of speculation about his political aspirations in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will not ask anyone to vote for him at stops in Columbia
and Greer. Events in both cities are fund-raisers for his buddy
David Beasley, a Republican seeking re-election as governor of
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   But South Carolina GOP Chairman Henry says South Carolina is the
perfect place for Bush to kick off a presidential campaign.
McMaster argues that the state has provided key wins for other
Republicans in recent years. Most recently, Bob Dole grabbed the
lead and kept it by winning the state's primary in early March
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan and the other George Bush, the governor's father,
also collected key wins in South Carolina, a state the GOP claims
stages ``the decisive must-win presidential primary.''
</P>
<P>
   McMaster said Governor Bush could take a big step toward the
2000 nomination by skipping Iowa, New Hampshire and other
lesser-known early battlegrounds and heading straight to South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is superlative in every category,'' McMaster said
in going as far as he could without violating his chairmanly role
of neutrality. ``I think he would make an excellent president.
There are many people here in South Carolina that are hoping he
will run. I certainly do hope he will run.''
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina, said McMaster, would be a great place to start
that race.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I would do. Iowa and New Hampshire do not
represent the conservative thought as clearly and consistently as
South Carolina does,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush placed second in a straw poll in May at South Carolina's
GOP state convention.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, McMaster said the straw poll, won by Missouri Sen.
John Ashcroft, was far from indicative of how South Carolina
Republicans feel about the emerging presidential field.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft's backers worked hard to make a strong, early showing
for their man. Bush was absent, physically and politically.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were to vote today, Governor Bush would either win or .
. . be at the top somewhere,'' McMaster said.
</P>
<P>
   Today's campaign stops _ though not for himself _ will further
cement Bush as a favorite in South Carolina, McMaster added.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will engender a lot of good will,'' he said. ``And unlike
some of the other potential candidates for president, Governor Bush
is already well-known here. This will make him better known.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of preseason presidential talk that Bush has come
to hate. And, this past weekend, the Bush-as-presidential-candidate
image took another high-profile step when he showed up in the comic
strip ``Doonesbury.''
</P>
<P>
   At stop after stop on his re-election campaign, the governor
reiterates that his only immediate goal is becoming the first-ever
Texas governor elected to consecutive four-year terms. He will not,
however, promise to become the first Texas governor to serve
consecutive four-year terms.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Bush fielded a question about his presidential
ambitions from 10-year-old Holly Buck in Houston, where the
governor was touting a program to help at-risk youngsters make
responsible choices about drugs, sex and crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. I may. I may not. I'm a little worried what it
means to my daughters. They kind of like their privacy. I haven't
decided yet,'' said Bush, who has twin teen-age daughters.
</P>
<P>
   So, while most polls indicate he is the front-runner for the
2000 presidential nomination, Bush lists himself as an undecided.
</P>
<P>
   It's a crack in the door that Democratic challenger Garry Mauro
uses to try to persuade voters that Bush has his eyes on the White
House, and does his current job accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's South Carolina visit gives Mauro campaign officials a
chance to freshen up their he-wants-his-dad's-old-job line of
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in the process, what he is doing is taking Texas for
granted,'' said Mauro campaign manager Billy Rogers. ``Instead of
going to South Carolina, the governor ought to be trying to figure
out a way to end the teacher shortage crisis in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign insists today's events are routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Beasley is a friend of Governor Bush and, as he has said
before, Governor Bush is committed to helping his Republican
colleagues get elected to governorships,'' said Mindy Tucker,
Bush's campaign spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Bush curried favor with the friends of his friends,
including well-connected Republicans who are trolling for a
presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say at this point he is probably on top right now,''
said Jim Butts, a county GOP chairman in the northwestern part of
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Beasley, like Bush, is a favorite for re-election in November.
Also like Bush, Beasley is touting a record of tax cuts, welfare
reform, crime fighting and a strong state economy. Beasley also has
mounted a high-profile campaign to ban video poker machines that
have brought gambling to restaurants, truck stops and other
locations in his state. Similarly, Bush has led a battle against
devices like slot machines that have cropped up around Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Bush, Beasley is backed enthusiastically by his state's
social and religious conservatives. Bush's backing from groups like
the Texas Christian Coalition has been tepid at times.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. This article includes material from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
