<SLUG> BC-FORECASTERS-FLOODING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH-DEALNG STORMS AWESOME IN DESTRUCTIVENESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Core rains.'' It's a meteorological term worth remembering.
</P>
<P>
   When things go wrong weatherwise, as they did this weekend at
Del Rio on the Rio Grande, they can become death-dealing storm
systems awesome in their destructiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the daytime they may cover an area of 15 counties,''
explained Larry Eblen a meteorologist at the National Weather
Service's San Antonio-area office. At night, as temperatures drop,
``They collapse and intensify _ maybe they cover three or four
counties. They collapse just like a black hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a storm, the remnants of Tropical Storm Charley, which
smashed into the Texas Coast at Aransas Pass last week, dropped a
year's worth of rainfall _ about 18 inches _ near Del Rio between
Saturday night and Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The result was catastrophic. At 4:10 a.m. Monday, when the flood
gauge washed away, the Rio Grande was at 15.5 feet. Normally dry
creeks like the Devil's and Dry Devil's became raging torrents. The
flood claimed at least 17 lives in Del Rio, Ciudad Acuna across the
Mexican border and nearby Real and Uvalde counties. At least 20
other people were missing.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's forecast: a 70 percent chance of more rain.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Uvalde County, midway between San Antonio and Del Rio,
received about 7 inches of rain Saturday evening. A week earlier,
the area had received about 12 inches of rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saturated?'' Eblen said. ``Extremely so.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 75 flood warnings have been issued since Saturday
evening for parts of Southwest Texas, Eblen said.
</P>
<P>
   Val Verde County, of which Del Rio is the county seat, is not
particularly prone to flooding, Eblen noted, as the area rarely
gets enough rain to flood. San Felipe Creek, which provides the
city's water, is one of the few area waterways running year-round.
Val Verde normally gets about 1 1/2 inches of rain in August.
</P>
<P>
   But, Eblen said, when the area does flood, the result can be
devastating.
</P>
<P>
   ``The creeks that basically had no water flood rapidly,'' the
meteorologist said. ``They're very flashy. They come out of the
banks. Our main concern is the low-water crossings, trying to keep
people out.''
</P>
<P>
   While rainfall continued Monday, its intensity was diminishing.
Nonetheless, authorities were concerned about flooding on the Rio
Grande downstream in Eagle Pass. The river was expected to reach 38
feet, 22 feet above flood stage Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our second concern is that the system is beginning to move
back to the east,'' Eblen said. ``That means the Uvalde County area
is about to experience its third major rain event.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
