<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCAM-PAYMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEEPSTAKES IN AGREEMENT TO REIMBURSE NEW YORKERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Conn., N.Y., W.Va., Ind.)   (jw) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The mailing sent out by American Family Publishers
early this year for a multimillion-dollar sweepstakes carried an
eye-catching inducement. ``It's down to a two-person race for
$11,000,000,'' the promotion said. ``You and one other person in
New York were issued the winning number ... whoever returns it
first wins it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Saying the advertisement violated New York state's consumer
protection laws, Attorney General Dennis Vacco announced Monday
that he had reached a settlement of more than $800,000 with
American Family Publishers, based in Tampa, Fla. The settlement
includes a $60 rebate for 12,000 consumers who bought seven or more
magazine subscriptions from American Family.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said that they received more than 300 complaints
regarding the company, which features the television personalities
Ed McMahon and Dick Clark in its advertising. ``In the future they
will stop telling consumers that they have won a prize,'' Vacco
said at a news conference in Manhattan, referring to American
Family. ``Or that they are part of a select group with a better
chance of winning unless that is true.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials said an independent accounting firm using
records from American Family Publishing will identify who is
eligible for the $60 refund, to be mailed at the end of September,
and New Yorkers do not need to apply for it. They said a New York
resident must have bought six or more magazine subscriptions from
American Family Publishing between November 1996 and November 1997.
They must also have purchased at least one new subscription in
December 1997 or January 1998, whenthe ``two-person race'' mailing
went out.
</P>
<P>
   The New York settlement is the latest in a series of legal
battles entangling the company and the first to include a rebate.
In March, 32 states and the District of Columbia reached a joint
settlement with American Family Publishers, which is owned jointly
by a unit of Time Inc. and an investment group associated with the
Pritzker family of Chicago. To settle that case, the company paid
$50,000 to each state and agreed to stop telling people they were
winners unless they had actually won. It also agreed to state in
the mailings that it was not necessary to buy subscriptions to win
the sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco said American Family had admitted no wrongdoing in
reaching the settlement with New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Andrus, a spokesman for American Family Publishing, said
the company sends out more than 200 million pieces of mail each
year. He said that the mailings do not mislead people into thinking
that they have won the sweepstakes, or into thinking that buying
subscriptions will increase their chances of winning. ``We do try
to have people understand exactly what our promotions entail,'' he
said. ``We make it very clear that a person is not required to buy
subscriptions to enter our sweepstakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Four states, West Virginia, Connecticut, Indiana and Florida,
are pressing suits against American Family Publishers. Clark and
McMahon are also being sued by these states, and the company also
faces at least 26 class-action civil suits and 11 lawsuits brought
by people seeking millions in damages.
</P>
<P>
   Until March, New York was one of the nearly three dozen states
negotiating a group settlement with the company. But Vacco said
that when he saw the final terms of the agreement, he felt a better
settlement was possible and withdrew.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-24-98 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
