<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE'S QUEST PUT ON HOLD FOR A DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL MODOONO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Mark McGwire's pursuit of Roger Maris'
single-season home run record went on vacation Monday, as McGwire
was rested by Cardinals manager Tony La Russa. But, as luck would
have it, the game between St. Louis and Pittsburgh was rained out
with the score tied at 5-5 in the bottom of the seventh. Since the
Pirates and the Cardinals will meet again in St. Louis for three
games beginning Sept. 14, the game will be replayed in its entirety
as part of a doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, McGwire did not lose any ground in his quest to get
to 62. Instead, he got to sit in the dugout and rest and listen to
the chorus of boos that serenaded John Mabry, his backup at first,
each time Mabry went to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame the fans,'' Mabry said of the 28,435 who showed
up on a rainy afternoon at Three Rivers Stadium. ``They wanted to
see Mark hit. It's like paying to see Elvis and getting a garage
band instead.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, McGwire, who has 53 home runs, did not seem
thrilled by the prospect of an extra game, even if it may give him
one extra shot at catching Maris.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the ridiculous rules of Major League Baseball,''
he said minutes after the game ended. ``Why do the stats count and
they still play it over? Why does it have to begin again in the
first inning?''
</P>
<P>
   Last week in New York, McGwire sat out one game during
back-to-back doubleheaders against the Mets. La Russa said Monday
that he would ``play it by ear'' on whether McGwire would sit out
any more games the rest of the way, including either game of the
newly scheduled doubleheader. One factor La Russa will weigh is
that the Cardinals already have three off days scheduled in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on how his body feels, and what type of game he'd
be playing,'' said La Russa, who has rested McGwire five games this
season and seen the slugger sit out three other games with minor
ailments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in a while you have to give him a chance to catch his
breath,'' La Russa added. ``But if you take care of a player for
the first four and a half months of a season, he should have enough
gas in the tank for September.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, La Russa said that if he did rest McGwire again,
he would not subject Mabry to another round of catcalls. Mabry has
been booed in Milwaukee, New York and Pittsburgh while performing
in his understudy role.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guarantee you I'll play Willie McGee at first,'' La Russa
said. ``And if you boo him, you get ejected from the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh fans had no chance to see any of McGwire's show
Monday. An early morning rain canceled batting practice (McGwire
was expected to participate), and the seventh-inning downpour kept
La Russa from using him as a pinch-hitter. McGwire's only on-field
appearance was to pose for a picture with the former Pirate stars
Dave Parker and Willie Stargell.
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious that McGwire was the sole attraction. The
Pirates' public relations director, Jim Tridinich, even fielded
some hostile phone calls from fans who had bought tickets in
advance only to learn Sunday that McGwire would not play. La Russa
and McGwire had planned the day off weeks earlier, but only made
their decision public on Sunday. Tridinich was chastised by one
irate caller who said he ``didn't do his homework.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not paying $50 to see Kevin Polcovich,'' Tridinich said
the fan told him, referring to the Pirates' reserve shortstop who
is hitting .189.
</P>
<P>
   On his day off, McGwire spent much of his time before the game
talking on his cell phone. He did agree to a request to sign a
baseball from a young fan who had caught one of his weekend homers.
McGwire refuses to sign the actual home run balls, but he did give
the youngster his signature on another ball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
